<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0001 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-OLYSCANDAL-COX     02-10 1843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-OLYSCANDAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne memo lists IOC lures
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (I) International and (S) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the final, frenzied push before the International
Olympic Committee's vote to award the 1996 Centennial Games,
Atlanta bid chief Billy Payne considered a college scholarship,
medical treatment and free plane tickets as gifts for IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum Payne addressed to a top aide, he suggested
inducements such as a University of Georgia scholarship for IOC
Executive Board member Pal Schmitt's daughter and an invitation for
medical treatment from the Emory Clinic to Bashir Mohamed
Attarabulsi, the Libyian IOC member who recently resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum, written Aug. 20, 1990, one month to the day
before the announcement of Atlanta's stunning win in Tokyo, is the
first evidence Payne even considered gifts for IOC members that he
acknowledges today were ``out-of-bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said Tuesday he doesn't remember the memo, but concedes he
must have written it after it emerged in a search of Olympic
records currently stored at the Atlanta History Center. He also
said he does not recall whether he sent the memo, which was
addressed to his bid team colleague Ginger Watkins. Nor does he
believe any of his suggestions were acted upon.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to characterize the environment in which he wrote
the memo, Payne said the final few weeks before the vote were
``unbelieveably tense and busy,'' and the competition among the six
bidding cities ``was fierce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In those frantic few weeks before the announcement, I was
continually thinking out loud about things which might have made a
difference in our campaign,'' he acknowledged. ``None of these
directives were ever seriously discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the memo was ever sent _ and I suspect it never was since
no one remembers receiving it _ none of those suggestions, which
could have been deemed inappropriate, were ever acted upon,'' Payne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said Tuesday she didn't remember receiving the memo,
titled ``Personal Gift List'', and agreed with Payne that even if
she did, none of his suggestions was acted upon. ``None of the
things that are on there ever occurred,'' she said Tuesday, sitting
at a table in the History Center archives with the original copy of
the memo in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the memorandum was sent to the Atlanta Journal-Consti-
tution this week. When queried about the memo Monday, Payne's
attorney and Watkins searched the records and found the original in
a box containing some of Watkins' files.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's memo suggested an array of gifts, such as complimentary
airline tickets for two IOC members from South America; a suit of
clothes made by a specific Korean haberdasher for the member from
Panama; and a letter showing support for Atlanta signed by all the
members of the U.S. Supreme Court for the head of the IOC's
juridical commission.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging gift ideas, however, were the medical
treatment for Attarabulsi and a tennis scholarship for Schmitt's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The first item on the list was headed ``Attarabulsi.''
Underneath that name, Payne suggested they come up with ``a letter
from Emory Clinic acknowledging that we would like him to come to
Atlanta for medical treatment whenever he needs it and an offer to
pay his air transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   An Emory Clinic spokeswoman said corporate policy prohibited the
clinic from confirming or denying whether Attarabulsi ever received
treatment. Attarabulsi, an IOC member since 1977, resigned from the
IOC because of revelations that his son, Suhel, received tuition to
attend an English language center at Brigham Young University and a
community college, plus $700 a month for expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the name Pal Schmitt, Payne wrote: ``Get a letter from the
University of Georgia offering a scholarship to his daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   A UGA spokesman said there is no record of Schmitt's daughter,
Petra, attending the university. She enrolled at the University of
Southern California in 1992 and was two-time all-American on the
tennis team.
</P>
<P>
   That perk came with the aid of Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice
president from Los Angeles. DeFrantz acknowledged she telephoned
the former athletics director at USC and asked him to consider a
position on the tennis team for Schmitt's daughter. She denied
trying to sway Schmitt's vote toward Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz and Schmitt are members of the IOC's 11-member
executive board.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt is on the IOC's special investigation panel reporting on
allegations that Salt Lake City bidders bribed IOC members with
scholarships for their relatives, free medical care and lavish
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he believes providing medical treatment and
scholarships would be improper. But he suggests because his
proposal to do just that was dismissed is ``testimony to the high
standards, under enormous pressures, used by our team in pursuit of
the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The other six gift ideas on his list were simply personal items
that would have fallen within the IOC's rules at the time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones that would have been out-of-bounds would have
been the offer of free non-emergency medical assistance and the
scholarship,'' he said. ``I was brain dumping, which is not
uncharacteristic of me. For every good idea I had, I had a thousand
bad ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Payne said he never acted on his bad ideas, they
likely will come under the scrutiny of the IOC, which, in the wake
of revelations of payoffs in Salt Lake City, is investigating all
candidate cities from 1996 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has sent an inquiry letter to the U.S. Olympic Committee
seeking any evidence of improprieties in Atlanta's bid. Payne said
he has not received a formal inquiry from the USOC or the IOC.
However, he has prepared a response that maintains the Atlanta bid
team violated no laws or Olympic rules. It also asserts no bribes
or inappropriate gifts were sought by IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, no specific evidence of wrongdoing has surfaced in
the Atlanta bid. And Payne and Watkins both contend that none will.
``Our Games were won fairly,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the memo does indicate that Payne, who has vigorously
portrayed Atlanta's bid in the world press as squeaky clean, was at
least pondering some of the same types of gifts that have forced
the expulsion of nine IOC members. Four have already resigned.
</P>
<P>
   And Payne and his lawyers still decline to release their 4,000
boxes of Olympic records _ which could verify his claim _ to the
public. He said they will be made public after they are inventoried
and archived, although some will be released individually if needed
to refute specific allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are private records,'' said Joe Bankoff, the King &AMP;
Spalding lawyer who combed the boxes with Watkins to unearth the
original memo. ``When a specific issue is raised we will respond.
But we are not going to make the documents generally available.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne and other members of the volunteer bid team have
acknowledged extensive pampering of visiting IOC members, which
included first-class air travel, luxury accommodations, dinner in
private homes, chaffeured venue tours and bountless small gifts.
Local corporations, including Cox Enteprises provided private jets
to fly IOC members to and fro. Many went golfing at Augusta
National Golf Club, others went yachting on Malcolm Forbes'
Highlander, docked in Savannah _ all in the name of courtship.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for IOC votes in the final two years of the bid
effort, cost $7.8 million for everything from travel and
entertainment to publishing a slick five-volume bid book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we spent less than our competition when we bid for
the Games, it was a high-stakes endeavor to show the best of
Atlanta, the quality of our people and our desire to host the
Games,'' Payne said Tuesday. ``Competition, as in all years, was
fierce.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Atlanta bid team's secret weapon was personalized gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A part of our plan was to try and find small personal gifts
that meant something to each IOC member,'' Watkins explained.
``There were discussions among the people on the committee that
knew the IOC members, what are their interests, what are their
hobbies.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the months leading up to the bid, the personal entreaties
flowed. There was a print of a building at Amherst College for
Prince Albert of Monaco, an alumnus; a carved walking stick for an
IOC delegate from San Juan who walked with a cane; and a bulldog
for a Cuban IOC delegate who admired a statue of the University of
Georgia mascot in Payne's office, among others.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the suggested gifts on Payne's list are simply more
of the same.
</P>
<P>
   He sought ``some kind of horse memorabilia'' from Cot Campbell,
for Phillipp von Schoeller, an Austrian show-jumping champion.
Campbell is a Georgian who owns the reputable Dogwood Stables and
races top-notch thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   He considered a ``signed card from hundreds of school children''
in Savannah inviting the IOC's now-retired Irish delegate, Kevin
Patrick O'Flanagan back to grand marshall another parade.
O'Flanagan marshalled the St. Patrick's Day parade earlier in the
year. Payne suggested tossing a photo of him at that event in with
the card.
</P>
<P>
   For Raymond Gafner, a now retired IOC member from Switzerland,
Payne thought ``an agreement to publish his novel in English''
would be nice. Gafner has published several books in French, but
none have ever been publishing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Payne suggested complimentary American Airlines tickets for Ivan
Dibos from Peru and Fidel Mendoza from Columbia. Watkins believes
the two may have been attending an International All-Star Baseball
game in Atlanta two days later, but she did not know if the tickets
were provided or if the IOC members actually came.
</P>
<P>
   For Virgilio de Leon, a retired member from Panama, Payne
considered calling the owner of L.A. Town in Korea and ordering up
a suit. Payne apparently knew at the time de Leon bought clothes
there, and the owner would have his measurements.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, Payne dreamed big when he hoped for the signatures
of support of the entire U.S. Supreme Court for Juge Keba Mbaye of
Senegal, who is the honorary chief justice of the Supreme Court of
Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   Today Payne laughs at that possibility. ``I know no judges on
the supreme court; I know that was not produceable. No one took
these musings as anything but that -- musings. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Payne is a dreamer,'' said Watkins, who worked at
Payne's side through the 10-year effort to win and organize the
Games. ``We wouldn't have had these Games in Atlanta if Billy
hadn't been a dream, thinking big, thinking creatively. You can't
take a person who is a dream and put him in a box and say you can't
have any big ideas for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
