<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMLET-THEATER-REVIEW     02-10 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMLET-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, A NOT-SO-SWEET PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By B.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The members of the Frog and Peach Theater Company
have decided that ``Hamlet'' is pretty much a guy thing: a lethal
game between a young man and his stepfather who are out to destroy
each other and who end up obliterating their entire family, along
with another hapless family that just happened to be around.
Turning the play into a thriller of this kind requires very
different pacing from the usual classical productions and a marked
change in the personalities of some key characters.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing tentative about the Hamlet (Ted Zurkowski) in
this presentation; he has never heard of psychology, not to mention
psychiatry. He is all outside and very little inside, not much
given to introspection; his ``too too solid flesh'' speech is a
comment on his efforts to wipe his fingers clean after a handshake
with Claudius, and ``to be or not to be'' is spoken as a kind of
challenging flirtation to Ophelia. He hates Claudius and means to
kill him from word one; if it takes a little time, that is only
because Hamlet is gathering evidence of his stepfather's crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Claudius (Austin Pendleton), on the other hand, is all inside
and so little outside that courtiers walk right past him at the
outset, scarcely noticing he is there. But he is there, all right.
At first Pendleton makes it seem that Claudius hardly knows what to
say; he stops in mid-line to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   But in time this thoughtful caution becomes a calculating
menace. This Claudius is devious down to his toenails, and thus his
prayer scene is more convincing than in any performance I can
recall, ending as it does with his recognition that nothing can
stop him now, since he is damned anyway. And anyone who has ever
wondered what Rosencrantz and Guildenstern are doing in this play
need only watch Pendleton's crinkly-eyed self-satisfaction as he
manipulates them to realize what pawns of evil they are.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to cast Pendleton as the ghost of Hamlet's father
as well is rather ingenious. There is the advantage of the obvious
resemblance of the brothers. But more to the point, as the scheming
Claudius occasionally makes himself almost invisible to other
characters, the ghost is a commanding presence no one can ignore,
not even those who can't see him.
</P>
<P>
   Lynnea Benson, the director, makes this very much a domestic
drama by the simple device of staging virtually every one-on-one
confrontation out of sight and earshot of other characters. The
discrete, almost secret development of the crisis brought on by the
enmity of Hamlet and Claudius has a claustrophobic feeling that
fits the conception of the play as a thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Making Hamlet so brawny has telling effects on Horatio and
Laertes. Horatio (Joe Corey) is a kind of crumpled good old boy who
turns up when needed, and this notion works quite well until the
end, when ``good night, sweet prince'' sounds peculiarly soppy in
his mouth. For Laertes (Matthew D. Barton), the toughening of
Hamlet levels the field. When Hamlet is a brooding intellectual,
Laertes always seems just a youthful victim. Here Hamlet is no
smarter than Laertes, and Laertes' plotting with Claudius to poison
Hamlet makes both young men seekers of blood vengeance fated to
kill each other.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens to the women, Gertrude and Ophelia, roles so
appealing that directors almost always spotlight them? Ophelia
(Josephine Gallarello) does in fact seem a bit lost, just a nice
girl who walked into the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude (Vivien Landau) is something else. First, she is so
definite about her opinions and perceptions that she seems at times
almost to prop up the worried and ingrown Claudius. And that makes
what happens when Hamlet examines her conscience in her bedroom
especially striking; she looks absolutely terrified, so much so
that when the ghost tells Hamlet she is shaken, you wonder how he
thinks anyone could miss it. Besides all that, Ms. Landau's sense
of poise and style keeps making you wonder whether Wallace Warfield
Simpson might not have looked like this if she had ever been
allowed to run Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
   There are some unfortunate moments in this production and some
creaky transitions. But the determination of Ms. Benson and the
cast to realize all the implications of their overall conception of
the play makes it a very different and thought-provoking experience
of ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   HAMLET  &QL; 
By William Shakespeare; directed by Lynnea Benson; fight director,
Ian Marshall; play within a play staged by Tom Knutson; sets by
Eric Lemire; lighting by Jeanne Palomino. Presented by the Frog and
Peach Theater Company. At the Theater at West-Park Presbyterian
Church, 165 West 86th Street, Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ted Zurkowski (Hamlet), Austin Pendleton (Claudius and
Ghost), Vivien Landau (Gertrude), Josephine Gallarello (Ophelia),
Matthew D. Barton (Laertes), Joe Corey (Horatio), Jerry Less
(Rosencrantz) and Tom Marsden (Guildenstern).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 0009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RUSH-LADN     02-10 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUSH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLACE LIKE HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It has not gone as UCLA freshman forward JaRon
Rush planned, not even close. He was homesick in December. He was
too scared to fly in January. Last weekend he was booted from
practice and benched for the Oregon State game. His jumper arrived
just recently.
</P>
<P>
   Examine Rush through the lens of Los Angeles and his
vulnerabilities seem incongruous with his big, bad reputation and a
resume that includes a public feud with Kansas coach Roy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to unlocking his present is a past that tugs at him
from his native Kansas City, where he is both exploited and
glorified, where a circle of friends, family and hangers-on have
made him both the center of their universe and an outsider, filled
with contradictions and insecurities, trying to please others while
being true to himself.
</P>
<P>
   For Rush, college is a reclamation project, and the subject is
his soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I feel like my life is everybody else's,'' he said.
``Sometimes, I feel like it it's not my mind, it's theirs.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ Early and often &QL; 
Rush was cursed by being too good too young. In 1994, when Hoop
Scoop Magazine annointed him the best player in the high school
freshman class, his life disappeared. Coaches, boosters and
recruiters saw Rush as a meal ticket and scrambled for a piece of
the 15-year-old. (By contrast, Baron Davis was 5-foot-3 and unknown
as a ninth grader.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late-bloomers have it easier,'' Rush said. ``I've always been
in the spotlight and it's not much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush was Kansas City's version of L.A. phenom Schea Cotton. He
became immersed in expectations and attention. Every game was a
story, his recruitment a public saga and, even now, Rush makes
headlines in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   When he did not play Sunday against Oregon State, it was on the
front page of the Kansas City Star's sports section and a topic of
conversation on sports radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big celebrity back there,'' said UCLA guard Earl
Watson, a Kansas City, Kan., native. ``Anthony Peeler saved
basketball in Kansas City. JaRon was supposed to be the next
Peeler.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush's inner circle expanded with his fame. He had four homes,
five families and a slew of sycophants. It was a fantastic,
fractured world _ cars and trips for free, seductive yet
smothering, overpowering his core, vanquishing his sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   ``JaRon feels he has to please too many people,'' said Rush's
cousin, Tyrone Jacobs. ``A lot of people have tried to influence
him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is Tom Grant, the Kansas booster who became Rush's
benefactor, offering his house and car, funding a scholarship at
Pembroke Hill School and flying Rush around the country to visit
colleges. (The NCAA approved the Rush-Grant relationship,
concluding Grant was not acting on Kansas' behalf and has assisted
other prep athletes.)
</P>
<P>
   There's Myron Piggie, the former AAU coach who commanded a
stable of prep stars that included Watson. Through Grant, Piggie
gained early influence with Rush and eventually orchestrated his
recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   There's his girlfriend, Sarah Hofstra, the mother of his
14-month-old son, Shea. And Hofstra's parents. There's his mother
Glenda and his brother Kareem, himself a well-regarded prospect who
might sign with UCLA. Finally, Rush has his grandmother, Jeanette
Jacobs, whom he trusts above all, who sees through the presents,
the promises and the posturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When JaRon's (in Kansas City), he has people giving him what
he wants because they all want a piece of him,'' Jeanette said.
``It's been giving and giving. The Grants taking him on trips has
done this to him. He hasn't been able to live his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to choose a college, Grant and the Hofstras
wanted Kansas, Jeanette and Glenda did not. They saw the pressure
and the pampering and realized Rush could not be a Jayhawk if he
wanted a life. Glenda refused to co-sign the letter of intent, Rush
criticized Kansas coach Roy Williams' substitution pattern and,
with a city outraged, committed to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been great theater if it hadn't been his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's always telling him what he should do, what he
shouldn't do, where he should go to school, where he shouldn't go
to school,'' Jeanette said. ``I got tired of it. The best thing was
for him to go to California and be his own boss. He needs a life,
and if he stayed here he wouldn't have it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ The price of fame &QL; 
Rush was never more vulnerable than on the frightening flight to
the Louisville game. Trembling, crying, he put his head on Watson's
lap and prayed for his life, then refused to board the connecting
flight and drove from Memphis to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the only instance of insecurity. Throughout the
season _ in Puerto Rico and Eugene, Ore., against Kentucky and
against Stanford _ Rush has talked of nerves. His honesty is
refreshing, his problem mystifying: How can one of the nation's top
prep players be nervous, and not just once or twice, but for 15
games? The answer is in Kansas City, ground zero for pressure and
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   His Christmas break was a perfect example. He spent time with
Grant and with his friends and his family and with Piggie, who
tried to regain lost influence and, a source said, pressured Rush
into not returning to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piggie is just another voice,'' Rush said. ``He has tried to
take advantage of me financially.'' (Piggie could not be reached
for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Rush also spent time with Shea _ gave him a bitty basketball set
for Christmas _ and with Sarah. Her parents suggested a transfer so
he could be closer to home, closer to his son.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he went, every house he entered, someone had an
opinion. After five months away, he was once again at the center of
attention, people tugging at him from all directions. He wasn't so
much homesick as home-obligated. But what they really wanted,
everyone except Jeanette, was what was best for them. Deep down, he
knew he had to leave. It was just so hard to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   He returned a few days late, served a one-game suspension, then
returned to his internal war with nerves and expectations. His jump
shot arrived Feb. 4, with a 6-of-9 performance against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he was kicked out of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out of character and that's why I threw him out,'' UCLA
coach Steve Lavin said. ``Because he's finding a way to cope with
the pressure and the homesickness and having so much on his plate,
maybe being silly is a way to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush walked out of Pauley Pavilion, picked up the telephone and
dialed Jeanette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he needs to grow up a little,'' she said. ``Being
here, where people give him things, that's not the real world. I'm
trying to keep him out there, in the real world. I'm doing
everything I can. He's just been under tremendous pressure. I'm
surprised he hasn't gone bonkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does the saga end? Will Rush wilt under the pressure and
return to his Kansas City comfort zone? Or will he endure the
distance and forge his own life in L.A.? Watson, who battled
homesickness last year, believes Rush will be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, he'll be fine, just like I am now,'' Watson said.
``It's a long road. It definitely takes a year, but he'll mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Out here, at least, he has a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
