<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BRIBERYSCANDAL-HN     02-10 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERYSCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SALT LAKE CITY _ The printed report, with copious footnotes and
appendixes, was as thick as a phone book, but there was little
trouble cutting to the chase. After an investigation covering
nearly eight weeks and involving some 50,000 pages of documents, a
look into the inner dealings of the Salt Lake Bid Committee's
efforts to land the 2002 Winter Olympic Games yielded one
inescapable conclusion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's largely a world without rules,'' David Jordan, a member
of the five-person Board of Ethics charged with investigating a
process gone badly wrong, said Tuesday. ``Some function well in a
world without rules. Some don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a roomful of national and world media, Jordan and his
group shed a little more embarrassing light on some of those who
don't, implicating 10 more International Olympic Committee members
in the growing bribery scandal, bringing the grand total to 24.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations include cash payments, a bogus scholarship
program, expensive travel (including Super Bowl trips), medical
services, gifts and shopping sprees _ even a suspect deal involving
the United States Olympic Committee and an agreement to provide
training and support for Sudanese athletes.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the board blamed the largest scandal in
Olympics history on two men _ former Salt Lake Organizing Committee
head Tom Welch and his top lieutenant, Dave Johnson. SLOC chairman
Robert Garff went so far as to describe the behavior of the two as
``disgusting and disguised.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of things, though, it became clear there was
plenty of dirt to go around, much of it involving sticky-fingered
IOC delegates and relatives who were more than willing to accept
SLOC cash and favors. According to the report, ``the behavior of
some IOC members was eye-opening as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's findings also cast aspersions on the USOC's efforts
on behalf of Sudanese athletes in citing electronic mail from
former USOC official Alfredo LaMont, who wrote that ``a lot of
promises were made to secure votes.'' LaMont also is linked to a
pair of questionable consulting deals with ties to African Olympic
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding hints that the support had been linked to votes, USOC
executive director Dick Schultz noted that the organization
commonly gives aid to foreign athletes and insisted there had been
no wrongdoing on the organization's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to help Salt Lake,'' he said. ``There was no
attempt to buy votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the board painted a picture of a bid committee allowed
to run amok after the unsuccessful 1991 bid for the 1998 Winter
Games, which went to Nagano, Japan. While concluding that Welch and
Johnson were under a mandate to secure the Games for 2002 after
what several of those interviewed called ``more sophisticated and
extravagant'' efforts by the rival Japanese, Garff lamented that
the quest clearly had gotten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was not part of the plan,'' he said, ``was Mr. Welch and
Mr. Johnson making direct payments to IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   Those included more than $70,000 in cash to Jean-Claude Ganga,
part of an estimated $250,000 in benefits the Republic of Congo
native allegedly received. They also involved questionable
employment arrangements for relatives of IOC members and a
``scholarship program'' that often was nothing more than a front
for cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits included a Super Bowl trip (cost: $19,991) for three
couples with IOC ties, including Australian member Phillip Coles
and Guatemalan Willi Kaltschmitt, each of them newly linked to the
Salt Lake end of the scandal. Others were treated to trips to New
York City, Las Vegas and Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   The board stressed, however, that it could find no evidence of
rumored ``escort'' services for IOC visitors, a subject of
considerable local gossip in recent weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   While the group lacked subpoena power, and some subjects _
notably former SLOC finance chief Craig Peterson and one-time Welch
secretary Stephanie Pate _ declined to cooperate, the report
offered more detail than the IOC investigation and drew more of its
membership into the web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there is a great amount of detail in this,'' IOC
vice president Dick Pound, head of the organization's own
investigation, said in a conference call with reporters. ``This
will certainly supplement what we've been able to find, and I hope
it will fill in some of the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   SLOC's now-famous ``scholarship program'' was fertile and common
ground for abuse. Among the more blatant examples: $23,000 in
living expenses for Nancy Rignault Arroyo, 44-year-old divorced
daughter of Ecuadorean IOC member Augustin Arroyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, among six IOC members facing expulsion in the wake of the
scandal, accepted about $250 million in medical care, gifts,
travel, lodging and cash while making at least a half-dozen visits
to Salt Lake City during the bid process.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimated travel expenses alone for Ganga and his
family in excess of $115,000, plus $13,900 in meals and lodging.
Other benefits included an additional $45,000 in either paid or
donated medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga and his wife commonly ran up big bills on
bid-committee-sponsored shopping trips while in town. Between Oct.
25, 1994, and March 27, 1995, the bid committee also provided what
the report termed ``unexplained direct payments'' to Ganga totaling
$70,010.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Mukora, an IOC delegate from Kenya, received direct
payments totaling $34,650 between Nov. 26, 1993, and May 5, 1995.
Welch told the Board of Ethics that all but the first payment of
$5,200 was for Mukora's personal use.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean IOC member Sergio Santander-Fantini, president of his
country's National Olympic Committee during the time of Salt Lake's
bid for the 2002 Games, received two checks totaling $20,050,
believed to have been used for a political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in December 1994, the bid committee authorized four
$15,000 payments to Rene Essomba, the since-deceased IOC member
from Cameroon. It also spent $108,350 on tuition and living
expenses for Essomba's daughter, Sonia Essomba, and provided legal
advice in her efforts to break an apartment lease.
</P>
<P>
   The bid committee arranged for the daughter of Dr. Un Yong Kim,
the IOC member from Korea, to perform with the Utah Symphony on
March 24 and 25, 1995. Pianist Hae Jung Kim received $5,000 for her
appearance. Welch also helped John Kim, the IOC member's son, to
find consulting work at a local communications company, with the
bid committee paying at least $45,000 of the younger Kim's salary
and perhaps as much as $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bjarne Haeggman, then-husband of Finnish IOC member Pirje
Haeggman, received $33,750 for a consulting job with Great Basin
Engineering of Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   LaMont, the recently resigned director of international
relations and protocol for the USOC, was linked to a pair of
questionable consulting deals. In the course of the successful 2002
effort, the bid committee paid more than $18,000 to Arca Inc., to
which LaMont has been tied.
</P>
<P>
   Among fresh names undergoing scrutiny, Mohamed Zerguini of
Algeria reportedly was involved in securing a cash payment of
$14,500 for a grandson through consultant El Farnawani of Toronto;
$3,000 a month was found to pass through a consulting firm linked
to Austin Sealy of Barbados; and three others (Rampaul Ruhee of
Mauritius, Anani Matthia of Togo and Ashwini Kumar of India)
allegedly accepted trips for wives or family to attend the 1995
site election in Budapest, where Salt Lake City finally got the
call.
</P>
<P>
   While Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt lauded the report as the first step
in ``moving on,'' initial response elsewhere was less enthusiastic:
The John Hancock Co., a major Olympic sponsor, canceled
negotiations with NBC for $20 million in advertising to protest the
IOC's handling of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, meanwhile, officials hoped the disclosures would begin
to shift the focus to the Games, which now are less than three
years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened here wasn't right, and we're setting it
right,'' Leavitt said. ``Olympic corruption didn't start here, but
it must end here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
