<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     02-10 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO CUT MARINERS SOME PRESEASON SLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For months, or rather, for more than a year, the
favorite game in town has been ``Pin the Tail on the Mariners.''
</P>
<P>
   Rancor. Mistrust. Skepticism. Ridicule. You name it, the
Mariners have been dealt it.
</P>
<P>
   From John Ellis' crying game about the new stadium to Chuck
Armstrong's announcement in November '97 about no deal for Randy
Johnson to Glenallen Hill's beanball tactics in left field to Russ
Davis' bloopers, bleeps and blunders at third base to Bobby Ayala
and Heathcliff Slocumb's gas-house bullpen gang all the way down to
Woody Woodward's giving away the Mariner farm in trading-deadline
giveaways . . . no stone has been left unturned, no stone has been
left unthrown.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday marked the start of a kinder, gentler view of our
little M's.
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, i.e. until the Mariners are 10 games out
of first place in the AL West (OK, maybe eight games out), this
columnist is not going to assume _ even in the face of substantial
evidence _ that the M's don't have a clue about what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: In major league baseball, three days are reserved
for unabashed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   One is the first day of spring training, with that mind-altering
first brush with sunlight and the sweet, hypnotic THWACK sound of
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Opening Day, when the standings list every team as
being equal and the butterflies and excitement are palpable, from
the fans in the 300 level down to the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Third, if your home team is the Mariners, the other day for a
Pollyanna-ish demeanor is the team's annual Prespring Training
Luncheon at the Edgewater Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere else in the presence of a rubberized, vaguely edible
chicken fillet (not that we're complaining) can so much skepticism
be throttled by a such a gush of open-mindedness and good humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be positive and brief,'' Ellis said. ``You always have
such optimism this time of year. Any baseball fan does.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something very homey and nice about the Mariners'
prespring training gathering. The Pepsi people show up. The Compaq
computer guy is there. The KIRO gang, including broadcaster Dave
Niehaus, turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was on hand, too, pleasantly answering all the
questions about players and the minor league ranks and deals he
would have liked to have made, if money had been no object this
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way salaries took off, there was no way I can justify
spending that kind of money without wondering if it's good for
baseball,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we could have, we would have gone after Tim Belcher or
Todd Stottlemyre, two veteran pitchers who would have been a
welcome addition to any club.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, the M's did nothing to get a front-line pitcher, thanks to
the Microsoft and Nintendo millionaires who can't spend any more
money. (Hey, it's their money.)
</P>
<P>
   Just for being honest, Woodward made it hard to secretly crucify
him for trading away two or three players in deadline deals when
the other team was only expecting one or two Mariner prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Lou Piniella's turn at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella always comes in from Tampa with a nice tan, which
really helps freshen up this gray, wintry place. And this time,
Piniella looked rested, ready and, best of all, miraculously devoid
of that ``I am definitely going to kill someone'' look he exuded
throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this, we were all disappointed with last year's
record,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes, I think you can take winning for granted. What
happened last year has made me more determined. We might be picked
third in our division, which is to be expected. But I'll tell you
one thing, we're not going to finish third. We're going to finish
on top.''
</P>
<P>
   On such a day as this, you had to believe Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   When he starts slinging around the fact that he still has Alex
Rodriguez, Jay Buhner, David Segui, Edgar Martinez, Dan Wilson and
Ken Griffey Jr., it's hard to focus on the fact that Jamie Moyer,
Jeff Fassero and Billy Swift (three-fifths of the Mariners'
starting rotation) are nearly as old as the Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Piniella has had a change of attitude, which _
Mariner players beware _ will translate into a killer spring
training regime.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, head trainer Rick Griffin speculated drills would be
longer and harder, like in the old days, when ``five or six guys
vomited'' during a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the past two seasons, instead of walking into spring
training thinking World Series, the M's won't forget the
embarrassment of '98 and will have to work their butts off to stay
competitive. The Angels and Rangers will share top billing in the
West, even though the M's own those two teams, and not just
psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   A team with this sort of work ethic and mind-set is tough to
harp on.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, after vilifying the Mariners for A) Everything
(stadium costs, Randy Johnson debacle, the unwillingness to wade
into the sky-high free-agent market) and B) Anything (when will
Griffey and Rodriguez be locked up?), it suddenly dawns on you:
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, it's time to back off pummeling the good old
M's.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
