<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-JAZZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ TUNES IN FOR 4TH QUARTER, TOPS MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ This time the Mavericks did not have enough gas left in
their tanks to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Employing a defense that suffocated the Mavericks in the fourth
quarter, the Utah Jazz erased an 11-point, second-quarter deficit
and spoiled the Mavericks' home opener with a 90-79 victory before
a fired-up crowd of 17,070 last night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the frantic fourth quarter _ which started tied at 66 _ the
Mavericks made only 1 of 12 shots and committed eight turnovers
that led to 10 points for the Jazz (3-0).
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a real good job for three quarters,'' Mavericks
coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``They just turned it up in
the fourth quarter and outplayed us, and that's what great teams
are supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not discouraged. We did some good things. We just weren't
clicking on all of our cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   In the somber Mavericks locker room, rookie Dirk Nowitzki drew a
large crowd after his 15-point, nine-rebound effort. Two stalls
over, point guard Steve Nash was taking the loss personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though I let the team down,'' said Nash, who was
1-of-9 from the field and scored only four points. ``If I would
have shot the ball better, we would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone had nine of his game-high 31 points in the fourth
quarter. Malone scored seven consecutive points, and, combined with
John Stockton, helped the Jazz ease ahead, 85-77, with 2:26
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton finished with 12 points and five assists. Malone added
12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're the favorites because they were there last
year and took the best team in the NBA to the wire,'' said Cedric
Ceballos, who led the Mavericks with 19 points. ``They're real
competitive, they play at a high level, and they've got two great
players that really carry that ballclub and get them out of almost
any kind of danger that they get into.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks had put the Jazz in a lot of danger in the second
quarter. Dallas led, 39-28, after two baskets by Samaki Walker
midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone, who had 16 points in the first half, helped Utah
close to within 45-41 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pack, the Mavericks' backup point guard, scored nine
points in the third period. He highlighted the quarter when he
split the Utah defense, scored on a reverse layup, was fouled, and
completed the three-point play that sent the two teams into the
fourth quarter tied at 66.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth period the Jazz turned up the heat, and the
Mavericks couldn't hold onto the ball or make a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome left Michael Finley, who scored 15 points on 6-of-15
shooting, shaking his head in disbelief. But he said the Jazz
should be given credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put them up there, being that they're the
\Rtwo-time\S defending Western Conference champions, being that
they went to other arenas and won,'' Finley said. ``They're a
veteran crew, and until someone dethrones them they're the team to
beat in the West.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
