<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     02-10 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS HAVE NO ANSWER FOR MALONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It began with the lights off and Mavs Man suspended
upside down from the ceiling like some malevolent vampire last
night at Reunion Arena. If Don Nelson could somehow have arranged
to have him dropped on Karl Malone, maybe the Mavs would have had a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was ``The Mailman'' who drained everything in sight
and even gave the Mavs' head coach a forearm shiver to remember him
by as the Jazz spoiled the Mavs' home opener with a 90-79 victory
in front of a near sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hits you, you remember it,'' Nellie laughed afterward
of the psychological battle with Malone that actually turned
physical late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a little bump,'' Nelson confirmed of the forearm
Malone smacked into the coach's shoulder as he came by the sideline
at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Busy trying to hold his unraveling team together at the time,
Nellie barely reacted to Malone's hit. Malone looked back over his
shoulder as he loped down court, watching Nelson for a response
that never really came.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took that pretty good for an older fella,'' Malone chuckled
as he soaked his feet in a bucket of ice following Utah's third
consecutive victory to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   If the distracted Nelson was an easy target, the Mavs were like
tin cans in a shooting gallery. Malone drilled them for 31 points
and a dozen rebounds. Sitting at courtside, it felt more like 60
and 25.
</P>
<P>
   The stats sheet says Malone made 14 of 22 shots. Funny, I don't
remember him missing a thing, including Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy, but you get into a kind of rhythm in some
games and it feels like every shot you take is going in,'' Malone
said. ``They went small in the fourth quarter and I just tried to
exploit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploit it? Watching Malone toy with the Mavs was like watching
Gulliver playing H-O-R-S-E with the Lilliputians. At any moment you
can expect word from Reunion Arena that Malone has scored again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were giving him the jump shot and he was hitting it,''
Nelson conceded.
</P>
<P>
   One question: What kind of brilliant defensive strategy
``gives'' Malone the jump shot?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe giving Malone his jumpers wasn't in the game
plan. Maybe it's just what Malone took from hapless defenders like
A.C. Green, Hot Rod Williams and Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   The warm, fuzzy feelings left over from the Mavs' 45-41 halftime
lead had pretty well dissipated by the time the fourth quarter
began. Everyone in Reunion realized that the Jazz was just getting
warmed up while the Mavs seemed to be falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz turned up the intensity in the fourth quarter and the
Mavs couldn't match it. Veteran point guard John Stockton simply
wouldn't let the Mavs get anything going offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sniffed our poor passers out and gummed about five
possessions up,'' Nelson said. ``We're not ready to beat this team
yet. But I did think I could put a team out there that could score
more than 79 points. You shoot only 35 percent from the field, it's
going to be hard to beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the defending Western Conference champion Jazz, the
team many figure will supplant the Bulls as this year's NBA champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a veteran team and we're supposed to win that game,''
Malone said. ``They have a young team over there but they're
talented and everybody wants to beat the Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Nelson was trying to throw Malone off his game when he
said something to him in the first half last night. Malone did a
double-take, stared at the Dallas coach and then began to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important what I said,'' Nelson said with a smile.
``I've loved the guy so much over the years and have so much
respect for him. I was just having a little fun with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone seemed to enjoy the give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't say anything bad, but I'm not going to repeat it,''
Malone said, also grinning. ``I like having fun with him. There
aren't a lot of coaches around who'd do something like that and I
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because ``The Mailman,'' as usual, got in the last
and best shot. In more ways than one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
