<HEADLINE>
AXELSSON, BRUINS TOO SLICK FOR OILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ His nickname is Gumby because of the way he
bounces off checks from bigger, stronger players. His blond hair,
impish grin, stick-thin frame, and perennial good mood make him the
target of good-natured ribbing from his Bruins teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have great offensive gifts and has been known to miss
the net a time or two. But his determination and chemistry on
Boston's top defensive line earned him a regular job last season as
a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night P.J. Axelsson played the role of hero as he broke
a scoreless tie with a goal at 5:30 of the third period, propelling
Boston to a 2-0 victory over the Edmonton Oilers at the Skyreach
Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter, playing for the first time since spraining his
ankle Jan. 2 against Anaheim, scored the insurance goal when he
teed up a slapper from the right point at 10:07.
</P>
<P>
   Boston goalie Byron Dafoe stopped 31 Edmonton shots to register
the shutout, his sixth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The win, in the opener of a three-game road trip, extended
Boston's unbeaten streak to three games (2-0-1).
</P>
<P>
   Axelsson drove down the right circle, shook off an attempted
mugging by defenseman Janne Niinimaa, and beat Mikhail Shtalenkov
into the top right corner. It was Axelsson's sixth goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that I had a step on the defense, so I tried to go
around him,'' said Axelsson. ``He missed the hit on me, so I tried
to go to the net and he grabbed my jersey, so I just had to throw
the shot away and it went in. It was a little bit of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston found itself outmanned in a scoreless first period when
it lost two players. At 15:10, Darren Van Impe suffered a shoulder
separation when he was crushed by Georges Laraque after moving the
puck out from behind his net.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also lost forward Peter Ferraro late in the period
with a foot contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said Van Impe will fly home to Boston  &UR; today &LR; ,
and Ferraro's foot isn't broken but is very swollen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five guys left on defense,'' said Burns, ``and of the
five, three of their ages probably add up to over 100. They hung in
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good effort. We lost some soldiers along the way but
we battled strong. It didn't faze us. We hung in there and played a
patient game, and that's our strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter wasn't supposed to be back until Friday, but because of
his progress and the aid of a cortisone shot last Friday, he suited
up.
</P>
<P>
   After missing so much time _ first because of a contract dispute
and then the injury _ Carter had played only 25 games this season,
less than half of the schedule. The rust showed. It seemed that
both his conditioning and timing were off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' said Carter. ``You never know how you're
going to react after being out for a month. It felt good to be
sitting on the bench and in the heat of battle again. My timing is
a little bit off, but my legs were fine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle period, Boston got a huge scare at 11:16 when
Dafoe was crushed by former Boston University star Mike Grier. The
Bruins were on the power play and the puck got by Ray Bourque at
the point. Grier poked it ahead and started chasing it down. Dafoe
came rushing out of the net up through the left circle, and after
he cleared the puck, Grier ran right into him, hitting the
netminder in the head and sending him sprawling.
</P>
<P>
   After several seconds, Dafoe shook it off and remained in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' top line of Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov, and
Dmitri Khristich turned in a good effort during a power play midway
through the second but couldn't get anything past Shtalenkov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
