<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WOMEN GET EVEN WITH BOSTON COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ All week, maybe longer, the Huskies have been talking
about revenge against Boston College, payback for the upset loss at
Conte Forum last month. That long, dismal afternoon was an
embarrassment they had no intention of reliving in their rematch
Tuesday night, and they didn't care who knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most furious Husky was fiery guard Shea Ralph, who
in January could only watch dejectedly from the sideline with a
knee injury as her University of Connecticut teammates came out
flat, foundering, and fizzling their way to a rare Big East loss.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night the sophomore started her first game and turned in
a career-high 36 points (83 percent shooting) in leading the
Huskies to a crushing 107-77 win over BC before 16,294 satisfied
fans in the Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, fourth-ranked UConn improved to 21-3 overall, 14-1
in the league, while BC fell to 17-6 and 9-6. It was the third
straight loss for the Eagles, who have faced three Top 12 teams in
a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's just another night,'' said Ralph, grinning while
trying to shrug off her 10-for-12 shooting effort, including 4 for
5 from beyond the 3-point arc and 12 for 12 from the line. ``It's a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Her teammates were more effusive. ``She's so aggressive,''
explained Marci Glenney, who played 22 minutes off the bench. ``You
know she has games like that inside of her just waiting to come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alissa Murphy, who scored a career-high 32 points in BC's 78-66
upset of the Huskies, fouled out with 10:27 left after scoring 18
points to share the Eagles' scoring lead with backcourt mate
Brianne Stepherson. Becky Gottstein (5 points) soon joined Murphy
as the Eagles were in foul trouble early in a game in which 53
fouls were called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' said Murphy, who was called for three
fouls in less than a minute midway through the second half. ``I
don't know what else to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier meeting, UConn appeared hesitant, flat from the
outset. Not this time. Ralph hinted at things to come when she hit
a 3-pointer to open the scoring, and the outcome, for all intents
and purposes, seemed decided by halftime, even though UConn led by
only 14, 58-44.
</P>
<P>
   There were some bright spots for the Eagles, who coach Cathy
Inglese said were not at all nervous coming back to face a team
that had beaten them 16 straight times before last month's stunner.
One was freshman forward Nicole Conway, who had a career-high 14
points. After UConn jumped out to a 16-8 lead, the Eagles fought
back (thanks in large part to a couple of Conway 3-pointers) to
within 2 points, 20-18, with 12:30 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies put together runs of 15-6 and 11-2 on the way to
their halftime lead, earned largely on the back of Ralph (24
first-half points).
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Boston College could never whittle the lead
below 13, shooting only 37 percent coming out of the locker room to
UConn's 60.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Ralph. ``There's a certain way she plays that
makes you really appreciate the game of basketball,'' said UConn
coach Geno Auriemma. ``She knows exactly what to do when she gets
on a roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
