<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-SPILL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERED FREIGHTER DUMPING OIL ON OREGON BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 and SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOS BAY, Ore. _ Salvage crews will race time, weather and a
gooey mess befouling a pristine coastline Wednesday to protect a
beached freighter from a fierce storm expected tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Three fuel tanks on the New Carissa continued to leak oil slowly
Tuesday, spreading the thick tar on six miles of sandy beaches. The
tanks may hold as much as 140,000 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the rescue tug Salvage Chief will try to turn the
freighter's bow into the sea to better protect the ship from the
worsening weather.
</P>
<P>
   Winds of 50 knots and gusts of 60 knots are forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent is to put the bow into the seas, so we don't incur
anymore more structural damage,'' said Gene Maestas, a chief petty
officer with the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather will provide a brief window to do that. ``We
have one good day, then it gets worse,'' said Alan Hoffmeister, a
spokesman for the Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations also will begin Wednesday that could lead to
pumping oil out of the ship and into containers on the shore.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, environmental officials set in motion
preparations to deal with the spill in the state's beaches and
bays. Surveys of bird populations were begun and an advance team
from Washington state was dispatched to Coos Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the freighter is 200 miles from Washington,
officials worried that the northerly currents and southern winds
that are typical this time of year may push the heavy oil to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to move north,'' said Steve Hunter, who
supervises spill response at the Washington Department of Ecology.
``Just how and where it will move is hard to tell. But in the past
in winter spills, it has moved north.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the freighter carries as much as 400,000 gallons of
fuel, Hunter said the beached vessel has ``tremendous potential for
a major spill.'' Officials in Coos Bay said they did not know how
much oil the vessel was carrying when it beached.
</P>
<P>
   Most at risk are bird populations wintering on the Washington
coast, coastal razor clams and oyster beds in Willapa Bay and Grays
Harbor, said Dick Logan, who assesses spill damage for the Ecology
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The best guess is that tar balls from the New Carissa could come
ashore in Washington in three to five days, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Oregon, Coast Guard officials said they were doing
everything possible to contain the oil seeping from the 646-foot
freighter's ruptured fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 200 workers from 13 agencies in yellow slickers and
hard hats were called in to mop up oil the consistency of peanut
butter with shovels, squeegees and absorbent pompons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're skating on the edge here, hoping, praying, working hard
to avoid a disaster,'' said U.S. Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., who
was given a helicopter tour of the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Gov. John Kitzhaber said he may declare a state of
emergency, which would allow the National Guard to help in the
salvage and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage helicopters hauled heavy cables onto the ship that will
be used to stabilize it and ultimately pull it back out to sea. And
a crew of 13 was on board to check for structural problems and
prepare for the salvage.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-foot tug Salvage Chief, a veteran of the 1989 Exxon
Valdez recovery, is scheduled to motor out to the ship at first
light this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The tug will set out two huge anchors, then attach lines to the
bow of the freighter. A gun will fire the lines to the bow or they
will be dropped by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Then the tug will try to pull the bow around to prevent the
expected storm from breaking the vessel up.
</P>
<P>
   Construction also will begin on a series of posts that may
ultimately allow lines to be slung out to the ship from shore and
the remaining fuel to be pumped out.
</P>
<P>
   William Milwee, the salvage consultant representing the owners
of the ship, said salvage plans ``do not consist of just going out
there and pulling hard on the vessel and having it come off. It's a
matter of the Salvage Chief holding the vessel and working with the
sea to bring the vessel off.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the crew to use powerful pumps to suck sand from
underneath the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll use the ocean as one of the tools,'' Milwee said. ``We
have a saying in the salvage industry, `The ship will come when it
wants to come and stay there as long as it wants to stay there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Three oil-covered birds were found soon after the ship began
leaking Monday. Five more oily birds were spotted in the water
Tuesday. Crews equipped to deal with oiled wildlife were standing
by in case the slick moves into the nearby habitat of the Western
snowy plover, a threatened shorebird.
</P>
<P>
   Also in danger were oyster and clam beds in Coos Bay as well as
important estuaries farther south.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard said three of the ship's five fuel tanks were
leaking and one, containing heavy bunker oil, was ``seriously
breached.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil was described a ``blurping,'' slowly leaking out of the
boat with the rising and falling seas.
</P>
<P>
   Other leaks were found Tuesday in two empty cargo tanks toward
the back of the vessel, sending water gushing in and causing
structural problems. Heavy waves have turned the bow seaward,
causing it rock 15 degrees side to side.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, owned by a Japanese company, registered in Panama and
staffed with a Filipino crew of 23, went aground Thursday morning
about 150 yards offshore as it waited to come into port to pick up
a load of wood chips. Helicopters removed the crew the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Oil fumes mixed with salt air Tuesday as workers packed
oil-soaked sand into clear plastic bags and used front-end loaders
to pile up blackened driftwood.
</P>
<P>
   The thick oil penetrated less than an inch of the sand surface
and pooled into depressions. Hundreds of bags of oil-soaked sand
had been collected by Tuesday afternoon, but long stretches of
beach remained fouled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nasty, dirty hard work,'' said Milwee, the salvage
consultant. He said lighter elements of the oil have evaporated,
leaving behind only a gelatinous muck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just looks like somebody spray-painted the sand black,''
said Jamie Smith, who walked out to the beach to take a look at the
ship.
</P>
<P>
   The oil was relatively simple to pick up in sandy areas. Bits of
sand were scooped up and disposed of, said Hoffmeister, the
spokesman for the Bureau of Land Management. ``This morning there
was oil everywhere,
</P>
<P>
   but they did a great job of cleaning up.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials began notifying Indian tribes as well
as administrators of state and national parks about the potential
for a spill.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters were standing by to check for the spill, said Hunter
of the Ecology Department.
</P>
<P>
   Bird surveys were begun. Dead birds were being removed from
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys and removal of dead birds will help the state get a
better estimate of the damage done.
</P>
<P>
   Spilling oil is against the law in Washington state. Those
responsible for the spill are required to make restitution, said
Logan, the Ecology Department official.
</P>
<P>
   The state's last major oil spill occurred in 1991. A Japanese
fish processor sank after colliding with a Chinese freighter in
heavy fog. Up to 170,000 gallons of fuel were spilled.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, insurers and the owners of the processor and
freighter agreed to a $9 million settlement. That included $5.2
million for damage to natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   An advance team from the Ecology Department was in Coos Bay
Tuesday to learn about the vessel and to study how effective
cleanup efforts area.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the advance team will soon have to apply in Washington
what they learned remains an open question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early for us to know what the oil is going to do,''
said Robert Pavia, an oceanographer with the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Where the oil will go will depend on how much oil leaks and how
fast it is released, as well as on tide, wind and wave conditions,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ecology Department officials were preparing for a
landfall in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The hope Tuesday was that the flow of the Columbia, bolstered by
heavy rains, will push the oil out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   That may mean the oil would miss Willapa Bay and perhaps come
ashore around Westport and Ocean Shores, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
