<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KARACHI-CRIME (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Murderous and macabre,
Karachi is a patch quilt of robust commerce and urban detritus,
where for nearly a decade, two predatory political factions with
terrorist elements have fought each other and, very often, the
police and the army. Karachi has slipped back and forth between
times of deadly mayhem and brutal crackdowns, and now is a period
of crackdown. Much of Pakistan, not just Karachi, suffers from
lawlessness. While the get-tough tactics of Pakistan's Prime
Minister, Nawaz Sharif, may combat crime, it is commonly believed
that he also wants tighter control over his economically troubled
country at a time when his popularity has plummeted. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VA-GUN-SWEEP (Richmond, Va.) _ Authorities here contend that a
new program, backed by the NRA, to enforce gun laws already on the
books has helped drop the rate of homicides by firearms in Richmond
last year by 36 percent, to 78 from 122 in 1997. The program has
proved so successful that other cities, including Phildelphia and
Rochester, N.Y., have implemented versions of it, and a dozen more
cities are considering it. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR _ The Justice Department has decided to begin an
inquiry to determine whether Kenneth Starr's prosecutors misled
Attorney General Janet Reno about possible conflicts of interest
when they obtained permission to investigate the Lewinsky matter in
January 1998, government officials said on Tuesday. Exclusive. By
David Johnston and Don Vann Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS _ They are not deliberating: The senators are
jockeying for post-impeachment politics. That is evident on the
closed session and censure situations, and in the arguments they
make. A news analysis by Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAXES _ The plan for a 10 percent income tax cut that is
supported by leading House Republicans is running into trouble
within the party. And the balance of voting in the chamber is
delicate enough that an alternative proposal may be viable with the
support of only a small number of the party's moderate wing. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-RECRUIT _ The Air Force, facing a shortage of recruits,
for the first time joins the other services in paying for
television ads to attract new recruits. The Air Force's shortage
shows how widespread the recruiting problem has become for the
Pentagon. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB (San Francisco) _ There are many brand-name banks and
brokerage houses battling on the front-lines of American investing.
But only one, Charles Schwab, has made peace with the Internet.
Schwab, the quarter-century-old discount broker that has long cast
itself as a Wall Street outsider, has quickly come to dominate the
booming business of trading stocks online. It now handles almost a
third of all Internet trading _ meaning that one in 20 stock trades
in America now pass through the Schwab system. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on Schwab's average commission, Internet
trades and net income has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   USA-LYCOS-ASSESS (Undated) _ A closer look at the agreement by
USA Networks, the media company headed by Barry Diller, to buy
Lycos, the Internet portal, and combine it with USA's home
shopping, ticketing and online businesses. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   SURGE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Seeking to bolster the ``urge'' in
Surge, the Coca-Cola Co. is revamping its advertising and marketing
approaches for the fledgling soft-drink brand. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   GABELLI-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ After scaling back his annual
pay and agreeing to give his public shareholders first crack at his
best investment ideas, famed stock picker Mario J. Gabelli hopes to
finally bring his $16.3 billion asset management company public
this week. The deal is being watched as an indicator of investor
appetite for asset-management companies, as other private firms
weigh their own offerings. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-VAUDEVILLE (New York) _ On one level, they were simply
black men and women, sometimes wearing burnt-cork makeup, who spoke
in dialect and told jokes, danced and sang about life's ups and
downs. On another level, the language and the routines of black
vaudevillians reflected an era in which most Americans considered
blacks inferior and black entertainers used their separate sphere
to escape the pain or create other meanings for their lives. The
ghosts of that time, representing the place where history,
sociology and entertainment meet, have been resurrected in an Off
Broadway musical about the last days of black vaudeville, ``Rollin'
on the T.O.B.A.'' By Felicia R. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FILM (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: On the movie ``Asterix and
Obelix Against Caesar,'' or France fights Hollywood. By Alan
Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd says it's time to say
goodbye to Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich comments on the end of
Monica-gate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Olympics. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-CHEFS (New York) _ In the '80s, when women refused to
yield any corner of the work world to men, they began to make their
mark even in the competitive and brutal restaurant kitchens of New
York. Through persistence and sacrifice, skill and irrepressible
desire, an advance guard of women became stars on what was fast
becoming one of New York's most glamorous and visible stages. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CASSOULET (Undated) _ It is the perfect union of meat and bean
and as humble as bread. And it is quite possibly the most filling
dish ever created by man. But when cassoulet, a slow-cooked country
stew of plump beans, broth and various succulent meats, is right,
it can be one of the most memorable, most satisfying dishes in the
world. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-SPOON (Paris) _ ``What is that?'' asked the Frenchman at
the next table, eyeing the dish before me. ``Macaroni and cheese,''
I replied in fluent English. ``An American classic.'' We were
lunching, not together, at Spoon Food &AMP; Wine, Alain Ducasse's
newest restaurant and his third in Paris. It is billed as an
international restaurant and, indeed, features Asian, Indian, Latin
American and Italian dishes, with a touch of British cooking, such
as it is, and, for local xenophobes, even a few things French. But
they're the supporting cast; the stars at Spoon are American. At
least they try to be. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
