<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-NOMINATIONS-LAD     02-10 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-NOMINATIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY VOTERS LOVE `SHAKESPEARE,' `RYAN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three weeks ago, a beaming Steven Spielberg was
holding two Golden Globe statues won for directing and producing
his acclaimed World War II drama ``Saving Private Ryan.'' When
asked whether the awards, which often foreshadow the eventual
Academy Award winners, meant that he would cruise through the
Oscars with victory assured, Spielberg laughed nervously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be crazy to think that,'' Spielberg said. ``If
anything, this makes me (italics) more (end italics) nervous. You
just don't know how voters are going to think.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was certain Tuesday when nominations for the 71st
Academy Awards were announced. When the dust settled, it was
Miramax's festive costume romp, ``Shakespeare in Love,'' not
``Saving Private Ryan,'' leading the way. ``Shakespeare'' scored 13
nominations to 11 for ``Private Ryan.'' The three other best
picture nominees racked up nominations in bunches as well.
``Elizabeth,'' ``The Thin Red Line'' and ``Life Is Beautiful'' each
had seven nods.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it was a good day for war movies and Elizabethan
period pieces and a great day for Roberto Benigni, nominated for
writing, directing and starring in his touching Holocaust fable,
``Life Is Beautiful.'' Benigni is only the fourth person to be
honored for a single film in the actor, director and original
screenplay categories. The others: Orson Welles (``Citizen Kane''),
Woody Allen (``Annie Hall'') and Warren Beatty (``Heaven Can
Wait,'' ``Reds'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that I were a bluebird so that I could fly to
everyone's window and thank them,'' Benigni said. ``I'm
overjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty could have scored the hat trick again for ``Bulworth,''
but came away with only one nomination for original screenplay.
Perhaps for that reason, he was a little more subdued than Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at least maybe now Rupert Murdoch will see my goddamned
movie,'' Beatty said. Murdoch owns 20th Century Fox, which produced
``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Benigni in the best actor category are two-time winner
Tom Hanks (``Saving Private Ryan''), art-house favorites Ian
McKellen (``Gods and Monsters'') and Nick Nolte (``Affliction''),
and surprise nominee Edward Norton (``American History X'').
Notably absent: Golden Globe winners Jim Carrey and Michael Caine
and ``Shakespeare's'' Shakespeare, Joseph Fiennes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's very encouraging is to see Edward Norton's
nomination,'' McKellen said. ``He said to me I was the reason he
became an actor. I hope I'm the reason he doesn't win an Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolte, meanwhile, was happy to see his low-budget movie
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a small picture, $6-million-budget picture to gather
this much attention,'' said Nolte, who was also nominated in 1991
for ``Prince of Tides.'' ``One doesn't anticipate that. You make
those kinds of films for the sake of making them. You can't really
lose money on them, but it's just the love of filmmaking. It makes
it very special in that sense.''
</P>
<P>
   For best actress, nominations went to two Elizabethan women
(Gwyneth Paltrow for ``Shakespeare in Love'' and Cate Blanchett for
``Elizabeth''), two women struggling with illnesses (Meryl Streep,
``One True Thing''; Emily Watson, ``Hilary and Jackie'') and
Brazilian actress Fernanda Montenegro for ``Central Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Streep has now been nominated 11 times, tying her with Jack
Nicholson and leaving her one away from record-holder Katharine
Hepburn. Blanchett, Montenegro and Paltrow are all first-time
nominees. Watson was nominated in 1996 for ``Breaking the Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet a director friend of mine in Australia that I'd have to
buy her a pair of Rollerblades if we got seven nominations, and now
we have,'' Blanchett said. ``I'd better get moving.''
</P>
<P>
   In other categories, James Coburn (``Affliction''), Robert
Duvall (``A Civil Action''), Ed Harris (``The Truman Show''),
Geoffrey Rush (``Shakespeare in Love'') and Billy Bob Thornton (``A
Simple Plan'') were nominated for supporting actor; Kathy Bates
(``Primary Colors''), Brenda Blethyn (``Little Voice''), Judi Dench
(``Shakespeare in Love''), Rachel Griffiths (``Hilary and Jackie'')
and Lynn Redgrave (``Gods and Monsters'') were the choices for
supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine was the fifth name read, and I have to tell you I was
getting a little nervous,'' Redgrave said. ``But they read it, and
that's the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others in the movie industry would second that emotion
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 0120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
