<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWENSEN-VIOLINIST-2TA     02-10 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWENSEN-VIOLINIST-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO THE PODIUM BORN: A TRUE BELIEVER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By K. ROBERT SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a young violinist, Joseph Swensen had a rapidly blossoming
international career. He was retained by top management, ICM
Artists, which booked him for some 100 events a season. He had an
exclusive contract with a major label, BMG/RCA, which produced six
compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   He had studied with the world's most revered violin pedagogue,
Dorothy DeLay, at the Juilliard School, and had a blistering
technique second to none. He also had something infinitely more
precious: a restless, probing, highly personal musicianship.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991, at 31, Swensen did something shocking if not
downright heretical. He abandoned the violin and announced that he
would accept engagements only as a conductor. Eight years later,
violin cognoscenti still shake their heads at mention of his name,
whether in sadness, admiration or disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen has paid a heavy price for his independence. He no
longer has personal management or an exclusive recording contract,
and he has become nearly invisible in his native America. Based in
Copenhagen, he commutes to Edinburgh, where, since 1996, he has was
been principal conductor of the Scottish Chamber Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Now making their first American tour, Swensen and the orchestra
perform on Saturday at the Aaron Copland School of Music, of Queens
College, and on Sunday at Town Hall. Finally, New Yorkers will be
able to judge for themselves the wisdom of Swensen's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Many an instrumentalist has taken up conducting after
establishing a reputation as a soloist: Daniel Barenboim, Vladimir
Ashkenazy, Pinchas Zukerman and Mstislav Rostropovich, to name a
few. But most have pursued the two careers in tandem rather than
sacrificing the first.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen adamantly rejected that path, insisting that a complete
break with the past was necessary to underscore the gravity of his
decision. ``I didn't think I could be the conductor I wanted to be
if I also had to practice the violin every day,'' Swensen said
recently from Atlanta, where the Scottish Chamber Orchestra was
beginning its tour.
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Emanuel Ax, who used to perform chamber music with
Swensen, remembers a more compelling reason. ``He felt that he
would not be taken seriously as a conductor if he continued to play
the violin,'' Ax said. ``He didn't want people to treat his
conducting as a sidelight, something he would do in addition to
violin playing. Rightly or wrongly, he felt that the only way to
overcome this was to say, `Look, I am no longer a violinist.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Swensen may have been right. But even those who admire his
courage are saddened by what they consider an enormous loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strictly selfish point of view, I was upset, because I
was robbed of my favorite violinist colleague,'' said Carter Brey,
the principal cellist of the New York Philharmonic. ``What made him
such a special artist was his originality of style. Joey wasn't
about technique. His technique was so deeply integrated into his
music-making that only other string players were aware of what he
was accomplishing. Playing with Joey was like a drug, and I miss
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What few of Swensen's colleagues knew was that since the age of
9, he had harbored a desire to conduct. Advised by his father, a
clarinetist, to master an instrument first, Swensen unwittingly
backed into a major career as a violinist. He waited patiently
until the time was right to make the switch, but in the end he had
to act quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important factors in deciding to do it when I
did,'' he said, ``was that I was afraid the career as a violinist
was getting too big, and I would not have the courage to throw it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Swensen, born in New York in 1960 to Norwegian and Japanese
parents, began playing the violin at 5. At 10, he was accepted as a
DeLay pupil in the preparatory division of the Juilliard School. A
year earlier, he had initiated a private ritual: he would lock
himself in his parents' bedroom, retrieve a chopstick he had hidden
in his mother's bureau drawer, turn on the radio, stand in front of
the mirror and conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Even 10 years later, Swensen, then a Juilliard college student,
avoided mentioning his dream to most of his colleagues for fear of
ridicule. No 19-year-old violinist, especially an acknowledged
superstar of Miss DeLay's class, was likely to find support in his
effort to walk away from the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly everyone I told at Juilliard discouraged it,'' he said.
``Many people said things to the effect that I was being
treasonous, that I was somehow turning my back on my friends and
going over to the enemy. There was that sense of `us' and `them'
when it concerned conductors.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are still so angry at Swensen that they have not
spoken to him since 1991. ``The people who were most frustrated by
my decision have had no contact with me as a conductor,'' he said.
``So as far as they're concerned, I'm a useless failure who gave up
a useful violin career.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Swensen was engaged as a guest conductor with the
37-member Scottish Chamber Orchestra. Already at the first
rehearsal of Beethoven's ``Eroica'' Symphony, the players knew they
had stumbled on something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started the minute he arrived,'' said Ursula Leveaux, the
orchestra's principal bassoonist. ``It was the quality and
intensity of his vision, and his ability to communicate it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one critic reacted as if Beethoven himself had returned
from the grave. ``Back in January an unexpected bomb exploded on
the Scottish music scene,'' Michael Tumelty of The Edinburgh Herald
wrote in November 1995. ``The incendiary device was Beethoven's
`Eroica,' and the man with his finger on the trigger was a
conductor called Joseph Swensen. At the hands of Swensen, who
erupted acrobatically and volcanically, the stupendous performance
recalled the musical revolution that formed the background to the
composition itself.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, a self-governing
ensemble, agreed. ``He drew everyone out, and he got the orchestra
not only to play their best but to forget about themselves and
therefore take risks,'' Ms. Leveaux said. ``We knew that if we
wanted to grab him, we had better take another huge risk, because
if we waited a year, until he came back to conduct, we might have
lost him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of that single concert, Swensen was engaged in the
fall of 1996 as the orchestra's principal conductor, and his
three-year contract was recently renewed. By all accounts, the
honeymoon of orchestra and conductor is not yet over.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen says he is unable to describe his approach to
conducting, but he regards the profession with lofty idealism. ``A
conductor has the responsibility to go deeply into a piece of
music, and by doing so, also to go deeply into the core of one's
soul,'' he said. ``The marriage of those two elements creates a
third thing that is new, original, authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Swensen the conductor have in common with Swensen the
violinist? ``Joseph's style is extreme physical engagement,'' Ms.
Leveaux said. ``As a violinist, he expressed himself so much
through physical movement, and he continues to do that. He has a
very clear stick technique, and he communicates rhythm with the
whole of his body. He makes eye contact with everybody, so he gets
the best out of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Leveaux has detected a new maturity, a new poise, in
Swensen's approach of late. ``The element of fire and brimstone
allowed him to draw the orchestra out of itself, which unleashed
huge reserves of energy that had to be be contained,'' she said.
``In this new phase he's finding more colors, more variety of
sound. He's focusing the energy so it doesn't escape in all
directions. A new sense of space in the music seems to have
surfaced in the past few months.''
</P>
<P>
   So why has Swensen the conductor been so slow to reveal his
extraordinary talents to American audiences?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, I've barely appeared in the United States at all as
a conductor,'' he said. ``I married a Danish woman and live in
Copenhagen and have a young son, and I have a deep commitment to
the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, which takes most of my musical
energy. Having said that, I think American orchestras present a
challenge that so far I haven't been able to rise to.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, it seems, is psychological, not physical. When
Swensen conducts in America, he feels surrounded by invisible yet
implacable foes: the same colleagues who were angered by his
decision and have never forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they're there or not,'' he said, ``I feel the presence
of my former colleagues, who saw me as having gone over to the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees this tour as a turning point. In his own mind, he knows
that despite the loss of fame and fortune, his change of career was
inevitable, and he has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stopped accepting violin engagements, I had one week of
work as a conductor in my date book,'' he said. ``So I'm far beyond
my expectations. I conduct primarily because I feel as if I was
born to do that, and so I can only say I'm grateful to have done as
much as I have. One of my dreams would be to have a relationship
with a big symphony orchestra in a major city in America, where the
trust level would be as it is with the Scottish Chamber Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had turned out to be a terrible conductor, I might have
felt I made a foolish decision, but so far it hasn't developed that
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
