<HEADER>
A8714 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-CLASSICAL-CDs     02-10 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CLASSICAL-CDs-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEED THE CD GLUT? AN ODD CURE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE B. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back when the LP still reigned, long before the classical CD
glut, a new recording of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony or
Tchaikovsky's ``Pathetique'' would inevitably draw some critic's
weary sigh, ``Do we really need another one?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as CD bins groan _ and the browser's mind reels _ with
choices beyond number, a new wave of mainstream classical CDs from
England washes on these shores. And the old refrain echoes: do we
really need this?
</P>
<P>
   Not to milk the suspense, the answer in this refreshing case is
yes. Well, mostly yes. At hand is a boxful of budget-price CDs
offering a potpourri (or is it a hodgepodge?) of composers and
works, all performed by the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra of London
with various conductors.
</P>
<P>
   While rhyme may not be evident, the reason is fairly solid: many
first-rate performances, handsomely recorded, at the irresistible
price of $6 per disk.
</P>
<P>
   The first batch of releases, on the Intersound label, includes
60 disks, most of them recorded in the mid-1990s and none ever sold
previously in the United States. Another 120 disks are scheduled
for release by midyear.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of Intersound's multifarious project, I focused
on 30 releases chosen through a quasi-scientific scheme of whim,
hunch and curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   As I made my way through the heap, I separated the auditioned
disks into three piles: those distinctive at any price; those quite
acceptable and representative of the work, and those that might
serve as pocket-size Frisbees. Surprisingly, more than half
measured up to the blue-chip competition, and several others did
the music justice. I'm holding five disks back for the first warm
day of spring.
</P>
<P>
   The long roster of conductors involved somewhat mirrors the
extensive cast of characters who hold official leadership positions
with the Royal Philharmonic. Founded in 1946 by Thomas Beecham, the
orchestra today lists eight conductors in one formal capacity or
another, starting with Yehudi Menuhin as president and associate
conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin appears in these recordings, but the orchestra's music
director, Vladimir Ashkenazy, and its principal conductor, Yuri
Temirkanov, do not.
</P>
<P>
   Although most American record collectors are probably familiar
with the Royal Philharmonic, this concentration of releases may
afford a new appreciation of an ensemble that has tended to dwell
in the shadow of the London Symphony and the Philharmonia. The
Royal Philharmonic generally displays a thoroughly musical
temperament; its strings are pliant and its winds almost liquid in
their blend.
</P>
<P>
   And at its best, which is heard consistently under the baton of
the Russian conductor Yuri Simonov, the Royal Philharmonic plays
with a collective sense of rhythm as finely tuned as its pitch.
Simonov, a former music director of the Bolshoi Opera, leads
several distinguished performances, including a sinuous and
colorful account of Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring,'' coupled with a
dynamically charged ``Firebird'' Suite (Intersound 2829).
</P>
<P>
   In elegantly cast suites from Tchaikovsky's ``Nutcracker'' and
``Swan Lake'' (2812), Simonov uses more elastic rhythms to set off
opulent textures.
</P>
<P>
   A listener might well assume that a Russian also presides over
the Royal Philharmonic's darkly poetic reading of Rachmaninoff's
Second Symphony (2822). But in fact the baton belongs to Vernon
Handley, one of the orchestra's four associate conductors.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly less captivating is Handley's treatment of a spate of
Wagner favorites (2808). Speaking of rhythm: it is wonderful to
hear ``The Ride of the Valkyries'' lifted above hurdy-gurdy
mechanics to the pulse and urgency of human passion.
</P>
<P>
   As for heart, adaptability and sheer musical elan, the Royal
Philharmonic's grand old maestro, Menuhin, brings the insight of a
lifetime to two radically different works that nonetheless share a
profound humanity: Elgar's ``Enigma'' Variations (2833) and
Tchaikovsky's ``Pathetique'' Symphony (2811). In both, Menuhin
elicits subtextures (and even subtexts) where one often hears only
harmonic underpinnings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If there is one area in which Intersound's $6 bargain becomes
problematic, it is in the core repertory of Austro-German
Classicism. Performances of Beethoven and Brahms, with various
conductors, range from benign to benumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ermler's lugubrious treatment of Beethoven's ``Pastoral''
Symphony (2801) leaves one wishing to come back when rehearsals are
farther along and the band is ready to play at tempo. And James
Judd's meandering Brahms Second Symphony (2850) gives routine a bad
name.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing predictable or cloudy about Jane Glover's
excursions into Haydn and Mozart. Her pairing of Haydn's ``Clock''
and ``Drum Roll'' Symphonies (2849) exudes the vibrancy, wit and
finesse that made the English mad for the composer two centuries
ago.
</P>
<P>
   And at these prices, Ms. Glover's Mozart is a gift, pure and
simple. Her wondrous Symphony No. 40, driving but somehow lighter
than air, is only topped by a ``Jupiter'' Symphony that begins with
splendorous pomp and ends in a hair-raising contrapuntal blaze
(2804).
</P>
<P>
   On grander canvases, Charles Mackerras, the Royal Philharmonic's
principal guest conductor, leads two impressive performances: a
Shostakovich Fifth Symphony (2837) that seems to take energy from
the conductor's very restraint and a Berlioz ``Symphonie
Fantastique'' (2831) that shimmers with stylish decadence. These
disks also share the luxury of first-class sound. In each case,
Intersound's bargain-basement price only masks the value of an
exceptional CD.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another supersonic disk, Dvorak's ``New World'' Symphony
conducted by Paavo Jarvi (2810), inspires a bit of deja vu. Jarvi
engages Dvorak's dance rhythms and long-lined melodies with the
same affinity that helped make the reputation of his father, Neeme
Jarvi, a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   And like Jarvi pere, the younger conductor has a knack for
delineating tunes beneath the music's surface. This
well-constructed, eloquently played ``New World'' is a compelling
reminder of why collectors-at-heart will always welcome one more.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, a disk of Vaughan Williams' most popular pieces
might seem as redundant as that Dvorak symphony. But a Vaughan
Williams program conducted by Christopher Seaman (2836) is an
exceptional compendium, both in its completeness _ ``The Lark
Ascending,'' the ``Tallis'' and ``Greensleeves'' Fantasias and
other works _ and in its idiomatic flair. Talk about empathy!
Britain's National Orchestra, as the Royal Philharmonic styles
itself, wears Vaughan Williams on its sleeve (not necessarily
green).
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on standard repertory in this first batch of
recordings extends to the concerto. And here the musical results
are spotty. Performances of the Tchaikovsky Violin Concerto by Zino
Vinnikov (2832) and the Mendelssohn Violin Concerto by Leland Chen
(2823) both suffer from a lack of vision and, for that matter, a
lack of brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   More successful is a pairing of Mozart's Piano Concertos Nos. 21
and 23 by Ronan O'Hora, whose silvery tone serves the vitality and
songfulness shared by the two works (2843).
</P>
<P>
   A surprise pleasure is Vivaldi's ``Four Seasons,'' with Jonathan
Carney, the Royal Philharmonic's concertmaster, as soloist and
conductor (2809). Carney's tempos are brisk; his own playing is
clean and animated, and a reduced ensemble produces clear textures
with confident style.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect also profits from Harold Lester's harpsichord
continuo, which is prominently displayed in the sound balance. As
foil to Vivaldi, Carney leads a propulsive turn through Bach's
Third ``Brandenburg'' Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Adagio from Rodrigo's ``Concierto de Aranjuez'' has
been loved nearly to death, its beauty and mystery emerge anew in
the hands of the guitarist Carlos Bonell (2820). Naturally, that
concerto is paired with the ``Fantasia Para un Gentilhombre,''
which Bonell likewise dispatches with affection and craft. A
bargain at twice the price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-ART-SONGS-2TAKE     02-10 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-ART-SONGS-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLACK ART SONG: A FORGOTTEN REPERTORY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Cori Ellison is the dramaturg at the New York City Opera and a
singer.  
 By CORI ELLISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Aristotle, and on through Newton, Baudelaire and Scriabin,
progressive thinkers have linked the aural sensation of music to
the visual sensation of color. But is the color of the composer
ever audibly discernible?
</P>
<P>
   The distinguished American mezzo-soprano Florence Quivar
explores that question Sunday afternoon, when she and the pianist
Wayne Sanders present a recital of art songs by black composers at
the 92d Street Y.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Quivar has long wished to mine the rich but
little-known lode of black American art songs, this is only the
third opportunity she has had to do so. She performed a variant of
the current program in 1997 to celebrate the centennial of her
church in Philadelphia, and later gave a similar recital in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered a program like this to an African-American school
which shall remain nameless, and I was told thanks but no thanks _
it wouldn't sell,'' Ms. Quivar said recently from her home in
southern New Jersey. ``They wanted a traditional `European'
recital.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the difficulty of getting American art songs
performed _ let alone commissioned, published, kept in print,
recorded, and embraced by critics and the public _ is not peculiar
to black music, as any American singer trying to assemble and
peddle a program of home-grown material can attest.
</P>
<P>
   But for blacks, the challenge may be greater. The phenomenal
success and influence of jazz, the blues and the many forms of
popular music sprung from them have tended to stereotype black
music and musicians in the eyes of the public _ even the black
public.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fine six-part documentary on black American artists
recently shown on PBS barely mentioned classical musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Black classical music is, like almost all American music,
``hyphenated'': a result of the fusion of old- and new-world
cultures. But as involuntary emigres, African-Americans have often
had understandably mixed feelings about both ends of the hyphen.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual, the earliest music of black Americans, was
crossbred from tangy, sinewy African melody and the foursquare
hymnody of white Protestant churches. And like many a bastard, it
was often viewed with abashed ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freed men have an unfortunate inclination to despise this
music as a vestige of slavery,'' Thomas Fenner wrote already in
1865. ``If efforts are not made for its preservation, this country
will soon have lost this wonderful music of bondage.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Reconstruction era, the spiritual, previously passed
down by oral tradition, acquired another layer, in the form of
hymnlike choral harmonies. Beginning in 1871, they were introduced
to the world by the tours of the Jubilee Singers, a small choral
group from Fisk University in Nashville, one of several schools
founded for the education of former slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Spirituals then entered the solo singer's repertory through
Harry T. Burleigh's moving arrangements for voice and piano. Though
remembered chiefly for these, Burleigh yearned to make a mark in
mainstream vocal literature.
</P>
<P>
   His mentor, Antonin Dvorak urged him to draw inspiration from
black folk sources, but Burleigh's 300-odd art songs are closer in
form and spirit to the parlor ballads of white contemporaries like
Horatio Parker and Edward MacDowell, as Ms. Quivar will demonstrate
when she sings two of Burleigh's succinct, lyrical ``Saracen
Songs'' of 1914.
</P>
<P>
   If Dvorak was a mentor, Samuel Coleridge-Taylor, the
Afro-British composer and conductor, was a role model.
Coleridge-Taylor took a lively interest in black American culture,
which culminated in three extended visits to the United States
between 1904 and his death in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time, he gave of his sympathy, advice and help,'' Wendell
Whalum, a musicologist, wrote in 1977. ``Each time, he left young
Negroes with new hope and broader vision.'' Black pride
notwithstanding, Coleridge-Taylor's ``Sorrow Songs,'' which Ms.
Quivar will excerpt, mirror the perfumed lilt of Christina
Rossetti's Pre-Raphaelite verses.
</P>
<P>
   During the first few decades of this century, the blacks who had
begun to gain access to American and European mainstream
conservatories and universities were ready to reclaim their musical
heritage and synthesize it with their new skills and perspectives,
exercising what W.E.B. Du Bois, a spark plug of the Harlem
Renaissance of the 1920s and 30s, termed ``dual consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifted composers including Edward Boatner, Margaret Bonds,
William Dawson, Nathaniel Dett, Hall Johnson, Camille Nickerson,
Florence Price and John Work expanded the art-song repertory, yet
most of them are known for their arrangements of spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first black American to etch a profile predominantly in
classical music was William Grant Still. Having attended Oberlin
Conservatory and later studied with the conservative George
Whitefield Chadwick and the avant-gardist Edgard Varese, Still
aimed for a happy medium: in his words, ``to elevate Negro musical
idioms to a position of dignity and effectiveness in the field of
symphonic and operatic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Still was long obliged to earn his living in popular music,
serving as an arranger for Artie Shaw, Ethel Waters and Sophie
Tucker, playing the blues with W.C. Handy and tossing off film
scores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, a Guggenheim Fellowship finally allowed him to focus on
classical music. His large and diverse catalog holds seven operas
(including ``Troubled Island,'' the first opera by a black American
to have been performed by a major company); symphonies (including
the landmark ``Afro-American Symphony,'' of 1931), and choral,
band, chamber and keyboard music, but only a handful of songs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quivar will present several items from Still's ``Songs of
Separation,'' a 1949 cycle of five songs about separated lovers, on
texts by black poets. These sophisticated, vaguely impressionist,
mildly dissonant miniatures belong to what the musicologist Aldrich
Adkins, in his 1971 study ``The Development of the Black Art
Song,'' calls Song Period II, from 1934 to 1949.
</P>
<P>
   During these years black composers often based their songs on
the poetry of black Americans, and they felt less constrained to
please white composition teachers and freer to plumb their African
roots, using syncopation, blue notes and the pentatonic scale.
</P>
<P>
   The simmering civil rights movement sparked Song Period III,
which extended the innovations of the second period into atonal,
polytonal and polyrhythmic realms, as well as incorporating jazz
and blues idioms. Songs by composers including Ulysses Kay, Julia
Perry, John Carter and Betty Jackson King sometimes made use of
nontraditional accompaniment like percussion and electronic tape.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Edwards' ``Ballad of Birmingham'' is a particularly powerful
example from this period, underlaying traditional strophic
structure with spiky harmony and swelling drama to achieve a
visceral impact reminiscent of Ives' ``General William Booth.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights movement of the 1960s and the American
bicentennial celebrations of the 70s spurred serious consideration
of black classical music. The pioneering musicologist
Dominique-Rene de Lerma and his Black Music Center, then based at
Indiana University, sponsored conferences and performances from
1969 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Patterson, a singing teacher, edited a groundbreaking
anthology of black art songs in 1977. More recently, adventurous
vocalists have issued modest but fascinating recordings of this
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But the lion's share of this literature still languishes
unpublished or out of print and unrecorded. Ms. Quivar and Sanders
began their unscientific search for material by raiding the music
cabinet of Benjamin Matthews, a baritone who is the artistic
director of Opera Ebony in New York and has been collecting black
American art songs for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started reading through things and saw what hit our
spirits,'' Sanders said. They supplemented what they found there
with songs pulled from their own collections, sent by colleagues or
drawn from the archives of the Schomburg Center in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``A program like this is just the tip of the iceberg,'' Sanders
said. ``There's a wealth of material out there. I've been at it for
a while, but I'm still just on the fringes. We'd love to perform
and record as much of it as possible. It's our obligation but also
a great joy. I really believe it's a question of accessibility. All
we need to do is get these songs off the closet shelf and do them
as simply and honestly as we can, and their quality will speak for
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
