<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-INDIE-CRED-$ADV1     02-10 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-INDIE-CRED-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT JAZZ COULD USE ABOUT NOW: `INDIE CRED'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for JAZZ-LABELS-MERGER)  
 (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, two of the seven recording imprints that make up
the major-label jazz industry _ Verve and Impulse! _ merged. They
came together under the umbrella of the Verve Music Group, a
subsidiary of the new, expanded Universal Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   (They will still be kept separate as labels, but they will be
presided over by the same marketing and sales department and
general manager.) Aside from the lost jobs, it's a sure thing that
plenty of artists will be dropped from the rosters.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer major-label jazz records coming out, and many great
musicians without contracts, it's now or never for for the
independent label to become an important force in jazz again. Much
of the jazz canon came out on independent labels: Blue Note was one
until the mid-70s; Riverside recorded Thelonious Monk's best
groups; Prestige put out as much fresh John Coltrane and Miles
Davis music as could be pried from their horns.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if there's a paucity of independent labels in jazz.
But few of them mean much. What they're lacking is summed up by the
term ``indie cred.'' Used in rock since 1985 or so, it refers to an
unhyped credibility based on unpredictability, on the thrill of new
music that is not formulaic.
</P>
<P>
   To consumers, indie music at its best alters old forms and
creates new modes of listening; it carries a buzz that comes from
meaning rather than from advertising. It's time for independent
labels in jazz to get radical _ to flout convention, to put care
where big labels worry about bottom-line and to produce labors of
love that create excitement and further careers.
</P>
<P>
   The new indie jazz needn't be brattily oppositional to the
mainstream. It should, however, suggest the river of potential in
jazz's future.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few smart ideas from 1998's jazz records that indie
labels could take and run with. Some are actually small records on
major-labels, but indies have always scavenged ideas wherever they
can find them. With more ideas like the following, jazz could have
its own form of indie cred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUND On Sex Mob's ``Din of Inequity'' (Columbia/Knitting
Factory). For its debut, an eclectic jazz quartet hired as engineer
and mixer Scott Harding, most of whose credits had been on hip-hop
records by groups like the Wu-Tang Clan and Gravediggaz. It was an
inspired move. Hip-hop is all about sound enhancements that you can
feel, smell, taste, whereas in jazz, engineers seem afraid of the
idea that there could be anything to jazz records beyond the
musicianship in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Din of Inequity'' has a thoroughly different character than
most jazz records: it leaps out at you, with a shockingly hot
sound. The trumpet solos crackle like the sound of ripping
newspapers; the drums are crisp cracks, not muffled thuds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHIC DESIGN On Dave Douglas' ``Charms of the Night Sky''
(Winter and Winter) and Tim Berne/Michael Formanek's ``Ornery
People'' (Screwgun). Stephen Byram's CD cover designs used to adorn
all the releases on the now-defunct JMT label; he's now the house
designer for Winter and Winter and Screwgun. For Screwgun, his
designs are arch: in a riot of type and ink drawings, he slips
baking recipes in among the recording credits.
</P>
<P>
   For Winter and Winter his impulses are more subdued: he makes
colored, corrugated-cardboard boxes with an attractive paper image
stuck to the front. Compare this to the design on most indie-jazz
labels, which tend to adorn their releases with high-school
yearbooklike color photographs of the band, usually dressed in ugly
sweaters. (The current lack of wardrobe-style among jazz musicians,
though, is a whole other issue.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VERITE-STYLE RECORDING On the Jacky Terrasson Trio's ``Alive''
(Blue Note). It's too simple: indies should approach artists with
good working bands and offer to record them live and loose. In
jazz, performance is the coin of the realm, but live jazz records
still haven't reached their potential; too often they're just
studio albums that happen to have an audience. At a club, young
jazz groups like Terrasson's experiment with their rhythm section,
their pacing, their form. Shouldn't that be captured on the fly and
hustled quickly into the public's hands? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL-SCENE DOCUMENTATION On ``Los Hombres Calientes'' (Basin
Street). There's often something special going on in regional
scenes; Basin Street records nascent New Orleans groups, like this
one, a Latin-jazz band that includes the drummer Jason Marsalis,
the trumpeter Irvin Mayfield and two singer-percussionists. After
all the genuine buzz three years ago about the jazz scene at
Smalls, in New York's West Village, one wonders why there are still
so few independent-label records that capture those bands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXPANSION OF JAZZ PALETTE On ``Brian Blade Fellowship'' (Blue
Note). A drummer-led album, it's anchored by strong rhythms. But
its overall textures are from the ambitious side of 1970s Los
Angeles pop, halfway to film-soundtrack music: steel guitar,
electric guitar and two saxophones create large, pretty chords that
slide into each other. As it happened, the album came out on a
major; but jazz with such a new sense of form could have been the
high-priority project of an indie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LABEL CROSSOVER On Chicago Underground Duo, ``12 (DEG) of
Freedom'' (Thrill Jockey). The indie-rock scene has reached a dry
point, so more small rock labels ought to take a chance on jazz, as
this one did; their approach to recording the music, and the
meaning of their imprimatur to an entirely different group of
listeners, could rejuvenate jazz's constituency. Young people put
their money where the excitement is; they don't care what it's
called.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
