<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8723 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINYL-RECORDS-ANTIQUE     02-10 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINYL-RECORDS-ANTIQUES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS BEGIN TO RISE FROM THE VINYL UNDERGROUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLETCHER ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, a market in vintage records has quietly flourished
among a small but dedicated group of collectors. They buy and sell
through an informal network of used-record stores, mail-order
houses, magazines and, more recently, Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it the vinyl underground. Of late, however, even the
auction houses have begun to take notice. A few years ago, a New
York house put a collection on the block, but the sale, by all
accounts, was a disappointment because many of the offerings were
overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   But with rare albums now commanding as much as five figures, the
William Doyle Galleries in New York are betting that the time is
right. On Tuesday, Doyle will hold what it's billing as
``Rockin'/Rhythm-and-Blues: The Fine Vinyl Auction,'' the sale of a
collection of some 50,000 45s, LPs, CDs and memorabilia that span
the history of post-war popular music, from rockabilly and early
rhythm to rock, country, jazz and blues.
</P>
<P>
   It was amassed by Thomas Margellar Jr., a little-known
Detroit-area disk jockey. The biggest prize is a 45 of Elvis
Presley's first recording, ``That's All Right, Mama,'' still in its
original Sun label paper sleeve (estimate, $3,000 to $5,000). The
collection also includes hits like ``Walkin' in the Rain'' by the
Ronettes ($150-$250) and ``Lucille'' by the Shantons ($700), along
with rarities from Buddy Holly, the Beatles and the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers see the sale as an opportunity for records to
cross an important commercial threshold: from the domain of the
hobbyist to that of the high-powered collector, much as baseball
cards and comic books have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It elevates records into a different level of collectible,''
said Greg Loescher, editor of Goldmine, the biweekly magazine that
is considered a bible among collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the collection and its owner is the stuff of
rock-and-roll legend. Margellar, who was known professionally as
Tom Knight, devoted much of his life to building the collection. In
June 1997, Margellar, 47, was killed in the basement of his
suburban home in Brighton Township during an argument with his
wife, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Robert Bulger, intervened to help his sister,
hitting Margellar with a crowbar. Bulger and his sister later
admitted that they had cleaned up the blood stains from the carpet
and walls and dumped Margellar's body along a gravel road near his
home. Both pleaded no contest to charges: he to second-degree
murder and she to being an accessory after the fact. Both are
serving prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Ashleigh, a Doyle representative responsible for
spotting potential consignments in the Midwest, learned of the
collection when she read an account of the killing in The Detroit
Free Press. After gaining permission to inspect the collection, she
drove out to Margellar's home, a ``nondescript ranch-style house,''
as she put it, that was ``in the middle of absolutely nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   She was astounded by what she found inside. Margellar kept his
collection in a 20-by 34-foot climate-controlled space in the
basement. The records were arranged alphabetically by artist on
shelves, stacked floor to ceiling. ``Everything was documented,''
Ms. Ashleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle acquired the collection from Margellar's parents, Thomas
and Estelle. (Doyle declined to say how much it paid.) Their son
had died without a will, and they gained possession of the
collection as a result of a wrongful-death suit against his widow.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Doyle shipped the collection, which weighed 21,000
pounds, to its headquarters on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. It
also hired Chester Prudhomme, of Port Townsend, Wash., an appraiser
with 25 years of experience, to assess the collection.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the Doyle gallery expecting to spend five days
inventorying the collection. But, he said, working with six Doyle
employees, it took eight 11-hour days to go through the boxes that
filled ``a very large room'' on the fourth floor of the gallery.
The first thing he pulled out was a 45 with two hits by Norman Fox
and the Rob Roys, ``Dream Girl'' and ``Pizza Pie'' (estimated
price, $600).
</P>
<P>
   The collection was so chockablock with gems, he said, that it
got to a point where pulling out a handful of $100 records ``didn't
even impress me.'' Many of the records were in such pristine
condition that it was clear that they had never been played.
Prudhomme said that Margellar had apparently bought records ``by
the bushel'' simply to put them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more an archivist than a collector,'' Prudhomme said.
He put the value of the collection at $1.2 million, four times the
estimate of the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle is pleased by the presale buzz generated by the
collection. Tara Ann Finley, the director of collectibles at Doyle,
said she had received numerous requests for catalogues and other
information about the sale, much of it coming from those she hoped
to reach: newcomers to the auction process. Many inquiries, she
said, were from record collectors who wanted to know how to sell
their own collections.
</P>
<P>
   Prudhomme, however, offers a different perspective on the
changing marketplace. He noted that while he was appraising the
Margellar collection, another copy of Elvis's' ``That's All Right,
Mama'' sold in California for $17,820. Perhaps records, ``dare I
say it, are becoming an investment category,'' he said. Prudhomme
foresees the day when collectors will keep valuable records in safe
deposit boxes alongside their stocks and bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
