A8747 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-COACH-TURNED-PROD     02-10 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-COACH-TURNED-PRODUCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GYMNAST SUCCESSFUL AS PRODUCER, COACH IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD TIJERINA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Meet Sean Hamilton, the man behind the scenes.
Behind the on-air presence of KXAS/Channel 5 sports anchor Scott
Murray. Behind the high-flying acrobatics of Aaron Jackson, one of
the best high school gymnasts in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Murray goes on the air and every time Jackson soars
into it, Hamilton has played a part.
</P>
<P>
   But you never see him.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a former gymnast at L.D. Bell High School, is used to
playing the role of the Invisible Man.
</P>
<P>
   As a gymnast, he was part of one Blue Raiders state
championship, but was not the star. As a coach, he was instrumental
in the early development in Jackson _ now one of the state's top
all-around gymnasts at Trinity High School _ but does not share any
of the glory.
</P>
<P>
   And as executive sports producer for Channel 5, Hamilton helps
make the calls on what you see and hear on air. Except you're
seeing and hearing the high-profile Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton even remains largely unnoticed in the world of high
school gymnastics. He judges various events throughout the state,
including the Texas high school state tournament, but is usually
another suit and tie with a scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has perfected the art of invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get all the accolades that someone in the public
eye would get,'' Murray said. ``There are pros and cons to that.
But I can't give him enough credit for what he does. If you have a
good producer, it speaks volumes as to how your product will come
across to the viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys training camp? Hamilton was there. The Super Bowl?
Hamilton was there. For the past two years, he has been behind the
scenes at most of the important sports events in the Fort
Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Channel 5 from WFAA/Channel 8, where he was a
producer of ``Good Morning Texas''. But before Channel 8, he was an
intern for Murray at Channel 5. And when the opening came up for an
executive sports producer, Murray called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask for anybody better,'' Murray said. ``He brings
to the job great knowledge, great creativity, great consistency,
great credibility and great continuity, but most importantly, he's
honest and he's real.''
</P>
<P>
   But being honest and real doesn't make it any easier when you
are dealing with professional athletes, Hamilton said. They are a
far cry from the occasional media interview requests you get when
you are a high school gymnast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing about this job now is probably dealing with
the athletes that don't want to be dealt with,'' Hamilton said.
``You've got Dallas Cowboys who you do specials on and you want to
do a one-on-one interview with Deion Sanders, and he limits you.
You go to Rangers spring training and try to talk to John
Wetteland, and he won't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports has dominated Hamilton's life. His father, Terry
Hamilton, was a high school coach in Lewisville, Andrews and
Mineral Wells. His uncle was a sportswriter. And at Bell, Hamilton
was an important role player for Raiders gymnastics teams in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Those teams were led by state champions such as Shaun Bonavita,
Jim Endres and Chris Keller. But Hamilton was there, too, competing
in floor exercise, vault and pommel horse.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was part of Bell teams that made it to state in 1985,
1986 and 1987. He competed at state his final two years.
</P>
<P>
   At Bell, he was not the star, but he shined anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a great star, but he was a great worker and he
contributed and did everything he was asked to do,'' said former
Bell coach Emil Milan, now the executive director of the Texas High
School Coaches Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of kids on your team, and some of them have
that right attitude that helps the others who need to improve their
attitudes. Sean was just a good influence.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Hamilton's influence that Jackson remembers. As a skinny
sixth-grader, Jackson's only interest in gymnastics came from
watching his older brother _ future state all-around champion Micah
Jackson _ compete. But one day, Hamilton approached him and gauged
his interest in picking up the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a former coach in the Hurst-Euless-Bedford gymnastics
feeder program, also worked with other gymnasts, future Bell and
Trinity stars such as Chip Zahn, Brett Isbell and Marc Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me the basics, and then some, to pretty much every
event,'' Jackson said. ``He's one of the reasons why I stuck with
it and why I learned so much. It's important to start a gymnast off
with the right attitude and right skills, so you can build on those
skills you learn. He did a great job of giving me the foundation to
go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years after he met up with Jackson, Jackson can do it all.
</P>
<P>
   And it all started with Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching is something I really do miss,'' he said. ``It's fun
seeing the kids progress. It makes you feel a part of their
success. The D/FW area is such a mecca for high school gymnastics.
To me, gymnastics was not only about the individuals. It was the
team. It teaches you discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   The days as a Bell gymnast are far behind him, but his days in
high school gymnastics have not faded. This past weekend, he was at
it again, judging at an area optionals meet, making gymnasts
breathlessly wait for his score just as he once did.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Tijerina writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 685-3871. E-mail:
tijerina(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 0207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
