<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVASION-CRASH-2takes     02-10 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVASION-CRASH-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE SEEK KIDNAP MOTIVE, SUSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Phillip W. Brown contributed to this story.) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN, PHIL DAVIS AND STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An ordinary errand _ a nighttime run to get
diapers for his baby _ ended tragically for Chris Rawlings, with a
vicious abduction that left police Tuesday searching for clues.
</P>
<P>
   The former Crespi High School football star lay in critical
condition with serious head injuries, a day after two men snatched
him from the garage of his Woodland Hills home, stuffed him into
his Bentley's trunk and led police on a wild, 100-mph chase that
ended in a fiery crash in suburban Tarzana.
</P>
<P>
   The crash Monday knocked out power over a 20-block area as
police searched unsuccessfully for the two men.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police puzzled over whether the attack was merely a
robbery or whether he was targeted for personal, business or other
reasons. Also unclear is whether the attack was timed to occur on
his 30th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know,'' said Los Angeles Police Department
spokesman Lt. Anthony Alba. ``We just hope that we can get a break
in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives were investigating whether the attackers followed
Rawlings from a supermarket where he had gone on an errand or lay
in wait at the home that he and his wife, Barbie, 26, were leasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know, because there's so many things,'' said
Detective Andrew Purdy, who is heading the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One avenue of investigation is whether the attack is tied to an
attempted robbery of a home not far from the Rawlings' and some 45
minutes before the abduction, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The prowlers tried to gain entrance, but failed and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suspect they are related,'' said Officer David Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   If the motive for the attack was a residential robbery, it would
be among several hundred that occur every year in the San Fernando
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Police widened their manhunt Tuesday for the two men, one of
whom escaped into the Tarzana neighborhood and another who
carjacked a car, later abandoning it on a freeway near suburban
Sylmar. Because the men were masked, police are unable to provide a
description of the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and business partners described Rawlings as
successful, hard-driven and focused on money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very successful. He's a hustler. Money's his gig. He's
into making it,'' said Roland Winkler, who lives next door to
Rawlings' parents in Chatsworth. Rawlings frequently visits his
parents and has lived there on and off, Winkler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is definitely an intense guy. He's alive. He's got
plans,'' Winkler added. ``He's a flashy kind of guy. Not a lot of
people in Woodland Hills drive Bentleys. It's a Bel-Air car, not a
Valley car.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the Rawlingses began leasing a home in
suburban Woodland Hills, which, according to property records, is
2,845 square feet and was valued at $514,000 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings, who police said is not related to the Rawlings
sporting goods company family, is part owner of the Gentlemen's
Quarter's, a Woodland Hills clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   He also works for Amazon Leasing, where he conducts seminars and
sets up and sells software, said John Perrin, Amazon's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fabulous individual. He's a wonderful dad. We're really
all devastated,'' Perrin said. He added that Rawlings has leased
several cars from Amazon and refers customers.
</P>
<P>
   Perrin added that Rawlings graduated from college, having
attended on an athletic scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a silver and gold medalist in track,'' Perrin said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Rawlings made a living through auto leasing
and the stock market, Alba said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 Daily News retrospective story on the 1986
championship Crespi football team, Rawlings was listed as a
financial adviser for the gaming industry.
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred as Rawlings returned home from the
supermarket, where he had gone to pick up diapers and other items.
</P>
<P>
   After he pulled into the garage and the automatic door closed
behind him, two men carrying at least one gun assaulted Rawlings,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering why her husband was taking so long to enter the home,
Rawlings' wife opened the inner door that connects the garage to
the home and saw her husband being beaten, said Sgt. Gregory Hoyte
of the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   She shut the door, locked it and led their children upstairs,
where she called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Officers in the neighborhood spotted the white Bentley pulling
away from the house and began to chase the $250,000 luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   Police pursued the Bentley east on the Ventura Freeway, reaching
speeds of 100 mph before the gunmen exited at Tampa Avenue and
drove north, Alba said. The turbocharged Bentley often outdistanced
the patrol cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just had incredible acceleration,'' Alba said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the driver lost control, hit a blue 1995 Chevrolet
Cavalier and then knocked down a power pole, coming to rest on a
tree near Califa Street, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk of the car flew open, spilling groceries, baby food _
and apparently Rawlings, Alba said. The Bentley then burst into
flames.
</P>
<P>
   Police initially thought a deep puncture wound to Rawlings'
temple was a gunshot, but later decided the wound was caused by the
crash, Alba said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The men fled on foot, and one carjacked a 1981 white Mazda RX-7
minutes later on Wilbur Avenue, police said. The Mazda owner,
identified as an attorney, was not injured, Alba said. This vehicle
was found abandoned on the Foothill Freeway at Maclay Avenue. The
victims in the Cavalier suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   At the all-boys Crespi Carmelite Catholic High School in Encino,
Rawlings was remembered as a popular, affable and dedicated
student. He specialized in the 100-meter dash and wore No. 28 as a
defensive back for their championship football team.
</P>
<P>
   Former Crespi football linebacker Chad Santander, 29, now a
mortgage broker in the Bay Area, said Rawlings was widely popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got great grades and was seen as an overachiever at the
time. He wasn't really into the partying scene. Just a real
responsible guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Quirici, who taught Rawlings in his morality and social
justice classes, remembered Rawlings as ``very intense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked very hard at what he wanted to achieve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches remember him for making a pivotal play in the 1986
California Interscholastic Federation-Southern Section football
playoffs, in which Crespi won a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris was one of the leaders,'' Quirici said. ``He had
tremendous athletic aggressiveness, but was self-disciplined. He
was very committed to what he believed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it meant his life, he would give it up for his family,'' he
said. ``He never dropped the ball when he was responsible for
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
