<HEADLINE>
K-SWISS SHARES GAIN FOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ Despite the carnage on Wall Street on
Tuesday, K-Swiss Inc. escaped the ax that befell many stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of the Westlake Village-based shoemaker shot up $7.875
to $42.50 for a 23 percent gain on volume of 530,000 shares, more
than 12 times the 30-day average of 43,000 shares per day.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were impressed by a strong earnings report, issued
after the market closed Monday, and a subsequent upgrade by analyst
Margaret M. Mager at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. to ``trading buy'' from
``market outperform'' with a 12-month target price of $50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   K-Swiss' fourth-quarter earnings per share came in at 65 cents,
beating a Wall Street consensus estimate of 54cents. The company
attributed its sterling quarter to strong domestic sales that
offset some weakness in international markets.
</P>
<P>
   K-Swiss also disclosed in Monday's announcement a 2-for-1 stock
split effective on March 26 and a 50 percent increase in its
quarterly cash dividend payable April 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
