<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESERVES GET EXTENDED TIME AS SONICS CRUISE TO 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When games start piling up faster than days off, the
Sonics will need to rely on their reserves to make sure the
mainstays remain fresh and sharp.
</P>
<P>
   A few games like Tuesday night will come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Against a Golden State Warriors team that couldn't shoot
straight almost from the national anthem, the Sonics bolted to a
double-digit lead in the first 10 minutes and methodically expanded
the bulge into an eventual a 90-71 victory _ Seattle's third
straight to open the season _ before 17,072 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more blowouts we can get the better it will be, and
tonight was good for us,'' said guard Gary Payton, who scored a
team-high 20 points in 30 minutes. ``I hope we get more of these.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Seattle starters played in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But there wasn't much of a dropoff as the Sonic bench
contributed 42 points, four coming on a pair of impressive slam
dunks by Aaron Williams. Dale Ellis, a reserve who plays starters'
minutes, had a season-high 13 points, and Hersey Hawkins added 10.
</P>
<P>
   After two difficult wins to begin the tardy season, Sonic coach
Paul Westphal was able to substitute freely, using all 14 of his
players. Everyone except rookie Jalani McCoy scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really looking for a chance to get those young guys into
the game,'' Westphal said of Vladamir Stepania (two points), James
Cotton (one point), Rashard Lewis (four points) and McCoy. ``With
the shortened preseason and no summer leagues, we're kind of going
blind with what we have. I liked what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Don MacLean also got his first minutes of the season,
scoring four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The reserves) held the lead and might even have built on
it,'' Westphal said. ``It didn't get crazy out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics built a 23-point lead in the first half and led by 21
at the break before the Warriors chipped away and sliced the gap to
13 points at 62-49 before Seattle regained control.
</P>
<P>
   An appropriate promotion occurred between the first and second
quarters when a blindfolded fan attempted to make a basket from the
free throw line and in the paint. He resembled a Warrior in missing
all 10 of his ``shots.''
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable display of inaccuracy, even for this early in
the season, the Warriors didn't score until the game was nearly
four minutes old and ended the quarter with as many turnovers as
points. Golden State shot 21.4 percent (3-for-14) to fall behind
23-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible start,'' Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo said.
``We weren't sharp early, got some `touch' fouls and got some
people in foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors became tentative, never became assertive and fell
to 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and did what we wanted to do,'' Sonic forward Vin
Baker said. ``We played good defense and limited them to one
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And a majority of them missed.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State shot 35.2 percent (25-for-71) from the field and
had 20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense and rebounding are going to be the keys for the whole
season,'' said Olden Polynice, who had nine rebounds. ``If we can
play the Sonic defense that we know we can play and keep teams off
the boards, we're always going to have chances to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all games will be against the at-times inept
Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   But the next one is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think it's going to be easy (Wednesday night in Oakland)
because we rested our starters a little bit or because we had a big
win (Tuesday), we'll go down there and get beat,'' Westphal said.
``So it's good, but at the same time it doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year Warrior guard John Starks didn't leave the arena
waving a white flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get back in there and fight again,'' he said. ``We
as a team have to be ready. The starting unit has to come out and
set the tone of how the game is going to be played. The last two
games we haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks led the Warriors with 12 points and also got plenty of
rest.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that went wrong for the Sonics was free
throw shooting. Baker, for instance, continued his free throw woes,
missing four more Tuesday to extend his consecutive misses to 10
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Sonics were 20-for-35 from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to shoot free throws better than we are,'' Westphal
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
