<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON-ADS-SFCHRON &LR;      02-10 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM AGREES TO CALL DISCLOSE PAYMENTS FOR PLACEMENT
OF  BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JAMIE BECKETT and JON SWARTZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Responding to allegations that it charges book
publishers for recommendations on its Web site, online bookseller
Amazon.com Tuesday offered customers full refunds for any book it
had touted, and promised to begin disclosing when it has received a
fee for prominent placement of a book.
<P>
   ``We heard from our customers,'' said Bill Curry, spokesman for
Seattle-based Amazon.com, the largest online bookseller and one of
the most successful Internet companies of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Monday that Amazon had stepped up
its sale to booksellers of promotional packages, costing up to
$10,000. A package might include prime placement on a particular
page, inclusion in the ``What We're Reading'' feature, an author
profile or interview and ``complete Amazon.com editorial review
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said, ``Such promotions do not contain any notice or
visual clue to indicate that publishers have backed the
recommendations with advertising dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry would not comment on the Times story. But Amazon said in a
press release that ``its recommendations are not and never have
been for sale to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The company did acknowledge that publishers can pay for prime
placement. And beginning March 1, it will list which featured
placements are paid for and which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Effective immediately, Amazon also said it would ``widen'' its
book-return policy. ``Customers can return any book Amazon.com has
recommended, even after it has been read.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon chief executive Jeff Bezos added, ``It doesn't matter how
dog-eared or worn it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Payments for prime placement of products is common in
bookstores, supermarkets and other ``bricks and mortar'' retailers.
But, as Amazon.com learned, the rules are different on the Web,
where editorial content such as book or product reviews is
interspersed with, and often indistinguishable from, paid
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's expectations are different online,'' said Julie
Wainwright, chief executive officer of movie retailer Reel.com,
which does not publish any paid editorial content. ``The problem
(for Amazon.com) is that they tried to appear more pure than they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Ron Rappaport of Zona Research Inc. in Redwood City,
Calif., said the Amazon affair ``casts a slight smudge on
e-commerce. Consumers already have a stigma about shopping online
because of concerns over privacy. An admission from the leading
e-commerce company that it has misled them is a hit for e-commerce.
This isn't fastbuck.com that stacked the deck; it's Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon had revenues of $610 million last year and expects more
than a billion this year. It has 6 million customers around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Internet observers said the Amazon situation illustrates how
consumers should be aware when they visit any Web site that the
lines between advertising and editorial content are not always
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be a clear distinction between what is content
and what is not. Right now there isn't,'' said Susan Scott,
executive director of TRUSTe, a nonprofit Internet privacy group in
Palo Alto, Calif. ``Consumers should be aware what on a Web site
has been paid for and what hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott criticized Amazon.com's refund offer as a ``Band-Aid,''
saying that few consumers would bother to return books or recall
which books they had purchased based on a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the line between advertising and editorial will
become clearer as consumers get more sophisticated and e-commerce
matures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers aren't stupid, especially book lovers,'' said Peggy
O'Neill, an Internet analyst at Dataquest, a San Jose, Calif.,
research firm. ``They will jump on you if they figure out you're
shilling for publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said she expects that other Web retailers will be forced
to follow Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo and Excite, the two leading Internet guide companies, said
that advertisers cannot pay for higher placement of Web sites
listed under search results. But they do sell ad space in specific
areas under sponsorship arrangements. Charles Schwab, for instance,
is one of the sponsors of Excite's Money &AMP; Investing section.
</P>
<P>
   GoTo.com, a Pasadena, Calif.-based Internet search engine, does
charge companies to have their Web sites listed in search results.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company's pay-for-placement system only lists Web
sites that pay a fee. Those that pay the most get the highest
billing. The Web site promotes itself as ``the only search engine
where you can actually determine your placement within the search
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com stock, a high-flyer, fell $9.13 to $100 per share
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
