 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 420 - February 10, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 420 -- Feb. 10, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. AND ANOTHER THING FROM DAVID HARE British playwright David
Hare loves an argument and so, it seems, does Broadway, which will
have imported four of his plays within a single year. By Sarah
Lyall. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (3,000 words)
+ edited article available. 2. 'ER'S' GEORGE CLOONEY ANSWERS HIS
FINAL CALL Dr. Ross is about to make his final regular appearance
on ``ER.'' David Kronke takes a retrospective look at George
Clooney's years on the series, what it was that made him so popular
with audiences, what comes next for the departing star and what the
future holds for ``ER.'' By David Kronke. From TV Guide Canada.
1,300 words + photo. 3. MEN ARE FROM MARS, ELIZABETH HURLEY IS FROM
VENUS Elizabeth Hurley is a one-woman conglomerate: actress, model,
producer and also a stunningly beautiful woman who, with longtime
companion Hugh Grant, is a prime target for paparazzi all over the
world. Hurley talks about her next movie, the comedy ``My Favourite
Martian,'' her cameo role in ``Austin Powers 2,'' how her
relationship with Grant has survived his 1995 arrest for soliciting
a prostitute and why it's hard for an actress to be simultaneously
beautiful and funny. By Jeanne Wolf and Shep Morgan. 1,400 words +
photo. 4. MOMENTS OF THE HEART : THE STORIES BEHIND HOLLYWOOD'S
FAVOURITE LOVE SCENES Not all of the movies' most celebrated love
scenes were all that romantic, at least to the stars who made them.
Here are some behind-the-scenes stories. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
AN IGLESIAS FOR THE NEXT GENERATION When you're the son of singer
Julio Iglesias, it's only natural that you might take advantage of
the industry doors that open to you. But young Latin superstar and
heartthrob Enrique Iglesias, 24, first applied to record companies
under an anonymous name, refusing to use his dad's influence. Once
he had a contract he didn't tell Julio until four months later,
typical of his desire to do things on his own. By Steve Morse. From
The Boston Globe. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. RENEE FLEMING READY TO FLY SOLO Renee Fleming shines as the
brightest soprano star in opera today. In this interview she talks
about her life and career - she creates a glamorous image on stage,
but is streetwise about her singing. By Richard Dyer. From The
Boston Globe. 1,700 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
JOHN BOORMAN IN COMMAND For more than 25 years, John Boorman has
been an Englishman in Ireland, residing and raising a family in
County Wicklow. The director-writer has used the countryside around
the former Georgian rectory that he calls home for such far-flung
movie backdrops as the illusionary utopia in the science fiction
film ``Zardoz,'' (1974) and Camelot in ``Excalibur,'' (1981.) For
his new film, ``The General,'' Boorman employs these locations to
play, finally, Ireland in the 1980s and early '90s. ``Belonging to
the European Union has made a huge difference for Ireland,'' he
says. He cites two other developments as having radically changed
the nation: ``The Catholic Church has lost its grip on the country.
And a huge amount of political corruption has come to light.
There's a revolution taking place.'' By Betsy Sherman. BPI. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
IRAN THROUGH THE EYES OF CHILDREN It has been argued that
filmmakers in Iran often tell stories through the eyes of a child
in order to get around the Islamic regime's strict censorship code.
Whatever the motive, Iran has produced films about children that
share a delightful down-to-earth quality and a refreshing attention
to the moral weight of the decisions made in everyday life. In
``Children of Heaven,'' Majid Majidi's film about a poor Tehran
family, the emotionally charged object is a pair of pink shoes. By
Betsy Sherman. BPI. 1,200 words + photo. 9. ``LAST DAYS'' REVISTS
THE HOLOCAUST Steven Spielberg's Survivors of the Shoah Visual
History Foundation is releasing its first feature-length Holocaust
documentary, ``The Last Days.'' The powerful 90-minute film takes
five Hungarian-Jewish survivors back to Europe for the first time
in more than 50 years to revisit their home towns. By Tamara
Conniff. BPI. 900 words + photo. Please fax to Paris
33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81
