<HEADER>
A8981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Feb. 10, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANGELA-DAVIS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Nearly three decades
after her political activism landed her in jail after a celebrated
stint on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list, Angela Davis is more
troubled than ever about the number of black and disadvantaged
Americans being swept out of circulation behind prison walls. By
CATHY WOODRUFF.
</P>
<P>
   EARL-CALDWELL (Oakland, Calif.) _ Seldom has so much happened to
one black journalist as Earl Caldwell has experienced in his
career. Caldwell, writer-in-residence at the Robert C. Maynard
Institute for Journalism Education in Oakland, will share his and
other black journalists' stories about the early days of newspaper
integration in serial narratives that will run on the Maynard
Institute Web site. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-TEACHER (San Francisco) _ As parents, teachers and
students continued their impassioned push to have a popular school
principal reinstated, new details emerged over the anti-Semitic
remarks she allegedly made. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-OBIT (San Francisco) _ With the death of Reggie
Williams, San Francisco has lost another hero of the AIDS epidemic
_ a gay African American man who was former head of the National
Task Force on AIDS Prevention. Mr. Williams, 47, succumbed to
complications of the virus Sunday in Amsterdam, where he had lived
for the last five years. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COOKBOOKS (Undated) _ The bold, brassy flavors of the American
West and Southwest, and the pleasures of Mexican food team up to
dominate a trio of new cookbook. So, if you hunger for the likes of
roasted corn soup, sopa seca, tenderloin alambre and ensalada con
camarones, pull up a chair and start studying. By WILLIAM M. DOWD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-X-FILES (Undated) _ At the very end of watching the upcoming
``The X-Files'' episode in my office, I took off my headphones and
began to yell, ``Holy --!'' An immediate cry went up from a
co-worker: ``DON'T TELL US!'' Don't worry about it, I won't. But
for fans who have followed this Byzantine show for almost six
seasons, this is the moment you've been waiting for: answers, and
Mulder's vindication. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT-RESPONSE (San Francisco) _ Several thousand people
have flooded The San Francisco Examiner with letters, faxes and
e-mails about impeachment in recent months. The response represents
the largest volume of correspondence to The Examiner on any news
story in at least a decade, and editors at major newspapers across
the country say they, too, are hearing from huge numbers of
readers. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ All right, put down your pencils,
Republican presidential candidates, your time is up. Pass your
litmus tests to the right. I do mean right. Former Vice President
Dan Quayle, publisher Steve Forbes and ``traditional values''
activist Gary Bauer spent last week answering a 10-page take-home
questionnaire from a conservative group called the Committee to
Restore American Values. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
