<HEADER>
A8982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX     02-10 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some fine tunes to hit the road with
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I geared up for a recent road trip by
making some tapes of a few new CDs I've bought over the past few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four artists I brought along with me are from
Texas. The other one ought to be. I thought I'd pass along my
observations in case anybody's interested in listening to some good
ridin' down the road music.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Speak of The Devil,'' by Chris Isaak. Isaak, alas, is an
ex-surfer from California. He is also, I'm convinced, the
reincarnation of the late Roy Orbison, the great West Texas
rockabilly singer and songwriter. I've been in mourning since
Orbison died 10 years ago last December. Isaak is doing his best to
fill the ``My baby done left me'' void in the rockabilly genre.
</P>
<P>
   Issak sounds like a young Roy Orbison, writes nearly all his own
songs, and wears his hair slicked back. I figure women swoon over
him.
</P>
<P>
   A word of warning: Don't listen to Isaak if you're already down
in the dumps over a woman (or man, as the case may be.) You'll end
up lower than road kill after listening to songs like ``Breaking
Apart'' and ``Walk Slow.'' He's got the tearjerker down pat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' by Lucinda Williams. Williams
and my other two picks for this road trip, Robert Earl Keen and
Chris Wall, are more-or-less headquartered in Austin, Texas, though
all three tried their luck in Nashville to no avail. Tennessee's
loss is the Lone Star State's gain. Williams is a fine songwriter
whose tunes have been covered by Emmylou Harris and others. ``Sweet
Old World,'' a song on her last album about suicide, is possibly
the saddest song ever written. The latest CD continues the theme of
lost loves and sorry boyfriends who either end up in prison, jump
off bridges or drink themselves into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Nacogdoches even gets a mention in a song entitled ``Lake
Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' voice won't appeal to everyone. Think of Sheryl Crow
with a slight twang. But she sure knows how to tell a story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Walking Distance,'' by Robert Earl Keen. Keen still hasn't
made it to the big time despite an avid following among college
students that borders on idolatry. He plays around these parts
regularly, and always packs the house. His latest CD is a tad
uneven, in my view, but still contains enough strong selections to
make it worth buying. For example, ``I'll Be Here for You'' is a
sweet love song along the lines of ``I'm Coming Home,'' one of
Keen's better-known tunes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be here
</P>
<P>
   when the sky turns gray
</P>
<P>
   The sun goes blind
</P>
<P>
   and the moon won't stay
</P>
<P>
   I'll be the light to guide your way
</P>
<P>
   onto some place new
</P>
<P>
   I'll be here
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd is gone
</P>
<P>
   The last note fades
</P>
<P>
   on the very last song
</P>
<P>
   I'll be the road to take you home
</P>
<P>
   I'll be here for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen's penchant for funny, throwaway songs results in ``That
Buckin' Song,'' which will doubtless be loved by beer-swilling
college students but doesn't add much to the CD. The CD concludes
with ``Happy Holidays, Y'all,'' a sequel to ``Merry Christmas From
the Family.'' Unfortunately, like most sequels, it's not nearly as
funny as the original.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Keen's latest is well worth the price even with its weak
spots. If you ever get a chance to see him live, go for it. He puts
on a heckuva show.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finally, Chris Wall, my favorite country-rodeo singer, is back
with ``Tainted Angel.'' Wall wrote ``I Like My Women A Tad on the
Tacky Side.'' He went to Nashville and never got discovered, and it
hacked him off. He now bears a grudge against pony-tailed
heartthrob Billy Ray Cyrus that borders on the hilarious, since it
keeps showing up in his songs. He's also the only country singer
and writer I know that quotes Shakespeare and uses the Pythagorean
theorem in his lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   This selection contains such gems as ``Gimme Half of What Killed
Elvis'' and ``I Never Really Got Over Losing You.'' It's good road
music.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up one or more of the above and head on down the road. It's
good to get out of town every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel, Nacogdoches, Texas. E-mail: gborders(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
