<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN11-CO     02-10 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American partners, waiting to dance
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ `I, too, sing America,'' wrote poet
Langston Hughes. For black people, this cry expresses a profound
hunger, a need to assert the important truth that despite the
limits that laws and institutionalized bias impose, black people
helped make this country great.
</P>
<P>
   That premise sums up the purpose of Black History Month, a
celebration made necessary because our unique experience of racial
slavery in this country has predisposed many of us to hate
ourselves, and many of our fellow countrymen to deny our worth as
citizens. The tendency is to judge all of us by the least of us and
to declare our greatest achievers separate and apart from the rest
of us. If we applied that perspective to all ethnic groups, none
would escape hanging.
</P>
<P>
   This month, newspapers are recounting local black history.
Schools and colleges are putting on celebratory programs and art
exhibits. Magazines contain ads that herald the accomplishments of
black people and articles disclosing facts of black history unknown
to me though I have been a zealous student and minored in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   No longer can any of us say that we don't know black American
history because we were not taught that part of the record in
school. All that's required to complete our education is a desire
to fill in the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Most commendable for this purpose are the many presentations on
the black experience offered by WXEL, the Boynton Beach public
television station.
</P>
<P>
   A must-see is Africans in America. First shown last fall, this
four-part PBS series, covering the period from Jamestown in 1607 to
the Civil War in 1861, will air for 90 minutes every Friday night
this month.
</P>
<P>
   This documentary informs us that many slaves labored unceasingly
to purchase their own freedom, becoming landowners and planters,
until this possibility was outlawed. Unlike white indentured
servants, indentured black people ultimately were denied freedom,
and their bondage was extended to their children. Many benevolent
masters, in gratitude for service rendered, would have set
individual slaves free, but state laws required them to pay a
prohibitive emancipation tax.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's WXEL-FM has a centennial-year tribute to Duke
Ellington on Feb. 15. Remembering Slavery, on Feb. 21 and
broadcasts the recorded voices of slaves complemented with dramatic
readings of slave monologues by noted actors. The arts have magic
to prove universal human worth.
</P>
<P>
   That thought came to me the other night at the Rinker Playhouse
of the Kravis Center, as I witnessed the extraordinary dance of
Koffi Koko, an internationally acclaimed African dancer from the
Gulf of Benin. In his ritual dance for ancestors, symbolized by the
ashes of a loved one presumed to be in an earthenware urn, he
performed with a disciplined fluidity. In the second movement, Mr.
Koko, painted white from head to toe, became Everyman _ and Woman.
Through dance, he lived out the passage from birth to death,
transforming himself from vibrant youth to decrepit age with total
control. The sufficiency inherent in one's own humanity was also
symbolized in the music, created with drums, sticks, bowls, even
the musicians' own bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the audience, I was enthralled. I also became
aware that, at some point in my education, I was taught to devalue
all art indigenous to my African roots _ except when African
artistic expression is incorporated in the artistic works of other
cultures, such as in the paintings of Picasso or dance movements of
a Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   Because of conscious or unconscious prejudice, most Americans
share my plight. This destructive blight on the intellect and the
spirit can be cured by a dose of uncensored American history. To
grow beyond our prejudices, we must drink it down. In our current
state of ignorance, we are unlikely to ever sing America, together,
in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
