<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Names grace Bubbaland's brash statues
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last week, I asked y'all to submit names for the
trio of classical-looking statues who are holding a bowl on their
shoulders. The winning entry came from Patricia Scott of San
Leanna, in south Travis County, Texas. She played on the angle that
these synthetic goons are out there next to the highway with no
pants on.
</P>
<P>
   The bald-headed statues are on top of a 69-foot-tall tower at
the theater, which is scheduled to open Feb. 26. It's lucky we're
having a mild winter, or these guys would be covered with
unattractive goosebumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked at that and saw they didn't have anything on and
thought, `Wow, the perfect South Austin thing,' because every
convenience store you walk into, that's what (the sign) says,''
Scott explained of her choice to name the trio.
</P>
<P>
   I call this work in its entirety the Colossus of Roads (Rhodes _
get it?), since it is big and sits next to a major road.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant aspect of this artwork is that it's lit up
at night. So it's like the Statue of Liberty, since you can see it
from a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   It's the new town greeter. Shoot, pilots going and coming from
the new airport are bound to use it as a landmark.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be long before fraternity boys climb up on this
monstrosity and paint mustaches on these cats.
</P>
<P>
   I received about 70 suggestions for names for these statues.
Some were what you'd expect _ Moe, Larry and Curly; Huey, Dewey and
Louie, that kind of stuff. But not all the suggestions were
intellectual. Artly Snuff, of South Austin, suggested calling the
statues Owah, Taygoo and Siam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember this Boy Scout initiation chant?'' Snuff wrote.
``When you say all three words together, it sounds like: `Oh! What
a goose I am!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Snuff pointed out that the statues fill an artistic void because
of a shortage of statuary in South Austin. Sadly, most of the
statues south of the river are private yard works, such as ceramic
toads.
</P>
<P>
   ``North of the river, there are plenty of statues of people,
mostly around the state Capitol building and the University of
Texas,'' Snuff wrote. ``How many statues are there in South Austin?
I can only think of Stevie Ray Vaughan and these GBHF (great big
honking fiberglass) guys. ... South Austin seems to be
statue-impaired. Is this a problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other name suggestions I received:
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, Stills and Nash; The Counts of Bubba Cristo; Stud, Buck
and Jake; Bo Diddley, Diddley Squat and Don't Know Diddley; Dick,
Jane and Spot; The Burghers of Bubbaland; Shadrach, Meshach and
Abednego; Hoss, Bubba and Tex; Hear No Evil, See No Evil and Speak
No Evil; and Manny, Moe and Jack, the guys who make up the logo for
the Pep Boys auto parts chain.
</P>
<P>
   I thought one offshoot of the Pep Boys logo was more original,
however, since it lends a Cajun twist to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Austin attorney Carter White suggested calling the fiberglass
works Manni, Meaux and Jacques. And now I'm out of here because I
can't stand no Meaux of this.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears in the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
