<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Affirming inequality: U.S. Supreme Court needs to hear appeals
on race-based admissions
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Texans know how Boston schools officials felt when
a federal appeals court ruled that a race-based admissions policy
at America's oldest public secondary school was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in Louisiana, Mississippi and California also
understand the bind many Boston citizens found themselves in after
the 1st Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Nov. 19 against Boston Latin
School's affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   Boston school officials should have appealed the federal appeals
court ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court. They nearly did.
Unfortunately, they were talked out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Boston school officials first swore they would appeal the
adverse ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court. Boston school board
members so voted.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according the Associated Press, school officials began to
hear from representatives of the NAACP and other civil rights
groups who pleaded for the board to rescind its decision to appeal
the ruling against the celebrated school's affirmative action
program.
</P>
<P>
   Boston school officials now have done a full about face. They
voted unanimously to not pursue an appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country would have to live with the decision,''
Superintendent Thomas Payzant told the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legal Defense fund of the NAACP certainly was very strong
in their encouragement of us not to appeal, as were a number of
civil rights organizations,'' said another school official.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fight to maintain their affirmative action program,
Boston school officials accepted the arguments that a Supreme Court
ruling against Boston Latin School's admission policy could shut
down all race-based affirmative action programs throughout the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi are disappointed
with the Boston decision to back out on an appeal to the Supreme
Court. That's because the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck
down a race-based admission policy once used by the University of
Texas Law School to increase black and Hispanic enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   From a Texas point of view, that ruling meant that my alma mater
and all other Texas colleges and universities suddenly had to
compete for minority students under a court-ordered handicap not
imposed on the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi come under the 5th Circuit
Court ruling. California colleges come under a self-imposed ruling
due to the referendum approval of Proposition 209, an
anti-affirmative action proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Latin School and the colleges in four states now are
struggling to enroll minority students who are attracted to schools
that maintain race-based policies for admission, scholarships and
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Supreme Court hears an appeal of a race-based
affirmative action program, different parts of America will have to
play by different rules, which is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is a diverse state and it needs to have that diversity
represented on its college campuses, in its work force and in its
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights officials responsible for getting Boston school
officials to drop their appeal probably are right about a Supreme
Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the justices rejected hearing a challenge to
Proposition 209 that prohibits discrimination in state programs
based on ``race, sex, color, ethnicity or national origin.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that language tracks the language in the Civil Rights Act,
which tracks the Constitution, it is likely that policies that
offer preferences based on race or gender will be ruled
unconstitutional discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to something as fundamentally important as pursing
racial and gender diversity, all of America should play by the same
set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
