<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE     02-10 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: King Hussein died of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Isn't that what
Jackie Kennedy died of? And is there a Hodgkin's lymphoma?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis did indeed die of non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma. Other well-known victims of the disease have included
Shah Mohammed Riza Pahlevi of Iran, former Democratic Sen. Paul
Tsongas of Massachusetts, former CIA Director William Casey and
Hungarian Prime Minister Jozsef Antall.
</P>
<P>
   Lymphomas are cancers of the lymphatic system. There's a
Hodgkin's disease, named after Thomas Hodgkin of London, who first
described it in 1832. And there are a number of other forms,
grouped under the umbrella name of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
Hussein's cancer was believed to be the most common type of the
latter group, known as B cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. While many
people with lymphoma live for decades, others _ such as King
Hussein _ develop highly aggressive forms and succumb quickly. He
died less than eight months after the diagnosis was first made.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A psychologist friend told me that Dr. Laura Schlessinger's
doctorate is in nutrition, not psychology or psychotherapy. Is that
true?
</P>
<P>
   A: She earned a doctorate in physiology at Columbia University
before heading for Los Angeles, where she evolved from a talk-show
caller to a host. She also has done postgraduate work in psychology
and has had a private practice as a marriage and family counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent movie about the '60s on TV prompts the question:
When did our military draft start, and when did it stop?
</P>
<P>
   A: The draft existed well before the '60s. Conscription in this
country dates to Colonial times when the colonies drafted men to
serve in their militias during the Revolutionary War. In 1790,
Secretary of War Henry Knox and President George Washington
proposed a universal military service plan, but Congress rejected
it. During the Civil War, both the Union and the Confederacy
drafted men.
</P>
<P>
   In more recent times, the United States used a draft in 1917-18
during World War I, and the government began to draft men again in
1940, the year before the United States entered World War II. That
draft ended in 1946. The government also drafted men from 1948
through 1972 because of the country's deep involvement in world
affairs, the tensions created by the Cold War, and U.S. commitments
in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the government stopped drafting men and began accepting
only volunteers into its armed forces. A stand-by draft also was
created, but it was discontinued in 1975. In 1980, Congress passed
legislation resuming registration requirements for the draft.
Beginning in 1981, all men were required to register, but no one is
being drafted now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much is the national debt now, and is it continuing to
grow?
</P>
<P>
   A: In recent decades, the national debt has known only one
direction _ up and up and up. The debt at the end of fiscal year
1998 was estimated to be $5.544 trillion, up from $5.370 trillion
the year before. Despite payments in recent months of $145 billion
against the debt, the interest clock is ticking faster than the
payments. For fiscal 1999, which ends Sept. 30, the U.S.Treasury
estimates the debt will be $5.738 trillion; for fiscal 2000, $5.916
trillion; and for fiscal 2001, $6.079 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent news article referred to Philips Electronics as an
early marketer of the compact disc player, but was not Sony the
manufacturer that developed the compact disc player?
</P>
<P>
   A: Credit for developing and marketing the CD player can go to
both Philips and Sony, according to Famous First Facts. The players
were first sold in the United States in 1983, and were made by Sony
using technology pioneered in 1979 by Philips.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does country music singer Mel Tillis really stutter or is it
just part of his act?
</P>
<P>
   A: The stuttering is for real. Born in 1932 in Pahokee, Fla.,
Tillis contacted malaria as a 3-year-old child and the fever left
him with a chronic stutter. When he sings, however, the stutter
disappears, and in the 1970s and 1980s he recorded a number of hit
country songs, including six that reached the No. 1 spot. Tillis
lightheartedly used his speech impediment to name one of his
albums, ``M-M-Mel Live,'' and his autobiography, ``Stutterin'
Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is New York City called the Big Apple?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Big Apple has been New York's nickname since the early
1960s, but its origin is unclear, according to the Facts on File
Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins. It is known, however, that
Big Apple was used for a while in New Orleans around 1910 by jazz
musicians as a loose translation of the Spanish ``manzana
principal,'' the main ``apple orchard,'' meaning the main city
block downtown, the place where all the action is. In addition,
Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins says the Big Apple
nickname for New York possibly relates to a popular dance of the
1930s called the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I often hear or read of people, including some famous people,
receiving cancer treatments at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center in Seattle, but nothing is ever said about the center
itself. Who was Fred Hutchinson?
</P>
<P>
   A: Known among cancer researchers and doctors as ``the Hutch,''
the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center was established in 1975
by Dr. William Hutchinson and the Pacific Northwest Research
Foundation that Hutchinson started in 1960 with the help of the
federal government. The center, staffed by 2,300 scientists,
doctors, researchers and assistants, is widely known for its bone
marrow research. Many people, including famous ones such as the
late astronomer and TV personality Carl Sagon, have received bone
marrow transplants at the center.
</P>
<P>
   William Hutchinson named the center after his brother, Fred
Hutchinson, who died of lung cancer in 1964, at the age of 45. Fred
Hutchinson, as long-time baseball fans will remember, was a Major
League baseball pitcher and manager. He pitched for the Detroit
Tigers in the 1940s and 1950s, then managed the Tigers, St. Louis
Cardinals, and Cincinnati Reds, whom he piloted to the World Series
in 1961. William Hutchinson died in 1997 at age 88.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard on the radio recently that an employer can look at my
credit report if I ask for a job. That sounds like an invasion of
privacy to me? Is it true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Invasion of privacy it might be, but the Fair Credit
Reporting Act permits a potential employer to look at your credit
report. However, the employer must notify you in writing of the
intent to look at the report and get your permission in writing.
You don't have to give permission, of course, but that probably
means you won't get the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the Postal Service recorded a $550 million
surplus for the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, and it was the fourth
year in a row that it had recorded a surplus. If that is the case,
why did it increase first-class mail postage to 33 cents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Michael Miles, a Postal Service spokesman in Atlanta, said
the Postal Service receives no tax dollars and has to fund its
operations from the sale of mail service and other products. The
increased funds from higher postage will help the Postal Service
continue to invest in new facilities and equipment to boost
productivity so the agency can compete better with private delivery
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971, the Postal Service has been a semi-independent
agency with oversight by a board of governors appointed by the
president and approved by Congress. Otherwise, however, the Postal
Service operates basically as a private business.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
