federal government. The center, staffed by 2,300 scientists,
doctors, researchers and assistants, is widely known for its bone
marrow research. Many people, including famous ones such as the
late astronomer and TV personality Carl Sagon, have received bone
marrow transplants at the center.
</P>
<P>
   William Hutchinson named the center after his brother, Fred
Hutchinson, who died of lung cancer in 1964, at the age of 45. Fred
Hutchinson, as long-time baseball fans will remember, was a Major
League baseball pitcher and manager. He pitched for the Detroit
Tigers in the 1940s and 1950s, then managed the Tigers, St. Louis
Cardinals, and Cincinnati Reds, whom he piloted to the World Series
in 1961. William Hutchinson died in 1997 at age 88.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard on the radio recently that an employer can look at my
credit report if I ask for a job. That sounds like an invasion of
privacy to me? Is it true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Invasion of privacy it might be, but the Fair Credit
Reporting Act permits a potential employer to look at your credit
report. However, the employer must notify you in writing of the
intent to look at the report and get your permission in writing.
You don't have to give permission, of course, but that probably
means you won't get the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the Postal Service recorded a $550 million
surplus for the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, and it was the fourth
year in a row that it had recorded a surplus. If that is the case,
why did it increase first-class mail postage to 33 cents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Michael Miles, a Postal Service spokesman in Atlanta, said
the Postal Service receives no tax dollars and has to fund its
operations from the sale of mail service and other products. The
increased funds from higher postage will help the Postal Service
continue to invest in new facilities and equipment to boost
productivity so the agency can compete better with private delivery
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971, the Postal Service has been a semi-independent
agency with oversight by a board of governors appointed by the
president and approved by Congress. Otherwise, however, the Postal
Service operates basically as a private business.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
