<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE     02-10 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   News Questions
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: continued)
</P>
<P>
   Q: How far is the distance from Earth to the moon?
</P>
<P>
   A: The moon is a moving target. Although people generally say
the moon is a quarter-million miles (250,000 miles) away from
Earth, the distance actually varies because the moon's orbit around
Earth is not a circle but an oval, which resembles a slightly
flattened circle. At its ''perigee,'' the closest approach to
Earth, the moon is 221,456 miles away. At its ``apogee,'' the
greatest distance from Earth, the moon is 252,711 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the Euro, the new European currency, backed by gold? Were
any of the old currencies that the Euro is replacing backed by
gold? Is the U.S. dollar backed by gold?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Euro, which became the common currency of 11 European
nations on Jan. 1, is not backed by gold, says Pierce Nelson,
spokeman of the Atlanta Federal Reserve Bank. In recent years, the
old currencies of the 11 nations _ Spain, Portugal, Ireland,
Netherlands, Luxembourg, Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany
and Italy _ have not been backed by gold. The U.S. dollar, although
once tied to a gold standard, is no longer backed by gold. The
dollar and the Euro are backed by the ``faith and credit'' of the
nations they represent. For the time being, the 11 European nations
are accepting both the Euro and their old currencies as legitimate
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Congress may soon consider legislation
permitting local telephone companies to charge a toll each time the
Internet is accessed?
</P>
<P>
   A: The issue at hand here is not accessing the Internet for
information purposes, but making long-distance telephone calls over
the Internet. The Federal Communications Commission has been
studying the matter, but has yet to make final recommendations to
Congress. With regular long-distance telephone service, the
long-distance provider pays ``access'' fees to the local companies
where the call originates and terminates. So, the question to be
answered eventually is whether the providers of Internet
long-distance telephone service should also pay similar fees to
local telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the words to the honor codes at West Point and the
Naval and Air Force academies?
</P>
<P>
   A: The words to the honor code at the U.S. Military Academy at
West Point are: ``The cadet will not lie, cheat or steal nor
tolerate those who do.'' The Air Force Academy's honor code is
similar, adding only the words ``among us'' after ``those.''
</P>
<P>
   The Naval Academy has a ``honor concept'' that is longer. It
reads: ``Midshipmen are persons of integrity. They stand for that
which is right. They tell the truth and ensure that the full truth
is known. They do not lie. They embrace fairness in all actions.
They ensure that work submitted as their own is their own, and that
assistance received from any source is authorized and property
documented. They do not cheat. They respect the property of others
and ensure that others are able to benefit from the use of their
own property. They do not steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to all the Social Security money that belongs to
someone who dies before retiring?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the deceased person had no spouse or minor children, no
benefits are paid from the taxes that she or he paid while working
_ except, of course, the benefits they helped to pay other
retirees. If the deceased left a spouse or young children, benefits
may be paid to them depending on a number of factors, including
their ages.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read about William McCorkle's conviction in
Orlando on fraud charges. I sent money to him and ordered his
books. Is there someone I can contact about getting my money back?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the U.S. attorney's office in Tampa at 1-813-274-6245
for information on filing a claim for possible return of your
money, or at least part of it. McCorkle has been ordered by a
federal judge to forfeit more than $10 million to the court, but
it's uncertain how much of the amount will be collected.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkle, an infomercial con artist, and his wife were sentenced
last month to 24 years in prison each for swindling customers with
a get-rich-quick real estate scheme. McCorkle, 32, and his wife,
Chantal McCorkle, 30, were sentenced for fraud and money laundering
in the scheme that grossed about $72 million in sales of books,
videotapes and seminars that fraudulently promised to teach victims
how to make money on foreclosed real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A politician was described by the media as giving a
``stem-winding'' speech. What is the origin of that expression, and
what does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Stem-winding means strong persuasion or powerful rhetoric,
according to the New Directory of American Slang. It's assumed to
be related to the 19th century term ``stem-winder'' that meant
``something excellent,'' in turn related to the stem-winding watch,
which was considered advanced and first-rate when introduced. Older
people also may recall that early auto models that had to be
handcranked were sometimes called stem-winders.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the date that tobacco advertising on billboards is
scheduled to end?
</P>
<P>
   A: April 22 is the date the Marlboro Man and other tobacco
billboard advertising is scheduled to end. Forty-six states have
signed a $206 billion settlement with Big Tobacco. In addition to
stopping billboard advertising, tobacco companies agreed to sharply
restrict sponsorship of sporting events and to quit putting brand
names on T-shirts, caps and other similar items.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has any Super Bowl team ever played the game on its home
field?
</P>
<P>
   A: It hasn't happened yet, but Super Bowl teams have played in
their home areas, including the San Francisco 49ers who played in
Stanford Stadium in Palo Alto, Calif., in 1985, and the Los Angeles
Rams who played in the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif., in 1980. The
game is scheduled for the Georgia Dome in Atlanta next year. Who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I move to Puerto Rico, do I have to pay federal income
taxes on my retirement benefits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't pack your swimsuit yet. In its Publication 17, the
Internal Revenue Service says that ``generally if you are a U.S.
citizen and a resident of Puerto Rico, you have to file a return if
you meet the filing requirements'' for your age and income. Puerto
Rican natives normally pay a local income tax, but not federal
taxes unless they receive income from outside Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep reading and seeing references to the 21st century and
the millennium beginning with the year 2000. Is that not wrong? I
thought it began Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   A: Since our calendar began with the year 1, that means the 1st
century was year 1 through year 100 inclusive. In turn, that means
the 2nd century began with year 101, the 3rd with 201, and so until
the 21st, which begins Jan. 1, 2001. Millennium means any period of
1,000 years; for example, the year 500 to the year 1500 was a
millennium. But, in normal usage, a millennium covers the same
years as a century.
</P>
<P>
   Given our fondness for seeing special meaning in numbers (such
as lucky 7 and unlucky 13), it's not surprising that the year 2000
carries special significance. Add to this the potential problem of
the Y2K computer bug when 1999 becomes 2000, many people are
concerned about what may happen in 2000, whether or not the new
century and millennium start then.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of when the millennium really begins, you'll
never be able to stop people from celebrating Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have seen the signs on the Interstates stating it is the
Eisenhower Interstate System. I assume the Eisenhower is President
Dwight Eisenhower, but why is the system named after him?
</P>
<P>
   A: When older people think of Eisenhower, they probably remember
him as a military hero and leader of Allied forces during World War
II. But it was as President Eisenhower, in 1956, that he persuaded
Congress to pass legislation and funding that began the
construction of the Interstate highway system. In 1990, to honor
Eisenhower, Congress voted to name the system after him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I lived in Miami many years ago and don't remember anything
about South Beach. But we hear or read so much now about South
Beach. Where is South Beach in relation to Miami Beach?
</P>
<P>
   A: South Beach, which received extensive publicity during the
Super Bowl, is a ``has been'' that has made a big comeback in the
last decade or so. It is situated at the bottom _ or southern _ end
of the long series of beaches that make up greater Miami Beach.
South Beach is generally considered to be centered on Ocean Drive
south of 15th Street. From Miami, it is most easily reached by the
MacArthur Causeway, the southernmost causeway across Biscayne Bay.
</P>
<P>
   South Beach was one of the ``original'' beaches in the area that
lost its lure as new hotels and clubs were built on beaches north
of it and, by the late 1960s, it was inhabited largely by retirees
and Cuban refugees. But a recovery began in the 1980s, with the
area's old Art Deco hotels being renovated. Younger inhabitants
started moving in, which led to the construction of cafes,
boutiques, clubs and other commercial construction. The growth has
accelerated in recent years, and _ in addition to models, actors
and other ``beautiful people'' _ South Beach has become a
destination spot for tourists seeking a warm place in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am confused by the Clinton impeachment deal. I know that a
Senate conviction would remove him from office, but now they are
talking about conviction, but not removal, from office. How can
that be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since it now seems likely the Senate will vote to reject the
articles of impeachment against President Clinton, some senators
are looking for a way to punish him for his actions. A censure, or
some similar action, is not a conviction _ so therefore the
president remains in office.
</P>
<P>
   End
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
