<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD REVIEWS: `Valence Street' sets higher a standard for the
Neville Brothers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Valence Street''
</P>
<P>
   Neville Brothers
</P>
<P>
   Columbia
</P>
<P>
   If not quite an artistic rebirth, the Neville Brothers' first
album since signing with Columbia is easily their best in a decade.
Not since 1989's ``Yellow Moon'' has the New Orleans band fashioned
such an ambitiously cohesive song cycle while refusing to reduce
the brotherly collective to the Aaron Neville show. Though the
results may not satisfy either the cult of Aaron or the
groove-happy, neo-hippie contingent that the band inherited from
the Grateful Dead, the production _ by the Nevilles with Tommy Sims
_ underscores the crucial distinction between the recording studio
and the concert stage, a consideration often ignored on lesser
Neville releases.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of renewal announces itself with the album-opening
``Over Africa'' as the whip-crack dynamism of the arrangement
reinforces the oracular authority of Art Neville's baritone, while
the chorus' fraternal harmonies soar around him. A similar spirit
infuses his reading of Richard Thompson's ``Dimming of the Day,''
where Art's open-hearted phrasing is so down-home country it
recalls George Jones, yet the soulfulness of the sound is pure
gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Such performances transcend conventional categories, while
synthesizing the disparate strengths of the Nevilles. Where
youngest brother Cyril has typically served as the band's social
conscience, the romantic balladry of his ``Utterly Beloved'' shows
the softer, more supple side of his vocal range, while the closing
``Tears,'' written with saxophonist Charles, offers a full-circle
return to the spiritual/mystical roots of rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The four songs showcasing Aaron's trembling, aching falsetto
never succumb to schmaltz. Instead, the album's first single, ``A
Little Bit of Heaven,'' has enough of a liltingly rhythmic
insistence to it that the song seems very much a part of the pulse
of the album as a whole, as does a reggae transformation of ``If I
Had a Hammer.'' On Wyclef Jean's ``Mona Lisa,'' Aaron even ventures
into hip-hop territory, his warble providing effective complement
to Wyclef's streetwise drawl. Only the Cate Brothers' ``Give Me a
Reason'' reflects the sort of balladry that one might more
typically find on an Aaron Neville solo album.
</P>
<P>
   As for saxophonist Charles, his horn work effectively punctuates
the performances of the others, providing as much of an
instrumental signature as Art's keyboards, but his spotlight turn
on the title cut finds him stuck in a time-warped '70s groove.
Similarly, Art's ``Real Funk'' genre excursion might well move some
bodies in concert, yet sounds like filler on a studio recording.
Though such filler was way too prevalent on previous Neville
albums, ``Valence Street'' raises the standards and the stakes.
After almost 50 years of making music, individually and
collectively, it's something of a miracle for the brothers to sound
as fresh as the Nevilles do here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don McLeese, Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   ``How It Feels to be Something On''
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Day Real Estate
</P>
<P>
   Sub Pop
</P>
<P>
   Since its initial breakup in 1995, Seattle's mood-swinging
indie-rock outfit Sunny Day Real Estate has sort of taken over the
Flatlanders' slogan of being ``more a legend than a band.'' Many
people found out about the group after the split, when it released
its second album (self-titled) just as bassist Nate Mendel and
drummer William Goldsmith joined the Foo Fighters and singer Jeremy
Enigk began work on his freakish yet acclaimed solo debut, ``Return
of the Frog Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reformed last year minus Mendel, Sunny Day is apparently out to
further its cult-legend status rather than just lay claim to it.
The band's third album, ``How It Feels to be Something On,'' is its
most realized and fine-tuned if not gutsiest effort to date.
Brooding and biting at the same time, it features the emotional
roller coaster sound that originally made the band so likable.
There's greater attention paid to arrangements, though (check out
the ``Quadrophenia''-derived track ``The Prophet''), perhaps a
result of Enigk's work with a 21-piece orchestra on his solo album.
</P>
<P>
   This one deserves to be filed next to Radiohead more than Foo.
Enigk takes on a Roger Waters-like quality on songs such as ``Two
Promises'' and the gorgeous ``Guitar and Video Games.'' The band as
a whole, including guitarist Dan Hoerner and new bassist Jeff
Palmer, sounds like it never even took a holiday, especially on the
tight-as-sardines title track. A reunion for all the right reasons,
this installment of Sunny Day may be the one that indeed becomes
the stuff of legend.
</P>
<P>
   (Sunny Day Real Estate performs Friday at Liberty Lunch.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   ``Blaze Foley: In Tribute and Loving Memory''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   Deep South
</P>
<P>
   Coming 10 years after his murder, and some five years after this
project was started, Blaze Foley's much-deserved tribute album has
all the qualities one would hope for _ which is a lot of heart and
warmth, if not perfection. Best known as the songwriter of ``If I
Could Only Fly,'' covered by Waylon and Willie, as well as the
posthumous subject of Lucinda Williams' ``Drunken Angel,'' Foley
wrote lovin' and drinkin' songs that could melt the toughest of
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the singer-songwriters featured here were cut from the
same cloth, including Townes Van Zandt and Jubal Clark, themselves
now deceased, plus Timbuk3 (broken up) and Austin fixtures such as
Kimmie Rhodes, the Texana Dames, Mandy Mercier, Calvin Russell and
more. The disc has an unwavering old-Austin feel to it, which is as
appealing now as it was back before Foley was shot. As this tribute
points out, a piece of that Austin was lost with Blaze, but it can
be reclaimed anytime we want.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   ``I Left My Heart . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Red Garland
</P>
<P>
   32 Jazz
</P>
<P>
   The late Texas pianist Red Garland was a major force in the
evolution of modern jazz through his classic work with the
legendary Miles Davis Quintet of the '50s, but he virtually
disappeared from the scene in subsequent years as he returned home
to Dallas and maintained a low profile until his death in 1984.
Garland, however, was lured out of semiretirement in 1978 for a
recording session at San Francisco's quintessential jazz venue,
Keystone Korner, and the results stand the test of time quite
nicely on the newly reissued recording.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, frequently stepping outside his signature block chords
for a more enlightened swing approach, is ably backed by a rhythm
section of Bay Area stalwarts, drummer Eddie Moore and bassist
Chris Amberger, but it's a fellow Texan who lights the spark that
sets the session on fire. Garland leads the trio through several
straight-ahead standards, including ``Bye Bye Blackbird'' and a
bluesy rendition of Percy Mayfield's ``Please Send Me Someone To
Love'' before alto saxophonist Leo Wright, an early fixture on the
Dallas scene who became a successful European jazz emigre, joins in
the action.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, beginning with a gorgeous treatment of ``Body and
Soul,'' elevates what was previously an enjoyable live piano trio
date into something special with uniformly superlative soloing.
Garland, who backed everyone from Coleman Hawkins to John Coltrane,
exhibits his deft expertise at accompaniment while also
contributing some tasty moments of his own. The quartet bops the
blues on Milt Jackson's ``Bag's Groove'' before concluding the
session with a timeless take of ``I Left My Heart in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a barrier-breaking set by any means, but it is an
excellent and highly entertaining example of the subtle and
unpredictable synergy of live jazz, as well as a rare and valuable
addition to the Texas jazz catalog.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Point, Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
