</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, February 11, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ I geared up for a recent road trip by making
some tapes of a few new CDs I've bought over the past few months.
Three of the four artists I brought along with me are from Texas.
The other one ought to be. I thought I'd pass along my observations
in case anybody's interested in listening to some good ridin' down
the road music. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EMURRAY-COLUMN _ As more Yankees seek out the warmer climes,
these bits of wisdom sent to me offer some helpful hints for those
``not from around these parts.'' Rules for a Northerner movin'
South. (EMurray, Lufkin Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Texans know how Boston schools
officials felt when a federal appeals court ruled that a race-based
admissions policy at America's oldest public secondary school was
unconstitutional. A lot of people in Louisiana, Mississippi and
California also understand the bind many Boston citizens found
themselves in after the 1st Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Nov. 19
against Boston Latin School's affirmative action program. Boston
school officials should have appealed the federal appeals court
ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court. They nearly did. Unfortunately,
they were talked out of it. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Last week, I asked y'all to
submit names for the trio of classical-looking statues who are
holding a bowl on their shoulders. The winning entry came from
Patricia Scott of San Leanna, in south Travis County, Texas. She
played on the angle that these synthetic goons are out there next
to the highway with no pants on. The bald-headed statues are on top
of a 69-foot-tall tower at the theater, which is scheduled to open
Feb. 26. It's lucky we're having a mild winter, or these guys would
be covered with unattractive goosebumps. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ `I, too, sing
America,'' wrote poet Langston Hughes. For black people, this cry
expresses a profound hunger, a need to assert the important truth
that despite the limits that laws and institutionalized bias
impose, black people helped make this country great. That premise
sums up the purpose of Black History Month, a celebration made
necessary because our unique experience of racial slavery in this
country has predisposed many of us to hate ourselves, and many of
our fellow countrymen to deny our worth as citizens. The tendency
is to judge all of us by the least of us and to declare our
greatest achievers separate and apart from the rest of us. If we
applied that perspective to all ethnic groups, none would escape
hanging. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
