<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON-BOOKS-1STLD-WR     02-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-BOOKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM PLANS TO REVISE ITS AD PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds, fixes hed; no other changes)   (nk)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with e-mail rebukes from its customers, the online
retailer Amazon.com on Tuesday revised its new advertising policy,
pledging to disclose every time when book publishers pay to feature
titles on its electronic bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company said it was still figuring out the
mechanics of this new policy, but it will take effect March 1. In
the meantime, Amazon has expanded its book-return policy to
demonstrate its faith in its recommendations, vowing to accept
titles from dissatisfied customers ``no matter how dog-eared or
worn it is,'' in the words of the company's chief executive and
founder, Jeff Bezos.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy comes after The New York Times reported Monday
that Amazon had fashioned an ``e-merchandising'' program for book
publishers that sought advertising dollars for featured treatment
of titles in categories that range from ``What We're Reading'' to
``Destined for Greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon did not disclose the advertising fees, which ranged from
$250 to $12,500, to its customers. The bookseller contended that
its sites were not for sale because editors screened and vetted
books worthy of highlighting.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's change in policy signaled a recognition that Amazon _
with its reviews, recommendations and friendly interaction with
customers _ is a hybrid, both bookseller and electronic adviser,
somehow different from bookstore chains or supermarkets that
commonly sell shelf space for products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always listening to our customers and it was clear that
our customers had a higher expectation for us than the physical
bookselling world,'' said Bill Curry, a company spokesman, who said
that customers had sent electronic mail expressing surprise at
Amazon's advertising approach.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said that Amazon would continue to offer the advertising
program to publishers, but that it would create a system indicating
which features have been paid for. Amazon started the program last
June and then expanded its scope and prices in January, attracting
money called ``cooperative advertising allowances'' from many major
publishers including Random House, Simon &AMP; Schuster, HarperCollins,
Warner Books and Penguin Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon had offered the program to about 20 to 50 publishers, and
planned to extend the same opportunities to more publishers later
this year. The program drew a mixed response from publishers,
ranging from smaller presses that feared they would not be able to
afford to play to larger publishers who considered the promotions
equivalent to the front table space or shelf-end caps offered for
co-op advertising dollars by bookstore chains.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Random House, now owned by Bertelsmann A.G., paid
Amazon for featured treatment of Peter Jennings' best seller, ``The
Century.'' Simon &AMP; Schuster, a unit of Viacom, backed titles on
Amazon ranging from Stephen King's ``Bag of Bones'' to a seasonal
Valentine's promotion for ``Best American Erotica.''
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive category for promotion was computer books,
critical placement that resulted in significant sales increases for
IDG Books Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Laurence J. Kirshbaum, chairman of Time Warner Trade
Publishing, which includes Warner Books and Little, Brown &AMP; Co.,
called Amazon's new policy of openness ``a sensible step'' that
will only enhance the credibility of the online bookstore and
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   His own company had paid to feature more than a dozen titles,
some of which experienced significant sales increases such as Roy
Blount Jr.'s photo book of dog poetry, ``If Only You Knew How Much
I Smell You: True Portraits of Dogs'' or Tom Grace's first novel,
``Spyder Web.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kirshbaum said he did not believe that Amazon's change in
policy would have an impact on future promotions subsidized with
advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the customers will respond to the new system because
the publishers can muster very effective advertising concepts that
will appeal to them,'' he said. ``All we really want as publishers
is a chance to display our wares and this will give it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-BILLBOARDS11-CO     02-10 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BILLBOARDS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beach billboards may be coming to a vacation site near you
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Forget sweet proclamations of love. The
next message you read in the sand at dawn's first light may be
urging you to drink Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Dori, the owner of a small New Jersey ad agency, is pitching
a concept as new as beaches are old: Billboards in the sand. And
the Sunshine State is high on his list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first new medium since the Internet,'' says Dori, who
said the idea to mass produce advertisements on the beach came to
him in a dream. ``It's biodegradable advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   It works like this: A 4-foot-high cylinder wrapped in a rubber
mat and imprinted with a commercial advertisement is pulled behind
a truck that rakes the beach every morning. As the cylinder rolls,
graphics and slogans from the mat are pressed a half-inch deep into
the sand. The result is a parquet of product placement which
crumbles as soon as it's touched.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial possibilities, Dori gushes, are endless: Soft
drinks, sun tan lotion, ice cream, restaurants, movie promotions,
mile after mile of slogans, row after row of peppy mascots 12-feet
long and 4-feet wide. Forget Frank Loves Angela. Welcome to `Your
Ad Here.'
</P>
<P>
   Dori landed his first client last summer. He ran a one-month
trial hawking Skippy Peanut butter on the beaches of Seaside
Heights on the New Jersey Shore. Skippy paid Dori $25,000 for the
exposure, the town charged him about $3,000 to use the beach, and
everybody who went to the shore looking for suntan got an ad
between their toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very happy with it,'' said Michael Lyon, director of
promotions for Skippy in New jersey. ``We weren't able to measure
sales with it but were happy to be able to remind people of our
product, especially where there are a lot of families and they're
feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyon said Skippy will do it again, and this winter, patent
firmly in place, Dori has been traveling the coasts _ east and west
_ pitching his product. He says the ads drew applause from
passersby on the cliffs overlooking the San Diego shoreline. But in
Miami, where Dori show-cased the billboards during Superbowl
weekend, the city's tourism and promotions Director, Michael Aller,
said no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over-commercialism,'' he said. ``We want to keep the
beach the beach.'' Fort Lauderdale, Fla. has been more liberal with
its definitions. The city's beach advisory board voted 13-2 in
favor of letting Dori sell their sand this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would bring revenue to the city,'' said Johnny Alexander,
an advisory board member. ``I don't have a problem with it. I know
some people thought it was a bit much but with it being in the sand
I thought it was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Smith, another board member disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a horrible idea,'' he said ``People come to the
area to enjoy the natural beauty here. This won't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Before billboards in the sand start rolling out in Fort
Lauderdale, city attorneys have to determine whether they violate
an ordinance prohibiting billboards on the beach. If they get a
legal OK, the issue goes to the city commission, said Fort
Lauderdale Parks Superintendent Phil Thornburg. He said the city
will likely make a decision by May.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Dori said he expects his idea to catch on, but right
now he must sell it beach by beach. In Florida he has pitched the
product to five high-traffic hot spots. Officials in Volusia
County, Fla., who oversee Daytona Beach, heard about the wash-away
billboards through word-of-mouth and are considering the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a commercial beach and we have a lot of promotions so
this might work here,'' said Joe Wooden, Deputy Chief of Volusia
County Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden said the promotion could appeal to tourists without
flattening the beach's other draw: nesting turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any concern, the turtles win,'' he said. ``But
they're not incompatible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth, Fla. Mayor Tom Ramiccio, who has not yet been
approached by Dori, said the idea had some merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want alcohol advertised but yeah, I'd consider
it,'' Ramiccio said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the pitch more palatable to cities queasy about the
overt commercialism, Dori says every ad will carry a reminder not
to litter or to avoid trampling sea turtle nests. He says the
billboards are win-win deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only taking this to beaches that are high traffic
areas,'' he said. ``As much as anything, it's a public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
