   The commercial possibilities, Dori gushes, are endless: Soft
drinks, sun tan lotion, ice cream, restaurants, movie promotions,
mile after mile of slogans, row after row of peppy mascots 12-feet
long and 4-feet wide. Forget Frank Loves Angela. Welcome to `Your
Ad Here.'
</P>
<P>
   Dori landed his first client last summer. He ran a one-month
trial hawking Skippy Peanut butter on the beaches of Seaside
Heights on the New Jersey Shore. Skippy paid Dori $25,000 for the
exposure, the town charged him about $3,000 to use the beach, and
everybody who went to the shore looking for suntan got an ad
between their toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very happy with it,'' said Michael Lyon, director of
promotions for Skippy in New jersey. ``We weren't able to measure
sales with it but were happy to be able to remind people of our
product, especially where there are a lot of families and they're
feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyon said Skippy will do it again, and this winter, patent
firmly in place, Dori has been traveling the coasts _ east and west
_ pitching his product. He says the ads drew applause from
passersby on the cliffs overlooking the San Diego shoreline. But in
Miami, where Dori show-cased the billboards during Superbowl
weekend, the city's tourism and promotions Director, Michael Aller,
said no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over-commercialism,'' he said. ``We want to keep the
beach the beach.'' Fort Lauderdale, Fla. has been more liberal with
its definitions. The city's beach advisory board voted 13-2 in
favor of letting Dori sell their sand this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would bring revenue to the city,'' said Johnny Alexander,
an advisory board member. ``I don't have a problem with it. I know
some people thought it was a bit much but with it being in the sand
I thought it was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Smith, another board member disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a horrible idea,'' he said ``People come to the
area to enjoy the natural beauty here. This won't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Before billboards in the sand start rolling out in Fort
Lauderdale, city attorneys have to determine whether they violate
an ordinance prohibiting billboards on the beach. If they get a
legal OK, the issue goes to the city commission, said Fort
Lauderdale Parks Superintendent Phil Thornburg. He said the city
will likely make a decision by May.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Dori said he expects his idea to catch on, but right
now he must sell it beach by beach. In Florida he has pitched the
product to five high-traffic hot spots. Officials in Volusia
County, Fla., who oversee Daytona Beach, heard about the wash-away
billboards through word-of-mouth and are considering the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a commercial beach and we have a lot of promotions so
this might work here,'' said Joe Wooden, Deputy Chief of Volusia
County Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden said the promotion could appeal to tourists without
flattening the beach's other draw: nesting turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any concern, the turtles win,'' he said. ``But
they're not incompatible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth, Fla. Mayor Tom Ramiccio, who has not yet been
approached by Dori, said the idea had some merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want alcohol advertised but yeah, I'd consider
it,'' Ramiccio said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the pitch more palatable to cities queasy about the
overt commercialism, Dori says every ad will carry a reminder not
to litter or to avoid trampling sea turtle nests. He says the
billboards are win-win deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only taking this to beaches that are high traffic
areas,'' he said. ``As much as anything, it's a public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
