<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMINIST-BARBIE11-COX     02-10 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-BARBIE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mother-daughter feminists still clash over Barbie
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Growing up with a nationally recognized
feminist for a mother, Katie Roiphe had a special perspective on
Barbie dolls and The Brady Bunch, she told a woman's group Monday.
Her mother, author Anne Roiphe, stood beside her at the lectern,
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather brought us a giant Barbie Beauty Palace,'' said
Roiphe the Younger. ``And we spent a whole day playing with it,
setting up the shampoo machine and the hair dryer and cutting
Barbie's hair. And we went to bed that night and woke up the next
morning, looking forward to this wonderful toy ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Barbie Beauty Palace was gone!
</P>
<P>
   ``And we went to my mother and asked her where the Barbie Beauty
Palace was. And she looked at us and said it was lost. This
gigantic thing! It was lost!''
</P>
<P>
   The Barbie Incident still rankled a bit, even years later.
``This Barbie Palace was trash for a very good reason,'' Roiphe the
Elder told the women's group, who turned out to show support for
Israel's Ben-Gurion University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me wrong at the time to tell little girls they
should be playing with their hair, they should be leaving math
equations alone.''
</P>
<P>
   As for The Brady Bunch, Roiphe permitted her five girls to watch
the show but insisted on ``hovering the entire half hour, telling
us, `Girls shouldn't want to be cheerleaders, girls shouldn't want
to be cheerleaders,''' Katie Roiphe recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Roiphes (pronounced roy-phees) have written several books
and numerous newspaper and magazine articles exploring the twists
and turns American feminism has taken in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Roiphe is the author of Up the Sandbox and Fruitful: My
Real Life As A Modern Mother. Katie Roiphe stirred a minor
controversy when she wrote an article for Esquire magazine titled
The Independent Woman And Other Lies, in which she confessed
enjoying having the man pay for dinner on a date.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Roiphe told a lunchtime crowd at Palm Beach's Poinciana
Club that early, radical feminism had erred occasionally, in its
strident militancy. The errors have had surprising after-effects,
she said, including President Clinton's current imbroglio in
Congress over his affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began with two slogans that turned out to be completely
mistaken,'' the older Roiphe said. ``One was: `Women need men like
a fish needs a bicycle.' Wonderful statement, but completely
untrue. Women need men for the next generation, and we also have
hormones that make us so we cannot live without men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second slogan was: `The personal is political.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington,'' Katie Roiphe interrupted, ``what we're seeing
now is this slogan taken to its astounding, natural extreme. It
started with Clarence Thomas and even before that, when every dirty
joke a man told in the workplace was seen as a political act. The
personal is not political. This is an error of the feminist
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women pointed to the president's wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, as a living example of the ambiguities and contradictions
that becloud feminist issues that once seemed crystal-clear. Should
a woman leave, or stay with, an unfaithful husband? Is such
fidelity a sign of weakness?
</P>
<P>
   The Roiphes are undecided but clearly find the first lady
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to figure out what we feel about Hillary
at present,'' Anne Roiphe said. ``To some of us she seems extremely
noble, she has a lot of strength. At first she was despised the way
Eleanor Roosevelt was despised. Now she is widely admired and
looked up to. Is it just because she started to stand by her man?''
</P>
<P>
   Katie Roiphe likened the shift in public opinion in Hillary
Clinton's favor, after the scandal broke, to the thawing in British
opinion toward Princess Diana, after she went on television and
confessed she had bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like her because we see weakness. We like her because she
seems vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks flew at this point. One woman rose to blast Clinton, even
as the plates containing the remains of the poached salmon and
caviar with herbs, which had been served for lunch, were being
cleared away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is emotionally and psychologically abusive to his
wife. I don't see why anybody should be lionized for standing next
to a man who is an icebox. He was unfaithful!'' the attendee
declared.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's name is still one to conjure with: Angry murmurs
and even shushes could be heard as the woman spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that I agree with you that I would not want to
be married to the man,'' Katie Roiphe replied. ``But I do see some
strand of something that is romantic in this relationship. I think
she really loves him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Lady Bird Johnson once said of Lyndon Johnson: `My husband
loves all the world's people, and half the world's people are
women.'''
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon raised at least $100,000 for the Ben-Gurion
University medical school in one fell swoop: Retired biochemist Meg
Kramer, a well-known Palm Beach philanthropist, pledged the sum
after hearing Dr. Rivka Carmi describe how the university, which is
located at the edge of the vast Negev Desert in southern Israel, is
working to improve women's health, not only among Jews but among
Bedouin women.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
