<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-RANDALL-AND-JACK-KLUGMAN-TEAM-UP-AGAIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO AND ONLY: TONY RANDALL AND JACK KLUGMAN ARE BACK ON
`BROTHER'S KEEPER' 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Tony Randall and Jack Klugman with
William Ragsdale and Sean O'Bryan in a scene from ``Brother's
Keeper.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Call it a two-for-one sale _ two great actors, that is, for one
terrific team.
 &HT;    Jack Klugman and Tony Randall are used to working in tandem. The
two are old pals, not to mention co-stars not only of television's
beloved series ``The Odd Couple'' (1970-1975) and a 1993 reunion
telemovie, but also of numerous stage plays and television
commercials.
 &HT;    On Feb. 19 they'll be back, turning up in the ABC sitcom
``Brother's Keeper,'' in a episode entitled ``An Odd Couple of
Days.''
 &HT;    What convinced them to agree to this latest pairing?
 &HT;    ``That's easy,'' Randall says by telephone from his New York
apartment.
 &HT;    ``A lot of money,'' Klugman says by telephone from his Los
Angeles home.
 &HT;    Ba-da-bing!
 &HT;    ``For television, we actually don't get that many offers to work
together,'' the 76-year-old Klugman says more seriously, his voice
still hoarse after a successful battle with throat cancer. ``Tony
and I work together mostly in the theater.
 &HT;    ``In this case,'' he says, ``the show's producer, Jonathan
Axelrod, was the son of a friend of Tony's. He gave us carte
blanche in terms of improvising and doing anything we wanted. That
made it very attractive.''
 &HT;    Randall, who will turn 79 on Feb. 26, interrupts.
 &HT;    ``Jack put his finger on it right away,'' he says. ``They paid
us a lot of money.''
 &HT;    And the two share a laugh.
 &HT;    For those not familiar with ``Brother's Keeper,'' it's a sitcom
nestled in ABC's family-friendly Friday-night schedule. The show
revolves around 8-year-old Oscar (Justin Cooper), who lives with
his straitlaced father (William Ragsdale) and his father's brother
(Sean O'Bryan), a likable but chronically reckless sports star.
 &HT;    In the upcoming episode, Ragsdale and O'Bryan encounter Klugman
and Randall, who play bickering brothers-in-law, and wonder if
they're seeing their own future before them.
 &HT;    ``It'll be familiar stuff,'' Randall says. ``We play characters
people are pretty accustomed to seeing us play. We get into
struggles and we fight.''
 &HT;    The episode marks the first time in 24 years that Klugman and
Randall have teamed for a sitcom.
 &HT;    ``It was 1975 that we finished `The Odd Couple,''' Randall says.
``But it's really like riding a bike when Jack and I work together.
We did long runs of `Odd Couple' as a play, and we did `The
Sunshine Boys' for eight months last year, a good part of that on
Broadway. We work together frequently.''
 &HT;    ``As often as we can,'' Klugman says.
 &HT;    Some actors have resisted being paired with the same performer
too often _ Richard Burton famously warned Elizabeth Taylor that he
didn't want them to turn into Laurel and Hardy _ but Randall and
Klugman don't mind at all.
 &HT;    ``We work well together,'' Randall says. ``I guess that's
obvious. It's a pleasure to work with Jack.''
 &HT;    ``We appreciate each other,'' Klugman says. ``We work the same
way. It's good to work together a lot, because you get to know the
other person.
 &HT;    ``You get a sense of comfort, but also a spontaneity that you
can spark in each other,'' he adds. ``On stage, we're confident we
can do anything, and we know the other guy will be there to support
it.''
 &HT;    ``And there's no competition between us,'' Randall says.
 &HT;    ``It's very, very rare,'' Klugman concludes, ``to find someone
you can act with who makes you feel so comfortable.''
 &HT;    Randall's career dates back to 1941 and his stage debut in the
play ``The Circle of Chalk.'' His numerous subsequent credits
include the movies ``Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?'' (1957),
three Doris Day-Rock Hudson outings and ``The King of Comedy''
(1983). On television he's starred in ``Mr. Peepers'' (1952-1955)
and ``Love, Sidney'' (1981-1983), while on the stage he's appeared
in everything from ``The Music Man'' to ``M. Butterfly.''
 &HT;    Since 1991, Randall has immersed himself in his dream project,
The National Actors Theatre, a not-for-profit company that stages a
variety of shows each season.
 &HT;    Klugman launched his career in 1949 opposite Rod Steiger in the
play ``Stevedore,'' and subsequently appeared in ``Mr. Roberts''
and ``Gypsy,'' as well as a 1998 production of ``Death of a
Salesman'' in Los Angeles. His films include ``12 Angry Men''
(1957), ``Days of Wine and Roses'' (1962) and ``Dear God'' (1996).
 &HT;    On television, Klugman acted in several classic episodes of
``The Twilight Zone,'' starred as the title character in ``Quincy,
M.E.'' (1976-1983) and won an Emmy for a 1964 appearance on ``The
Defenders.''
 &HT;    And, along the way, they met each other.
 &HT;    ``We met doing a show people mention frequently,'' Randall says,
deadpan. ``I bet people think of it all the time.''
 &HT;    He and Klugman crack up.
 &HT;    ``It was called `Appointment with Adventure,''' Randall says.
``That was sometime in the last century.''
 &HT;    ``It was 1954,'' Klugman says. ``It was a summer replacement.
Shows would play all winter, and in the summer a stock company
would come in with a replacement.
 &HT;    ``Who was in it with us, Tony?''
 &HT;    ``Gena Rowlands,'' Randall says. ``She was the only good thing
in it.''
 &HT;    Klugman laughs.
 &HT;    ``It was terrible,'' he says. ``Terrible.''
 &HT;    ``Jack played a gangster and I was a professor,'' Randall says.
``It was really bad.''
 &HT;    It never occurred to either actor that, 45 years later, they'd
still be friends, still sharing the stage and screen.
 &HT;    ``No, no, no,'' they say simultaneously.
 &HT;    ``We didn't see each other for almost 20 years after that
show,'' Klugman says. ``Until we did `Odd Couple.'''
 &HT;    Airing from 1970 to 1975, ``The Odd Couple'' cemented the
perception of Randall and Klugman as comedians. Both men swear,
rather unconvincingly, that the label doesn't bother them.
 &HT;    ``Whatever the public likes is fine,'' Randall says. ``They
decide, but we know better.''
 &HT;    ``In the final analysis,'' Klugman adds, ``you can get
categorized, but if you categorize yourself or put yourself in a
pigeonhole, then you become that type.
 &HT;    ``When I was up for `Odd Couple,''' he recalls, ``they said to
Garry Marshall, `But he only does drama. He can't do comedy.' Then
when I was doing `Quincy' they said, `He only does comedy. He can't
do drama.' You can't listen to anything they say.''
 &HT;    ``People only remember the last thing they saw,'' Randall says.
``That's not only the public, it's the people who give jobs. And
it'll never change.
 &HT;    ``After I did `The Seven Faces of Dr. Lao'' (1964),'' he
recalls, ``I was offered nothing but ancient Orientals! It sounds
ridiculous, but it's true. For one of the movies I couldn't do they
got John Gielgud _ I've always liked that.''
 &HT;    ``I never knew that, Tony,'' Klugman says, chuckling. ``Look,
it's just a way of a studio protecting itself, protecting its
dollars.''
 &HT;    Randall and Klugman are both busy with a variety of activities.
Randall, the father of a 2-year-old daughter and an 8-month-old
son, is gearing up for the National Actors Theatre production of
``The Night Must Fall,'' starring Matthew Broderick. Klugman, the
father of two grown sons, hopes to star soon in a two-hour
``Quincy'' movie for television.
 &HT;    Later this year, the two will return to the stage for a
production of Tom Stoppard's ``Rough Crossing.'' If a Florida
tryout proves popular, they'll take the show to Broadway.
 &HT;    ``We've actually found two or three plays we might do in the
future,'' Randall says. ``The public likes to see us together, it
seems. That's good, because Jack and I like to work together.''
 &HT;    ``We've got a good thing going,'' Klugman says. ``Why stop
now?''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
