<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIZABETH-HURLEY-IN-M     02-10 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-HURLEY-IN-MY-FAVORITE-MARTIAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN ARE FROM MARS, ELIZABETH HURLEY IS FROM VENUS 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Elizabeth Hurley with Jeff Daniels in a
scene from ``My Favorite Martian.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Elizabeth Hurley isn't always as sexy as she looks in those
television commercials.
 &HT;    If you're in any doubt, check out her latest film, ``My Favorite
Martian,'' opening Feb. 12. The adaptation of the old television
series features Hurley and a great deal of mugging _ or, as she and
other Brits call it, ``pulling faces.''
 &HT;    ``I went to a screening this week, and I found myself quite
frightening,'' she says. ``I make those faces all the time in real
life, and now I realize what I must look like. From now on I'm
going to try to imagine that my features are frozen so I'll never
pull another face again.''
 &HT;    Director Dan Petrie has praised Hurley's willingness to set
aside her supermodel image to deliver the kind of off-the-wall
performance the film required.
 &HT;    ``I think you just have to throw away your inhibitions,'' she
says with a shrug. ``Otherwise every day on that set would have
been excruciating. If you get self-conscious, you're a goner. You
just have to close your eyes, take a deep breath and say to
yourself, `OK, get silly!'''
 &HT;    One particularly silly scene finds Hurley possessed by the title
alien, to the point of sprouting tentacles.
 &HT;    ``I practiced alone in my trailer for that scene,'' she admits.
``But occasionally Chris Lloyd, who plays the Martian, would come
by to give me a few tips. That was actually a nightmare, because
there I was, contorting my body for this brilliant comedian while
he was critiquing me.''
 &HT;    Hurley's character is an obnoxious television reporter, but she
denies modeling her on any single real person.
 &HT;    ``I can tell you it was not Barbara Walters,'' the actress says
with a laugh. ``Actually, it was sort of my revenge on some of the
reporters who've tortured me in interviews over the years. I just
sort of made a composite of all the worst so-called journalists
I've had to face, and there was my character.
 &HT;    ``It was actually quite liberating to play someone so beastly,''
she adds. ``Normally you get so obsessed with making yourself
charming and likable _ it was actually quite nice to forget all
that and just be a cow.''
 &HT;    There's nothing noticeably bovine about Hurley as she relaxes in
a Hollywood hotel suite. Her stunning beauty is set off by a pair
of tightfitting leather jeans and a form-hugging black sweater.
 &HT;    ``Normally it takes me a few good hours of hair and makeup to
look good on camera,'' she insists. ``People who see me looking
groomed and perfect in those cosmetics commercials don't realize
how much work it takes. In real life I like to dress down.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I think being pretty can sometimes be a liability,''
she adds. ``People think you're not very smart or interesting.
 &HT;    ``I fell into that trap the other day,'' Hurley admits.
``Somebody was talking about a very handsome actor for a dramatic
part, and I made a face. I realized I was thinking, `He's probably
too gorgeous to have any depth.' That's a hideously unfair
assumption _ it's absolute rubbish that people who look good can't
be clever.''
 &HT;    The actress has spent the last couple of years working to prove
that she's more than a pretty face. She and her longtime boyfriend,
actor Hugh Grant, have their own production company, Simian
Productions. They produced ``Extreme Measures,'' which fizzled at
the box office in 1997, and have another coming later this year.
 &HT;    ``It's called `Mickey Blue Eyes,''' she says. ``It's sort of a
romantic comedy about the Mafia. Hugh is the leading man, and he's
very, very funny in it. I think it's his best acting in a long
time. He spends half the movie trying to become a New York
goodfella with some help from James Caan, but he just can't get it
together.
 &HT;    ``Being a producer is not nearly as cushy as being an actor,''
Hurley adds with a laugh. ``When you're acting, you do your 10
weeks' work and get spoiled rotten, and very well paid to boot.
When I'm producing I spend a lot of time taking care of those perks
for my stars, and I don't get any.
 &HT;    ``But I love having the control over what we're doing. If things
don't work out you have no one to blame but yourself, and I rather
like that.''
 &HT;    When they aren't working, Hurley says, she and Grant hardly lead
glamorous lives.
 &HT;    ``We don't actually go out that much at the moment,'' she says,
``but I don't sit at home and watch TV, either. I don't have a set.
I probably haven't watched an entire program in 25 years _ I just
don't have the patience to sit still that long.''
 &HT;    The two spend much of the year in Los Angeles, but Hurley misses
her native Britain.
 &HT;    ``There's no street life here,'' she says. ``Nobody walks around
or sits at an outdoor cafe or anything. But I do find that I have a
little more privacy here. If you think the tabloid press is bad in
Hollywood, you should go to London _ the English press is insane.''
 &HT;    Few have endured the kind of press blitz that Grant and Hurley
faced after his 1995 arrest for soliciting a prostitute, and Hurley
says that she's still dealing with the consequences.
 &HT;    ``You have to be careful not to cocoon yourself,'' she says.
``Suddenly you find you're missing out on life. You say to
yourself, `I want to sit at a sidewalk cafe and watch people pass
by, because that was one of the favorite things that I ever did.'
You start to do your own grocery shopping again, just because it
feels weird not to do what normal people do.
 &HT;    ``Gradually you find a way to live with people staring at you
and stuff, as long as you feel safe. I live much more normally now
than I did a couple of years ago.''
 &HT;    Looking ahead, Hurley denies any master plan behind her rather
eclectic choice of projects.
 &HT;    ``I kind of look at a stack of scripts in the office and take
what seems best and right to do at the moment,'' she says,
laughing. ``However, I do get bored when I see a part that begins,
`A beautiful girl pulls up in a sports car, gets out and takes off
her dark glasses.' That's when I hear a voice in my head saying, `I
don't think so.'''
 &HT;    Next up is a cameo appearance in the sequel to ``Austin Powers:
International Man of Mystery,'' her surprise hit of 1997.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't disappointed that I don't last for the whole movie,''
she says. ``Austin Powers is like James Bond, he wants a new Pussy
Galore in every film. Anyway, the original was such a huge hit that
it gave my career a tremendous boost.
 &HT;    ``What's strange is, I get all these little boys coming up to me
wherever I go who loved the movie,'' she adds. ``They want me in a
silver miniskirt. It's a little bizarre, but quite cute.''
 &HT;    Those young fans don't get her thinking about a family of her
own, though.
 &HT;    ``My sister has two children, and I've become an extremely good
aunt,'' she says. ``I was a bit scared of them at first _ I didn't
have the faintest idea of how to talk to them. But now I'm
absolutely in love with them.''
 &HT;    Hurley pulls a face.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I'm quite ready to be a mother myself,'' she
adds. ``I don't think I'm that responsible. But, you know,
gradually I am getting more grown up.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
