<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIS11-COX     02-10 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews if movies released on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rounders'' (R) _ The snappy dialogue, Matt Damon's star
presence and John Malkovich's over-the-top Russian accent are the
main reasons to see this high-stakes gambling drama. Damon plays a
law student and card sharp trying to go the straight and narrow.
Edward Norton plays his unreliable friend, Worm. Problem is, Worm
is such a loser, we start to lose sympathy for Damon, whose loyalty
verges on self-destructive. Other minuses: A hypocritical,
mixed-message ending and whiny, blank Gretchen Mol as Damon's
girlfriend. (Famke Janssen, in a small role as one of his old
flames, blows her right out of the water.) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Clay Pigeons'' (R) _ The latest Tarantino/Coen brothers
clone, mixing serial killers, small-town crackers and general bad
taste. Joaquin Phoenix plays a guy who gets mixed up in the bloody
hobby of giggling psycho Vince Vaughn (who's very good). Janeane
Garofalo is also her reliably dry, sly self as a federal agent
tracking the killer. But the movie stumbles over a few too many
improbably plot twists. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' (R) _ A small wonder in its own
modest way. This charming low-budget romantic comedy about the
relationship travails of a Boston nurse (Hope Davis) is stronger on
character nuance than on plot; in fact, filmmaker Brad Anderson
loads it with too much plot. But by applying a naturalistic
independent film sensibility to a vintage glossy Hollywood
predicament, he comes out ahead. Think of a film where John
Cassavetes shares pillow talk with Doris Day. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Underground'' (unrated) _ Emir Kusturica's exhausting,
three-hour epic examines the recent history of what was once
Yugoslavia with his usual mix of exuberance, humor and surreal
imagery. Spanning 50 years and three kinds of war, the film starts
in 1941, setting up the love triangle involving Marko (Miki
Manojlovic), his best pal Blacky (Lazar Ristovski) and Blacky's
mistress, Natalija (Mirjana Jokovic). The film leaps 20 years
forward to find Blacky and dozens of others hiding in a basement,
convinced by Marko (now Natalija's lover) that Germany is
undefeated. From there the film leaps another 30 years, to the
Bosnian conflict, where the comic tone sours into bleak, bloody
absurdity. ``Underground'' changes moods constantly, ranging from
the heartbreaking bombing of a zoo, to an image of heaven that's
beautifully rooted in the Slavic soil. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
