<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ANTZ11-COX     02-10 0164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ANTZ11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bugging out to his own beat
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Antz'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   When our nebbishy hero, Z, frets to his shrink about his
insecurity, the voice is instantly recognizable as Woody Allen's.
The body isn't. Sporting six legs, a set of antennae and a bulbous
posterior, Z looks exactly like his gazillion neighbors in this
totalitarian ant colony. But he's about to make a very distinct
impression, as he literally decides to walk (and dance) to his own
beat.
</P>
<P>
   This visually remarkable, computer-animated feature, like ``Toy
Story,'' finds witty human satire in the least human places.
</P>
<P>
   But the script tends to be by-the-numbers predictable in its
fable about nonconformity and heroism. It doesn't help that almost
all of the characters look identical. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
