<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL11-COX     02-10 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the Oscar goes (or should have gone) to . . .
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The announcement of the Oscar nominations this week reminds us
that some of the most famous movies Hollywood ever made didn't make
the cut for best picture the year they were eligible. Consider
these titles, none of them nominees: ``City Lights,'' ``Young Mr.
Lincoln,'' ``Bringing Up Baby,'' ``King Kong,'' ``The Public
Enemy,'' ``The Women,'' ``Modern Times,'' ``Little Caesar,'' ``The
Bride of Frankenstein,'' ``The Blue Angel,'' ``My Man Godfrey,''
``Nothing Sacred'' and ``Intermezzo.'' And those are just from the
'30s. Here are some other what-were-they-thinking omissions:
</P>
<P>
   The '40s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``His Girl Friday'' (1940)
</P>
<P>
   This whip-smart reworking of Ben Hecht and Charles MacArthur's
famous newspaper play, ``The Front Page,'' got its inspiration at a
dinner party attended by director Howard Hawks. He had a young
woman read the part of reporter Hildy Johnson and he read the part
of Hildy's editor, Walter Burns. He then called up Hecht and said,
``What do you think about changing Hildy Johnson and making her a
girl?'' Hecht replied, ``I wish we'd thought of that.'' Not just
any girl, however. Rosalind Russell is at her fast-talking best as
Hildy, and Cary Grant is at his Cary Grant best as Burns. Hawks got
used to being snubbed by the academy. His classics ``The Big
Sleep'' and ``Red River'' were also ignored in the best picture
category.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``The African Queen'' (1951)
</P>
<P>
   The stars, Humphrey Bogart and Katharine Hepburn, were nominated
(Bogart won). So was the director, John Huston. But the movie
itself, a shamelessly entertaining opposites-attract tale about a
gin-soaked river rat (Bogart) and a prim missionary (Hepburn) going
downriver to elude the Germans, wasn't deemed as ``important'' as
the quasi-biblical epic ``Quo Vadis,'' which got a best picture
nomination. But then, the '50s were famous for that kind of
thinking. In 1954, ``Three Coins in the Fountain'' was considered
worthier than ``A Star Is Born'' or ``Rear Window.'' In 1955,
``Love Is a Many Splendored Thing'' was chosen over ``Rebel Without
a Cause.'' Ditto ``The Ten Commandments'' and ``Friendly
Persuasion'' over ``The Searchers'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   The '60s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968)
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's sci-fi mind-bender starts with apes and an
enigmatic obelisk and ends with a psychedelic orgasm and an
enigmatic embryo. In between, there are waltzing space stations,
``The Blue Danube'' and, of course, HAL the computer, who has
become a part of our culture (what other movie icon from the '60s
had a cameo in a recent Super Bowl commercial?) Maybe the film's
``stoner'' reputation scared off the academy. Ironic, considering
that, 30 years later, ``2001'' is on the pope's list of recommended
movies. Meanwhile, back in '68, with America going to hell in a
handbasket _ assassinations, protests, riots _ Hollywood decided to
accentuate the positive and nominate, not one, but two musicals:
``Funny Girl'' and ``Oliver!'' (the eventual winner).
</P>
<P>
   The '70s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mean Streets'' (1973)
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring Martin Scorsese's phenomenal early feature was just the
beginning of a long-standing Mexican standoff between one of our
greatest directors and the Academy Awards. Scorsese is the only
member of the '70s new wave (which ranges from Francis Ford Coppola
to Steven Spielberg) to never win an Oscar. ``Mean Streets'' may be
rough around the edges, but this story of some Little Italy
small-timers crackles with energy, intelligence and fine acting. It
helped establish careers for Robert De Niro and Harvey Keitel and
put Scorsese on the Hollywood map (his next film was the very
conventional ``Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore.'') Scorsese would
go on to win his share of nominations _ for ``Raging Bull,'' ``Taxi
Driver'' and ``GoodFellas'' to name a few _ but has yet to go home
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The '80s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Velvet'' (1986)
</P>
<P>
   Academy members had nothing against director David Lynch. They'd
nominated him before for ``The Elephant Man'' in 1980 (in both the
picture and directing categories). But when it came to his
disturbing walk on the wild side of ``See Spot Run'' America _ Kyle
MacLachlan and Laura Dern as amateur sleuths drawn into a nightmare
netherworld of sex, violence and unbridled Dennis Hopper _ the
academy went schizoid. It failed to nominate Lynch's film _ too
malignant, too provocative, too controversial _ but did nominate
Lynch himself for best director. Which meant Randa Haines, the
director of one of the best picture nominees, ``Children of a
Lesser God,'' was left out. Another case of The Movie Directed
Itself.
</P>
<P>
   The '90s
</P>
<P>
   And the Nominee Wasn't:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thelma &AMP; Louise'' (1991)
</P>
<P>
   It was ``The African Queen'' all over again. The stars (Susan
Sarandon and Geena Davis) were nominated. The director (Ridley
Scott) was nominated. The movie was one of the most talked about of
the year with its sexy feminism (an oxymoron according to some).
But while audiences were applauding Sarandon's and Davis'
accidental outlaws, Oscar voters were more comfortable with movies
focusing on lady psychiatrists (``The Prince of Tides'') and FBI
agents (``The Silence of the Lambs''). Sarandon and Davis canceled
each other out, giving ``Silence's'' Jodie Foster her second win.
But the film did take home one Oscar; it went to neophyte Callie
Khouri for best original screenplay. And the long-overdue Sarandon
finally did win an Oscar _ for playing a nun in ``Dead Man
Walking'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
