<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-CO     02-10 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Divining for dollars
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share their memories of growing up in small-town
America. Back then, or at least the way we remember it, life was
like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Milton Watts
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON, Texas _ My ancestors were deep in the Ozarks during
the Civil War. They settled in a community called Richland along
the Buffalo River in Searcy County, Ark. My dad left the Ozarks for
East Texas in 1923. I was born in Texas in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   I still have kin in the Harrison, Ark., area. On visits to see
our folks we always go back to the old homestead sites in the
Richland area. We call it the Old Country.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago my brother and I made an Arkansas trip to visit our
Uncle Jewel Watts. He was, then, running a grocery store in a small
town called St. Joe that was near Richland.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, Uncle Jewel revealed to us about this ``gift''
he claimed he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys,'' he said, ``I can 'witch' money. Can't everybody do it,
but I've got the electricity for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimming a small forked peach tree limb, he proceeded to
demonstrate, instructing us to take some dimes, quarters and halves
and hide them in little piles in the backyard, out of his sight.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jewel came out grasping the forks of the peach tree limb
and _ by golly! _ with the limb bobbing and dipping, more times
than not he would find the coins where we had hidden them.
</P>
<P>
   After several demonstrations, my brother and I became excited
about the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Jewel said, ``Boys, this is big. We can do something with
this.'' And he told us this story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Above Richland, in the Point Peter Mountains, there's this
place called McCutcheon's Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, during the Civil War, Missouri guerrillas attacked a
company of Yankee soldiers at this gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fought all day. During the night the Yankees pulled out,
leaving an empty payroll wagon and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word is that they hid the gold and silver payroll, and it's
never been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the morning we'll take axes, picks and shovels _ I've got
some dynamite _ and we'll go find that Yankee treasure!''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that early the next day, we struck out in Uncle
Jewel's four-wheel drive pickup on our way to McCutcheon's Gap.
</P>
<P>
   It was rough country. Precipitous bluffs bordered either side of
the gap. Boulders and smaller fallen rock crowded the base of the
bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least bit daunted, we unloaded our gear while Uncle
Jewel trimmed a forked peach tree limb and starting doing his
thing.
</P>
<P>
   For a long while nothing happened. But finally there was some
indication at a pile of smaller rock.
</P>
<P>
   We rolled rock and dug for better than an hour. The limb quit
bobbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not here,'' Uncle Jewel concluded. ``Let's move.''
</P>
<P>
   Caressing the limb, he took a few deep breaths and, right away,
got a strong indication by a boulder at the base of a high cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels like this is it,'' he exclaimed. ``Let's dynamite
this rock out of the way, dig down and that's where the money will
be!''
</P>
<P>
   As instructed, we dug under the boulder, buried half a stick of
dynamite, lighted the fuse and then ran for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty as you please, the explosion rolled the boulder away, and
we eagerly set to work with picks and shovels.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, nothing turned up, and again Uncle Jewel's limb ceased to
bob. As he criss-crossed the area, back and forth over new ground
and old, still nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   He grinned a little, shook his head and announced the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gather up the tools, boys. The gold rush is over _ we're going
back home.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on the way back that a game warden stopped us, suspecting
that we'd been dynamiting for fish.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Jewel knew the warden. Moreover, the warden knew Uncle
Jewel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot fire, Jewel,'' he said after hearing his explanation.
``I thought you too smart to go for something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't laugh,'' Uncle Jewel said. ``I know it looks crazy, and
we didn't find it. But we liked to have.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Milton Watts resides at Island View Landing, Lake O' The Pines,
Jefferson, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, mail it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
