<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-WASHINGTON21-C     02-10 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-WASHINGTON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With GEORGE-BOX. Moving in (w) Washington, (l) lifestyle and (t)
travel categories for release Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, Va. _ Nearly two centuries have passed since
George Washington _ after being bled by would-be healers and
prophetically reviewing his will _ whispered `` 'tis well'' and
died in an upstairs bedroom of his beloved mansion beside the
Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the bicentennial year of Washington's death on Dec. 14,
1799, the keepers of his historic homestead and his legacy are
fearful that the Father of His Country is being forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The number of visitors to Washington's carefully maintained
plantation has stagnated, and many schoolchildren are shockingly
ignorant about the life and times of the Revolutionary War
commander and the nation's first president, said Michael Quinn,
programs director at Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   Today's youngsters don't even know the boyhood legend of young
George declaring ``I cannot tell a lie'' and admitting to chopping
down his father's favorite cherry tree, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask people if they've ever heard of George Washington and
the cherry tree and they say 'No','' marveled Quinn, recalling the
familiar but apocryphal tale.
</P>
<P>
   So, seeking to restore Washington to his traditional place of
``first in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his
countrymen,'' the directors of Mount Vernon have begun a $3 million
campaign to spread his story far and wide during the bicentennial
year of his death.
</P>
<P>
   The effort features new programs, a re-enactment of his funeral
at Mount Vernon and a traveling exhibit of 100 artifacts ranging
from his infamous false teeth (made of ivory, not wood) to a
miniature replica of his home. This ``Only in 1799'' collection
will be at the Atlanta History Center from Oct. 14, 1999, until
Jan. 6, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers also have set up new Internet web sites
(www.gwashington1999.org and www.mountvernon.org) and contacted
communities across the country about staging their own
commemorations.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Vernon's bicentennial events officially opened on
Presidents Day (Washington's real 267th birthday is tomorrow) and
will continue into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to create a nationwide buzz about George Washington,
Quinn explained.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Washington's death, there was a remarkable
outpouring of emotion throughout the new nation. President John
Adams _ Washington's successor _ issued a proclamation that every
American wear a black armband for 30 days and most of the citizens
willingly complied, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Daughters of the American Revolution later did an historic
fashion study that showed most American women wore black mourning
dresses throughout the year of 1800, he said. Over 150 communities
staged their own funerals for this first national hero.
</P>
<P>
   The official funeral was held at Mount Vernon on Dec. 18, 1799.
From his deathbed, Washington had issued emphatic orders that he
not be entombed for at least three days. There was a widespread
fear of premature burial at the time. Washington also looked over
his last will and testament during the long day on his deathbed. He
died in the early evening of suffocation _ stricken by quinsy, an
abscess of the throat.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of her husband's final day at his bedside,
Martha Washington said ``all my trials are over'' after seeing his
life slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall follow soon,'' she predicted.
</P>
<P>
   She died three years later and is entombed next to her husband
in the Washington family vault.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Dandridge Custis had been a widow when she married George
Washington in 1759. She had two children at the time but the couple
would have no offspring of their own. Mount Vernon was inherited by
Bushrod Washington, nephew of the first president, after Martha
Washington died.
</P>
<P>
   In 1853, Washington's heirs sold 550 surrounding acres, the home
and outbuildings, and the tomb of George Washington to the Mount
Vernon Ladies Association _ one of the nation's earliest historic
conservation groups. The national organization has maintained and
preserved the place with private money ever since. Authentically
restored to its original appearance, Mount Vernon is open to the
public every day and close to a million people visit each year.
</P>
<P>
   However, annual attendance peaked at 1.3 million visitors in the
1960s. Now Mount Vernon's directors are hoping the bicentennial
year activities will inspire greater interest and enthusiasm about
the master of the manor.
</P>
<P>
   After considerable controversy over maintaining historical
purity, Mount Vernon was air-conditioned last year. One result of
the new, high-tech climate control was that collectors and museums
across the country were no longer afraid to lend back artifacts
that had been taken from Mount Vernon over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   So Washington's home is now even more stocked with stuff that
was there when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following his death, the law required that an inventory be
taken,'' said curator King Laughlin. That room-by-room accounting
of objects ``provided a virtual snapshot'' of what was in Mount
Vernon at the time and where everything was placed. Thousands of
those artifacts are now displayed in their rightful setting.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's library is now _ as it was then _ ``crammed full''
of books and chairs and maps and letters and a globe and 12
telescopes and ``a small arsenal,'' said Laughlin. Washington kept
seven rifles, several pistols, swords and ``a small cannon'' in the
room, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used the cannon to fire friendly salutes at ships passing
by'' on the Potomac, Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The huge table in the main dining room is arranged with 20 place
settings of the Washingtons' favorite china and silverware. The
first First Couple entertained often. In the Blue Room, a parlor
Washington called ``the best room in my house,'' the family's
gaming tables are set up with their chess set and playing cards.
The first president was an enthusiastic gambler. Among the displays
are lottery tickets that he signed.
</P>
<P>
   The upstairs bedroom is like it was the day Washington died.
There are even dark stains on the rug. Nearly a third of
Washington's blood, believed to be diseased, was drained in his
physician's effort to save his life. Curators considered piping in
odors but decided that authenticity couldn't be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias Lear, Washington's friend and secretary, was at his
bedside for most of his final day. During the bicentennial year, a
new multi-media presentation entitled ``Washington No More'' and
based on Lear's detailed account of those dramatic hours will be
shown in a theater built in the historic greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be provided black armbands for a new ``Death and
Funeral Procession Tour'' that will follow the route of cavalry,
Masonic brethren, family and friends from the dining room where
mourners viewed the casket to the tomb where he was laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Dec. 18, there will be a televised re-enactment of
the full funeral.
</P>
<P>
   During February, in observance of Black History Month, a daily
30-minute guided tour is focusing on the lives and contributions of
the slave who built and maintained the plantation home of the
Washingtons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mount Vernon Museum has been renovated and filled
with new artifacts, including furnishings from Washington's
presidential office in Philadelphia (the White House was not
finished until after he left office) and a carefully restored bust
of Washington cast in 1785 by French sculptor Jean-Antonine Houdon.
The terra-cruda(cq), or unfired clay, bust was made from a plaster
mask that Washington wore, and it is said by historians to be
supposed to be his best likeness.
</P>
<P>
   After layers of white paint were removed from the bust,
Washington ended up having a smaller nose and ears than had been
seen earlier, said Meg Craft, the curator restoring the bust.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Vernon's director James Rees hopes the bust and the rest
of the bicentennial campaign will help correct the ``travesty'' of
how little most people know about ``the man who led our country to
liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled one ``well-spoken adult'' visitor who asked a guide,
``Where's the mountain?'' The guide thought the visitor was
referring to the Blue Ridge Mountains but the tourist said, ``No,
the mountain with all of the presidents' heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourist had confused Mount Vernon with South Dakota's Mount
Rushmore, Rees said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
