<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKBOOKS-HNS &LR;      02-10 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE BOOKS UNLEASH THE FLAVORS OF SOUTHWESTERN CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What we have here is a convergence of tastes that border on ...
well, the border.
</P>
<P>
   The bold, brassy flavors of the American West and Southwest, and
the pleasures of Mexican food teamed up to dominate the trio of new
cookbooks presented here.
</P>
<P>
   If you hunger for the likes of roasted corn soup, sopa seca,
tenderloin alambre and ensalada con camarones, pull up a chair and
start studying.
</P>
<P>
   But before you do, please park the outdated notion that all this
food is spicy-hot. Some is, of course, but you can find that in any
cuisine. Look, instead, for the wonderful variety of flavors and
textures created by the many national and ethnic influences.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuisine of the American Southwest, Second Edition,'' by Anne
Lindsay Greer (Gulf Publishing Co. 288 pages, $29.)
</P>
<P>
   Greer is a restaurant consultant with several cookbooks to her
credit _ ``The Ultimate Low-Fat Mexican Cookbook'' and
``Contemporary Mexican Cooking.'' This effort, however, neither
overly relies on Mexican food, nor is it a Texas-centric cookbook,
as are so many that purport to represent the entire Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In this second edition, Greer has cleverly divided recipes from
all over the Southwest into intelligent categories, including
vegetables, beverages and morning meals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dozens of recipes, Greer has made this a solid,
if somewhat awkwardly sized (8 1/2-by-11-inch) reference book for
those unfamiliar with this cooking style. An excellent glossary
from achiote to zarzuel, ingredient lists, equipment and techniques
section, and menu and party suggestions will help you get started
or improve current skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirit of the West,'' by Beverly Cox and Martin Jacobs
(Artisan/Workman Publishing. 224 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   You can take the girl out of the country _ and in this case, it
was waaaay out of the country. Wyoming-born-and-raised Bev Cox left
the family cattle ranch to study at Le Cordon Bleu in Paris. She
used that classical training to work out her version of American
West cooking, and the industry has noted that.
</P>
<P>
   When she teamed up with photographer Martin Jacobs, the
collaboration resulted in ``Spirit of the Harvest: North American
Indian Cooking,'' which won a James Beard Cookbook Award. This new
``Spirit'' book is a Literary Guild selection.
</P>
<P>
   The collection of 100-plus recipes is a true representation of
the amalgam of backgrounds of people who developed the West, but
Cox included some family recipes. Cream Biscuits is particularly
interesting, developed by her great-great-grandmother, whose
husband founded the first dairy in Cheyenne, Wyo., in the late
1860s.
</P>
<P>
   Cox has a knack for relating anecdotes, catching bits of history
on ranches, and breaking recipes into periods such as pioneering
days _ both Spanish mission and U.S. expansion eras _ right up to
dude ranches. But when it comes to recipes, she shines even more
with such intriguing possibilities as atole (blue cornmeal
porridge), King Ranch chili steaks, butterscotch rolls, Dakota
golden pheasant fricasse and Oklahoma cowboy stew.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The El Paso Chile Company's Sizzlin' Supper,'' by W. Park Kerr
(William Morrow &AMP; Co. 194 page, $18.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is Kerr's third Southwestern cookbook, ``Burning Desires''
and ``The El Paso Chile Company's Texas Border Cookbook'' being the
first two. And, yes, there is an El Paso Chile Co. It's run by Kerr
and his mother, producing Southwestern food products.
</P>
<P>
   This nine-chapter offering relies heavily on robust-sounding
recipes (Fork and Knife Chicken Soup With Chile Corn Dumplings,
Horseradish Potato Salad, Going-to-Hell-in-a-Handbasket Pasta). And
the ingredients and preparation instructions support that attitude.
This is a small book of big tastes _ the fiery and sweet chiles so
popular in the Southwest; thick sauces and gravies for meats and
poultry; fresh vegetarian salads and salsas. No lists of utensils,
definitions or tips. Just flat-out, easy-to-follow recipes. Yee
hah!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
