<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE11-COX     02-10 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hail to their chief chow-down choices
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We who cook are known to follow the calendar closely, searching
for inspiration. Most of the time it's easy. Special occasions and
holidays usually have a signature dish that we merely need to find
a new and interesting twist for to keep our culinary repertoire
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   But Presidents Day is tough.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't exactly find such a signature dish on the Internet,
</P>
<P>
   but we did find some intriguing information about presidential
food preferences, as well as some interesting possibilities for
Presidents Day fare.
</P>
<P>
   At http://detroitnews.com/menu/stories/35819.htm we found ``All
the Presidents' Menus,'' a newspaper article that included a number
of recipes proving that if there is any food preference common to
most of the presidents, it's corn.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with George Washington, who regularly ate hominy and
hoe cakes made of cornmeal, most presidents, according to
historical record, are known to have enjoyed some form of corn.
James Madison loved Dolley's spoonbread. Rutherford B. Hayes and
Herbert Hoover could not pass up cream of corn soup. And Eleanor
and Franklin were known to start each day with fried cornmeal mush
for breakfast. And then, ``the corniest of all'' presidents,
according to the article, was Jimmy Carter, who served grits not
only at family meals but to foreign dignitaries as well. While all
this was interesting, the idea of grits and cornmeal mush on
Presidents Day did not set our hearts to fluttering.
</P>
<P>
   For that we went to http://www.soupsong.com/bfaves.html, a
humorous, award-winning site chock-full of _ of all things _ the
favorite soups of celebrities, presidents included.
</P>
<P>
   There is the mock turtle soup of Abraham Lincoln, JFK's cream of
chicken and onion soup, Gerald Ford's navy bean soup, Ronald
Reagan's hamburger soup and many more. Incidentally, Linda Tripp's
(who is listed as a late 20th-century audiotape specialist)
favorite is cabbage soup, and her friend Monica's favorite is
pumpkin (this info from the tapes).
</P>
<P>
   And then, at http://www.monticello.org/Day/dining/home.html, we
visited Thomas Jefferson, probably the greatest foodie president of
all and the one who came closest to giving us the quintessential
Presidents Day dish, or for that matter the quintessential American
dish _ macaroni and cheese. While early Colonists were known to add
this or that to boiled noodles, it wasn't until Jefferson came home
from Paris in 1787 with a pasta-making machine from Italy and had
his Monticello cooks start making ``Macaroni Pie'' that the dish
became de rigueur at American tables. For more on America's ``First
Gourmet,'' visit http://members.home.net/jjschnebel/Cookup5.html.
</P>
<P>
   This standard White House mac and cheese recipe, and the one for
Clinton's favorite casserole, can be found at
http://observer-eccentric.com/taste/archivebox/box110.html
</P>
<P>
   Other sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mtaonline.net/(tilde)dustys/1meats.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.homearts.com/depts/food/10capcf1.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/FirstLady/html/Recipes.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.caderbooks.com/exbill.html
</P>
<P>
   Layered Turkey Enchilada Casserole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 4-ounce can diced green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   9 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound cooked turkey, cut in 2-by- 1/4-by- 1/4-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   6 green onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce package frozen corn kernels, thawed, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups grated cheddar cheese (about 3/4 pound), divided
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Lightly butter a shallow 1-quart
baking dish. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix tomato sauce, chiles, garlic, chili
powder, cumin, oregano and black pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put three of the corn tortillas, overlapping, on the bottom of
the baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Spread with 1/3 of the tomato mixture. Cover with half the
turkey, green onions and corn.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with 1 cup of the cheddar cheese. Top with three more
tortillas, half the remaining tomato mixture, all of the remaining
turkey, green onions and corn and 1 cup of the cheese. Top with the
remaining three tortillas, remaining tomato mixture and remaining
1/2 cup cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, uncovered, for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 416 calories, 28 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 37 grams carbohydrates, 78
milligrams cholesterol, 998 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Macaroni and Cheddar Bake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 25
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups uncooked small elbow macaroni (about 1/2 pound)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated sharp cheddar cheese, divided (8 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce package frozen peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh chives or green onions (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Butter a 1 1/2-quart baking dish
and set aside. Cook macaroni according to package directions;
drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, put cottage cheese and mustard in a food processor
and process until smooth. Pour into a large bowl and stir in the
sour cream and pepper. Then stir in the cooked macaroni, 1 1/2 cups
cheddar cheese, peas and chives. Mix well and add salt to taste.
Put in baking dish and sprinkle with remaining 1/2 cup cheddar
cheese. Bake 25 minutes or until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 396 calories, 23 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 38 grams carbohydrates, 49
milligrams cholesterol, 485 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
