<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brussels sprouts get richly special treatment
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Shari DiBiccaro of Butler, Pa., asked for a
recipe for brussels sprouts using bread crumbs, butter and sour
cream or mayonnaise, Holly Quinn of Chamblee (Ga.) submitted this
one. It comes from ``Farm Journal's Country Cookbook,'' published
by Doubleday in 1959. It's as good now as it was then.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Creamy Brussels Sprout Casserole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2quarts fresh brussels sprouts or two 10-ounce packages frozen
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons butter or margarine, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1cup sour cream or mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup minced fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Sliced pimento-stuffed olives (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   If using fresh brussels sprouts: Wash sprouts, trim ends and cut
an X in the bottom of each to hasten cooking time. Remove loose or
yellow leaves. Let stand for a few minutes in cool, salted water.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   If using frozen sprouts: thaw and proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons butter in skillet over medium heat. Add
brussel sprouts to hot butter. Stir to coat. Cover and steam about
10 minutes, shaking skillet occasionally. Check with fork for
tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   Add lemon juice and steam 2 minutes more. Add sour cream,
parsley, salt and pepper. Mix well. Heat through but do not allow
to boil. Place in an 8-by-8-inch baking dish. Top with sliced
olives, bread crumbs and remaining 2 tablespoons butter, melted.
Bake until lightly browned, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 199 calories, 5 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 74), 11 grams carbohydrates, 17
milligrams cholesterol, 341 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Julie Driggers of Lawrenceville (Ga.) has two requests: ``I am
looking for a coconut layer cake that has coconut milk and sour
cream in the dough. It makes a real moist cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, there is a recipe for white icing I use to have that
tasted like whipped cream.'' It had whipped cream in it, along with
other ingredients, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to use it with a four-layer blueberry cake I made with
canned blueberries. I hope you can help me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Elizabeth Ann Wright of Savannah (Ga.) asks for the recipe for
a sweet potato bread pudding with walnuts, white bread and
cinnamon-covered raisins. She'd also like information about
cookbooks featuring bread puddings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Phil Panuska (e-mail) is looking for a recipe for Popcorn Soup
like some his wife had during a vacation in Gatlinburg.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eleanor Chesser of Doraville (Ga.) would like a recipe for
Cranberry Bars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Freida Land of Lawrenceville lost her recipe for Chocolate Pie
cooked in an iron skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
