<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-VALENTINE-RECIPE     02-10 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-VALENTINE-RECIPES11-1STT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cupid in the kitchen recipes
 &HT;    By Betty Parham, staff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A NICE GUY WHO COOKS
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Joe Dobrowolski is a cream puff, according to Fran
Plunkett of Peachtree City (Ga.) _ who is also Mrs. Dobrowolski.
She met him at the airport in December 1997 while she was waiting
for her sister's flight to arrive and he was killing time before
departing to his hometown of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was eating a burger and drinking a beer when I asked to
borrow his pen so I could jot down my parking spot number,'' she
recalls. They talked for several hours, and during that time Joe
revealed to her that he would never marry again _ and that he loved
to cook.
</P>
<P>
   They exchanged telephone numbers and ``as we parted, I thought
`what a nice man,' and I would probably never hear another word
from him.'' Two weeks later he called, and Valentine's weekend of
1998 she enjoyed the first of Joe's fabulous meals. They married in
October and Joe even catered their wedding. Her favorite thing in
Joe's repertoire: his cream puffs with chocolate sprinkles, which
he made for her birthday in place of a cake.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Joe's Cream Puffs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 40 puffs Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint of heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Few drops vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 small box (3 3/8-ounce) instant vanilla pudding
</P>
<P>
   For the puffs:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour (see note)
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons semisweet chocolate morsels
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: In a medium bowl, mix whipping cream and
vanilla. Add pudding mix and beat until mixture stiffens.
Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   For the puffs: Place water and 1/2 cup butter in saucepan over
medium heat. Remove from heat after butter has melted but before
water boils. Pour into large mixing bowl. Add flour, stirring
vigorously by hand. Shape into a ball. Chill in refrigerator for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Place ball of dough in large mixing
bowl. Add one egg at a time, stirring after each. Dough will be
sticky and watery. Drop by tablespoonfuls onto baking sheet.
Drizzle drops of water on top of baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake puffs 35 minutes or until golden brown. Remove from oven
and puncture each with a small knife. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff each with filling and place on serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolate morsels and remaining 2 tablespoons butter in
double boiler. Drizzle over filled puffs. Serve immediately or
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Our tester said self-rising flour works best.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (1 puff): 76 calories, 1 gram protein, 6 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 5 grams carbohydrates, 37
milligrams cholesterol, 89 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   THE WAY TO A MAN'S HEART . . .
</P>
<P>
   Cheese souffle never fails to revive poignant memories for
Janice Vernon Slocum of Kennesaw (Ga.) of her beloved late husband,
Richard.
</P>
<P>
   She relates this scenario, which she said played out several
times over the course of her married life:
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are tucked into bed, stories read and prayers
said. Now I hurry down the stairs to begin a special meal for my
</P>
<P>
   dearest Richard. . . . I hear the car drive up and the buzzer go
off at the same time. How perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quickly I put the salad on the table, light the candles and,
pulling the souffle from the oven, I carry it gingerly to (the
table.) As he comes through the door tired and dragging, his face
lights up at the sight of that fluffy, puffed-up golden souffle
sending out the most wonderful aroma. I get a great big bear hug
from my man, and the rest of the evening is a delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheese souffle always soothed away the rough edges and made
him soft and delectable, just like the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cheese Souffle
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 1
1/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups hot milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash of cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sharp cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Melt butter in a medium skillet.
Add flour and blend. Add milk and cook until thickened, stirring
constantly. Add salt, cayenne and cheese and stir until cheese
melts. In a small bowl, beat egg yolks, then add to cheese mixture.
Cool. As cheese is cooling, beat egg whites in a medium bowl until
stiff. Pour cheese into egg whites and fold in well. Pour into
2-quart souffle or casserole dish. Bake 1 hour to 1 hour and 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 350 calories, 18 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 8 grams carbohydrates, 281
milligrams cholesterol, 603 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SWEETS FOR HER SWEET
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Grimes of Jasper says she'll always remember the role
this cake played in her marriage. She baked and sold enough of them
to earn enough money to buy her husband, Greg, a wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cream Cheese Chocolate Chip Pound Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a 9-inch tube or
Bundt pan. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, cream margarine, cream cheese and sugar. Add
vanilla and eggs one at a time. Beat on medium speed 1 minute. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, mix flour, baking powder, soda and salt. Add half
to cream cheese mixture. Mix well. Add remaining flour mixture to
cream cheese mixture and mix well. Add milk. Mix 1 minute. Stir in
chocolate chips and mix well. Spread into prepared baking pan. Bake
30-40 minutes or until wooden pick inserted comes out clean. Cool
at least 10 minutes on rack.
</P>
<P>
   Note: May be served with chocolate syrup or glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 269 calories, 4 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 31 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams cholesterol, 234 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APHRODITE'S FAVE: CHICKEN POTPIE
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken potpie is an aphrodisiac. Just ask my husband,
Robert,'' wrote Betty Jean Jordan. She made it for him on their
second date, and Robert, who at that time was used to eating frozen
dinners, was smitten. In the four years they have been married,
Betty Jean has tried many new dishes on Robert, who, she says, ``is
still a good guinea pig.'' He is diplomatic, too. When something
isn't any good, the worst Robert will say is, ``It's interesting,''
she reports. Sometimes, though, she adds, ``I go back to the
tried-and-true favorites such as the aphrodisiac _ I mean chicken
potpie.''
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Potpie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 1 hour, 20 minutes Cooking
time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 whole chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   For pie crusts:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   For white sauce:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (or more) milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce package frozen mixed vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken in a saucepan, cover with water and boil until
done, about 30 minutes. Chill thoroughly, then cut in bite-size
chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil an 8-by-8-inch casserole dish.
</P>
<P>
   For the pie crusts: Blend flour and salt in a medium bowl. Cut
in shortening until pea-size balls form. Add water, 1 tablespoon at
a time, stirring after each addition. Divide dough in half. Roll
out each half on a floured surface. Place one pie crust in the
bottom of the prepared dish and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the white sauce: Melt butter in a skillet over medium-high
heat. Add flour and stir. Gradually add enough milk in batches to
reach desired consistency and to make at least 2 cups sauce. Stir
constantly with a fork or whisk. Sauce will thicken as you stir.
Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large mixing bowl, combine
cubed chicken, mixed vegetables and at least 2 cups white sauce.
Add salt and pepper to taste. Mix thoroughly and pour into
casserole dish. Place second crust on top and trim overhang. Cut
out shapes with the trimmings and place on top of crust for
decoration, or freeze leftover dough for later use. Bake about
30-40 minutes, or until crust is browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 654 calories, 33 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 45 grams carbohydrates, 91
milligrams cholesterol, 573 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
