<SLUG> BC-FOOD-VALENTINE-RECIPES11-2ndTA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   ALL'S FAIR IN LOVE AND WAR
</P>
<P>
   As Ken Cain was preparing to move, he called Bobbie Pardue, the
agent who had sold him his home, to list it for sale. ``He
suggested I come to dinner and I thought it a little strange but
said, `why not?' said Bobbie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken started the evening with a glass of wine, then shrimp
cocktail, and then on to salmon steak. At that point I thought the
next course was going to be breakfast,'' she laughed. She did go
home that night with a doggie bag of delicious desserts, though.
</P>
<P>
   Three nights later he called again ``under the guise of showing
me something on the computer,'' said Bobbie. The menu consisted of
Rock Cornish hens and wild rice. They eloped 90 days later.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roast Cornish Game Hens
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 1 1/2
hours
</P>
<P>
   1 game hen per person (usually 1 1/2 pounds each), thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, quartered
</P>
<P>
   String
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons mandarin orange sauce (found in the Oriental foods
section of supermarkets) or sweet-and-sour sauce
</P>
<P>
   Canned mandarin orange slices (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Wash hen inside and out with cool
water. Pat dry with paper towels. Sprinkle 1/2 teaspoon salt and
1/2 teaspoon pepper into body cavity and rub it all over inside.
Sprinkle remaining salt and pepper on the outside and rub it all
over. Put quartered onion in body cavity. Truss bird by crossing
legs and tying them together, then folding the wings as though you
were putting an arm in a hammerlock. It might be necessary to tie a
string around the breast area to hold the wings in place. Smear a
thick coat of mayonnaise all over bird. Place on rack in shallow
baking pan lined with heavy aluminum foil. Place in center of oven
and cook for 1 hour, then baste liberally with orange or
sweet-and-sour sauce. Raise oven temperature to 400 degrees and
continue cooking for 30 minutes, basting with sauce every 10
minutes. Place on plate and garnish with drained orange slices
drizzled with sauce. Serve with rice pilaf.
</P>
<P>
   Per hen: 792 calories, 56 grams protein, 50 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 57), 27 grams carbohydrates, 187 milligrams
cholesterol, 1,926 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   THEY LIKE SHARING HEART TO HEART
</P>
<P>
   When Mattie Ulrich wants to cook her husband a romantic meal,
she gets right to the heart of the matter and prepares pizza shaped
like a valentine. ``Give my husband Italian food and he is a happy
man,'' says Mattie, who's been married to Ed for 39 years. She has
a nighttime version of her romantic pizza in which she shapes
salami and refrigerated pizza dough into a heart and uses tomatoes,
peppers and onions from her garden. She also makes a special
breakfast pizza.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast Pizza
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
about 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 can refrigerated pizza dough
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons diced green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons diced onion
</P>
<P>
   3 links precooked breakfast sausage links, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 slices American cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon strawberry jam
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Press pizza dough onto round pizza
pan. In a medium skillet, melt butter. Add eggs and cook, stirring,
until almost set, about 2 to 3 minutes. Spread eggs on top of
dough. Sprinkle with peppers, onions, sausage and shredded cheeses.
Bake until lightly brown and cheese is melted. Decorate each slice
with a heart-shaped cutout of American cheese with a drop of
strawberry jam centered on the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 366 calories, 19 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 58), 19 grams carbohydrates, 214
milligrams cholesterol, 746 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING UP SOMETHING NICE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is one of the many reasons Roberta Shambaugh fell
for her husband, Dr. George Shambaugh III. They're shown below and
on cover.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Catfish Fillets Twice-Cooked With Spicy Tomato Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 green bell pepper, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons fresh lime juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 14 1/2-ounce can Italian-style stewed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 catfish fillets (6 to 8 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh cilantro sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, combine olive oil and canola oil over
medium-high heat. Add pepper, celery, onion and garlic and cook,
stirring constantly, until onions are translucent. Add mushrooms
and saute until they are lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Add Tabasco sauce, cilantro, lime juice and tomatoes to skillet.
Cover, reduce heat to medium-low and simmer 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Shake lemon pepper on tops of fillets, then broil 4 minutes, or
until the surface is browned. Turn fillets and sprinkle with lemon
pepper. Broil for 4 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Add broiled fillets to skillet and simmer, covered, for 10
minutes. Turn fillets, baste and simmer 10 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer fillets to serving plate and spoon sauce with
vegetables over fillets. Garnish with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 290 calories, 34 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 9 grams carbohydrates, 115
milligrams cholesterol, 315 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT A DISH FOR ROMANCE
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Gamberetti La Donna or Gamberetti Valentino
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 large servings Preparation time: 40 minutes Cooking
time: about 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped sweet white onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   2 coarsely chopped cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Few stalks fresh basil, without leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh colossal shrimp
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound fresh small shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch powdered saffron
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh Italian flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh marjoram leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced brown Italian mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup artichoke hearts (bottled or canned)
</P>
<P>
   1 roasted red pepper (fresh or jar)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces angel-hair pasta, prepared according to package
directions
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, heat olive oil over medium heat. Add onion,
fennel and chopped garlic, stirring until soft but not brown, about
5 to 7 minutes. Pour into a blender container and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a steamer pot, place white wine, 1 clove quartered garlic and
basil stalks and simmer 5 minutes. While stock simmers, wash and
drain shrimp. Place colossal shrimp in bottom of steamer basket and
top with smaller shrimp. Cover and steam over wine stock about 3
minutes. When cool enough to handle, shell small shrimp and shell
colossal shrimp leaving tails on, and set aside. Strain the wine
stock and reserve. Add stock to blender container along with cream,
flour, lemon zest, salt, white pepper and saffron. Blend until
smooth, then return mixture to the saucepan. Add chopped basil,
Italian parsley and marjoram and simmer for 10 minutes over medium
heat to thicken. While the sauce is simmering, place Italian
mushrooms and butter in a pan and saute over medium-high heat.
Drain and prepare artichoke hearts by discarding the woody outer
leaves. Add the steamed small shrimp, sauteed mushrooms and
artichoke hearts to the sauce. Heat thoroughly. While the sauce is
heating, cut two 2-inch heart shapes from a roasted sweet red
pepper section.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon sauce over prepared pasta. Place a red pepper heart on top
of sauce in center of plate. Arrange two colossal shrimp around the
heart so that the tails form a point at the bottom of the heart and
the heads touch in the notch at the top of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 1,139 calories, 42 grams protein, 79 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 62), 69 grams carbohydrates, 380
milligrams cholesterol, 951 milligrams sodium, 8 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE MINE MALLOW
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1969 and Laura Shevlin, who now lives in the ``the
far exurbs of Atlanta _ Auburn, Ala.,'' was newly and unexpectedly
single and setting up a new apartment. She needed to lay carpet and
called on her friend Phil Shevlin to help. As compensation for his
efforts, she prepared a meal they still remember: Chicken Cordon
Bleu, Twice Stuffed Potatoes and her mother's recipe for Coffee
Mallow. They sprawled out on the new shag carpet and watched the
movie ``The Young Lions.''
</P>
<P>
   They married a few months later. This Valentine's Day, as they
fondly remember that ``lastingly successful dinner from long ago
and far away,'' the Shevlins will likely sip champagne by the fire
and maybe even rent ``The Young Lions.''
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Coffee Mallow
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup strong brewed coffee
</P>
<P>
   20 large marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Place coffee in a saucepan over moderate heat. Add marshmallows
and stir often until melted, about 5 minutes. Add vanilla. Place
saucepan in larger pan of ice water and chill mixture until it
sheets thickly from spoon. While the coffee mixture is chilling,
whip cream fairly stiff. Blend a little cream into the coffee
mixture; then fold the coffee mixture into the rest of the whipped
cream. Spoon into serving dishes and refrigerate until serving
time.
</P>
<P>
   Note: May be topped with a dollop of sweetened whipped cream and
a chocolate covered coffee bean.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 166 calories, 1 gram protein, 15 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 81), 8 grams carbohydrates, 55 milligrams
cholesterol, 19 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   COUPLE MAKES LOVING DEAL
</P>
<P>
   As far as Sally Boice is concerned, the present her husband,
Chris, gave her for Christmas was better than diamonds. Sally is a
dietitian and health educator, so food and nutrition play a big
part in her professional life as well as at home, where she is the
primary chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating her delicious meals day after day, I realized I may
have been taking her efforts for granted,'' said Chris. So for
Christmas he presented her with a ``check'' for 52 meals, to be
cooked by him every Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's even part of the deal that I don't have to clean up,''
says Sally. And that, to her, ``has to take the cake for the most
romantic cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is one early success:
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Maple Glazed Roasted Salmon
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings Preparation time: 5 minutes Marinating time: 20
minutes Cooking time: 22 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peeled fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons maple syrup, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 12-ounce salmon fillet
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   In a large platter, combine ginger, vinegar and 2 tablespoons
syrup. Add fish, skin side up. Cover and refrigerate 20 minutes.
Remove fish and pat dry. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Place a
baking sheet in the oven for 5 minutes. Place shallots and fish,
skin side down, on sheet. Sprinkle with salt and pepper and 1/2
tablespoon syrup. Bake 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Brush on remaining syrup and bake another 7 minutes or until
fish flakes. Sprinkle with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 320 calories, 34 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 31), 20 grams carbohydrates, 94
milligrams cholesterol, 79 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN CORDON WOO
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Price isn't sure if it was her Chicken Cordon Bleu that
took her friendship with husband Byron to the next level, but it
certainly didn't hurt. She rounded out the meal with Steamed
Artichokes With Lemon Mayonnaise, Green Beans Amandine and Garlic
Mashed Potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Cordon Bleu (The Easy Way)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   4 slices Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 slices honey-cured ham
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Parmesan bread crumbs, or 3/4 cup bread crumbs mixed with
1/4 cup Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pound chicken breasts lightly with a meat mallet to even
thickness. Place Swiss cheese and ham in center of each chicken
piece. Roll the breast to cover cheese and ham. Secure with
toothpick. Dip in butter, and then coat with bread crumbs. Place in
a pan and bake for 30-35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 477 calories, 62 grams protein, 22 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 4 grams carbohydrates, 174
milligrams cholesterol, 498 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
