<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-VALENTINE-COUPLES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cupid in the kitchen
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Henry Kissinger was wrong. Power is not the ultimate
aphrodisiac. Seductive as private jets, fat stock portfolios and
overnights in the Lincoln Bedroom may be, it's food that truly
warms the heart, heals the hurt and nourishes not only the body but
the soul.
</P>
<P>
   This was the sentiment shared by readers who wrote and called to
tell us sometimes funny, sometimes poignant and often very romantic
stories about how food, thoughtfully prepared and lovingly served,
sparked love and lasting admiration for a special person in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   In Donna DiLoreto's case, that would be her husband, Vincent
(she calls him Vincenzo). He's been lavishing his Irish-American
wife with loving gestures and romantic culinary feats for 32 years.
He sent flowers after their first date, roses on the second, then a
poem with her name in every line and, finally, an engagement ring
sparkling in a cocktail. On their fifth date, they married.
</P>
<P>
   One Valentine's Day, she recalls, he prepared her swordfish in
the shape of a heart, and then surprised her with a heart-shaped
diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people go on cruises to faraway places and think it's so
romantic,'' says Donna, a high school Spanish teacher from
Alpharetta (Ga.). ``For Vincent and me, preparing a meal together,
sipping wine, listening to music, and then eating fabulous food,
now that's amore.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dr. George Shambaugh III, his talents in the kitchen helped
lead him to the altar.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the widowed Chicago endocrinologist retrieved
from his briefcase the business card of a woman he'd met briefly
seven years earlier at a convention here. Recalling the pleasant
conversation they'd had at a booth at the World Congress Center, he
decided to write her. A telephone friendship ensued. He invited her
to visit him in Chicago. But having suffered a traumatic divorce,
she was skeptical _ until her daughter convinced her to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the chicken etouffee, the twice-cooked catfish and the
homemade cherry pie, and things warmed up considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``His food was a balm to emotional recovery,'' said Roberta
Shambaugh, who then struck up a long-distance romance with him and
married him a year later. ``Before he would return to Chicago, he
would even make sure I had food in the freezer until the next time
he came.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues to ensure she's well-fed in between commutes until
he retires this summer and moves to Atlanta permanently.
</P>
<P>
   A great meal was also the turning point in Byron and Shannon
Price's relationship. The two had been platonic friends for years.
After Byron helped Shannon cope with the death of her mother, the
two began to realize that their relationship went deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon invited him to her apartment for ``a thank-you meal to
see what was what.''
</P>
<P>
   After dining on steamed artichokes with lemon mayonnaise,
chicken cordon bleu, green beans amandine and homemade garlic
mashed potatoes, Byron declared his love that night. ``I don't know
whether it was me or the food, but we were engaged a year later and
married last November,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Rachel Grimes of Jasper don't go so far as to credit
her chocolate chip poundcake with their engagement. But it will
forever hold a place in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   When the couple decided to marry, Rachel, a college student on a
limited income, wanted more than anything to buy Greg a fine
wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying about how to get the ring when I heard God say,
`You can cook, can't you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   She could _ and she did, making more than 70 of her renowned
poundcakes and selling them for $10 apiece. Today, ``Greg never
takes his ring off and I still make these cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not always a sumptuous feast or prized culinary
specialty that resonated in the hearts of the people who wrote to
us.
</P>
<P>
   For Deanna and Walt Pettit of Marietta (Ga.), it was the memory
of a disastrous chocolate cake they made together nearly 50 years
ago as kids. She was 11 and he was 12 ``when somehow we got elected
to bake a chocolate cake for a Valentine's Day party we were having
with our friends,'' Deanna wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The cake was ``so bad we threw it around like a Frisbee, dropped
it and it bounced . . . but we put icing on it and served it
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   That memory lingered long after Deanna's family moved away and
they married different people. But both marriages ended in divorce,
and eventually the childhood friends found their way back to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   They've been married 39 years and have three children and three
grandchildren. And yes, every time they eat chocolate cake, they
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
