<HEADER>
A9125 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-RESPONSE-     02-10 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-RESPONSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS FACE DELUGE OF LETTERS ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some Americans may be tired of the impeachment
trial of President Clinton, but not Wil Watkins of Vallejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described artist and patriot has written 100 letters
this year to newspapers and members of Congress urging that Clinton
be removed from office. He has watched the Senate proceedings every
day on public television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care a great deal,'' said Watkins, 69, who writes under the
pen name Captain Omoo, a character in a Herman Melville novel.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins is one of many people who have flooded newspapers around
the country with letters, faxes and electronic mail about
impeachment in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The response represents the largest volume of correspondence to
the San Francisco Examiner on any news story in at least a decade,
and editors at newspapers across the country say they, too, are
hearing from huge numbers of readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not care, but they're writing us to tell us they
don't care,'' said David Boerner, Voice of the People editor for
the Akron Beacon-Journal in Ohio. ``They keep writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Johnson, letters editor at the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
said the flood of mail began last August when independent counsel
Kenneth Starr released his report on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Starr report came out, we were just inundated,''
Johnson said. ``We were getting upwards of 300 letters a day. It
ran that way for two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the volume of letters has since dropped, but
remains heavy _ about 75 impeachment letters each day, or half of
all letters received.
</P>
<P>
   David Kirp, a professor at the Goldman School of Public Policy
at the University of California at Berkeley, said the people
writing letters represent the vocal minorities on both sides of the
impeachment debate who remain engaged, while polls show most
Americans want Congress to move on to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the CNN junkies, the MS-MonicaWatch junkies,'' Kirp
said. ``It doesn't surprise me that there is a continued
fascination with it. The people who watch the impeachment trial all
the time are the same folks who want to talk about it and write
about it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ora Jones, an employment counselor at St. Anthony Foundation in
San Francisco, was steamed up enough last week to fax a letter:
``Even Jerry Springer knows when to stop the show. Why don't the
Republicans?''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 54, a die-hard Democrat from Richmond, said the story
remains the hot topic of conversation at her office and her Baptist
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like it to be over with, but I still keep up with
what's going on,'' Jones said. ``The man made a mistake. He
apologized. I think we should forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   Letter writers tend to break into two types: first-time writers
who get fired up about a particular issue, and regular writers who
make a hobby of making their opinions known.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter camp is Thomas Edwards of San Francisco, a
67-year-old conservative Republican. He boasts that he stopped
counting after 6,000 of his letters were published in the Examiner,
gay newspapers, news magazines and on ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and his partner, Thomas Lundquist, 45, also a regular
letter writer, share a disdain for Clinton. They often post their
published letters in the front window of their San Francisco flat,
along with a couple of anti-Clinton books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of one-finger salutes,'' said Edwards, who posts
all his letters with stamps of President Richard Nixon, his hero.
``It's politically incorrect to be a gay Republican. I wear that
badge with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards served in the U.S. Army in Europe for two years, and has
repeatedly blasted Clinton in print for dodging the draft. He
detested the New Deal liberalism of Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt,
and calls the Clintons the ``Marxist god-children'' of the
Roosevelts.
</P>
<P>
   For Edwards, impeachment has just provided another avenue for
his anti-Clinton rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that a man who is an admitted liar, who is
significantly a perjurer, who is an adulterer, who is a
draft-dodger who turned his back on his country. ... I don't think
the man deserves to be in office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others said only something as serious as the possible
removal of the president would inspire them to write.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren Callister, an 82-year-old architect from Tiburon, said he
was so bent out of shape by the Republican efforts to impeach
Clinton that he typed nearly two dozen letters to members of
Congress, newspapers, the American Civil Liberties Union and the
California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``In architecture, we think of things being in scale. This is
just so out of scale,'' said Callister, who said he fears the
precedent of removing a president for relatively minor misdeeds.
``It's like making the medicine cabinet the most important project
in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise Hullinger, a retired elementary school teacher from
Chicago, said she decided to write to the Examiner while reading
the newspaper on a Hawaiian cruise and seeing an item asking for
readers' views on impeachment. On stationery from American Hawaii
Cruises, she wrote: ``Despite the polls showing that people favor
Clinton, I have NEVER MET a person who thinks he should remain in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Woodruff, editorial page editor for the Missoulian in
Montana, said he has seen a slight drop in letters since January.
``I think what you see and have seen is a realization that the
president is not going to be removed from office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Writers of letters to the editor do not necessarily reflect the
views of the populace. According to Richard Aregood, editorial page
editor of the Newark Star-Ledger in New Jersey, they are more
likely to be older, retired and ``have more time to fulminate and
get p----d off.''
</P>
<P>
   And editors say the letter-writers reflect a more conservative
point of view than that of the communities the newspapers serve.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment letters still make up close to 75 percent of the
average 225 letters the Star-Ledger receives each week. But Aregood
said he believes the people writing are the only ones who still
care about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about as tired of (impeachment letters) as I am of this
whole thing,'' Aregood said. ``The ones who hate him, hate him. The
ones who don't hate him, don't hate him. ... I can remember no
issue with the boring sameness of opinion in such profusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
