<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAKU-STRATEGY-BOS &LR;      02-10 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKU-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPIAN PORT'S OIL GUSH TRICKLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ In a way, Scott Barber's map of the Caspian
Sea resembles those lottery tickets Americans scratch to win _
except the jackpot here could be worth several trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, who heads the Baku office of the US oil company Unocal,
displayed a line of green patches extending offshore from
Azerbaijan's capital. These are the winners, where ``world class
oilfields,'' as Barber puts it, have been found, fueling dreams of
rapid prosperity for Azerbaijan and the other impoverished former
Soviet republics of the Caspian basin.
</P>
<P>
   But those dreams, echoes of Baku's storied past as a source of
the oil fortunes of the Nobels, Rockefellers, and Rothschilds have
yet to come true. An ambitious $4 billion plan to build a pipeline
to ship the crude out of the landlocked region to Western markets
has stalled; so has the Clinton administration's strategy to change
the geopolitical order in a part of the world that has spent most
of the century as Moscow's colonial outpost.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the delay is that world oil prices have hit
25-year lows, making potential investors wary of spending to build
a new pipeline. But Barber's map reveals another snag. Around the
green patches are many more pink spots. These are areas where there
ought to be oil, but no one will know for sure until someone
explores them. And then there are the offshore projects that have
already turned up losers.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the field where a consortium led by Unocal has
already drilled twice, and come up dry. If one more scratch of the
ticket, a test drilling scheduled for this summer, fails to yield a
winner, Barber says the consortium is going to pack it up. It would
not be the first. Last month, a $3 billion project led by the US
company Pennzoil, another of the Western oil giants that flocked to
Azerbaijan after the 1991 Soviet collapse, announced it would close
down its operation after its test wells revealed disappointing
crude reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is: Which estimates of the Caspian's reserves
are true? Some say 200 billion barrels, which would make it second
only to the Persian Gulf and the world's most important new source
of energy well into the next century. Others say it is closer to 20
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Oil executives here say it is too early to declare Baku's boom a
bust. About 15 other international consortiums are still in the
early stages of seismic research of their plots. But the mood has
definitely soured in this rundown medieval city of abandoned oil
derricks and faded mansions _ traces of last century's boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are starting to get negative about it,'' said
Sabit Bagirov, a former president of Azerbaijan's state oil
company. ``The early estimates were exaggerated, and now we are
coming down to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Azerbaijan International Operating Co., a consortium
of international oil majors that in 1994 signed the $7.4 billion
``Contract of the Century'' to drill the first wells, announced
plans to cut costs by 20 percent and eliminate 25 to 30 expatriate
staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the international consortium controls the winners on
Scott Barber's map. The flow from these fields is being pumped out
through two small pipelines, one that takes it north through Russia
out to the Black Sea port of Novorossiisk, and another that travels
through the Georgian port of Supsa. These two routes are capable of
carrying the 105,000 barrels per day that Azerbaijan International
Operating Co. expects to be shipping by the end of the year, but
inadequate to manage the 800,000 barrels a day expected by the year
2007.
</P>
<P>
   To meet this demand, the plan has always been to build a larger
pipeline out. But now questions have arisen about the Azerbaijan
International Operating Co. timetable. Plans to raise production
from current levels to 300,000 barrels per day in 2002 are on hold,
the consortium's officials say, because the transportation costs
too much to make it profitable given the low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Now, low prices and concerns about reserves have added doubts to
plans for a new pipeline already embroiled in international
controversy over which of several routes should be chosen. The US,
Azerbaijan, and Turkish governments are pushing to build it through
Turkey to the Mediterranean port of Ceyhan. But oil companies, wary
of the high cost, would prefer the shorter, cheaper route through
Supsa, where it could be shipped across the Black Sea and through
the Bosphorus out to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a final decision on the route for the main pipeline
was delayed three times. This year looks like more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're by no means close to deciding which of these routes we
should take,'' said the consortium's vice president, Robin
Branagan. ``What we need as we move toward making this decision is
an idea of how much oil there is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, oil executives are indicating that the amount of oil
flowing out of Azerbaijan will not exceed the capacity of the
existing pipelines for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's naturally dialing down each time we delay the formal
announcement,'' said Barber of Unocal, which is also a member of
Azerbaijan International Operating Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends that the Ceyhan route, which
runs 1,075 miles through Georgia and across Turkey, would secure
Turkey's role as a major player in the Caspian region. That, in
turn, would enhance the status of a loyal NATO ally and Islamic
nation whose secular, European-style society could serve as a role
model for post-Soviet states like Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, and
Turkmenistan. The Turkish route would also mean the oil would avoid
Russia and Iran, traditional powers in the region that covet the
pipelines for the chance they provide to earn transport fees and
influence local politics.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is building a pipeline to the Caspian in an apparent effort
to lure the oil companies, but while that would be the shortest
route, the threat of US sanctions against companies that deal with
the Islamic state has kept American firms from participating and
put a damper on any other deals.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is also lobbying to have the large pipeline go through
its territory. Initially seen as a security risk, because of a
60-mile stretch that goes through separatist Chechnya, the Russian
route has operated without problems since the first small amounts
began flowing out in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of Russia controlling all the oil has little
support in Azerbaijan, where Moscow's past rule is remembered with
bitterness and current intentions are seen with suspicion. When
Russia recently agreed to base state-of-the-art weapons in
neighboring Armenia, with whom Azerbaijan fought and lost a war ,
Azerbaijani leaders saw it as an attempt to pressure them, and one
official even called for NATO bases near Baku to counter the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest opponents to the Turkish route are the oil
companies, who say the $4 billion cost is too steep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put the oil out through Ceyhan, you could be looking at
$4 per barrel transport costs, which, given today's low cost of
oil, could make profits nonexistent,'' Branagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has threatened to block the other routes by limiting
traffic through the Bosphorus straits, which it controls. All this
adds up to a mess no one has figured out how to solve. Some oilmen
are encouraged by a Ukrainian project to build a pipeline from
Odessa to its main pipeline that transports Siberian oil to Europe,
but that, too, has its pitfalls, among them the proximity of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   About the only people optimistic that a deal will be concluded
are Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there can be an agreement within the next year,''
Richard Morningstar, US special envoy on Caspian issues said last
week, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijanis are beginning to realize that their economy will
not feel the salutary effects of their oil for years to come. The
first profits will go to the companies to pay for their costs. And
that is only when the pipeline is built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there would be instant millions,'' said Etibar
Mammadov, who finished second in Azerbaijan's presidential
elections in October. ``Now these hopes are fading.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
