<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HEARTLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWLING BUDDIES SEE `FACE-SAVING EXERCISE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The politics of the sometime bowlers in lanes
seven and eight follow the same trajectory as too many of their
rolls: far left of center.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the six breaks 100; two score 81. Everyone cheers
the rare spare. Gutter balls elicit a group groan. No one really
wins, and no one playing below an impressive collection of neon
beer signs really loses.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than the friends can say about Washington and the
rest of the country these days. A while back, they decided to stop
discussing the presidential impeachment proceedings at the
nonprofit housing agency where they all work. Otherwise, they
figured, someone might quit in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they wish the Senate would do the same. They say they want
the closed-door debate that got under way Tuesday to lead to a
quick resolution. None of them expects serious discussion, on the
assumption that all minds are made up already. Instead, hours,
maybe days, will be devoted to devising strategies to do no more
than save face, as they put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they're trying to do is figure out how to get it over
with,'' said Anne Mavity, 35, who scored a
none-too-shabby-for-her-crowd 96.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just finishing the face-saving exercise,'' said Herb
Frey, who ran unsuccessfully for the Minnesota legislature and
didn't fare much better at the bowling alley, bringing in an 81.
``I don't expect anything out of Washington anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Steve Thomas, 42 and the victor with a score of 125, ``The
biggest issue for people is frustration. And it's both parties.
There's nothing coming out of the Democrats or Republicans. They're
all meant for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say these bowlers don't lean toward one side. They
do. Two voted for consumer advocate Ralph Nader in the last
presidential election, and another two say he's too centrist for
their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the friends and colleagues are clearly among the 65
percent of Americans who polls say did not favor impeachment by the
House and who do not want President Clinton removed from office by
the Senate. Although they vary in their condemnations of his affair
with a former White House intern _ ranging from ``Who cares?'' to
``His behavior disgusts me'' _ they mostly say enough with the
partisan attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is we've elevated this to an impeachment trial,''
Thomas said. ``He did wrong. But it seems like this was the only
way they could come up with to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Melanie Majors, a 32-year-old who bowled an 81: ``It
proves we don't control the process, or else this wouldn't be
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even in go-its-own-way Minnesota, where former wrestler
and Reform Party candidate Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura is now
governor, the friends' political views are uncommonly liberal. And
yet they assume _ and polls show _ that their outrage over wasted
time and energy in Washington isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this country really wants to be outraged about ethical
issues, let them be concerned about homelessness,'' Majors said.
``Those of us who don't live in Washington and aren't glued to our
TV sets are concerned about real problems. I tell you I want my
money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Thomas, untying his rented black-and-tan bowling shoes,
``I'm not saying I'm not outraged by what happened (between Clinton
and Monica Lewinsky) but how much more do we need to talk about it?
What does anyone in Congress have left to say on the subject?''
</P>
<P>
   The colleagues, taking in a quick game or two at trendy Bryant
Lake Bowl, say no one they know obsesses about Clinton's fate
anymore. Each read sex-drenched report put out by independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr, but now they try to avoid news on the
trial. Thomas even turned off Minnesota Public radio, a beloved
institution in the state where the program Lake Wobegon is set,
after a report left him explaining ``sexual relations'' to his
7-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me everyone is apathetic by now,'' said Mavity, an
ardent Clinton defender who calls him ``a policy wonk
extraordinaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Interjected Thomas, ``Well, everyone has an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Mavity, ``but when you're out with your friends,
this isn't what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bowling alley's smoky restaurant and bar, Eileen Shore's
reaction to a question about the trial seemed to underscore
Mavity's remark. Shore laughed. Then she added that she had sworn
off the subject after a friend asked if she could please change the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been following it way too closely,'' said Shore, a
51-year-old lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Added her sister, assistant preschool teacher Donna Shore, 46,
``Every waking moment, I'd say.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sisters opppose forcing Clinton from office, although both
also say he should have resigned. Both also voted for him twice but
say they might not again, if he was able to run and depending on
his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, they have grown disillusioned: with Clinton,
with Congress, with press coverage that they say has focused too
much on the salacious aspects of the scandal and not enough on the
substance. They don't expect their opinions to change in the coming
days because they have no expectations of Washington politicians
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's going to be a discussion in the Senate, it's going
to be all about saving face,'' said Donna Shore. ``I don't think
anyone is under the illusion that he's going to be convicted.
Whatever they talk about at this point doesn't matter. The whole
thing is moot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1338EST &QL; 
