u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      02-10 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE KILLING RENEWS BRUTALITY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Amadou Diallo walked home last Thursday morning,
a little past midnight, he probably had little cause for worry. His
block on Wheeler Avenue, in the Bronx, is quiet and reasonably safe
_ a row of two-story brick apartment houses, with well-kept stoops
and nice cars parked along the curb.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he stood in his doorway, the world now knows, Diallo _ a
22-year-old African immigrant, a street vendor who kept out of
trouble and carried no weapon _ was gunned down by four police
officers firing a total of 41 bullets from their 9mm semiautomatic
handguns, hitting Diallo with 19.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since, Diallo has supplanted Abner Louima _ the
Haitian immigrant who was tortured and sodomized by police officers
two summers ago _ as a symbol of New York City's problem with
police brutality and race.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting has also rekindled concerns that the brutality
might be the flip side of the police department's crime-fighting
strategy, which has led to the city's lowest level of felonies in
over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, more than 2,000 protesters, mainly black, held a
peaceful rally outside the US courthouse in downtown Manhattan to
demand that federal prosecutors take over the case. The US
attorneys office is ``monitoring'' the probe, which is being
handled by the Bronx district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   This was a follow-up to a rally in the Bronx last Sunday, half
as large. The Reverend Al Sharpton, who led both demonstrations,
promised more to come.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers, who have been placed on desk duty but not yet
arrested, are members of an elite corps called the Street Crimes
Unit, whose unofficial motto is ``We Own the Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit's 200 officers _ one-half of one percent of the city's
police force _ were responsible for 40 percent of the gun seizures
last year. They are openly aggressive, frequently shaking down
``suspicious'' characters for the slightest reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that the aggressive policy is one of the
cornerstones of why crime has been reduced,'' Norman Siegel,
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, said Tuesday. ``On
the other hand, it is also why civilian complaints against the
police have increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Formal complaints have risen 39 percent since Rudolph Giuliani
became mayor, from 3,600 in 1993 to 5,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Though African-Americans constitute a quarter of the city's
population, they have filed more than half the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The darker your skin,'' Siegel said, ``the more chance you'll
have your civil rights violated.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, Latinos, who tend to be lighter-skinned,
have filed 27 percent of the complaints. They make up 26 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesmen have said Diallo was ``acting suspicious'' when
the four plainclothes officers approached. They also say the
officers mistook him for a rapist and that he did not respond when
they told him to ``freeze.''
</P>
<P>
   Every speaker at Tuesday's rally scoffed at this claim, and said
it did not explain, in any case, why the officers fired 41 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the officers emptied their 16-bullet chambers. One fired
five bullets, another four.
</P>
<P>
   A deliveryman for a nearby hamburger and pizza restaurant, who
gave his name only as Robert and said he is known to everyone in
the neighborhood as ``Flaco,'' said he was standing on the corner,
a few hundred feet away, when the shooting took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like an Uzi war,'' he said Tuesday afternoon,
standing outside Diallo's apartment house. ``I thought it was a
drug fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This description was consistent with that of another witness,
who told columnist Juan Gonzalez in Tuesday's Daily News: ``First
came three shots _ bang, bang, bang. Then there was a pause. Then
came a barrage . . . like a machine gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the questions that must be answered,'' Siegel
said. ``If they fired, then paused _ and, as they now admit, Diallo
was unarmed _ why did they proceed to fire some more?''
</P>
<P>
   The red vestibule at 1157 Wheeler Ave., where Diallo stood as
his body was pumped with bullets, has an area of only about 24
square feet. The bullet holes _ made by the 22 shots that missed
him _ are now labeled with detectives' markings: ``BH1'' (for
bullet hole 1), ``BH2,'' and so forth. Some of the holes are more
like gashes, tearing out huge slices of the side wall's plaster.
</P>
<P>
   The streets a couple of blocks away are not considered safe at
night. Drug sales are common, and the police are a constant
presence.
</P>
<P>
   But Wheeler Avenue, a working-class block of mainly Africans and
Dominicans, appears different. ``This is a quiet block,
family-oriented, people know each other,'' Maria Gonzalez said,
walking her daughter home from school.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Delgado, a retired warehouse worker, remarked, ``This is
safe. You can send your kid to the corner store any time.''
</P>
<P>
   A retail manager, who would give his name only as Joe, agreed:
``Rarely anything happens on this block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
