u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-ABDULLAH-BOS &LR;      02-10 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-ABDULLAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SCHOOLMATES REMEMBER A KING IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He waited on tables, vacuumed rugs, made his bed, shot pool,
chewed tobacco, obeyed curfew, captained the wrestling team, and
often played a prank that would trigger an international crisis
today.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's newly crowned king, during his formative years at
boarding school in Western Massachusetts, delighted in his ability
to ditch his well-armed bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he could scare them,'' recalled Jim Smith, a coach and
instructor at Deerfield Academy when King Abdullah of Jordan was
just a boy and a prince. ``He was a rascal. But he was a wonderful
young man.''
</P>
<P>
   That man, who watched somberly Monday as his 63-year-old
father's shroud-wrapped body was lowered into a grave at the royal
cemetery in Amman, Jordan, has indicated he will continue his
father's moderate policies _ a task for which his western friends
and former schoolmates said he is well-prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah, they said, has always exceeded the expectations of
headmasters and coaches, teachers and proctors, and kings and
queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known Abdullah to be extremely wise,'' said
Christopher Smith, one of the king's closest friends at Deerfield
and a guest at his 1993 wedding. ``He was more mature really than
people of our age when we were growing up. I've always known him to
be compassionate. This is a man who is truly genuine and eager to
take advice from wherever it may come.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old father of two was first sent off to boarding
school in England when he was 4. But most of his youth was spent in
Western Massachusetts, where in 1977 he enrolled as a sophomore at
Deerfield, where the boys wear ties, today's tuition is $23,500,
and even princes are expected to toe the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Abdullah, he was beautifully attired in his
best Seville Row clothing, and I said, `Young man, do you know how
to run a vacuum cleaner?' '' said Bryce Lambert, a now-retired
English teacher. ``And he said, `I've Hoovered.' I told him to keep
on `Hoovering' because he was moving into the cleanest dormitory at
Deerfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert said Toni Gardiner, Abdullah's English-born mother and
the second wife of King Hussein, told Deerfield faculty members
that she was intent on raising her son to ensure that he could take
care of himself if his father ever suffered a reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   That meant, with the exception of the beefy security guards who
waited outside his classrooms and accompanied the team bus to
sporting events, that Abdullah was treated like any other student
in a school whose alumni include US senators, Nobel laureates,
acclaimed authors, and titans of industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Smith, whose duties at the school included running its
dining hall, recalled how Abdullah feigned indignation when it was
his turn to wait on tables, a duty expected of every Deerfield
student.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me and said, `I think it's a shame that the
prince of Jordan has to wait on tables,' '' Smith recalled. ``It
was tongue in cheek, you know. And I grabbed him by the necktie and
I said, `Your old man might be king of Jordan, but I'm king of this
dining hall.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when the prince put up a large contingent of
American friends at a plush Jordanian hotel for his wedding, he
greeted Smith at the airport, telling him: ``I wanted another king
at my wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him today and I think, God bless him, he's really got it
in his lap now,'' said Smith. ``We know this is a kid who can do
it. I'm sure he's going to rise to the challenge. Being an old
football coach I just want to say to him, `You know, kiddo, it's
now the second half. Get out there and give it your best.' And I
know that's exactly what he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Smith, a Connecticut native and now an advertising
copy writer in Los Angeles, said he has turned down national
television interviews because he did not want to risk saying
anything that could be misinterpreted about his close friend and
old classmate, now a key figure in the fragile world of Mideast
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abdullah has many of the same qualities that his dad did,
including that great human ability to touch people without making a
big deal of who he was,'' Smith said. ``At the same time, Abdullah
has always had the confidence and natural leadership ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship, Smith said, was cemented by the unwritten rule
that the prince's station in life would command him no special
deference except for intense loyalty and protection of his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the occasions when Abdullah had to be the prince, it was
instantly clear that he was prepared and capable of acccepting the
mantle of responsibility,'' said Smith, who as a 17-year-old
acompanied his friend to his native land. ``When I witnessed him
meeting with dignitaries and the people of Jordan, he had a direct
way of communicating and still had a very common touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert said he recently sent a letter to Abdullah, who as a boy
lived with him at the 1760 Ephraim Williams House, where they shot
pool and watched football games together. The letter, he said, was
to encourage the new king during trying, transitional times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had such a great sense of humor, and I wrote him and I
said, `Whatever you do, don't let them take that wonderful smile
away from you that you always had at Deerfield,' '' Lambert said.
``It was interesting to watch him today as he carried himself with
such dignity and then to think of the times I'd beat him in pool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
