<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EXPAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS LOSE REHBERG IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Cleveland Browns decided not to do their
established opponents any favors. In Tuesday's expansion draft,
they left the salary cap cloggers alone and decided to take chances
with the young, the unproven, and the inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the established Todd Rucci, who had played in 44
straight games for the Patriots, the Browns selected third-year
guard/tackle Scott Rehberg, a 6-foot-8-inch, 335-pound project who
never could climb past Damon Denson, Ed Ellis, and even rookie
center Jason Andersen on New England's depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns made Rehberg their third pick. Pro and college
personnel assistant Joe Ziobro, who was representing the Patriots
at the draft in Canton, Ohio, then pulled back running back Sedrick
Shaw from their list of exposed players, a logical move given the
recent injury to running back Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Rehberg was drafted by New England in the seventh round, the
230th player taken in 1997, out of Central Michigan. His claim to
fame is that he was a teammate of New York Yankees shortstop Derek
Jeter at Central High in Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Rehberg had been notified by the Browns that he would be
selected early in the draft, and he made the trip to Canton, where
he donned a Browns cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' said Rehberg. ``I enjoyed my time with the
Patriots and I think I've learned a lot from (former offensive line
coach) Paul Boudreau and (assistant line coach) Jeff Davidson. To
come to a new situation where there's a chance to step in and play
is something I've been building up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehberg might be one of the linemen protecting Tim Couch, the
University of Kentucky quarterback who is expected to be the top
selection by the Browns in the college draft in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful to block for a guy like Couch,'' said
Rehberg. ``But I'll do my job for whoever is back there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns liked the film they saw of Rehberg, who started his
Patriots career as a tackle and was moved to guard at the start of
training camp by Boudreau (who was let go at the end of the
season).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of our younger offensive linemen ahead of
Scott,'' said Patriots head coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   No other Patriot players were taken by the Browns, so wide
receiver Vincent Brisby ($1.8 million), defensive lineman Ferric
Collons ($2.2 million), and Rucci ($1.75 million) remain on the
Patriots' payroll.
</P>
<P>
   But for how long?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we feel a player isn't playing up to the salary we're
paying him, we may attempt to restructure the contract so it's more
in line with what we feel the player should be paid,'' said
Patriots vice president Andy Wasynczuk. ``The players not selected
come back to us, and now we'll make decisions based on our cap
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   They have already attempted to restructure Brisby's deal, but
agent Michael George has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Rucci's agent, Jack Bechta, said, ``As long as other starters
are being paid in Todd's range, I see no reason to restructure the
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bechta is concerned about Rucci returning to the Patriots,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally and emotionally,'' said Bechta, ``Todd and his
fiancee were planning on living in Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, of the five Patriots on the list, the most logical to be
taken was Rucci, a younger veteran whose salary was high but not
enormous. The Browns made Detroit Lions center Jim Pyne, at $1.85
million, their top pick, and the salaries of players chosen
thereafter seemed to decline rapidly until the Browns took 49ers
cornerback Antonio Langham and his $3.02 million salary at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear that the Browns' objective was to take younger
players with smaller salaries,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Collons, whose salary rises from $535,000 to $2 million next
season, with a $725,000 bonus due March 1, may not be back. The
Patriots put him on the list because they didn't want to pay that
large an increase in his salary. Two years ago, the Philadelphia
Eagles made Collons a big offer as a restricted free agent and the
Patriots matched it, feeling they couldn't do without him at the
time. But since then, Chris Sullivan has supplanted Collons as the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, the first player selected with a Bill Parcells
compensation pick (third round in 1997), hasn't blossomed as
Patriots vice president Bobby Grier had hoped. Shaw did come to
camp last summer with a better attitude, but it became evident that
Edwards was a better player and he easily took the starting job
after the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots attempted to use Shaw as a kick returner, but he
never showed the ability to break one. Late in the year, after Shaw
had a meeting with Grier, he began to play more to give Edwards a
break.
</P>
<P>
   Had Edwards not been injured, Shaw would have been left exposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
