<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI COP-OUT WON'T HELP DSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts families in crisis need an advocate. Governor Paul
Cellucci is sending them a cop.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Jeffrey A. Locke as interim commissioner of
the state Department of Social Services confirms the worst fears of
those who worry that this administration does not know the
difference between child protection and parental prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Locke is a career prosecutor, the former head of a
white-collar-crime unit in the Middlesex district attorney's office
and a specialist in drug cases in the US attorney's office. He has
no background in social work, no experience in child welfare
administration, no record on the divisive issues he will confront
as head of an embattled agency that handles more than 100,000
complaints of abuse or neglect every year.
</P>
<P>
   What he does have is strong Republican ties, and time on his
hands. He is the son of former state Senate Minority Leader David
Locke and the brother of state Representative John Locke. He lost
his campaign for Norfolk district attorney last fall and was then
passed over by Cellucci for public safety secretary. He is said to
be angling for a judgeship, though he denies any such lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Locke's personal merits, it is clear that politics and
public relations played a bigger role than policy considerations in
his selection. Coming on the heels of two high-profile raids on
allegedly neglectful households, the appointment of Locke will
reinforce long-held suspicions on the street that the mission of
DSS is to take your kids, not to help your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first job is keeping kids safe,'' Locke said Tuesday. ``I
don't think my experience as a prosecutor is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency, under fire for failing to remove five children from
squalid conditions in Everett, last weekend pulled a total of 10
children out of homes in Methuen and Framingham, citing unsanitary
conditions. This was a coincidence? Does the governor think we do
not recognize damage control when we see it? Does he think reactive
measures are a substitute for a genuine child-protection
philosophy?
</P>
<P>
   In trying to stem the flow of bad ink about DSS, Cellucci
continues to ignore the underlying cause of the hemorrhaging. This
is a department at war with itself. One blue-ribbon commission
after another in the last decade has studied the problems plaguing
DSS, only to have their recommendations ignored or underfunded. The
outgoing commissioner, with no frontline experience in social work
herself, was unable in six years to form an alliance with the
caseworkers she was expected to manage. Caseworkers, scapegoated by
those at the top, resort to practicing defensive social work rather
than risk having their decisions second-guessed on the 6 o'clock
news.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cellucci insisted on Monday, DSS is ``not in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his record, it is hard to understand why the governor
would think we would take his word for that. During his campaign
against Scott Harshbarger last fall, he refused to participate in a
debate on issues affecting children or even to respond to
pre-election questionnaires about those issues.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Jeffrey Locke is more realistic about the
challenge he is undertaking. ``We certainly have a department that
could use some direction,'' he said. ``I bring an outsider's
perspective, a common-sense approach that, in the interim, might
get the place on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke anticipates he will serve no longer than six months,
during which time the Cellucci administration will conduct one of
those ``nationwide'' searches that too often unearth the perfect
job candidate right there on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Locke should pick up where the last Foster Care Commission left
off. That panel pulled dozens of DSS cases at random for review by
an independent team of experts. Expecting to find a handful of
troublesome cases, the commission instead found widespread problems
with resources and referrals indicative of a systemwide breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Why not repeat the experiment? If, as the governor insists, the
Everett ``house of horrors'' was just an aberration, we will all
feel reassured. If not, perhaps Paul Cellucci might see the wisdom
of having the state's child welfare agency run by a social worker,
not a cop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
