<HEADLINE>
AS SITE FOR CONVENTION, HUB COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &UR;  &LR; _ The finalists have showcased their assets and
soft-pedaled their liabilities, but as the Democratic National
Committee decides where to hold its 2000 national convention,
numbers matter.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates, alternates, and hangers-on need to get there, then
find a place to meet and a place to sleep. The numbers are kept by
PKF Consulting, leading analysts of the hospitality business. The
numbers-crunchers at Parnell, Kerr, and Forrester, headquartered
here, tabulate hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really makes money from a big political convention, but
it does give you exposure,'' says Gary L. Carr, PKF's director of
communications. ``Planning for a big convention goes through a
nuts-and-bolts process that asks three basic questions. One, how
big is the convention center? Two, how many hotel rooms does the
city have? Three, is there good airline access?''
</P>
<P>
   If proximity and efficiency of the airport dominated, Boston
could weave the bunting now. But the size of the hall and the
number of mattresses are powerful, too. PVF's 1998 report finds the
following:
</P>
<P>
   Boston's convention center is 193,000 square feet. It has 12,220
rooms and 22,000 in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's convention center is 297,000 square feet. The airport
sits in a distant prairie, and Denver has 4,800 hotel rooms
downtown and 17,200 in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the convention center is 894,000 square feet.
While the leading airport, LAX, is frequently fogged in, the City
of the Angels has 92,350 hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Boston argues that the Fleet Center could serve as a big hall
and claims that more hotels are en route, too. ``People who plan
conventions are really uneasy about these things. They want to know
if a facility is up and running,'' Carr says. ``It would be nice if
Boston had that extra square footage, but right now it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But PKF's senior vice president, John A. Fox, sees a bright
future for Boston's convention business even if new hotels are
stalled by politics and financing. (The hotel phrase, ``turn-down
service,'' takes on a perverse meaning in Boston, where bankers and
politicians ignore or oppose projects that provide economic
stability.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the investment community's view, the break-even point in
hotels is an occupancy rate in the high 60s,'' Fox says. ``Boston's
rate is close to 80 percent. To be precise, in 1998, it was 78.8
percent, with an average room rate of $177.65. That puts Boston
right up there with the highest rates in the Northeast, right
behind New York and Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very healthy occupancy level and one of the highest
that Boston has run for some time,'' says Fox, who has studied the
hotel business since 1971. He suggests that convention centers and
hotels share prospects for a long life. ``We're not looking at the
next quarter, but 20 to 30 years,'' he says. ``Step back and take a
look. Faneuil Hall and the waterfront were all undeveloped in the
early '70s. State Street office building hadn't happened. Boston
had that significant tourist component, the whole historical thing,
but now Boston is known as a much more urbane, sophisticated
business center.''
</P>
<P>
   Geography once dominated convention choices, which explains why
Democrats and Republicans have assembled in Chicago 25 times.
Baltimore is the runner-up, but the Crabcake City last held a
convention in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolic choices are sometimes successful. Republicans met in
Detroit in 1980 to suggest that the GOP was a pal of working
stiffs, even if the choice meant that some delegations stayed in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, where Democrats met in 1908, and Los Angeles, host to
Democrats in 1960, are trying for their second conventions. But
important politics happened in Boston, in 1775. Numbers matter, but
the ``historical thing'' that describes Boston also defines much of
America. In 2000, it would mean more than a mint on the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
