<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STEP CLOSER TO PROTESTANT UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An important religious event took place in St. Louis recently _
and it wasn't Pope John Paul II's whirlwind 30-hour tour through
the Midwestern city on the banks of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant meeting largely overshadowed by the pontiff's
visit, representatives from nine Protestant denominations,
representing 20 million members, convened in St. Louis and moved
one step closer to realizing a 37-year-old goal of forging a united
Christian body.
</P>
<P>
   The Consultation on Church Unity was born out of a desire to
fulfill a Biblical mandate summarized in the book of Ephesians:
``There is one Lord, one faith, one baptism, one God.''
</P>
<P>
   As the report issued at the end of the meeting noted, ``the
unity we seek to manifest is not our choice but God's gift.'' But
living up to the words in Ephesians has been difficult for
denominations with long histories of strained relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have figured after all these years that folks would
have quit, but they didn't, and I think they are going to be
rewarded for it,'' said the Rev. Ed Rodman of the Episcopal Diocese
of Massachusetts, who attended the meeting late last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to divisions among the churches that have, in
many instances, existed for hundreds of years it should not be
surprising that it takes a good number of years to heal those
divisions,'' said the Rev. Diane C. Kessler, executive director of
the Massachusetts Council of Churches, who also was at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   For people in the pews, the agreement among the nine mainline
denominations may eventually mean this: exchanging clergy for
Sunday services; having one universally recognized baptism, and
pooling resources by, for example, combining youth groups and
sharing a youth minister.
</P>
<P>
   These would be big steps considering that in many communities
there is still little collaboration among Protestant churches of
different denominations, even though the churches typically share
very similar theological roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even something that would seem so simple as picking up the
phone can be a big deal for people,'' Kessler said. ``That's what
makes this kind of ecumenical work so challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, a more closely allied Protestant body also might
bring renewed vigor and political clout to mainline denominations
whose influence in wider American society has been steadily
declining for the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2002, according to the agreement hammered out in St.
Louis, the nine denominations would publicly proclaim that they
have joined together to form a new religious body _ Churches
Uniting in Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later the denominations would agree to accept each
other's clergy _ a step that is still uncertain because of
disagreements over the office of bishop, which is central to the
Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this agreement were to come to pass it would literally
reverse the Reformation, which led to the fragmentation of
Christianity,'' Rodman said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult obstacles on the road to Christian
unity is the issue of race and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the nine denominations _ the African Methodist
Episcopal Church, the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church and
the Christian Methodist Episcopal Churches are among denominations
that exist because blacks were not welcome in white churches. And
the vast majority of the nation's churches are still racially
distinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really can't talk about becoming one until we deal with
racism,'' said the Rev. Gregory Groover, pastor of Charles Street
A.M.E. in Boston, who represented the African Methodist Episcopal
Church in St. Louis. ``If there is one factor that really separates
us more than doctrine, more than theology, more than tradition, it
is race.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine denominations committed themselves to overcoming the
legacy of racism by signing an agreement to, among other things,
identify and end church practices that smack of prejudice and
actively promote the integration of congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The other congregations participating in the Consultation on
Church Union are the Episcopal Church, Presbyterian Church U.S.A.,
the United Church of Christ, the United Methodist Church, the
Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) and the International
Council of Community Churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a lot of hard work but I'm very excited about
this,'' Groover said. ``I do believe in Scripture and I do believe
it is the will of Christ that we should be one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the defender of Roman Catholic
doctrine and one of Pope John Paul II's closest confidantes, will
come to the United States to discuss the controversial issues of
homosexuality and feminism with bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, starting Wednesday, Feb. 10, will take place in San
Francisco, a stronghold for the gay rights and women's movements,
both of which have criticized the Vatican's position on
homosexuality and the role of women in the church.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican considers homosexuality a sin and opposes same-sex
unions and allowing gay couples to legally adopt children. The
church also has tried to shut the door on debate on whether woman
can be priests.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzinger, a conservative intellectual who has punished liberal
clergy and Catholic theologians, is scheduled to meet with bishops
from North America and Pacific islands.
</P>
<P>
   --Several hundred clergy members across the nation have signed a
petition calling on Israel and the Palestinian Authority to respect
human rights as a necessary step to achieving peace in the Middle
East. The petition is sponsored by the Search for Justice and
Equality in Palestine/Israel in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   --The Massachusetts Historical Commission has awarded the Old
North Church a $100,000 preservation grant to finance the
restoration of two historic church properties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have comments or ideas, we want to hear from you. Send them
to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; or via e-mail to religion(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
