<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONES WE LIKE ARE THE ONES LIKE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The screenwriter Nora Ephron has made a great deal of money
exploiting the premise that a scrawny, shambolic guy with a
receding hairline (Tom Hanks) can hook up with Ms. Wholesome
Suburban Glamorpuss (Meg Ryan) through a random series of events.
In Ephron's ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' the pair met on a radio
call-in show. In ``You've Got Mail,'' they meet via the most random
medium yet invented _ the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up to Valentine's Day provides fertile ground for
Hollywood hankie jobs extolling the chanciness of true love. In the
just-released ``Message in a Bottle,'' yet another megastar with a
hair problem (Kevin Costner) links up with a gorgeous, blond Boston
newspaper columnist, thanks to Neptune's nautical note-bearing
network.
</P>
<P>
   New story same as the old story. Noel Coward worked this
territory in his screenplay for David Lean's enchanting ``Brief
Interlude,'' in which Celia Johnson and Trevor Howard make love (in
the old-fashioned sense of the phrase) in a suburban train station.
It is certainly romantic to imagine that chance encounters at
commuter stops lead to true love, that Internet chat rooms aren't
populated only with sickos and pedophiles, or that messages loosed
upon the waters will be retrieved by drop-dead blondes hankering
for romance.
</P>
<P>
   It is romantic, but not very realistic.
</P>
<P>
   What better time to dust off the lecture on assortative mating,
or how men and women really find their partners? Assortative mating
is the opposite of random mating. Like, say, the otters, we humans
climbed off the ark with one purpose in mind: to make the world a
better place. If you think this means being nice to your neighbors,
pledging money to public television, and voting Democratic, you are
wrong. It means strengthening our gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish this, we select mates whose characteristics match
our own. This is called positive assortative mating and is probably
the main reason why the chimpanzees were reduced to bit parts in
the movie ``Jumanji,'' while we humans produced it.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists, biologists, anthropologists _ the whole science
gang _ have known for several decades that men and women who marry
tend to have similar IQs, comparable waistlines, a predetermined
height ratio, and even correlate positively for earlobe length.
People with nice teeth marry other people with nice teeth. The rich
marry the rich. Random mating would be disastrous for the gene
pool, as even Hollywood acknowledges. Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks
correlate positively on many different indices, not least of which
is asking price per picture.
</P>
<P>
   This subject is close to my heart because I am a victim of
positive assortative mating. When my wife and I tell friends that
we met in the Country Formerly Known as the USSR, we hear the
inevitable reaction: ``Oooh, how romantic!'' Not really. After a
small amount of informational foreplay, we learned that we had
grown up in the same quadrant of the same city and even attended
the same grade school. Indeed, our third-grade teacher came to our
wedding and gave us Ernst Mayr's classic ``Populations, Species and
Evolution'' as a wedding present. (Just kidding about the present.)
</P>
<P>
   The dream dies hard. The largest-selling category of books in
the country is romance. These novels often focus on what the
science gang calls negative assortative mating _ the forbidden
couplings of field hand and mistress of the house, or the
impossible liaisons of lord and scullery maid. People love to read
them because they have so little to do with real life.
</P>
<P>
   It is surely no accident that the most ``romantic'' relationship
in Western literature is an example of positive assortative mating.
Romeo and Juliet were both marriageable teenagers from noble
families in Verona. It would have been a very dull wedding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
