<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-FIANDACA-2TAK     02-10 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FIANDACA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFREDO IN WONDERLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In his 41 years in the fashion business,
designer Alfred Fiandaca has catered to every kind of lady who
lunches, from Joan Rivers to Joan Collins to Joan Bennett Kennedy.
Still, even this seasoned friend-of-the-prima-donna didn't know
what to think of the devastated client he found crying on his
boutique doorstep here early one morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darling, what's wrong?'' he exclaimed, in his soft
stage-whisper voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alfred, I couldn't sleep all night!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sick?'' Fiandaca asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what came over me Tuesday,'' she said, sniffling.
``I don't know why I ordered chiffon ruffles on my dress rather
than crepe. I hate chiffon!''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Fiandaca's winter wonderland. It's another world down
here; almost a throwback in time. Wealthy women spend their days
shopping, lunching, and then shopping again to prepare for a
whirlwind of at least three charity parties every night of the week
during the social season.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these women are so concerned about image that they
refuse to wear the same dress twice in one season, or even in
subsequent winters. ``I'll pull a dress out in a few years.
Definitely not the next year,'' says Eileen Cornacchia, a Palm
Beach resident and race-horse owner who attends 15 black-tie events
a year.
</P>
<P>
   In this circle, department store shopping isn't an option
because it's imperative to have a dressmaker who keeps track of who
among the who's who bought which gown. ``This is a small town,''
says Joanne Cutner, associate publisher of the local Palm Beach
Society weekly magazine and a Fiandaca customer. ``The worst thing
is to see someone else in your dress.''
</P>
<P>
   So this explains why Fiandaca _ a 60-year-old East Boston, Mass.
native _ winters here rather than near his stores on Boston's
Newbury Street or Madison Avenue in New York. ``Women work in New
York,'' he says. ``They don't have time to shop. Here, women need a
new outfit every night.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, really, that, amid such a harvest of evening-gown
wearers with money, Fiandaca would be disenchanted. But frankly, he
finds Palm Beach confining. He literally can't go anywhere without
bumping into someone he knows. Virtually all conversation revolves
around money (Who has it and where did they get it) and image (Has
she had a facelift? Who did it? Is she the second or third wife?
Which beachfront property do they own?).
</P>
<P>
   Women introduce themselves the old-fashioned way, by their
husband's name. ``I'm Mrs. William Ireland,'' said one Fiandaca
client visiting his shop recently.
</P>
<P>
   And the party circuit is so ingrained in the city's culture that
even Fiandaca's doorman gets excited when the designer's picture
appears in Palm Beach Society.
</P>
<P>
   Fiandaca _ who spends his evenings with friends when he's in New
York or Boston _ is literally obligated to attend client functions
or dinner parties five nights a week here. ``If the co-chair or
chair of an event is wearing my gown, I have to buy a ticket,'' he
says. ``That's how you drum up business.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Fiandaca isn't complaining. After all, the designer
_ who specializes in day and evening women's wear that can be
customized by fabric, color, and design _ relies on these women for
his livelihood and personal fulfillment. ``This is my passion. Take
this away and you take my life away,'' he says. ``A day without the
next collection would be like a day without the sun. . . . Watching
a woman feel wonderful about herself, that's a joy. It's worth the
price of admission.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this isn't hard labor. Over the course of a recent
weekend, Fiandaca's workload included attending a Friday night
cocktail party at Connoisseur Antiques. Standing in a room filled
with glittering $6,000- to-$180,000 antique European chandeliers, a
dapper Fiandaca _ dressed in a beige Italian suit and yellow Hermes
tie _ sips champagne and munches on shrimp hors d'oeuvres. When
someone asks ``Do you know the lord?'' he doesn't even blink; he
quickly extends his hand. (Jesus? No, Lord Peter Knowland of
Alswick _ Belgium).
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as he and two clients stroll down Worth Avenue (an
upscale boulevard featuring the likes of Chanel, Tiffany &AMP; Co., and
Louis Vuitton), Fiandaca patiently smiles as the two women gossip:
</P>
<P>
   Customer 1: ``Have you been lifted? (That's face-lifted.) You
definitely look different. Not that you looked bad before.''
</P>
<P>
   Customer 2: ``I just had my eyes done. I did the lift last year.
I'm almost too tight.'' She doesn't bother to mention, although
Fiandaca knows, that she's also just had her lips done, which is
why she's talking through her teeth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Fiandaca keeps a straight face during the pomp and
circumstance of the International Red Cross Ball, the No. 1 party
of the year here, according to some socialites.
</P>
<P>
   For the big event, the designer is picked up at home in a
chauffeur-driven white Jaguar by his date and client Emily DiMaggio
(the wife of former Red Sox Dominic DiMaggio, who didn't want to go
to the ball). ``We're going to have fun tonight!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the lobby of The Breakers Hotel, as hotel guests
stop and stare, Fiandaca (in a white tie and tuxedo tails) and
DiMaggio (in a pink-and-red Fiandaca sheath gown) are greeted by
three men in red-velvet medieval costumes who blow trumpets to
announce their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-FIANDACA-2ND &LR;      02-10 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FIANDACA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PALM BEACH, Fla.: ... their arrival.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The couple pass through a receiving line where nine US
ambassadors to Bosnia, Romania, Sweden, Columbia and other
countries (who are the recipients of Red Cross funds) shake hands
stiffly, alongside their tiara-wearing wives. ``It's considered
tacky to wear a tiara if you're not in the (ambassadorial) court,''
he whispers, referring to other tiara wearers in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real program begins. A Marine color guard enters the
grand ballroom (decorated in fragrant roses, orchids, and lilies)
and all guests rise. Then they sit. Then they stand as the
ambassadors are announced one by one. Then the guests sit. Then
they stand for the national anthem and Fiandaca can't contain
himself. ``This is like going to Catholic Mass,'' he quips.
</P>
<P>
   But his efforts pay off. The following Monday, a picture of
Fiandaca and DiMaggio appears on the front page of The Palm Beach
Daily News in a story about how DiMaggio dropped a $4,000 brooch
from local jeweler Seaman Schepps at the ball. ``There's no way you
can pay for that kind of publicity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's funny that Fiandaca is now traveling in the circles his
father envisioned for him when he encouraged him to become a doctor
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiandaca family has been stitching for three generations.
His grandfather Alfred designed women's clothing for a company on
Boylston Street. His father, Pasquile, designed men's suits for a
Cambridge store. And his mother, Adeline, designed costumes for
local performers. Working in his father's store at 12 years old,
Alfred says, ``I learned tailoring there and pattern drafting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fiandaca says he was never interested in men's clothes.
``Working with my dad, it was the same old suit: two-button,
three-button, single-breasted, double-breasted . . . With women's
clothes there is so much more drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiandaca attended the now defunct Traphagen School of Design in
New York in 1956. At 19, he returned to East Boston and rented an
empty shop on Maverick Street for $25 a month. ``My dad knew all
these men, so he sent me the wives,'' he says. Before long, a woman
named Jennie Volpe showed up. Her husband, John Volpe, had just
been elected governor and she needed an inaugural suit and gown.
The singer Connie Francis followed and then the socialite Frances
Fahnestock. ``She came every week. She became my patroness. From
her, I got anyone who was anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 21, Fiandaca was on Newbury Street, and his
designs were selling in Jordan Marsh's designer salon. Later he
would sell in Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue, and Bergdorf
Goodman as well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the actor Michael Douglas called to request a gown for
actress Louise Fletcher to wear to the Academy Awards. Douglas had
co-produced ``One Flew Over the Cukoo's Nest'' and Fletcher was
nominated for playing nurse Mildred Ratched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Fiandaca says. ``And then she
actually won!'' Fiandaca would later design clothes for Joan
Rivers, Joan Bennett Kennedy, Anita Baker, and Raquel Welch.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of client roster, Fiandaca would probably be a
household name today except for a disaster that hit in 1981. He
became involved in a palimony suit with a former partner. The
battle between the two men in court generated headlines, which
wasn't good for business. ``He was suing me for half my assets,''
Fiandaca says. ``It was devastating emotionally and financially.
The only way to get out of it was to stop working.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiandaca has since restructured his company, working with
business partner Caroline Collings, a Boston entrepreneur. He
opened his store in Palm Beach three years ago because so many of
his clients winter here. ``I felt it was a shoo-in,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the designer's hunch was right. His cozy salon with
upholstered walls, marble fireplace, and wooden ceiling (located
parallel to Worth Avenue on Via Mizner) is like the town hall.
Customers like Eve Holmes drop in all the time to gossip. ``Has
Jean been in? What did she get?'' Holmes asked on a recent
afternoon, referring to another client.
</P>
<P>
   Clients like Claude Rosinsky _ a former saleswoman in New York
for Hubert de Givenchy _ come in to admire his work. ``His dresses
are elegant and stunning. They're the kind of thing you want to
keep and pass on to your daughter-in-law,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And shoppers like Joan and Randall Yearwood, of Franklin, Tenn.,
stop by because they consider Fiandaca more than a designer; he's a
friend. ``Alfred, did I hear you may not come to the Swan Ball (a
Nashville society event)? You'd better be there,'' said Randall
recently. ``I want you to come to the house for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, in a town so caught up in style that even the
parking tickets are wrapped nicely in plastic, there are few other
designers taking up seasonal residence. For women like Cornacchia,
that means Fiandaca's custom-made clothes are one of the few
options in town. ``Start thinking Kentucky Derby, Alfred,'' she
said one recent Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Juggling three stores in three cities takes its toll. Fiandaca _
who does his sketching and design work late at night after his shop
here is closed _ says he sometimes wishes he could just be a
designer who ``sits in an ivory tower'' and creates. ``But then I
would lose human contact,'' he says. ``That's what gives me the
spark, the inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   And _ for better or worse _ the social invitations. ``Next week,
I have three parties so far,'' he says. ``But I think one more is
coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
