<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIA'S YOUTHFUL LEADER EYES US AS KEY TO KOSOVO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you are the youngest prime minister on the planet,
wide-eyed in the ways of wielding power, you tend to notice things.
</P>
<P>
   When Pandeli Majko, age 31, was chosen for the perilous task of
leading Albania four months ago, the first thing he noticed upon
entering the prime minister's office in his capital, Tirana, was
the bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of them,'' he grinned Saturday in an interview in
Boston. His country of 3.5 million Albanians, with the seething
Serb-run cauldron of Kosovo on its doorstep, is struggling to
restabilize after a chaotic emergence from a half-century of
communist dictatorship that kept that the hilly Balkan backwater
imprisoned in a preindustrial-age straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off a giddy meet-everyone-who-counts stop in Washington _
where Petrit Bushati, Albanian ambassador to the United States,
scored face time for his new boss with President Clinton, the
Cabinet officers running State, Defense, Justice and Commerce,
various congresspersons, and Richard Holbrooke, the Clinton
administration's chief Balkan troubleshooter _ Majko (pronounced
May-co) heard Clinton single him out at the capital's annual Prayer
Breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I shook hands with him after the Prayer Breakfast,'' said
Majko over coffee at the Ritz. ``With him praying aloud for us, and
his interest in our problems in Kosovo, after that, I did not feel
(I was) the youngest prime minister in the world. He filled me with
optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeached president was on trial for his political life down
the street, where his enemies run the show, but the Albanian was
convinced he had the commander-in-chief's undivided attention.
``When I met with President Clinton, you cannot imagine how much
attention and how much concern he felt about the problems of our
region, and of Kosovo in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congress may have been derailed by the Impeachment Express,
but the US role of policing the planet is still ongoing, 24-7
despite whatever the domestic squabble, no matter how squalid. Our
NATO allies want up to 4,000 US ground troops in harms way to deter
Slobodan Milosevic, the odious Serb Slaughterer, whose depredations
have roiled the Balkans for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Majko picks his words carefully; he was trained as a mechanical
engineer at University of Tirana, and can converse in Italian,
German, and English as well as his native tongue, though his
French, he shrugged, is a tad rusty.
</P>
<P>
   America's role as superpower, its military might, as well as our
economic firepower, make the United States the one power base that
can make undeniable impact on all the other players, Majko
suggests. It was the threat of air strikes by US and British
aircraft that forced Milosevic to accept an emergency international
diplomatic powwow on Kosovo in Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   Majko thinks having US troops on the ground in Kosovo will be
crucial to separating the combatants. Why? ``American soldiers
proved so far to be the only ones who were not taken hostage in
Bosnia,'' he replied. Neither the Serbs nor the other factions in
the bloodied former Yugoslavia wanted to risk the kind of
retaliation the US Air Force can bring within hours of an outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my strong belief that without this very serious
involvement of the US administration, we will not have a
longstanding peace in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: If you guys don't do it, no one can.
</P>
<P>
   He is embracing the US free-market model, and in the place of a
torn-down monument to the late dictator Envir Hoxa, ``We will again
put a monument there _ to Mother Teresa,'' the Albanian girl who
became a nun.
</P>
<P>
   Did he get everything he wanted in D.C.? Not quite. He wanted to
pick up a toy for his child. And he wanted to meet a Kennedy; JFK
was his hero from boyhood. He raved about a friendly letter from
Ted Kennedy. ``I believe President Kennedy made a real revolution
in politics,'' said Majko, echoing something similar said by
Mikhail Gorbachev years ago of Kennedy's skill:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a very important element _ communication.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to communicate with one's political foes is what is
missing in the Balkans, said Majko, where the blood over ethnic
cleansing flows from a root cause that ``we have so much history''
in such a small space.
</P>
<P>
   With a prescience that is in short supply in Washington these
days, Majko stressed the need to communicate, ``talking to people,
particularly your opponents.'' Lean of frame and with streaks of
premature gray in his black hair, Majko laughed. We just had a
``friendly soccer match'' with the opposition in Tirana, he said.
Soccer balls instead of bullet holes in just four months, he
laughed. ``We won, by the way.''
</P>
<P>
   He also won in Washington, scoring diplomatic commitments, and a
$320 million contract between the Albanian telephone apparatus and
New World Telecom, which Majko hopes will lead to further
privatization of formerly state-held enterprises and a new wave of
Western investment.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank and International Monetary Fund meetings laid
groundwork for further investments, he said, and he is hopeful that
the advent of the euro will lift all the boats, in JFK's famous
phrase, even Albania's little put-put of an economy. ``The euro is
one of the good things, new, and very positive for the psychology
of Europe . . . the old Europe after two world wars does not exist
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the American presence is indispensable in our region to
guarantee a peaceful settlement. Yes, there is the euro,'' and that
it connotes, ``but Europe still needs the American presence,''
which means the attention of whoever is president, for which Majko
is exceedingly grateful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
