<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-MUSEUM-ART-BOS &LR;      02-10 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-MUSEUM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAX CONNECTS CANDLES AND CARS AT THIS MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH DEERFIELD, Mass. _ OK, auto aficionados, Valentine's Day
is a week away, and I'm going to whisper two ``can't-miss'' words
in your ear.
</P>
<P>
   Ready?
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Candle.
</P>
<P>
   Did you get it?
</P>
<P>
   Good.
</P>
<P>
   Now to explain what links cars 'n' candles in Western Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when young Mike Kittredge was following the
American Dream and building his Yankee Candle business, one of his
personal indulgences was a neat car or two.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 was a 1970 Jaguar, bought in 1972 with the first of his
hard-earned candlemaking profits. Fortunately (in retrospect), that
Jag cost him so much to repair that he sold it and used the
proceeds to resume his candlemaking business.
</P>
<P>
   But cars remained a key component of his operation.
</P>
<P>
   As Yankee Candle grew, many times Kittredge would be leaving the
building only to find a cluster of folks around his car, talking
about (no surprise) cars.
</P>
<P>
   These folks were the shopped-out companions of Yankee Candle
patrons. Mostly, but not always, they were males.
</P>
<P>
   They had come along for the shopping, but ran out of gas (so to
speak) before their companions were finished and stepped outside
only to find a special interest car.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yankee Candle, being a good corporate neighbor, also
started hosting an annual antique- and special-interest-car show to
benefit Mothers Against Drunk Driving. The shows were a huge hit,
bringing in big crowds and making some serious money for the
charity.
</P>
<P>
   But they also made a lot of money for Yankee Candle, too. On
auto show days, the daily receipts were up appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mr. Kittredge didn't build a company that was sold for a
reported $400 million last April by ingnoring details like this.
</P>
<P>
   So he opened a small auto museum across the street from the main
Yankee Candle operation on Route 5. He put some of his own cars on
display and also exhibited other folks' cars as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he expanded the main retail building to include a
separate museum (we told you this is a big place) capable of
displaying 85-90 cars. ``The kind of cars that make you go WOW!''
is how YC describes its ever-changing display. An example: A 1977
Volkswagen Beetle with 150 original miles that was bought from
Jerry Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cars belong to the museum, some belong to Kittredge,
and many are on loan from individuals. How do these latter cars
wind up in a museum?
</P>
<P>
   That's where museum employees such as historian John Schieffelin
come in.
</P>
<P>
   He's constantly overseeing the collection and schmoozing with
visitors, many of whom surprise him with their revelations of rare
or restored cars, trucks, and motorcycles in their possession and
in need of a safe place to be stored and displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Ken Burian of Hampden, Mass., was visiting the museum
and mentioned to Schieffelin that he had a rebuilt 1948 Indian
Scout racing motorcycle sitting in his grandmother's cellar. The
two got talking, and now the motorcycle is on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people call to offer cars,'' said Schieffelin. ``Some
are just looking for winter storage, but our goal is to find cars
that fit in our displays.'' When the two goals agree, a vehicle
goes on display.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's exhibits fit various loose categories, generally
displayed in rows. There's a row of early 1900 steam, electric, and
gas vehicles; an oddball row, featuring the Seinfeld VW, a
Metropolitan, Isetta, Citroen, Amphicar, and Messerschmitt; a
tremendous collection of eight Ferraris scattered throughout the
room; a row of American Muscle cars; a row of NASCAR and other
American race cars; a row of European sports car racers and much
more.
</P>
<P>
   One current favorite is a 1912 Renault Brewster Landaulette. You
might not recognize the name, but one was in the hold of the
Titanic and now rests at the bottom of the North Atlantic. And a
similar one was used in the movie for a love scene with Leonardo
DiCaprio and Kate Winslet.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the ``Do not touch'' signs are out on 85 of the 87
cars on display.
</P>
<P>
   But not on two of the cars.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has a 1982 Ferrari 308 GTsi and a 1961 Rolls-Royce
Silver Cloud II on the floor as ``photo op'' cars. Visitors can
climb in and have their pictures taken _ as long as they remembered
a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if they didn't, one-time-use cameras are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Mike Kittredge didn't build a company that was sold
for a reported $400 million last April by ignoring details like
this.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Museum admission is $5 for adults, $2 for children under 11;
children under 4 are free.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
