<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-IMMUNOGEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMUNOGEN SAVED BY $45 MILLION INFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With just over $2 million in cash and no chance of
commercializing a promising drug, ImmunoGen Inc. was facing a bleak
future.
</P>
<P>
   But in an 11th-hour rescue, SmithKline Beecham PLC, the large
British and American pharmaceutical company, agreed last week to
spend up to $45 million to develop and commercialize ImmunoGen's
proposed cancer-fighting drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were living hand-to-mouth for the past four years, and at
one point we were down to just enough cash to meet two bimonthly
payrolls,'' recalled Mitchel Sayare, chairman and chief executive
of the 18-year-old Norwood, Mass. biotechnology company. ``Now we
can at least focus on science instead of fund-raising, and morale
is up.''
</P>
<P>
   ImmunoGen, whose research pedigree is from Boston's Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute, was among the first generation of Boston-area
biotech firms. At one point it employed 180 people and had
extensive Massachusetts manufacturing facilities in Canton and
Norwood, plus laboratories in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   But it also hit hard times before many others, when its
first-generation cancer drug, a monoclonal antibody, proved
disappointing during extensive clinical trials. Without its lead
drug, the company downsized, laying off more than 100 people and
shutting down most of its manufacturing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, ImmunoGen's auditor, PriceWaterhouseCoopers LLP
said it had substantial doubts that the company would be able to
continue, citing significant losses and the need for additional
financing. The company said it had enough cash on hand to last
until February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of its leading drug candidate, ImmunoGen stock
plummeted from a high of 24 in January 1992 to a recent low of 1
1/16, only to climb back to about 3 after last week after the
SmithKline deal was announced. ImmunoGen shares closed Tuesday at 2
3/4, down 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   And while its other research area looks to find potential
cancer-fighting drug candidates under a partnership with BioChem
Pharma Inc., a Canadian pharmaceutical company, ImmunoGen's major
cancer research had to be cut back for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sayare maintains the new drug is designed to treat colorectal
cancer, pancreatic cancer, and certain forms of lung cancer. It
works by using toxins, drugs coupled with monoclonal antibodies,
that promise to destroy cancerous cells in tumors without adversely
affecting nearby healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   ImmunoGen has completed extensive testing of its newest drug in
mice and monkeys, said Sayare. Those trials showed such promising
results that SmithKline agreed to fund human testing. Sayare said
he hopes to begin a phase 1 safety trial this fall. ``We never lost
hope,'' said Sayare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
