<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KISS COLLECTION MAKES A BIG IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a kiss is just a kiss, sweeter than wine but just
something to build a dream on. Or something to put in your pocket
and take home like a souvenir ballpoint pen.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schaible, a 36-year-old eligible bachelor, has been
collecting kisses for the last 16 years. ``I must have, oh, about
1,500, maybe more,'' said the traveling automation technician from
Kirkland, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Some technician, huh? Like, how or why does a guy go about
collecting kisses, say, like butterflies or stamps? ``Well, I do a
lot of traveling in my work, and I began collecting what are really
just `lip prints' so I would have something to show where I was,
and when,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are, on the brink of Valentine's Day, remembering first
kisses _ Scott says his first real kiss was when he was ``about
15'' _ and hoping for others, when along comes a guy who collects
them with all the apparent detached passivity of a postage stamp
collector. (I would use that numiswhatever word, but it always
makes me stumble.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one was a lady here in Seattle. We were just friends
going out, and she had dabbed her lips with a napkin before eating,
and I saw her lip print on the napkin and said: `Hey, would you
sign that and put today's date on it?''' Schaible recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this frequent flier became a frequent trier of lines like
that throughout the United States, Mexico, Canada, South America
and Australia _ everywhere his work took him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, a lot of women think it's weird ... but they still
do it. I figure only 5 percent, probably even less, won't.''
</P>
<P>
   So, let's get this straight. A reasonably good-looking guy from
Seattle is spending the week on a job assignment in, say, Brazil,
and he showers after a long day's work and goes down to the hotel
lounge and orders a pre-dinner drink and notices across the room a
strikingly beautiful woman twirling an ice cube around in a tall
frosted glass.
</P>
<P>
   Right off the travel brochure. She has long, glossy black hair
that falls like silk over her sandlewood shoulders, and her dark
eyes move slowly in the back bar mirror, taking in everything and
everyone and finally stopping as she meets his reflected gaze.
There is just a moment of lock-on as her radar paints his target
... or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   And then he takes his glass, stands up and slowly approaches her
at the bar. He smiles softly, nods, never taking his eyes off hers,
and he puts his drink down, extends his hand. She notices he is
handing her a ballpoint pen like the ones in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' he says, ``but my name is Scott Schaible and I'm
from the United States ... from a place you probably never even
heard of, called Kirkland, actually Juanita, in Washington state,
and I couldn't help noticing your exquisite lipstick color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to have an extensive lip-print collection and was
wondering if you wouldn't mind simply making a lipstick impression
on your drink napkin there and signing it ... just your first name,
and put the date on it, too, if you would. I sure would appreciate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   I was getting all warmed up about this scenario when Scott
assured me that it wasn't like that most of the time. He doesn't
date these women, doesn't even try most of the time. ``That's not
the intention. I just want to have something to remind me of where
I've been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lip-print trolling is particularly good in Seattle on, say,
Halloween, when women are doing their Vampira numbers. ``Sometimes
I might get into Seattle on Halloween and be partying at the J&AMP;M
(Cafe) and one year I got 113 in one night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, obviously at least one of those black, purple and other
exotic lip impressions should remind him of where he was and what
he was doing on Halloween of a given year.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he's never met anyone else who collected lip prints,
but that he doesn't consider it particularly odd. ``I don't have
them displayed like trophies or anything like that,'' he said. ``I
do have some albums with some (lip prints), but all of the rest are
in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, they think I'm joking, or that it's sorta weird,
but they usually do it. I just explain what I'm doing. And I have
bought some drinks,'' he said, to help convince the lipstick wearer
that he's not some subterranean scuzzbag trolling for victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never any pressure. If a lady is sitting with her
boyfriend, usually the boyfriend encourages her to do it. And then
they both think it's sorta funny.''
</P>
<P>
   These lip-printers are not all fabulously beautiful. Neither are
they all complete strangers. ``I have prints from my mother, and
many of my former girlfriends,'' Scott noted. ``And on the
girlfriends, usually I got their prints before we got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   And they don't ask for their lip prints back when they split up,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   There's a country-western song title somewhere in all this
lip-smacking stuff, but I'd better kiss it off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
