<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-FAILURES-ART-     02-10 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-FAILURES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISE UNFULFILLED AT ALPHA-BETA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The year was 1992, and while the rest of the
nation was starting to shake off a devastating recession,
Massachusetts was still in the dumps. Unemployment was 8 percent
and layoffs in the computer industry were almost daily events.
</P>
<P>
   The only Bay State companies showing hope were those in health
care and biotechnology _ and other states were actively wooing the
biotech companies with lower costs and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   And then Alpha-Beta Technology Inc., a biotechnology start-up
that had been nurtured for five years by a public-private
partnership that provided investment capital and low rent in
Worcester's state-backed biotech park, made its move . . . to Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha-Beta wanted to build a factory, and couldn't get the
financing it needed in Massachusetts. The Rhode Island Port
Authority and Economic Development Corp. offered an incentive
package that included $30 million in state-backed bonds and a site
in an industrial park in North Smithfield. The plant was expected
to eventually employ 200 people or more.
</P>
<P>
   The company's move set off a political firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more Alpha-Betas!'' Governor William F. Weld shouted, as he
successfully pushed for legislative approval of tax credits and
other retaliatory weapons in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The company didn't intend to be a poster child, says Spiros
Jamas, its cofounder and chief executive. ``We were trying to make
the right decisions for the company. At the time, it was a win-win
situation for Alpha-Beta and for Rhode Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Time, however, has dealt a far different outcome than anyone
envisioned, and one that underscores the overconfidence both state
economic development officials and investors once placed in
biotechnology as an industry with unlimited promise.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after 11 years and nearly $200 million in spending,
Alpha-Beta, with its headquarters still in Worcester, announced it
was going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   A series of costly tests on human patients failed to show that
its infection-fighting drug, Betafectin, worked.
</P>
<P>
   Along with 85 layoffs, Alpha-Beta defaulted on its loan, leaving
Rhode Island with a building and equipment that a Port Authority
spokeswoman said will be difficult to sell and is unlikely to fetch
the $26.8 million still owed. Others at the Port Authority didn't
return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha-Beta's abrupt end is just one in a recent series of
failures among small biotechnology companies whose products didn't
work or that ran out of money. Some were sold to bigger
pharmaceutical companies; some simply disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge NeuroScience Inc. of Cambridge, EcoScience Corp. of
Worcester, Institute of Molecular Biology Inc. of Worcester, and
Seragen Inc. of Hopkinton _ the latter backed heavily by Boston
University _ all are gone. On Monday, ImmuLogic Pharmaceutical
Corp. of Waltham joined the list, announcing the sale of its assets
following setbacks in its development of drugs to combat allergies
and treat multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Far from delivering on its early promise of effective cures for
exotic diseases, biotechnology has instead proved to be a complex
endeavor, with high costs and long lead times requiring the
financial stamina only big corporations can usually deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, faced with uncertainties about when they would get
their money back, have accordingly steered away, often just as many
firms needed fresh money the most, to pay for clinical trials that
determine whether their products do work.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Massachusetts boasts several successes,
including Biogen Inc., Genzyme Corp., and Genetics Institute Inc.,
all of Cambridge. And Peter Feinstein, whose Cambridge public
relations consulting firm had Alpha-Beta among its clients, says:
``There are few bankruptcies in the biotechnology industry.'' But
delays hurt a company's credibility and worry investors. Without
investment, ``they can't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pops, president of the Massachusetts Biotechnology
Council and chief executive of Alkermes of Cambridge, adds: ``The
risks (for investors) are high; the lead times are long; and there
are alternatives for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those alternatives is a new breed of companies that is
abandoning the painstaking and often spotty laboratory approach to
research in favor of using higher mathematics to draw a genetic map
_ the human genome _ to better target that research.
</P>
<P>
   In his cluttered office at the Massachusetts Biotechnology
Research Park in Worcester, Jamas, 38, who founded Alpha-Beta in
1987 while at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, talked
last week about his company's bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by half-filled boxes, the slightly-built,
black-haired son of Greek parents, born in Zambia and educated in
Athens and in England before enrolling at MIT, said last year was
especially hectic as Alpha-Beta set out on a last-ditch effort to
prove Betafectin would be a useful drug.
</P>
<P>
   Developed to stop staphylcoccus and other infections common to
hospital patients after abdominal surgery, Betafectin failed to
deliver clear-cut results in a first clinical test concluded in
1987. But that test also hinted that it might work in cases
involving only the upper gastro-intestinal tract. Alpha-Beta
commissioned a second clinical trial, involving 612 patients at
more than 30 hospitals _ half of whom would get a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   The new test could cost more than $5 million and would take
until the end of 1999 to complete. But by mid-1998 it was clear
Alpha-Beta would run out of money in early 1999. Through September
1998, the company had spent $157 million, most of it raised in
public stock offerings. Those shares, once worth $30.50 each, by
last fall were trading at less than $2.
</P>
<P>
   By November, Jamas and his chief financial officer, Joseph M.
Grimm, had arranged to raise $3 million more from a New York
investment group. Alpha-Beta got $1.5 million right away. The rest
would be paid only if an interim report on the trials, due Jan. 21,
was rosy. Investors would then get up to 30 percent control of the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jamas, ``We were running against the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   One evening in mid-January, Grimm went shopping and the next
morning entered Jamas' office with a small burgundy-colored placard
reading, ``Ask me about January 21st.'' It came from a store
counter and referred to an upcoming sale. Jamas put it on his desk.
``It was just a coincidence,'' he said, and amid the tension it
brought laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late on Jan. 21, in a light rain, Jamas and others drove
to Boston, to the offices of Goodwin Proctor &AMP; Hoar, the company's
lawyers. There, closeted in a conference room, three scientists
chosen jointly by Alpha-Beta and the US Food and Drug
Administration _ and whose names are kept secret from others _ were
reviewing the preliminary data.
</P>
<P>
   Around 8 p.m. the scientists emerged and told the Alpha-Beta
team they saw no indication Betafectin worked much better than the
placebo, even in this select group of patients. ``They told us they
did not think the study should continue,'' Jamas said.
</P>
<P>
   About that finding Jamas will say only: ``The facts are what
they are. . . we are still trying to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning the company announced the news and that in
addition to 60 people laid off last September, 85 more in Rhode
Island and Worcester would also go. Only seven in a Denver
subsidiary with federal funding for its antifungal product research
were spared.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on Jan. 28, with its shares worth only pennies,
Alpha-Beta announced it had entered into a legal assignment for the
benefit of creditors and arranged to liquidate its assets,
including patents and technology for producing Betafectin's core
ingredient. Jamas believes beta glucans will eventually find a use
_ perhaps by veterinarians; perhaps as a food thickener. ``We feel
after 11 years there is a lot of value here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? For one thing, Jamas said, initial animal
studies and trials on small numbers of humans may have been too
limited to yield accurate results. But, he said, ``In the heat of
the moment . . . we made a conscious decision to go forward with
the Phase 3 tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamas, who has been in school or running Alpha-Beta all his
adult life, has no idea what he will do next. He sees himself in an
entrepreneurial role, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has probably been the best business school I could go
to,'' he said of his experience.
</P>
<P>
   Others don't see biotechnology's future as sanguinely. Janice
Bourque of the Massachusetts Biotechnology Council, an industry
organization, agrees with Feinstein that this is work left to big
companies with big bankrolls.
</P>
<P>
   And in Worcester, the Massachusetts Biotechnology Research
Initiative, formed with state and federal support in 1989 to
attract biotech companies to the research park here, changed its
name last year to Massachusetts Biomedical Initiatives and shifted
its focus to recruitment of medical devices companies _ a sector
with a far better success and employment record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotechnology has proved to be a very risky investment,'' says
Mark Roosevelt, the Democrat who opposed Weld in the 1994
gubernatorial election and who is now the organization's top
officer. Furthermore, he said, ``the jobs biotech has produced just
aren't as many as people hoped. . . In terms of job growth, medical
devices is a better place to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
