<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSISTED-LIVING FIRMS TAKING A BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new year was barely a month old and the stocks of
assisted-living companies were already taking a beating. Then the
market went from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Carematrix Corp. came under more pressure when an
influential stock analyst sounded a warning Feb. 4 over a wild card
in Washington: a government report on the assisted-living industry
that has been in the works for two years and is likely to be made
public in April. No one knows what it will say.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Sheryl Skolnick of BancBoston Robertson Stephens pulled
her recommendations on a handful of companies, worried about the
unknown conclusions of the General Accounting Office report and the
wet blanket it will likely throw over the stocks for months to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives cried foul. Other analysts downplayed the
impact of the pending GAO report, being prepared for the Senate's
Special Committee on Aging. Skolnick dug in and aggressively
defended her actions.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a business better positioned to capitalize
on the graying of America than assisted-living companies, which
build and manage residences offering varying degrees of care to
seniors. They are also a prime example of a group of young, small
stocks that were whipsawed by events and fears mostly beyond their
control.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies were already fighting stock slides before the
GAO report became an issue. Some were hurt by a roiling market for
securities backed by commercial mortgages, a source of financing.
Others were affected by confusion over so-called ``black box''
arrangements that help finance the construction of some residences
using development partners. Those deals are expensive but keep
projects off the balance sheets of assisted-living companies.
Critics complained the arrangements mask financial risks and make
it hard to evaluate the health of individual companies.
</P>
<P>
   An important industry merger, the $484 million purchase of
Assisted Living Concepts Inc. by American Retirement Corp.,
collapsed on Feb. 1. The leading issue: a restatement of earnings
based on the accounting of reimbursements from a development
partner.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report, requested in 1997, is based on survey
information in four states. Most observers believe it is highly
unlikely to prompt new regulation of assisted-living companies.
Medicare doesn't pay for assisted living so the government has
almost no ability to institute pricing regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick's report pulled her recommendations for four stocks.
She had rated Carematrix a ``strong buy'' and the largest public
assisted-living company, Sunrise Assisted Living Inc., a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she took the action this month because, in her
experience covering health care stocks, such government reports
become market influences once a date is set to make them public.
(Committee officials said Tuesday they hoped to release the report
in April, but no firm date had been set.)
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick warned investors that the GAO report might not lead to
regulation but could still have something to say about prices as a
consumer-protection issue: Do people really get what they pay for
and are they being pitched things they don't need?
</P>
<P>
   It might not have sharp teeth, but the report could be bad
publicity that hurts business. It could be even worse for investor
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you have great companies whose stocks
can't get ahead to save their lives,'' she said Tuesday. ``You can
have spectacular earnings reports and it won't matter one iota.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report ``could eventually have no impact on these
businesses, but it will likely have an impact on their stock prices
over the next six months,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carematrix shares, already beaten down to 24 by Feb. 4, have
fallen to 16 15/16 in the week since. Sunrise lost slightly less
than 10 percent of its value. Some other assisted-living stocks
suffered no impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies lost hundreds of millions of dollars (in stock
market value) on a very speculative report and we think it's an
injustice,'' said Karen Wayne, president of the Assisted Living
Federation of America, which has worked with the GAO on its report.
</P>
<P>
   The industry line on the GAO report is that it will recommend
only that services and expenses are clearly disclosed to clients by
all assisted-living companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a nonissue to us,'' said Robert Kaufman, chief
executive of Carematrix. ``This is just a disclosure issue; it's
not an industry regulation issue. You're talking about something
that's been going on for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony: Skolnick's report really didn't say anything that was
very different. It might have sounded a bit more alarmist and
focused on psychological stock market impact. But it didn't predict
any dire concrete change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this industry is going away and I don't think it
will be regulated heavily by the federal government anytime in the
near future,'' she said Tuesday. ``If investors have patience these
are fundamentally sound companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached at syre(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
