<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-10 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Brandeis University professor Stuart Altman is one popular
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Thier, who runs the growing Massachusetts General and
Brigham &AMP; Women's hospitals, has called, as has Mitch Rabkin, the
former boss at the struggling Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
He has heard from the chiefs of nearly every other hospital in
town, too.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old Altman, who has spent a lifetime working in
health care, has known these people for years, but they are not
calling to chitchat. Instead, they are worried _ worried about a
train that is coming down the tracks that could profoundly affect
the future of their institutions and Boston's entire world-class
medical complex.
</P>
<P>
   That train is Medicare reform. And Altman is very much a man on
the spot right now.
</P>
<P>
   From his relatively obscure seat as the Sol C. Chaikin Professor
of National Health Policy at Brandeis, Altman has emerged as one of
two critical swing votes on a presidential commission that is
nearing the end of an increasingly contentious deliberation on what
to do about Medicare, the government program that controls $1 in
every $5 spent on health care in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare story has been pushed off the media's radar by the
Bill &AMP; Monica Show. But the Medicare commission _ now getting Page
22 treatment in the papers _ is debating radical changes in the
basic health care plan for the elderly and disabled that could
affect virtually every baby boomer and the institutions that
provide their care.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the debate: Will Medicare remain a form of social
insurance, with wide responsibility for helping the nation keep
teaching hospitals and hospitals for the poor up and running? Or
will it become a basic, low-cost provider of care, with the rewards
going to whomever can provide care at the lowest price?
</P>
<P>
   All of the giant building blocks of the $200 billion Medicare
program are in play.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John B. Breaux (D-La.), the commission's chairman, is
pushing a ``premium support'' system (read: vouchers) in which the
government would give people money to pay the premium for whatever
health care insurer they want. There is debate on raising the
eligibility age and including prescription drug coverage. And, most
worrisome to teaching hospitals like Mass. General and inner-city
facilities like Boston Medical Center are attempts to end the
Medicare payments that compensate them for teaching and caring for
the poor, and replace them instead with a separate appropriation
Congress would consider each year.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Congress is going to have much to say on these issues.
But the Breaux commission, like the Social Security panels before
it, will go far in shaping the debate. Are the vote there for a
radical remaking of Medicare into a more market-oriented system?
</P>
<P>
   That's where Altman becomes so critical.
</P>
<P>
   All recommendations need 11 votes of the commission's 17
members. The eight Republicans have been in lockstep since Day One.
Breaux and Senator Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.) are also on board. That
makes 10 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The swing votes are both Clinton appointees, Laura D. Tyson, the
president's former chief economic adviser, and Altman.
</P>
<P>
   Altman, an economist who worked on health care in both the Nixon
and Clinton administrations, is clear that he could well vote for
moving to a more market-driven system. ``I don't think people are
inherently evil if they make a profit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he is just as clear on the price of his vote: Medicare
coverage for prescription drugs, a ``reasonably high'' level of
premium supports, and assurances the needy will not get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   As for the teaching hospitals, Altman said they would lose a
straight up-or-down vote on the commission today. He doesn't want
to see that vote happen; he thinks it is unfair to pick on the
subsidy to the hospitals if the commission isn't willing to put all
subsidies on the table.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help but wonder: Aren't you protecting your hometown
hospitals? Altman's answer: ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach Steve Bailey at sbailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
