<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FELDSTEIN-SECURITY-AR     02-10 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELDSTEIN-SECURITY-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN FELDSTEIN HAS A PLAN FOR PERSONAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a prominent conservative and presidential
adviser, Harvard economist Martin Feldstein has long antagonized
liberals with his views on taxes and social programs. Now, the man
known as ``Dr. Gloom'' has whipped up something so seductive, so
politically intoxicating _ something, his critics fear, that is so
downright diabolical _ that labor unions and left-wing policy
groups have sounded a red alert.
</P>
<P>
   Feldstein has a plan to fix Social Security. Congress is
considering a half-dozen ideas for shoring up the program's weak
finances, but this one makes a nearly irresistible claim: Feldstein
says he can save the program from insolvency without raising taxes
_ all while boosting the payments that retirees receive each month.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the critics say?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Feldstein plan is likely to lead to the unraveling of the
current Social Security system,'' claims Alicia Munnell of Boston
College, a former economic adviser to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a seductive headline, but it doesn't stand up to
scrutiny very well,'' says David Smith, policy chief for the
AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears as a free lunch. . . But of course there is no free
lunch,'' says Robert Greenstein of the Center for Budget and Policy
Priorities, which advocates on behalf of low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Martin Feldstein to kick up some dust. For more than
a quarter-century, the 59-year-old economist has put himself at the
center of some of the most important policy battles in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as 1974, Feldstein wrote an influential paper on
Social Security that is still fodder for academic debates. As
President Reagan's chief economist in the early 1980s, his warnings
on the dangers of the federal budget deficit earned him the
nickname ``Dr. Gloom'' and led to public fights with other White
House aides. The spectacled, mild-looking economist landed in such
unusual venues as People magazine and ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Feldstein has again become a force in Washington. He is the
most prominent of several Boston economists who play leading roles
in the high-stakes debate over how to repair Social Security, the
nation's most popular and expensive domestic program.
</P>
<P>
   Munnell, director of the new Center for Retirement Research at
Boston College, has become a leading opponent of the most radical
proposals to alter Social Security. Peter Diamond of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology led a prominent panel of
economists in studying Social Security reforms at the National
Academy of Social Insurance. At Boston College, Laurence Kotlikoff
is known for studies on how Social Security, and fiscal policy in
general, affects the broader economy. Boston College's Joseph Quinn
writes about factors that affect the decision to retire.
</P>
<P>
   But more than any academic, Feldstein has made the leap from
economic abstraction to the political realities of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has affected peoples' thinking and the nature of the debate
probably more than any other academic or think-tank participant,''
says economist Robert Reischauer of the Brookings Institution, who
nonetheless opposes Feldstein's prescription for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last fall, White House aides were intrigued enough
by Feldstein's plan that the AFL-CIO, Jesse Jackson, and a coterie
of liberal and seniors groups mounted a furious campaign to warn
the president away. ``This plan is still alive,'' says Smith of the
AFL-CIO. ``There is still a lot of interest on Capitol Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm of Texas, a Republican and former economics
professor, studied Feldstein's ideas in detail before writing
legislation that looked remarkably similar. Though he later backed
another proposal, Senator Judd Gregg, Republican of New Hampshire,
clipped a copy of Feldstein's plan from The Wall Street Journal and
sent a copy to all of his Senate colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has drawn such interest _ and heat _ because it claims
there is a pain-free way to do the one thing liberals fear the
most: privatize Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization is the idea that workers should invest their
Social Security taxes for themselves. Those taxes are high: Workers
pay 6.2 percent of their wages, and employers pay an additional 6.2
percent. Yet, it is not enough. Social Security will likely run
short of money early in the next century, as the wave of baby
boomers begins to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of privatization say that if workers could pay some
of that tax money into their own stock and bond accounts, they
would grow a big nest egg for retirement. As it is now, they say,
Social Security offers too little in benefits for all those tax
payments. And benefits might drop lower, once the system is forced
to support millions of baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   But many people believe that private accounts violate the spirit
of the national retirement program. To them, Social Security is not
an investment plan but an insurance policy against poverty in old
age. Everyone pays in, and everyone is guaranteed a pension.
High-earners subsidize pensions for low-wage workers, helping
assure them a decent retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FELDSTEIN-SECURITY-2N     02-10 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELDSTEIN-SECURITY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... decent retirement.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock picking, on the other hand, produces winners and losers _
and the losers might fall into poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, say opponents of private accounts, Social Security is
already sure to run short of money in a few decades. Allowing
workers to divert tax money into their own accounts would only make
the problem worse, forcing benefit cuts for people who are already
retired or who will retire in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Feldstein's trick is to plant a foot in both camps.
</P>
<P>
   He would keep Social Security intact, but create a private
account for every worker. Under the plan he wrote with Andrew
Samwick, every year the government would deposit money into each
private account equal to 2 percent of the worker's wages. The money
would come from the huge budget surpluses that both Congress and
the White House foresee for the next decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   When the worker retired, money in the account would be used to
buy an annuity, a financial vehicle that gives a fixed payment
annually until death.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many other private account plans, the worker would
keep only one-quarter of the annuity payments. The rest would go
back to the Social Security system to shore up its weakened
finances. At the same time, the worker would receive every penny of
Social Security benefits that is promised today.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the worker would get all benefits offered by the
current system, plus one-quarter of what he or she accumulated
through years of stock picking for the private account.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed system,'' Feldstein said recently at his office
in Cambridge, Mass. ``It's not privatized in the sense that we say
`Good luck, fella. Hope you have a nice retirement.' This is very
much a government-organized system, and it guarantees that the
benefits will be at least as much as you would have gotten from
Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question is how the government can afford to do it
all _ continue the underfunded Social Security program that exists
today while putting an extra 2 percent of wages to each private
account.
</P>
<P>
   Feldstein's answer: Use the budget surplus for as long as
possible. Then, he acknowledges, the government might have to raise
taxes for a few years. But by 2030, he says, the system would be
self-financing. All those individual accounts would have
accumulated trillions of dollars _ money that would find its way to
businesses through stock and bond sales. Businesses would use the
money to expand and become more productive. Profits would rise,
producing more corporate tax revenue for the government.
</P>
<P>
   And the government would use that money to finance its hybrid
Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   One notable feature of Feldstein's plan is its political savvy.
By claiming that the current system will survive, Feldstein
challenges the idea that private accounts divert tax money away
from today's retirees. And by saying workers keep all their current
benefits even if stock prices fall, he makes it safe for
politicians to embrace the risk of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people make a bad stock decision, Marty's plan seems to
say, `Don't worry, you won't do worse than under the current
system,' '' Munnell says. ``Now, I view that as extremely clever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty is not an ivory tower academic who thinks up grand
schemes with no relation to the political system,'' Greenstein
says. ``I think he knows exactly what he is doing politically.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear that these and other analysts have is that Feldstein's
true goal is to eliminate Social Security and to move to a totally
private system. They also say that Feldstein is overstating the
corporate tax revenues that his plan would produce. As a result,
his plan would create a huge budget squeeze in a few decades,
forcing the government to cut vital social programs in order to
keep its commitments to both Social Security and the new system of
private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Even some lawmakers who strongly favor private accounts have
backed away from the Feldstein plan for fear that it would bust the
budget some time in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ironic charge for Feldstein, who is best known as a
deficit-fighter. Nearly two decades ago, President Reagan told the
nation that it could afford to cut taxes while spending more on
defense. Introducing the term ``supply-side economics'' to the
nation, Reagan's aides argued that tax cuts would spur people to
invest and businesses to expand, which in turn would boost tax
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Feldstein was well known as a conservative thinker. He was an
advocate of cutting capital gains taxes, and he had earned plenty
of enemies for arguing that Social Security should save money by
limiting annual cost-of-living raises. When Reagan appointed
Feldstein to be chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers in
1982, even some Republicans who voted for him felt the need to
repudiate his views.
</P>
<P>
   But Feldstein publicly contradicted many of Reagan's economic
ideas. He feuded with the ``supply-side extremists'' who said a
large tax cut would pay for itself. He argued that high budget
deficits hurt the economy. At one point he and then-Treasury
Secretary Donald Regan gave opposite views of the deficit in
speeches on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the White House tried to muzzle and belittle
Feldstein. In one noted example, Reagan spokesman Larry Speakes
appeared to demean him by intentionally mispronouncing his name.
</P>
<P>
   After two outspoken years at the White House, Feldstein returned
to life in Cambridge. He informally advised President Bush in the
1992 presidential campaign. His newspaper column, co-written with
his wife, Kathleen, also an economist, appears in The Boston Globe
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard University professor since 1967, Feldstein also serves
as president of the National Bureau of Economic Research, a major
force in research funding. The post gives him unusual influence in
his profession, and he has held it for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Even Feldstein's political opponents say his time in Washington
combined with his mastery of economics make him a formidable figure
as Congress grapples with Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Says Greenstein: ``Lots of us who work on policy wish we could
find things that intoxicate people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
