<HEADLINE>
SAVARESE GETS A FRESH START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Giovanni Savarese planned to be in Italy
this week, but not with the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese was the New York/New Jersey MetroStars' leading scorer
and the No. 3 scorer in Major League Soccer after the league's
first three seasons. But Savarese felt rejected by the MetroStars
and was unable to negotiate a satisfactory raise from MLS, so he
had been exploring other options.
</P>
<P>
   The search became a return to roots for Savarese, whose family
emigrated from Campania to Caracas and then Massachusetts. He lived
with relatives while training with AS Napoli's ``B'' team and would
have stayed, but the Revolution acquired his rights and offered a
fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   So Savarese returned last week to become acquainted with his new
teammates and left with them Wednesday bound for Tuscany, where the
Revolution begin a six-week training camp.
</P>
<P>
   With the MetroStars, Savarese earned a reputation as an
opportunist and overachiever. He scored 41 goals in three seasons,
the team's most consistent and dynamic offensive weapon. But he was
relegated to reserve status and did not seem likely to emerge under
coach Bora Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga hopes to use Savarese in a
starting role to help set the tactical tone. The team's strikers
will be expected to close down opposing attacks before they can get
started _ and score goals as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Walter about a lot of things,'' Savarese said
Tuesday. ``But we haven't really talked about my role on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great in New York because of the fans. The people
treated me well. But things didn't go so well with the team. I'd
rather not talk about the problems in New York because I'm happy to
be here now, for a lot of reasons _ I have a lot of faith in
Walter, I have family living here, it's a great stadium to play in
with great fans, and I'm still close to New York and Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese was recruited to the United States by former Long
Island University coach Arnie Ramirez and played for LIU and the
Long Island Roughriders. He is among the few athletes from
Venezuela to achieve success in the US other than in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to love him in Boston,'' Ramirez said. ``I don't
know why three coaches benched him, but he was still the
MetroStars' top scorer. If they give him confidence there, he will
show what he can do. He's an excellent player who gives everything.
Anyone who watched the MetroStars the last three years can't say he
was ever going through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played sweeper, stopper, and forward at LIU. People think
he can only score very close to the goal, but it's not true. In a
game against Syracuse, he took the kickoff, took a pass from Walter
Bustamante, and scored in seven seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese has had to work fast during the offseason. He was
married in November in Caracas _ there were more than 450 guests _
but skipped the honeymoon to pursue his soccer career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe after the season, we will take a cruise,'' Saverese
said. ``Where? Probably in the Mediterranean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
