<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA IS ASWIRL WITH GRAPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ It's an ordinary, economy class,
hourlong shuttle flight on South African Airways. The stewardess
asks what I would like to drink. White wine, I tell her. What kind
of white wine, she wants to know. Chardonnay. What style of
chardonnay? She places a stemmed glass _ real glass _ on my tray
table and asks if I'd like to taste her recommendation. I swirl it.
It's fine. But is it the right temperature? she asks. It is. She
calls back to her colleague in the galley, asking her to put
another bottle in the fridge, in case I'd like more.
</P>
<P>
   South Africans take their wine seriously, in the air or on the
ground. I met a group of University of Cape Town students, party
animals all, who knew their way around a wine list as few American
undergrads would (and who mentioned that when students hit a wine
route, one wine farm will call ahead to warn the next one down the
road, which will promptly close in self-defense).
</P>
<P>
   Wine in South Africa is an everyday beverage at an everyday
price. At Delheim Wines near Stellenbosch, east of Cape Town, I
chanced upon a tasting of 15 or so South African whites from
various wine farms _ all selling for under $5 a bottle. Many were
quite good, although some were a bit sweet for American tastes.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing grape variety in South Africa is still chenin
blanc, used primarily in off-dry wines, but the wine industry,
conscious of what sells abroad, is catching up to other countries'
preference for dry wines, focusing more on sauvignon blanc and
chardonnay. The chardonnays are often lighter and less wooded than
Californian and Australian versions, and the sauvignon blancs more
assertive. Before my recent trip to South Africa, a sauvignon blanc
with a flinty finish _ from Neil Ellis, another vintner in the
Stellenbosch area _ had already become my house wine. It sells for
$11.99 in my suburban Boston wine shop, and for $5 at the winery.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa also has a wine unique to the country _ pinotage, a
hybrid born of the 1920s marriage of pinot noir and cinsault. A
South African oenophile tells me that in the 1980s, pinotage used
to taste like nail polish remover (which I had to assume he'd
tried, but I didn't ask under what circumstances). A
light-to-medium red wine, often with banana flavors, pinotage is
being taken more seriously now than in the past and allowed to
mature in oak more often. The new, more grown-up pinotage is
perfectly paired with South Africa's most popular specialty meat _
ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more liberating aspects of a wine-lover's trip to
South Africa is that even in restaurants and hotels, wine is
affordable. Consider a favorite chardonnay from my trip, the '96
Glen Carlou, a voluptuous, buttery, award-winning wine, the kind of
chardonnay that feels fattening. It was unavailable at the winery,
so I started asking for it in restaurants, even when it wasn't on
the wine list. Finally, I lucked out at a chic Cape Town cafe
called Fresh, which sold me its last bottle for $10.
</P>
<P>
   While the focus on improved table wines is recent, South
Africa's wine industry _ currently eighth largest in the world _
has a long history. Thanks to Jan van Riebeck, founder of the Cape
colony, the beginning of the industry can be pinpointed precisely.
On Feb. 2, 1659, van Riebeck wrote in his diary, ``Today, praise be
to God, wine was made for the first time from Cape grapes.''
Shortly after, Cape Governor Simon van der Stel started South
Africa's first wine estate, Groot Constantia, which became famous
for its sweet wines. French Huguenots, fleeing their native country
because of religious persecution, arrived later in the 17th
century, bringing with them a knowledge of and taste for fine
wines. The exiled Napoleon drank wines from Groot Constantia
exclusively, but that might have had something to do with
bitterness toward France as well as with the sweetness of South
African wines. Truth to tell, the quality of Groot Constantia today
isn't up to the level of many vintages produced by the region's
smaller estates.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has a complex relationship with France in matters
of wine. One South African told me that during apartheid, when
South Africa was cut off from much of the world, guests would be
invited to homes to drink French wine, specifying ``French'' in the
invitation because it was more prestigious than the native tipple.
Another South African told me that was nonsense, that the country
realized the potential of its wines right along, and bought French
wines only for comparative purposes. France exerts a certain amount
of influence over the naming of South African wines. The French
Institute of National Origin, which protects its wine industry,
recently forced South Africa's Haute Provence Vineyards to remove
the labels from 6,000 bottles of its 1998 sauvignon blanc, because
``Haute Provence'' is also the name of a wine region in France.
</P>
<P>
   Politics, phylloxera, government regulation, and the loosening
thereof have all affected South Africa's wine industry. What
matters most to the wine tourist of today, though, is that you can
have a wonderful time exploring the wine estates clustered within
an hour's drive of Cape Town, which is often touted as the world's
most beautiful city. The wine farms are also beautiful, each with
its own personality. The historic ones have Cape Dutch architecture
that suggests Amsterdam South _ whitewashed homesteads topped with
ornate curling gables. Newer ones have a futuristic feel.
</P>
<P>
   Vergelegen is both. The gorgeous property in Somerset West, on
the edge of the winelands, dates from 1700. But in addition to a
classic Cape Dutch manor house with thatched roof, there is an
ultramodern winery whose octagonal shape mirrors Vergelegen's lush
flower garden. The winery burrows into a hilltop, to exploit
gravity in the wine-making process. The grapes travel ever
downward, from harvest to fermentation to press to barrel, which is
at the bottom. The building is actually inside a moat, the water
providing insulation, the theory being that grapes respond well to
gentle handling. Vergelegen's wines are exported to Europe _ but
not yet to the United States. So you'll have to travel to try the
excellent '96 chardonnay reserve.
</P>
<P>
   One of South Africa's greatest reds is the 1993 Saxenburg Shiraz
Private Collection, included in Wine Spectator magazine's 1996 list
of the world's top 100 wines _ the only South African to make the
cut that year. It's an opulent wine, with peppery and blackberry
flavors. Unavailable at the wine farm, it is on the wine list at
the Guinea Fowl Restaurant, another part of the estate. Its price _
about $32 _ is among the highest you'll find on any South African
menu. Saxenburg's Swiss owners are also the proprietors of Chateau
Capion in the South of France. Hence the marriages of wines from
both estates, overseen by winemaker Nico van der Merwe, who divides
his time between South Africa and France.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're exploring South African wines in American shops
or trekking to the country of origin, arm yourself with the current
edition of John Platter's annual ``South African Wines.'' The most
respected overview of the field, it is written with clarity and
without overdoing the technical terms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the chance to sample the many wines that aren't
exported to the United States, one of the pleasures of enjoying
South African wine in South Africa is the many restaurants attached
to wine farms. They range from humble and publike to world-class
and sophisticated. In the former category is Delheim's Vintner's
Platter. Among the wines I sampled was the fresh, clean,
easy-to-drink Woolworths Bianca Light. After I expressed surprise
at the name, Delheim's vintner, Spatz Sperling, assured me that in
South Africa, Woolworths is a more upmarket store than in the
United States. ``It's more like Harrods,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Among the very top restaurants affiliated with a winery is
Buitenverwachting, where I had an elaborate lunch, trying different
wines with each course. ``Buitenverwachting'' I found impossible to
pronounce, but I had no problem at all with the very familiar name
of the winery's top red. A mostly cabernet sauvignon blend that
regularly ranks among South Africa's greats, it's called
``Christine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
