<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-10 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALLY, THIS CALL IS OUTRAGEOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Zebra Chronicles, Part Whatever . . .
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you caught the end of last Saturday's DePaul-Cincinnati
men's basketball game at the Rosemont Horizon. If you did, you may
not have been as outraged as I, but I'd be very surprised if you
weren't, well, perplexed, because what happened was so completely
out there as to border on the surreal.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 seconds or so remaining in the overtime of a tie game,
Cincinnati had the basketball. It was holding for the last shot.
Bearcat star Melvin Levitt was, as Johnny Most would say,
``fiddling and diddling'' with the ball when he got a bit too cute
and attempted a crossover dribble in front of DePaul's Willie
Crawford, who said, ``I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Crawford was dashing the other way with Levitt in pursuit.
The seconds were trickling away. Not long after he crossed
midcourt, a completely out-of-control Crawford, his (itals)back to
the basket,(unitals) flung the ball in the general direction of the
hoop. The ball fell several feet short. The buzzer went off. Second
OT, no?
</P>
<P>
   Uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   That's because referee Paul Kaster, to the delight of DePaul,
the horror of Cincinnati, and the astonishment of both the crowd in
attendance and the many thousands watching on television, blew the
whistle. He called a foul on Levitt, whose only crime might have
been loitering. If anything, Crawford lunged into Levitt.
</P>
<P>
   Confusing the issue even more was the fact that Crawford was
given two shots when he was clearly far outside the 3-point arc.
Anyway, the DePaul kid missed the first and ba-boinged in the
second. Final score: DePaul 61, Cincinnati 60.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-to-10 scale of injustice, this was at least an 11 1/2,
and I say that as no lover of Cincinnati, a leading candidate for
the Evil Empire in the college basketball world. But fair is fair,
and what happened to Cincinnati was not just a bad call. A sincere
misjudgment on a block-charge, shot block vs. hack, or goaltend is
one thing, but this was something else. This was a referee
demonstrating a complete and utter lack of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referees' guiding principle,'' says Hank Nichols, the
NCAA's national coordinator of men's basketball officials and
himself one of the great referees of all time, ``is to let players
do whatever they can to win the game without your interference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to use `referees' smarts,' '' concurs Atlantic 10
officiating supervisor Micky Crowley, another of the great
common-sense referees in the history of college basketball. ``You
let the kids determine who wins and loses ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these esteemed experts would comment directly on the
call in question, for obvious reasons. Of course, it's not as if I
need any confirmation that this was a truly disturbing call.
</P>
<P>
   This had nothing to do with ``letting them play.'' Many people
are of the opinion that it's not proper for the referee to call
anything short of first-degree murder in the waning seconds of
game, a notion that makes both these gentlemen sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circumstances are irrelevant,'' stresses Nichols. ``If it's a
foul, it's a foul, and it doesn't matter if it's the first
possession of the game or at the buzzer. If a guy thinks he sees a
foul at the buzzer, he has an obligation to call it. That's why
he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can argue? We've all seen any number of situations at every
level in which something takes place requiring a very tough
decision in the waning seconds. A guy goes to the hoop, for
example, and there is a blocked shot. A referee has to decide if
contact was made either way. That's difficult, but it has to be
done. We all understand that and we all understand that
(itals)someone(unitals) will be outraged, no matter which way it
goes.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But this thing last Saturday now serves as Exhibit A to support
my basic thesis about basketball officiating. Simply put, before
taking the floor, every official should ask himself the following
question: Why am I here?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, I submit, is to adjudicate the smooth flow of the
game. Anyone adhering to that principle may still make errors in
mechanics and specific call judgment, but he will not make idiot
calls such as the one that decided last Saturday's game in
Rosemont.
</P>
<P>
   If Mr. Kaster had any idea why he was sent to officiate the
DePaul-Cincinnati game, he would never have sent someone who had
just flung a basketball _ again, I stress, (itals)with his back to
the basket(unitals) _ to the foul line with a chance to win the
game. If he understood why he was there _ if he understood that
when in doubt, let the players decide the game _ then he would have
allowed the game to head into a second overtime. What he did was
take 44 minutes 59 seconds of hard-nosed basketball and render it
secondary to his bizarre interpretation of what constitutes justice
in a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the game,'' says Nichols, ``you hope you have
something legitimate if you blow the whistle. But officials aren't
told anything specific about the end of a game. Having common sense
is implicit in the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to make a call at the end of a game,'' adds
Crowley, ``you'd better be (itals)sure(unitals) you've got
something good.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, not all officials are created equal. ``I don't know if
there is anything you can say or do to make 700 officials all see
the same thing,'' sighs Nichols. ``That's why you have great
officials, mediocre officials, and bad officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most inappropriate display Saturday was the sorry
act put on by DePaul coach Pat Kennedy, who was beaming broadly and
high-fiving half of Illinois after his team had been handed this
bogus win. Has he no shame whatsoever? What he should have done was
walk with his head down toward Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins and
whisper, ``Hug, I'm truly embarrassed. I hope this evens out for
you somewhere down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be asking too much of a college coach in the pressure
cooker, just as it may be asking too much of every official to ask
himself just why it is someone is paying him to run around with
that whistle. But if some referee wants to know what not to do in
an end-of-game situation, all he has to do is grab the tape of last
Saturday's DePaul-Cincinnati game. It doesn't get any more
ludicrous that that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
