<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ACTIVIST REGGIE WILLIAMS DIES AT 47 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Ohio, California)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reggie Williams, the former head of the National
Task Force on AIDS Prevention, died Sunday in the Netherlands of
complications of the AIDS virus. He was 47.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Williams was viewed as a hero for his fight against the
cultural barriers that continue to keep the AIDS infection rate
high among non-white Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we've lost many heroes, but he was an
extraordinary individual. He was one of the more effective leaders
during the entire peak of the AIDS epidemic in the city,'' said Dr.
Sandra Hernandez, who worked closely with Mr. Williams during her
years in San Francisco's AIDS Office and as the city's public
health director.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Williams grew up in Cincinnati, became an X-ray technician
and moved to Los Angeles in the exuberant days of gay liberation in
the 1970s. It was at Cedars Sinai Hospital there that he first
began seeing patients severely ill with what was then called
Gay-Related Immune Disease.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he settled in San Francisco in the early 1980s, the
acquired immune deficiency syndrome was approaching its full fury _
and Mr. Williams was one of the first to recognize that prevention
efforts weren't reaching gay and bisexual blacks, or other gay
minorities. He called a meeting at his home to take action,
according to colleague and friend Al Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the AIDS Task Force of the San Francisco chapter
of Black and White Men Together (now Men of All Colors Together),
from which emerged the National Task Force on AIDS Prevention,
which Mr. Williams ran from 1988 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Its aim was to break down the homophobia and other cultural
barriers that kept black, Hispanic and Asian men who had sex with
other men from seeing themselves as gay _ or from recognizing the
risk of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the first national survey of its kind, Mr. Williams'
organization discovered that a full third of black gay and bisexual
men were privately homosexual but publicly involved with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men go into a relationship with a woman because they
need to feel accepted within the ranks of the black community. As a
result, there's greater risk that the virus will spread not only
among them, but among women and the family when they go home,'' Mr.
Williams said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Williams himself served as a role model, and as a leader who
was able to reach bureaucrats as well as people on the street. All
the while, he battled the human immunodeficiency virus, which leads
to AIDS, for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very much an unsung hero,'' said Hernandez, now head of
the San Francisco Foundation, a philanthropic organization. ``He
didn't get a lot of awards. But he was a bridge builder across a
lot of different communities, especially in the African-American
community, which early on didn't embrace this epidemic as being
relevant to them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Mr. Williams moved to Amsterdam to be with his partner,
German-born Wolfgang Schreiber. Schreiber was prohibited by U.S.
law from moving here because he has HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The organization Mr. Williams founded has since folded. But his
work continues through Cunningham and Yours in the Struggle, a
multimedia and community education project.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities now accounting for 58 percent of new HIV infections
nationally, Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Schreiber, Mr. Williams is survived by four
sisters, Connie Rudolph and Phyllis Williams of Cincinnati, Denise
Williams of Landover, Md., and Vanessa Williams of Encinitas,
Calif.; three brothers, Aaron, Dwight and Michael of Cincinnati;
plus many nieces and nephews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
