<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGELA-DAVIS-HNS &LR;      02-10 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELA-DAVIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60S ACTIVIST BLASTS PRISON POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CATHY WOODRUFF  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Nearly three decades after political
activism landed her in jail after a celebrated stint on the FBI's
10 Most Wanted list, Angela Davis is more troubled than ever about
the number of black and disadvantaged Americans being swept out of
circulation behind prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this society so willing to lock up people in cages?''
Davis told more than 300 people at Skidmore College.
</P>
<P>
   She argued that prisons are the nation's most common
post-slavery technique for legally denying African-Americans their
civil rights and shutting the door on people troubled by mental
illness, drug addiction, illiteracy and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prisons have become a place to throw away people with problems
... and act as though we have solved those problems,'' Davis said
in the Sunday address. ``Prisons have become places of exile for
people who are considered expendable.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, now in her mid-50s, is a professor at the University of
California at Santa Cruz. She lost an early teaching job at the
University of California at Los Angeles in 1969 because of her
affiliation with the Communist Party, and she spent 16 months in
jail after advocating the release of the ``Soledad Brothers'' held
in a California prison.
</P>
<P>
   She was released in 1972 after she was acquitted on charges that
she was involved in a kidnapping attempt. Today, the Afro is gone,
and her hair is now highlighted and worn in long, soft curls.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Davis said, a black man is five times more likely
to be found in prison than in a state university. And in New York,
she said, increased spending on prison construction is an example
of how the ``prison-industrial complex'' robs funding and attention
from education, health care, and treatment of mental illness and
drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Often, those serving long prison sentences for nonviolent drug
crimes would pose little danger to others in their community, but
their incarceration serves a political urge to ``construct an
enemy,'' she said. She equated it with the Cold War view of
Communists as the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prison expansion serves an ever-expanding world of
capitalist commercial interests _ including collect telephone
services, construction trades and the sale of security technology _
that reinforce the drive to build more prisons, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   As she concluded, Davis urged her listeners to reach out to
those inside prisons. A ``go to prison week'' is slated for April
11-18 as part of a campaign to change U.S. criminal justice and
prison policies, and she encouraged audience members to visit
people they know in prison or arrange prison tours with church or
school groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a little time in jail, and I definitely do not want to
go back, but I will try to get in for at least a few hours,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davis offered a professorial lecture infused with warmth. As a
high school senior, she told the group, she applied to Skidmore and
was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always tried to imagine what it would have been like if I
had come here,'' she said, evoking murmurs and quiet laughter as
older listeners mulled the unspoken reference to her life as a
famous California campus radical.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spoke for more than an hour and then responded to
questions and comments from her listeners, including anti-prison
activist Alice Green, a frequent critic of Gov. George Pataki and
New York's prison policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
