A9266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCIPAL-OUSTED-HNS &LR;      02-10 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCIPAL-OUSTED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SYSTEM URGED TO REINSTATE PRINCIPAL ACCUSED OF
ANTI-SEMITISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for SPANISH-TEACHER)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Parents, teachers and students are pushing the
San Francisco school district to reinstate a popular principal who
was accused of making anti-Semitic remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Cesar Chavez Elementary School Principal Pilar Mejia,
who started her career in the school district as a bus driver and
went on to become one of the most outspoken defenders of immigrant
children, apologized Tuesday for having lamented that ``three white
Jewish women'' were teaching Spanish-speaking kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention was simply to point out that Spanish-speaking
children at the pre-K level were being taught by teachers who did
not speak Spanish and were not of Hispanic descent,'' Mejia said,
drawing a standing ovation from some 100 parents, teachers and
children gathered at Everett Middle School in San Francisco Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time the statement was made, it was not intended to
reflect negatively on anyone's ethnic or religious background, but
I can understand how it could be interpreted as such,'' said Mejia,
52. ``I would like to sit down and resolve this.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's school superintendent, Bill Rojas said: ``If that was
the only thing she said, then it wouldn't be problematical.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas said Mejia's transfer on Feb. 1 to the district's
curriculum improvement and professional development center was
final and non-negotiable. He characterized a claim filed by a
teacher charging Mejia with anti-Semitism as ``an issue of very
serious litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Mejia's desire to settle the claim, Rojas said, ``That's
nice _ and naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's transfer from the Mission District school _ where half
the 540 children are Hispanic and 65 percent speak little if any
English, and 71 percent qualify for free or reduced-price lunches _
came more than 18 months after Mejia made the ``three white Jewish
women'' statement.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Mejia said, she told four part-time
pre-kindergarten teachers that when she first arrived at Cesar
Chavez in 1991, the teachers were Jewish and did not speak Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia said she later had apologized for the remark, explaining
she hadn't meant to offend anyone. The trouble began for Mejia when
she moved to consolidate the four part-time positions into two
full-time positions, according to San Francisco teachers union
President Kent Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mitchell, the four part-time teachers were equally
qualified. One, however, had seniority. Because she was not chosen
for the full-time position, she filed the grievance.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher won the grievance and works part time at Chavez.
``During the course of investigating that grievance, the
allegations came up of anti-Semitic conduct,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, in what began as a candlelight march from the
school to the Board of Education meeting, parents decried the
district, denounced the superintendent and deified Mejia.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's former husband, Frank Duhl, was the first in line to
assail the anti-Semitic charges against Mejia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Pilar for 30 years,'' said Duhl, who is Jewish.
``We have two sons. She is not anti-Jew. She is a strong, caring
Latina woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superintendent removed her because she was accused of
intolerance,'' he said. ``This is a woman who has been fighting
intolerance and injustice for all of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   The only person to speak in defense of the superintendent's
decision was Tracy Salkowitz, executive director of the American
Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that angered the crowd, she said, ``The
superintendent is a man of incredible integrity. He has made a
thoughtful decision. If a white principal were to insist that all
white kids be taught by white teachers, that principal would be
removed _ immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
