<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-     02-10 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'RE BEING WATCHED _ OR MAYBE NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I heard that Microsoft is planning to make the
new Pentium with a special transmitter that will let them track you
whenever you log on to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heightened Awareness
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HEIGHTENED: You have a mighty high opinion of yourself. Why
in the world would Microsoft care what you do? You're really not
that interesting. I know. I've been tracking you myself.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I know everybody thinks Microsoft is pure evil,
but this really isn't its doing. It makes software. Intel makes the
chips, and even though most Intel machines run on Microsoft
operating systems, they don't absolutely have to.
</P>
<P>
   Intel built what amounts to a unique serial number inside the
new Pentium III chips, ostensibly as an added level of security.
Let's say your rat-faced neighbor swipes your user ID and password
for your online travel service. Since your credit card number is on
file there, he can easily sit next door and book himself and his
frumpy wife and ugly kid on the next slow boat to China, all at
your expense. If, however, that site also required that any
transaction be done from a PC with a known serial number, they
could reject the sale and notify you. You'd be well within your
rights at that point to walk next door and knock over his stupid
birdbath and ceramic chickens.
</P>
<P>
   When the self-appointed guardians of Internet privacy got wind
of this serial-number plan, they went ballistic and started
threatening boycotts. Intel reacted by turning the security feature
off, but that doesn't mean some Poindexter with an itch to see how
many times you visit the Nervous Sheep in Bondage home page can't
figure a way to switch it back on.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there are already so many ways to keep track of things
like that, one more isn't going usher in the New World Order. Waste
your paranoia on better stuff.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: The majority of the people believe that the
21st century starts on Jan. 1, 2000. It should commence on Jan. 1,
2001. Please help correct this general fallacy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stickler
</P>
<P>
   DEAR STICK: Blah blah blah blah blah blah blah. Who cares when
it begins? Our calendar is just an arbitrary numbering system that
not everyone uses anyway. In fact, I declare that the 21st century
begins ... wait a second ... almost ... hold it ... now! Happy New
Year!
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I want to buy a program so that all a seller
has to do is type in the product code and it will print the
invoice, deduct the item from inventory, add in the tax, etc. It
must be so simple that my rather slow wife can use it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Merchant Of Venom
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MERCHANT: You know, I'm so happy my appeal extends even to
folks like you. Here, I'll speak so you can understand:
</P>
<P>
   Wife not slow. Wife no like magic box. Mama Bombay no like magic
box either. You call Mama slow too? Me get club and spear. Unn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
