<SLUG> BC-CPT-CABLE-TV-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S AT&AMP;T VS. AOL IN LOBBYING WAR OVER HIGH-SPEED INTERNET
CONNECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As AT&AMP;T Corp. aggressively enters the cable
business, with plans to offer high-speed Internet connections to
millions of American homes, a growing group of rivals and consumer
groups has begun a nationwide lobbying effort to force the
telephone giant to open its system to Internet competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The fight pits AT&AMP;T, which has struck cable deals in recent
months that will give it access to nearly half of the nation's
homes, against a coalition led by America Online, the world's
largest internet service provider with 15 million customers. It has
also drawn a large group of companies that are the Internet
gateways for millions of Americans, as well as some prominent
former Washington officials who are now lobbyists working for the
telephone industry, the cable industry and the Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest issue in the whole technology
communications realm,'' said Charles M. Brewer, chairman and chief
executive of MindSpring Enterprises Inc., an Internet service
provider with about 340,000 subscribers, which has joined with
America Online, US West, MCI WorldCom and others on Wednesday in
formally announcing their coalition, called OpenNet.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is expected to receive approval from federal regulators as
early as this month to complete its $31 billion acquisition of
Tele-Communications Inc., a leading cable company. Earlier this
week, AT&AMP;T also reached an agreement with Time Warner to offer
local telephone service through that company's cable systems, which
serve 12 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   By marrying cable and the Internet, AT&AMP;T will be able to offer
consumers throughout the nation the ability to navigate through the
World Wide Web at speeds up to 100 times as fast as those provided
by ordinary telephone lines. With high-speed service delivered over
cable modems, images on personal computers appear so fast that they
resemble television screens, a prospect that holds the promise of
significantly expanding commerce on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch. AT&AMP;T intends to require that any customer
who subscribes to its high-speed cable modem service must also pay
a monthly fee of $40 or so for the Internet access that will be
provided by At Home Corp., of which AT&AMP;T will be the largest
shareholder after it completes its acquisition of TCI.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted protests by other Internet providers, who fear
they may be frozen out and who complain that AT&AMP;T will control the
computer standards on the Internet for video, audio and other kinds
of transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say the outcome of the battle _ which is just
beginning before regulators and Congress here and in courts and
municipalities around the nation _ may determine whether the
Internet will continue to be a free-wheeling technology or will be
dominated by a handful of large corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   And both say the fight will determine the speed with which the
Internet develops into a more accessible force in commerce,
entertainment and research, as well as which companies survive the
shakeout of the nascent industry and which profit the most as the
Internet matures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet would not be happening but for the fact that
consumers can now choose their service provider in an unimpeded
way,'' Brewer said. ``If we had to rely the owners of the last mile
of transmission, it's unquestionable that the Internet would not
have developed as it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at AT&AMP;T and the cable companies respond that America
Online and other competitors are trying to muscle in and make use
of technological improvements to the cable systems that are
requiring investments of billions of dollars. They say there will
be plenty of other providers of high-speed access to the Internet,
such as digital telephone technology and satellites. Moreover, they
say, customers will be able to use other Internet providers on
their system, although the customers will have to pay extra.
</P>
<P>
   The executives of AT&AMP;T and its cable allies contend that
revenues from At Home will help to defray the huge capital costs
associated with upgrading the cable system and that the cable
companies did not develop the technology simply to provide what
they call a ``dumb pipeline'' for competitors to take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the fight is over the most valuable real estate of the
Internet, the desktop, which holds the promise of delivering
advertising, commerce and entertainment on an unparalleled new
scale. Consequently, the struggle is as much over pixels as it is
over pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain arrogance to their position, which confuses
what's good for AOL with what's good for the Internet,'' said James
W. Cicconi, general counsel and head of government relations at
AT&AMP;T. ``It's certainly disingenuous and borders on hypocrisy to say
for years that the government should stay out of regulating the
Internet and then suddenly invite the government in when their
business interests change. This is just a very big competitive
player trying to disadvantage a smaller player that came up with a
better idea.''
</P>
<P>
   While scores of companies are trying to develop higher-speed
Internet service through telephones and satellites, some experts
believe that cable modems ultimately hold the greatest promise of
making the World Wide Web much faster, and therefore much more
attractive to computer users and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   At least 350,000 homes _ some estimates run as high as 700,000 _
now have some kind of high speed Internet service, according to a
study released on Wednesday by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts like Forrester Research Inc. estimate that by the
end of 2002, 16 million American households will have high-speed
computer connections to the Internet, and nearly 80 percent of
those will be through cable-based providers like At Home and its
top competitor, Road Runner, a unit of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Although some analysts and executives involved in the fight
believe the regulatory war is simply a sideshow to a possible
commercial settlement, both AT&AMP;T and AOL are prepared to spend
millions of dollars for lobbying and legal expenses and have
retained a number of the biggest lobbying and press relations firms
in Washington and around the nation. The fight is being waged on
four fronts: in Congress, at the Federal Communications Commission,
before local cable regulators in cities around the country, and in
the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have lined up with AOL, contending that AT&AMP;T and
the cable companies are attemping to control the content of what
passes through their wires, just as they tried to control what
programs appeared on their channels before that practice was
prohibited by an act of Congress.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On one side in the fight are the formidable lobbying forces of
AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc., two of the most powerful players
in Washington. The companies have an impressive roster of lobbyists
and lawyers who once worked in the federal government and Congress.
They include Cicconi, a former top White House official in Reagan
and Bush administrations and now the general counsel of AT&AMP;T;
Philip L. Verveer, a leading telecommunications lawyer and close
friend of Bill Clinton since their days together at Georgetown
University, whose wife is the chief of staff to Hillary Rodham
Clinton; and Kevin Joseph, who recently stepped down as senior
counsel to Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition on the other side is being led by Greg Simon, the
former domestic policy adviser to Vice President Gore, and Richard
Bond, former chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing what Microsoft is accused of doing - building a
system where they say you can't separate the transmission from the
actual content,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the
Washington office of Consumers Union, referring to the government's
antitrust suit filed against the software company. ``They're saying
if you want AOL, we'll let you have it but you have to pay At Home
first. This is precisely what telephone companies can't do. The
request from our side is, Let's open up access to cable wire the
same way we require them to open up for programming.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Federal Communications Commission has
declined to step into the fight but has said it will watch the
situation closely. Officials there say they do not want to do
anything that might impede the progress of upgrading the cable
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But cable regulators in a growing number of cities, including
San Francisco, Los Angeles and Seattle, have held hearings and
vowed to consider the issue as franchise licenses are renewed this
year. And one city, Portland, Ore., has blocked AT&AMP;T's cable
venture from moving in without first opening its proposed new
broadband pipeline to rival gateways like America Online. The move
by the city's cable regulators recently prompted the telephone
company to file a lawsuit in federal court there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-03-99 2053EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
