<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-     02-10 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RADICAL IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lame as Sunday's Super Bowl was, the people who bought tickets
still couldn't have gotten a refund. Too bad the game wasn't
sponsored by Sierra Inc. of Bellevue, Wash. Sierra is a software
company that's busily making amends for its own lousy football
game, and providing an admirable new quality standard for the
entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, Sierra pulled thousands of copies of its
Football Pro 99 game from store shelves around the nation. No, the
program didn't contain a deadly computer virus. It didn't delete
vital operating system files by mistake, or make smoke come out of
your monitor. Football Pro 99 worked. It just wasn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   To Sierra executives, this was reason enough for a recall. In
addition, Sierra is doling out refunds and free goodies to unhappy
customers, and company president David Grenewetzki publicly
apologized for selling a product before its time. ``We let the
impending end of the football season influence our decision
process,'' said Grenewetzki. ``We figuratively dropped the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   This end-zone grovel is infinitely more attractive than the
preening and strutting we generally see in the computer industry,
so let's give Sierra high marks for doing the right thing. But
let's not forget to ask the obvious question: How does a bad piece
of software come to market in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   I asked Dan Rogers, who oversaw the Football Pro 99 project, and
who describes himself with pulse-quickening candor as ``the guy
that released that really crummy product.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wasn't supposed to be crummy. The idea was to
create a game that would let hardcore fans simulate entire NFL
seasons, with the computer depicting the probable performances of
actual players and teams. Sort of like Microsoft Flight Simulator
with blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is that simulation games are murderously difficult to
create, and Sierra wanted this one on store shelves before the end
of the football season. People were putting in 120-hour weeks, said
Rogers. ``I had guys who were sleeping there. I was sleeping there.
I hadn't seen my wife in a month.''
</P>
<P>
   And it still wasn't enough. The only way to make the deadline
was to cut corners. ``You start talking to the quality-assurance
guys and inch by inch your quality seems to slip and you start
making compromises,'' said Rogers. ``You don't even realize you're
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game wouldn't work properly with a number of those popular
three-dimensional graphics accelerator cards that gamers love.
Equally important, it just didn't simulate the NFL with sufficient
accuracy. Running backs didn't gain as much yardage as they should
have; quarterbacks didn't pass for the right number of yards. But
hey, it's a game. Who's going to know or care?
</P>
<P>
   The gamers, that's who. ``The user reactions from our fans was
immediately very bad,'' said Rogers. ``We just said, `My gosh, what
did we do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's more a question of what they didn't do. Software quality
experts say there are fundamental flaws in the way most programs
are designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can deliver much higher quality than they do today. Most
of them just don't understand how to do it,'' says John Pustaver,
president of Creative Data Systems in Sudbury, Mass. and an
experienced software tester. Pustaver said many software firms
neglect rigorous planning and testing, and instead just strive to
get the product out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bampos, vice president of software quality assurance at
Metamor Software Solutions in Newton, Mass., says the Internet has
made the problem worse, by allowing firms to rush bad products to
market and then post repair patches on line.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra, too, is offering a patch for Football Pro 99 users, but
the firm has gone much further. Customers can also get their money
back, plus a credit good for any $30 Sierra game. In addition, the
company created a Web site called Home Team where customers can
consult with Sierra developers about the design of Football Pro
2000, to make sure they get it right. ``We have been overwhelmed
with customer support,'' he said. Then again, Sierra may have
overwhelmed its customers by embracing the radical idea that
software shouldn't be sold until it works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-04-99 1320EST &QL;
</P>
