<SLUG> BC-90210-RENEWED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX BRINGING BACK `90210' FOR 10TH SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fear not, friends of the ZIP code gang. ``Beverly
Hills, 90210'' will still be around in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Already one of the longest-running prime-time dramas on
television, ``90210'' is set to go it at least one year longer.
Doug Herzog, Fox network's entertainment president, announced
Tuesday that the show has been renewed for a 10th season, with
episodes set to air through 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ```Beverly Hills, 90210' is one of the most entertaining
ensemble dramas on television, and we're happy to be bringing it
back for a 10th season,'' said Herzog, who took over the helm at
Fox in January.
</P>
<P>
   The drama, which marked a comeback for Spelling Entertainment,
has followed a bunch of friends from their sophomore year in high
school into their 20s and adulthood. It originally focused on the
Walsh family _ Brandon (Jason Priestley), Brenda (Shannen Doherty),
Jim (James Eckhouse) and Cindy (Carol Potter) _ who moved from
Minnesota to the high-brow Los Angeles County neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, none of those characters remains. Priestley, who
was also an executive producer and directed several episodes, left
earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining from the original ensemble are Kelly Taylor (Jennie
Garth), Donna Martin (Tori Spelling), David Silver (Brian Austin
Green) and Steve Sanders (Ian Ziering). Original character Dylan
McKay (Luke Perry) returned to the show this season.
</P>
<P>
   The show still wins its time slot in key demographic groups,
including adults ages 18 to 34; the show ranks seventh in prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   There had been talk that Spelling Entertainment would replace
the current ``90210'' and begin another generation of the show with
a new cast that would start out in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came about a week after the network announced
that ``Melrose Place,'' another Spelling show on Fox, would not
return next season. Its final episode will air in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
