<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-BLACKSOFTWARE-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Microsoft Encarta African-- a distinguished addition to software
targeting African-Americans 
By Shelia M. Poole  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Walk the bustling streets of Timbuktu.
</P>
<P>
   Trace the trans-Atlantic slave routes and learn about customs
that survive today and can be traced directly to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the gravelly voice of Louis ``Satchmo'' Armstrong belt
out ``Back O' Town Blues'' during a 1965 performance.
</P>
<P>
   All with a mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other features are now available on Microsoft Encarta
Africana software, which was released on the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr.'s birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tree needs plants to grow, and we need a sense of who we
are,'' said G. Ewa Ealy, co-manager and special events coordinator
for the Shrine of the Black Madonna bookstore in Atlanta who plans
to carry the product. ``I don't think you can underestimate the
potential this product has to our community and to our world.''
</P>
<P>
   Encarata Africana, which sells for $70, offers a groundbreaking,
comprehensive encyclopedia of Africans and people of African
descent throughout the world _ from the shores of Africa to the
United States, the Caribbean, South America and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was the brainchild of Dr. Louis Henry Gates Jr., noted
author and chairman of the Afro-American Studies department at
Harvard University, and Dr. Kwame Anthony Appiah, professor of
Afro-American Studies and Philosophy at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The two made a pact 25 years ago that they would bring the dream
of W.E.B. DuBois, a leading African-American scholar of the 20th
century, to produce a comprehensive encyclopedia of Africana.
</P>
<P>
   The first companies they approached about the project _ then as
a book _ were lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   They were told by one company it was ``not economically viable''
and were asked if Gates could possibly raise $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   They struck gold, however, when an executive at Random House
suggested doing the project on CD-ROM. With financial backing from
the likes of composer Quincy Jones and others, they came up with a
prototype. But even with a good prototype, they continued to hit
snags.
</P>
<P>
   Once, they were told the timing was off and that it might work
better as a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have cried,'' said co-editor Gates. ``They all said,
`Great project, but its not commercially viable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Microsoft. The parties got together, and soon plans were
made to launch Encarta Africana.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing quite like this out there,'' said Gates, who
said the editors and publishers are making a concerted effort to
reach schools, churches and universities. ``This is the whole black
world. This is the bottom line. We want to make the African and
African-American experience a fundamental part of the fabric of
culture itself, of knowledge itself and of education itself. Not
just something that is done in the coldest, darkest, dampest month
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said talks are under way about a second version, which will
be ``bigger and badder'' than the first.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the attention has been focused on Encarta
Africana, other software titles are available that either target
African-Americans or address some aspect of African-American
culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Learning Co. last summer published Essence
Virtual Makeover, beauty software created specifically for
African-American women. The software, created in conjunction with
Essence magazine, has gotten off to a good start. Learning
officials say it is the seventh-best-selling product in its
category, personal improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Users load a photo into their computer and within minutes can
try out hundreds of different hairstyles, hair colors, cosmetics
and contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has done pretty well considering it has a smaller
demographic target than a lot of our software,'' said Pamela Sooge,
vice president of lifestyles. ``We estimate that 2 million
African-American women use computers at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The project made sense, Sooge said, considering on average
African-American women spend more on hair care and cosmetics than
their white counterparts. But that was not being addressed in
previous computer makeover products. African-American women found a
very limited number of styles that would fit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue really comes down to PC penetration and
purchasing behavior, and that will grow obviously as there are more
computers in those households,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs available include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Black Wings: The program chronicles African-Americans in
aviation. Black Wings is a joint project of the National Aerospace
Museum and Fairfax, Va.-based SSB Inc. It was released in 1996 and
includes interviews with many of the original Tuskegee airmen and
information on aviators in the Korean and Vietnam wars, then takes
users into the space age. $39.99
</P>
<P>
   _ Clip Art With Color Volumes I-IV: Published by Gikuuri
Software, this series contains more than 300 color images of
African-Americans in different settings. The images can be used in
newsletters, invitations and brochures. $29.99-$49.99
</P>
<P>
   _ Encyclopedia Britannica Profiles Black History: This software
program answers such questions as what was the Dred Scott decision?
When were the Fugitive Slave Acts passed? This interactive program
contains time lines, more than 500 articles, 275 photographs and
audio and video clips. $29.99
</P>
<P>
   While these and other black-oriented software programs have
gotten a thumbs up from many, others bemoan the dearth of computer
products that specifically target African-Americans or that include
African-Americans in prominent roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably an issue of critical mass,'' said Patrick
McElroy, president of the Freedom Group, an Atlanta-based Internet
consulting firm and owner of EverythingBlack.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a company with $20 million in overhead a year, it's
probably not worth your while to do Afrocentric software
exclusively. But if you're a one- or two-person shop, obviously you
can make enough money to pay expenses and have some extra.
Oftentimes we are underserved because we are waiting for some big
corporation to satisfy a niche when perhaps a niche player should
come in and take care of that need.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-08-99 1109EST &QL;
