<HEADLINE>
APPLE AIMS FOR BUSINESS NICHE WITH NEW GE SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WENDY TANAKA   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer Inc's powerful new G3 computers
represent a crucial step for the company into the arena of business
computing.
</P>
<P>
   The G3 design has the same unconventional look as Apple's
enormously popular iMac. But that's where the similarity between
the two computers stops.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is designed for the home and sells for about $1,200.
The new G3 is aimed at design professionals and ranges in price
from $1,600 to $3,000. It is a much faster version of Apple's
original G3, introduced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The G3 has up to a gigabyte of memory and 100 gb of internal
disk storage. It also has processor speeds of up to 400 megahertz
and a built-in, high-performance ATI RAGE 128 graphics card. The
G3's minitower flips open so users can add memory, storage or PCI
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said Web site designers, publishing houses, schools and
video editing companies will be some of the main G3 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a loyal following, and this machine is exactly what
they've been looking for,'' Apple spokesman Russell Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the iMac have exceeded industry projections. Since its
launch in August, 800,000 iMacs have been sold _ about 300,000 more
than analysts had projected. And Apple just introduced a newer
version of the iMac, offering slightly more speed and a new array
of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said figures for the new G3, introduced last month,
wouldn't be available until April, when Apple's first-quarter
results are posted.
</P>
<P>
   Technology analysts predicted that the G3 would not be a
barn-burner product like the iMac because Apple missed the boat
several years ago and didn't expand its base of business customers.
As a result, Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT operating platform
swooped in and has become the dominant business desktop workstation
for producing graphics and three-dimensional visuals.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Specker, an analyst in Soundview Technology Group Inc.'s
San Francisco office, said Apple's failure to penetrate the
business market stems from the ``fundamentally poor decision'' by
former Apple chief executive John Sculley to not license Apple
technology to other vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest Inc. of San Jose, Calif., estimated about 63 million
Windows NT operating units will be sold in 2001. That is roughly
nine times more than the 7 million NT computers sold in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said 1.6 million older Apple G3 units were sold, and he
said the newer series offers heftier sales potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at the high end of Web design and graphics will be
doing back flips over the G3. It's a great install-based extension,
but it won't do anything to get into Microsoft's space,'' said John
Oltsik, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc., a market research
firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Apple die-hards are most likely to purchase the new G3, Specker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The G3 target market is people with a lot of money who like
Apples,'' he said. ``That's a substantive revenue opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-08-99 1400EST &QL;
</P>
