<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-PLASMA-SFCHRON &LR;      02-10 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PLASMA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Welcome to the Net's Little Shop of Horrors  
 By Jamie Beckett   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most online shoppers don't have a pressing need for green
fluorescent protein, nucleic acid or moose intestine.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, there's Chemdex. The Palo Alto startup has
opened an online store where scientists can buy these and thousands
of other biochemical substances from dozens of different
manufacturers. Although small, this nascent Web marketplace is one
sign of a dramatic shift in how businesses purchase goods.
</P>
<P>
   While Amazon.com, eBay and other online retailers that sell to
consumers have grabbed all the attention, Internet buying by
businesses has been growing _ fast. Last year, business-to-business
e-commerce reached $43 billion, nearly 10 times consumer online
spending, according to Forrester Research. The Cambridge, Mass.,
research firm expects that to soar to $1.3 trillion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that commerce comes from companies such as networking
firm 3Com or PC supplier Dell. But a whole new breed of online
merchant is opening up shop, representing not just one manufacturer
but dozens in one industry, selling plastic or metal or fabric or
even intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   ``These middlemen help buyers do comparison shopping,'' said
Chuck Shih, research director for Electronic Commerce at Gartner
Group. ``They're just exploding now. It's a model of commerce that
lends itself to the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Chemdex, most researchers purchased materials for their
experiments from catalogs. These catalogs are a far cry from Land's
End or J. Crew. They're dense volumes of mostly text and as thick
as telephone books. Although a few manufacturers had their own Web
sites, there was no Chemdex-style supermarket for researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Customers include cancer researchers, cell biologists,
neuroscientists and biochemists _ both individual researchers and
those who work at large companies. They're ordering biochemicals
used in scientific research such as antibodies, proteins and
enzymes.
</P>
<P>
   On average, a research scientist might spend five hours a week
flipping through 40 or 50 catalogs, scribbling product numbers and
prices on scraps of paper. The scientist or an administrator would
then transfer that information to a purchase order form _ one form
for each manufacturer. Orders may then have to be approved by
several people before they get sent to the supplier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's enormously inefficient,'' said David Perry, co-founder of
Chemdex (www.chemdex.com). While a student at Harvard Business
School, Perry helped start a small biotech company and saw
firsthand how much effort researchers put into simply ordering
materials. ``I figured there had to be a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and Jeffrey Leane, Chemdex's chief technology officer
founded the company 15 months ago. It now offers more than 150,000
products from 60 manufacturers. The online ordering system works
this way: buyers who sign up for the service search the database
for the products they need. Each search returns a list of suppliers
and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Say, you need some DMEM, which is a sort of food for cells. A
search turns up 13 items _ different types of DMEM, different
quantities and prices and, in this case, one supplier. The
researcher clicks on the desired items. The information's entered
onto an order form comparable to the online shopping baskets
e-retail sites use. When the order is complete, the researcher
clicks to purchase. If the order requires spending approvals, it
will go to the appropriate corporate officials, then to the
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Chemdex's biggest customer is Genentech, the South San
Francisco biotech giant. Most of its other customers are smaller
companies like Eos Biotechnology, a South San Francisco startup
doing DNA research. Privately held Chemdex doesn't disclose
revenues but says between 50 and 100 researchers sign up every day.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing up for Chemdex, scientist Kim Ha of Eos was
trying to juggle two jobs: handling purchasing for her lab while
still carving out time to conduct genetic research.`I'd spend an
hour or two every day taking care of purchasing. So then I'd be
working 10 to 12 hours a day just so I'd have time for my
research,'' she said. Now, the lab's scientists can place most of
their own orders. Not only does it make Ha's job easier, but
there's less chance of error and researchers are able to track
their own orders directly. Accounting is happy, too, Ha said, it is
easier to track of what is ordered and how much is spent.
</P>
<P>
   Perry and Leane weren't the only ones to spot opportunity in
providing online ordering for the $10 billion scientific materials
marketplace. SciQuest, a North Carolina startup, began offering an
online database of scientific materials in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   SciQuest is aiming at a slightly broader market. In addition to
the substances Chemdex offers, the companysells testing materials
for industrial markets and scientific equipment. It also offers
www.labdeal.com, an online clearance center for surplus lab
supplies. The main site, www.sciquest.com, will be capable of
handling transactions by April, but a beta version is being used by
a few customers now. Last year, SciQuest had $1.5 million cq in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Campbell, electronic commerce project manager for
pharmaceutical giant Hoffman-La Roche, said her company is moving
to online ordering _ and it's already made the process more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first big difference is the online catalog is more current
than the paper one,'' Campbell said. ``If you use a paper catalog,
sometimes you have an old part number, sometimes a page is ripped
out. It doesn't show prices your company may have negotiated with
the supplier. I have to search one (paper) catalog at a time, and
I'll have catalogs open all over my desk.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning. Online ordering cuts out some
stops along the ordering process where things can go wrong. An
administrator may enter the wrong product number. The order could
get lost on the way to the vendor. The vendor may not have all of
the materials and hold the order for full shipment. Or the vendor
could send the order and it gets lost in shipping. And lots, lots
more.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman La Roche's electronic ordering system includes data on
what each scientist can spend and it automatically routes orders to
the right person for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Varda Lief, an analyst at Forrester Research, said she doesn't
expect SciQuest and Chemdex to face many competitors because the
cost and complexity of setting up a site that is so technical is
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly a niche market, but one where there will be
considerable growth,'' she said. She estimates the overall market
for online pharmaceutical and medical supplies will be $1.4 billion
this year and $44 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about efficiency,'' said Martha Greer, vice president
of marketing at Chemdex. ``If scientists save time (ordering) they
have more time at the research bench to discover something of use
to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-07-99 2204EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
