<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARL-CALDWELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE TO FEATURE STORIES FROM PIONEERING BLACK JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ When friends talk about Earl Caldwell, they
use phrases such as ``steel in his constitution'' to describe his
dead-on aim to succeed against any odds _ and then they mention the
honey-dripping charm that he emits.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has so much happened to one black journalist. He's
nothing if not a storyteller _ and he has tales to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell, the writer-in-residence at the Robert C. Maynard
Institute for Journalism Education in Oakland, will share his and
other black journalists' stories about the early days of newspaper
integration in serial narratives that will run on the Maynard
Institute Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time, we have wanted to do more work on the history
of journalists of color,'' said Stephen Montiel, president of the
Maynard Institute. ``So many younger journalists weren't aware of
who came before them. We also wanted to do more on Bob's life as a
journalist. ... There's no journalist better to do that than Earl
Caldwell through his life experience and his relationship with Bob
Maynard.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those stories destined for the Web site
(www.maynardije.org) will include newspaper clippings of Maynard,
the late Oakland Tribune owner and first black publisher of a major
metropolitan newspaper in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to present a clear, sharp picture of Maynard, try to
archive black journalists, re-create that period, what we struggled
with, what we started,'' said Caldwell, 60. ``Bob Maynard was one
of the great journalists of his era.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell's friendship with Maynard began in 1961, when they were
the only black reporters at two Pennsylvania newspapers, Maynard in
York and Caldwell in Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a guy (Maynard) from New York City who wanted to be a
journalist and couldn't get a job in his own hometown _ not because
he wasn't good enough but because he's too black,'' Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell, a former New York Times reporter and New York Daily
News columnist, has had quite a career himself.
</P>
<P>
   Like who really killed the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.? It
wasn't James Earl Ray, Caldwell says. He was a witness to the
shooting and saw a man crouched in nearby bushes. Whatever happened
to him?
</P>
<P>
   Like refusing to be a spy for the FBI or turn over notes to an
organization that Americans later learned was setting up the Black
Panthers. Yes, Caldwell was in the midst of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell began working on mainstream newspapers in the early
1960s, one of a handful of black reporters at daily papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who bridged an era,'' said longtime friend Leroy
Aarons, former executive editor of the Oakland Tribune and founder
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a guy who wanted to make it in the newspaper
business,'' Aarons said. ``He was obsessed with newspapers. But he
was coming up against a hostile environment for people of color.
Right away, here's somebody with a tremendous amount of steel in
his constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell had to walk the fine line of black reporter on a white
newspaper and black man in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sooner had he landed,'' recalled Aarons, than the civil
rights movement exploded. ``Earl was thrown in the middle. Here you
are trying to survive and prove you're just as good as anyone with
a Caucasian background, and suddenly you're faced with an explosive
and divisive social change in which you have to reconcile your
professional and personal ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   For Caldwell, who had grown up in the nearly all-white town of
Clearfield, Pa., the experience was educational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think of myself as black,'' Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   But as rioting erupted in cities across the nation, and the
black community demanded ``white reporters out,'' reporters such as
Caldwell and Maynard were sought after to go places where white
reporters were not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks at the bottom said, `White reporters out.' That's what
opened the door (for newspaper integration). Editors had to give
the blacks jobs,'' Caldwell said. ``Diversity in the newsroom
didn't start because some editors decided it. The community rioted,
and their reporters couldn't cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At papers where there were no African-Americans, news executives
sent the first black person they encountered _ be he janitor,
messenger or artist _ to the scene of trouble to report back to
white rewrite men, Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   When Caldwell joined the New York Times and was dispatched to
San Francisco to cover the Black Panthers, the FBI decided it
wanted Caldwell to be an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some satisfaction in being tested, and meeting the
test,'' Caldwell said. ``All of these stories have to be told. The
Internet is a great vehicle to tell them. There's an urgency to
tell them. My hair has turned white.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
