<HEADLINE>
CRITERIA PROPOSED FOR ISSUING OF INTERNET ADDRESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Companies wanting a piece of the lucrative business
of issuing Internet addresses will need at least $100,000 in the
bank, $500,000 in liability insurance and a proven computer
infrastructure, under minimum requirements proposed Monday by the
nonprofit corporation that has been tapped to take over
administration of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, ``domain registration,'' as the issuing of Internet
addresses is known, has been the government-sanctioned monopoly of
Network Solutions Inc., a Virginia-based company that grew rich on
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Network Solutions priced a new stock offering
Monday. In the more than a year that it has taken the Clinton
administration and the nonprofit Internet Corporation for Assigned
Names and Numbers to open the business to competition, Network
Solutions has set up an international network of partners to
administer its domain registration business around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed guidelines were announced just as Network Solutions
completed what is expected to be the largest secondary stock
offering ever by an Internet company. The offering of 4.58 million
shares was priced Monday by J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. to open Tuesday on
Nasdaq at $170 a share. The sale is expected to bring in about $780
million for Network Solutions' parent company, the Science
Applications International Corp., which will reduce its ownership
in the company to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Network Solutions, based in Herndon, Va., has had
the exclusive worldwide right to assign Internet addresses that end
in .com, .net and .org, charging $70 to register a domain name for
two years. The result has been phenomenal growth, with net income
in the first nine months of 1998 growing threefold, to $7.5
million. Although 1998 revenues have not yet been reported,
analysts have predicted they could hit $90 million, compared with
$6 million, $18 million and $45 million, respectively, in the
previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the nonprofit corporation, known as Icann, also posted
competing sets of proposed bylaws for the supporting organization
being formed to help the nonprofit corporation decide when and how
to add new ``top-level domains'' _ the three-letter suffixes of
Internet addresses, like the popular .com.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines and bylaws have been posted for public comment.
Final versions are expected to be approved by Icann's board of
directors at its next meeting, to be held in Singapore March 2
through 4.
</P>
<P>
   Icann's initial goal is to introduce five competitors to Network
Solutions by the end of April. That test is expected to last about
two months. Then Icann plans to let an unlimited number of
companies around the world participate in the registry.
</P>
<P>
   But the board first must decide a number of other issues,
including how it will pick the first five companies and how much
they will have to pay Network Solutions for its operating of the
main registry, the worldwide list of addresses that directs
Internet traffic around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Esther Dyson, interim chairman of Icann, said the
board would likely hold an international lottery to pick the five
test companies. That option, however, is being reconsidered because
of opposition from a number of groups, including the European
Union, which fears that domain registration will not be
geographically balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dyson said the board wanted to insure that the first five
included a variety of big and small companies from different parts
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines say the primary criteria for selecting
participants for the test phase ``would be the applicant's
technical and business capabilities to support the test and its
willingness to commit the resources and to collaborate closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary considerations ``include the extent to which the
applicant's participation would promote early robust competition,
wide geographic availability of domain name registration services,
and accommodation of alternative business models and types.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed guidelines are outlined by Icann in a 30-plus page
document posted on its Web site after the stock markets closed
Monday. In addition to minimum technical, operational and financial
issues, the criteria also deal with protections against fraud and
infringement of intellectual property rights; data security,
privacy and special technical requirements to protect Internet
stability and operational integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Icann has proposed that applicants who want to compete in the
test phase pay a $2,500 application fee. That would drop to $1,000
when competition is opened to an unlimited number of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Companies would then be required to pay an additional $3,000 to
$6,000 accreditation fee, and would give Icann $1 a year for each
domain name registered. Network Solutions last year registered
about 1.9 million new domain names.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary requirements are likely to raise protests from
smaller Internet groups who fear that Icann is being driven by
large corporate interests. However, Ms. Dyson said that the board
was trying to ``make it pretty easy to be one of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that implementing changes in the domain name
system will be a contentious issue,'' she said. ``The point is to
make the transition fair and the results fair. As long as everyone
knows the rules and can play on the same terms, we will have
achieved that. As the initial board considers comments on the
guidelines, we will work hard with the Internet community to
develop guidelines that strike everyone as reasonable, sound and
transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Bura, president of Alldomains.com, a Pleasant Hill,
Calif., company that plans to apply to be a test registrar, said
the guidelines and capital requirements looked ``doable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
