<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE09-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Won't you be my online valentine? 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Valentine's Day _ in theory at least _ should be one
of the most personal holidays on the calendar. It should be a time
to turn off the computer and take the person you love to a
restaurant, buy flowers, send notes written in longhand and, my
gosh, hug.
</P>
<P>
   But in this cyber-world, there are complications.
</P>
<P>
   There may be people whom you'd like to take to dinner, but _
because of distance or circumstances _ cannot. Or perhaps your
excuse is even more flimsy _ maybe you just flat forgot to buy the
candy or the card and need a last-minute way to say ``I care.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to decide for yourself if an electronic greeting
from the Internet has the warmth and feeling you would like to
convey. For some folks, it would be better to just pick up the
phone instead. But if your valentine would enjoy an electronic
greeting, then the Web can furnish plenty of choices.
</P>
<P>
   The first site on our tour of love offers electronic greeting
cards for free. You'll find all types, including cards customized
for Valentine's Day, as well as cards for friends, lovers, bosses,
casual acquaintances (why the heck are you sending them a card
anyway?) and almost any other occasion or relationship possible.
It's called Blue Mountain and is located at
http://www1.bluemountain.com.
</P>
<P>
   Just click on the category of card you'd like to send,
personalize the message and push the button. Your greetings arrive
almost instantly. And there are cards in other languages. In this
wide world, that's a handy thing to have. There's no charge at all.
</P>
<P>
   The next site isn't free, but it's worth mentioning since it
offers to send real paper greeting cards for you. Just select the
card online and give the address. You'll find the site at
http://sparks.com. Prices vary, but most of the cards, including
mailing, go for about $2.75. If a card isn't enough, you can also
send other gifts, including chocolates, from the same site.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you do for the unconventional valentines on your
list? One thing, for those who have an out-of-this-world valentine,
is to send one of the science-fiction-oriented Valentine's Day
cards from 3D Adventure at
http://www.dair3.com/greeting/valentin.cgi. Some of the cards are
really quite beautiful, and many include animation.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all these sites work in the same general way. You select
a category, click on the card that you like, furnish your e-mail
address and the address of your valentine, and the card is sent. In
almost every case, your recipient will need access to the World
Wide Web to view the card. So if the person you care about has
access to e-mail only, perhaps you should try sending a personal
message, instead of an e-card.
</P>
<P>
   A personal favorite is a Web site called Regards.Com. It's also
free and _ as you would expect _ includes an assortment of
ready-made Valentine's Day cards. But if you have a Web site, you
can use Regards to send a greeting card that includes an electronic
image or photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Just place the image or photograph on your own Web space and
then fill in the blanks at Regards to include that image in a
customized card. If you don't have a Web site, you can also include
Web addresses for images that you've found on other sites.
</P>
<P>
   If none of these sites suit you, simply do a search for ``free
electronic greeting cards,'' and you'll find literally hundreds of
other places that offer everything from sweet sentiments to racy
adult-oriented cards. And keep in mind that there's still plenty of
time to do something really crazy: Buy a real card and send it
through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
