<HEADER>
A9383 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NASCAR-ART-2TAKES     02-10 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NASCAR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR WAVES TECHIES AWAY FROM TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ As his stock car roared past the empty
black-and-white-checkered spectator stands at 190 miles per hour,
Jeff Gordon could barely hang on to his steering wheel, let alone
check his rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Under the brilliant blue Florida sky at the Daytona
International Speedway, Gordon and a crowd of other drivers were
testing themselves and their cars one day not long ago in
preparation for the Daytona 500, the biggest event in the world of
the National Association of Stock Car Auto Racing.
</P>
<P>
   After a few laps, Gordon thundered to his service spot in the
infield garages, which reeked of gasoline and sweat. Two crew
members jacked up the left side of his charcoal gray Chevy, which
bore an orange skull and crossbones on its hood as it awaited a
rainbow-colored paint job.
</P>
<P>
   One crew member slid under the tailpipe. Another plugged in the
laptop. That data link to the car can reveal a stream of details,
from rpm to shock-absorber performance _ but come race day, on Feb.
14, that data link will be banned.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's carefully calibrated approach to technology creates
both an opportunity and a conundrum for drivers like Gordon, a
superstar of NASCAR racing. Gordon and his crew are among the most
technologically adept racing teams in NASCAR competition, a hugely
popular sport that draws television ratings second only to those of
the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is central to the sport, yet apart from it on race
day. On-board computers, for example, can be used for manufacturing
and test drives, but not during an actual event.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a factor in Gordon's victories but not the
deciding factor. His team clearly relies on computers for data that
enable him to reach new performance highs, but a lesser driver
would very likely get into that same technology-enhanced car and
drive it into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology makes the car better, which forces me to drive
faster,'' said Gordon, 27, taking a break from his racing in a
rainbow-colored fireproof racing suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's total 1998 race winnings were $9.3 million _ he is the
two-time defending champion on NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit _ and
he earned much more in endorsements and licensing. Some fans love
him, and some don't, because he wins almost all the time. Some love
him, and some don't, because of his Tom Cruise good looks and
squeaky clean image. (He appears in ``Got Milk?'' advertisements.)
</P>
<P>
   He is the top driver in recent NASCAR history, perhaps a direct
result of the technical prowess that helps give him his winning
edge. He also has one of NASCAR's richest sponsors, DuPont
Automotive Finishes.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's limits on technology are tough. That may seem odd,
considering the millions of dollars spent on high-tech car design
and improvements. It is also true that in NASCAR racing, as in many
other sports, the debate on pushing the rule book on admitting
certain technologies is almost as old as the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But NASCAR officials say such limits are the only way to keep
the sport affordable and, more important, human _ a contest of men
and machines, without computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to throw a rope around the technology,'' said
Gary Nelson, director of the Winston Cup, NASCAR's most elite
series of races. ``If you don't keep that in check, then the team
with the best tech wins. The exciting thing about NASCAR is that
you never know who's going to have a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials have been trying to preserve the soul of their
machine-driven sport since the first race, in the late 1940s, when
drivers drove stock cars from the factories to the beaches of
Daytona, where they would compete without modifications to the
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular forms of auto racing, like Championship Auto
Racing Teams, the sort seen at the Indianapolis 500, and Formula
One, the high-tech European sport, allow telemetry _ the
transmission of data to and from on-board computerized sensors
during a race. Using equipment similar to that employed during
NASCAR test runs, these drivers and crews can ascertain everything
from the left rear tire's pressure to the car's fuel consumption
while the car is moving.
</P>
<P>
   As Nascar racing grew in popularity in the 1960s, Bill France
Sr., the promoter who was largely responsible for that, tightened
the rules for car design and performance improvement to maintain a
level playing field. On-board computers were outlawed as soon as
they became available in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the rules have grown to include several dozen pages of
guidelines, which are continually updated. These govern the size
and specifications of virtually all internal components, from
shocks to telemetry. During the Daytona 500 test drives, a dusty
card table displayed some recent shock absorbers that had been
approved for use.
</P>
<P>
   Though NASCAR has complete jurisdiction over what parts and
technology may be used during a race, it has no authority beyond
the track. As a result, teams like Gordon's might spend up to $10
million per year to develop and manufacture their cars. But no
matter how much they spend, the result must meet with NASCAR's
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technical viewpoint, it's extremely frustrating,'' said
Jim Wall, lead engineer for Hendrick Motorsports of Harrisburg,
N.C., the company that modifies stock cars for Gordon and other
Nascar stars, like Terry LaBonte and Wally Dallenbach Jr. ``It's my
job to make the car go faster. If there's a problem, I have to find
the solution to fix it, but often I can't use that solution because
it's not legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they must abide by the guidelines, which can change as
frequently as every two weeks, the crews are extremely high tech.
Hendrick Motorsports relies on computers for every step of the
production process.
</P>
<P>
   Using computer-aided design and manufacturing software on
Windows NT work stations, Hendrick is able to design a car, down to
a tiny cylinder head, in a completely virtual environment. A
computer-controlled machine then cuts the parts, making them comply
with NASCAR specifications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   On race day, NASCAR employs a team of 70 inspectors _ usually 8
per car _ to inspect parts and check for hidden computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to train our personnel to find telemetry in the nooks
and crannies,'' said Mike Helton, NASCAR's vice president for
competition. ``We don't want to have to tear a car apart after a
race is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of monitoring for technological compliance is becoming
more difficult. Of special concern are tiny chips that provide
traction control, which helps a car improve performance on turns.
Though NASCAR says it has found no violations, Nelson said the
association had recently received a report that a British
manufacturer might be selling hard to detect traction-control chips
for $1 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these chips are purchased and used, Nelson said, they
will probably be discovered eventually. ``If there's traction
control on a car, then the wheels won't spin,'' he said with a grin
as cars rolled out for their test drives. ``That's all we'd have to
look for.'' Throughout the sport, that kind of low-tech swaggering
reinforces the high-tech restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Until telemetry became available in the early 1990s, NASCAR
crews had to rely on the driver's feedback to determine what areas
might need improvement. Today this feedback is measured in
conjunction with what is known as a Pi system, the on-board
telemetry used by the vast majority of the teams during test
drives.
</P>
<P>
   The Pi system, manufactured by a British company named Pi
Research, contains two black boxes, each the size of a pack of
cigarettes, on the floor next to the driver. Transducers run from
the boxes to dozens of locations throughout the car _ the steering
wheel, the shocks, the tires and so on. Pi's sensors measure the
movement of, say, the steering wheel; voltage changes reflect the
movement changes.
</P>
<P>
   When a driver pulls into his garage after a practice lap, his
crew engineer plugs a Windows laptop into a port inside the car.
Within seconds, the data acquired by the Pi system is downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Pi's specially designed analysis software graphs the car's
performance. Back at the shop, crew members interpret the data and
make appropriate changes to the car's parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sending out the space shuttle and bringing back some
rocks,'' said Gordon's crew chief, Ray Evernham, as he checked a
laptop. ``You don't know what to do with it until you get back.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials say they limit on-board telemetry in part to
keep down costs for the owners. ut there is still a high cost. A Pi
system can cost up to $50,000 without software modifications; Pi
has no major competitors in this area. Though some drivers earn
millions annually, the price tag remains too high for others.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Marcis, a veteran NASCAR driver who has been in more than
30 Daytona 500's, could not afford to buy the telemetry for his
test drive. If he wants to know how his shocks are handling the
bumps, he does not have a computer graph; he must look under the
hood to see how high the oil ring on the shock shaft has risen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this new technology takes away from the sport,'' he said.
``I hope it doesn't ruin it. Nascar tries to keep it out, but
there's not much they can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR might restrict computer use inside race cars, but it
relies on them heavily for scoring and timing. An antenna loop is
buried under the track just before the finish line, and each car is
equipped with a radio transmitting transponder that emits its own
unique frequency.
</P>
<P>
   When the car passes the antenna loop, a signal is sent through a
cable to the scoring terminal, which records the car number and the
time.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR began using this system in 1995. But NASCAR cannot afford
to make a mistake, so it has several lower-tech backup systems (and
a second transponder system in place for redundancy). In fact,
extra timekeepers stand at the pit stops to record entrance and
exit times manually.
</P>
<P>
   System crashes are rare, said Phil Housely, NASCAR's timing and
scoring engineer, although the car transponders experience errors
one out of six times. When that happens, ``we always fix it,'' said
Sharon Spicer, an operator, ``but we panic first.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Gordon's recent day in Daytona, he had the fastest
average speed on the track. He pulled back into his garage after
his last lap, and the crew downloaded the Pi system information
while Gordon headed through a crowd of fans to his trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Between bites of a banana, he said the technology enabled him to
be a faster driver. But when the Daytona 500 begins on Feb. 14,
with him in the pole position, he and his crew will be on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see that green flag,'' he said, ``I'm the on-board
computer. I'm the telemetry.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
