<HEADLINE>
RACING AROUND WITH NO WORRY ABOUT CRASHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike most sports fans, auto racing die-hards are unable to
mimic their heroes' feats. ``You can't play NASCAR in your
backyard,'' said Blake Davidson, director of interactive marketing
for the National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing.
</P>
<P>
   But you can play it on line, courtesy of NASCAR's interactive
division, which is dedicated to producing realistic computer games
and a behind-the-scenes Web site. Fans can race as fast as they
like and if they crash, all they have to do is reboot.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts for multiplayer games have been competing over the
Internet through the NASCAR Racing Online Series (www.nros.com), a
Net-based game site available through the pay-to-play Total
Entertainment Network. After buying an accompanying CD-ROM and
downloading free software that makes Internet play possible,
players choose and modify cars based on those used by actual
drivers, like Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   The speed might be sluggish compared with the real thing, but
it's enough to keep fans coming back. ``It's a total adrenaline
rush, even when I feel like I have no idea what I'm doing,'' said
Andrew Sarnow, 32, a marketing director from New York who recently
spent $150 on a special computer-game steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But the NASCAR Online Web site (www.nascar.com) is a fan's most
important link to the racing world. The site employs five full-time
writers who travel to events throughout the year and report back
immediately. There is also a live feed of each event's timing and
scoring _ crucial to fans who cannot tune in to the television
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are occasional snags. Since many NASCAR tracks are
in remote rural locations, it can be difficult to find a stable,
dedicated phone line for uploading the data. ``No matter how high
tech we get,'' Davidson said, ``something like that is hard to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Though NASCAR drivers do not use auto simulators, the
association has designed a fleet of the machines for the general
public to use at arcades in shopping malls. Using the interactive
NASCAR Silicon Motor Speedway, fans can get behind the wheel in
scaled-down replicas of actual racing cars in five cities: Chicago;
Minneapolis; Dallas; Irvine, Calif., and West Nyack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Up to eight players compete head-to-head inside the vehicles,
which rumble and sway on a moving platform. Plans are under way to
network the five centers together so racers can compete across the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
