<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOCOLATE-GUIDE11-COX     02-10 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-GUIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A little chocolate goes a long way for Valentines day
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He says, ``I love you'' with dozens of chocolates in a
big, red, heart-shaped box the size of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She says, with that hurt look guys never see coming, ``You must
think I'm fat.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how innocent his intentions, he's what plenty of men
end up being on Valentine's Day _ a big loser.
</P>
<P>
   It's a double-edged sword. If your sweetheart is like many
women, she's passionate about chocolate. Liz Cipro, manager of
Atlanta's Paris Market, Georgia's only outlet for Belgium's
Leonidas praline chocolate, knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a woman who called a couple of months ago from
Tallahassee, Fla.,'' Cipro begins. ``She was afraid to have her
Leonidas shipped to her.'' After all, the delicate chocolate candy
is flown in from Europe and has a shelf life of about a week. ``So
she was going to drive up here _ five hours _ to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean she wants to eat a truckload of the stuff.
For many women, chocolate is an indulgence. Just a single serving
of Guylian's delicate, delectable Belgian chocolate seashells, for
instance, contains more than twice the calories and as much
saturated fat as 1 tablespoon of butter.
</P>
<P>
   Liza O'Hare, 37, of Roswell (Ga.), says her husband, Ed, once
gave her a giant heart-shaped box of chocolates for Valentine's.
``This is before I trained him properly,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men equate a giant box of chocolates with their giant love for
you,'' O'Hare says. ``I'd say, `Whooo, that's a lot of chocolate.
You think I'm a pig, and obviously you don't know the rule.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And what is this super-secret maxim?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little chocolate goes a long way,'' O'Hare says.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Retail Federation, Americans spent
$725 million on candy in 1998, with at least a third of that being
boxed chocolate. And the American Boxed Chocolate Manufacturers
expects more than 35 million heart-shaped boxes of chocolate will
be sold for this Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   This year, opt for expensive, high-quality, Lamborghini-style
chocolate that says, ``I love you,'' and still leaves you with a
fat wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Use one or two pieces to finish off a Valentine's dinner and
movie date or pair a small quantity of high-grade chocolate with an
affordable bouquet of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   We've gathered a few samples of great chocolate, each renowned
for its enticing flavor. Just a bit of any of them _ even spending
as little as $5 or less _ will say a lot to your sweetie.
</P>
<P>
   THE SWEET HEREAFTER
</P>
<P>
   We hardly have to tell you of Godiva. With three confectionery
boutiques in metro Atlanta malls, Godiva Chocolatier sells
exquisitely packaged truffles, creams and more than 150 different
chocolate pieces for as much as $125 a box.
</P>
<P>
   But Godiva can be had a lot cheaper. For $5, you can get a
cleverly packaged, red-and-white ruffle-heart box with eight
assorted cordials and bonbons. A four-piece gold ballotin
accompanied by a solid chocolate heart wrapped in red foil and tied
up with a red ribbon sells for $6.50. In fact, the red foil heart
(sold individually for $1.75) might be perfect to place on a loved
one's pillow.
</P>
<P>
   A more adventuresome valentine might like Godiva's solid
chocolate cigars ($2.50 each or $12.50 for a black-and-gold box of
four).
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Godiva Chocolatier boutiques are at Lenox Square
(404-262-2108), North Point Mall (770-442-8670) and Perimeter Mall
(770-671-9650). Limited selections are at major department stores,
including Neiman Marcus, Macy's and Rich's. Godiva Direct
(1-800-946-3482 or http://www.godiva.com) guarantees delivery by
Friday.ALL THE WAY FROM BELGIUM
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's world-class Leonidas come in a variety of shapes and
flavors, including the best-selling Manon Cafe (white chocolate
with a light coffee-flavored fresh cream filling topped with a
roasted hazelnut) and Cerise (a whole cherry in kirsch sealed in
dark chocolate). The chocolates sell for $22.95 a pound ($1.43 an
ounce). About four choice pieces cost a little over $3, or you can
get a small wrapped box of these chocolate jewels for $11.99.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Paris Market, 1833 Peachtree Road N.E.,
Atlanta(404-351-4212). Store hours: 10:30 a.m.-9:30 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays; closed Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ELEGANT EYE CANDY
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years, San Francisco's Joseph Schmidt Confections has
been making chocolate not only to tantalize the tongue, but to
dazzle the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Each piece is sculpted, molded and hand-colored into dainty,
pleasing shapes, including the company's signature egg truffles. We
found a cute Panda with a delicate red heart for $5 and a trio of
eye-popping heart truffles (one amaretto, one cherry and one Grand
Marnier) for $7.50.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Neiman Marcus at Lenox Square (404-266-8200).
</P>
<P>
   SHE SMELLS SEASHELLS
</P>
<P>
   The aroma of Guylian's Belgian chocolate wonders can be
intoxicating. Shaped into delicate, swirling white- and
dark-chocolate-covered shells and sea horses, their smooth praline
centers can be as comforting as a warm bath.
</P>
<P>
   A 4.41-ounce box of 11 pieces sells for about $12. We also found
a mini-box of three chocolates for a mere $1.79.
</P>
<P>
   Source: At many gourmet stores, including Atlanta's the Paris
Market, eatZi's Market &AMP; Bakery (3221 Peachtree Road N.E.,
404-237-2266) and Le Gourmet Chef (North Georgia Premium Outlets,
706-216-3993).
</P>
<P>
   A NEW DISCOVERY
</P>
<P>
   Chances are she's never seen this chocolate before. A small
wooden box, sealed with French ribbon, holds the tasty chocolate
morsels from L.A. Burdick Chocolate of Walpole, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Saveur magazine recently extolled the virtues of Burdick's
delectables, which include truffles, tortes and dainty chocolate
mice that arrive with colorful silk tails.
</P>
<P>
   For Valentine's, Burdick's signature wood box with about 16
assorted heart-shaped candies, truffles and mice sells for $22 plus
shipping. You can even order the mice individually for $1.75 a
squeak.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the catch: Burdick, with two stores in Walpole and
Cambridge, Mass., ships only on Mondays, Tuesdays and Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two ways you can use these chocolates for
Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who totally forgets to get a gift can call up and ship
these unique beauties as a special way to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   The smarter fella can extend Valentine's. On Sunday, he rewards
his sweetie with dinner or a few flowers. Then, a couple of days
later, a box of chocolate wonders arrives. You can even have
Burdick tuck in a special message with a few tasty chocolate mice.
Perhaps it could read, ``Me and the meeces still love you to
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Source: L.A. Burdick Chocolate (1-800-229-2419; fax:
603-756-4326). Shipping is $9 for two-day delivery or $18
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
