<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DISCRIMINATION-EXHIBIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas' Science Place is taking on issues of prejudice
and discrimination with its most controversial exhibit to date,
``Face to Face.'' Is engineering social justice within the mission
of a math and science children's museum? Despite some community
resistance to the idea, museum officials say yes, it is. By GRACIE
BONDS STAPLES. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRAZZLED-PARENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Settling back into the brown, faux-Naugahyde seats on the big
yellow bus, those of us who had volunteered to chaperone the
elementary-school field trip were startled to discover a large
silver box secured to the bus's interior, just above the
windshield, and to the left of the first-aid kit. ``For Clean Up of
Bodily Fluids'' the label read. ``Eeeeuuuwwhh,'' we squealed
collectively. ``What do you think that means?'' By CATHERINE
NEWTON. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F O O D A N D D I N I N G &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MENUS-VALENTINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Love American style is fast, fast, fast. Who has time
to canoodle between work, soccer practice, the school play, the
extra-credit science project, the hairdresser appointment, the
teeth cleaning, getting the oil changed, waiting for the cable guy,
buying groceries? Forget the time _ who has the energy? But this
year, Valentine's Day is Sunday, giving you all day to prepare,
with love, a feast for two. Here, we offer three menus from which
to choose, each paired with a side dish and matched divinely with a
bottle of wine. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move in ``d'' food and
dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ One of the most popular spots for insiders
at the Fort Worth Stock Show is in the horse barn, near the entry
to Will Rogers Coliseum, back where the photographer is set up to
take pictures of all the horse show winners. There is a small table
placed in a corner near the main aisle. There's a coffee pot, a
couple of grocery sacks with snacks and usually a Tupperware-like
cake or pie holder that contains a Birdie Auerbach dessert. There
is always a certain curiosity about Auerbach's desserts. Kind of a
``what in the world did she make this time?'' question about the
contents of the creation. By ART CHAPMAN. Story will move in ``d''
food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
