<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE ARRIVES FOR THE `X-FILES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Subs 6th graf, ``The future,'' to correct EDT to EST; pickup:
You will)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ At the very end of watching the upcoming ``The
X-Files'' episode in my office, I took off my headphones and began
to yell, ``Holy ...''
</P>
<P>
   An immediate cry went up from a co-worker: ``DON'T TELL US!''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about it, I won't.
</P>
<P>
   But for fans who have followed this Byzantine show for almost
six seasons, this is the moment you've been waiting for: answers,
and Mulder's vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``The X-Files'' movie, integral to understanding the
show this season, was subtitled: ``Fight the Future.'' Well, the
wait is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is here,'' Mulder says Sunday, ``and all bets are
off.'' The ``perfect conspiracy with an alien race'' is out in the
open. The door was kicked in this past Sunday with the first of a
two-part episode. This Sunday (9 p.m. EST on Fox, check local
listings), Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian Anderson)
will come storming through.
</P>
<P>
   You will find the answers, too. To what happened to Mulder's
sister. To the background of the Cigarette Smoking Man (``Smokey's
got a name,'' Mulder says). To the agonizing decision made by
members of the Syndicate. To whether Agent Fowley is working for or
against Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   The last episode was titled ``Two Fathers.'' This coming episode
is called ``One Son.'' On Sunday, Mulder will get what he wants.
But he and the viewers are left with the same question: Now what?
</P>
<P>
   There is a built-in caveat for fans of the show: call it the
Christmas Eve factor. While these conspiracy episodes are
well-executed, expect a letdown. The anticipation is always better.
</P>
<P>
   And here is fodder for debate: Will ``The X-Files'' still be
able to do those offbeat, light episodes it has artfully mixed in,
especially as worldwide cataclysm looms? The show that has built a
lasting legacy by piling on more questions than answers, ``The
X-Files'' is an intriguing position.
</P>
<P>
   The show probably has one more season left after this _
creator/executive producer Chris Carter has said repeatedly seven
years was the goal. And even as more within the FBI believe Mulder
_ at one point he turns skeptic and Scully becomes the conspiracist
_ the agent still has the toughest task left: The future. It's
here. And, yes, all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
