<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Senators hold their second day of
closed-door deliberations Wednesday as supporters of censuring the
president concede that they are unlikely to prevail. Senate
Republican leader Trent Lott said he hopes to have the final vote
at 5 p.m. Thursday. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ Several prominent former and current
GOP lawmakers _ including Gerald B.H. Solomon of New York, Pete
Sessions of Texas, David Dreier of California and Porter Goss of
Florida _ urge Texas Gov. George W. Bush to run for the presidency
in 2000, saying he is the most likely Republican to defeat Vice
President Al Gore. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOOMSDAY-CULT (Houston) _ Two 14-year-old Texas girls vanished
earlier this week and their parents fear they may have joined a
millennium doomsday cult in Mexico. One left a note asking that the
police not be contacted and claiming she was ``safe in the arms of
God.'' Agents along the Texas-Mexico border on are the lookout for
the girls. By STEVE OLAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A Senate committee is expected
to approve a bill that would crack down on the practice of
advancing failing students in Texas schools, a top priority of Gov.
George W. Bush. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ A jury of seven men and five
women has been seated in Jasper, where the trial will begin next
week in the racially-tinged murder of James Byrd Jr. Officials
won't reveal the racial makeup of the jury except to say it's not
all white. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   FRATERNITY-DEATH (San Marcos, Texas) _ The investigation
continues into the killing of Nicholas Armstrong, the Southwest
Texas State University sophomore who was found beaten to death in a
fraternity house. The suspect, a former Southwest Texas student who
was working for a plumbing company, killed himself Tuesday. By
THADDEUS HERRICK and CINDY HORSWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRASH-FEUD (Charles City, Va.) _ Houston-based Waste Management
Inc. will begin unloading up to 3,900 tons of garbage a week at a
landfill here. Much of it will be barged in from New York, which
has lawmakers in Richmond hustling to restrict the transport and
disposal of solid waste in the state. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DAYTONA (Daytona Beach, Fla.) _ When Dale Earnhardt ended
his two-decade quest to win the Daytona 500 last year, Texan Terry
Labonte became the ``best driver never to win at Daytona.'' Labonte
hopes it's his turn in the Daytona winner's circle this week. By
TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ With three players sidelined and a
fourth limping with a sore knee less than a week into the season,
the Houston Rockets play host to the Sacramento Kings on Wednesday
night. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Conventional wisdom says that in
the aftermath of the impeachment trial, the Republicans will suffer
and Democrats will prosper at the hands of the voters. But anyone
who watched the proceedings with an open mind had to be impressed
by the demeanor, dedication and potential of four young House
Republicans _ James Rogan of California, Asa Hutchinson of
Arkansas, Edward Bryant of Tennessee and Lindsey Graham of South
Carolina. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
