BISCUITS WITH YEAST, REUBEN `SANDWICHES' WITHOUT BREAD (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A number of years ago there was a recipe for angel biscuits
printed in the Star-Telegram, which I cut out and used for many
years, but have since lost it,'' Pat Boyd writes. ``It's a great
recipe (the recipe has yeast in it) and makes delicious biscuits.
Do you or your readers have this recipe?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a version of the biscuits from ``Country Living Country
Mornings Cookbook'' (Hearst, $23.95), which we ran in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ANGEL BISCUITS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup warm water (105 to 115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, sprinkle the yeast over the water. Stir in sugar
and set aside until mixture is foamy, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In medium-size bowl, combine flour, baking powder and salt. With
pastry blender or 2 knives, cut in butter until mixture resembles
coarse crumbs. Add yeast mixture and milk; mix lightly with fork
until well-combined.
</P>
<P>
   Cover dough with clean cloth and let rise in warm place, away
from drafts, until it doubles in size, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grease large baking sheet. On lightly floured surface, with
floured rolling pin, roll dough to 1/2-inch thickness. With floured
3-inch cutter, cut dough into rounds. Place biscuits, 1 inch apart,
on baking sheet. Prick tops with fork. Pat scraps together, reroll,
and cut out more biscuits. Cover dough with clean cloth and let
rise again until double in size, about 45 minutes. Heat oven to 375
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Bake biscuits 15 to 18 minutes, or until golden and firm on top.
Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per biscuit: 193 calories, 8 grams fat, 4
grams protein, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 376 milligrams sodium, 39
percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Turn a sandwich into a casserole: Another reader would like us
to repeat a recipe for a Reuben casserole that we ran several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipe is from ``Better Homes and Gardens' America's
Best-Loved Community Recipes'' (Meredith, $29.95). The second is
from ``Country Inn Cooking With Gail Greco'' (Rutledge Hill Press,
$17.95).
</P>
<P>
   REUBEN CASSEROLE A LA ORCAS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces wide noodles, cooked and drained
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sauerkraut, drained
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped corned beef
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Thousand Island salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (8 ounces) shredded Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 crisp rye crackers, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon caraway seed
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease 2-quart baking dish. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add butter or margarine to hot noodles and stir to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Layer noodles, kraut, corned beef and tomatoes in prepared
baking dish. Dot with salad dressing and sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Top casserole with crushed crackers and caraway seed.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, covered, in 350-degree oven for 40 minutes. Uncover and
bake for 15 minutes more or until bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 417 calories, 22 grams fat, 20
grams protein, 30 grams carbohydrates, 65 milligrams cholesterol,
1,018 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   REUBEN STRUDEL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   Dough:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Thousand Island dressing
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sauerkraut, drained well
</P>
<P>
   4 cups coarsely ground corned beef
</P>
<P>
   Egg wash of 1 egg, whisked, or plain water
</P>
<P>
   Assembly:
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour and salt in large bowl and set aside. In another
bowl, mix butter, water and eggs. Add flour mixture to make a soft,
but not sticky, dough. Knead for about 150 strokes. Place in
greased and covered bowl in warm place for 1 hour. Roll out on a
floured cloth and stretch very thin, making an 18-by-24-inch
rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. To make strudel, layer the dressing
over the dough and add the remaining filling ingredients in the
order listed, making sure ingredients are evenly distributed.
Dampen the edge of the crust with egg wash or water. Roll strudel
up jellyroll-style, beginning at the shorter end. Place on greased
baking sheet, seam side down. Brush with egg wash. Bake 40 to 45
minutes or until golden brown. Serve mustard on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 692 calories, 40 grams fat, 33
grams protein, 43 grams carbohydrates, 202 milligrams cholesterol,
1,856 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
