<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
STOCK SHOW DESSERT LADY DOESN'T DISAPPOINT HER FANS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most popular spots for insiders at the Fort Worth
Stock Show is the horse barn, near the entry to Will Rogers
Coliseum, back where the photographer is set up to take pictures of
all the horse show winners.
</P>
<P>
   A small table is placed in a corner near the main aisle. There's
a coffee pot, a couple of grocery sacks with snacks and usually a
plastic cake or pie holder that contains a Birdie Auerbach dessert.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a certain mystery about Auerbach's desserts.
Kind of a ``What in the world did she make this time?'' question
about the contents of the containers.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach, Stock Show regulars have come to know, can whip up a
dessert from just about anything edible. The Springtown woman has
proved it time and again.
</P>
<P>
   She proved it last year at the Stock Show when she cooked her
pinto bean pie. There were lots of doubters when she announced that
she could make a delicious, sweet pie out of mashed pinto beans,
sugar and coconut, but those doubters evaporated when she handed
out slices.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just to prove it wasn't a fluke, she showed up with
nutcracker pie, a crustless pie that is made with a dozen or so
saltine crackers and a meringue mixture.
</P>
<P>
   It was great.
</P>
<P>
   But this year she one-upped herself. This year she made pinto
beans and saltines look like child's play. This year, while she and
her family worked as security guards at the Stock Show, she came up
with chocolate sauerkraut cake and _ this was the real coup _ a
fruitcake that was actually welcoming to the palate.
</P>
<P>
   It was good!
</P>
<P>
   ``My children wouldn't even lick the bowl,'' she said of her
first effort at the chocolate sauerkraut cake. ``Now, it's their
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Robert, said he turned his nose up at the mention
of the cake. He really didn't want to taste it. But knowing his
wife's knack for making the impossible possible, he did, and it is
now among his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jr. says it is his favorite as well, and when she brought
a sampling to the Stock Show this year, he was at the front of the
line protecting his piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with an old German couple a few years ago,'' Robert
Auerbach said, ``and they told me this recipe was the way German
chocolate cake was originally made _ with sauerkraut instead of
coconut.''
</P>
<P>
   Birdie Auerbach doesn't remember where she got the recipe, but
she said she has had it for years.
</P>
<P>
   The fruitcake recipe is hers. It was one of those improvisations
that occurred when she didn't have enough of this or that and just
used what she had on hand.
</P>
<P>
   She calls it her instant fruitcake because it is made with a
mix. It is not as dense as normal fruitcake, but it is far more
flavorful and edible.
</P>
<P>
   Here are her recipes from this year's Stock Show. Next year,
we're all hoping for her Jack Daniels Chocolate Mousse Pie.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE SAUERKRAUT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8-10
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped sauerkraut, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and sugar. Add eggs and vanilla. Sift in all dry
ingredients. Slowly add water to flour mixture. Add sauerkraut.
Bake in 2 greased and floured pans at 350 degrees for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Whipped Cream topping:
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce container of nondairy whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons instant coffee
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons instant chocolate drink mix (such as Nestle's Quik)
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and frost cake.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 493 calories, 25 grams fat, 64
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 93 milligrams cholesterol,
447 milligrams sodium, 46 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   INSTANT FRUITCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10-12
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce package mincemeat
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped or whole pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped or whole walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water, or combination of water and choice of rum,
brandy or bourbon
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce package mixed candied fruit
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce spice cake mix
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Soak mincemeat, pecans, walnuts, candied fruit and liquid for at
least 30 minutes. Add to that mixture, package of spice cake mix
and eggs. Blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into greased and floured tube pan. Bake at 350 degrees for
one hour or until toothpick comes out clean. Can be glazed and
decorated with nuts and candied fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 501 calories, 26 grams fat, 64
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 35 milligrams cholesterol,
262 milligrams sodium, 46 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes about food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
