A9469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-10 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO REALLY NEEDS TO HEAR MORE ABOUT THE SCANDAL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So the Senate is deliberating the president's fate in secret. So
what?
</P>
<P>
   There must be lots of folks who wish that the entire impeachment
debacle had been conducted in secret. At least that would have
reduced the public's daily intake of indigestible legal palaver and
mind-numbing political prattle.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I'd like to see and hear what's going on behind those
closed chamber doors as the collective judge/jury known as the
United States Senate argues the question of guilt or innocence in
President Clinton's trial on two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Are senators on either side of the Republican-Democratic divide
``deliberating'' _ the way that an actual jury in an actual trial
would do? Or, more likely, are they simply availing themselves of
the opportunity to dish up some self-serving rhetoric that they can
later repeat for the media and the voters back home?
</P>
<P>
   Interesting? Sort of. Meaningful? Not really.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that most Americans long ago tuned out just about
every aspect of the presidential sex-and-lies scandal _ including
the impeachment proceedings _ and have been waiting impatiently for
the politicians and media to catch up with public opinion on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   One of the opinions expressed most frequently by the public has
been a decided preference for knowing less, not more, about
Clinton's involvement with Monica Lewinksy and his failed attempt
to keep the relationship a secret. Having had it up to here with
the saga of Monica and Bill, plenty of Americans no doubt find
themselves less outraged by Clinton's alleged lawbreaking than by
his incompetence as a cover-up artist.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton had succeeded in his purported efforts to suborn
perjury and obstruct justice, maybe the scandal never would have
happened and the country would have been spared a year's worth of
Monica madness.
</P>
<P>
   It just doesn't seem fair. Here we have Clinton's enemies
claiming that he has covered up crimes from money laundering to
murder, but when his country desperately needs an effective
cover-up, he bungles the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should have impeached him for felonious failure to keep
a secret.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, with the populace already overdosed on public
discussion of the scandal/impeachment _ there are cable TV channels
that talk about it virtually around the clock _ it is highly
improbable that the American people will be upset with the Senate
for ducking behind closed doors to while away the final hours of
the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Any Americans who truly want to know what's being said in those
``secret'' deliberations need not fret. The media hordes will be
waiting right outside the doors to provide instantaneous secondhand
reports of what goes on inside.
</P>
<P>
   The only aspect of all this that might be more predictable than
the eventual acquittal of the president is the post-deliberation
parade of senators quoting themselves in the pursuit of historical
perspective and elevated approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing that is said during the deliberations, of course, is
expected to affect the verdict of the senatorial judge/jury _
although the anti-Clinton forces are obviously hoping that the
enforced freedom of a secret discussion will somehow instill in
Democrats a sense of outrage toward the president that can be
assuaged only by a vote of ``guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   This is more than an uphill battle: To convict the president and
remove him from office, pro-removal senators must drum up a
two-thirds majority _ 67 votes if all 100 members are accounted for
_ on at least one of the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Locking the doors and shooing away the TV cameras cannot make
such a vote achievable. Anyone who believes otherwise is hereby
awarded the Wishful Thinker of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen and heard the endless media overkill. We've seen and
heard the redundant pleading and cajoling by the president's
prosecutors and defenders. We will surely survive without seeing
and hearing the final huffs and puffs of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
