<HEADER>
A9473 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DISGRUNTLED-ART-N     02-10 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DISGRUNTLED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEB SITE FOR THE DISGRUNTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fed up with hearing about the glories of the Internet? Fed up
with watching your sister-in-law get rich investing in tiny
Internet companies you just (italics)know(end italics) will tank
any day? Fed up with Pollyannas singing the economy's praises even
as your boss kicks you in the shin?
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps, simply fed up?
</P>
<P>
   Well, never fear _ there are Web sites for you, too.
</P>
<P>
   What's your pleasure (or pain)? Are you disgusted, in despair or
merely disgruntled?
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled, you say? Then hie thee to Disgruntled and get it
out of your system (www.disgruntled.com). There you'll find ``an
online magazine that combines news, feature, satire and commentary
about the darker side of the world of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's creator, Daniel S. Levine, writes, ``I invite all
takers to use these pages to vent and tell their tales of horror,
disgust, frustration, liberation and revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   At last! Spill out, sweet rage! You start typing your particular
horror story _ you're really on a roll _ and sure enough, there
comes your boss, looking for a reason to kick your other shin.
Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   But never fear. Disgruntled has imagined this exact scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are reading Disgruntled at work and your boss is
heading your way, just hit the Boss button'' _ a green frowny face,
complete with cigar. Click on it, and up pops a screen headed:
``Our mission is to increase shareholder value,'' followed by a
list of revenue figures. (Hmmm. If you're a writer or artist on
deadline, that might not cut it.)
</P>
<P>
   Now click on Readers' Tales, where the categories include Around
the Water Cooler, Family Business, Fed Up, Getting Even, Getting
Gruntled, Inhuman Relations, Temporary Insanity and Work Is
Hazardous to Your Health.
</P>
<P>
   Getting even. That sounds juicy.
</P>
<P>
   Did some workplace nightmare drive Levine to create this site?
Not really. ``Listening to some of the horror stories,'' he said in
a telephone interview, ``I've come to realize I've been fairly
fortunate in my work experience.'' Then again, when asked about his
worst job, he said, ``I guess in some ways they all were.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine, 37, a freelance business writer based near Berkeley,
Calif., started the site three years ago, he said, because ``when I
pitched a story from the perspective of employees, editors weren't
interested.'' But in his reporting, he said, he found ``people on
all rungs of the ladder increasingly expressing frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, basically a one-person operation, carries some
advertising, from Amazon.com and others, but it is no moneymaker.
``The revenues,'' Levine said, ``have gone from negligible to
insignificant.'' So where can Levine _ whose book ``Disgruntled:
The Darker Side of the World of Work'' (Putnam) was published last
fall _ vent his own disgruntlement? ``At myself,'' he said with a
laugh, ``for not paying myself enough.''
</P>
<P>
   If you still don't feel better after exploring his site, click
on this link: Feeling De-Motivated? Click Here to Show It. And you
soon find yourself at Despair Inc., which says it employs or works
with ``a wide variety of writers, designers, programmers and
fulfillment personnel, all of whom remain hopelessly dissatisfied
with their jobs, their relationships and their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This chronic state of frustration guarantees that the fruits
of their labor won't be diluted with hope, sentiment or good
cheer,'' it adds.
</P>
<P>
   Here you can order Despair Wear _ T-shirts, say, with messages
like ``I found the cure for hope'' or ``Another dissatisfied
customer.'' And there's a Despair calendar, with Jan. 12 listed as
the Procrastinators' New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you want to up the ante, to progress from
disgruntled to despair and downright disgusted?
</P>
<P>
   Too late. These folks must have taken their name to heart and
packed it in. ``For Sale: www.disgusted.com,'' the screen says.
``This domain may be available for your project!''
</P>
</TEXT>
