<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDSOR-CHAIRS-ART-11     02-10 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDSOR-CHAIRS-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DO-IT-YOURSELF WINDSOR CHAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BILL WELLMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, N.H. _ ``Probably the greatest public relations coup in
the history of humanity was the Shakers convincing the rest of the
world that they made good chairs,'' Michael Dunbar is telling a
shopful of would-be Windsor chair makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaker chairs are terribly uncomfortable,'' he continues while
drawing a chair with a back at 90 degrees to the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave found a picture a while ago of a Shaker dining room,'' he
adds, referring to his assistant Dave Wachnicki, ``and they didn't
have Shaker chairs _ they had Windsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out selling these to the rest of us!''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Dunbar's shop, the country's only full-time school
for Windsor chair making. If you can't afford an icon of the
American antiques world, you can learn to build one. In five days,
Dunbar, 51, will teach 11 students to do just that, in a class that
is fun but intense. It gets rolling the first day with riving, or
splitting, wood from oak logs with an ax and an old tool called a
froe. Then the chair's arm and bow are shaped with drawknife, plane
and spokeshave before being steamed for 15 minutes and then bent
around a form and put aside to dry.
</P>
<P>
   The students come from across the country: engineers, doctors,
drywallers, teachers, carpenters and the occasional journalist.
(One missed a plane because security guards mistook his spoon bits
_ the chair maker's answer to drill bits _ for bullets.) Many will
complain of sore muscles and sleepless nights, waking up at 3 a.m.
wondering if the chair will really come together or if the mistakes
they have already made will prove fatal. There may be no dustbin of
history in the shop, but there is a wood-burning stove that is even
more unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar's infatuation with Windsors _ he calls it ``a hobby that
got out of hand'' _ began when he was studying French at Worchester
State College and fully intending to teach it eventually. He saw a
Windsor at a yard sale and has been in love ever since.
</P>
<P>
   He started making chairs full time in 1973. After almost a
decade, he began to offer classes occasionally. A self-taught
woodworker, he is the author of seven books and something of a guru
to many hand-tool enthusiasts _ a Norm Abram without power cords.
It was not until 1994 that he and his wife, Sue, began running the
classes by themselves here near the New Hampshire coast, working
their way up to the current 23 one-week classes a year, each
student paying $600. The class has evolved over the years, with
Dunbar offering mea culpas for past sins, like telling people to
dry tenons in hot sand, something he now feels the need to
constantly apologize for.
</P>
<P>
   During one class, the assistants included Wachnicki, a
dentist/woodworker (what George Washington wouldn't have given for
a guy like this!) and a 1995 inductee into Dunbar's own Chair
Making Hall of Fame. An intern helps out _ Dan Hein, a Wisconsin
computer teacher. After he was seen putting the end of a chair leg
into his mouth to wet it before a test fit, making the fit that
much tighter, he won his second Hall of Fame nomination. This
little gimmick Dunbar calls the ``Hein Lick Maneuver.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people have taken a Windsor chair class with
Dunbar, and he estimates that 10 percent of them are making chairs
commercially, at least part time.
</P>
<P>
   The first Windsor chairs were developed in England between 1710
and 1720, says Nancy Goyne Evans, the author of ``American Windsor
Chairs'' (Hudson Hills, 1996). The chairs are called Windsors, she
adds, because ``it was on the grounds of Windsor Castle where this
rustic furniture was first placed.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Heritage College Dictionary defines a Windsor as
``a wooden chair having a high spoked back, outward-slanting legs
connected by crossbars, and a saddle seat.'' But Ms. Evans says
``the critical element'' is the seat, which is made of a thick
piece of wood, allowing the upper and lower structures to work
independently of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The early Windsors were the period equivalent of Adirondack
chairs, she says, and probably had plank seats. They were the
replacements for cane-seated chairs, which were on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   By 1736, Windsors had arrived in Philadelphia, Ms. Evans says,
and the desire ``to keep up with the Joneses'' was enough to
support craftsmen capable of copying the chairs. In the mid-1700s a
high-back Windsor was still a chair for the well-to-do. But after
the Revolution, the Windsor became the most common seating form in
America. A visitor to Monticello in Jefferson's day would have
found Windsors.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the style was to paint most Windsors green. But
painting them was, and is, more than just a question of fashion _
for early makers of Windsors a key question was, If you are going
to paint a chair green anyway, why waste time and money on
expensive, hard-to-work woods that won't be seen?
</P>
<P>
   The Windsors made in a class last July used maple legs and some
maple parts for the back, a pine seat one-and-three-quarters inches
thick, red oak riven from logs for the spindles, one-piece arm and
bow and some small cherry parts for arm extensions _ a variety of
woods that cries out for camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   Where an early Windsor was built, Ms. Evans says, can sometimes
be determined by the types of wood used. Philadelphia makers, for
example, used yellow poplar for the seats, but pine was more common
from Rhode Island north. Hickory was a popular wood for spindles,
but oak and other woods were also used.
</P>
<P>
   Some contemporary makers have opted for all-hardwood
construction, which allows the texture and beauty of wood to be
accented, but, Dunbar contends, ``If somebody makes you a Windsor
chair with a hardwood seat, he's made you a bad chair.'' He thinks
the legs and spindles fit better in the softer pine, but that's up
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Rodriguez, who has made plenty of Windsors himself and
teaches woodworking at the Fashion Institute of Technology in
Manhattan, also prefers pine for the seat, but not because of any
inherent flaws in hardwood seats _ it simply takes, he says, four
or five times as long to carve a hardwood like curly maple or
burled walnut. Why? ``Because the grains are so convoluted,''
Dunbar says.
</P>
<P>
   Even pine can be hard to carve. The seat Dunbar is using as a
class model had such swirly, difficult-to-work grain that he
concludes it was from a ``miserable tree'' that ``deserved to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   A chair made with rectangular or square mortise-and-tenon joints
can loosen over time as torque is applied by twisting, turning and
leaning back _ all of the things your mother told you not to do.
Sitting in a Windsor made to Dunbar's specifications actually
tightens leg joints that may have come unglued. The legs use a
locking taper _ bigger at the bottom, smaller at the top _ to fit
into the seat, so it is solid and tight even before glue and wedges
are added. The joint is fitted under compression to keep it
together; if the glue fails, the joint still holds.
</P>
<P>
   The materials fail before the joinery. ``Hundreds of thousands
of 200-year-old Windsors are still as tight as the day they were
made,'' Dunbar says.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But if the beauty of natural wood is removed from the chair
maker's consideration, how does a craftsman make an appealing
chair? Windsor chair makers relied on line. The chair makers pull
the viewer's eye up quickly through the back spindles into the
heavy line that makes the bow of the back. The heavy line then
accelerates the eye and eventually pulls it down into the rest of
the chair. Rounding the edge makes the thick seat, needed for
strength, appear much thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar now buys the legs and some back parts preturned. But
instead of using relatively expensive dimensioned hardwood from a
lumberyard, he buys a much cheaper red oak log and rives the wood
for the spindles, arm and bow _ a log 18 inches in diameter will
supply wood for about 50 chairs and costs him less than $100. These
parts are all made using wet wood and traditional tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The making of a spindle,'' Dunbar says, ``is like what
Michelangelo said about a block of marble. You envision a sculpture
that's in there and then you take away everything that's not part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While students might take half an hour or more to make a
spindle, Dunbar can do one in about five minutes. An entire chair
takes him less than 10 hours and sells for $700 with a finish, $650
without.
</P>
<P>
   Carving the seat is where the strangest tools come into play _
strange for modern times, but once common. After cutting the basic
oval with a bow saw, Dunbar turns to the gutter adze, which looks
something like a pickax, with a sharp, curved edge designed to
remove large chunks of wood quickly. ``You don't swing the gutter
adze where your feet are,'' he advises. He appears to have all of
his toes, buried though they are in sweat socks on which he wipes
voluminous amounts of Elmer's white glue as it leaks out of joints.
</P>
<P>
   After the adze has done the rough removal, a scorp is used to
clean up the surface. Then a compass plane cleans up after the
scorp, and a travisher _ a curved spokeshave _ cleans up after the
compass plane. Then sanding. A drawknife and spokeshave shape and
smooth the outside of the seat, leaving a much sought-after
hand-crafted look.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to boring holes, many students have used angle
gauges and the assistance of another student in an attempt to get
the 45 holes in a sack back drilled at just the right angle, only
to miss by several degrees. Dunbar will walk up, eyeball the
correct angle, and when students check it, find that he has hit it
on the button. Students think of him as a human protractor.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings Dunbar back to those Shaker chairs he says are
so uncomfortable, and to his first official Windsor chair joke:
</P>
<P>
   ``A duck walks into a Windsor chair shop and says to the chair
maker, `Got any Shaker chairs?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The chair maker says, `This is a Windsor chair shop _ we don't
make Shaker chairs.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Next day, the duck comes in again and says, `Got any Shaker
chairs?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The chair maker, annoyed, says: `Look, this is a Windsor chair
shop. If you come in again, I'm going to nail your feet to the
floor.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Next day, the duck comes back and says, `Got any nails?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The chair maker says, `This is a Windsor chair shop _ we don't
use nails.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The duck says: `Oh, good! Got any Shaker chairs?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar's chairs are a lot better than his jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Information on Dunbar's classes: (603) 929-9801. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
