<SLUG> BC-MENUS-VALENTINE-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START A ROMANTIC EVENING WITH ONE OF THESE DELICIOUS DINNERS FOR
TWO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love American style is fast, fast, fast.
</P>
<P>
   Who has time to canoodle between work, soccer practice, the
school play, the extra-credit science project, the hairdresser
appointment, the teeth cleaning, getting the oil changed, waiting
for the cable guy, buying groceries? Forget the time _ who has the
energy?
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Valentine's Day is Sunday, giving you all day to
prepare, with love, a feast for two. Here, we offer three menus
from which to choose, each paired with a side dish and matched
divinely with a bottle of wine. Choose duck with rice and crisp
green beans, rack of lamb with a spice-and-pepper crust, or
sensuous mussels, cooked in a sauce of Calvados, apple cider and
cream.
</P>
<P>
   MENU NO. 1
</P>
<P>
   Duck is a grown-up treat. Because of the ratio of meat-to-bone,
one duck is not enough to feed a family, but for two diners, it's
perfect. Pair the rich meat with savory rice and simple green
beans.
</P>
<P>
   COLONIAL ROAST DUCK WITH WILD RICE STUFFING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   4- to 5-pound duck
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 breakfast sausage links
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced peeled apple
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon rubbed sage
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked wild rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Wash duck, remove and discard
giblets (or cook them for the cat). Pat dry. Cut any excess fat
around cavity. Combine salt, pepper, sugar, turmeric, orange peel
and coriander. Season the duck heavily inside and out with the
mixture. Place duck on rack in roasting pan; cook 15 minutes, while
making stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Fry sausage links over medium heat in small pan. When sausage is
crispy and brown, remove to paper towel. Drain off all but 1
teaspoon fat from pan, then add minced onion, apple, parsley, sage
and thyme to pan. Reduce heat to low and cook for 2 minutes,
stirring regularly. Mince sausage, place in large bowl with cooked
wild rice, fresh bread crumbs and apple/onion mixture. Break egg in
small bowl, mix briefly with milk, then add to stuffing mix along
with 1/4 teaspoon salt. Toss to coat.
</P>
<P>
   When duck has cooked for 15 minutes, remove from oven and lower
heat to 325 degrees. Spoon stuffing into duck cavity; tie legs shut
with a string, if desired. Roast for 2 hours at 325 degrees. Duck
bastes itself; just drain off fat that accumulates in bottom of pan
a few times during the cooking process. When the 2 hours is up,
remove duck from oven and let stand 10 minutes. Remove stuffing
from cavity to serving plates. Cut duck in half with a sharp, heavy
knife or cleaver. Cut carefully through breast along one side of
bones. Spread 2 halves out and cut along both sides of back bones,
discarding back bones.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 1,560 calories, 118 grams fat,
37 grams carbohydrates, 82 grams protein, 437 milligrams
cholesterol, 1,528 milligrams sodium, 68 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``Penzeys Spices'' catalog
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BEANS WITH HAZELNUT BUTTER
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound green beans, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup hazelnuts, skinned and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Cook beans in boiling water until just tender, about 3 minutes.
Drain and place in pot of cold water to stop the cooking process.
Melt butter in large skillet and add beans. Stir-fry for 2 minutes,
then add hazelnuts and stir to combine well. Remove from heat and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 193 calories, 17 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 21 milligrams cholesterol, 8
milligrams sodium, 78 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fast, Fresh &AMP; Spicy Vegetarian'' by John Ettinger (Prima,
$14)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   And from our wine list ...
</P>
<P>
   This wine bears a familiar name, Mouton Cadet, but it is
something quite new. This is 1994 Mouton Cadet Reserve, a $12 blend
of red grapes _ cabernet sauvignon, cabernet franc and merlot _
from the Medoc region of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   This wine stayed at the winery longer than the usual cadet, for
extra wood aging. The wine has a complex flavor with dried cherry
and red currant in the forefront. As will happen with Bordeaux
blends, it hides behind a light curtain of tannin. But that will
disappear in time, and even now it is neutralized when the wine is
drunk with food.
</P>
<P>
   Mouton Cadet Reserve is also good with roast beef and
soft-ripened cheeses such as brie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MENU NO. 2
</P>
<P>
   Rack of lamb offers up delicate bones with succulent moons of
fragrant meat. You may have to order the rack of lamb in advance.
</P>
<P>
   RACK OF LAMB WITH SPICE-AND-PEPPER CRUST
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4- to 1 1/2-pound rack of lamb, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon green peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Sprinkle lamb with salt and pepper.
Enclose cumin, coriander and peppercorns in small resealable
plastic bag. Using mallet, coarsely crush seeds and peppercorns.
Add garlic, orange peel and oil to bag and mash to coarse paste.
Smear paste over meat portion of lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Place lamb, paste side up, in small baking pan. Roast lamb 10
minutes. Reduce heat to 400 degrees. Continue to roast until
thermometer inserted in lamb registers 135 degrees for medium-rare,
about 15 minutes longer. Cut lamb between bones into chops and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 417 calories, 24 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 46 grams protein, 148 milligrams cholesterol,
115 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bon Appetit
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
