<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRASH-FEUD-HNS &LR;      02-10 1895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASH-FEUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK WASTE LEVEL TROUBLES VIRGINIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLES CITY, Va. _ English settlers first cleared the land at
Shirley Plantation in 1615, five years before the Pilgrims sailed
for the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson was married nearby, while Robert E. Lee spent
much of his youth at this stately manse on the banks of the James
River.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to this historic locale, Houston-based Waste
Management will begin offloading up to 3,900 tons of garbage a
week, much of it barged in from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter family, which has owned the plantation east of
Richmond for 11 generations, supports the project. But much of the
rest of the Old Dominion is up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the thought of their genteel Virginia becoming an
increasingly important dumping ground for Gotham's garbage,
lawmakers in Richmond are hustling through a series of new bills to
restrict the transport and disposal of solid waste in the
commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   But Waste Management may be able to dodge a more devastating
development, a reigniting of a national debate over interstate
movements of trash, no small issue for the nation's largest garbage
hauler.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Virginia, the District of Columbia and seven other
area states launched a major inspection of garbage trucks rolling
through the region. And now, pressure is growing on Capitol Hill to
grant states the right to control the amount of trash that crosses
their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, in part, has become a victim of regional
politics, as New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Virginia Gov. Jim
Gilmore engaged in the worst rancor between the North and the South
since the fall of Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to revive the Civil War,'' says Shirley
Plantation heir Charles Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But the company can credit its own missteps, from excessive
dumping to improper transport of medical waste, for many of its
problems here in the Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   The trash debate stems from New York's decision to close the
city's colorfully named Fresh Kills Landfill on Staten Island by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   The city has hired contractors such as Waste Management to
export the trash elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In stepped Waste Management, which, following Houston-based USA
Waste Services' purchase of Oakbrook, Ill.'s Waste Management,
boasted 304 landfill sites.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, which operates five of Virginia's seven
largest landfill sites, won a contract to handle 2,400 tons of
Brooklyn trash a day. That work was in addition to the numerous
commercial contracts the company already has with New York
apartment buildings, restaurants and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia was already the nation's second-largest trash importer,
taking in an estimated 2.8 million tons of trash _ mostly from New
York _ in 1997, according to a study last year by the Congressional
Research Service.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's importation of trash had grown by more than a million
tons in less than two years. And residents here feared the closing
of Fresh Kills would mean an even more dramatic influx of new trash
into the commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management transports New York trash by truck and rail to
three Virginia landfills, as well as to several other states from
Ohio to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had unloaded trash at a temporary port
adjacent to the Shirley Plantation for years, won approval to build
a new, $20 million facility at the site dubbed Port Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   When the port opens later this spring or early summer, the
trash, which will be transported in specialized containers mandated
by the commonwealth, will be loaded onto trucks for the road trip
to a county-owned landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management leases the property, which was once part of the
Shirley Plantation, from the Carter family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of the James River, for basically four centuries,
is one of commerce,'' Carter argues. ``It was the nation's first
highway. ... The notion we need to preserve everything and not do
anything new is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also has a financial incentive _ the need to pay the
inheritance taxes when his parents die to keep the estate in the
family. He already pays more than $40,000 a year for life insurance
for his parents, so he can collect a payment large enough when they
die to handle the death taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is simple: Preserve, protect and pass on the
plantation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen miles up the road, pearl-gray seagulls circle and dive
into the trash heap at the Charles City Landfill, while
steel-wheeled vehicles grind and crush the collected debris.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management dumps about 3,500 tons of garbage into the
landfill each day, about half the 6,900 tons allowed under the
county permit.
</P>
<P>
   For rural counties like Charles City, such large, regional
landfills are money-makers. Waste Management pays the county
government for every ton of trash dumped at the site, while also
providing garbage services for local residents.
</P>
<P>
   For companies like Waste Management, the issue of landfill
dumping is economics. The company makes a profit by winning
contracts in cities like New York to take trash and then disposing
of that waste in a company-run landfill. New York is providing a
new source of trash, while Charles City has the capacity to take
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economics of garbage and the politics of garbage are two
totally separate issues,'' said Marc Sulam, an analyst with
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say Virginia, by creating large regional
landfills, has been able to consolidate trash dumping into
substantially fewer, more environmentally controlled sites. And
they point out that if greater restrictions are imposed on dumping,
consumers will pay for those regulations through higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   Americans generated 210 million tons of solid waste in 1997,
with the typical person producing about 4 1/2 pounds a day,
according to the U.S. Industry &AMP; Trade Outlook '99.
</P>
<P>
   While the nation's consumers are often chastised for our
disposable society ``Americans produce little solid waste relative
to the country's total economic output,'' the study asserts.
</P>
<P>
   While Virginia's trash import volumes have been on the rise,
Pennsylvania ranks _ far and away _ as the nation's largest trash
importer.
</P>
<P>
   The furor in Virginia might well have died down, if not for the
comments of New York's less-than-tactful chief executive, Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the ``great benefits'' the nation enjoys from New
York as a cultural and business center, Giuliani suggested the rest
of country owed it to the Big Apple to take some of its trash.
``This is a reciprocal relationship,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's Gilmore shot back, saying he was ``offended'' by
Giuliani's comments.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorial page, referring to Virginia's
concerns about becoming ``Fresh Kills South,'' noted that
``Virginia's solemn insult has about as much sting as an air kiss
in New York's City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all enjoy the banter,'' the paper added, ``but if Mr.
Giuliani is going to offend every statehouse, we'll have to secede
from this country. Then where will we put the garbage?''
</P>
<P>
   Even Katie Couric, the ``Today'' show's co-host and a Virginia
native, got into the act, blasting _ and then later apologizing _
to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, for its own part, has contributed to the
public relations debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, the company was forced to halt barging operations
next to Shirley Plantation after Coast Guard officials noticed
``trash juice'' leaking from the garbage barges. Waste Management
was ordered to use new, more leak-proof containers to transport
barges up the river.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, a subcontractor-operated tractor trailer
hauling garbage from New York to a Waste Management-operated
landfill in Virginia crashed in the Chesapeake Bay Bridge Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The truck, the investigation revealed, was carrying not just
household trash but medical waste _ including syringes, catheters,
bloody sheets and other hospital debris _ as well, materials not
permitted in the company-operated landfill sites.
</P>
<P>
   Since Waste Management is responsible for screening waste dumped
at its landfill sites, the Virginia Department of Environmental
Quality ordered the Houston company to pay a $70,000 fine and spend
another $55,000 to produce two training videos.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management exceeded the daily dumping limit of 4,800 tons
at the King George County Landfill east of Fredericksburg, Va., 22
times last October and November.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contended this excess dumping came just as lawmakers
started talking about limiting dumping in the commonwealth's
landfills at 1998 levels.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Schotsch, Waste Management's district manager at the
site, said the excess dumping was caused by an unexpected surge in
volumes and difficulty in coordinating truck and rail deliveries.
The problem was corrected before King George County officials sent
the company a notice ordering them to stop the excessive dumping,
company officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In this political climate, Virginia Commonwealth Sen. Bill
Bolling _ with the support of the governor _ has proposed
legislation that would limit dumping in the state's landfills to
2,000 tons per day or at 1998 levels, whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   Bolling argues caps like those Charles City has placed on its
landfill are virtually meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might as well not have any cap at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill would ban the barging of trash on Virginia
waterways. The Virginia attorney general's office has issued an
opinion arguing that such a bill would pass Constitutional muster,
but it would likely face an immediate court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate, Waste Management's ``attitude on this
whole thing has been one of `Stick it in your eye,' '' Bolling
said, adding ``I think that's ruffled a few feathers.''
</P>
<P>
   While at least some kind of legislation is likely to be signed
into law, state efforts to control the importation of trash have
been thrown out repeatedly by the courts over the last two decades.
That's because the Interstate Commerce Clause of the U.S.
Constitution gives Congress, not the states, the authority to
regulate commerce across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, over the last decade, has considered numerous bills to
restrict waste shipments across state lines but has failed to enact
any legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Gillmor, R-Ohio _ no relation to Virginia's governor _
introduced legislation last month that would grant states the right
to limit the amount of trash that crosses their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Such a bill would be debated in the House Commerce Committee,
which is headed by Virginia Republican Tom Bliley of Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   But Bliley, the former mayor of Richmond, pushed a compromise
bill a few years ago that would have given states greater control
over trash movements, only to see the legislation die on the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bliley says the nation's governors will have to reach some
kind of consensus on the issue before he'll go to bat on another
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interstate wars over garbage have been going on for quite
some time,'' said Leone Young, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney
in New York. ``They flare up in different places. ... It's really
nothing new. It's just a different location.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
