r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCRIMINATION-EXHIBI     02-10 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCRIMINATION-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CONTROVERSIAL EXHIBIT, DALLAS' SCIENCE PLACE TAKES ON
DISCRIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A child is being heckled while looking for a seat on a
school bus. Six kids have room in their seats, but none of them
will let him sit down.
</P>
<P>
   This scene is out nearly daily across the country. Maybe the kid
is being excluded because he's fat or wears glasses; maybe it's
because she's African-American or doesn't speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, children can heap much pain on one another, pointing
out the differences that separate them.
</P>
<P>
   But is this scenario fodder for a crash course on prejudice and
discrimination? And should that course take place at, of all
things, a children's museum?
</P>
<P>
   Despite some community resistance, executives at The Science
Place think so.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the museum has been known as a venue for illustrating
principles in mathematics and science, not for engineering social
justice. But in perhaps their most controversial hands-on exhibit
to date, museum officials are planning on doing just that. By
giving patrons an up-close view of discrimination, they hope to
change the way people, children particularly, interact with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of designers at the Chicago Children's Museum,
``Face to Face: Dealing With Prejudice and Discrimination'' will
open Saturday and run through May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, aimed at children ages 7 to 12, explores
stereotyping, name-calling and exclusion through interactive videos
and role-playing exercises. It is designed to provide children and
their families with the tools needed to help them recognize and
respond to prejudice and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Kid's Bridge video, children hear other
children talk about how they have been discriminated against and
how they felt about the experience. In another activity, visitors
write hurtful names on a slip of paper and then feed it into a
paper shredder.
</P>
<P>
   Due primarily to the controversial nature of the exhibit, Mac
Sudduth, president and chief executive officer of The Science
Place, said raising advance money has been a challenge. To date,
the museum has brought in only half the funds its leaders had hoped
for. Although ticket sales will help to support the
$10,000-per-month price tag of the exhibit, Sudduth says tickets
can't be counted on to carry the full cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the museum is financed primarily through ticket
sales,'' he said. ``But it's hard to count on increased ticket
sales because of the controversial nature of the exhibit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudduth said he is not surprised by the community's comparative
lack of interest in this exhibit, because people often don't want
to admit that discrimination is still a major societal problem.
And, he said, ``even people of good faith can have differences of
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that one potential donor told him, ``She could not be
involved in something that even talked about name-calling because
it encourages people to call people names.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudduth also says some people have ``said in private that they
don't think this is the way to address the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Although discrimination may seem an unusual topic for The
Science Place, Sudduth said that it fits within the organization's
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our jobs is to better serve the community,'' Sudduth
said. ``That includes getting women and minorities to understand
that they too can do science and math.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, people who harbor prejudices or face
discrimination often suffer from health problems such as
hypertension. The museum's Hall of Health and Medicine focuses on
such issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sudduth, who has not seen the exhibit, said ``Face to Face'' was
brought to the museum's attention by Janice Westbrook, a volunteer
coordinator for the Family Friends Project in Dallas, who saw it
during a visit to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook said she thought the exhibit could help with ongoing
racial tensions and tensions related to gender and disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, in this city we have a lot of issues that need to
be dealt with,'' she said. ``If we were doing a good job (of
educating people) we wouldn't need this exhibit, but we're not
doing a good job.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is one of 10 cities that ``Face to Face'' will travel to
this year before becoming a permanent fixture at its birthplace in
Chicago, where it has also met with controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lach, public relations manager of the Chicago
Children's Museum, said reaction to the exhibit has been mixed.
Most of the criticism, she said, centered on the Prejudice Bus part
of the exhibit, in which unpleasant epithets are hurled at patrons
as they walk through. Once off the bus, visitors watch a video
showing how to handle such situations in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Although the actual bus will remain in Chicago, in Dallas kids
will have a similar experience by listening to a list of derogatory
names via a telephone and then learning some appropriate responses,
such as walking away.
</P>
<P>
   Lach says ``Face to Face'' can't provide all the answers for
kids, ``but we hope conversations are started and continued in the
classroom and at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sudduth said, he thinks the real opportunity for the
exhibit may be with parents, who will learn a range of options for
helping their kids deal with situations in which they feel
excluded.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he believes, is important for all families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face to Face'' may eat into the museum's resources, he says,
but ``we've said we're going to bring it here, and we're going to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Face to Face: Dealing with Prejudice and Discrimination'' will
be open Feb. 13 through May 30 at The Science Place in Fair Park;
9:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Sunday through Saturday. General admission
is $6 for adults, $3 for children, but group rates are available.
</P>
<P>
   To make a donation to the museum, call Mac Sudduth, president
and CEO, at (214) 428-5555, Ext. 311 or Starr Arnold, director of
individual, foundation and governmental funding, at (214) 428-5555,
Ext. 318.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
