<HEADLINE>
GOP HEAVY-HITTERS URGE BUSH TO RUN FOR PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of prominent Republicans Wednesday called
Texas Gov. George W. Bush the party's best shot to recapture the
White House and urged him run for the presidency next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty former and current Republican members of Congress signed a
``Draft Bush 2000 Committee'' letter encouraging the governor to
announce his candidacy quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is the best candidate,'' said former Rep.
Gerald B.H. Solomon of New York, chairman of the move to draft
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many candidates already in the race for president, the
depth of support displayed ... for Governor Bush is truly
remarkable,'' Solomon told a Capitol Hill news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is weighing a presidential bid and is expected to form an
exploratory committee in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is honored to have this support, but he has still
not decided whether or not he will run for president,'' said Mindy
Tucker, a Bush spokeswoman in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said Bush remained focused on his legislative agenda to
overhaul the state's education system and provide $2.7 billion in
property and sales tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he has a job to do,'' Tucker said. ``His focus is
the legislative session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, was elected to a second term in a landslide November
election victory. The son of former President George Bush touts
``compassionate conservatism'' and has made inroads among Hispanic
and black voters, key constituencies of the likely Democratic
nominee, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party's other potential nominees include former
Vice President Dan Quayle, magazine publisher Steve Forbes, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former American Red Cross
president Elizabeth Dole, the wife of former GOP presidential
nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Recent visits to New Hampshire, the state where the first
presidential primary is held, gave Dole a narrow lead over Bush in
popularity polls released earlier this week. Dole led with 25
percent compared to 21 percent for Bush in a poll of 454
Republicans. The poll by the American Research Group had a margin
of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates are building organizations and speaking to
potential voters in early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Guy Molinari of New York said the movement to draft
Bush had ``a tremendous amount of support in every region in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter Goss of Florida said support for Bush was especially
strong in California, Florida and Texas, vote-rich states needed to
win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush backers said the support comes from the governor's message
of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly conveys how our approach to government and belief
in American values can really make everyday life better for
Americans who are struggling and suffering,'' said Solomon, who was
co-chairman of Ronald Reagan's 1980 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's message appeals to conservatives, moderates,
minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support for Bush eclipses that for Reagan during the same
time in his career,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   The draft Bush letter was signed by 35 current House members,
and 15 former members.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Sessions of Texas said the Draft Bush 2000 Committee
was really an ``outreach program for people outside Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions said Bush would receive the support of Texas' entire
GOP delegation if he declares his candidacy, which many at the news
conference here predicted he would.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said the committee would ``ask the people of Texas ...
to share their governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kay Granger, also of Texas, signed the draft Bush letter.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier of California said Bush's ``message of
inclusion is one the Republican Party needs to put forward. It's a
positive message.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls showing voter anger with the Republican-led
Congress for pursuing the impeachment of President Clinton and the
loss of House seats in the 1998 election have Republicans divided
over how to win votes in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier said Bush ``has the opportunity to not only bring the
Republican Party together, but to bring the country together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
