A9542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-COMPETITION11-COX     02-10 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-COMPETITION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T'S FUTURE RIDING ON CABLE TV LINES, CHIEF SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AT&AMP;T is betting on cable television lines in its
quest to become a 21st century communications powerhouse, Chairman
C. Michael Armstrong said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious from our investments, we're putting our money
where our mouth is on this one,'' Armstrong said in a National
Press Club speech. ``We believe hybrid fiber coaxial has the
potential to carry the most capacity over the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, AT&AMP;T announced a deal to spend $48 billion to
buy the cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. and has reached a
multibillion-dollar agreement with cable conglomerate Time Warner
Inc. Together, these deals will give AT&AMP;T access to the cable lines
into 40 percent of American homes.
</P>
<P>
   And while Armstrong still sees a place for the twisted-copper
wire of the 20th century, he wants to boost the company's cable
coverage to between 60 percent and 70 percent of American homes.
</P>
<P>
   That means more cable deals may be in the works, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take investment,'' said Armstrong. ``We believe
we can get up to 70 percent of our local telephony strategy covered
by broad-band cable relationships. And 30 percent to 40 percent of
that strategy'' would be wireless or standard telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, consumer groups and some online service providers
have been pressing the Federal Communications Commission to require
an AT&AMP;T-TCI conglomerate to share its cable lines with competitors.
However, FCC Chairman William E. Kennard has indicated that he will
not require AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines as part of the agency's
approval of the merger, expected in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong said he doesn't expect AT&AMP;T or cable companies
to operate closed, proprietary cable systems. The companies will
want to partner with content companies such as America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you make money in the networking business is to have
the most traffic over your facilities,'' said Armstrong. ``And that
way you have the most traffic is to attract the most content, ...to
maintain some closed proprietary systems, like some content
providers do, is not in our best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong took several swipes at the regional Bell companies for
what he called ``excessive'' access charges for carrying calls on
their networks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Armstrong said regional Bells charge 4.6 cents per
minute to carry calls through local networks when the actual cost
to the companies is only six-tenths of a cent. ``How long do you
think you as a new competitor could last with that as your cost
base?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But in a news conference immediately following Armstrong's
appearance, Roy Neel, president of the U.S. Telephone Association,
took issue with Armstrong's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Neel estimated that regional Bell companies charge an average of
2.9 cents per minute to carry local traffic, and those prices are
set by state and federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling about access charges presages a large battle to
come later this year, when the FCC tries to design a new system to
subsidize rural phone service. That plan to revamp the nation's
``universal service'' program is expected to be completed by July.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
