<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUOMO-LOGO-NYT &LR;      02-10 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUOMO-LOGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LOGOS, BIG LOAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Md., Nev., N.M., N.Y.)  (js) 
 BY KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The logo is nothing spectacular. If it were for a private
business, an ethnic restaurant, say, I wouldn't give it a second
glance. It's just three lowercase letters topped by what looks like
a giant circumflex. But this understated, economical symbol
represents the U.S. government _ Housing and Urban Development
Department, to be precise. The big accent mark is actually a roof.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, branches of the government represent themselves with
something that looks official, which these days means a minimalist
rendition of an eagle. HUD is no exception. The logo that still
appears on its fax cover sheets is a big bird with its wings
abstracted and cropped to resemble a city skyline. But last year,
the department adopted a mark that is jeans-and-T-shirt casual.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa MacSpadden, the department's deputy assistant secretary for
public affairs, explained that the new symbol was a pet project of
Andrew M. Cuomo, the HUD secretary. She volunteered Cuomo, a
Cabinet member with a $25 billion bureaucracy to run, for an
interview about the logo.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the secretary didn't exactly want to discuss
the logo. He had a grander agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said first we'd change the reality of the department, then
the reality would change the perception,''he began. Once he had
begun, there was no stopping him. ``The reality is about a
downsizing, its new system design, its new management structure,
its new employees, its new training. Part of changing the reality
is changing the culture and the stance, the positioning of the
department. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, like his father, Mario M. Cuomo, does not believe in
brevity. But what he was saying, in short, is that HUD's image,
which never quite recuperated from the department's losses during
the real-estate collapse of the '80s, is being made anew.
</P>
<P>
   The logo, which was designed by the BBDO South advertising
agency in Atlanta and first appeared in television spots featuring
the consummate nice guys Bob Vila and Tim Allen, is only one facet
of the department's new anti-bureaucratic style.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture firm of Gensler was hired to invent ``HUD Next
Door,'' a program for transforming departmental offices into
wide-open storefronts where the public can drift in, lounge in
comfortable, brightly patterned chairs, fiddle with computers and
learn what HUD can do for them. All that's missing is a coffee bar.
</P>
<P>
   Gensler also designed a logo: a silhouette of a house with a
pitched roof next to a squarish apartment building, with ``HUD''
inset into the base of the buildings and the phrase ``next door''
extending into space. Gensler's icon appears on HUD's stores, its
new information kiosks and its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   A departmental booklet issued in December, ``100 Questions and
Answers About Buying a New Home,'' so cheerful-looking that it
could be a prospectus for Celebration, the Disney town, displays
the BBDO logo on the front cover and a version of the Gensler logo
on the back.
</P>
<P>
   John Bricker, a Gensler vice president, who helped conjure up
the ``next door'' concept, said he didn't understand why the
department would need or want an additional logo. ``I'm surprised
by the disconnect,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the dual logos, David Stanton, BBDO South's
group creative director, was tactful. ``We would like to have more
synergy,'' he said, and suggested that HUD could ``connect the dots
tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not surprised that this megalithic federal agency, so
chronically entangled in its own bureaucracy that in January it
made the General Accounting Office's list of ``high risk'' agencies
for the fifth year running, commissioned two different graphic
symbols of its new, approachable nature. Of course, it's not as if
either design were going to waste. HUD Next Door stores are opening
in city after city. Washington was the first, followed by
Albuquerque, N.M., and Buffalo, N.Y. Stores are due soon in Reno,
Nev., and Baltimore. And the little roof logo will soon appear in a
string of increasingly kooky television spots by BBDO.
</P>
<P>
   The point of all this creative ferment, Cuomo explained, is to
persuade the home-buying public that HUD is ``on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're battling is disenfranchisement from
government, negative feelings about government,'' he
said.``Especially the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that this is a monumental task for one
unpretentious little logo. I can see that HUD might need two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-COMPETITION11-COX     02-10 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-COMPETITION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T'S FUTURE RIDING ON CABLE TV LINES, CHIEF SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AT&AMP;T is betting on cable television lines in its
quest to become a 21st century communications powerhouse, Chairman
C. Michael Armstrong said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious from our investments, we're putting our money
where our mouth is on this one,'' Armstrong said in a National
Press Club speech. ``We believe hybrid fiber coaxial has the
potential to carry the most capacity over the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, AT&AMP;T announced a deal to spend $48 billion to
buy the cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. and has reached a
multibillion-dollar agreement with cable conglomerate Time Warner
Inc. Together, these deals will give AT&AMP;T access to the cable lines
into 40 percent of American homes.
</P>
<P>
   And while Armstrong still sees a place for the twisted-copper
wire of the 20th century, he wants to boost the company's cable
coverage to between 60 percent and 70 percent of American homes.
</P>
<P>
   That means more cable deals may be in the works, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take investment,'' said Armstrong. ``We believe
we can get up to 70 percent of our local telephony strategy covered
by broad-band cable relationships. And 30 percent to 40 percent of
that strategy'' would be wireless or standard telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, consumer groups and some online service providers
have been pressing the Federal Communications Commission to require
an AT&AMP;T-TCI conglomerate to share its cable lines with competitors.
However, FCC Chairman William E. Kennard has indicated that he will
not require AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines as part of the agency's
approval of the merger, expected in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong said he doesn't expect AT&AMP;T or cable companies
to operate closed, proprietary cable systems. The companies will
want to partner with content companies such as America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you make money in the networking business is to have
the most traffic over your facilities,'' said Armstrong. ``And that
way you have the most traffic is to attract the most content, ...to
maintain some closed proprietary systems, like some content
providers do, is not in our best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong took several swipes at the regional Bell companies for
what he called ``excessive'' access charges for carrying calls on
their networks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Armstrong said regional Bells charge 4.6 cents per
minute to carry calls through local networks when the actual cost
to the companies is only six-tenths of a cent. ``How long do you
think you as a new competitor could last with that as your cost
base?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But in a news conference immediately following Armstrong's
appearance, Roy Neel, president of the U.S. Telephone Association,
took issue with Armstrong's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Neel estimated that regional Bell companies charge an average of
2.9 cents per minute to carry local traffic, and those prices are
set by state and federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling about access charges presages a large battle to
come later this year, when the FCC tries to design a new system to
subsidize rural phone service. That plan to revamp the nation's
``universal service'' program is expected to be completed by July.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
