<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLISON-NOVEL-NYT &LR;      02-10 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLISON-NOVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDOM HOUSE TO PUBLISH ELLISON'S UNFINISHED NOVEL, `JUNETEENTH' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okl. Texas, Ala., Ill., Ore., Mass. Italy   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly a half century after the publication of Ralph Ellison's
landmark novel, ``Invisible Man,'' Random House is preparing to
publish his second novel, a work he struggled with for more than 40
years and left unfinished when he died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison began writing the book in 1954, seemed on the verge of
completing it in 1967, then kept revising and rethinking it until
his death at the age of 80. The novel, ``Juneteenth,'' is set for
publication on June 19 or Juneteenth, the anniversary of the day in
1865 when Texas slaves finally learned of the Emancipation
Proclamation, which had taken effect two and a half years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited book figures to be one of the major publishing
events in years. Ellison's life largely was defined by his one
classic novel, but his words are now pouring out in a spate of
publishing productivity he never matched while he was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the New Republic is printing 16 pages of previously
unpublished letters from a collection of several thousand at the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The letters and certainly the novel are expected to provide new
insight into one of the most celebrated literary figures of the
century and one of the most distinctive and idiosyncratic voices on
race. Along with collections of essays and early short stories
already posthumously published, fragments of an early novel, a
novella and memoir have also been found, an enormous literary
output coming to light after Ellison's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really iceberg time,'' said John F. Callahan, Ellison's
literary executor and a professor of humanities at Lewis and Clark
College in Portland, Ore. ``He had all this stuff, and he might not
have polished it and done the final revisions to suit a
perfectionist like him, but there is a huge amount of work and much
of it is very worthwhile stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Of most interest, of course, will be ``Juneteenth,'' a 350-page
meditation on race and identity. The novel tells the story of a
black jazzman-turned-minister named Hickman, who raises a little
boy of ambiguous background, bringing him up as a black child
although he looks white. The boy eventually runs away and grows up
to be a race-baiting senator from a New England state. After being
shot on the Senate floor, the politician summons Hickman to his
side and their conversations spin out their shared past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who has been affected, moved and influenced by
`Invisible Man' is going to want to read this book,'' Callahan
said. ``It's a very important book. The title refers to the day of
liberation, and this book is very much about liberation and the
complexities of liberation. Given all the denials and attempts to
gloss over the meaning of race, it's an attempt to remind people of
some of the profundities of race and of being an American, which
was Ellison's great theme. What it means to be a true American was
almost a sacred thing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who was born in Oklahoma City in 1914, began playing
the trumpet at age 8 and gravitated toward both music and writing.
Visiting a friend in Vermont after World War II, he typed out, ``I
am an invisible man,'' and thus began his great novel, which was
written over seven years and published in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The book tells the story of an unnamed black man who grows up in
the segregated South and moves to New York and battles to create an
identity apart from the stereotypes of race. The book, with its
famous last line, ``Who knows but that, on the lower frequencies, I
speak for you?'' transcends the black experience as a meditation on
identity, alienation and self-definition influenced as much by
Dostoyevsky as by black authors such as Richard Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The insistence on an individual identity apart from a group
identity often made him a controversial figure and put him at odds
with the reigning black intellectuals of his time, particularly the
black militants _ he uses the words often in his letters _ of the
1960s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   He started thinking about his second novel (it is not a sequel
to ``Invisible Man'') even before his first one was published and
started working on it in 1954. He was supposed to be close to
finishing it in 1967, but a fire at his summer home in the
Berkshires destroyed a summer's worth of revisions and he spend the
rest of his life refashioning the work.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said the novel being published is the major part of
what will eventually be a larger scholarly edition with other
sections of the sprawling manuscript included.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't finish the novel because it became a saga, and
within the saga were a number of possible novels,'' he said. ``But
in the midst of it all was this novel that had come to fruition.
It's entirely his. Every word. What was needed was extracting it
and to some extent getting guidance from his notes about things
like sequencing.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``What he left was like an unfinished house of
fiction, and to keep the metaphor, this is like the essence of the
house, something he had all but completed. There are other wings of
the house that are a good deal less finished and hang together less
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said the novel is about the evasion and discovery of
identity, a theme that, along with Ellison's efforts to avoid the
oversimplifications of race, echo through the letters being
published in The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest ones, from 1933 to 1936, were to his mother when
Ellison was at Tuskegee Institute, now Tuskegee University. Others
are exchanges with leading literary figures like Saul Bellow,
Robert Penn Warren, Albert Murray, Richard Wright and Alfred Kazin.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, who culled and annotated the letters for the magazine,
plans at some point to put together a collection of Ellison's
letters, which are mostly carbons of letters he sent to friends and
family members over six decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see very clearly in the letters is the way he saw
American culture and American identity as being of a whole,''
Callahan said. ``Over and over we see Ellison rejecting what people
call racial determinism. One of the things that really irked
Ellison was the idea that because of slavery and segregation, black
folks had become dehumanized. Instead, he saw black culture as
something that is beautiful and profound but with an influence on
the larger culture that is indisputable.''
</P>
<P>
   His views on culture and race were perhaps most succinctly
stated in a 1971 letter to a student at Southern Illinois
University who had asked him to contribute to a study entitled:
``Toward a Model With Rationale for Black Studies Curriculums.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe, however, that I can be of any assistance to
you, since I have never taught black studies as such. It is my
opinion that disciplines such as history and literature when taught
must include Negro American reality but that it cannot be taught
separately since it did not evolve separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said the letters both reinforce and expand the public
image of Ellison. The themes in the letters are entirely consistent
with the work, he said, but the letters also show a more playful,
humorous side than the more austere, intellectual image he had.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1978 letter he writes of walking down a street in
Northhampton, Mass., carrying a new rake and coming upon a black
student, his hair bushed out in an Afro, wearing new overalls and
doing ``a pimp limp or hustler's walk.'' Ellison stopped him and
said, ``Just look at us, brother. My father and your grandfather
probably worked like hell to get away from the farm so we could be
born to an easier life, but just look at how it all turned out.
You're going to a fancy college wearing overalls, and I'm walking
around this white man's city carrying a cast-iron rake.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1958 letter to Time, he seemed to enjoy taking issue with
the magazine's assertion that he was self-exiled in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I am too vindictively American, too full of hate
for the hateful aspects of this country, and too possessed by the
things I love here to be too long away,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And in another letter he throws off what Callahan said could be
an epigraph for his life and work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to integration,'' he wrote. ``The only integration that
counts: that of the personality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
