<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ASTEROID-GAME-NYT     02-10 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASTEROID-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID THE FRILLS OF ASTEROIDS, A CLASSIC TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing the new version of Asteroids, you realize that the
biggest difference between this game and the original arcade
classic isn't the 3-D graphics, the hopped-up special effects or
the orchestral score. It's the context.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years have passed since Asteroids was first released. In
1979, oil prices were shooting up, and the fallout from Three Mile
Island was floating down. Margaret Thatcher had just been elected.
Iranians were holding hostages in Tehran. Girls were wearing
designer jeans, and Blondie's ``Heart of Glass'' was on the radio.
``Saturday Night Live'' was still funny. The first NASA shuttle had
yet to be launched, space was still mysterious and inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   In that year of recession and turmoil and disco, a
refrigerator-size machine made its appearance: Asteroids. On
screen, pencil-thin white lines floated on a field of black. A
small wedge darted and fired at flying space boulders, smashing
them into smaller rocks, then into oblivion. Their outlines fell
apart with balletic precision as a vaguely hypnotic bass line
thumped in the background. A tiny glowing saucer flew by, shooting
deadly dots of light. Asteroids had the elegance of good modern
architecture. It was the video game the Bauhaus would have
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1999: Asteroids is a CD-ROM running on a
200-megahertz PC. The game still plays out in two dimensions, but
the targets have volume and texture. There are more enemies, more
weapons, explosive visual effects and high-resolution cinematic cut
scenes, all in color.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 space worlds, some with deadly black holes, some
with hostile suns that shoot flames as they go supernova. The
thumping bass line of the original game has been incorporated as a
leitmotif in the surging electronic soundtrack that swells as your
ship is sucked from wormhole to wormhole.
</P>
<P>
   In the final showdown, an ``Independence Day'' Meets ``Deep
Impact'' scenario, the extraterrestrials launch an asteroid attack
on Planet Earth. Bauhaus it's not. Compared with the stark
minimalist original, Asteroids 1999 is baroque.
</P>
<P>
   The new game makes you realize how the esthetics of technology
have changed in the last 20 years and how our visual sensibilities
have changed with them. In the 70s, technology was square and
vaguely forbidding. It had sharp edges. It had corners. Ten years
later, industrial design got curvy and ergonomic. On the outside,
everything was egg-shaped, but on screen, there weren't many
whistles and bells. We were working with word processors and
spreadsheets and Unix command lines. Form followed function.
</P>
<P>
   As the chips became faster and the operating systems grew
fatter, icons and windows and menu bars staked their claims on the
desktop. CD-ROMs and Web browsers splashed thousands of colors
across the screen; 3-D accelerators gave us dynamic lighting
effects and video game characters with realistic hair.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, we had Java and Shockwave. Web pages started to
blink. Things began to spin. Animated characters now dance little
jigs in their banner-ad playpens. The reigning design philosophy
is, in a word, (italics)more.(end italics) More images. More
gimmicks. Everything must be expanded, improved, revised!
</P>
<P>
   Technology has become baroque. Ornamental overkill is something
we have come to expect. Indeed, it's what the market demands. But
at some point, rococo technology, like rococo painting, becomes
overblown and ridiculous, to the point of self-parody.
</P>
<P>
   That becomes achingly apparent in Asteroids when you hit an
overrendered 3-D spinning boulder, and a number flashes, ``1979,''
pitching you into the original arcade game. All the flourishes and
gilding are stripped away, and what's left is the essence of this
game, white lines on black.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Proustian frisson, if you are old enough to remember
playing Asteroids the first time around. But mostly, it's just a
relief to have the overblown production wiped away so you can
concentrate on the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Because what's really fun about Asteroids, or any video game, is
the structure of the thing: the rhythms and the patterns and the
mechanics of interaction.
</P>
<P>
   And to the extent that the surface esthetics distract from that
core experience, the game is less absorbing. It does not immerse
the player because immersion is about forgetting. It's about losing
your self-awareness, blurring the distinction between what's
happening in front of you and what's happening in your head. The
more cluttered the screen becomes, the less likely we are to lose
ourselves in it.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 version of Asteroids is immersive because it is
transparent _ there is not a single pixel of descriptive
information on the screen. Everything you see is essential to the
mechanics of game play. That's why, with all the structural
elements held constant, the 1979 version is addictive and the 1999
version is not.
</P>
<P>
   All the video sequences and visual overproduction pull you out
of the experience. By calling attention to themselves, they turn
you into a viewer, rather than an integral part of this universe.
So it's easy to say, at the end of a game, ``I'm through watching
now.'' At the end of Asteroids '79, all you can say is, ``One more
game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, our media have become increasingly opaque,
promising richer content while inducing visual indigestion. With
500 channels and animated mascots turning somersaults on the World
Wide Web, it's no wonder we have become jaded and restless,
compulsively clicking in search of something that commands our
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, it's easy to see why people get nostalgic for
20-year-old technology. Its limits, born of necessity, look like
virtues in retrospect. If elegance is refusal, old media seem even
more elegant in hindsight because now there's more to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Classic arcade games had an incredible amount of ingenuity and
clarity per line of code. It will be a long time before the
creators of today's interactive media can say the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's Asteroids (polyester shirts optional).
</P>
<P>
   Published by Activision; for Playstation and Windows 95 and
later; $39.95; all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
