<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9582 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FAMILY-ORGANIZE-N     02-10 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FAMILY-ORGANIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL FRIDGE DOOR, MINUS MAGNETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Saturday, I forgot that my 7-year-old daughter was supposed
to go to a birthday party. I am at a loss to explain how I forgot
because the invitation was prominently displayed at eye level on
the refrigerator door. It was between my second-grader's most
recent spelling test (``100 plus plus _ excellent!'') and a photo
of the baby getting a kiss from a jelly-faced friend, and it was
barely covered by the corner of the school cafeteria's monthly
menu, on which someone had scrawled ``Bring lunch from home!'' next
to ``Feb. 22 _ Pork sausage parmesan.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning I phoned the parents of the birthday girl and
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it because I also had the time and date
written in my schedule book,'' I said. ``Of course, I'm not sure
where I left the book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand completely,'' the mother said. ``Last fall, I
totally forgot about a meeting at work. Missed it. For no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a good reason, at least in my case. With my family of
five, I would need the choreography skills of Balanchine to execute
gracefully all the steps needed to complete my competing
obligations: the after-school Web Page Club, the dentist, the
working lunches and the (increasingly frequent) pit stops at a
local Starbuck's.
</P>
<P>
   But after I found a coffee-stained scrap of paper covered with
the inscrutable message ``Friday, 11 a.m., IMPORTANT,'' I realized
that things were out of hand. It was time to clean up the whole
mess _ to solve the mystery of the missing schedule book, to
liberate the refrigerator and to enter all the flotsam of our lives
onto a master calendar that I could check daily. And never
misplace.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the best place for such a calendar would be the
Internet, a place I visit religiously after the rest of the
household disperses to various schools, offices and morning naps.
</P>
<P>
   Since I was already online to check e-mail and my favorite Web
sites, it would make sense to add the ritual of checking a daily
calendar based on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   To test my theory, I went to a site called
www.familyshoebox.com. This site, which is operated by Koz Inc.,
offers a number of free services designed to streamline family
life. Its easy-to-use templates let you do things like creating an
umbrella site, linking an extended family's various Web pages,
publishing an online newsletter and organizing threaded
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to start slowly, by registering for a free family
calendar. After choosing a member name and password, I was almost
instantly assigned a Web headquarters for my family.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I clicked on Calendar, and a divided page appeared. The
left side displayed a one-month calendar for February 1999. If I
clicked on any specific date, that day's schedule would appear on
the right side of the screen. When I clicked on Update, editing
tools appeared.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to enter ``Ella's piano lesson, 4:30,'' using a
pull-down menu to decide whether it would be a one-time event or
should be entered as a daily, weekly, monthly or even annual event
on my family calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Ella, I chose ``one-time only.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, the site prompted me, with easy-to-complete forms, to
enter a description of the event, the location and the time it was
to start and end. The site enabled me to enter far more details
about an event than would fit in my date book.
</P>
<P>
   After I clicked on Save, the site entered the information under
the correct date on my calendar.
</P>
<P>
   I was pleased _ until I realized that entering a single event
had used up roughly 30 seconds of my time. With 54 more events to
enter for the remainder of February, this project might consume
enough time to conflict with the day's scheduled 3:30 p.m. pickup
at school.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I flashed back, recovering an unpleasant memory from
the early 1990s of an attempt to enter my household financial
information into the Quicken software program. I aborted the effort
before I was even halfway through my checkbook register.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid admitting defeat again, I took a cleansing breath and
decided there must be some way to speed up the process.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Koz for advice. Instead of entering and saving events
one at a time, could I, for instance, click on a date and then type
in all the day's events in a single entry?
</P>
<P>
   ``That suggestion has been brought up before,'' said Doug
Patton, a Koz product manager. ``It's in the queue _ not a hard
thing to change. It's an enhancement that we're working on.''
</P>
<P>
   I returned to my calendar, entering such vital events as ``pick
up vacuum from repair shop'' and ``Hebrew school _ car pool,'' but
I found the process too tedious. I then went over to www.yahoo.com
to check out that site's free calendar service.
</P>
<P>
   While the design was remarkably similar and the event-entry
process only sligh &QC; ly faster, I preferred two other Yahoo features
greatly.
</P>
<P>
   One was the To Do list that appeared under the monthly calendar,
making it easy to lump mundane chores like the vacuum cleaner
expedition together in one place instead of entering each
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Yahoo calendar can communicate with a Palm Pilot or a
Microsoft Outlook 97 or 98 schedule, enabling you to trade
information back and forth. None of that would help me, however,
because I don't own a Palm Pilot (I would just lose it) and I don't
use Microsoft Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Will either calendar organize my life? Not totally. But there
was a nice side benefit to the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   When I was looking for the vacuum cleaner receipt, I found my
date book _ on top of the refrigerator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
