<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, February 11, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-SICKOUT _ AMR Corp.'s American Airlines, the world's
No. 2 carrier, asked a federal judge to end a five-day pilots
sickout and canceled 40 percent of its flights today, heading into
a busy holiday weekend. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/AMERICAN-HUB _ AUSTIN _ Austin became a temporary hub for
American Airlines today due to re-routing of traffic because of the
work action by the pilots. (Breyer, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-CHILE _ The world's biggest do-it-yourselfer is
looking for a helping hand in tackling its new Chilean market. On
Tuesday and Thursday, Home Depot sent top management to classes
conducted by the Southern Center for International Studies to learn
about Latin America culture. The Atlanta-based company seems to
know everything about American culture -- what will it learn about
Chile? (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-INDUSTRY _ Consumers are more athletic than ever, but
even the biggest jocks would get worn out at the choices of
sporting goods stores. Just For Feet is building up its arsenal by
50 stores this year, for example. Galyan's Trading Co. is forging
ahead with its giant retail-entertainment format. Manufacturers
like Nike and Reebok are opening up retail outlets at a fast clip.
And then there's the NBA and NASCAR testing their own retail
outlets. Oversaturation is the biggest problem in the industry.
(Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HARTSFIELD-BUSIEST _ Hartsfield Airport is officially over the
top. Hartsfield reports it handled 73.5 million passengers in 1998,
eclipsing Chicago O'Hare as world's busiest in passenger volume.
But O'Hare remained tops in takeoffs/landings. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MADISON _ A 10-day trading suspension on five stocks that used a
Madison phone number ends Thursday night. But more information
would have to be available to investors than there is currently
before trading can resume. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CABLE11 _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Four Austin investors have bought out
World Satellite Network Inc. and announced plans to move the cable
programming provider from Minneapolis to Austin starting March 1.
(Hight, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
