<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALT-COX     02-10 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC vows swift action in Salt Lake City probe
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The embattled International Olympic Committee on Wednesday said
it would act swiftly in response to the findings of a Salt Lake
City investigation into the campaign for the 2002 Winter Games that
implicated 10 additional members in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   With the new names surfacing in the report, the number of IOC
members linked to the ethical violations reached 24, one-fifth of
the committee's membership at the time of the 1993 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Pal Schmitt, an IOC vice president and member of the six-person
internal commission investigating the Salt Lake allegations,
refused to comment on the report. ``I'm sure we have a copy now and
can begin to examine it,'' Schmitt said from his office in Bern,
where he is Hungary's ambassador to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt said he expected the commission to meet soon to review
the report before the full IOC meets in a special session to
address the scandal in March.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC said in a statement it would act promptly after its
commission reviewed the report. The IOC remains fully committed to
investigating and taking action based on available evidence, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, led by Canadian IOC member Dick Pound, is
recommending the expulsions of five members because of their
actions during Salt Lake's bid. Investigators have said that IOC
members accepted more than $1 million in cash, gifts, first-class
travel and college scholarships from the Salt Lake bidding
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Four members have resigned, and one was issued a warning. One
member died before the scandal erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC commission will examine the 300-page report for any
fresh allegations against three members whose cases remain under
investigation. They are Kim Un-Young of South Korea, Louis
Guirandou-N'Diaye of the Ivory Coast and Vitaly Smirnov of Russia.
Each has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Two IOC members cited in the report denied on Wednesday that
they did anything wrong. An attorney for Australian IOC member Phil
Coles denied to reporters in Sydney that his client accepted four
expenses-paid trips to the United States during Salt Lake's bidding
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Coles intends to submit a report to the IOC to clear his name as
soon as possible, his lawyer said. The ethics report alleged that
Coles had taken his family on paid vacations to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, the highest-ranking member named in the scandal, has
demanded that the IOC inquiry commission clear him, and he is
expected to renew his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, Kim said he thinks that the Salt Lake report cleared
him of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake report indicated that neither Kim nor his son were
aware that the bidding committee was providing $45,000 to Keystone
Communications, a Utah company, to fund a job for Kim's son, Kim
Jung-hoon, also known as John Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Any secret deal between the bid committee and Keystone was a
contrivance solely between those two entities, and was unknown to
the elder Kim or his son, said Howard Graff, Kim's U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who makes no secret of his desire to succeed Juan Antonio
Samaranch as president of the IOC, said he will not resign and
intends to fight any attempt to expel him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such persistent attempts to smear both my reputation and the
leadership of president Samaranch are political and designed to
undermine the stability of his leadership as well as to affect the
succession of his presidency,'' Kim told the Associated Press.
``When the time comes, I will fight back. I have a lot of
ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
