<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FURNTITURE-AUCTION-3T     02-10 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNTITURE-AUCTION-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTIONING A RARE BOOKCASE: THE DAY HEARTS SANG AT SOTHEBY'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, R.I., Mass.)   Thatcher Freund, who lives in Chapel Hill, N.C., is the author of
``Objects of Desire'' (Pantheon, 1993).  
 (bl)  
 By THATCHER FREUND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One afternoon in January, Leslie Keno, the director
of the American furniture department at Sotheby's, waited in the
main auction room for the sale of lot 704, a rare and important
secretary bookcase that he hoped would highlight the bidding that
day.
</P>
<P>
   As an employee of Sotheby's for 18 years and as one of the
experts on the popular PBS program ``Antiques Roadshow,'' Keno, 41,
has examined as many as 100,000 objects in his life. But none had
ever affected him the way this one did. Its great rarity, its
superb craftsmanship and its strange beauty all seduced and
mesmerized him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to take my eyes off of it,'' Keno recalled. ``I
had never seen anything this magnificent in my career. I would come
into the room where we had it on display and find myself drawn to
the piece. It had that effect on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Keno's colleague William W. Stahl Jr. was conducting the sale
that day. Stahl had already hammered down a Queen Anne bonnet-top
chest of drawers that alone brought $266,500, together with
assorted tables, chairs and chests. Though Keno tried to
concentrate on them, he found it difficult to keep his mind off lot
704. He had estimated the secretary bookcase at between $500,000
and $800,000. He hoped it would bring much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, Jan. 17, at Sotheby's most important American
furniture sale of the year, the ``Appleton secretary bookcase,'' as
it was called, sold for $8,250,500, the second highest price ever
paid for a piece of American furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary had led an astonishing life, from its creation in
Newport, R.I., in the 1740s through a lengthy residence abroad.
Many experts believe that the discovery of so unique and fine an
object, from such an early period, will have lasting implications
for the study of American furniture.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Leslie Keno's twin brother, Leigh Keno, a New
York dealer and no less an authority, ``It shatters the notions of
what cabinetmakers did and didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Appleton secretary stood nearly 9 feet tall, with four
drawers leading from its feet to the slanting lid of its desk, or
secretary. Above the desk were two doors, each with a carved shell
at its top, that opened onto the bookcase. And the piece was
finished with a tall arched ``dome,'' complete with three finials.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Keno had first heard of the secretary some years earlier,
when a dealer of French antiques walked into Sotheby's in Paris to
say that he had seen such an object in a small apartment on the
Right Bank. Keno made a point to keep in touch with the French
dealer. Over the next few years, he learned a great deal more about
this extraordinary American creation.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary had been made for a distinguished New England
clergyman named Nathaniel Appleton and had descended in his family
ever since, through a U.S. diplomat who settled in France. From
photographs Keno had seen, he also concluded that it had been made
in Newport by the celebrated Goddard-Townsend family of
cabinetmakers, considered by some to be the best ever to work in
America. One of these craftsmen, a Quaker named John Townsend,
built the Nicholas Brown secretary, which sold in 1990 for $12.3
million, still a record for American furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Keno could tell from photographs of the Appleton secretary that
its doors, its desk lid and its drawer fronts had been constructed
of an extremely rare wood known as ``mottled'' or ``plum-pudding''
mahogany, for the dark spots that fill its surface and give it
depth and character. But he wondered about the chances of also
finding the mottling on those hidden surfaces usually given over to
less expensive ``secondary'' woods.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the promise of exotic wood, Keno had noted
another feature that would make the secretary not just a
masterpiece but an icon of American furniture. With most fine
American pieces, the drawer handles, locks and other hardware are
so commonly made of brass that people in the trade refer to them as
``brasses.''
</P>
<P>
   What struck Keno about the Appleton secretary was that all its
handles and knobs _ even the little parrots that were used, like
handles, to pull out the supports for the desk lid _ were made of
silver. What was more, these silver ``brasses'' were said to be
marked by a well-known Rhode Island silversmith named Samuel Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Keno could hardly credit this account, since no American
furniture with such silver mounts had ever been discovered. For
most of this century, in fact, dealers and collectors of American
antiques have talked of finding a piece with silver hardware as one
might speak of searching for the Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day last spring, following a death in the family that
owned the secretary, two elderly French gentlemen _ descendants of
Nathaniel Appleton _ invited Keno to view in person the object that
had so enthralled him. He flew to Paris at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I just stood there without even pulling the drawers
out,'' Keno said. ``I just looked at it for a long time. I had
never seen plum-pudding mahogany on the side panels of a piece like
this before. Over the next two hours, I pulled the drawers out,
opened the upper doors. Normally with Newport furniture you'll see
chestnut or some other local tree used in the secondary woods. When
I saw that the drawer  &UR; sides &LR;  were mahogany, too, I thought, `This
is incredible.' It was absolutely incredible. I just stood there in
awe.''
</P>
<P>
   As he studied the secretary _ still filled with all those books
and papers it was meant to hold _ Keno helped the two gentlemen see
the great unity of its design . He pointed out how the profiles of
the silver parrots' beaks were echoed in the curving outlines of
the bookcase shelves and how the silversmith _ Samuel Casey, it
turned out _ had stamped the handles. He showed them how the shape
of the dome was reflected in the shells on the front and in the
arched drawers of the writing desk. From the top of its dome
through the shells on its doors and the silver handles on its
drawers, it was, to him, a nearly perfect object.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One element alone had always given Keno concern, which seeing
the secretary in person did nothing to relieve. There could be no
doubt that however great the piece was, it lacked the proper height
for its otherwise magnificent proportions. Keno did not think this
awkwardness a fault of its design. He had long since recognized
that objects that begin their lives at 9 feet tall do not always
survive two centuries with every inch in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the gentlemen I thought the feet were a problem,'' he
remembered. ``I told them, `I think the feet have probably been cut
down 5 or 6 inches.'''
</P>
<P>
   Keno did not dwell on this unhappy news, of course. When two
handshakes sealed the deal for him to sell the secretary, he left
with a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   It is Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   As he stands on the floor of the auction room, waiting for Stahl
to say the words that will send his treasure on its way, Keno knows
that much has happened to Nathaniel Appleton's secretary that might
help its chances here.
</P>
<P>
   On the day it arrived at Sotheby's and he could finally view its
base, Keno discovered to his surprise that it had not been cut down
after all. In every corner he found a square hole that had once
held a foot beneath it. As Keno and his colleague John Nye tried to
imagine what could have been there, they thought of the bracket
bases on early Georgian dome-topped secretary bookcases, which
sometimes stood on four ball feet.
</P>
<P>
   That was it. Now that he could imagine how this piece, too, had
stood on four such balls, he could get Sotheby's restoration
department to replace the missing feet. And when, in time, the
secretary was heaved up once again, the effect was striking.
Suddenly it was clear that these ball feet were just what had been
missing all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put the piece in a totally different perspective,'' Keno
will recall. ``It gave it the right height. It made it rarer,
because we'd never seen such feet on Rhode Island furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who might desire a masterpiece of American
furniture, and have the wherewithal to buy it _ the people to whom
such differences might matter _ is usually about 10.
</P>
<P>
   They include Theodore Alfond, who once owned Dexter Shoe Co. and
who has come to Sotheby's today. Anthony Wang, whose father is
Charles Wang, a computer software magnate worth an estimated $975
million, has showed up, too. Others who might want such a piece
include Robert Bass, the Dallas billionaire who paid $12.3 million
for the Nicholas Brown secretary; Ned Johnson, the chairman of
Fidelity Investments, and Tim Robertson, a son of evangelist Pat
Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   As Keno looks out on the crowd, Stahl turns his attention to the
object whose sale everyone has waited for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lot 704,'' he calls out. ``The Appleton desk bookcase.''
</P>
<P>
   The lights dim. On a screen at the front of the room, Keno shows
a slide of a signature he found that week on the secretary's top
drawer. The signature is that of its maker, Christopher Townsend,
patriarch of the great Newport cabinetmaking family.
</P>
<P>
   The lights come back up. Stahl begins the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred and fifty thousand,'' he calls out. Keno will
remember that his heart was pounding.
</P>
<P>
   With Stahl on the podium, the bidding proceeds in an orderly
fashion, back and forth and up and up, in increments of $50,000. As
the bidding rises to $1 million and the increments to $100,000, the
number of players grows smaller and smaller.
</P>
<P>
   At $2.1 million, Stahl takes a bid from William Samaha, one of
the country's leading dealers, in Ohio, whom he has known for
nearly 25 years. Keno is glad to see that Samaha has come prepared
to bid and wonders what his limit is. ``In the past, he's gone very
strong on some major items,'' he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   From the photographs Sotheby's sent to him, Samaha thought the
secretary looked, in his words, ``awkward, in a way.'' But on
seeing it in person, he found to his surprise that he could not so
easily dismiss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those damned signed brasses that said, `S. Casey,' rang a
bell,'' Samaha will say. ``You have to look closely. You have to
think, `This could really be major.' When you see it's not just
mahogany, but fine mahogany in the secondary wood, that telegraphs
a message, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two million, one hundred thousand,'' Stahl says.
</P>
<P>
   He looks below the podium to the bank of white telephones, where
Roberta Loucks, a vice president of Sotheby's, has given him the
previous bid.
</P>
<P>
   Just in front of her, Leigh Keno is sitting next to Wang. It's
widely known that Keno has advised the collector on occasion. Some
people suspect _ wrongly, in fact _ that the person on the
telephone is bidding for them. Leigh Keno is certainly not bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two million, one hundred thousand,'' Stahl says. ``Do I
hear $2,200,000?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Loucks nods her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two million two on the telephone,'' Stahl says and looks back
to Samaha. ``Do I hear $2,300,000?''
</P>
<P>
   Samaha nods. Back and forth the bidding goes between the
telephone and Samaha, in increments of $100,000 _ $3 million, $4
million, $5 million. At this level, the Appleton secretary has
already become the second most expensive piece of American
furniture ever sold.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stahl believes he has enough confidence in these two buyers
to jump his bidding in increments of $250,000. ``I'll push it along
a little,'' he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five million, two hundred fifty thousand,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Though many people believe Samaha to be bidding for Johnson, he
has more than one client interested in this object. He is really
bidding for the secretary itself, which has worked the same spell
on him that it worked on Leslie Keno.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a couple of days before it all came together,''
Samaha will say. ``There are not many things that will move me at
this point like that one did. I just thought it was one of the
absolutely most important masterpieces of American furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   The bidding between Samaha and the telephone reaches $6 million
_ back and forth and up and up in quarter-million-dollar jumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven million, two hundred fifty thousand'' Stahl says to
Samaha.
</P>
<P>
   He nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven million, five hundred thousand,'' Stahl asks the
telephone. Few of the experts in the room know who that is on the
phone. Leslie Keno will not say.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   1740s: Nathaniel Appleton, pastor of the First Congregational
Church in Cambridge, Mass., with land holdings in Massachusetts and
what will be Maine and Vermont, who is said to be ``venerable for
his piety'' and to live ``quietly'' on his minister's salary
(though ``very merry at whist''), orders a secretary bookcase that
is perhaps the most lavish and expensive piece of furniture ever
commissioned in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Townsend, a Quaker joiner of Newport, R.I., and
patriarch of the distinguished Townsend family of cabinetmakers,
fashions a masterpiece entirely of rare ``plum pudding'' mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Casey, a young silversmith of Exeter, R.I., who later
escaped a sentence of hanging for counterfeiting coins, casts the
silver handles for Appleton's secretary bookcase, the only such
hardware ever discovered on a piece of American furniture.
</P>
<P>
   1784: Appleton dies in Cambridge at 91, leaving the secretary
bookcase to his eldest son, Nathaniel, and his son's wife, Rachel
Henderson Appleton. The younger Nathaniel, 53, a former Son of
Liberty who paid 50 pounds sterling to avoid service in the
revolutionary army, is now a wealthy Boston businessman with
interests in shipping and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   1804: Following the death of her husband in 1798, Rachel
Appleton dies in Boston, perhaps having sent the secretary bookcase
to her eldest surviving son, John, 46, who is the U.S. consul in
Calais, France. John has had two children out of wedlock _
including his eldest son, John James Appleton _ with Mary
Whitbread, an Englishwoman who subsequently will marry an English
officer named Major Petrie and is known to all the Appleton family
as Aunt Petrie. Three years later, John will marry Sarah
Fayerweather of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   1829: John Appleton, 71, dies in Rennes, France, leaving the
secretary bookcase as part of a rich estate to his son John James,
37, a Harvard graduate, diplomat and former secretary to the U.S.
legations at Portugal and Spain. He is now the U.S. charge
d'affaires to Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   1864: John James Appleton, 72, dies in Rennes, leaving the
secretary to his 18-year-old son, Charles-Louis.
</P>
<P>
   1935: Charles-Louis Appleton, a law professor in Lyon, France,
dies at 89, leaving the secretary to his son Henri.
</P>
<P>
   1999: Nathaniel Appleton's descendants sell the secretary
bookcase at Sotheby's for $8,250,500, the second-highest price ever
paid for a piece of American furniture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
