<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Feb. 11, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, residents of Salt Lake City awakened to a burst of
heavy snow as a potent jet stream disturbance crossed through the
central Rockies. Thursday, the disturbance will emerge onto the
Plains, setting the stage for a round of volatile weather.
</P>
<P>
   As a cold front associated with the disturbance encounters a
fast flow of humid air from the Gulf of Mexico, a line of very
strong thunderstorms will erupt from eastern Texas to eastern
Kansas. A few of the storms will spawn hail and destructive winds.
Isolated tornadoes are also possible. The storms will press east
during the day, reaching the southern and middle Mississippi Valley
toward evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sharply falling temperatures behind the front will combine with
residual moisture to produce a narrow swath of wet snow from
central Kansas to southern Minnesota. Accumulations will generally
range from 2 to 6 inches though gusty winds will cause considerable
drifting of the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening breezes from the south will direct unseasonably
warm air northward into the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes on
Thursday. Indeed, afternoon readings will reach the 60s as far
north as southern Michigan. Partial sunshine and very warm
conditions will also reign across the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly start, sunshine dimmed by cirrus clouds will
cover the Northeast and Middle Atlantic States where it will also
be mild.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a stream of Pacific moisture will bring heavy rain
to the Olympic peninsula while sunshine and dry weather covers
California and the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Avalanche
</P>
<P>
   A large avalanche careened down a mountain slope near Reno,
Nev., on Tuesday. The avalanche followed in the wake of a major
snowstorm that raged in the Sierra Nevada the past few days. At
least 90 percent of all avalanches occur during or just after a
snowstorm. These snowslides are triggered in response to heavy snow
accumulating on steep slopes. There are two kinds of avalanches. A
loose-snow avalanche begins at a point and then grows as it
cascades down the mountain, while a slab avalanche occurs when a
large rectangular slab of snow breaks free and slides down a slope.
</P>
</TEXT>
