<HEADLINE>
WHEN SPEAKERS MAKE WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I see wavy lines on my monitor. Could my computer's speakers
be the cause?
</P>
<P>
   A. Try moving the speakers farther from the monitor and see if
the distortion goes away. If you are using speakers designed for
audio components, not speakers marketed for use with a computer,
the problem may be magnetic interference.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer speakers are magnetically shielded so they do not
distort the picture on your monitor, while many types of speakers
used with traditional audio equipment are not. It is probably a
good idea to buy speakers that are designed for use with a computer
anyway because some stereo speakers cannot pick up the audio signal
very well from a computer's sound card.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a subwoofer hooked up for extra-nice audio, try
moving it farther away from the monitor as well. Subwoofers, a
favorite accessory of those who like an enhanced bass sound, are
usually not magnetically shielded either.
</P>
<P>
   Many other types of electrical devices positioned too close to
your computer can also cause distorted, wavy lines to appear on the
monitor. Small desk fans or other appliances can affect it, as can
another monitor that is too close to your own. Power supply boxes
from certain external devices, like Zip drives, can also affect the
picture on the computer's screen if they are plugged in too close
to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd
St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
