<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALI-HOUSE-950(2TAKES     02-10 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALI-HOUSE-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATURE COMFORTS AMONG THE KOI AND HIBISCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A list of U.S. stores carrying Balinese goods is at end of
article.) 
(js) 
 Clifford A. Pearson is a senior editor of Architectural Record and
the author of ``Indonesia: Design and Culture'' (Monacelli Press,
1998). 
By CLIFFORD A. PEARSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  ISEH, Indonesia _ Hugo Jereissati, a wealthy Brazilian, fell in
love with Bali on his first trip to Indonesia in 1976. But only in
the last two years has he been able to live in a house with perhaps
the best view on the island. The little stucco house, in eastern
Bali, packs a lot of history and serves up a classic Balinese
scene: terraced rice fields and Mount Agung, the volcano that is
the island's most important natural feature.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Indonesia is the world's largest Muslim nation, Bali is
predominantly Hindu. The Balinese worship Agung as the center of
their universe. When the long dormant volcano blew its top in 1963,
the lava flow destroyed much of the surrounding area but stopped
just short of Iseh, preserving this sleepy village.
</P>
<P>
   Jereissati's house was built in the 1930s as a studio and
mountain retreat for the German artist Walter Spies. Since then, it
has also been home to Theo Meier, a Swiss artist and playboy; a
wife of the local rajah, and the Italian writer Idanna Pucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house is pregnant with spirit and history,'' said Ms.
Pucci, who now divides her time between a new home nearby,
Florence, Italy and New York. Living in a historical house, though,
``can be a burden,'' she explained, especially one that until 1986
had a leaky roof, and until two years ago no electricity or running
water.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pucci first stayed at the compound in 1977 at the invitation
of its owner, a local prince. Though Ms. Pucci came to Bali to
write about Balinese painting, and had ``no mind to change
anything'' in the house, the roof and wood columns supporting it
were lazily rotting away in the humid air. By the time the prince
asked Ms. Pucci and Made Wijaya, a landscape architect born in
Australia as Michael White, to restore the house in 1986, it had to
be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   New wood columns with lotus-leaf capitals were carved, new roof
joists cut, new split-bamboo eaves woven, new ceramic floor tiles
installed _ all done with traditional materials and techniques. Ms.
Pucci and Wijaya also added a larger terrace for taking in the
spectacular view of Mount Agung and opened the original Spies
studio to the new terrace. ``The most essential thing about the
house has always been the view,'' Ms. Pucci said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years it has been Hugo Jereissati's turn to
enjoy the view and make a few improvements. (Foreigners are not
allowed to own property in Bali, though they are allowed to take
out long-term leases.) ``I've tried to keep the original character
of the house as much as possible,'' he said. ``To do otherwise
would have been a scandal. Mostly, I've made it more comfortable.''
That has meant wiring the house for electricity, installing modern
plumbing, building a white stucco water tower out back and trading
in the old Balinese charcoal-fired stove for Western kitchen
appliances. For the first time, guests can enjoy hot showers.
</P>
<P>
   From the road, there are no clues alerting visitors to the view
that lies beyond the small entry and car port typical of any
Balinese family compound. But once inside the gate, guests find
themselves in a tranquil Asian garden with koi pond, frangipani and
hibiscus. To one side is a guest cottage with a columned walkway.
On the other side is the master bedroom wing. Straight ahead is the
original Spies studio and the drop-dead view of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Jereissati, 44, works as a consultant for Amanresorts, which has
three luxury hotels on Bali as well as properties in Thailand, the
Philippines, Myanmar and Europe. (The company recently opened its
first resort in the United States, the Amangani, in Jackson Hole,
Wyo.) A large man with an easy manner, Jereissati showed visitors
around his house wearing a colorful Balinese sarong, plaid shirt
and plastic flip-flops. Thick-rimmed glasses give him the look of a
tropical Peter Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his love for the island, Jereissati left in the early
1980s and didn't return for five years. ``I thought Bali was
finished,'' he said. ``They had just built the first supermarket.
When I came back, I fell in love all over again.'' He laughed.
``Now, they have 50 supermarkets.''
</P>
<P>
   What keeps him enthralled are the Balinese people and their
culture. Spies, whose studio is Jereissati's dining pavilion, was
important in keeping that culture vibrant. Painter, choreographer,
musicologist, collector and bon vivant, Spies was a cofounder of
Bali's first artists' association and the curator of Bali's first
museum. After being rounded up during World War II because of his
German citizenship, he was killed in 1942 when Japanese planes sank
the boat on which he was being transported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spies was a Renaissance man beamed down into prewar Bali,''
said Rio Helmi, a Bali resident and photographer, who is
responsible for such books as ``Bali Style'' (Vendome Press, 1996).
Spies also marketed Bali as a tropical paradise to Europeans hungry
for the exotic.
</P>
<P>
   To get away from a busy social life at his primary home in the
arts-oriented town of Ubud, Spies would escape periodically for the
two-to-three-hour drive to Iseh. Here, he found some property with
a stone shrine on it and a view that would inspire several of his
paintings. What he built was just one small, hip-roofed stucco
cube. The expanded celadon-tiled viewing terrace now connects it to
a small kitchen building on one side and a bedroom cottage on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent residents have, like Spies, eschewed neo-Balinese
kitsch and kept the architecture clean and quiet. Decorative
elements like carved and painted wood doors and window trim provide
a few welcome flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Hugo has done is give it the sense of one house,'' Ms.
Pucci said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jereissati has imprinted the house with what Wijaya calls an
``estancia Brasilica'' style, which incorporates subtle and
original paint finishes to walls, doors and architraves, as is done
in country homes in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Helmi said that Jereissati's house ``has become kind of a
symbolic center of the genteel side of the interaction between the
West and Bali, with a touch of jet set and a pinch of glamour.'' As
beautiful as the setting is in Iseh, the weather this time of year
can be more like Seattle than St.-Tropez. ``Sometimes it's very
beautiful to be in Iseh during the rains,'' Jereissati said. ``But
other times it's just too wet.'' So, he makes the drive to south
Bali, where he has a ``funky bungalow'' on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the house in Iseh that exerts a pull. ``Hugo has
opened everything up and made comfortable the secret hideaway,''
Helmi said. But, he added, ``the house has always had something
special.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Rustika, 63 Crosby St., (212) 965-0004, and Boca
Grande, 66 Greene St., (212) 334-6120, sell Balinese items. Zen Zen
Garden and Home in Studio City, Calif., can provide sources
nationwide for Balinese bamboo and baskets, (888) 769-9705.
Balinese furniture is available at Batavia Interiors in San
Francisco, (888) 435-2254, www.balistyle.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
