<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR YOUNG LAWYERS WHO LEFT LASTING IMPRESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Release Sunday, Feb. 14)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As four American presidents gathered with other
world leaders to bid farewell to Jordan's King Hussein last week,
younger men who hope to be America's leaders of tomorrow made a
final, desperate bid to oust Bill Clinton from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The younger men, Republican House members, accepted defeat like
champions who exit the field of battle promising to be victorious
when they next enter the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom dictates that in the aftermath of the
aborted impeachment drive, the Republicans will suffer and
Democrats will prosper at the hands of the voters. But conventional
wisdom can be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched the impeachment proceedings with an open mind
had to be impressed by the demeanor, dedication and potential of
four young House managers under the tutelage of eloquent
74-year-old Henry Hyde. They led the charge against Clinton and, in
doing so, made clear to the nation that they possess the qualities
to become leaders of the future.
</P>
<P>
   They are James Rogan of California, Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas,
Edward Bryant of Tennessee and Lindsey Graham of South Carolina.
They are very different in personality and background but in their
respect for the rule of law, they stand as one.
</P>
<P>
   Watching them make their legal and moral case against the
president, my mind raced back across the decades to first steps
toward fame and glory taken by Republicans of the World War II
generation.
</P>
<P>
   In those impeachment prosecutors, I could see young Richard
Nixon, pressing his investigation of Alger Hiss, young Gerald Ford,
beginning his climb up the House leadership ladder, young Bob Dole,
overcoming severe war injuries to launch a successful political
career and young Howard Baker, who during the Watergate probe a
quarter century ago demanded repeatedly to learn what the president
knew and when he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   The argument of the four impeachment prosecutors was that the
current president is not above the law, that he lied and obstructed
justice to cover up his misdeeds and that he is a lousy role model
for American youth.
</P>
<P>
   We can argue endlessly as to whether Clinton committed the high
crimes and misdemeanors which the Constitution decrees should cost
him his presidency. But we cannot argue about the passion and
perception that the young prosecutors brought to the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   They, like Hyde and other members of the prosecution team,
contended that senators voting on the articles of impeachment
should not be swayed by public opinion polls showing that a vast
majority of Americans opposed ouster of the president. But that is
a difficult argument to uphold in a democracy where the will of the
people is supposedly the rule of the land.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the historic dispute, there were men and women
who acquitted themselves with honor and brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   No members of the Senate fought harder to find a fair and
honorable way out of the impeachment morass than California's
Dianne Feinstein, Texas' Kay Bailey Hutchison and Maine's Susan
Collins and Olympia Snow.
</P>
<P>
   No members worked harder at trying to steer clear of the narrow
partisanship that prevailed during the House debate on impeachment
than Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and Minority Leader
Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the final analysis, it was the young House lawyers who,
even in defeat, left the most lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of history's ironies that as they were making their
case against Clinton, he and three of his predecessors were on a
somber mission to Amman to pay their last respects to a fallen
comrade in the crusade for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The farewell to Hussein brought together leaders who have made
their mark on history but who in the passage of time will become
history themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, although only 52, has less than two years left in his
battered presidency. The former presidents who flew with him to
Jordan, Gerald Ford, 85, and Jimmy Carter and George Bush, both 74,
have seen power shift to younger hands.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin, the ailing chief of once-mighty Russia, was so
feeble he had to be led in and out of the palace where Hussein's
coffin stood. Yassir Arafat reportedly showed signs of failing
health. Hosni Mubarak was vigorous but 70 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the scene, either because of death, retirement or
defeat, were the men and women who but a few years ago were the
prime movers on the world scene: Britain's Margaret Thatcher,
Germany's Helmut Kohl, France's Francois Mitterrand and Israel's
Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after Edward VII's funeral in 1910, World War I began
and four years after that many of the monarchs who had ridden
proudly through London's streets at his funeral pageant, including
Germany's Kaiser Wilhelm, were but a part of history.
</P>
<P>
   So it will be one day with those who marched through the palace
grounds behind Hussein's coffin in 1999. And chances are that the
leadership torch will have been passed to those young lawyers whose
mark will remain indelibly on the trial that Henry Hyde described
as ``this melancholy procedure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
