<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAVORITE-MARTIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY FAVORITE MARTIAN' PROJECTS ARE WORLDS APART FOR WALSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ray Walston had mixed feelings about taking on the
role of the original ``Favorite Martian'' in the early '60s. A
Broadway star who had leading roles in ``Damn Yankees'' and ``South
Pacific'' in the 1950s, Walston recalls colleagues warning him
about playing an alien on the relatively young medium of
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job, a lot of people in Hollywood said,
`You're crazy, don't do this,' '' Walston confesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martian'' did prove a success, though, soon after hitting the
air. The year was 1963: The United States had landed its first
space probe on the moon the year before and was preparing to launch
a probe that would photograph Mars. The idea of a Martian landing
on Earth enthralled viewers.
</P>
<P>
   A big-screen version of the TV show hits theaters this Friday.
It stars Christopher Lloyd and Jeff Daniels, but the 81-year-old
Walston has an amusing role. While the new movie employs the latest
in special-effects wizardry, techniques were primitive on the
original show. ``They used fishing poles to do the levitation
scenes,'' reveals Walston. ``They put a motorized contraption on my
back, to make my antannae go up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   The show quickly departed, though, from its original
semi-serious take on a Martian stranded on Earth, Walston says.
``They started appealing more to kids, and had the Martian talk
with every kind of known animal from the barnyard,'' Walston
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would put something sweet in my ear,'' Walston continues,
``and the animal would approach me and lick my ear. It would look
like the animal was `talking' to me, and I would translate to the
boy (the late Bill Bixby, who co-starred in the show with Walston).
And I thought, I came from Broadway to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Walston put a halt to this technique after being mauled by a
chimp. ``He went berserk and chewed my face to pieces,'' Walston
says. ``After that, I said no more animals of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show went off the air in 1966, Walston stayed busy as
an actor in theater, television and films. He had memorable roles
in movies, from ``Paint Your Wagon'' to ``Popeye,'' and won two
Emmy Awards for his role of Judge Bone in TV's ``Picket Fences.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that though he still enjoys working in each medium, he
more recently has preferred films for their leisurely schedule.
``They take their time _ the pace isn't as hectic as television,''
Walston says. ``In television, the hours have gotten out of hand.
They work people from very early morning to late at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Walston adds with a laugh: ``But I really only have one
preference now: I don't want to work anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't take that too seriously, though. He delivers the line with
the mischievous glee that has been his trademark for decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
