<SLUG> BC-MENUS-VALENTINE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Bon Appetit 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DROWNED ASPARAGUS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound asparagus spears
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2-3 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2-3 cloves garlic, pressed
</P>
<P>
   Snap off or trim the tough bottom portion of asparagus spears.
Place in glass loaf pan, cover with plastic wrap and microwave for
3 minutes, or until slightly bendable. Refresh under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Place in flat bowl, or back in loaf pan. Combine remaining
ingredients and pour over asparagus. Serve at room temperature.
Make this dish before starting the entree. It does not keep well
overnight because the dressing eats up the asparagus. The dressing,
however, can be drained off and stored in the refrigerator for a
later batch of asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 38 calories, trace fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 1,028
milligrams sodium, 6 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ORZO WITH MINT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked orzo
</P>
<P>
   Freshly chopped mint
</P>
<P>
   Lime juice, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients. Dress with olive oil to taste, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 198 calories, 1 gram fat, 40
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 2 milligrams
sodium, 4 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Also from the red side of the wine list ...
</P>
<P>
   Fetzer was a pioneer in producing red wines that were both
substantial and easy to like. That tradition continues with this
``barrel select'' merlot.
</P>
<P>
   This 100 percent merlot ($14.99) was fashioned from grapes
picked in four north-coast counties and aged for 13 months.
``Barrel select'' in this case means that much of this wine was
aged in French oak barrels made at nearby Mendocino Cooperage,
where the barrels are toasted to winemaker specifications.
</P>
<P>
   What has emerged after a brief period in the bottle is a ripe
cherry-flavored, friendly wine with a long, vanilla-tinged finish.
This wine will also enhance a winter meal of stew or roast beef as
well as vegetable or meat-sauced pastas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MENU NO. 3
</P>
<P>
   Mussels are sensuous food at its best. This wonderful sauce
calls for a loaf of excellent bread to soak up every last morsel.
And to further the pleasure of the senses, spread some mozzarella
from the salad on the bread as well.
</P>
<P>
   MUSSELS COOKED IN CALVADOS, APPLE CIDER AND CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   30 to 32 mussels, rinsed and beards removed
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Calvados
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, kosher preferred
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sparkling water, such as Perrier
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan just large enough to hold the mussels, combine the
cider, cream, 6 tablespoons Calvados, salt, shallots and 1 teaspoon
parsley. Bring to a boil, stirring to blend ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Add the mussels, cover the pan and cook, shaking the pan several
times, until the mussels have opened, 4 to 5 minutes. Transfer
mussels with a slotted spoon to a bowl, discarding any that remain
unopen. Add a little hot broth and cover the bowl to keep the
mussels warm.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the liquid in the pan to a boil and reduce by half over
medium-high heat. Add remaining 2 tablespoons Calvados and
sparkling water. Taste and add salt if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Divide mussels between 2 bowls or soup plates. Pour sauce over
mussels and garnish with remaining parsley. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 424 calories, 27 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 138 milligrams cholesterol,
736 milligrams sodium, 57 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MOZZARELLA WITH BROILED PLUM TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   8 plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh chopped oregano
</P>
<P>
   One hour before serving, remove cheese from refrigerator. Slice
into 1/4-inch-thick pieces and set aside. Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   To peel tomatoes, bring 2 quarts water to boil. Score tomatoes
with an X opposite the stem end, using a paring knife. Place in
boiling water for 30 seconds. Remove and refresh immediately under
cold running water. Peel with paring knife. Remove stems and slice
tomatoes in half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Scoop out and discard tomato seeds with a teaspoon. Pat pieces
dry with a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   Brush baking sheet with olive oil. Lay tomato halves, cut side
up, on the sheet so they look like little dishes or cups. Season
with salt and pepper and sprinkle with oregano. Broil for 8 to 10
minutes or until they have softened and started to brown around
edges. When done, remove from boiler and cover with foil to keep
warm.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange tomatoes in center of a platter. Place slices of cheese
around them. Grind fresh pepper over cheese. Drizzle remaining
olive oil over platter and serve while tomatoes are still warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 708 calories, 55 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 36 grams protein, 133 milligrams cholesterol,
668 milligrams sodium, 70 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Salads'' by Leonard Schwartz (HarperCollins, $23)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   And from the white side of our wine list ...
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then a wine appears that is so admirable and
pleasing that it becomes a benchmark. So it is with this chardonnay
from Matanzas Creek.
</P>
<P>
   This is a textbook Northern California chardonnay from a
splendid vintage. Very high-quality fruit was given the red-carpet
treatment in the winery. That means full malolactic fermentation to
provide buttery richness; aging on the lees in small oak barrels
adds complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The wine, still evolving, is a pretty gold color with an aroma
of apple, vanilla and lemon. There's citrus, too, but it doesn't
dominate the fruit. The final impression is of balance and harmony.
Wine this well-made doesn't come cheap: $30 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
