A fan letter to Patricia Cornwell, mystery writer 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Patricia Cornwell:
</P>
<P>
   I hope you understand how hard it is for me to write these
words. You're a bestselling novelist, and I'm just a fan, but I
wanted you to hear from me why I won't be buying any more of your
books.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia, it's over between us.
</P>
<P>
   I know you're upset. So am I. But I've been thinking a lot since
I read your new book, ``Southern Cross,'' and I honestly think this
is the best thing for both of us. Just hear me out.
</P>
<P>
   Where to start.... We had some good times, didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   I remember back in 1990, when your first Kay Scarpetta mystery
came out. That Scarpetta, chief medical examiner for the
Commonwealth of Virginia: Now, she was a protagonist you could grow
old with. Intelligent, complicated and tough on serial killers.
Then there was Marino, the sidekick cop. And Lucy, Scarpetta's
niece. Boy, those were the days.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Body of Evidence'' followed ``Postmortem,'' I finished it
in a day. When ``All That Remains'' and ``Cruel and Unusual'' came
out later, I was among the first to buy them. I stayed up late to
finish ``The Body Farm'' and ``Cause of Death.'' I couldn't wait to
see Scarpetta catch the killers in ``Unnatural Exposure,'' ``From
Potter's Field'' and ``Point of Origin.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't put you down. You had good guys, bad guys, pacing,
plot, close calls, everything a man wants in a mystery. Then you
found somebody new.
</P>
<P>
   Did you think I wouldn't notice when ``Hornet's Nest'' appeared
in 1997 and there was this female police chief, acting tough and
intelligent and complicated as if she was Scarpetta? Well, I
noticed, and so did others. But I forgave you.
</P>
<P>
   I told myself you were trying to be writerly. I said maybe you
needed to sow your oats or be alone or whatever; it was OK with me
_ the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how I felt when I opened your new book, and it's not
Scarpetta but this other woman. And it's not even a mystery. I'm on
Page 24, and nobody's died yet. Page 190, still nothing. Nobody
even fires a gun until Page 212.
</P>
<P>
   This is a satire or a spoof or social commentary. This is what a
fan deserves?
</P>
<P>
   You know, it's not only me. Have you looked at Amazon.com
lately, at the reviews? There's this one from Georgia: ``I've read
them all with great enjoyment but this one just wouldn't fly.''
This from Oregon: ``Disappointed!!!'' And this from Tennessee: ``It
was a completely different type of novel and had it been written by
any author other than Cornwell, I probably would not have bought
it. From now on, I'll just wait for the next Scarpetta novel.''
</P>
<P>
   So with these words, I say goodbye, Patricia Cornwell. I hope
you find what you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Fondly,
</P>
<P>
   A fan
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: Did I tell you I'm seeing someone new? I've been reading a
book by James Patterson. He's got this detective, Alex Cross, and
so far, so good. I think we'll be happy together.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
