<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELROSE-PLACE-NYT &LR;      02-10 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELROSE-PLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING AS DESTINY ON `MELROSE PLACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In three months, the Fox network will evict prime time's most
feared, most microskirted landlord, Heather Locklear's Amanda
Parezi Woodward Burns Blake McBride _ with her latest husband,
Kyle, her sometime paramour, Peter, the scheming Michael, and his
crazy ex-hooker ex-wife, Megan.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of ``Melrose Place'' in May, announced last
week, is likely to provoke a rash of magazine tributes and specials
on E! saluting the seven-year-old series as addictive soap opera
and camp classic. But maybe the real appeal of ``Melrose'' is not
just the guilty, sometimes kinky pleasure of living vicariously
through beautiful people with big problems, but also a different
kind of fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Dorm life, in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, college is the last time when all our friends,
lovers, enemies and nemeses live under one roof. Not so for the
revolving residents of ``Melrose,'' who continued to cohabit well
into their 30s in a cool building in Los Angeles with a pool.
</P>
<P>
   Their attenuated adolescence is our paradise lost. It's one
thing to have a ``Honeymooners''-style married couple upstairs or a
nut across the hall a la ``Seinfeld.'' In the sexier extended
``Melrose'' family, it's possible to know all your hot neighbors,
as well as to sleep with most of them. Thy neighbor's sex life
supplies the suds for every long-lasting bar of prime-time soap.
</P>
<P>
   But the genius of ``Melrose'' lies in housing almost all the
players in the same place. Which, not coincidentally, is how many
obsessive fans have watched it, huddled in tightly knit viewing
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   (``Friends,'' which started two years later, played off the same
neo-dorm construct, as did its failed Gen X clones.)
</P>
<P>
   The building itself is a Spanish colonial echo of the glamorous
garden apartments of Los Angeles (like the Villa d'Este, designed
in 1928 by the architect brothers F. Piermont Davis and Walter S.
Davis), but with one key anachronistic amenity: a pool. The walls
drip with bougainvillea, the patio with chlorinated puddles left by
lithe, tan bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The apartments themselves are nice, not lavish one-bedroom
backdrops for their owners' psychodramas. Amanda's leopard-print
sheets telegraph her core being, as Alexis Carrington's spiky
Memphis-style desk did on ``Dynasty'' _ another decade-defining
Aaron Spelling production.
</P>
<P>
   Spelling, the elfin mogul in charge of television's most
productive dream factory, knows a thing or two about fantasy
dwellings. He was able to build a 45-room, 56,500-square-foot
megahome of his own by turning cheesy television into, well,
fromage _ from ``Charlie's Angels'' to ``Fantasy Island'' to
``Beverly Hills 90210,'' off which ``Melrose'' was spun.
</P>
<P>
   The title was intended to evoke ``Peyton Place,'' said Darren
Star, 37, who created ``Melrose Place'' from his own experience as
a struggling writer-waiter in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in a courtyard apartment with a pool,'' he recalled
the other day. ``Most of the inhabitants were in their 20s. It was
that transitional period between college and becoming an adult.
Everybody had roommates. There was a lot of sex. It was one of
those '60s-era Motel 6-looking places. Really ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Melrose'' idea of home looks like a classy motel.
</P>
<P>
   Star may not have realized it, but his tarted-up no-tell motel
is a descendant of ``Grand Hotel,'' said Donald Albrecht, adjunct
curator of the National Design Museum of the Smithsonian
Institution and a historian of film.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the Lubitsch films of the 1930s, certain kinds
of environments force social and sexual collisions, like the lobby
of a hotel,'' he said, alluding to Ernst Lubitsch, the
Hungarian-born director of ``Grand Hotel'' (1932).
</P>
<P>
   He sees the ``Melrose'' courtyard as one of those environments _
``a place where all the characters come out of their apartments and
meet each other,'' he said. ``There is this idea of spatial
proximity equaling easy sexual access.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubitsch, Albrecht also noted, ``did a lot with opening and
closing doors.'' As ``Melrose'' does. Characters are forever
catching one another sneaking in and out after their dangerous
liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that Lubitsch lifted from Georges Feydeau, the great
French farceur, and that the architectural footprint of Amanda's
complex dates back to the Roman villa. It appears that ``Melrose''
may tap into even deeper collective cultural memories than dorm
life.
</P>
<P>
   What does Spelling make of his creation? Through a spokesman, he
said that he would comment, on one condition. Disclosing that the
apartment complex is not real would be a deal breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Come on.
</P>
<P>
   A show that blew up the pool in an act of ratings desperation at
the end of last season demands to be considered realistic?
</P>
<P>
   Photographers and outside television crews may visit on the set,
only if they agree not to shoot rafters, boom mikes, craft services
food tables _ anything that would compromise the so-called fourth
wall of make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   So committed to this illusion is Spelling that he wants to
preserve it even now that ``Melrose'' is effectively dead. Agree to
his terms or no access to the ``Melrose'' cast or crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a philosophy in terms of creating an aura around the
show,'' explained Spelling's press agent, Kevin Sasaki. ``A
longstanding policy of all his shows is that _ whether it's
`Melrose' or a high school or a home _ it is a place where people
actually live.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place'' is filmed on three sound stages in an
industrial park in a Los Angeles exurb called Santa Clarita, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mihaly, a former photo editor at Entertainment Weekly has
been there. ``It was a broiling hellhole,'' Ms. Mihaly said of the
time she spent on the set, supervising photography for a special
issue of the magazine. ``We called it `Hellrose.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, she agreed to the unusual restrictions. ``They were
totally like, `This is the only way it's going to happen, if you
don't show the tops of the walls,''' she said. ``We had to promise
to crop out all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The real Melrose Place is half a block of decorator furniture
stores on the edge of Beverly Hills _ a bummer for the fans who
find it, though perhaps not as traumatizing as a trip to Santa
Clarita might be.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Melrose'' slips into the afterlife of reruns, and
before all the props _ Ms. Locklear's stiletto heels, the condoms
Michael keeps next to his bed _ are looted or relegated to the
dustbin of history, Albrecht should see to it that some piece of
the series winds up at the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   There is one true-life relic to be had out there, if anyone can
find it. The exterior wall used for establishing shots of the
show's address _ 4616 Melrose Place _ is a genuine piece of Los
Angeles real estate, Star said, though he would not give up the
location.
</P>
<P>
   Figures. Only the facade is real.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
