Legend is bigger than the real Ringo (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Johnny Ringo appears in the movie ``Tombstone.'' Was he a
real person or a fictional character? _ B.W., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: There was a real John Ringo, but he probably wasn't a
legendary gunfighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true Johnny Ringo was merely a cattle rustler and
bushwhacker, not the steely-eyed quick-draw artist portrayed in
western literature,'' Gail Hahs writes on Discovery Channel Online.
</P>
<P>
   Ringo wasn't involved in the 1881 shootout outside the O.K.
Corral with the Earps and Doc Holliday, but he was a friend and
business associate of the men who were killed: Billy Clanton, Tom
McLaury and Frank McLaury.
</P>
<P>
   His only documented gunfight was an 1879 incident at an Arizona
tavern. Louis Hancock was grazed by a bullet fired by Ringo, but
criminal charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 book ``John Ringo: The Gunfighter Who Never Was,''
author Jack Burrows writes that the main source for Ringo's legend
was William Breakinridge, a deputy who hated the Earps.
</P>
<P>
   Ringo was found dead July 14, 1882, in Turkey Creek Canyon near
Tombstone. ``No one really knows how he died, although evidence
points to suicide,'' Hahs writes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the movie ``That Thing You Do'' based on a '60s one-hit
wonder group or was it fiction? _ G.B., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The Wonders and their only hit song were entirely fictional,
according to interviews with director Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers listened to 300 versions of ``That Thing You Do!''
before settling on one by New York City songwriter Adam
Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 1964-era music from the film is real. ``A vast chunk
of that music has been co-opted by Madison Avenue,'' Hanks said in
an Oct. 11, 1996, ``Entertainment Weekly'' interview. ``You can't
escape this stuff because now it's being used to sell tennis shoes
and Pepsi.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and producer Gary Goetzman composed several of the film's
songs, including Voyage Around the Moon and Mr. Downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The program ``Sightings'' featured a healer named ``Amazing
Grace'' from Danbury, Conn. Where can we write to her and find out
about her upcoming appearances? _ A.B.E., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Pastor Grace at Grace 'N Vessels of Christ
Ministries, Box 3257, Danbury, CT 06813-3257.
</P>
<P>
   The ministries has a Web site at www.gracenvessels.org.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
.MDBR/
</P>
</TEXT>
