<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TOYS PUT CHILDREN IN MIDDLE OF THE ACTION  
 FOR FAX USERS ON THE GO, A FREE SERVICE, BUT WITH ADS   
 A NEW WAY TO TRADE STOCKS, EVEN IF YOU'RE ON THE FREEWAY  
 A VIRTUAL TIME CAPSULE IS FIRED INTO CYBERSPACE   
 GOT A BIG CRUSH ON SOMEONE? SEND A SECRET E-VALENTINE  
 BIRDER'S EYE VIEW HELPS IN TRACKING MIGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two new high-tech toys can help children shrink
images of themselves, and greatly magnify images of bugs and fleas
and the inside of the children's noses, then project all the images
onto a computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The toys, the Me2 Cam and the X3 Microscope, got a formal
introduction at this week's Toy Fair in Manhattan. They are both
products of a joint venture by Intel and Mattel, which said the
toys would be on the market in mid-September. The Me2 Cam lets
children literally lose themselves in video games. The toy, which
lists for $99, is a digital video camera that captures a child's
image, sends it to the computer through a Universal Serial Bus
port, and allows the child to appear inside a game. With the camera
trained on the game player, the child can move around and interact
with the animated objects in the game.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a game called Bubble Factory, players get
points by popping bubbles that fall from the sky. To do that, the
child pokes and gestures in front of the digital camera, thus
manipulating the on-screen image. The game's software then
incorporates the image into the animated game play, enabling the
off-screen player to participate with the animation.
</P>
<P>
   In another game, Mountain Madness, players jump and tilt and
sway to navigate a snowboarding course.
</P>
<P>
   The X3 Microscope is also a digital camera that hooks up to a
computer. But instead of projecting a user's image onto the screen,
it magnifies tiny images up to 250 times and displays them on a
computer monitor in a live video feed.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Norris, project director of the Intel and Mattel toy
line, said the possibilities were numerous. ``Kids can look in
their mouths, ears, look at scabs, look at tattoos,'' she said.
``They can pick up bugs, pick the flea off the dog and instead of
squinting at it, go and put it under the microscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Free Faxes With a Catch
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers accept the fact that commercials subsidize
free programming, but will they accept advertising as a way to
support free faxes? A Silicon Valley company is banking that they
will, particularly if it means they do not have to buy an actual
fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   The company, eFax.com, this week began offering a service that
will direct a subscriber's incoming faxes to an e-mail address, not
a fax machine. A subscriber signs up with eFax for a personal fax
number. Calls made to that number will be routed through eFax in
Menlo Park, Calif., where they will be directed to a user's e-mail
address. The service is free, but the catch is that the faxes that
arrive in e-mail will be accompanied with four small banner
advertisements above each message.
</P>
<P>
   There are already services that direct faxes to e-mail accounts,
but this one is the first to try to use advertising to foot the
bill, said Ron Brown, vice president for eFax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the service was aimed at mobile professionals who
could not sit by a fax machine waiting for a document, but he said
the company hoped that it would cut into the demand for home and
home-office fax machines. ``It's a pretty cool way to get around
cumbersome second phone lines and leaving machines on all night,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Market Vibes
</P>
<P>
   Users of the latest mobile gizmo will know that it's time to buy
or sell stocks when they feel vibrations in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The device, called the Mobile Broker, is a pager configured to
permit users to buy and sell stocks, check portfolios and real-time
stock prices, and send and receive e-mail. The pager can also be
programmed to tell investors, either through a beep or vibrations,
when a desired buy or sell price has been received.
</P>
<P>
   The pager is made by BellSouth, but the $49-per-month stock
service is being offered by Siebert &AMP; Co., a small, independent
discount broker based in New York. Muriel Siebert, the company's
founder and chief executive, said that in addition to the monthly
fee, pager traders would pay a $29.95 fee per transaction. She said
that was a fair price for a service that lets an investor trade
stocks while driving or playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   But this idea may have its pitfalls for the rest of us. Imagine
being stuck behind a day trader toting a Mobile Broker on the
freeway as he or she tries to navigate a wildly fluctuating stock
market while driving at 75 miles an hour, using the free hand to
chat on the cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Digital Time Capsule
</P>
<P>
   Virtual reality claimed yet another vestige of the physical
world last week at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The
Sloan School of Management there sealed and launched a time
capsule, but the contents are all digital, the capsule merely
virtual and its destination not deep space, but cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   In the encrypted capsule, which is held on a server at MIT, are
symbols of life and business on the Internet, including audio files
of the impeachment proceedings, a sample of the Victoria's Secret
Web site, Amazon.com pages and snippets of Dilbert and South Park
cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   The capsule also contains predictions of what will transpire in
the next five years. The predictions come from accomplished MIT
graduates and also several celebrities, including Bill Gates and
Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the prognostications are to remain a secret until the
cybervault is opened in five years, although one Sloan official
offered a guess at Gates' vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's hoping his trial will be over by 2004,'' said Mary
Schaefer, the school's director of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Secretadmirer.com
</P>
<P>
   For this Valentine's Day, the Web offers no end of personal
advertisements and chat rooms to hook up total strangers. But one
site has found a way to find out if the object of a crush returns
the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Secretadmirer.com allows a visitor to send an anonymous e-mail
to a person the sender has a crush on. The receiver is then
informed that he or she has a secret admirer and is given the
option of sending a note, also anonymous, to whomever he or she
might have a crush on.
</P>
<P>
   If the notes make a match, then the computer program informs
both parties. If there is no match after two weeks, the computer
sends the original sender a rejection note. Of course, the original
anonymous note might have inspired the receiver to send a note to
someone else, not the sender.
</P>
<P>
   ``One sender's note can start a chain reaction of crushes,''
said Miles Kronby, the founder of Secretadmirer.com.
</P>
<P>
   Kronby, a graduate of New York University's interactive
telecommunications program, devised the site after a co-worker told
him that she had a crush on a co-worker but was scared to approach
him. He encouraged her to tell the co-worker anyway, but when she
did, she got a very chilly response. ``After that, it made it
really uncomfortable for them to work with each other,'' he said.
``It got me thinking that there must be a better way to test the
waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Kronby said the free matchmaking service had been responsible
for more than 10,000 matches since it started in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer Murray, an 18-year-old college freshman from Seattle,
said he had recently used the site to get in contact with a woman
he met at a party. To his relief, Secretadmirer.com alerted him
that they were a match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really shy, so it saved me from the nightmare of having to
talk to her in person,'' he said. ``I don't think we would have
gotten together otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   _ RACHEL LEHMANN-HAUPT
</P>
<P>
   Birds on the Net
</P>
<P>
   From the 19th to the 22nd of this month, bird watchers
nationwide can use the Internet to help the National Audubon
Society track the winter bird migration. The Audubon Society, along
with Cornell University, is seeking volunteers in the second annual
``back yard bird watch'' to report their daily sightings to the Web
at birdsource.cornell.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Taking birding information online will allow scientists to
digest and publish the daily sightings more quickly, said John
Bianchi, spokesman for National Audubon Society, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``As results come in, we'll publish them on a map,'' he said of
the bird-watching updates. ``It will be just like election
returns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
