<HEADLINE>
ROLLING STONES SQUEEZE MORE OUT OF LESS AT POND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Much has been made of the fact that the Rolling
Stones' current ``No Security'' tour is their first trek through
the relatively cozy confines of arenas in 20 years. But Tuesday
night at the Arrowhead Pond in Anaheim, it was the venerable band's
three-song set on a tiny stage in the middle of that cozy arena
that gave fans more than their fair share of satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   With a loose feel that gave the impression of a jam session, the
Stones tore through playful versions of ``Route 66'' and ``Just My
Imagination'' before delivering a thunderous ``Midnight Rambler''
that matched the definitive cut on their magnificent live album
``Get Yer Ya-Ya's Out.'' Scorching guitar work from Keith Richards
and Ron Wood pushed Mick Jagger to explore the song's dark
underbelly. It was the defining moment in a concert full of raw and
raucous rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Stones have scaled back their stadium theatrics for this
arena tour, giving the songs more immediacy and power. For one
thing, warhorses like ``Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and ``Honky Tonk
Woman'' were shorter and punchier because Jagger didn't have to run
around a stage the size of an aircraft carrier, trying to keep a
stadium full of people happy. Jagger has also given up wearing the
outlandish costumes, sticking instead to a series of tank tops and
tight jeans. He wore them well.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Jagger also gave a nod to his current marital
troubles with a set of songs that could easily have been called
``The Jerry Hall Suite.'' Starting with the classic ode to
misogyny, ``Some Girls,'' the band continued with ``Saint of Me''
(``You'll NEVER make a saint of me'') and a fantastic, stomping
``Paint It Black.'' It was impossible to miss the message.
</P>
<P>
   The band remains in excellent form, Jagger strutting and
contorting his body every which way and Richards striking the
classic guitar-god poses he trademarked. Wood still ably lays down
his lead guitar lines and drummer Charlie Watts holds the whole
thing together with his rock-solid beat.
</P>
<P>
   The show ended with one classic after another: ``Tumbling
Dice,'' ``It's Only Rock 'n' Roll (But I Like It),'' ``Start Me
Up,'' ``Brown Sugar'' and an encore of ``Sympathy For the Devil.''
We've all heard them a thousand times, but somehow the songs still
sound fresh and alive.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this could be the last time, but let's hope not. These
Stones are still rolling, gathering no moss along the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
