<HEADLINE>
TV NEWS VETERAN PREFERS BEING BEHIND RADIO MICROPHONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All-news KFWB-AM's new co-anchor and reporter
Kathleen Sullivan might just have the brightest smile on the dial _
not that you'll see much of it.
</P>
<P>
   Emmy Award-winning Sullivan, who anchored the 1984 Winter
Olympic Games in Sarajevo and that year's Summer Olympics in Los
Angeles for ABC-TV, spent many years in television but actually
prefers her new home behind the radio microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to write and report, and TV doesn't lend itself to a
lot of interesting stories because of its constant demand for
visuals,'' Sullivan offers. ``I love the news, but the attention to
my hair color got a little exhausting. When that became more
important than the lead story, I said, `Please.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena-bred Sullivan has worked at CNN, CBS and ABC in her
20-year career as a broadcast journalist. More recently, she
received Emmy nominations as host of E! Entertainment Television's
``E! News Daily,'' which she joined after anchoring the cable
channel's gavel-to-gavel coverage of the O.J. Simpson murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although she's already on the air at KFWB (980), Monday is the
official launch of the station's five-hour morning show, which also
features co-anchor Dan Avey and senior correspondent Bob Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kathleen brings a wealth of knowledge and experience to the
KFWB news team,'' said program director Dave Cooke, adding that
listener reaction has been ``overwhelmingly positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is no stranger to radio. She's done fill-in work at
talk station KABC-AM (790) in the morning and other times during
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed news can be written and presented in an
entertaining fashion,'' she said. ``So, if anything, you can expect
the presentation to be a little spunkier with some interesting
points of view.''
</P>
</TEXT>
