<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE SPELLS OUT ITS LITTLE LESSONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughter Asha handed me another stack of graded papers
recently from a week of school, including a spelling test with two
parts.
</P>
<P>
   She received a 95 on the portion in which she had to spell the
words of the week and made one error and a 100 on the other
section, in which she had to use the words correctly in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   What she wanted me to take special note of was that in both
parts of the test, she had misspelled the word paint as P-A-N-I-T
and that she had pointed this out to her second-grade teacher, Mrs.
Plummer. Because of Asha's honesty, she told me, Mrs. Plummer
allowed her to keep the grade of 100 on the sentence-formation
section.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't that nice?'' Asha asked me with a great big smile.
</P>
<P>
   I agreed that this was a nice gesture and made special note of
Asha's willingness to risk getting a lower grade by telling the
truth. Then I asked her for the correct spelling. ``P_A_I_N_T,''
she responded ever so slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good girl,'' I said, slapping her little hand in a high five.
</P>
<P>
   Asha skipped off to add the papers to the rest of the stack from
the year, and I was left thinking how often life offers us teaching
moments, moments to impart wisdom to others and//or learn from our
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they come from a loved one or a friend or one of life's
experiences, such moments happen to all of us _ but for one reason
or another, not all of us take advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, I sometimes get too busy to take time for such
moments with my girls. If I'm lucky enough to get home from work at
a reasonable hour, there's still dinner to be prepared and homework
to be checked in the three hours before my daughters' bedtime. And
teachers often don't see imparting morals as part of their jobs _
even if they did have the time, which, these days, is increasingly
rare.
</P>
<P>
   And so I was more than a little grateful for Mrs. Plummer and
proud of Asha. Because I know how important getting A's is to my
little girl, I'm aware that she could have kept silent. She didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes honesty is clear-cut. Other times, it's not so simple.
Despite our intentions, we often send children mixed messages.
Recently, for instance, I promised my daughter Jamila that I would
purchase her a telescope. When the next Saturday morning rolled
around, she wanted her telescope. Right then. But I had thought it
would make a good birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   So I had lied to her.
</P>
<P>
   Some people argue that school isn't the best place to teach
children character, and maybe it isn't. But it's comforting knowing
that my daughter's teacher took the time to spot opportunity in
that teaching moment.
</P>
<P>
   When teaching moments are clear-cut, we need to act as Mrs.
Plummer did. We also need to remember that kids learn from us even
when we're not teaching them _ and if we're not paying attention,
we might not be saying exactly what we mean.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
