<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-651-ARTS-DANCE-$ADV14     02-10 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-651-ARTS-DANCE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A BROOKLYN MISSION TO BE A GOOD NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 14)  
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the best-kept secrets in the performing arts
in New York City is 651 Arts. The Brooklyn-based producing and
presenting organization is often confused with the Brooklyn Academy
of Music, a separate corporation that helped found it nearly 10
years ago and has maintained a symbiotic relationship with it. But
the work and mission of 651 Arts are very clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about connections: artist to audience, artist to
community, community to community, audience to audience, artist to
artist and organization to organization,'' Maurine D. Knighton,
executive director of 651, said in a recent interview. ``We're
always looking to do that in ways that are meaningful and positive
and move things forward for the people involved in the connecting.
Ultimately, everybody wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, 651 is a developer, producer and presenter of
contemporary performing-arts works by black artists like Donald
Byrd (``Harlem Nutcracker'' and ``Jazz Train''), Anna Deavere Smith
(``Fires in the Mirror'') and Randy Weston (a production of his
rarely performed 1961 ``Uhuru Afrika'').
</P>
<P>
   This month, 651 is one of 13 organizations citywide that is
participating in a salute to the documentary ``I'll Make Me a
World.''
</P>
<P>
   Events include a Sunday film series, ``Black Beyond Borders:
Mapping the African Diaspora,'' as well as ``Story Corner: African
American Stories'' on Feb. 27, both at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
Behind the scenes, 651 is also developing music projects with Nona
Hendrix, Sekou Sundiata and Craig Harris and a workshop in the
Katherine Dunham technique with the Philadanco dance troupe of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Money is being raised for ``Black Dance: Tradition and
Transformation,'' a project for next February that will present
performances and commission companies nationally to create and
reconstruct dances. And 651 has provided rehearsal space to the
choreographers Dianne McIntyre and Ron Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in the city-owned Majestic Theater, which it leases
rent-free from the Academy, 651 takes its name from the address of
the Majestic, at 651 Fulton Street, two blocks from the Academy. It
was founded in 1988 with a mandate from New York City to provide
cultural programming of interest to neighboring communities, many
of whose populations are predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be more responsive to the community in a smaller
house with some union breaks, so that it was financially possible
to do more than we were able to do at BAM,'' Harvey Lichtenstein,
the executive producer of the Academy, said.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenstein chose Mikki Shepard and Leonard Goines, arts
consultants who had produced large-scale black dance and music
events at the Academy, to shape and direct 651. In the first few
years, 651 got administrative help and $100,000 a year from the
Academy. It now contributes $60,000 annually to the center's
budget, which is $1.6 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The organization started as a traditional presenter. ``We were
not trying to shape something for a specific audience,'' said Ms.
Shepard, who left 651 in September to become director of arts and
humanities at the Rockefeller Foundation. ``We wanted to know what
was important to them. And over time, things began to emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Artist Residency Program and Neighborhood Arts
Network were added and soon became as important as the
performances. The Artist Residency Program sends artists out into
the community to teach, create and perform. Africa Exchange,
supported by the Ford Foundation, brings African artists to the
United States to work with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Neighborhood Arts Network links 651 and its artists with
arts organizations in eight Brooklyn neighborhoods.The five core
constituents are El Puente de Williamsburg, a public high school
and community center; the Gowanus Arts Exchange, an organization in
Park Slope that offers classes in the arts and presents dance,
music and theater performances; the Ifetayo Cultural Arts Facility,
a community arts center in Flatbush; Medgar Evers Community College
in Crown Heights, and the Fort Greene Senior Center. In addition,
651 develops and presents events with other arts organizations
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the core organizations had a track record in its
community. ``Mikki Shepard's vision was not to reinvent the wheel
but help community organizations to become stronger and more what
they were,'' Sister Kwayera D. Cunningham, the executive director
of Ifetayo, said. ``It was not `This is what we want you to do' but
`What do you need?' We needed technical assistance in various
areas. They provided us with a development consultant. They never
wavered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ifetayo Youth Ensemble has a repertory that includes pieces
created for the teen-age dance troupe by three 651 artists, Byrd,
Kevin Jeff and Abdel Salaam. Family members and adults studying at
the center have come to know more about the arts through that work.
Parents approach Sister Kwayera, as she is known to all, and say:
``Oh, 651 is doing this. Do you have tickets?''
</P>
<P>
   Marya Warshaw, executive director of Gowanus, describes it as
``a developmental home'' for artists as well as a presenting
organization. Gowanus, which has the largest white constituency of
the network groups, has acted as co-producer with 651 and received
help with fund-raising, marketing and in-kind services. Other help
included vouchers for tickets from backers of 651 and master
classes taught by 651 artists.
</P>
<P>
   All 651 constituents are considered to be interlocking
communities, whether neighborhoods, audiences, artists or
contributors. The Ifetayo ensemble is working on a new piece with
Salaam, to be performed in April at the Medgar Evers theater, and
the choreographer has also acquired a badly needed booking agent
through 651.
</P>
<P>
   Another example is the ``Dance and Spiritual Life'' program in
November, one aim of which was to provide audiences with an unusual
and thought-provoking way to look at dance by three familiar female
choreographers: Dianne McIntyre, Bebe Miller and Jawole Willa Jo
Zollar, founder of Urban Bush Women. The Cornerstone Baptist Church
in Bedford-Stuyvesant came to know 651 through an event in 1997.
Dancers spent a day at the church teaching the 72 children in the
day care center, working with the Praise Dancers, a troupe of
teen-agers interested in the relationship between the body and the
spirit, and sharing a meal with both groups. ``We were so
impressed,'' said the Rev. Harry S. Wright, Senior Pastor of the
church. ``And so, a year later, the partnership continued in a
deeper way.''
</P>
<P>
   The church was chosen to hold a panel discussion on the
involvement of the black church in dance in connection with ``Dance
and Spiritual Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine a more conservative setting to talk about
dance and spirituality,'' Wright said. ``I wanted to have this
panel of experts come out, particularly with a black dance
historian and real live professional dancers who were also members
of other churches. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've found real friends in 651. And they have also
sensed a tremendous hunger and appetite in our neighborhood for
arts and humanities appreciation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
