<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-PROFILE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMMY NOD REGISTERS HIGH NOTE FOR ALTO SAX PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES_ Latin-American alto saxophonist Paquito D'Rivera
doesn't make music to win awards, but he admits his recent Grammy
nod just plain feels good.
</P>
<P>
   D'Rivera is up for best Latin jazz performance for the album
``Live at Manchester Craftsmen's Guild'' (Blue Jackel), cut in 1997
with his United Nation Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Havana in 1948, D'Rivera was introduced to jazz by his
father and heard the music of his earliest influences _ Benny
Goodman, Charlie Parker and Paul Desmond _ on Voice of America
broadcasts. He defected to the United States in 1980 while on a
tour of Europe and moved to New York, where he began playing with
Dizzy Gillespie and McCoy Tyner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worked for awards,'' D'Rivera said. ``But when
people recognize the fruit of your work, it's nice. The award has
really been the pleasure of being in this business for so many
years. But it's nice to be recognized by the record academy. So
many wonderful artists never get any awards at all, while so many
terrible artists get awards who shouldn't be allowed to perform in
public. In many cases, though, they do award the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Rivera won a Grammy in 1996 for best Latin jazz performance
for his musical salute to his homeland, ``Portraits of Cuba''
(Chesky). A new album, ``Paquito D'Rivera With Strings: 100 Years
of Latin Love Songs'' (Heads Up), was issued recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a group of people recognize my work, I'm very thankful,''
the saxophonist said Tuesday. ``It's better to have it than not.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Rivera, working on a jazz piece for the New Jersey Chamber
Music Society, boasts a strict work ethic. He usually cuts an album
a year while touring and composing music at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a studio person, I'm more a performer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The 41st annual Grammy Awards will be announced Feb. 24 at a
televised ceremony at the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
