<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IF THE `PEANUTS' GANG GRADUATED TO CHEEVERSVILLE?
</HEADLINE>
  (For Release Sunday, Feb. 14)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That Charles Schulz doesn't rate an entry in the
Oxford Companion to American Literature can only be explained as
some ghastly oversight on the part of the editors. It is true that
Schulz is known primarily as a cartoonist. Yet he not only writes
his own scripts for ``Peanuts,'' which first appeared in 1950; he
also letters his own dialogue in the balloons that float over his
characters' heads. Not even John Cheever, John Updike or any of the
other esteemed chroniclers of life in the American suburbs and
exurbs after World War II could make such a claim. What, after all,
do we mean when we speak of ``a man of letters?''
</P>
<P>
   Ponder that.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if you're looking for a gentle, wise, very
cheering entertainment, you couldn't do better than to visit the
Ambassador Theater to see the almost-new, pocket-size musical
``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.'' This is Michael Mayer's
revival of the 1967 Off Broadway hit, based on the ``Peanuts''
comic strip, for which Clark Gesner wrote the music, book and
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, you will discover a blissfully sunny
alternate universe to the one of broken marriages, career
compromises, alcoholism, mental breakdowns (plus the occasional
redemption) that became so familiar in American literature of the
postwar years.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to suggest for a minute that Schulz had any such
ideas in mind when he created the born-to-lose Charlie Brown and
the other members of the ``Peanuts'' gang. They remain forever
young in Schulz's static universe, where no one seems to be older
than 10 and where the most poetic mind among them is possessed by a
beagle named Snoopy.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape around them is generic and two-dimensional: a tree
is a tree, a cloud a cloud, a doghouse a doghouse. Yet Schulz's
characters are so accurately and eccentrically realized, you
suspect that if they ever grew up, they would be much like
Cheever's, getting into boozy Saturday night scrapes in a town with
a name like Shady Hill. Charlie Brown and his friends may be
children, but they wear their neuroses with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Lucy, a crabby child only too happy to tell someone the
blunt, embarrassing truth, who is madly in love with the
piano-playing Schroeder and serenely unaware that, for him, she
doesn't exist. The adult Lucy will be the last to know her husband
is sleeping with every woman in the neighborhood except her.
Schroeder will leave home hoping for a career as a concert artist,
but he will wind up playing the organ in any church that will have
him. Then there is Linus, who walks around clutching his beloved
blanket, an embryonic fetishist's festishist if there ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown's little sister, Sally (who replaces the character
of Patty in Mayer's revival of the show), is all Shirley Temple
corkscrew curls and simpering grins. But as played by the
spectacularly funny Kristin Chenoweth, she has a voice that is
sharp enough to etch monograms into Baccarat crystal. She will be
Shady Hill's most successful fundraiser, at least in part because
people will pay her to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Dear sweet clumsy Charlie Brown? He will drop out of college,
run a hardware store, coach a second-rate Little League team and,
in his middle years, start to (lower your voice so the children
can't hear) d-r-i-n-k. The most humane, least neurotic of the gang
is Snoopy, and he will be long gone by the time his old pals fall
apart.
</P>
<P>
   These fantasies are not meant to belittle Schulz's classic
strip, but to explain its long-term appeal. His accomplishment has
been to create children who are recognizable both as children and
as the adults they will become. They are not exactly the kids next
door. They live in a reality that is singular to the Schulz strip.
</P>
<P>
   It is this quality that makes Mayer's ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown'' such an endearing endeavor, a series of sketches
intended to represent an average day in the life of Charlie Brown.
In most cases the members of the cast, never attempt to deny the
evidence of their actual ages. Instead, they play their roles
straight, that is, from the inside out, without resorting to
all-purpose kiddie mannerisms.
</P>
<P>
   The results are astonishing in several cases. Ms. Chenoweth's
Sally is both a kid you might want to swat if you had to live with
her, and a personality who tomorrow could play Miss Adelaide in
``Guys and Dolls.'' She is magical on stage. So, too, is B.D. Wong,
who made his Broadway debut in ``M. Butterfly'' in 1988. Now in his
later 30s, he appears to be having the time of his life giving a
priceless performance as the thumb-sucking, blanket-clutching,
singing and dancing Linus. Not for a minute does he disguise the
man he is but, in him, Linus lives. How does he do it? I haven't a
clue. That's theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ilana Levine, whose grating voice is also a superb musical
comedy weapon, is enchanting as the furrow-browed Lucy, as when she
instructs Linus to study Charlie Brown's ``Failure Face.'' ``Notice
the deep lines,'' she says with nasty pleasure, ``the dull, vacant
look in the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the show's star beagle is Roger Bart, a marvelous clown
whose manic energy and facial expressions are reminiscent of Ronnie
Graham's. He is an explosively comic joy as Snoopy, whether doing
imaginary battle with the Red Baron in the skies over France,
lolling in the sun atop his doghouse or anticipating the delights
of his evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Wayne Mathis is as lively as his meager material allows
in the role of Schroeder, while Anthony Rapp, a good actor you may
remember as the camcorder operator in ``Rent,'' appears to be
bewildered as Charlie Brown. The role is not especially rewarding,
I suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown is a passive figure. He is diffident, lonely,
apologetic, not easily brought to active life by someone who does
not yet have his own idiosyncratic stage presence, such as a young
Robert Morse. Rapp's way is sometimes to play down to Charlie
Brown, as in his taking small, childlike steps, and at other times
to play him as a more or less conventional musical comedy juvenile
in the middle of what is otherwise a cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lippa, the show's musical supervisor and arranger, has
written new material for some of the Gesner songs and two new
numbers of his own. The one you will remember: ``My New
Philosophy,'' in which Sally realizes that she can respond to
almost any statement by saying ``That's what you think,'' and
Schroeder decides that his comeback will be, ``Why are you telling
me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' is small in scale, simply
but effectively set in a cartoon world, and demands a certain
knowledge of and affection for Schulz's work. Mayer, whose last
major Broadway hit was the powerhouse revival of Arthur Miller's
``View From the Bridge,'' is clearly a man who likes to test his
range.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Heart'' is the collective title for the program of two
hilarious and mysterious Caryl Churchill plays that will be ending
their 24-performance run at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's
Majestic Theater next Sunday. My advice: run, don't walk, to
Brooklyn or, if you live in Manhattan, take the BAM Bus. Otherwise
you will miss one of the wittiest, most gorgeously performed
theatrical events since last year's Broadway engagement of the
London revival of the Ionesco classic, ``The Chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chairs'' does not come to mind by chance. Ms. Churchill,
who writes in all sorts of veins, from the documentary (``Mad
Forest'') to the metaphysical (``The Skriker''), is here entering
territory that, superficially anyway, looks a lot like Ionesco's
absurdist theater at its most bracing.
</P>
<P>
   The first play, ``Heart's Desire,'' also recalls the blithe
surrealism of Luis Bunuel's ``Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie.''
A lower-middle-class Mum, Dad and Auntie sit in the kitchen of
their London council house awaiting the arrival of their daughter,
who is coming home from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the play can never quite get going: it keeps changing its
mind. Mum and Dad's bickering is interrupted by a call that there
has been a terrible accident, at which point the play starts again.
Each time it begins, something else interrupts things, forcing the
actors to start over once more. We learn a body has been found in
the garden. At another point, two gunmen show up. Later, a huge
ostrich ambles on.
</P>
<P>
   As the absurdities accumulate and the familiar opening scene is
played for the umpteenth time, the pace becomes increasingly
frantic. Is it the playwright who can't make up her mind? Is this a
meditation on life lived not in the present but entirely in
expectation, often in dread? The answers are unimportant. For some
reason, seeing theatrical reality turned on its ear in this giddy
fashion is a kind of liberation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Kettle,'' the second play, features a genially shabby man
in his early 40's who has a scam: he collects mothers, each a woman
to whom he announces himself as the baby she put up for adoption
years before. He is not sure what his motive is, though he thinks
there may be money in it.
</P>
<P>
   As his conquests go on, something very strange happens: language
begins to lose its meaning. The words ``blue'' and ``kettle'' turn
up with increasing frequency as substitutes for words in otherwise
coherent sentences. Eventually, ``blue'' and ``kettle,'' the only
words left, disintegrate into their isolated letters that, in their
turn, vanish, leaving only a ``b'' and ``k.'' Yet no one seems to
notice; life goes on with its usual mindless self-absorption. The
play's ending, though spoken in gibberish, is utterly clear and
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Max Stafford-Clark is the wizardly director of the program,
which is a production of Out of Joint, the London-based touring
company founded in 1993 by Stafford-Clark and Sonia Friedman. The
production at the Majestic is the one that played at the Royal
Court in London in 1997 with many of the same superb actors.
Everything about the performance is immaculate. The writing
dazzles.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Pinter's ``Ashes to Ashes,'' the Roundabout Theater
Company production now Off Broadway at the Gramercy Theater, is
less a play than a formless reverie. Here is a brief (40-minute)
duologue that considers (with a good deal of self-importance) what
it is like to be civilized and physically unscathed in, say, an
English university town, while being aware of the unspeakable
atrocities committed every hour of the day elsewhere in the world.
They seep into our collective unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Pinter seems to be saying that we pay a terrible price. Our
dreams are turned into nightmares. We feel guilt. Even healthy,
robust sex loses its rosy glow. If this is another way of
suggesting that we are all victims, we must learn to pity the rich,
the secure and the overfed.
</P>
<P>
   The setting looks to be the study in the house of a professor,
though the two characters are not identified beyond their names.
When the lights come up, Devlin (David Strathairn) stands, a drink
in his hand, listening to a seemingly transfixed Rebecca (Lindsay
Duncan).
</P>
<P>
   Staring straight ahead from her easy chair, she meticulously
describes something that seems to have been a bit of the old S&AMP;M
with an earlier lover. Devlin, who could be her husband, her
psychiatrist, her lover, or maybe all three, has not heard the
story before. He is anxious.
</P>
<P>
   They are having trouble making connections, possibly because
Pinter's dialogue keeps sliding back on itself, like a car with
slipping gears trying to go up a steep hill. ``What did you say,''
says Devlin. ``You said? What did you say?''
</P>
<P>
   As the evening wears on, she remembers events that could be
dreams inspired by newsreels of the Holocaust, television reports
on the war in Bosnia, memoirs about the ``disappeared ones'' in
Pinochet's Chile, a scene from William Styron's ``Sophie's
Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashes to Ashes'' ends as it begins, in silence.
</P>
<P>
   A clue as to what Pinter is doing here can be found in an
interview he gave in Barcelona in 1996, published in a recent Grove
Press collection of Pinter pieces titled ``Various Voices.'' In
that interview the playwright congratulates the Barcelona audiences
for being more receptive to ``Ashes to Ashes'' than London
audiences. ``In Britain,'' he says, with the authority of someone
who has abandoned all self-doubt, ``there is no tradition of
artists being respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinter himself directed the play when it was done at the
Ambassadors Theater in London three years ago with Ms. Duncan and
Stephen Rea. Karel Reisz is the director of the New York
production, which appears to be almost everything a play-proud
dramatist could desire. Ms. Duncan is firm, intense and centered as
the grieving Rebecca, and though Strathairn's accent is uneasy, his
presence is secure.
</P>
<P>
   The piece has moments of haunting eloquence. Too often, though,
it sounds like self-parody from a master who has no awareness he is
producing hot air. These are not 40 minutes to leave home for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
