<HEADLINE>
`BE COOL': CHILI PALMER'S LATEST MOVIE IDEA
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: Publication notes at end of review) 
 (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the way through Elmore Leonard's thoroughly
entertaining new novel, ``Be Cool,'' a police detective says to
Chili Palmer, the protagonist: ``My wife wants to know how come I'm
putting in so much overtime lately. I told her 'cause Chili
Palmer's making a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers will recognize Chili Palmer as the small-time Brooklyn
crook turned Hollywood movie producer who appeared in Leonard's
novel ``Get Shorty,'' made into the film starring John Travolta as
Chili. That story established how Chili's way of developing a film
script was to create a situation in actuality and then see what
happens. ``I start with different characters and see where they
take me,'' he explains in ``Be Cool.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Chili says about one possible film idea: ``It's believable
because it happened. It's real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this contradicts what Chekhov discovered when he
tried putting a real peasant onstage and found that he looked
unreal. But the method seems to work for Chili. He has made a
successful film called ``Get Leo,'' featuring an undersize loan
shark, as well as a sequel, ``Get Lost,'' whose failure he blames
on the studio's stupidity. Now, at the opening of ``Be Cool,'' he
thinks he has found another character with potential.
</P>
<P>
   She's a girl who works for one of those dating services, Chili
tells his lunch companion, Tommy Athens, an old buddy from Brooklyn
who has made it big in the recording business. ``This one I talked
to, soon as I heard her voice and the beginning of the pitch? I
thought, This could give me an idea. So I put her on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy counters, ``I called you 'cause I got an idea for a
movie.'' ``Can you pitch it in 25 words or less?'' Chili asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell it in one word,'' Tommy says. ``Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chili excuses himself to go to the bathroom. On the way there he
toys with the idea of combining Tommy's story with that of the
dating service girl, Linda Moon, whose ``real life'' is singing
with a rock band. As he returns to the table he sees a black car
pull up. Out of it steps a short guy with a gun who starts shooting
at Tommy and kills him with a bullet to the head.
</P>
<P>
   When the police come, Chili keeps ``his mouth shut looking at
the scene again, starting to rewrite it in his mind, the guy
playing Tommy no longer the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have the star get popped 10 minutes into the
picture,'' he thinks. ``No, but it could be the way to open it. A
movie about the music business.''
</P>
<P>
   What's impressive about ``Be Cool'' is the number of plot
complications Leonard juggles so wittily. Linda Moon is stuck with
a manager she detests who calls himself Raji. (``Raji coming with
his slouch strut, his shades, his black Kangol cap on backwards the
way his hero Samuel L. Jackson wore his.'')
</P>
<P>
   Raji intimidates people because he keeps a bodyguard who is
``built like one of those giant Samoans you saw, this one going at
least 260 in his tank top, a do-rag down on his eyebrows, thick
black hair to his huge shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes by the name Elliot Wilhelm (``What he doesn't look like
is an Elliot,'' Chili remarks), and his special skill is throwing
people out the windows of upper stories. But Chili knows that
Elliot dreams of making it ``as a star of stage and screen,'' as he
puts it. Eventually Chili's very life will depend on Elliot's
believing his promise of a screen test.
</P>
<P>
   Other plot wrinkles involve a very inside knowledge of the music
industry. Leonard seems to have mastered it. His characters
certainly talk the talk: ``I got an artist I just signed and I'm
ready to break, Derek Stones, with Roadkill,'' Tommy tells Chili at
their fateful lunch. ``It use to be a hair band, now they do
post-metal funk with a ska kick. You have any idea what I'm talking
about?''
</P>
<P>
   No, this reader didn't, but the wonder is, you get enough of the
drift not to feel too left behind. In many of the scenes where
music is performed, you can even imagine the sound.
</P>
<P>
   The nagging question remains, Why do you keep rooting for Chili
so completely?
</P>
<P>
   After all, back in Bay Ridge he used to sell goods ``that fell
off the back of trucks,'' and later, in Miami, he was ``you might
say, a loan shark,'' even if he does take the unusual position that
``there may be a certain amount of satisfaction in breaking a guy's
leg that gets behind, but how does he repay the loan if he's laid
up?''
</P>
<P>
   He's attractive because he's so smart and quietly sure of
himself that throughout ``Be Cool,'' despite the brutal world in
which he operates, he doesn't have to commit a single act of
violence. Certainly the women in the story like him, yet in
contrast to the studs of Leonard's early fiction, Chili is
considerate, even sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   When he spends the night with an old friend and she asks him if
he had ``a nice time,'' he tells her ``he had a wonderful time,
terrific, and that he felt _ it was funny, but he felt that being
good friends first and then going to bed . . . Elaine stopped him,
saying `Don't strain yourself, Chil. Listen, ``wonderful'' and
``terrific'' are fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, wonderful and terrific is what I'll say about ``Be
Cool.'' Leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BE COOL'
</P>
<P>
   By Elmore Leonard
</P>
<P>
   292 pages. Delacorte Press. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
