<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BURTON COMMITTEE TURNS ATTACK TO 'ALARMING' WASTE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional panel that spent the last two years
probing White House scandals refocused its attack Wednesday on
waste and fraud that it says drain billions of taxpayer dollars in
executive agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had controversy,'' Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., told his
House Government Reform Committee, of the tumultuous investigations
of President Clinton during the past congressional term.
</P>
<P>
   Burton pledged a bipartisan campaign to bring more efficiency to
the federal bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go before the American people get their
money's worth from the federal government,'' he said as he pointed
out three of the most waste-prone federal departments that, he
said, ``paint an alarming picture of the state of affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those chief problems:
</P>
<P>
   The Housing and Urban Development department remains a
``management basket case,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   That view was largely endorsed by the department's inspector
general, Susan Gaffney, who told the panel that she opposes
Clinton's budget proposals for some 18 new programs added to the
350 now run by the Housing Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense to me,'' Gaffney said. ``HUD is
struggling. I don't understand why we want to make that struggle
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a recent audit of ``Empowerment Zones'' in Atlanta,
Chicago, Detroit and Philadelphia showed there was no federal
oversight of the program, which gives federal assistance to
selected high-poverty areas. ``Now we are having designated another
15 empowerment zones,'' she said of expansions ordered late last
year for that program by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   HUD's deputy general counsel Howard B. Glaser, objecting to some
of Gaffney's descriptions, said in an interview that the department
had already reformed itself. But Gaffney said that ``no one knows
if it's going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare dramatically reduced improper payments for
fee-for-service from $20 billion in 1997, but it still paid $12.6
billion for improper billings in 1998, reported June Gibbs Brown,
inspector general for the Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Tuesday, Brown credited a government
crackdown plus more cooperation from hospitals for reducing the
problem in the fee-for-service billings. ``Nevertheless, we still
have a long way to go,'' she told the House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Burton called the trend ``encouraging'' but said the level of
problem payments was ``still unacceptable'' and totalled enough to
buy a personal computer for every third- and fourth-grader in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture holds $12 billion in
delinquent debt from mortgages in a lending system that is rife
with conflicts-of-interest, said that department's inspector
general Roger C. Viadero. He acknowledged that, in some cases, loan
recipients help decide who receives the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Food stamp fraud is also a top problem, Viadero said. New
electronic debit cards, now being phased in, are more difficult to
misuse than paper food stamps, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Viadero told Burton that the debit cards don't track
purchases to verify whether recipients are buying beer, cigarettes
or other ineligible items.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, how much money do we want to put into it?''
the inspector general said of the electronic system. He said that
with the new card system, his investigators found $12 million in
food stamp fraud in five New Jersey counties over five months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
