<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Some legislators' reaction to attack on food tax was rotten  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports of the demise of Kansas Rep. Cliff Franklin's popularity
may be as exaggerated as those of Mark Twain's death more than a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   After the Merriam Republican last week led an effort resulting
in a House vote approving elimination of the Kansas sales tax on
food, the buzz in Topeka was that Franklin's brash move had made
him unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   What the buzzsters overlooked, however, was that unhappiness
with Franklin wasn't all that widespread. It certainly didn't
include the 86 House members responsible for a 70 percent
bipartisan majority voting in favor of the bill that carried
Franklin's controversial amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Those with whom Franklin had become unpopular, however, weren't
bashful about expressing their displeasure. One colleague called
him clumsy. Another reportedly stopped speaking to Franklin. The
House speaker called Franklin's action ``the poorest display of
statesmanship I've ever seen.'' The words ``irresponsible'' and
``affront'' were also heard.
</P>
<P>
   The worst censure, it's worth noting, came from the
Legislature's leadership. Since they can make life hard for
Franklin, this gives his stand a heroic quality.
</P>
<P>
   All of which Franklin greeted stoically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd get myself in a little trouble, (but) some issues
are worth taking arrows for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What terrible act did Franklin commit to deserve such opprobrium
from some of the Legislature's most powerful movers and shakers?
</P>
<P>
   He stood up for the best interests of those who elected him to
office.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, like most anyone able to tell the difference between
right and wrong, knows it's wrong for government to enrich itself
from the sale of the food needed to sustain human life. What
distinguishes Franklin is that he's a politician conscientious
enough to act on this awareness. As a result, he has crusaded for
some time against the Kansas sales tax on groceries.
</P>
<P>
   He and legislators of a like mind haven't prevailed because the
tax generates well over 200 million bucks a year in revenue. If
Kansas political leaders did the right thing and ended the grocery
tax, they'd feel obligated to rearrange things in a way that didn't
``cost'' the state money. The process of keeping things ``revenue
neutral'' might discombobulate some special interests apparently
considered more worthy of consideration than all the Kansans who
buy groceries on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Those angry at Franklin are upset because he violated protocol
by forcing a potentially embarrassing tax issue into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   How do we know his detractors care more about their own agendas
than they care about Kansans for whom the food tax is an
abomination? We know this because when they criticize Franklin,
they don't address his proposal's merits. Small wonder. Who, after
all, would be foolish enough to attempt to defend the indefensible?
</P>
<P>
   Thus frustrated, they try to deflect attention from the
righteousness of Franklin's cause by focusing on how he put them in
an uncomfortable spot politically.
</P>
<P>
   For the establishment protectors of the status quo, Franklin's
initiative is like a dead cat someone threw on their doorstep.
There's simply no way to get rid of it without the chore becoming
an unpleasant bit of business.
</P>
</TEXT>
