<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: PRECIOUS CARGO; BAUSCH WINS DANCE AWARD; SARGENT
DRAWINGS ON DISPLAY; CELEBRATING BLACK COMPOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Germany)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two units at a time, in unmarked vans and limousines, the cargo
was transported to the Performing Arts Center at Purchase College
in Purchase, N.Y. Heavily insured, the cargo consisted of 30 of the
world's most precious violins _ 15 by Antonio Stradivari
(1644-1737) and 15 by Giuseppe Guarneri, known as del Gesu
(1698-1744).
</P>
<P>
   In late 1994, the concert violinist Elmar Oliveira was recorded
playing 15 pieces by composers like Bloch, J.S. Bach, Brahms and
Paganini, first on a Stradivari and then on a Guarneri. Afterward
he played all 30 instruments sequentially in an excerpt from
Sibelius' Violin Concerto in D minor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening at Steinway Hall in New York, at a gathering to
celebrate the release of the CDs ``The Miracle Makers,'' by Bein &AMP;
Fushi, the Chicago dealers and restorers who organized the project,
Oliveira will play five of the violins.
</P>
<P>
   Honor Bound
</P>
<P>
   Pina Bausch, who achieved international fame as the director and
choreographer of the Tanztheater Wuppertal of Germany, has been
named the winner of the 1999 Samuel H. Scripps American Dance
Festival Award honoring lifetime achievement in modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   The $25,000 prize will be presented by Harvey Lichtenstein,
president of the Brooklyn Academy of Music, in ceremonies on June
20 at Duke University in Durham, N.C., the home of the American
Dance Festival. Among past recipients of the award are Martha
Graham, Merce Cunningham and Alvin Ailey.
</P>
<P>
   Time for Sargents
</P>
<P>
   Tapping its permanent collection, the Corcoran Gallery of Art in
Washington will open an exhibition on Saturday of more than 70
drawings by John Singer Sargent (1856-1925). Rare early drawings,
several large-scale portraits and preparatory studies for late
murals in Boston are features of this show, continuing through May
9 and timed to coincide with a major retrospective of Sargent's
paintings and watercolors from Feb. 21 to May 31 in Washington at
the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Lights
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Classical composers of African heritage will be the
focus of a concert at the 92nd Street Y Tisch Center for the Arts
at 3 p.m. on Sunday as part of ``The Singer's Art'' series and as a
commemorative event in Black History Month. Featuring the
mezzo-soprano Florence Quivar and the pianist Wayne Sanders, ``A
Celebration of Black Composers'' will comprise works in the
classical, operatic and art-song styles, as well as modern
arrangements of spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the composers are England's Samuel Coleridge-Taylor; Henry
Thacker Burleigh, whose mentor was Dvorak, and William Grant Still,
the first African-American to have a symphony performed by a major
orchestra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
