<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHES-PLATH-930(2TAK     02-10 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHES-PLATH-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXES OPEN, AND HUGHES SEEMS AS REAL AS PLATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (Eds: The Hughes poem `Perfect Light' is included at the end of the
2nd take.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For all the notoriety and ugliness that made them the
century's most talked-about literary couple and divided their
admirers into warring camps, the poets Ted Hughes and Sylvia Plath
will remain forever intertwined in the boxes of documents now
emerging from the darkness here at the Emory University library.
</P>
<P>
   Emory, which began buying Hughes' collected papers two years ago
as part of its growing archive of English and Irish writers, has
now begun to catalog and release some of the most important
documents to scholars, just as interest in the British poet
laureate is increasing with the publication of his confessional
``Birthday Letters'' and his death last year.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Hughes' independent reputation has begun to rise,
the papers lead inevitably backward to his seven-year marriage to
Plath, which ended with their separation and her suicide in 1963.
After the publication of her autobiographical novel, ``The Bell
Jar,'' and ``Ariel,'' a posthumous collection of poetry, the
American poet became a feminist icon of victimization, with Hughes
blamed by some for her depression and death.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after her death, Hughes never spoke publicly about
Plath even as he edited and published her work and never publicly
tried to defend himself before her partisans, quietly plowing his
own deep furrow as a symbolist poet in the face of what he
privately called ``Hurricane Sylvia.''
</P>
<P>
   A new trove of letters and papers recently acquired by Emory,
however, show the immense weight that her death held over Hughes in
the next decades, along with the similar suicide in 1969 of the
woman for whom he left Plath, Assia Wevill, who killed their
2-year-old daughter at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep writing this and that, but it seems pitifully little
for the time I spend pursuing it,'' he wrote to a close friend,
Lucas Myers, in 1984. ``I wonder sometimes if things might have
gone differently without the events of '63 and '69. I have an idea
of these two episodes as giant steel doors shutting down over great
parts of myself. Leaving me that much less, just was left, to live
on. No doubt a more resolute artist would have penetrated the steel
doors. But I believe big physical changes happen at those times,
big self-anesthesias. Maybe life isn't long enough to wake up from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jottings in a well-thumbed notebook show him recalling dreams he
has had of Plath, imagining her returning to life to see the
couple's two children, then slipping away again into permanent
sleep. He scrawled poems on the backsides of her own works, using
her old manuscripts in an act of recycling that kept their words
microns away from one another. Hughes seemed to long to separate
his wife's memory from the immense literary industry that had grown
up around her, which he refers to as an ``octopus,'' and struggles
to break out of the ``pyramid tomb of oppression'' produced by the
world's interest in Plath.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this agony is reflected in the poems collected in the
``Birthday Letters,'' his first published work about Plath, which
recently won the Whitbread Prize in England. But Stephen Enniss,
curator of literary collections at the Robert W. Woodruff Library
here at Emory, said the new material would still be a revelation to
Hughes scholars and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is thought of by critics as being so self-protective and so
unrevealing of himself, but here we can finally see the burden that
he lived with,'' said Enniss, who has been going through some
two-and-a-half tons of papers for the last two years. ``Everyone
always imagined the cost to him personally, but it's remarkable to
encounter his own description of it. I think the archive will make
him appear more human, more sympathetic than the detached voice and
aloofness we had known.''
</P>
<P>
   The archive also includes numerous unpublished drafts of Hughes'
poems, along with uncategorized jottings, photos and legal
documents. These include Plath's passport (showing a beaming
``Sylvia Hughes'' and marked ``Canceled, holder died''), her death
certificate and the couple's marriage license. Enniss said he might
have found some previously undiscovered poems of Plath on the back
of some of Hughes' work but that he had not yet been able to
determine whether they were new.
</P>
<P>
   The papers cast considerable light on Hughes' method of work,
his fascination with natural and occult symbols (he drew a zodiac
wheel on one of Plath's poems) and the sources of inspiration for
the ``Birthday Letters,'' all of which has produced considerable
excitement among Hughes and Plath scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Wood Middlebrook, a professor of English at Stanford
University, said the documents seemed to confirm a theory of hers
that Hughes wrote the ``Birthday Letters'' while assembling Plath's
papers for sale to Smith College, with many of the poems inspired
by specific letters, poems or photographs of her. One poem in the
collection, ``Perfect Light,'' is clearly based on a 1962 photo of
Plath holding the couple's two children in a field of daffodils
behind their home in the west of England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed by the fact that someone who was so private in
life decided not to destroy things of this kind,'' said Ms.
Middlebrook, a biographer of the poet Anne Sexton who recently
wrote an introduction to a new edition of ``The Bell Jar'' and is
planning a book on Hughes. ``I can't wait to see more of this
archive: it's a real jewel of a collection.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Plath, there is page after page of undiluted Hughes _
painstakingly writing out his poems on the insides of envelopes,
the margins of notebooks, the reverse side of the ``Bell Jar''
typescript. Many of the unpublished poems are from one of his
best-loved periods, when he was writing about Crow, a dark
incarnation of the natural life force. Scholars hope that once they
are published and biographies based on the papers are written,
Hughes will be seen as one of the century's giants, alone in his
own portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people are just about exhausting their interest in
Hughes considered as the husband of Plath and starting to take an
interest in Hughes as a great poet, quite apart from her,'' said
Keith Sagar, a leading English scholar of Hughes and a close friend
for many years. `` `Birthday Letters' is a wonderful book, but the
reason it has sold so well is because it casts the reader into the
role of voyeur. Where were all the readers, where were all the
prizes when Hughes was writing some of the greatest books in the
English language back in the 1970s?''
</P>
<P>
   `Perfect Light'
</P>
<P>
   There you are, in all your innocence,
</P>
<P>
   Sitting among your daffodils, as in a picture
</P>
<P>
   Posed as for the title: `Innocence.'
</P>
<P>
   Perfect light in your face lights it up
</P>
<P>
   Like a daffodil. Like any one of those daffodils
</P>
<P>
   It was to be your only April on earth
</P>
<P>
   Among your daffodils. In your arms,
</P>
<P>
   Like a teddy bear, your new son,
</P>
<P>
   Only a few weeks into his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and infant, as in the Holy portrait.
</P>
<P>
   And beside you, laughing up at you,
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter, barely two. Like a daffodil
</P>
<P>
   You turn your face down to her, saying something.
</P>
<P>
   Your words were lost in the camera.
</P>
<P>
   And the knowledge
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hill on which you are sitting,
</P>
<P>
   A moated fort hill, bigger than your house,
</P>
<P>
   Failed to reach the picture. While your next moment,
</P>
<P>
   Coming towards you like an infantryman
</P>
<P>
   Returning slowly out of no-man's-land,
</P>
<P>
   Bowed under something, never reached you _
</P>
<P>
   Simply melted into the perfect light.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Birthday Letters,'' a collection of poetry by Ted
Hughes (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 1998)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
