<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-A     02-10 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARTHA GRAHAM: FINDING FRESHNESS IN WORKS OF THE '40s  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(bl) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no doubt that Martha Graham is as
old-fashioned as Shakespeare. Anyone shopping around for depth and
universal resonance in the dance world would have to turn to works
like ``Appalachian Spring'' and ``Herodiade,'' two great Graham
works of the 1940s. When they were performed for the first time in
the Martha Graham Dance Company's current season at the Joyce
Theater, on Tuesday night, they were also magnificently danced.
</P>
<P>
   On the novelty side, there was a strange grab bag of a suite
entitled ``Duets for Martha.'' The four duets included
``Histoire,'' a very fine premiere by Lucinda Childs that would
have looked good in a movie by Antonioni, and the U.S. premiere of
an excerpt from Maurice Bejart's ``Notre Faust.'' Two friends of
the company helped out. Robert Wilson was represented by ``Shaker
Interior,'' an excerpt from ``Snow on the Mesa,'' which he created
for the troupe in 1995. After Graham died in 1991, Twyla Tharp was
the first outside choreographer to do a piece for the company,
which was ``Demeter and Persephone'' (1993). But here she was
represented by a duet from the familiar ``Nine Sinatra Songs,''
danced by two guests from American Ballet Theater, John Selya and
Ashley Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us, however, might prefer the old hat to the latest
beanie. Genius produced ``Appalachian Spring'' and ``Herodiade,''
and they have worn particularly well. You can even hear an excerpt
from Aaron Copland's score for ``Appalachian Spring'' in a TWA
commercial nowadays. The Library of Congress, through its
distinguished patron Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge, commissioned the
Copland score and the music by Paul Hindemith for ``Herodiade.'' To
see the two works on the same program is to recall that they had
their premieres on the same program at the library in Washington in
1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appalachian Spring,'' is familiar in its image of a pioneer
couple's frontier optimism. But ``Herodiade'' remains an
experimental, enigmatic work. The heroine onstage, attended by a
faithful maid servant, prepares to meet an unnamed destiny. But the
specifics are never described. Graham is often at her best when she
is at her most hermetic. ``Herodiade'' is a piece to be absorbed
through the pores rather than the brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine appears to be looking deep into herself. The conceit
is that she is looking into a mirror, evoked by Isamu Noguchi's
striking frame of skeletal shapes, augmented by his sculptured
chair and cloak rack. Certainly Terese Capucilli suggested that she
was involved in an interior dialogue, looking at bones, her
essential self. Advancing and retreating, she violently threw off
Denise Vale's entreaties. Ms. Capucilli shed her outer dress, which
this season is modeled after Graham's loose gray gown with purple
fabric. Purified in a white robe, she wrapped herself in a cloak;
the light caugt her head, dangling backward.
</P>
<P>
   To digest the dance into a date with death would be to ignore
the layers of meaning in Graham's universe. Hindemith named his
score after a poem by Mallarme, but Graham rejected its theme of a
queen of antiquity meditating upon her chastity. In her exploration
of legends, Graham was always probing the psyche of our time. Ms.
Capucilli's acceptance of life through age and death is embodied in
articulate turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   There is a stunning kinetic precision to her movement: energy is
channeled into rage. But Ms. Capucilli no longer turns away in
revulsion from what she sees in the ``mirror.'' It is rather her
determination that colors the entire performance. By contrast, Ms.
Vale's sorrowful nurse is striking in its quiet earthiness and the
beauty of every gesture. One has to look quickly to see how the
attendant takes off her mistress' invisible shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Younger performers were seen in ``Appalachian Spring,'' and here
one commends Miki Orihara for the gorgeous freshness of her dancing
as the frontier bride. She needs only to nuance her two solos so
that the dynamics do not look the same. Katherine Crockett, as the
pioneering woman, was a true voice of wisdom, knowing how to make
her gesture grand without being grandiose.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men this season are new and have yet to reach the
women's polished level of execution. But Tadej Brdnik's husbandman
caught the spirit of his role and he and Ms. Orihara offered a true
love duet. Peter Roel, more of a veteran, got his vain preacher off
to a dramatic start but needs to make his solo less small-scale.
The preacher's followers, Elizabeth Auclair, Sandra Kaufmann,
Virginie Mecene and Alessandra Prosperi kept the faith and the form
of Graham's idiom.
</P>
<P>
   As for the duets, Ms. Childs had Roel and Ms. Capucilli face in
opposite directions, side by side, before she expanded upon this
idea. In chic dark brown costumes by Suzanne Gallo and Ronaldus
Shamask, the pair resembled a sophisticated couple working out a
relationship that left them where they began. The back-to-back
image was the theme and the variations moved beyond the original
walking. Ms. Capucilli and Roel had a superb worldly polish and
their versatility in a different idiom was admirable. This is a gem
of a piece with the right score, Krzysztof Knittel's ``Histoire
III'' for a harpsichord and tape.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lofsnes was the devil in red tights and Kenneth Topping
was Faust in black tights, involved in some sort of symmetrical
encounter in ``Notre Faust,'' to music by Liszt. The Wilson duet,
out of context, suggested an encounter between a geisha and a
clown, and Rika Okamoto and Daniel Cardoso were amusing in it. Ms.
Tuttle and Selya were brief and smooth in the Tharp duet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
