<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      02-10 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: BE AN ART EXPERT IN FIVE MINUTES! 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it is the tremendous popularity of the ``For Dummies''
series that has made a grail of the idea that art, like the
alphabet, must be intellectually obtainable by anyone with the
least possible thought and effort. Now that quest for instant
accessibility _ some might say it's simply a dumbing-down frenzy _
has, alas, spread into the publication of art books. Many would
argue that mystery and complexity are often the essence of great
art.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, bartending, beauty secrets, basketball, personal
finance: all have lent themselves in the popular books in the
``Dummies'' (and its competing ``Idiot's'') approach. So it's not
altogether surprising that that most venerable publisher of art
books, Harry N. Abrams Inc., in partnership with the Wonderland
Press, has created a sort of Cliff Notes of art. That is, a series
of books of almost primitive simplicity with ``The Essential'' in
the title, like ``The Essential Jackson Pollock'' and ``The
Essential Vincent van Gogh.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams publishes some of the most elegant and sophisticated art
books and museum exhibition catalogs. Paul Gottlieb, its president,
publisher and editor in chief, said that he certainly did not
consider ``The Essentials'' (there are also a Dali and a Hopper in
print and four more to come this spring) ``a dumbing down, and we
would resist any attempt to dumb down.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes ``The Essential'' reader as ``a person who knows
virtually no more than that van Gogh was an artist worth knowing
and understanding, and yet it's very difficult to understand why
he's important to know about.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that these are books for people who might
otherwise never be exposed to art but will experience it because of
this series. There's something to be said for that since, for
instance, it wasn't until quite recently that art education was
reintroduced into New York City's public schools after nearly a
quarter-century of absence, Gottlieb said. Of course, another
justification is money. Some 20,000 to 30,000 copies of each of the
four ``Essentials'' are in print, and they sell for $12.95 though
bookstores, gift shops, book clubs and gift and school-supply
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   The books, each 112 pages, are written by the art smart (the
authors are all critics, and one is a freelance curator as well)
for the art dumb. But while the words may be embarrassingly
rudimentary at times, their printing and the reproduction of the
artwork are in the high-quality tradition of Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Are these ``Essentials'' an incentive to study art or merely
empty lowbrow calories? Will they inspire someone to go to a
museum? Obviously they are mostly for schoolchildren, but one
imagines they have other uses. If you know naught about art but
have a blind date with someone you have been told is an art buff,
perhaps you can read an ``Essential'' for a quick fix, to give you
something to talk about at dinner. (But suppose you read Pollock
and your date is into van Gogh or Hopper?)
</P>
<P>
   At their worst (and perhaps at their best, too) the books
provide art education through one-liners, sometimes with an
attitude that, if not snide, is flip and condescending.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in listing the artistic innovations of Pollock's
work, there are six pithy paragraphs with these headings, all in
capital letters:
</P>
<P>
   1. New! Larger-Size Canvas for Abstract
</P>
<P>
   2. New! Physical Presence of the Painting
</P>
<P>
   3. New! Painterly Vocabulary
</P>
<P>
   4. New for This Year! Gestural Automatism (Huh?)
</P>
<P>
   5. New and Improved! De-emphasis of the Frame
</P>
<P>
   6. All-New Idea! The Painting as Optical Field.
</P>
<P>
   And the books are stippled with put-downs for the reader as
dunce, i.e.: ``Hello! _ It's paint on canvas!''; ``you get the
picture''; ``van Gogh's first work, very Dutch: cabbages and
clogs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's art education by sound bite, and indeed scattered
throughout each book under the rubric ``Sound Byte'' are meaningful
pronouncements like ``Starting a painting is starting an argument
in terms of canvas and paint,'' an observation by the artist and
author John Graham.
</P>
<P>
   There are some other easy-to-understand, relatively short
paperback art series books of a much higher level, including the
``Discovery'' series, of which Abrams is a publisher, and Thames &AMP;
Hudson's ``World of Art'' series.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the dumbing down of art books and criticism is a
concern to many art critics and historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``With few exceptions the middle discourse has disappeared,''
said David Hickey, a critic for Art Forum magazine and a teacher of
art criticism at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas. ``Either the
writing has become so popularized or so hyper-professional. The use
of regular adult English prose about art has almost totally
disappeared. It's now either popularizing by journalists just
throwing stuff together or academics who have their own agendas and
careers to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not complete agreement on this. Peter Plagens, the art
critic for Newsweek, said that he found ``The Essential Vincent van
Gogh'' ``fairly witty and incisive and useful.'' But the owner of
an important art bookstore, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that books like ``The Essentials'' really don't educate.
``They're designed to be a social prop, and that's exactly the
market they are aimed for,'' the store owner said. ``People would
get a better feeling for art paying half the money of one these
books and walking through the doors of a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to make these art books, like the ``Dummies'' books,
so user friendly that they will seduce people with their easy
obviousness. But art is not about assuagement.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Varnedoe, the chief curator of painting and sculpture at
the Museum of Modern Art, said, ``Often there's something difficult
and demanding, and often there's something dangerous about art.
It's mystery, and it's challenging.'' Varnedoe, who wrote the
material for the accessible but sophisticated and highly praised
catalog for the Modern's recent Pollock exhibition (published by
Abrams), said he didn't ``want to handicap art books,'' and
declined to comment about any.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the Modern's understanding of what is truly
essential about Pollock can best be appreciated by what's on sale
in the museum's bookstore. There are Pollock scarves and Pollock
tote bags and, in addition to the catalog, about 10 book titles on
the artist. What isn't being sold is ``The Essential Jackson
Pollock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
