<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS11-COX     02-10 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another generation gap developing
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Move over X, make way for Y _ Generation Y, that is.
</P>
<P>
   According to Business Week (Feb. 15), marketers are beginning to
cope with the needs and wants of today's teens, the children of the
Baby Boom generation. At 60 million strong, they make up the
biggest population group other than the 72 million members of the
post-World War II boomer generation.
</P>
<P>
   Born roughly between 1979 and 1994, members of Generation Y
appear to be indifferent to some of the biggest, most successful
brand names of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a gulf between the tastes of boomers and their
offspring. If boomers like baseball, their children choose
skateboards; if boomers liked the Beatles, Generation Y members
like the Spice Girls; if boomers are politically active, their
children are big on community volunteering; if boomers like a Lexus
LS400, the kids will take the Jeep Wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   FIRSTS OF A DIFFERENT KIND
</P>
<P>
   February is a milestone month for two Atlanta-based business
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Trend is out with its first issue under the ownership of
developer Thomas G. Cousins and journalist Neely Young. They
acquired the 14-year-old magazine from Grimes Publications of
Athens. House speaker Tom Murphy is the subject of the magazine's
first cover story under new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Business to Business, launched in 1997 as a quarterly, becomes a
monthly publication with its February edition. It's published by
the Leader Publishing Group, headed by Chief Executive Officer Gina
Wright. The first cover story as a monthly looks at ``women in the
boardroom'' _ and asks ``why aren't we seeing more?''
</P>
<P>
   WORTH MENTIONING...
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor says it's not too late to get on the big-cap
bandwagon, featuring stocks such as Microsoft, Coca-Cola, or
Pfizer, to mention a few. ...Bloomberg Personal Finance says much
the same thing about technology stocks generally. They are ``wildly
volatile,'' but one good strategy is to ``buy the big brand names,
firms that have a No. 1 position in a growing field of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
