<HEADLINE>
TEJANO MUSICIANS DEFINED A TIME AND PLACE IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walk and drive around north Fort Worth, just south of the
Stockyards, with Leo Saenz and you can almost hear the ghosts of a
million long-ago Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   There, on Main Street, is where the honky-tonks were; music
poured out of the first-floor doorways, and the shadier goings-on
were upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away is the site of the old paper plant, which
provided a living for scores of families. And over there was the
Mona Lisa Club, where ``everybody'' played and danced and had fun.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeding over to the corner of Northeast 14th Street and North
Commerce Street, Saenz points out the old San Jose Catholic Church
and its Catholic Men's Club, where the Mexican-American community
gathered for quinceaneras and dances and weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Saenz is pointing all this out, at least in part, to make a
point: The music made back in the '50s and '60s by men like his
father, Nicho, Dick Pacheco and Joe Rodriguez has never been
properly documented or appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these guys, their sons played, too,'' says Saenz, who
began playing drums in his father's band and founded Latin Express,
Cowtown's premier Latin band. ``So a lot of people got their start
because of these guys. I decided I wanted to be a horn player
listening to Dickie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people got their start because of these guys,'' he
says. ``People think Tejano just came around, but these brothers
were knocking it down in the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the older musicians say, there weren't that many
bands. They played to supplement their day-job incomes. And back in
the '50s, they say, segregation was prevalent: A Mexican-American
who crossed over to the west side of Main Street risked a beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of racism, and not that many places to go and
get together,'' says Nicho Saenz. ``I remember that real clear. The
community was small, and we'd get together at the (Catholic Men's)
Club. We'd play the weddings and festivals.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco remembers hooking up with Rodriguez and Nicho Saenz back
in the mid-'50s; they had one amplifier and one microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go down to Ennis and Corsicana,'' he says, ``and play for
the field workers, the cotton-pickers. We didn't have all the
equipment they have now, but we'd get by.''
</P>
<P>
   The musicians worked hard for little money; several of them
recall ``ping-pong'' nights, when two bands would be booked to the
Rocket Ballroom and the Casino. They'd do a set at one venue and
have 15 minutes to get to the other, where the other band had just
played. Then they'd switch again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   And in doing so, they showed the younger musicians, such as Leo
and Carlos, the ropes. Then the younger generation carried on the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the musicians from back in the '50s, such as Pacheco,
still play. Others don't, having given up the long nights and smoky
bars. But all of them, Leo Saenz says, deserve to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to have regular summit meetings of the old guys, and
eventually record them, before their music is lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna play all the old songs,'' he says. ``It's a
spiritual thing. We need a venue for these old guys. They deserve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
