<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADISON11-COX     02-10 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADISON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trading suspension leaves investors in limbo, too
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier and David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trading suspensions ordered by the Securities and
Exchange Commission on five small companies with a connection to
Madison, Ga., are to end at 11:59 tonight. But before trading in
the stocks can resume, the companies would have to make more
information available to investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, investors like Chuck Martin of Pittsburgh and
Phuong Lee of San Jose, Calif., are stuck with stocks they can't
sell, and on which they've already lost money.
</P>
<P>
   They have something else in common: both have been investing in
stocks for a very short time.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, the 41-year-old Martin had never bought a
stock. He was led to Citron Inc. _ one of the suspended stocks _
from an Eric Clapton online fan club. There was a message on the
site that Citron was providing a link to a Web site for Crossroads,
a rehabilitation facility Clapton helped establish in Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been looking at investing in Internet stocks since they
had really taken off, and here was one that looked like it was
trying to help a rehab facility,'' said Martin. ``I thought, this
sounds like a good company, this sounds like some honest people.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 26, he bought $1,000 worth of Citron at $39 a share and
$1,000 of Electronic Transfer Associates Inc. at $30 a share. Three
days later, the SEC suspended trading in those two companies as
well as in Polus Inc., Smartek Inc. and Invest Holdings Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions were ordered because the SEC had questions about
the accuracy of information released by the companies. All had used
a Madison phone number at 115 South Main St. as a contact in their
press releases. All are believed to have been based elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The last available stock quote for Citron was $9.93 3/4. For
Electronic Transfer Associates, it was $14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm smart enough to know that when you play with stocks you
have to be ready to take the hit,'' Martin said. ``But it's made me
want to puke.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a 40-year-old software engineer, stands to lose even more
than Martin, a former FedEx employee.
</P>
<P>
   She bought 800 shares of Citron at $25 each and 930 shares at
$22, all on Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had been investing only since last fall, and said she bought
Citron after hearing about it from a friend. Lee said she looked
for information about the company, but couldn't find any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do a very good investigation,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's rule dictating under what conditions trading in a
suspended stock can resume is designed to make available
information that might have helped Martin and Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Before stock brokers and dealers can offer to buy or sell a
stock that has been suspended, or indicate they are interested in
buying or selling, they to have specific information from the
company, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The exact name of the company and its predecessor, if any.
</P>
<P>
   _ The address of its principal executive offices.
</P>
<P>
   _ The state of incorporation, if it is a corporation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of shares or total amount of the securities
outstanding at the end of the company's most recent fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The name and address of the transfer agent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A description of the company's business.
</P>
<P>
   _ The nature of the products or services it sells.
</P>
<P>
   _ The names of the chief executive officer and members of the
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The most recent balance sheet and profit and loss and retained
earnings statements, and similar financial information for the past
two fiscal years, or for whatever part of the two years the company
was in existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is designed to insure that reasonable current
financial information is available for investors to make an
intelligent decision about the investment merits of the company,''
said J. Michael Bishop, a partner with the Atlanta law firm of Page
&AMP; Bacek LLP.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a specialist in securities arbitration and litigation,
noted there is an exception to the rule. Brokers and deals can
offer to buy or sell a stock that has been suspended, even if they
don't have the specific information cited in the rule. They can do
so if an investor goes unsolicited to the broker and wants to buy
or sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop also noted: ''The broker or dealer would want to be
cautious in entering a (stock) quotation, since it is unlawful for
a broker to submit the quotation unless he is in strict compliance
with the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
