<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCUM WHAT MAY, MOM'S THE CLEAN MACHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Settling back into the brown, faux-Naugahyde seats on the big
yellow bus, those of us who had volunteered to chaperone the
elementary-school field trip were startled to notice a large silver
box secured to the bus's interior, just above the windshield and to
the left of the first-aid kit. ``For Clean Up of Bodily Fluids''
the label said. ``Eeeeuuuwwhh,'' we squealed collectively. ``What
do you think that means?''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, we already knew. Because we were all mothers.
The unhailed, underappreciated, destined-to-become patron saints of
bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
   My own full-body immersion into the flow of fluids began soon
after my son Jack's birth, when I was unofficially baptized into
the Divine Order of Dripping Nostrils, Dirty Diapers, Ear Wax and
Nonstop Drool. My son ruined every shirt I owned, depositing chunky
sour milk stains on the shoulders. I started wiping his viscous
drool across my jeans with ease. I handled weighty, wet diapers
with aplomb. I perhaps suspected that all these fluids were
disgusting and that I should have been repulsed. But I didn't see
Gross. I just saw Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Then we moved into toddlerhood.
</P>
<P>
   The level of challenges increased. At this stage on the road to
sainthood, I began, as all mothers do, to dedicate my days to the
service of my preschooler. I began to cut off phone conversations
without warning so I could clean up potty-training accidents. I
woke up, cranky but without fail, for middle-of-the-night bed linen
changes, and I learned to pull snot from my toddler's tiny little
nose during the day and to extract boogers that threatened his
breathing at night. I stocked up on paper towels, diaper wipes and
cleansing agents with bleach and scrubbing bubbles and other battle
agents. No longer the naive novitiate, I found myself smiling
serenely most of the time, as I learned to almost-kiss a slightly
infected boo-boo to make it all better.
</P>
<P>
   I was becoming a seasoned mother, a fact that became apparent to
me only when I leaned across a restaurant table one afternoon to
wipe an especially ugly sleep particle out of a good friend's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting the fluids, my immunities to them gathered strength,
which was good, I suppose, because when my son hit first grade, we
moved steadily into the realm of the extremely vile. Accidents and
illnesses will happen, of course, but at this age kids become
fascinated by the release of bodily fluids and actually even
encourage it. To this day, I carry a mental map of my own
elementary school and can tell you exactly who vomited on which
sets of stairs and when. I remember nothing about a boy named
Steven who was in my second-grade class except that that was his
name, I think, and that he once failed to make it to the
first-floor boys' room on time. My ex-husband liked to recall his
own fifth-grade year, when he and his friends would chug 2-liter
bottles of Coke just for the satisfaction of seeing who would throw
up first.
</P>
<P>
   As my son entered the same wonder years, I knew to expect tests
of a mother's love that would reach biblical proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can never be fully prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Take one night last week, when Jack was running a high fever and
had gone into the bathroom to brush his teeth before bed. I picked
up a glass of water that looked as if it had undissolved particles
of Crystal Light mix on top. Thinking that Jack must have gotten
himself a glass of lemonade (a sign of self-sufficiency at last!),
I picked up the glass to take a sip just as Jack slumped back into
the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack, what's in here anyway?'' I asked, the glass's rim inches
from my lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's just some throw-up,'' my child explained as he
crawled back under his comforter.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges on the road to sainthood have been both sacred
and sick. I've held my feverish child in bed to comfort him and
been suddenly deluged with this morning's breakfast. I've
sequestered myself with my child in a men's room of a McDonald's
off a highway in Maryland when I heard Jack calling from inside
that he was sick and needed help cleaning up _ and could I bring
some new clothes? I've held Jack's hand with a forced smile on my
face as blood streamed across his cheek from a gouge that would
require seven stitches.
</P>
<P>
   And really, the trials are just beginning. The preadolescent
years with their coming-of-age bodily fluid issues loom before me
as walking-on-coals tests of faith that no amount of Formula 409
can handily wipe away.
</P>
<P>
   Get halo ready.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
