<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-AFFLICTION-TEX     02-10 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFLICTION-TEX </SLUG>
 
Nick Nolte's mastery commands this woeful tale 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIW MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doom seems inevitable in writer//director Paul Schrader's
adaptation of Russell Banks' novel ``Affliction.'' Snowbound, the
small New Hampshire town where the story is set, is bleak and
unforgiving. Spiritually, it's a backdrop that Schrader, as the
writer of ``Taxi Driver'' and the writer//director of ``American
Gigolo'' and ``Light Sleeper,'' has used almost all his career.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, his protagonist doesn't exist as a solitary
figure, an alienated loner in a sleek, grim city. Instead, Schrader
drops us into the burg that Wade (Nick Nolte) can't escape and
shows us the damage that led to his main figure's current state.
</P>
<P>
   As Wade, the lawman, Nolte is determined, decent, but lost. He's
almost incapable of doing the right thing. Trying to get to the
bottom of a hunting-related death, Wade is well-meaning, but all
his gestures are abrasive. He can't help rubbing people the wrong
way, being insistent when he shouldn't be. It's as if he were born
with no spaces between his fingers. Burly and big-spirited, he
shambles into a crime scene, or a kids' Halloween party, where it's
evident that even his little girl is wary around him. An ominous
narration by Wade's brother (Willem Dafoe), who had fled their
hometown, tellingly frames the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' is a little rough around the edges. Partially
because Nolte, who received a Best Actor nomination for this role,
is so good that the rest of the movie seems a little threadbare.
Canada was substituted for New England, and many of the actors have
accents and a genteel quality that sticks out. (As with many other
pictures, Canada was used because it's cheaper.) But Schrader's
ease with actors has increased. ``Affliction'' is affecting because
it doesn't feel nearly as schematic, or inexorable, as it might.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Glen (James Coburn) _ Wade's abusive, constantly drunk
father _ enters the picture. Despite his Best Supporting Actor
nomination, Coburn's badly used here. He's all elbows and grimace.
He's the wrong actor for a part like this _ fury and soiled
bitterness. In flashbacks, when we first see him, Glen snarls and
belts his boys, and it's painful to watch. Schrader has built so
painstakingly toward this revelation that we want Glen to match
Wade more convincingly. Coburn's facility is polish and slickness;
we don't quite buy him. Though in the present day, when he's
curdled and spent, Glen's more affecting _ a dying monster.
</P>
<P>
   There can't be much more than a 10-year age difference between
Nolte and Coburn, but because they're of divergent generations _
and techniques _ as actors, they're believable as father and son.
Coburn is all surface. Nolte burrows in so deep, it's as if he's
discovering his character before our eyes. He's all invention;
there's no complacency in him as an actor. Schrader has talked
about having to wait for Nolte to be available to start the picture
and that he was determined to use him. It was worth the wait.
Nolte's physical eloquence and expressiveness take up the entire
picture. He invests the film with a freshet of emotion _ a needy,
searching quality _ that we've not seen in Schrader protagonists
before. They tend to be either angry or depressive, and Wade is
both. Although he lacks self-knowledge, Wade isn't stupid, which is
why his rage causes him as much trouble as it does those around
him.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to see Sissy Spacek again _ she plays Wade's
girlfriend, a refuge from the losses inflicted on him in every
other relationship in his life. She's mostly just the understanding
woman here. Mary Beth Hurt, in a fleeting role as Wade's intolerant
ex-wife, makes a much more vivid impression. Intriguingly, it's not
just the women in Wade's life who have a perspective on him. Sadly,
everyone understands Wade all too well. It's hard to imagine that
Schrader, with his love of cold European archetypes, could show
such a keen insight into the most American of themes, the ache in
the folly of good intentions. (He and Banks are made for each other
in this case _ the story seems to have autobiographical resonance
for Schrader.) But Nolte continues in his trajectory of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' is rated R for violence, adult situations and
adult language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' 3 stars on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Paul Schrader
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Nick Nolte, James Coburn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
