<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CANDIDACY-HNS &LR;      02-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CANDIDACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MEMBERS URGE BUSH TO RUN FOR PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a dramatic quickening of the 2000 presidential
campaign, more than 50 current and former Republican members of
Congress pledged ``our commitment'' Wednesday to a White House
candidacy by George W. Bush and urged the Texas governor to enter
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Styling themselves the Draft Bush 2000 Committee, the
legislators represent constituencies from across the country as
well as across the Republican ideological spectrum, including at
least two female House members who support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis was on the party's broad conservatism in a
letter that the group drafted and is sending to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as members and former members of the U.S. House of
Representatives, committed to the Republican ideals of less
government, lower taxes, personal responsibility and a strong
national defense, hereby ask you, because of your exemplary
performance as governor of Texas and adherence to these ideals to
commit to running for the office of president of the United
States,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, the letter had been signed by 44 current
House members, one senator who is a former House member _ Ben
Nighthorse Campbell of Colorado _ and 15 former House members no
longer in national office. A spokesman said additional signatures
were being gathered and an attempt was under way to include state
and local officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   The group, led by recently retired Rep. Gerald Solomon of New
York, had been considering its course of action for some time, a
source said. It was moved to announce its formation, the source
said, by the publicity splash made recently by Elizabeth Dole, the
former Republican &UR;  &LR; Cabinet member and wife of the GOP's 1996
presidential nominee, as she moves toward formal announcement of a
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll among Republicans in New Hampshire, traditional site
of a presidential campaign's first primary, showed Dole had zoomed
into a virtual tie with Bush, who once held a commanding lead in
the New England state.
</P>
<P>
   Dole campaigned Monday in New Hampshire as the poll was being
released. She will be speaking in Houston at a sold-out charity
luncheon Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's House backers was quick with a bid to dampen
Dole's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has not been a governor, and she's never held elected
office,'' Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., told the Pueblo Chieftain
newspaper Tuesday as he announced his support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But McInnis said Dole, most recently president of the American
Red Cross, would be ``the best choice'' for Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Another draft committee source took a fairly dismissive tone
toward other possible Bush opponents for the nomination, saying
that while all of the Republican contenders would have ``good ideas
to offer. We think George W. Bush is the total package.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said the draft committee was the biggest, earliest
outpouring of House Republican support for a prospective
presidential candidate since a 1979 effort urging Ronald Reagan to
run.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, one of the other GOP prospects was Bush's father,
who subsequently was Reagan's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said the committee's effort was ``an absolutely
independent movement'' from the governor's political operation.
Solomon said he had talked with Bush several times, ``but he is not
asking me to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he will announce a decision on a presidential bid
later this year, probably after the Texas Legislature adjourns in
late spring. Bush could announce formation of a preliminary
exploratory committee sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman in Austin, Texas, said the
governor ``is honored that fellow Republican elected officials
recognize that he is a principled conservative who has proven his
ability to reach across party and gender and ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hopes they understand that he has commitments to fulfill
here in Texas,'' Hughes said. ``He is in the process of making a
decision and assures them that as quickly as possible this spring
he will announce what his decision is.''
</P>
<P>
   While some other prospective Republican candidates have
belittled Bush's call for ``compassionate conservatism,'' the
legislators hailed the governor's stance as a call to women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A message of inclusion is one which the Republican Party needs
to put forward,'' said Rep. David Dreier of California, chairman of
the House Rules Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the 13 House Republicans from Texas initially
signed the letter, part of what Rep. Pete Sessions, R-Dallas, said
was an effort to keep the list from being top-heavy with Bush's
fellow Texans. Signing the letter with Sessions were Republican
Reps. Kay Granger of Fort Worth, Joe Barton of Ennis and Sam
Johnson of Plano.
</P>
<P>
   Other states represented by signers are: Alabama, Alaska,
Arkansas, California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Iowa,
Indiana, Kentucky, Louisiana, Michigan, Nebraska, New Jersey, New
York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Dakota, Virginia,
Washington and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The signers included pro-abortion rights Reps. Jennifer Dunn,
R-Wash., and Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, one of the more
liberal House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Roukema's signing prompted the archconservative Solomon to
remark: ``When you've got everybody from Marge to me, you've got
about everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
