<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-10 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER JURY CHOSEN IN DRAGGING DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A jury of seven men and five women, including at
least one black, was picked Wednesday to decide the fate of a white
man accused of capital murder in the brutal dragging death of a
black man.
</P>
<P>
   John William ``Bill'' King, 24, is one of three white men
charged with chaining James Byrd Jr. to the back of a pickup and
dragging him about three miles along back country roads in the
early morning hours of June 7.
</P>
<P>
   It took lawyers about 20 minutes Wednesday to pick 12 jurors and
two alternates from a pool of 50 citizens certified to serve as
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden conducted the striking
process in the jury deliberation room so that news reporters
couldn't hear who was being chosen for the final pool.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said only that
the jury is ``not all white,'' refusing to say how many of the
seven black certified panel members are on the jury. Gray said
Golden wants to protect the jurors from being identified.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is scheduled to begin hearing testimony Tuesday. If
King is convicted of capital murder _ killing Byrd while kidnapping
him _ he faces either death by injection or life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's father, James Byrd Sr., said he was happy to hear that at
least one black person will be on the jury. ``I think it'll be
fair,'' he said. ``That's all we want is justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile King, who twice before has written letters to
newspapers, wrote another letter to the Jasper NewsBoy. Much of the
letter was in praise of Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheriff Rowles, I am genuinely thankful for the kindness and
generosity you have extended to my family as well as myself,'' he
wrote. ``I truly appreciate all you've done, and the lengths at
which you've gone to ease some of the stress and frustrations
during a time of despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowles said he has treated King like any other inmate. He said
the letter was ``embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowles said King, who at one time tore up his cell and broke a
television during a tantrum and once refused to leave his cell for
a court hearing, has calmed down since his trial started. The
sheriff is also letting him smoke cigarettes during court breaks.
Smoking isn't allowed in the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   During one break King also was allowed a brief visit with his
father, girlfriend and his 6-month-old child. It was the first time
he'd ever been allowed to hold his son.
</P>
<P>
   That visit prompted Byrd's mother, Stella, to say that when she
wants to visit her son she has to go to his grave.
</P>
<P>
   Trials for Shawn Allen Berry, 23, and Lawrence Russell Brewer
Jr., 31, also charged with Byrd's murder, have not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
