<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Feb. 11. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Developments on impeachment: Senators
continue deliberating behind closed doors. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars: IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LIEBERMAN,
IMPEACH-GRAMM.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-CUBANS (Miami) _ Castro has survived for so long that he
has made Miami not only a Cuban city but one where cultural clashes
are often between cubans of different generations. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report: One City, Two Cubas, 2,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo package.
</P>
<P>
   AMR-PILOTS (Undated) _ American Airlines pilots are ordered back
to work by a federal judge. The airline sought the order as their
sickout entered its fifth day, forcing the cancellation of more
than 40 percent of American's flights and inconveniencing tens of
thousands of passengers around the world. It was not immediately
clear whether or when the pilots would obey the judge's order. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA-RIGHTS (Undated) _ It sat there unused by prosecutors
for thirty years, but this week, a law passed by Congress in 1968
was dusted off by a federal appeals court in Virginia and used to
declare that federal law enforcement officials need not follow one
of the best known Supreme Court decisions of this century, Miranda
vs. Arizona, under which criminal suspects are routinely read their
rights everywhere in America. From coast to coast, prosecutors,
defense lawyers and legal experts said the ruling provided the most
serious challenge to the Miranda ruling since it was issued in
1966, and opened an unexpected debate about one of this country's
bedrock legal rules. By William Glaberson. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SALESMAN-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ In the harrowing revival of
Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman'' that opened Wednesday night
at the Eugene O'Neill Theater, 50 years to the day after it made
its epochal Broadway debut, you walk right into the mind of its
decimated hero, played with majestic, unnerving transparency by
Brian Dennehy. Reviewed by Ben Brantley. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WELFARE (London) _ Saying he's ending the era of the
``something for nothing'' welfare state, Prime Minister Tony Blair
proposes legislation requiring that anyone receiving welfare
benefits _ including housing benefits _ appear for a job interview.
By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
