<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ON CUSP OF HISTORIC VICTORY IN IMPEACHMENT FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton appeared Wednesday on the cusp of
a historic victory in his impeachment fight with Congress as three
Republican senators broke ranks to say they will vote against
conviction even as a campaign to censure the president was
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   The final Senate verdict vote on Thursday or Friday would mark
the finale to a sex scandal that has consumed the White House and
Congress for months.
</P>
<P>
   The three Republican senators who indicated they will vote
against convicting Clinton are James Jeffords of Vermont, Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania and John Chafee of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   All three said they believed the charges against Clinton weren't
sufficiently serious to merit his conviction and automatic removal
from office. The House impeached Clinton in December for perjury
and obstruction of justice in connection with the cover-up of his
sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a leader in the push
for censure as an alternative to conviction, said she may circulate
a petition among senators to allow them to indicate their support
for censure even though they won't actually have a floor vote on
censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another, it's going to see the light of day,''
Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein, who has redrafted a censure resolution more than two
dozen times, pleaded with Republicans to allow a floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on the Republican side who adamantly oppose
our ability to bring this to the floor,'' Feinstein said, adding
that they should debate censure rather than block it. ``At least
give us an opportunity to bring it to the floor. Right now that is
not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., another supporter of censure,
said censure advocates would sign a statement Friday that would
contain the same language that would have been in a censure
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is, instead of voting for it, members
would sign it'' and it would become part of the congressional
record and be sent to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Senate foes of censure, led by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, have
threatened to use parliamentary tactics to derail any vote on
censure. Graham believes a censure violates the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he would kill any censure proposal by filibustering
against it. That would require Feinstein and her allies to muster
60 votes to shut down the filibuster and it was unlikely that she
could gather that much support..
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, also signaled censure is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think censure is becoming more and more problematic and
difficult,'' Hatch said, adding that some say that Democrats ``just
want to cover their backsides'' by pushing censure so they don't
appear to approve of Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who said he was ``in a distinct
minority'' as a Republican who favors censure, said members of his
party fail to realize that a harshly worded censure would serve to
``elevate the actions of the House.'' The Republican-led House
approved two articles of impeachment against Clinton in December,
charging him with perjury and conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert J. Kerrey, D-Neb., summed up the fate of censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bird without wings,'' Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of the three Republican senators raised the
prospect that the verdict vote on Thursday could fall short of a
51-vote majority. Such an outcome would be embarrassing to
Republicans, who hold a 55-45 majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It's been apparent for weeks that the House prosecutors would
fail to win the 67 votes _ a two-thirds majority _ needed to
convict the president. A 51-percent majority in favor of conviction
would still add up to acquittal but would give House Republican
prosecutor bragging rights that even though they failed to get 67
votes, at least they persuaded a simple majority of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury article was stacking up as the weaker of the two
impeachment accusations. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., announced he
planned to vote against the perjury charge, while other Republicans
have indicated they are leaning the same way.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his plan to vote to acquit Clinton, Chafee said
House prosecutors hadn't proven their case.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee said that while the president exhibited ``reckless,
tawdry behavior,'' much of the evidence was ``conflicting'' and
doesn't rise to the standard that merits removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, another moderate, said that while the facts and
circumstances of the case are ``low and tawdry,'' they do not rise
to the level of impeachable acts. Jeffords predicted the
obstruction of justice charge would get no more than 48 votes and
that there would be ``considerably less'' support for a perjury
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords said he hoped ``we will get a very well done apology
from the president. I hope he apologizes to the children and the
women of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, announcing he won't vote for conviction, cited the laws
of Scotland for his concept that there could be ``three possible
verdicts: guilty, not guilty, not proved.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he would choose to vote ``not proved.'' He said
only ``partial justice'' was done because House prosecutors hadn't
been able to call live witnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
