<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR LEADER'S TRANSFER FROM PRISON COMES AS TALKS HEAT UP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ With Indonesia edging toward a new status
for the disputed territory of East Timor, officials Wednesday moved
the independence leader, Alexandre Gusmao, halfway to freedom,
transferring him from a prison to a barred and guarded house.
</P>
<P>
   Clenching his fist briefly in a modest salute, the trim and
bearded Gusmao said he expected to play a full role, from his new
home, in international negotiations over whether the former
Portuguese colony is to become independent or remain linked to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always optimistic about independence in East Timor,'' he
said. ``We know that negotiation on many conflicts in the world
have run for years. If all parties are not willing to reduce the
violence and hatred, the dialogues are useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of other East Timorese leaders, Gusmao, 52, who
has been in prison for seven years for his role in leading a
separatist insurgency, has recently argued against moving too
rapidly toward freedom or even toward a referendum on freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Since Indonesia invaded the remote and tiny territory in 1975,
annexing it the next year, human rights groups say, up to 200,000
people have died in fighting and human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Emotions have grown hotter, and renewed violence has flared in
recent weeks as Indonesia has, for the first time, said that it was
ready to consider loosening its grip on the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which has never recognized Indonesian
sovereignty in East Timor, is brokering talks over the status of
the territory, which Indonesia claims as its 27th province.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, who met his Portuguese counterpart
in New York over the weekend, said last week for the first time
that Indonesia would consider full independence if the people of
East Timor rejected a new autonomous relationship with Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he ruled out holding a referendum on status, a vote
that many East Timorese are demanding, saying it could lead to
civil war among opposing factions.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao, who is popularly known by his nickname, Xanana, has said
he is also concerned about the possible destabilizing effects of a
referendum. He said such a vote should be held only after a 10-year
period of social reconciliation and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic negotiations are focusing on what status to seek for
East Timor, how soon and how to determine what it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question now is just to find out how we are going to
consult the people of East Timor,'' said Joao Carrascalao, a former
governor of the territory and an advocate of separation from
Indonesia. Carrascalao has also said he believes that after
independence has been granted East Timor would need the presence of
a United Nations peacekeeping force for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   The East Timor talks are a chief product of the ``reform''
period overseen by President B.J. Habibie since President Suharto's
ouster in May.
</P>
<P>
   But like other changes, the opening of debate and the loosening
of harsh controls have given rise to new uncertainties and violent
confrontations. Separatist guerrillas who had become dormant in the
hills grew active again.
</P>
<P>
   In a controversial move, the Indonesian military, which says it
has pulled its combat troops out of East Timor, recently began
arming untrained civilians, ostensibly to provide security.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say they fear that those irregular soldiers
may be trained to fight against the guerrillas. Given the
bitterness that infuses the territory after more than 20 years of
fighting, some diplomats warn that the moves toward a peaceful
resolution could instead cause a surge of bloodshed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
