<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GRAMM-NYT &LR;      02-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GRAMM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMM HAS HISTORY OF STUBBORN (AND OFTEN SUCCESSFUL) RESISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-LIEBERMAN) 
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Comity is the grease that allows the Senate to run.
That is why Sen. Phil Gramm, who has a propensity for throwing sand
in the Senate's gears, stands out so starkly.
</P>
<P>
   His determination to block a bipartisan move to censure
President Clinton is completely within character. Year after year
since he has been in politics, Gramm, the staunchly conservative
Texas Republican has frustrated his colleagues on matters he has
felt strongly about, and more often than not, he has gotten his
way.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, for instance, Gramm almost single-handedly
blocked a Senate vote on a carefully arranged compromise bill that
would have lifted some of the barriers separating commercial banks,
investment banks and insurance companies. Never mind that
supporters of the bill were among the largest benefactors of the
Republican Party and that the chief sponsor of the Senate
compromise, Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., badly wanted the bill to pass
to help in his re-election race, which he ultimately lost.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last year, Gramm led the opposition to legislation that
would have raised cigarette taxes and permitted more government
regulation of tobacco companies. Never mind that the chief sponsor
of the tobacco bill was his best friend in the Senate, John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with his peers, he often doesn't observe the
traditional niceties,'' said a former staff member who insisted on
not being identified.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's press secretary, Larry Neal, expressed what is doubtless
the senator's self-image: ``There will always be a
Horatius-at-the-gate element to him.'' Horatius was a legendary
Roman hero who, with two lone companions, held an invading Etruscan
army at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, 56, who is his 15th year in the Senate, seems to
delight in being cantankerous, even when his allies call him a
nuisance and his enemies call him much worse.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly jokes about his reputation for being mean. He cites
the evident affection of his wife, his staff and his dog. And at
least once he told a dinner audience that he really did have a
heart, adding after the requisite pause, ``I keep it in a quart jar
on my desk.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the Senate's consideration of impeachment
this year, Gramm played the surprise role of conciliator. He and
his ideological opposite, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., sold the
Senate on a plan that allowed the trial to begin and deferred a
decision on summoning witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is back in his familiar position as a roadblock. Most
Democrats and some Republicans favor a resolution to censure
President Clinton after the vote to remove him from office fails.
</P>
<P>
   To pass, such a resolution would require 51 votes, a simple
majority, which might be possible, but Gramm has vowed to block the
vote. Under the rules, it would take 60 votes, probably an
unattainable number, to bypass him.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's opposition to censure is both practical and
political. As a practical matter, he said Sunday on the NBC News
program, ``Meet the Press,'' it would open the door for the Senate
to vote censure whenever it disapproved of actions by a president _
when, for instance, ``a future Harry Truman fires a future General
MacArthur.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically, he said, he did not want to give the senators who
vote not to remove Clinton from office the ``political cover'' of
being able to say officially that they disapprove of Clinton's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   There is hardly a more formidable opponent in the Senate, in
large part because Gramm is so smart, so tenacious and so quick on
his feet in debate. In an interview last year on another topic,
Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said he expected that on an
intelligence test, Gramm, who has a Ph.D. in economics, would score
higher than anyone else in the Senate. Coincidentally, Bennett is
now one of the leading Republican proponents of censure.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's apparent lack of concern about irritating his colleagues
has been the dominant characteristic of his years in Congress. He
was elected to the House as a Democrat in 1978, and in 1981, at the
beginning of his second term, he was put on the Budget Committee
after signing a promise to Democratic leaders that he would be
loyal to the party's budget. Instead, he secretly collaborated with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   When Democratic leaders retaliated in 1983 by kicking him off
the Budget Committee, Gramm quit the party, resigned from the
House, was handily re-elected as a Republican in a special election
and then, in 1984, was elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   When Gramm ran for the 1996 Republican presidential nomination,
his sometimes abrasive personality came back to haunt him in the
early contests in small states where personal contact with voters
can be crucial. He finished an embarrassing fifth in the Iowa
caucuses and dropped out of the race before the New Hampshire
primary, when polls there showed him far behind.
</P>
<P>
   With his presidential race behind him, Gramm has thrown himself
into the business of the Senate, becoming centrally involved not
just in the impeachment trial but in almost all the major
legislation before Congress. In an interview in January, he said
his main goal this year was legislation that would turn Social
Security into a mostly private system in which workers controlled
their own retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opposes this approach. Gramm said he was not even
thinking about compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
