<HEADER>
A9757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-EXHIBITION-NYT     02-10 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-EXHIBITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT AN ARTIST LEARNED FROM THE WORKS SHE CREATED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.Y.)   By   EDWARD M. GOMEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. _ La Wilson recently made a journey through a
snowstorm from her art- and book-filled home in Hudson, Ohio, to
Hudson, N.Y., to show her newest work at a gallery in this growing
upstate center of art and antiques dealers. At first the
coincidence of identical town names seemed almost too cute to suit
the unaffected character of Ms. Wilson, a 74-year-old mostly
self-taught maker of box sculptures that are as quietly enigmatic
as she is genial and straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then,'' she said, ``I got it. It fit. It made sense that I
should travel from Hudson to Hudson to present this work.''
</P>
<P>
   That Zen-like remark baffled some guests at the opening of her
show, which runs through the end of the month at the Davis &AMP; Hall
Gallery on Warren Street, Hudson's main thoroughfare. But for Ms.
Wilson and her dealer, John Davis, an Ohioan whose soft-spoken
manner belies a grit nurtured by many seasons in the art world, the
artist's comment was simply the last word _ for now _ on a creative
relationship that has spanned nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered her a show the day I met her,'' Davis said recently.
``That was at my first tiny gallery, in Akron. We painted the walls
pink and purple, hauled in La's furniture and piano, and recreated
her home for a show of 90 pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Davis and his business partner, Frank Hall, an
architect, opened their gallery for contemporary art and unusual
antiques _ school worktables, famous-building souvenirs, taxidermy
items _ in Hudson after a long run in downtown Manhattan. They
first operated an art gallery in SoHo in the late 1980s and then an
antiques-cum-home-design store called Sammy's, before the
district's art galleries began giving away to designer clothing
chains. ``It became boring and expensive,'' Davis said. ``It was
time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, meanwhile, a fire destroyed part of Ms. Wilson's
studio. ``So this show is about survival,'' the artist said.
``Where else could I have shown these new pieces but with John?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson grew up in Corning, N.Y., where her first name, Mary,
gave way to her childhood nickname, La, which she has used ever
since. She describes herself as shaped by the values of the 1940s
era in which she came of age. Marriage to a lawyer took her to
Ohio, where she reared her three children. (She also kept rabbits,
a dog and, at one time, a crow.)
</P>
<P>
   Around that time Ms. Wilson began dabbling in art, but her only
formal instruction came from a two-year course for adults at the
Akron Art Institute in the 1950s. ``I started making boxes after I
had done some thickly painted, nearly sculptural pictures,'' she
said. ``It all developed little by little, accidentally. The art
sort of found me.'' It also became her refuge from life's
vicissitudes, including divorce, family illnesses and the fire.
</P>
<P>
   First impressions of her work suggest that the artist has
perfected a scavenger-tinkerer's practice of stumbling upon old
wooden packing boxes and stuffing them full of industrial doodads
and the detritus of mass production. But the magic of her art,
which is about examining, collecting, sorting and assembling, lies
in its unexpected transformation of ordinary, even bland, items
into objects of power, danger, wonder or warning, all with a
mysterious aura and an offbeat, lopsided charm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson's assemblages are very different from the works of
Joseph Cornell. They feel less literary and romantic, more
down-to-earth. However abstract Ms. Wilson's box works may appear,
they always feature recognizable elements, from earrings or watch
faces to spigots and rosary beads, that serve as familiar points of
entry to the psychologically intense zones of emotion and sensation
that her art evokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilson works unconsciously and intuitively, skillfully
arranging her objects in an allover manner suggestive of a Jackson
Pollock painting,'' Tom Hinson, curator of contemporary art and
photography at the Cleveland Museum of Art, has written. Hinson,
who has has closely followed her work and frequently put it on
display, most recently in an exhibition of art from Cleveland's
private collections.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Wilson's ``Crossways'' (1998), now on view in Hudson,
drumsticks, electric-train tracks and rusted, cross-shaped cookie
cutters come together in a near-Gothic evocation of the sacred
within the mundane. ``Montage,'' another new work, suggests wry
nostalgia and moody elegance, in a multilayered composition of
boxes within boxes. In it, there are shiny black calipers like crab
claws on the loose; odd tools peeking out of partly opened lids,
and a Japanese alphabet tile in the corner of a wire basket that
appears to be an animal's cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``La's works create meditative spaces that pull you in,'' said
Linda Mussman, a visual artist and arts administrator, on a visit
to Davis &AMP; Hall. ``You feel a sense of grace and serenity coming
from them, from who she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mussman, a veteran theatrical director and producer, left
New York seven years ago and, with Claudia Bruce, an artist and
musician, founded Time and Space Limited, Hudson's most visible
performing arts center. Last year in the center's gallery, ``we
presented a show that looked at found objects as art, and it shook
up local audiences in a stimulating way,'' Ms. Mussman said. ``La's
work does this, too, but in a seductive, surprising way, with lots
of conflict in the signs and symbols in those meditative spaces.
She can turn an innocent clothespin into a threatening weapon.``
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is a riverside town and former whale-processing center
whose ambience reminds visitors more of Edward Hopper's edge than
Norman Rockwell's sweetness. In recent years, it has become a major
hub of the New England antiques trade and the home of many art and
antiques dealers, artists and writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, Davis &AMP; Hall does that rare thing that thrills artists
and is now almost impossible in New York's elitist art world _ it
gives them a chance to actually touch the wider, general public,''
Ms. Mussman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson said she was ``amazed at how the process of making
these boxes, then experiencing them, has taught me to let go, to
let the materials reveal their personalities, to remain open to
possibilities.'' She added: ``Can I apply that same open-mindedness
to people? What I'm getting from the art is a spirit I want to
bring into the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if endorsing a critical notion she herself would only
modestly propose, she emphatically said: ``I get that. That fits.
That makes sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
