u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GILLETTE-DURACELL-BOS     02-10 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-DURACELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURACELL ULTRA A SUCCESS, GILLETTE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Declaring its Duracell Ultra batteries to be a major
success, Gillette Co. said Wednesday it has improved the
performance of its new line and will expand the Ultra brand into
additional alkaline battery sizes besides AA and AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Duracell also plans to add lithium batteries to the Ultra line
later this year, said David W. Young, Duracell's president.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Energizer claims to be unimpressed. In the ongoing battery
wars, Duracell is playing ``catch-up,'' trying to match advances
Energizer made months ago, said spokesman Keith Schopp.
</P>
<P>
   With its razors, Boston-based Gillette has been consistently
successful at persuading consumers to trade up to premium-priced
products that arguably offer better performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultra line marks an attempt by Gillette to apply the same
strategy to Duracell, which it acquired in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced last year, the Ultra looks to segment the battery
market into two categories: the standard Duracell and the Ultra,
which is specially designed for high-drain devices such as digital
cameras and palm-sized computers. Ultra batteries cost about 20
percent more than the standard Duracell line.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics scoffed at the idea of a premium-battery line, and some
cite a Consumer Reports study that said batteries are a commodity
and advised consumers to buy batteries based on price rather than
on hard-to-prove claims of longevity.
</P>
<P>
   But Duracell points to recent sales figures as proof that its
strategy of offering a premium battery line is working.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Duracell said its batteries surpassed the
50-percent mark of US dollar sales and now enjoy a ``19
percentage-point share gap'' over Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duracell is clearly the market leader,'' said Tony Vento, an
analyst with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to widen its US lead, Duracell said it will spend $140
million to advertise and promote the Ultra brand as Ultra batteries
in C, D, and 9-volt sizes come onto the market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Energizer's parent, pet food giant Ralston Purina Co.
of St. Louis, suggested last month that quarterly profits failed to
meet expectations because of lower battery sales.
</P>
<P>
   A third company, Rayovac Corp., seems intent on positioning
itself as a lower-price alternative to Duracell and Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   While Duracell Ultra has enjoyed early success in the United
States, Canada, and Western Europe, it is still unclear whether
consumers in economically ailing parts of Asia and Latin America
will want to pay a higher price for a premium battery.
</P>
<P>
   Duracell accounts for about 25 percent of Gillette's annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Gillette shares rose 2 1/4 to
close at 56 1/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
