<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX PERVADES TELEVISION, BUT LET'S NOT BECOME EUNUCHES OVER IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex is good. They say that's how I got here.
</P>
<P>
   But I admit I feel uncomfortable when every other joke on some
sitcoms is a sex joke, or when every other comedy ``situation''
involves a coupling, an attempted coupling or a thwarted coupling.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for dramas. That doesn't make me a bluenose as much as
it makes me someone who sees a lot of bad TV.
</P>
<P>
   But I like it even less when someone tries to mandate what TV
ought to be doing. It appears The Kaiser Family Foundation did that
this week by releasing a study of sexual content on TV. To no one's
surprise, the study found that more than half (56 percent) of some
1,300 programs studied during the 1997-98 season contained sexual
content, including 85 percent of soap operas, 83 percent of movies,
78 percent of talk shows, 58 percent of dramas and newsmagazines,
and 56 percent of sitcoms. Useful information, but the foundation
went farther, suggesting that many shows were irresponsibly
offering no information on the risks and responsibilities of sexual
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Altman, president of the foundation, said, ``Surveys tell
us that young people get a lot of their information and ideas about
sex from TV. With the problems facing adolescents today, how sex is
shown on TV is just as important as how much sex is shown on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   One would naturally extrapolate that, every time a scene shows a
person getting into a car, The Kaiser Family Foundation will
request a responsible demonstration on seat-belt use. Similar
script advisories would accompany scenes of cigarette smoking,
cursing, jaywalking and any other real-world activities we don't
want our kids to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, an episode of ``Felicity'' dealt reasonably
well with the issue of first-time sex. In it, Felicity (Keri
Russell) was trying to schedule her first sexual encounter as if it
were a dinner date or a dorm party. She eventually saw the folly in
that, and never did have sex. Still, a friend of mine forbade his
two teenage daughters to watch the show, basing his decision on The
WB's commercials, which were titillating, and entirely misleading.
He made a straightforward _ and unpopular _ parenting call that The
Kaiser Family Foundation wants the TV networks to make.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the foundation should be looking at the commercials.
Better yet, as a philanthropic group interested in the public's
well-being, maybe it should be aiming its studies not at the
creative process but at the nurturing process.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me. I like responsible programming, but I cherish
creative freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to keep harping on sex, but the Rev. Jerry Falwell started
it. He worries that one of the ``Teletubbies'' is overtly
homosexual. Seems Tinky-Winky carries a purse and has an antenna in
the shape of a triangle, the symbol of gay pride. If the good
reverend has that much time on his hands, perhaps he could check
out the antenna on Dipsy's head. Suspiciously erect, no? I suspect
it would indicate the alpha male of this kinky group. And that
circular thing on Po's head would seem to fit nicely around Dipsy's
doodle. Could an international sex scandal (``Teletubbies'' is made
by a British company) be brewing on PBS! And what's up with
Laa-Laa's corkscrew. Bisexual? Wino? Walked into the door of a
leather bar looking for Tinky-Winky? We'll keep you posted.
</P>
<P>
   Short-timer George Clooney begins heading for the exit in
earnest Thursday night tonight when ``ER'' begins a two-parter
titled ``The Storm,'' in which Clooney's character, Dr. Doug Ross,
goes from hot water to rolling boil for his flouting of hospital
rules. The good news: Ross doesn't die, leaving him available for
an occasional visit to County General in future seasons. Clooney
will make his last appearance as a regular cast member next week.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to rumors recently swirling around ``Beverly Hills,
90210,'' Fox has picked up the series for next season, which will
be its 10th. No word yet on whether the title will be changed to
``Beverly Hills, 90210, the Post-Post-Graduate Years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
