<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLISON-HOLIDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY SINCE SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Okl., Ariz., Calif.)  (Sidebar with ELLISON-NOVEL) 
(DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holiday called Juneteenth dates back to June 19, 1865, when
Union forces sailed into Galveston Bay, established control of
Texas and enforced the emancipation of the slaves that had taken
effect, if only symbolically, in 1863 with the Emancipation
Proclamation issued by President Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years the holiday has become something of a metaphor
for the vagaries of memory.
</P>
<P>
   It was celebrated by the former slaves, who took the name from a
colloquial rendering of the date. For decades it was essentially a
local observance by blacks in Texas and to a lesser extent in other
states west of the Mississippi, particularly Oklahoma, where Ralph
Ellison grew up.
</P>
<P>
   During segregation, the day was marked by celebrations in black
neighborhoods. In Houston, whites-only rules were suspended at
parks and fairgrounds for the day.
</P>
<P>
   But even in Texas, Juneteenth celebrations began to wane after
World War II and the day declined in importance as the last
survivors of the era of slavery died. But then, with the Civil
Rights era and the growth of black political power in the South,
interest in the holiday increased again. A black state
representative from Houston, Al Edwards, proposed in 1979 that it
be made an official state holiday, and the proposal was
overwhelmingly adopted by the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Juneteenth has gained visibility outside Texas. When
some blacks called for a ``Day of Absence'' in 1992, asking blacks
to boycott schools, shops and workplaces to protest the not-guilty
verdict in the Rodney King beating case, Juneteenth was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   There are occasional parades and observances east of the
Mississippi. But the holiday remains most vital in Texas and to a
lesser extent other Western states like Arizona and California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
