<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PRISON OFFICIAL TESTIFIES TO IMPROVED CONDITIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A state prison administrator testified Wednesday
that Texas penitentiaries have vastly improved since the dark days
of the 1970s, and officials have no desire to backslide to the era
of widespread inhumane conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Janie Cockrell, deputy director for security, told senior U.S.
District Judge William Wayne Justice that she's witnessed a variety
of modernizations since she began prison work in 1976. Her career
started four years after inmate David Ruiz filed a class-action
lawsuit that led to dramatic changes _ ordered by Justice _
beginning in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell, one of the last witnesses in a three-week hearing over
alleged constitutional violations, said the improvements include
better guard training; wiser use of force and attention to inmates'
medical needs. Gone are the days of hellish overcrowding, when
inmates guarded their own cellblocks, violence reigned and other
unconstitutional conditions prevailed, she indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison. It has been a tremendous change for
good. I can tell you not a one wants to go back to those days,''
Cockrell said.
</P>
<P>
   However, an inmate-hired expert rebutted Cockrell's claims,
saying uses of force are not thoroughly investigated and are rarely
deemed excessive. They also seldom result in penalties for guards,
said Allen Breed, former director of the National Institute of
Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Breed also testified that prison officials probably ``grossly
understate'' the estimated 8,000 annual uses of force _ twice the
number in similarly sized California.
</P>
<P>
   Documented use-of-force injuries included broken jaws and other
bones; cuts requiring stitches and eye injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell, who rose through ranks to become the state's first
female warden in 1990, had contradicted earlier testimony from
inmates and their expert witnesses alleging a pattern of excessive
use of force. Cockrell described force as a last resort and said
the number of reported incidents _ some as minor as incidental
touching _ dropped 28 percent from 1994-98.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed the decline to better guard training and
regional-level monitoring to verify whether force was necessary.
Disciplinary and medical reports are cross-checked for consistency,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, injuries remain common in use of force incidents. Of 589
system-wide incidents reported in February 1998, 375 had no
injuries; 204 involved injuries and 10 were invalid, Cockrell said,
adding that the rate spikes upward in summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's hot, people tend to get agitated and frustrated,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why officials last summer added fans and water coolers;
allowed inmates to wear shorts in more areas; adjusted bus
schedules; and limited the heat exposure of inmates taking certain
drugs, Cockrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Breed said he measured temperatures in excess of 100
degrees in some women's units, where he also said inmates appeared
to be kept in leg irons _ unconstitutionally _ for punitive, not
security, reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell also had responded to numerous inmates' claims that
they were sexually assaulted but their complaints rarely resulted
in penalties for their inmate attackers. Cockrell said the message
is clear that rape ``won't be tolerated and we will hold offenders
accountable.'' However, she acknowledged that of the 81 sexual
assaults alleged in 1997, only seven were verified and resulted in
sanctions against attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate witnesses last month described being repeatedly raped;
and having to pay for protection by using commissary credits. Some
prisoners claimed their formal complaints and requests for
safekeeping were ignored, allowing retaliation and more assaults.
Breed said a lack of safekeeping cells was a cause for the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   A prison captain had testified Tuesday that sexual assaults
often are difficult to verify, and many are deemed consensual when
the victim ``doesn't even attempt to defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate of sexual assault has declined, Cockrell said, in large
part due to a 1995 law that causes inmates to forfeit good-conduct
time credits and lose privileges if they are found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, some amount of inmate aggression is inevitable,
Cockrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they victimize because they're mad at them _ or
they're just perverts,'' she said. ``There's all kinds of reasons
why they victimize each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimony before Justice is expected to concludeThursday. After
final arguments, Justice will decide by March 1 whether on-going
constitutional violations warrant his continued supervision of the
140,000-inmate Texas Department of Criminal Justice-Institutional
Division.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
