<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE OFFICIAL SEEKS TO BOOST REGIONAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Secretary of State William F. Galvin flies to
Washington Thursday as a man on a mission: To transform the chaotic
demolition derby the presidential primary season has become into an
orderly system of rotating regional contests.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Galvin hopes to have won the imprimatur of the
National Association of Secretaries of State, which would give the
regional primary proposal a big boost, and kick off a nationwide
effort to make it a reality.
</P>
<P>
   The current system now has so many big primaries so close
together that it has become a front-loaded contest that is over
almost before it begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved to the Big Bang theory of presidential
selection, which rewards high name recognition or a lot of money or
both,'' said Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   How rushed is the current schedule? The Iowa caucuses, the first
contest in the nominating process, comes on Feb. 7, 2000; the New
Hampshire primary will follow within several weeks. ``Then, by the
end of March, 75 percent of the delegates will have been
selected,'' Galvin said. ``Most likely, the nominees of both
parties will be known by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Some think the primary campaigns will effectively end even
earlier, after March 7, when New York, the New England states,
California, Maryland, Washington, and probably New Jersey and
Oregon, will go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That is a big change over the traditional system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, on the Democratic side, for example, George McGovern
did not wrap up the nomination until he beat Hubert Humphrey in
California on June 6; in 1976, challengers chased Jimmy Carter
until his victory in Ohio on June 8; in 1984, Walter Mondale
battled Gary Hart to the last June primaries and beyond to win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But since then the process has yielded de facto nominees much
earlier. In 1988, Michael S. Dukakis was the inevitable winner once
he beat Al Gore and Jesse Jackson in New York's April 19 primary;
similarly, in 1992, Bill Clinton had the nomination in his grasp
once he defeated Jerry Brown in New York on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those years, however, the relatively staggered
primaries, occurring over several months, gave lesser-known
candidates a chance to emerge, and ensured that the frontrunner
would be examined and tested week by week.
</P>
<P>
   Such a marathon has its advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something about a longer process, moving from state
to state, dealing with wins and losses and adversity, that tests
your mettle and your ability to lead,'' said John Sasso, who
masterminded Dukakis's 1988 presidential campaign. ``That may be
missing this time, where it could be over, with the frontloading,
after the results are in on March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the National Association of Secretaries of
State's Committee on Presidential Primaries, Galvin, who in 1995
helped make the early March Yankee regional primary a reality, is
pushing a plan to change that.
</P>
<P>
   It will not happen by 2000, but Galvin has big hopes for 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal put forward by Galvin and committee vice
chairman Bill Jones, California's secretary of state, Iowa and New
Hampshire would retain their position at the start of the process,
since they are small states that favor face-to-face campaigning and
give dark horses a chance to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the country would be divided into four zones, the
West, the Midwest, the South, and the Northeast. Each region would
have a separate date for its primary contests. After one regional
vote, candidates would have a month to campaign in the next region
before its states hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The regions would rotate each presidential election, with the
area that was first moving to the end of the line for the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, Galvin says, would restore time and balance to the
nominating process, giving candidates a better chance to make their
case, and the voters an opportunity to evaluate the candidates over
time.
</P>
<P>
   Because a significant portion of delegates would remain unchosen
until the final regional primary, states would be less likely to
see their contests rendered moot because the nomination had already
been decided.
</P>
<P>
   That is why California moved from June to early March. It was
that move, in turn, that has helped galvanize sentiment for a
regional system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something that was talked about every four years and
then forgotten,'' said Jones, the California secretary of state.
``California's moving early pushed this rotation regional primary
system to the fore, and properly so.''
</P>
<P>
   With the association in Washington for its winter meeting,
Galvin and Jones expect the secretaries of state _ who, after all,
are the top election officials in each state _ will approve the
plan handily. Then each secretary of state has to carry the idea
back to his home state, where it would need legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   To build support, the association has pushed its proposal with
bipartisan organizations like the Council of State Governments and
the National Governors Association, as well as with both national
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not everyone is a fan. Outgoing Democratic National
Committee Chairman Steven Grossman worries such a system will give
regional candidates an unfair boost in years when their areas vote
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a candidate from the Midwest emerges and does very well in
a Midwestern primary, it gives that person an unfair advantage over
anybody else,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No system is perfect,'' Galvin said. ``But considering how bad
things are now, this would be a huge improvement over the current
system, which is the worst of all worlds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
