<SLUG> BC-READING-REPORT-ART-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING TEST SCORES HAILED FOR STOPPING THE SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration Wednesday reported
modest gains in student performance on reading tests, but said they
were significant because the increase reversed a downturn that
occurred in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gains are not huge, but they are statistically
significant,'' said Vice President Al Gore, who went to the
Education Department to announce results of the survey, the
National Assessment of Educational Progress, a widely used
yardstick of academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported test results for 31,000 children in the
fourth, eighth and 12th grades. At all grade levels, scores were
higher in 1998 than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But many children were just making up ground lost early in the
decade, when reading scores declined for reasons that were not
clear. The performance of fourth-graders and 12th-graders was about
the same in 1998 as in 1992. Only eighth-graders scored higher in
1998 than in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley said: ``We were on a downward
trend. Over the last four years, we have changed that trend and
moved upward.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the latest gains, most students were still reading below
the levels recommended by the governing board of the testing
program.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Feinberg, assistant director of the National Assessment
Governing Board, an independent bipartisan body that sets standards
for the tests, said: ``On a few occasions in the past, there have
been gains this large or slightly larger for particular age groups.
But this is the first time there have been statistically
significant increases in all three grades since the program began
testing reading skills in 1971.''
</P>
<P>
   A change is said to be statistically significant if there is a
high probability that it is real, not a result of a statistical
aberration.
</P>
<P>
   The government also pays for tests in mathematics, science,
history, geography and other fields. The results are usually
announced at a news conference. The event Wednesday, with Gore in
attendance, was more political than usual. Dozens of education
lobbyists attended the event, held in an auditorium at the
Education Department. The difference in tone was noted by the
collectors of education statistics, who pride themselves on being
nonpolitical.
</P>
<P>
   The governing board defines three levels of reading achievement:
basic, proficient and advanced. Only one-third of fourth-graders
and eighth-graders were deemed to be at least proficient, meaning
that they could understand a text and draw inferences from it.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one percent of 12th-graders were at or above the
``proficient'' level of achievement. But education experts note
that some of the poorest students have dropped out of school by the
12th grade, and dropouts are not tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's encouraging that scores have gone up,'' said Catherine
Snow, a professor at the Harvard Graduate School of Education who
led a study of children's reading problems for the National Academy
of Sciences. ``But my glee is somewhat muted. I'd like to see a
more rapid rise in scores for black and Latino kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Tests are graded on a scale from 0 to 500. The average score for
all eighth-graders was 260 in 1994, the same as in 1992, but it
rose to 264 in 1998. For black eighth-graders, the average scores
were 238 in 1992, 237 in 1994 and 243 in 1998. For Hispanic
eighth-graders, the scores were 241, 240 and 244, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The average score for fourth-graders of all races rose 3 points
in the last four years, to 217, with most of the improvement
occurring among poor readers. The average score for 12th-graders
rose 4 points, to 291, with most of the gains observed among
students in the middle and at the top of the class.
</P>
<P>
   Among 12th-graders, the government said, there was ``no apparent
difference between 1998 and 1992 in overall average scores for the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls scored better than boys at all grade levels. And scores
for public school students were, on average, lower than the scores
for children in the same grades at private schools. But average
reading scores for eighth-graders and 12th-graders at public
schools did show an increase from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, known as the nation's report card, found a widening
gap between good readers and poor readers at the 12th-grade level.
From 1992 to 1998, scores declined for the lowest 10th of the
senior class, but rose for the top-performing 10th of the class.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal education officials said they were pleased to see a
decline in the amount of time students spent watching television.
Not surprisingly, students who watched less television scored
higher on reading tests. Still, more than one-third of
eighth-graders and nearly a fourth of 12th-graders said they
watched at least four hours of television a day.
</P>
<P>
   The government strongly implied that watching too much
television was bad for children because it induced passivity and
took time from ``activities that contribute to literacy
development.'' But Dennis Wharton, senior vice president of the
National Association of Broadcasters, said, ``We don't have any
information suggesting that children who watch TV are less literate
than those who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the test results showed that Congress should approve
``the Clinton-Gore education agenda,'' including $392 million to
reduce class size, tutor children and help those with reading
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill Goodling, a former schoolteacher who is chairman
of the House Committee on Education and the Workforce, disagreed.
Billions of dollars spent on remedial education and federal
literacy programs have ``led to nothing but mediocrity and more
education bureaucracy,'' said Goodling, R-Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
