r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-TEX     02-10 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWELS, CAMELS, 13,000 EXTAS _ MUST BE A MINISERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Size has always mattered to Robert Halmi Sr., way before the
catch phrase became less a term of sexual bravado and more a matter
of cheesy film promotion plastered on the sides of city buses.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran producer with a reputation for making miniseries
magic, myth and money, Halmi is responsible for turning Ted Danson
into a towering giant in ``Gulliver's Travels'' and populating
``Merlin'' with a fanciful talking mountain, magical horses and
assorted fairies, demons and dragons.
</P>
<P>
   But the massive ``Cleopatra'' may be the mother of all Halmi
miniseries. Shot in Morocco and England over five months, the epic
saga made use of 13,000 extras, 7,000 horses, 300 camels and 1,500
pieces of jewelry in a production that, at last check, was coming
in at $30 million and change.
</P>
<P>
   With Timothy Dalton as Julius Caesar, Billy Zane as Marc Antony
and French-Chilean newcomer Leonor Varela as the Queen of the Nile,
ABC already is positioning the four-hour production as a sure-shot
ratings streamroller for the May sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   That would be some achievement, given the current scramble to
produce similar lavishly staged megamovies in which exotic locales
are a given, big-name stars a must, and budgets akin to those of
the heydays of the late '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, the most aggressive of the networks, kicked off the week
with a four-hour dramatization of ``The '60s,'' complete with
newsreel footage and era songs for which the airing rights cost a
small fortune. NBC has scheduled for Feb. 28 a three-hour
adaptation of Alice in Wonderland; on Feb. 14 and 15, ABC unveils
Stephen King's four-hour ``Storm of the Century,'' which spent $12
million on special effects and set construction alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noah's Ark'' airs in May on NBC with Academy Award winner F.
Murray Abraham, Jon Voight and Mary Steenburgen. The same month,
expect ``Atomic Train,'' a disaster-suspense epic whose special
effects will most likely get top billing over star Rob Lowe. CBS'
hopes fall on ``Joan of Arc,'' which is filming in Prague and said
to be costing up to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In production for November is another Halmi miniseries,
``Arabian Nights,'' for ABC. Airing the same month is Aftershock, a
CBS release about an earthquake that wipes out New York City.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the excessive spending here, consider that less
than $3 million is the top-end budget for a typical two-hour TV
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Budgets are soaring because, in true network fashion, the idea
has become to outspend and outpromote the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Where that puts quality is anyone's guess. But at least it will
look interesting. These movies are filmed in expensive, exotic
locations (''Arabian Nights'' in Turkey and Yemen), include the
latest eye-catching special effects, and lure stars with name
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice in Wonderland'' features Gene Wilder as Mock Turtle,
Martin Short as Mad Hatter, George Wendt as Tweedledee and Whoopi
Goldberg as Cheshire Cat. Tina Majorino (''Waterworld'') portrays
the adventuresome Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the costumes are gorgeous, the colorful scenery
breathtaking and the on-air promos intoxicating, you have to wonder
whether producers are giving Lewis Carroll's story the short
shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that what's significant at this point is whether you
can break out of the clutter,'' says Linda De Koven, NBC's
executive vice president for movies and miniseries. ``But, believe
me, it's also whether you can do not just bigger programs but
better ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the lavish sets and the stars. Fine. But the most
important thing remains the material. Once viewers are there, they
need to have a reason to stay for two hours at the outset and then
return for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Such miniseries assertiveness hasn't been witnessed since the
1970s and the days of ``Roots'' (12 hours over eight nights),
``Rich Man, Poor Man'' (12 hours over six nights) and ``The Thorn
Birds'' (10 hours over four nights).
</P>
<P>
   But with the cable explosion of the '80s, viewers refused to
commit to so many nights, and the networks pretty much abandoned
the genre, except for spotty successes such as ``Lonesome Dove'' in
1989. They turned instead to two-night miniseries dealing with
violence and sensationalism, such as ``Baby M,'' about the
high-profile child-custody case; ``Stay the Night,'' about a
teen-age boy who kills the husband of his adult lover; ``Diana: Her
True Story;'' and the unsinkable Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   Historical, biblical and fantasy classics are the current
fixation. ``Merlin'' and ABC's star-studded ``Cinderella,'' which
featured Whitney Houston and Brandy, so convincingly trounced their
time-slot competitors that it was inevitable that networks would
demand similar projects pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Obst, who produced ``The '60s,'' admits that sweeps films
these days must be ``events'' and that the pressure is sometimes
impossible: Make a production that's different than but still
similar to successful predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel incredibly responsible to get the backbone of
history right, without being a documentary,'' says Obst, whose
credits include the feature films ``Contact, Sleepless in Seattle''
and ``Hope Floats.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise for ``Cleopatra'' director Frank Roddam, who began
filming by calling 1,000 extras to work at 7 a.m. just to set ``a
discipline and a standard'' for the cast and crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to say, `Look, this is a big thing, that this
is an event, and we're going to do it. We're not going to let it
defeat us.' And everybody got on board with that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were inspired not only by the vast numbers of extras
and the beauty of the country, but also the incredible power of the
story, and the challenge that it offered us. So it was a big
challenge to do battle sequences, and huge fighting sequences all
around _ working with horses, working with so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Halmi: ``This is as good as it gets. Television in the old
days, when I first started watching it, was a wonderful medium.
Sunday evenings the family sat around and joined each other, and
enjoyed seeing programs. That disappeared rather fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magic is back in these programs, and when you take a look
at them, you'll see why everyone wins. The viewer, the network.
Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A popular miniseries also provides a network with opportunities
to promote its prime-time series and to keep viewers away from the
competition. Perhaps adding to the urgency of miniseries production
is the correct assumption that viewer interest in this form won't
last.
</P>
<P>
   Miniseries based on literary classics have already been soundly
rejected. Halmi's ``Crime and Punishment'' _ filmed in Budapest and
starring Ben Kingsley, Julie Delpy and Patrick Dempsey _ drew such
a paltry audience for NBC that the network pushed another classic,
``The Tempest,'' out of sweeps. It turned out to be a smart move,
as few viewers watched that, either. ``Moby Dick,'' another Halmi
movie, fared only a little better for TNT.
</P>
<P>
   If the cycle turns, Halmi will have to scale back his
productions. In the meantime, he has as many as six miniseries in
the works, including ``Tenth Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   No budget is set for that miniseries, but it's projected to be a
massive 10-hour production. If it airs, ``Tenth Kingdom'' will
truly mark the return of a TV dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDUL/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
