<SLUG> BC-HARTSFIELD-AIRPORT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heavy travel, Delta hub help make Hartsfield busiest airport in
passenger volume
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hartsfield International Airport is officially over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   The airport handled 73.5 million travelers in 1998, eclipsing
Chicago's O'Hare International as the world's busiest in passenger
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield's count rose 7.7 percent from 1997 and has nearly
doubled since 1991. The primary reasons: heavy travel spurred by a
strong economy and Delta Air Lines' steady expansion of its
connecting hub.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare, which had long held the title for most passengers,
handled about 72.5 million people last year, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare remains the leader in another measurement, takeoffs and
landings, with 897,354 last year to Hartsfield's 846,881. More
cargo flights helped O'Hare hold that lead.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Chicago has a second airport, Midway, that handled
11.4 million people and 278,919 operations. The Atlanta region is
among the largest in the country with only one airport allowing
airline service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a numbers game, and we still consider ourselves
busiest as well as best,'' said Monique Bond, spokeswoman for
Chicago's aviation department.
</P>
<P>
   So, is the ``busiest'' title any more than fodder for a public
relations debate?
</P>
<P>
   ``The most tangible effect is the ability to attract foreign
airlines, which always want a large volume of passengers when
looking for U.S. gateways,'' Hartsfield marketing chief Miguel
Southwell said. Yet he acknowledged Hartsfield's immensity is
already so well known that the recruiting impact may be minor.
</P>
<P>
   And the title comes with a price. Hartsfield's operational
capacity is 800,000 takeoffs and landings. It can handle more, as
it did last year, but not without extra delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now the most delayed airport in the country,'' Southwell
said, noting the average delay at Hartsfield is 8 minutes, compared
with 3 minutes at O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that dubious distinction helps Hartsfield officials
as they argue for two new full-length runways. Without them, they
say, delays will get worse and growth will stagnate, depriving the
region of economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say Hartsfield is big enough and suggest another
airport be opened to airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-Fort Worth International, Los Angeles International and
London-Heathrow will likely round out the top five-busiest airports
for 1998, but final numbers for them aren't available. Based on
partial-year numbers and growth rates, none was in a position to
overtake Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
