<HEADER>
A9784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEDEPOT-CHILE11-COX     02-10 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-CHILE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Culture in Chile `not that different,' Home Depot employees
learn
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nelson Tirado learned an important lesson about doing
business in Chile at a neighborhood barbecue in Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of working alongside many of the 300 workers at Home
Depot's first store in Chile, it was only natural that a group of
employees invited Tirado, a Home Depot regional vice president, to
one of their park picnics. After all, he unloaded trucks and helped
out on the floor just like the rest of them.
</P>
<P>
   As the meat grilled, the conversation turned to the topic of
responsibilities at home and on the job. A colleague pointed at
Tirado and joked, ``You ought to be in this guy's shoes. He's in
charge of expansion in Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the big orange sign at the bottom of the snow-capped
Andes. This was real culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just couldn't believe someone like me would help out on
the floor, let alone hang out with them,'' said Tirado, who had
previously downplayed his high-level position when he arrived to
help open the store last year. The picnickers were shocked to find
out they'd been rubbing elbows with an executive. ``They're used to
bosses in Latin America who don't associate with the working
class,'' Tirado said.
</P>
<P>
   Tirado's experience was one of many that were reviewed this week
during an international management workshop at Home Depot's Atlanta
headquarters. About 30 managers used the two-day session to review
both progress and obstacles six months into the Chilean venture,
the company's first store in Latin America. The company brought in
faculty from Atlanta's Southern Center for International Studies to
teach the seminar.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday afternoon, the classroom was filled with lists of
various perceptions about the Latin American culture and economy,
ranging from monopolies to merengue. Home Depot is now looking at
subtleties in Latin America business practices as it prepares for
expansion in Argentina. One of the biggest lessons the world's
largest do-it-yourselfer had to learn was that its gung-ho culture
can be somewhat unsettling overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Chile weren't quite ready for our entrepreneurial
spirit,'' admits Mauro Pinera, director of international human
resources. Home Depot is proud of a management style that
encourages people to speak up and take initiative, and managers
were eager for Chilean employees to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Chilean workers were brought up in an autocratic environment
in which superiors tell them exactly what to do. ``They're not used
to the freedom, so we'll have to go slower on that,'' said Bill
Pena, regional president for Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Pena says Home Depot will not force its culture overseas, but
he's hard-pressed to come up with examples of how the company is
adapting a Chilean flair. Except for tweaking its merchandise to
suit local home-building needs, the Santiago store looks exactly
like a U.S. store. It even has a McDonald's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean employees have embraced a number of Home Depot-isms.
Several employees cried when Pena and Tirado gave them award badges
for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   And when management brought in stools for the cashiers because
they are accustomed to sitting down in Chile, employees refused to
use them. ``They said, `If Home Depot cashiers stand up in the
U.S., we want to stand up, too,''' Pena said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the differences between the cultures
aren't that great,'' Pena said. ``Our associates there want the
same things that associates here want: recognition and reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
