<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL DUQUE'S MAN STASHES TWO MORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla. , Md., Cuba, Costa Rica , Spain, Venezuela)   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost everywhere El Duque goes, Joe Cubas is sure to follow.
But he's much more than the agent who measured Orlando (El Duque)
Hernandez for a Yankee uniform and a four-year, $6.6 million
contract. He's the anti-Castro of Cuban baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an enemy of the Castro government,'' he was saying, ``but
I'm a hero of the Cuban people.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cubas, born in Miami of Cuban parents and armed with a
business degree from Florida International University, has
shepherded two dozen Cuban defectors to baseball contracts in the
United States, including El Duque, the most celebrated of his seven
big leaguers. As spring training approaches, he has stashed two
recent Cuban defectors in San Jose, Costa Rica, for inspection next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is a tall, slender, 21-year-old right-handed pitcher who
defected in Spain in October while with a touring Cuban team,''
Cubas said. ``The other is a 21-year-old shortstop who defected in
Venezuela in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubas would not name the two players, but he acknowledged that
half a dozen major league clubs have inquired when they will be on
display in Costa Rica for big-league scouts, as El Duque was last
March. By staying in Costa Rica, the Cubans are free agents
available for auction to the 30 major league clubs; if they were in
the United States, they would be subject to baseball's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two players are among the 40 to 50 Cuban players that
I've had the opportunity to see,'' Cubas said. ``I'd say 80 percent
of these players are capable of playing either at the major league
level or in the high minors within the next two years, 95 percent
within the next five years. The other 5 percent, sadly, have simply
grown too old. They're now past their peak as players.''
</P>
<P>
   In that 5 percent, according to Cubas, are third baseman Omar
Linares, outfielder Victor Mesa and the right-hander Lazaro Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as good as the other Cuban players are,'' Cubas said,
``there will always be just one El Duque. Others are very talented
or as talented in ability as he is, but they might not be able to
make the impact he did. He's not just a pitcher; he knows how to
pitch, how to set up hitters. He's an old-fashioned player.''
</P>
<P>
   When El Duque was suspected of planning to defect in 1996, he
was suspended from Cuban baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was he suspended,'' Cubas said, ``they took away his
ability to make a living doing anything else; he was assigned to be
a rehab therapist at a psychiatric hospital. But it gave him an
opportunity to be humble, to understand what the handicapped and
the people with mental problems go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting a Thurman Munson Award at the Marriott Marquis
on Tuesday night to benefit the Association for the Help of
Retarded Children, Hernandez made it a point to sign an autograph
and pose for a photo with the AHRC youngsters there, then hugged
each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Miami, where El Duque is living now, he has his El Duque's
Kids, a foundation to help neglected and underprivileged kids,''
Cubas said. ``He's given $10,000 to the Hialeah Foundation for Kids
who have been battered and abused. And he went back to Costa Rica
to visit a hospital there for kids with cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has purchased a home in Miami for his two young
daughters and his ex-wife, and another home there for his mother.
Cardinal John O'Connor persuaded Fidel Castro to allow Hernandez's
family to visit him after the World Series. Now his daughters,
ex-wife and mother will remain in the United States permanently.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro's gesture to Hernandez's family and the negotiations
for two baseball games in Havana and Baltimore between the Orioles
and Cuba's national team have not softened Cubas' anti-Castro
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Orioles games will hurt,'' he said. ``This is like
America's Ping-Pong policy with China years ago. Baseball won't
solve Cuba's problems. The games would give Castro legitimacy. But
he's starving 11 million people.''
</P>
<P>
   But two of those people are now in Costa Rica, waiting for the
big-league scouts to assess them. Once they were Castro's baseball
players; now they're Joe Cubas' baseball players. There's more
where they came from. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
