<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEAL TO BE SIGNED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New England Patriots stadium development agreement
is expected to be completed Thursday in much the same way the deal
was speedily put together: quietly and behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   And while reports surfaced in the past week about newly realized
problems associated with the $374 million Hartford project _
including site, tax, and public works issues _ Connecticut Governor
John G. Rowland has virtually gone underground on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   His last major appearance on the stadium was a public relations
repair job a week ago when he announced inside the Capitol that the
final development agreement signing would have to be postponed for
a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, lawyers have worked arduously on the more than
250-page document to build in protection for team owner Robert
Kraft in case the state cannot deliver on its promise for a clear
site _ now occupied by a steam plant _ in time for the Patriots to
move to Hartford by 2002, at the latest.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland's press office, openly annoyed at the Boston media,
imposed a blackout for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we talk to the Boston press it comes out wrong,''
said Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani. ``We've already announced that
the development agreement is done except for the signing.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the governor is merely trying to control the
process just as he did at the start, and stifle any dissent on the
complex project after fast-tracking the legislation through the
General Assembly in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an understatement,'' said Senator John Fonfara, a
Democrat from Hartford. ``We've written a letter asking the
governor to see (key provisions of the development agreement)
before it's signed and we've never heard back regarding that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonfara, and the rest of the Hartford delegation, signed the
missive last week pressing to know if the agreement will force
Kraft to make payments in lieu of taxes on the stadium site and
whether local companies would receive construction job guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Neither issue, he said, was addressed in the initial agreement
Kraft and Rowland signed in November. Nor was it included in the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some estimates say the city will have to pay more than
$2 million a year to provide police details and other security
around the construction site.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Hartford representatives have not heard back from
Rowland's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be ignored like this,'' Fonfara huffed. ``The whole thing
has been underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford collects $2.1 million a year on the land that would be
used for the 68,000-seat open-air facility. However, it appears
that the Patriots would neither pay property taxes on the site nor
make payments in lieu of taxes. The team would be assessed taxes on
a hotel Kraft must build next to the stadium. But that land is not
currently assessed by the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get about $2 million in taxes on that
development,'' Nilda Torres, a spokeswoman for Hartford Mayor
Michael Peters, said referring to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Torres said Kraft will be responsible for paying any police and
security details on the stadium property, while the city would pick
up the tab for officers on the streets surrounding the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be that much of an increase or
that much of a problem,'' Torres said. ``The mayor and the (City)
Council feel comfortable with the picture. . . The points that were
a problem are on the road to being resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``It's pretty much the governor's project.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CTG Resources Inc., owner of the steam plant, has not
acted on an offer by the Connecticut Resources Recovery Authority,
a quasi-public power agency trying to buy the company, allowing the
land to be cleared for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steam plant,'' Pagani said, ``has not been resolved yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
