<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9800 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS &LR;      02-10 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MORTICIAN TELLS JURY HE REGRETS KILLING WIDOW, 81 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ Former mortician Bernie Tiede, sobbing
uncontrollably on the witness stand at his own trial, testified
Wednesday that he profoundly regrets killing wealthy Carthage widow
Marjorie Nugent, a woman, he insisted, he deeply loved.
</P>
<P>
   But describing what led him to shoot the 81-year-old widow four
times in the back as she stooped to pet her dog, he said: ``My life
had become a prison to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiede's testimony, alternating between tears and a sometimes
condescending tone, came in the punishment phase of the trial in
which he was convicted Tuesday of murdering Nugent and stuffing her
body inside her freezer.
</P>
<P>
   While eligible for probation, the 40-year-old former Carthage
Methodist lay minister _ who was Nugent's inseparable companion for
three years _ also could be sentenced to 99 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is expected to begin deciding his sentence Thursday.
The trial was moved to this East Texas community 50 miles south of
Carthage because of heavy publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Under the gentle questioning of his almost avuncular attorney,
Clifton ``Scrappy'' Holmes of Longview, Tiede said he became
acquainted with Nugent after directing her husband's funeral in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   He felt sorry for her, he said, because she seemed lonely and
had few friends.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, she urged him to quit his job at the funeral home to
become, in essence, her companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me I would have more free time,'' he said, ``and I
liked that idea. But I found I didn't have any free time at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the millionaire widow offered him the benefits of her
wealth, he quickly found himself in the position of a ``personal
valet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go over and make coffee early in the morning, between
7 and 7:30,'' Tiede testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked out the clothes she would wear. I helped with the
laundry. I trimmed her toenails. I pulled the long hairs out of her
chin. I combed her hair. I pulled on her shoes. I did just about
anything you could imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, he contended, was relentless in her demands. She'd page
him and leave multiple messages on his telephone answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   On one occasion, Tiede returned the remote control to her garage
and front gate and announced he was ending their relationship. As
he backed his car out of her driveway, she used the device to close
the gates behind him, thwarting his escape.
</P>
<P>
   When he re-entered the house, she emphatically told him she was
not going to let him go. Tiede told jurors he relented, accepted
the remote control and _ though plagued by the relationship _
continued the routine for about three more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had become her sole source of entertainment on a grand
scale,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede admitted that he had fantasized about beating her head
with a baseball bat. But, he testified, ``I prayed ... I wondered
how I was going to handle my feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously handled them the wrong way, didn't you?'' Holmes
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir,'' Tiede responded.
</P>
<P>
   He wept profusely when he described the jailhouse letters he
wrote to Nugent's relatives. ``I told them in those letters that I
wanted to apologize for abusing our friendship, ruining their
lives, my life and Marge's life,'' Tiede said. ``I pray God will
give them strength to face their lives and forgive me for the
things I've done wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Panola County District Attorney Danny Buck Davidson concentrated
on the privileges and wealth Tiede gained from his relationship
with Nugent. The defendant's stepmother had testified earlier that
even as a boy, Tiede was fascinated with money.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the aged woman, he made numerous trips to New
York, San Francisco and Las Vegas, flying first-class _ especially
on long foreign trips. ``The seats are somewhat larger and I'm a
big man,'' the 6-foot, 3-inch tall, 265-pound defendant said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede testified he and Nugent used her money to visit Germany,
Hong Kong, England, Scotland, Wales, Thailand, Russia, Canada and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   They also saw the Broadway musical, ``Les Miserables.'' Noting
Tiede's correct French pronunciation of the play based on Victor
Hugo's novel, the prosecutor asked, ``Do you feel you're a somewhat
sophisticated person?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meaning what?'' Tiede responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, how to pronounce the name of the play,'' said
Davidson, who earlier had mispronounced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't take much sophistication to do that,'' Tiede said,
somewhat haughtily, prompting laughter in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede testified that Nugent willingly paid his expenses and
often made arrangements herself.
</P>
<P>
   After he killed her, he spent hundreds of thousands of dollars
on businesses and to buy friends cars and other gifts. Shortly
before his arrest in August 1997, he visited Paris, financing the
trip with his former companion's money.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Davidson rolled Nugent's freezer toward Tiede _
the same appliance where Nugent's body had been hidden for nine
months. Tiede pointedly refused to look at it, while Davidson led
him on a methodically grim reprise of Nugent's final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie, you pointed the gun at her and pulled the trigger ...
''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir, I did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened after the first bullet?
</P>
<P>
   ``She fell to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was still breathing ... '' Davidson pressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I shot her again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tearfully, Tiede described how he emptied the freezer of food,
placed Nugent inside, covered her with a sheet, then replaced the
frozen vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   After washing blood from the garage and depositing the spent
shells in the garbage, Tiede went home to shower. Later he attended
a dress rehearsal of a play at a local college.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the day by treating 40 young actors to pizza at a local
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
