A9802 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SPECTER-PA     02-10 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SPECTER-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER WILL NOT CONVICT OR ACQUIT CLINTON IN IMPEACHMENT
TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 10 -- Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter will not
vote to convict President Clinton in the Senate's impeachment
trial, he announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't vote to acquit the president either.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``sham trial,'' Specter said he will vote that the
obstruction of justice and perjury charges against the president
were ``not proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Scottish law, Specter said a juror has three choices for
a verdict: guilty, not guilty or not proven.
</P>
<P>
   By not voting to convict, Specter said he doesn't necessarily
think Clinton is not guilty of the charges. He thinks the ability
of the House impeachment managers to prove the charges was hindered
because the Senate wouldn't allow live witness testimony. He also
said he thought there was a lack of relevant evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Specter was among three Republicans to announce Wednesday he
will break party ranks when senators vote on the two articles of
impeachment. Republican Sens. James Jeffords of Vermont and John
Chafee of Rhode Island made public their intentions to acquit
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``not proven'' isn't an option for senators when they
vote, Specter said he may have to vote ``present,'' which is
allowed under Senate rules.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is likely to be acquitted when the Senate takes its
final vote expected late Thursday or early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I vote 'not proven' and they lead me away, it will be one
of the only exciting elements of the day,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement, Specter broke his month-long silence
about the case. He had vowed not to discuss his thoughts while he
was a juror.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania's other senator, Republican Rick Santorum, respects
Specter's decision and will not announce his own intentions before
the vote, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his [Specter's] decision alone,'' Robert Traynham,
Santorum's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he knew his vote of ``not proven'' made his
feelings about the charges difficult to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being a little ambiguous,'' Specter said. ``I'm being
a lot ambiguous ... even amorphous.''
</P>
<P>
   Angering both sides of the political spectrum with his vote was
a risk Specter was willing to take, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've certainly done that before,'' he said and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he won't vote for a censure resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't vote for findings of fact and I won't vote for
censure,'' Specter said. ``I will vote 'not proven' and then go
home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
