</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-MANDATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO CURB LAWS THAT IMPOSE COSTS ON BUSINESSES  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the new Congress' first hard-fought vote on
legislation, the House of Representatives approved a bill Wednesday
that would make it harder for Congress to pass laws that imposed
costs on businesses, as environmental laws have done.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was strongly favored by business groups and was
opposed by labor and environmental groups. A similar bill passed
the House last year but died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 274-149, with support from dozens of Democrats and
all but 11 Republicans in the House, but it came after extensive
debate in which opponents twice failed by just a handful of votes
to significantly weaken the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The debate in the House shows that the question of relief for
businesses from what they see as burdensome federal regulations
remains a potent and divisive issue, as it has been since
Republicans gained control in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Called the ``Mandates Information Act,'' the bill would allow
any member of Congress to raise a parliamentary objection to any
bill whose provisions would impose costs of at least $100 million
on private businesses. That would cut off debate on the bill unless
lawmakers immediately voted to overrule the objection.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors said the measure would make sure that lawmakers did not
approve bills that might do unintended harm to businesses. But
opponents said its effect would be to stymie health, safety and
environmental protections for the public.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., who offered one of the defeated
amendments to the bill, said the proposal was ``designed to do one
thing and only one thing _ shut down debate on any measure that
someone claims will cost industry money, regardless of the evidence
on costs, regardless of the benefits, regardless of the public
purpose to be served, regardless of whether some companies support
the measure.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., said the bill would improve on a
1995 law that placed similar restrictions on Congress when it tried
to pass bills that cost state and local governments money to
enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``For far too many years,'' Linder said, ``this Congress has
voted for warm and fuzzy things, and not to tax the public for the
costs, but to pass them on to state and local governments and the
private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert's amendment was defeated by a vote of 216-210, with 34
Republicans voting to change the bill in ways that its sponsors
said would completely remove its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment by Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., also failed,
216-203. Supported by every major environmental group in the
country, this amendment would put the same procedural barriers in
place every time a bill or amendment threatened to weaken existing
environmental laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
