<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIGROUP-VISA-NYT &LR;      02-10 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-VISA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP RIFT WITH VISA SIGNALS SHAKEUP IN CREDIT-CARD INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, Visa International gave three of the nation's largest
banks extra seats on its board to appease the giants' concerns that
they got too little bang for their buck from the credit-card
association.
</P>
<P>
   Visa, which is owned by a consortium of banks that share
marketing and processing costs for the credit-card network, had
been sparring with the newly merged banking behemoths, especially
Citigroup and BankAmerica Corp., about how advertising and related
issues should be handled; additional board seats were awarded to
help calm things down.
</P>
<P>
   But this version of detente failed.
</P>
<P>
   And with Citigroup's decision last week to begin yanking a large
part of its business away from Visa and giving it to Mastercard
International, the credit-card industry's Cold War is heating up.
At stake is the shape of the credit-card business and the roles
played by the two dominant credit-card associations.
</P>
<P>
   The merger boom that has reordered the banking industry has
created a handful of giants who apparently feel little need to
share the costs and marketing arrangements that made Visa and
Mastercard so attractive: Thirty years ago, credit cards were
rarely-used pieces of plastic and banks were largely restricted
from operating nationally.
</P>
<P>
   While about 6,600 banks and other institutions now issue credit
cards, just seven companies control two-thirds of all cards issued.
Analysts expect the credit-card business to continue to consolidate
in fewer and fewer hands. Both Visa and Mastercard, recognizing how
much leverage the big banks wield, have been approaching the
biggest credit-card issuers recently with offers of lower fees in
return for transferring most of their business to just one of the
associations, according to bankers involved in the moves.
</P>
<P>
   A Visa spokesman said the company had been pursuing the discount
strategy since last year to ``award participation in Visa.''
Mastercard declined to comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the ante was raised last week when two Citigroup executives,
including co-chief executive John Reed, resigned from Visa's board
after the association failed to meet Citigroup's demand that the
``Citi'' brand name be more heavily promoted on television
commercials and on the cards. Citigroup will begin moving new
business exclusively to Mastercard, which is more amenable to
Citigroup's goals.
</P>
<P>
   Reed asserted recently that BankAmerica chief executive Hugh
McColl and Bank One Corp. chief executive John McCoy were inclined
to follow his lead in more openly flouting Visa's conventions _ a
proclamation that appears to be something of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, BankAmerica, and Bank One rank first, second and
fifth in size in the United States and are the biggest banks on
Visa's 11-member board. They are also the only banks that have two
board seats. Bank One is the leading credit-card issuer in the
country, followed by Citigroup. BankAmerica is the seventh-largest
issuer, according to the Nilson Report, a trade publication based
in Oxnard, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica, created by last year's merger of Nationsbank Corp.
and BankAmerica, declined to comment directly on its relationship
with Visa but appears to be disposed toward Citigroup's way of
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do remain advocates for changes in how the card
associations operate, not only in the brand but in the marketing
they do,'' said Robert Wynne, a BankAmerica spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Bank One, a product of last year's merger of First Chicago
NBD Corp. and Bank One, seems less inclined to share Citigroup's
views. While the bank declined to comment Wednesday, Bank One
executives close to McCoy said he thinks branding is not of
paramount importance to his bank _ largely because Bank One issues
a lot of affinity cards that already emphasize several different
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Citigroup has many more global interests than either
BankAmerica or Bank One. In overseas markets, Citigroup has ample
reason to believe it can carve out a distinct identity for itself
in the credit-card business. Although Visa has almost twice the
market share of Mastercard, analysts said consumers carrying
Citigroup cards would notice little change because Mastercard is
accepted at almost all the same places as Visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``For nearly two decades, Citigroup was the top dog at Visa and
now Bank One is and Citi has decided to take its ball and go play
in Mastercard's court,'' said David Robertson, the president of the
Nilson Report. ``Citi and other big banks were willing to be team
players in the financing of Visa until that payment system was well
established. Now that's accomplished and the landscape is
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing tensions between Visa and its member banks are likely
to be the main topic when Visa's board meets Friday. For its part,
Visa said it remained committed to operating as it always has _
putting the Visa brand name at the center of marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else, said Visa executive vice president Michael
Beindorff, ``would squander all of the elements of the Visa joint
venture with banks, which has been one of the most successful joint
ventures in history.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
