<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Friends'' reveal their secret twosome
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time isn't one of ``Friends' '' best buds.
</P>
<P>
   TV's perkiest bunch of pals is, if some of the characters aren't
already, cracking 30. And it's hard to imagine their over-the-top
lifestyles and whimsy will translate much longer. Turn around in a
couple of seasons and Jennifer Aniston's Rachel might play like
Kirstie Ally on ``Veronica's Closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope, we don't want to go there.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, ``Friends'' is working just fine. Even great
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Take tonight's episode _ ``The One Where Everybody Finds Out''
(8 p.m. on NBC (8343)). We've been waiting since the end of last
season for the whole gang to clue in that Monica (Courteney Cox)
and Chandler (Matthew Perry) are a secret twosome. And the final
revelations unfolding tonight are a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Joey (Matt LeBlanc) already knows. Rachel knows, but only Joey
knows that Rachel knows. And once Phoebe (Lisa Kudrow) knows and
Monica and Chandler don't know that their two gal pals know,
``Friends'' turns into a contest the likes of which TV hasn't seen
since ``Seinfeld's'' ``master of your domain'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. ``Friends'' isn't ``Seinfeld'' when
``Seinfeld'' was at its best. Not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   But it's likely TV's best sitcom this season. Monica and
Chandler's cute coupling is certainly more pleasing than the
previous angst-heavy pairing of Rachel and Ross (David Schwimmer).
</P>
<P>
   It's clear these actors are in perfect sync with their
characters. As poor, dumb Joey, LeBlanc's wise facial expressions
this season have been classic. And Kudrow has been as marvelous as
she was in her Oscar-worthy performance in ``The Opposite of Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, her Phoebe takes on Chandler in a laugh-out-loud,
toe-to-toe sex contest. She's a wonder to watch. She and all her
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Cranes in a triptyc a city street. Todd (Stephen Berra) was an
old flame of Felicity's (Keri Russell) who'd come back to bug her,
and she had just given him the brush-off when along came the bus
and boom! Followed by ``to be continued . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The WB didn't want to say whether Todd lives or dies, but in its
listing for next week's conclusion of the two-parter (9 p.m.
Tuesday), Berra is listed in the credits, so it must not have been
that bad of a bus accident.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer, TV critic
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino and Phil Kloer write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
