A9833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUBBIES-FALWELL11-COX     02-10 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUBBIES-FALWELL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falwell comes late to Teletubby psychobabble
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the flap over whether Tinky Winky the Teletubby is gay, the
real news is that the Rev. Jerry Falwell is late to the party.
</P>
<P>
   This little game has been played in some circles for almost two
years, and Falwell is only now getting it. Maybe he was still too
busy fuming over the woman he once called ``Ellen Degenerate'' and
just hasn't been paying attention. Some cultural watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   For those who missed it, Falwell has accused a character in the
popular children's show ``Teletubbies'' of being homosexual,
pointing out that Tinky Winky is a boy who carries a purse and has
a triangle (a gay symbol in some circles) on his head. The
Teletubbies are four British characters in big felt costumes with
TV sets in their bellies who speak mostly in nonsense, hug a lot,
dance around and are as popular as Barney the purple dinosaur among
2-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Itsy Bitsy Entertainment Co., which licenses the
Teletubbies in the United States, says Tinky Winky doesn't carry a
purse, he carries a ``magic bag,'' and that Falwell's charge is
``absurd and kind of offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also kind of old. The Tubbies debuted in England in March
1997 and were a huge hit with the zwieback and apple juice set from
the get-go. By July 1997, The Guardian newspaper in London was
calling TW a ``gay icon (who) . . . prances around in a
particularly camp fashion.'' That was about the time the producers
changed the actor inside the purple costume, reportedly, according
to whispers in the gay community, because the first actor was too
effeminate in his portrayal of TW.
</P>
<P>
   The gay subtext of TW became a running item in British papers.
``Tinky Winky is the first queer role model for toddlers,'' said
Andy Medhurst, a media studies lecturer at Sussex University.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, PBS brought the Tubbsters across the Atlantic,
figuring, correctly, that they were the next Barney (last year,
sales of Teletubby merchandise passed Barney and were second only
to ``Sesame Street'' among PBS kids' shows). And almost
immediately, Internet posters picked up the debate over whether TW
is gay, or at least if he could be considered gay.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Musto, gay nightlife columnist for Village Voice,
certainly thought so back in April 1997, and this year The
Washington Post matter-of-factly called TW ``the gay Teletubby'' in
an in-and-out list (not who's in and out of the closet).
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the gay magazine The Advocate presciently wrote
that ``PBS is clearly terrified that the same fundamentalists who
boycott Disney are going to flip once they get wind of the latest
lavender love puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   Which pretty much brings us up to date, meaning Falwell's
Earth-to-Jerry discovery that something is up in Teletubby-land.
The ensuing hue and cry calls to mind a widespread rumor in the
early '90s that Bert and Ernie of ``Sesame Street'' were more than
just roommates, which reached the point that ``Sesame Street''
producers had to deny it in The New York Times, as well as an
extremist whispering campaign that Barney was the Antichrist, which
so far has not yet come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   So if Musto and Falwell agree that Tinky Winky is a latter-day
Oscar Wilde (albeit one in a purple felt suit), does that mean he
is?
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, Itsy Bitsy Entertainment and PBS are in
this to make money. PBS got burned on the merchandising agreement
with Barney's creators several years ago and reportedly cut a
better deal to get a piece of Tubby sales. Some reports indicate
the Teletubby merchandise market may be worth as much as $2 billion
by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Do you really think they're going to jeopardize that to push a
sexual agenda on toddlers in the form of a debatable subtext?
</P>
<P>
   The color to think about when you think of ``Teletubbies'' isn't
lavender _ it's green.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
