<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.5 MILLION AWARDED TO SMOKER WITH CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state jury in San Francisco has awarded $1.5 million in
compensatory damages from the Philip Morris Cos. to a woman who
says her inoperable lung cancer was caused by more than 35 years of
smoking cigarettes, primarily Philip Morris' Marlboro brand.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, returned late Tuesday and followed Wednesday by the
beginning of the jury's deliberations on punitive damages, was the
third in the last three years in which judgments had been awarded
smokers who contended that cigarette makers had failed to warn them
adequately of smoking's hazards. The two other awards, both against
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., were later overturned, and no
such verdict has ever survived appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest judgment could portend further legal problems for
the tobacco companies in California, by far the most populous
state, because it resulted from the first cigarette lawsuit to
reach a jury since the 1997 repeal of a state law that barred
individuals' product liability suits against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of cigarette company stocks fell sharply Wednesday in
response to the verdict. Philip Morris was off $3.8125 a share, to
close at $41.5625, and the RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. was down
$1.375, closing at $27.3125.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Philip Morris, the largest cigarette maker,
said it would not comment on the case until after the
punitive-damages phase was completed. In addition to the $1.5
million to compensate the plaintiff, Patricia Henley, for medical
costs, pain and suffering, her lawyer, Madelyn Chaber, has asked
the jurors to award her $15 million to punish the company for the
negligence and fraud that was found in the verdict returned on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley, 52, of Los Angeles, discovered last year that she
had inoperable lung cancer. Although lawyers for Philip Morris
argued that she had understood the risks of smoking, her suit said
she had smoked since she was a teen-ager, taking up the habit a few
years before government-required warning labels began appearing on
cigarette packages in 1966. The tobacco companies, she said, never
told smokers that addiction might leave them incapable of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Until quite recently, though, Ms. Henley would have been
forbidden to bring her case. Under a 1987 tort reform law, product
liability suits against tobacco companies were prohibited in
California on the ground that the risks of smoking were universally
known. The law was repealed in 1997, around the time California
decided to file a claim against the tobacco industry in an effort
to recover smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   In November, California was one of 46 states that struck a $206
billion deal with Philip Morris and the other major cigarette
makers settling all remaining lawsuits brought to recoup those
costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
