<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC11-COX     02-10 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne to submit brief report to IOC
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite new questions about Atlanta's Olympic bid
effort, Billy Payne's report to the International Olympic Committee
will bear no resemblance to Salt Lake City's 300-page document
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who headed the volunteer Atlanta Organizing Committee bid
team, has not issued his formal response to the IOC's widening
inquiry into improprieties during the fierce competition among
cities bidding for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   When he does, it will be brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Atlanta bid group is concerned, we did
everything by the book and therefore have nothing to explain to the
IOC, and therefore the response is brief,'' Lee Echols, the new
spokesman for the bid team, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Echols, who has worked extensively with Atlanta Olympic
co-chairman Andrew Young, former mayor of Atlanta, has been brought
in to field media inquiries as the growing investigation expands to
Atlanta and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of a memorandum Payne wrote in 1990 to top aide
Ginger Watkins _ suggesting that IOC members be given gifts, some
of them considered excessive in the current climate _ has generated
global interest.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and Echols on Wednesday fielded calls and transmitted a
prepared statement characterizing the memo as musings that never
were acted upon. Payne consistently has denied any wrongdoing in
securing the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was written Aug. 20, 1990, just one month before the
IOC voted in Tokyo to elect Atlanta to host the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the last-minute inducements suggested in the memo:
</P>
<P>
   _ A tennis scholarship to the University of Georgia for the
daughter of Pal Schmitt, an IOC executive board member.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medical care at the Emory Clinic for Bashir Mohamed
Attarabulsi, the Libyian IOC member who has already resigned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free airline tickets for two other members interested in
attending an international baseball game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt, a Hungarian, said Wednesday he had three college-age
daughters in 1990 but none was offered scholarships to UGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never discussed this with Mr. Payne,'' Schmitt said.
``Perhaps he was thinking that this would be nice, to offer a
scholarship to one of my daughters. I am helpless that I was
mentioned in this.''
</P>
<P>
   One daughter went to school in Hungary, another to the
University of Southern California on a tennis scholarship. The
third did not attend college. Schmitt acknowledged that bid cities
research IOC members to figure out ways to secure their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They studied us and looked for a weak point to attack, whether
it was health reasons or children or poverty or whatever,'' Schmitt
said. ``Then they thought, 'What could we do to get the favor of
the IOC member?' ``
</P>
<P>
   However, Payne and his team say they never offered inappropriate
favors in exchange for votes.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly the nature of the information being sought by
the IOC. After completing its own investigation of excesses in Salt
Lake City's bid, the IOC announced that it would expand its inquiry
to include every candidate city from 1996 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Because most bid committees have disbanded, the IOC sent letters
of inquiry to national Olympic committees. The IOC set a Feb. 15
deadline for response.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, received the
request for information about Atlanta's bid and has talked to
Horace Sibley, the bid team's attorney. Sibley, who also was a
member of the volunteer bid team, and Payne are preparing their
response. Payne said he would make his response public when it is
sent to the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC investigators say they want evidence of any
inappropriate requests for material benefits or favors by its
members, multiple visits to candidate cities or excessive gifts
from by bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already prepared a brief summary of comments that we
will issue in response to the letter,'' Echols said Wednesday.
``Obviously, we'll need to see the letter first to crystallize our
own response. It'll certainly not be 300 pages like Salt Lake
City's.''
</P>
<P>
   The massive report issued by Salt Lake detailed cash payments, a
bogus scholarship program; expensive travel, including Super Bowl
trips; medical services; gifts and shopping sprees _ all delivered
to IOC members and their families in hopes of winning the 2002
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt suggested that every bid city undergo the
wrenching self-scrutiny that Salt Lake City has suffered the past
seven weeks. That would help clear a path to setting a new standard
of ``forthrightness'' in the Olympic world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened here was not right,'' Leavitt said. ``So
we're setting it right and we're paving the way for others to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
