<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS DISPLAY A FACT OF HUMAN NATURE: THE NEED TO TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Miss., N.Y., R.I., Vt., Colo.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-DEBATE,
IMPEACH-LIEBERMAN, IMPEACH-GRAMM) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drifting through the official silence of the
impeachment trial, individual senators on Wednesday began
exhibiting traits of adaptability worthy of Galapagos tortoises
maneuvering for scraps of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   With Darwinian aplomb, some spoke out to reporters in the subway
tunnel under the Capitol as they hurried to and from the trial,
making some points about their task even as they disowned any
intention of prejudgment. A few dared to be more direct and go on
television to pre-empt the momentous event of verdict-casting day
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they exhibited the invincible human dynamic that
did so much to drive the presidential sex-and-mendacity scandal to
the extreme of impeachment _the simple fact that people will talk;
there can be no true silencing of them, a senator no more than a
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   At its most controversial, this quality was exhibited by Sen.
Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who openly rebelled against the trial's
closed-door deliberations by leaving the chamber to deliver his
speech for acquittal even before he read it to the Senate court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the sordid affair of all sordid affairs,'' said the
senator, denouncing the House Republican prosecutors for a
political ``counterfeit case.'' His passion hinted at the kind of
clash the nation might have witnessed if deliberations were open
when he scored the investigative behavior of Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, even more than the misbehavior of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., later railed against
Harkin for the implicit insult of opting for television exposure to
the Senate court's ongoing deliberations. But through the day there
seemed no stopping the basic urge of elected senators to reach the
people: One by one, press releases leafed forth announcing
positions of individual senators. A second, then a third, followed
by a fourth senator went on television with their positions rather
than risk being lost in the mass of verdict statements on the final
day.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the Capitol tunnel, one of the alternative forums of
choice, senators made some interesting points even if they did not
formally announce their votes. Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, worried
about how any senator voting against perjury for good lawyerly
reasons could explain that to the average voter who remembers the
finger-wagging denial of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a simple common-sense standpoint, if there's anything out
there that's clear to the people it's that the president wagged his
finger at 'em a year ago and he actually lied,'' said Grassley,
heading for the trial. ``People back home might throw up their arms
and say, ``Why, ye gods, of all the things we know the president
did, he lied.'''
</P>
<P>
   The senator took this problem with him back into the trial as
the Senate doors closed once more, interrupting the scraps of
debate to be heard increasingly in the corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be saying this in my, uh ...'' began Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., during a recess, catching himself before providing
his undelivered trial speech. ``Let's say one of the things I'm
contemplating,'' he began again, finding safety in more general
language.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those who came forward on television displayed the problem any
senator will have in trying to discuss a verdict with any sense of
mastery in the face of the mass of confusing scandal details
constituents have been exposed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a murky area,'' said Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.,
pondering the Lewinsky gifts returned to the president as he
explained his vote before the cameras. He tried to take evidence
disputes in series. ``Now what about the suggestion of coaching?''
he went on. But before long, whether in mercy or despair, the
plainspoken lawmaker dropped the role of senatorial Hercule Poirot,
announcing, ``I'm going to skip,'' and cutting to the meat of his
decision to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   Another senator for acquittal, James Jeffords, R-Vt., was a
belt-and-suspenders man, issuing a detailed printed statement and
also going on television to broadcast his acquittal decision.
Speaking as a former prosecutor, he offered the most blunt opinion
of the day on the perjury article: ``Get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Those scratching around for post-impeachment hope in the Capitol
could stroll just a half-block to the House side of the building,
tracing the sound of happy laughter emanating from the Rules
Committee room. A simple ice cream party was under way as a welcome
from the new chairman, David Dreier, R-Calif. ``A new phase of
civility,'' said Dreier amid colored balloons and an assortment of
ice creams and sorbets that seemed a world away from high crimes
and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the Capitol tunnel that senators use to reach their
offices, Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., hurried past with
the latest intelligence from the closed trial: ``Most people want
to get it over with and get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., would entertain no questions about
his verdict. But as the Senate elevator doors closed on him, he did
accept a question on when the impeachment ordeal will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope in my lifetime,'' his reply rang out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
