<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JETS ATTACK IRAQI TARGETS AFTER BAGHDAD VIOLATES ZONE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (jw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a weeklong lull in the fighting, American and
British warplanes attacked air-defense sites in Iraq on Wednesday
after three waves of Iraqi MIG jets flew deep into the no-flight
zone over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The American and British jets made no effort to pursue the Iraqi
jets, which quickly retreated. Instead, they struck six targets
linked to two separate antiaircraft sites in southern Iraq, defense
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, the officials said, were in keeping with the
Pentagon's new, more aggressive strategy to allow pilots, when
provoked, to attack any military target, not just those that
threaten them directly.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's official news agency reported that ``criminal enemy
bombing'' killed one civilian and wounded several others, but
Pentagon officials said they could not confirm that. Iraq has in
the past issued casualty assertions that were false, although in
one instance last month, the Pentagon acknowledged that an American
missile had gone astray and struck a residential neighborhood. Iraq
said that that strike killed 11 people, but U.S. officials said
they could not confirm that information.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's strikes were the first in eight days. Foul weather
had limited patrols in the no-flight zones, which the United States
and its allies created after the 1991 Persian Gulf war to protect
rebellious ethnic groups in the north and south. The United States
and Britain also curtailed flights over the weekend, out of respect
for King Hussein of Jordan, who died on Sunday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's strikes, six American F-15E's and four British
GR-1 Tornado jets attacked a surface-to-air missile-launcher near
the city of Tallil, as well as radar and other air-defense sites
there and near An Najaf.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Joseph LaMarca, a spokesman for the U.S. Central Command,
which oversees American forces in the region, said the jets
appeared to have hit each of the six targets they attacked.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sites had threatened the American or British pilots,
either by opening fire or using their radar to track their jets, he
said. Under the more aggressive strategy, the allied pilots are now
patrolling with potential targets already in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we know and we look at different targets that we
would strike ahead of time,'' LaMarca said in a telephone interview
from the Central Command's headquarters at MacDill Air Force Base
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi incursions fit a pattern of defiance by Saddam
Hussein, the Iraqi president, who vowed to challenge foreign
control of Iraqi after the American and British strikes on Iraq in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The jets _ Soviet-made MIG-23s and MIG-25s _ penetrated as many
as 60 miles into the southern no-flight zone. Iraqi jets also flew
into the northern zone Wednesday, but that did not prompt
retaliatory strikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
