<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-SICKOUT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge orders American Airlines pilots to ground sickout
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston and Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal judge bluntly ordered American Airlines
pilots to stop a five-day sickout that grounded 1,000 flights and
disrupted travel to major cities.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall in Dallas issued sarcastic
comments Wednesday along with an order for pilots to resume both
normal work schedules and talks with management over how to absorb
pilots from recently acquired Reno Air.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would look up bad labor relations in the dictionary,
you would have an American Airlines logo beside it,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   When lawyers for American's pilot union argued there was no
``clear proof'' the union orchestrated the sick-out, Kendall
replied, ``Are you actually telling me all these pilots are really
sick? Have you notified the Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   Pilot union President Rich Lavoy said he had no way to predict
how many pilots will return to work or how soon, but he added the
union won't appeal the order.
</P>
<P>
   The sickouts forced Fort Worth, Texas-based American to cancel
44 percent of its flights. The effect was evident at Hartsfield
International Airport, even though American handles only 2 percent
of the traffic there.
</P>
<P>
   The line at American's ticket counter snaked almost out the door
at one point Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Turner of Chicago had been told by American he could
catch a connecting flight in Atlanta to Rio de Janeiro if he left
home at 5:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to leave my house eight hours early to just to get
here,'' Turner said. When he got to Atlanta, he found out his
American connection was canceled. Eventually he was booked on the
Brazilian carrier Varig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Varig. Is that a good airline?'' he asked as he headed for the
gates. ``I've never heard of them.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman yelled obscenities before leaving the ticket counter
in frustration. But most quietly bided their time, hoping the
airline would fix its mess or get them a seat on another carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, which handles 80 percent of the traffic at
Hartsfield, said seats on flights to Miami and Dallas, which are
American hubs, were especially high in demand.
</P>
<P>
   The job action began Saturday after the sides failed to settle
pay and job issues linked to the Reno Air deal.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during Wednesday's hearing, Kendall called a
two-hour break and invited the two sides to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem to me like a bunch of grown-up people with
cumulative IQs couldn't sit down and figure this out without
disrupting several hundred thousand people,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
