<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL AMENDS SCHOOL SOCIAL PROMOTION BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A bill aimed at curbing social promotion in
Texas schools sailed through the Senate Education Committee on
Wednesday, but not before it was amended to make enforcement
contingent on ``sufficient'' funding from the state.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted 9-0 to send Senate Bill 1 to the full
Senate, although sponsor Sen. Teel Bivins, the committee chair,
acknowledged that Gov. George W. Bush may not be happy with the
amendment's vague wording. The amendment does not define what
constitutes ``sufficient'' funding.
</P>
<P>
   Social promotion is the practice of moving schoolchildren ahead
in grade levels despite their failure to master lower-level
academic material.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue to let this happen, then it is we who are
failing, not the students,'' said Bivins, R-Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, public schoolchildren in grades three, five and
eight could be held back in school if they cannot pass Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills tests in reading. Fifth-graders also
would have to pass TAAS tests in math, and eighth-graders would
have to pass additional exams in math and writing.
</P>
<P>
   But under the amendment offered by Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas,
students, teachers and school districts would not be held
accountable under the law if the Legislature does not adequately
fund it.
</P>
<P>
   West said too often the Legislature ``sends a bunch of money''
in the first biennium of a new program, only to shift funding to
local levels in subsequent budget cycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the intent of the state of Texas to make it (anti-social
promotion programs) a priority in perpetuity,'' he said. If future
legislative sessions fail to continue financial support, he said,
the message should then be ``the Legislature ... is supportive of
social promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Bill Ogden, R-Bryan, and Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound,
voted against the amendment because of the vague wording. Ogden
said it would lead to interminable lawsuits, but Bivins said he
would work with West on language that would set objective measures
for determining sufficient funding levels.
</P>
<P>
   As for rushing it through committee with the vague wording on
funding, he said he did so ``probably because of my ego.'' The bill
is his top priority this session and a unanimous committee vote was
important to him.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bill will be debated next week on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The bill emphasizes early detection of reading problems,
beginning in kindergarten, and intensive instruction for those with
problems. The measure also would require that students be given at
least three opportunities to pass the TAAS test before being
subjected to possible retention in their grade level. An appeals
committee consisting of the child's parent, teacher and principal
or principal's designee could promote a student despite repeated
failures on the TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   All the major educators' organizations representing teachers,
administrators and school boards testified in favor of the bill, as
did several school superintendents and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kauffman of the Mexican-American Legal Defense and Education
Fund was one of the few voices in opposition to SB 1. He said the
proposal places too much emphasis on one test and would
discriminate against ethnic minorities and poor students, who
historically have scored lower on the TAAS than white students and
those from high-income homes. He also told lawmakers that the
appeals committee process is inadequate and that teachers and
principals would feel pressured to hold students back, given the
high priority the governor and key lawmakers have placed on the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   A key component in making the anti-social promotion bill work,
lawmakers and educators said, is getting teachers trained to detect
and correct reading problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has set aside about $200 million in his budget to fund the
program, most of which would go for teacher training. The Texas
Education Agency is developing a course that will be offered to
teachers, beginning this summer. Teachers who volunteer for the
program would get a $150 stipend for taking the course.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gregory Luna, D-San Antonio, however, said a flaw in the
bill is its failure to specify that only those teachers who have
completed the TEA training course could teach the intensive,
accelerated classes. The committee rejected his effort to amend the
bill to make such a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also approved other amendments that would reduce
the maximum student-teacher ratio in the intensive reading
instructions to 16-1 and mandates that the district provide
transportation to children required to attended extended-day and
summer programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
