<HEADLINE>
SHIP SINKS IN INDONESIA; 280 FEARED DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDONESIA-TIMOR) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ At least 280 people are feared drowned
after a passenger ship sank last weekend between the Indonesian
islands of Borneo and Sumatra, port officials said Wednesday. There
were different reports about the number of people on board, but an
official named Zainuddin said the Belize-registered Harta Rimba,
carrying more than 300 people and a cargo of timber, sank off
Tambelan island at midnight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A passing cargo ship rescued 19 people but some 280 are missing,
Zainuddin said.
</P>
<P>
   The ship sank about 500 miles north of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kompas reported Wednesday that the ship was bound
for Pekanbaru on Sumatra, Indonesia's largest island, and was
carrying 332 people including a seven-man crew.
</P>
<P>
   It quoted the vessel's captain, who is in a hospital in
Pontianak, Indonesia, as saying that his ship sank in rough seas
after the pumps failed. The crew distributed about 200 life jackets
and some people had to cling to oil drums or wood planks to try to
stay afloat, the captain was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors were collected in two batches _ 10 on Sunday and
nine the next day _ as rough seas and rain squalls hampered the
rescue effort, said Ari Jos Karauwan, captain of the MV Hamada, the
cargo ship that picked them up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      02-10 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN HUNTERS SLOW THE MARKET'S SLIDE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks meandered narrowly Wednesday as bargain
hunters stabilized some battered high-technology issues even as
most Internet companies continued to slide.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market finished virtually unchanged, edging lower by
one-twentieth of 1 percent, following Tuesday's third-worst-ever
drubbing in point terms. But it was a performance that offered
little reassurance that the 8 percent retreat from its Feb. 1
record close has ended.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did analysts take much encouragement from a bounce in the
session's final half hour that lifted the Dow Jones industrials and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 to gains of about half of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little concerned that earnings expectations are a
little high and valuations are full,'' said John Ballen, chief
strategist at MFS Investment Management in Boston. In coming weeks,
he said, ``You could have a pretty choppy market.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also expressed concern about the relative paucity of
stocks moving higher of late and a persistent erosion among a large
number of lesser issues. For example the Standard &AMP; Poor's 400
index of midsize stocks and the S&AMP;P 600 index of
small-capitalization stocks each slumped Thursday and are down more
than 8 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500, by contrast, which includes IBM, Intel, Cisco and
other high-tech heavyweights, is down less than half of 1 percent
so far in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Competition from rising interest rates, according to Mary
Farrell of Paine Webber, is also troubling stock investors. ``It's
backed the market into a trading range,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow's blue chip industrials showed a gain of
44.28 points, at 9,177.31, with a 6 1/2-point surge in IBM, to 168
7/8, accounting for 60 percent of it. J. P. Morgan was the second
biggest contributor, rising 3 5/16 to 103 13/16. General Electric,
up 2 to 97 15/16, was third.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, which lost a lawsuit involving a California
smoker, was the Dow's biggest drag, off 3 15/16 to 41 7/16 on
volume of 25.4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet stocks were lower, partly on disappointment that
Lycos commanded less than expected in the search-directory's buyout
deal announced on Tuesday. Lycos tumbled another 7, to 87 1/4,
after trading as low as 77. Amazon.com fell 2 9/16 to 97 7/16,
bringing its five-day loss to 22.5 percent. Its shares are worth
less than half their Jan. 8 peak of 199 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft inched up 9/16 to 160 5/8 as its chief financial
officer, Gregory B. Maffei, told a Goldman Sachs technology
conference in New York that he finds skidding prices for Internet
stocks a boon as his company explores acquisitions and partnerships
in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Bramwell, president of Bramwell Capital Management,
said on returning from the conference that the mood was ``really
upbeat'' and said she was skeptical about a widely -shared
prediction of a lull in computer-related business following the
surge from addressing the year-2000 computer clock problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if it will continue to be rolling past 2000,'' she
said, with electronic commerce becoming ``an enormous business.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, often a haven for nervous investors, were mostly
higher by large fractions Thursday, with Pfizer up 1 1/2 to 126 3/4
and Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn up 1 1/2 to 54 1/4, the latter reporting
sharply higher fourth-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declines outnumbered advances
1,855 to 1,177, with only 19 stocks making new highs and 95 new
lows. Volume was relatively light for the third consecutive day, at
721.7 million shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
