<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BANK-BOS &LR;      02-10 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED MISMANAGEMENT OF $50 BILLION RESERVE SHAKES RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ How much skulduggery does it take to shock people in a
country widely thought to be one of the most corrupt in the world?
</P>
<P>
   How about mismanaging as much as $50 billion of the country's
reserves by Russia's Central Bank?
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the accusations leveled by Russia's outgoing
general prosecutor, Yury Skuratov, just before he resigned last
week, citing health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1998, Skuratov charged, the Central Bank
allegedly paid an obscure offshore assets-management company to
handle the money, instead of managing it itself, as central banks
usually do. Western economists here call the practice unprecedented
for the caretaker of a country's national wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov also accused Central Bank executives of illegal sales
of government property and of maintaining extravagant lifestyles at
state expense.
</P>
<P>
   In many places, such charges lodged by a top law-enforcement
official would set off a political firestorm. Outside Russia, the
allegations are bound to raise even more doubts about the wisdom of
granting Moscow's request for new loans. But inside Russia, where
benefiting from government funds has been a traditional path to
upward mobility, the reaction has been rather quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank chairman, Viktor Gerashchenko, even confirmed
the practice, if not the sums involved. Gerashchenko said Russia
needed to hide its assets to avoid seizure by creditors owed
billions of dollars of Soviet-era debt that Russia has promised to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Gerashchenko said that in 1994 the Central Bank transferred $1.4
billion to the accounts of FIMACO, a company registered on the
Island of Jersey, off England.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time Russia was involved in difficult negotiations
with the (creditors), and there was a probability that the
country's foreign property could be seized,'' Gerashchenko said in
comments reported by The Moscow Times. ``FIMACO was set up to avoid
complications.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Skuratov's letter, which was handed out to members
of the State Duma lower house of parliament, the Central Bank
allowed FIMACO to handle $37.3 billion, 9.98 billion Deutsche
marks, 379.9 billion yen, 11.98 billion French francs and 862.6
million British pounds. This amounts to almost $50 billion at
current rates of exchange, and, Skuratov said, included funds from
multibillion-dollar loan packages from the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Western economists have been scratching their heads in
amazement. Eric Kraus, head of the fixed incomes desk at Dresdner
Bank's Moscow office, called the allegations and Gerashchenko's
partial confirmation ``astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraus said he thought the $50 billion figure was ``doubtless
exaggerated'' because the Central Bank ``never had that much to
manage.'' But he was left with more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who actually managed this money, and how was it invested, what
were the results, how much was charged for this service, to whom
did the profits go, and where is the money now?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows. Nor will they ever, if some Russian politicians
have their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to launch a criminal proceeding only on the
basis of the transfer of money to this firm,'' remarked lawmaker
Georgy Luntovsky, who chairs the Duma's committee that oversees the
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say nothing in Russian law prevents the Central Bank
from acting as it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing illegal about commercial activities by the
Central Bank that do not always coincide with the interests of the
state,'' said Georgy Bovt, political commentator of the liberal
daily Segodnya.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bovt said the government should investigate whether
anyone profited personally from the offshore investing of
government funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bovt and other analysts suggested that Skuratov's charges
stemmed from an investigation into the causes of Russia's financial
collapse last August, when the government devalued the ruble and
defaulted on $40 billion of domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
   The target of this investigation had been former Central Bank
chairman Sergei Dubinin, whom Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
replaced with Gerashchenko when Primakov was appointed in
September. But the current allegations have dragged Gerashchenko, a
former Soviet Central Banker who also held Russia's top bank post
from 1992 to 1994, into the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe this is what forced Skuratov to resign. Others say
the prosecutor's downfall was caused by another probe that came
into the open last week with a series of raids by security agents
on companies linked to the influential financier and power broker
Boris Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps both Skuratov's ouster and Berezovsky's troubles are
connected with Primakov's recent moves to consolidate the powers he
received when Yeltsin informally pass over day-to-day control of
the country to him last fall. Whatever the explanation, none of
this is improving the image of Russia's leaders abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are working out their differences in this way in public,
and no one is thinking how Western creditors are looking at this,''
Bovt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anastasia Saschikhin of the Globe's Moscow bureau contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
