<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-THEATER-ART-2TAK     02-10 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BIRTHPLACE OF THE METHOD, THE PROCESS MAKES ITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
Liz Welch has written about theater for Mirabella and Frank
magazine in London. 
(af) 
 By LIZ WELCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crowd at the Actors Studio Free Theater at Raw
Space spills into the small lobby at 529 W. 42nd St. A mix of young
people and old, their names are checked off a clipboard as they
arrive. There is a smattering of theater celebrity; the playwright
Romulus Linney and his daughter, the actress Laura Linney, came to
a recent performance of Clifford Odets' ``Awake and Sing!,'' as did
Ellen Adler of the Stella Adler Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   During intermission in the big barnlike space, people talk about
what they have just seen. This is a crowd that goes to plays and
performances like connoisseurs: on the lookout for the unusual.
That is certainly true of the price: it's free _ as it has been
since Arthur Penn, the president of the Actors Studio, created the
Free Theater in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, 76, has put on his director's hat for ``Power Failure'' by
Larry Gelbart, 75, a longtime friend of the stage and film
director. Based on the structure of ``La Ronde,'' involving 10
scenes with two people each, it opened last Friday and runs through
March 7. Two more plays follow in this season's series: Vaclav
Havel's ``Increased Difficulty of Concentration,'' directed by
Arthur Storch, in late March, and ``Passion Play'' by Peter
Nichols, to be directed by Elinor Renfield, in May.
</P>
<P>
   The series at Raw Space began when the famed Actors Studio, the
home of the naturalistic style of acting known as the Method, was
celebrating its 50th birthday. At the time, Penn was said to be
trying to widen the perception of the organization as well as
encouraging the creation of new plays with large casts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has presented plays by, among others, Jay Presson
Allen, Liz Swados, Jack Gelber and Migdalia Cruz. While there is no
charge, those wishing to attend must register with Ticket Central
at (212) 279-4200.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process,'' Penn said, ``has gone out of American theater
because of economics.'' It is important for actors to inhabit a
play, he said, and work through its problems, which takes time. The
``process'' applies to playwriting as well as to acting, Penn said,
and his mission is to have a ``place where a playwright can see a
play develop.'' As a result, critics are not invited.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Judith Ivey starred in ``Trudy Blue,'' a play by
Marsha Norman about a cancer victim. Ms. Ivey found the series ``a
great safety net'' and said: ``You walk the tightrope and, if you
fall, you come back the next night, get back up and find a change.
That kind of risk-taking doesn't happen in commercial venues.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Jackson, a board member of the Actors Studio, who played
the mother in ``Awake and Sing!'' said, ``It's a sacrifice for the
actors, yet it gives you freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Penn, the actors receive $100 a week for four weeks
of rehearsal and a total of 24 performances. ``That is all we are
allowed,'' by Equity, he said. ``We are doing it really on the
skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has helped is the television series ``Inside the
Actors Studio.'' ``Bravo licensed it and we began to receive a
certain amount of royalties,'' Penn said, though he would not
specify the figure. ``We are a not-for-profit organization, so I
thought: `What are we going to do? Why not start a live theater to
put actors to work on a project with playwrights who feel protected
to come and work.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Equity was wonderful about it,'' he added. ``We went to Equity
and explained that this was going to be a free theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Another windfall was the dollar-a-year lease, a handshake
agreement, Penn said, between himself and David Buckley, who
manages Raw Space. The deal will remain, Buckley said, ``as long as
Penn keeps his promise: free theater.''
</P>
<P>
   As Penn remembers it: ``When I first went to Buckley, he said,
`If you bring the Actors Studio here, it will validate this space.'
Raw Space was very generous. They said, `If you want to turn this
space into a theater, we will charge you a dollar a year.' '' In
exchange, Penn agreed to build the theater, which, according to
Gary Richards, the Free Theater's executive producer, cost roughly
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A couple of other windfalls didn't hurt. ``I called my friend
Hugh Hardy, the architect who did the New Amsterdam Theater, and we
designed it,'' Penn said. ``Robert Wankel, the secretary-treasurer
of the Actors Studio, is also on the executive board of the Shubert
Organization, so when they changed the seats in the Shubert
Theater, we got them.''
</P>
<P>
   Raw Space, part of a former Army Reserve Training Center (thus
the name of the Armory co-op in the adjoining building), is now a
35,000-square-foot theater and studio rental complex. In addition
to the 99-seat Actors Studio Free Theater, it houses a 35-seat
theater used by the Sage Theater company, and a 75-seat theater for
hire.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 rental studios _ ``The Civil War,'' the forthcoming
Broadway musical by Frank Wildhorn, has rehearsed in one; the
touring production of Wildhorn's ``Jekyll and Hyde'' in another _ a
camera rental shop, a sound stage, and a control room for
small-scale television productions.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbart, for one, is pleased about the chance to revise ``Power
Failure'' at Raw Space. ``Arthur and his work are not about making
product,'' Gelbart said. ``They are about making theater.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked on the script at his home in Los Angeles, sending
rewrites by fax, and arrived in New York the first week of February
for rehearsals with a cast that includes Earle Hyman, Richard Kind
and Joe Ragno.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbart and Penn met in the 1950s when Gelbart was writing jokes
for Bob Hope and Penn was a floor manager for the Colgate Comedy
Hour. Years later, Penn asked his friend to create a modern version
of Ben Jonson's ``Volpone.'' Gelbart's answer was ``Sly Fox,''
starring George C. Scott, directed by Penn on Broadway in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbart, who has hit the trifecta in television (``M-A-S-H''),
film (``Tootsie''), and theater (``A Funny Thing Happened on the
Way to the Forum''), wrote ``Power Failure'' for the 1990-91 season
of the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass. After mixed
Boston notices, he put the script in a drawer _ until Penn called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been ambivalent about the work,'' Gelbart
acknowledged. ``The problem is when you pick up a program that
reads `M-A-S-H,' `Tootsie' and `Forum,' that suggests you are in
for another laugh riot. This is not that. I think the most mature
thing about `Power Failure' is that I was willing to take off the
red nose and not be a clown.''
</P>
<P>
   While the structure of ``Power Failure'' is based on
Schnitzler's play ``Reigen'' (popularly known as ``La Ronde''), it
is much less about a sexual rondelay than the current ``Blue Room''
by David Hare on Broadway, also based on the Schnitzler play.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of encounters begins with a female journalist
interviewing a man on Death Row accused of murdering his wife and
children. The man recounts a dream in which someone is eating his
wife's hand, ``like ladyfingers.'' He says later, ``Who should be
me. In the movie. ... I know it's a wild shot. Tom Hanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelbart said: ``It is interesting to see when the first laugh
comes. Like, is it O.K. to laugh? The laugh stays uncertain because
it veers between pitch black and bright orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the play through the ``process,'' Penn said, helped work
through the kinks. ``The brilliant bits,'' he said, ``come out of
mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
