A9873 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMR-PILOTS-ART-568&AMP;AD     02-10 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-ART-568&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE ORDER AMERICAN AIRLINES' PILOTS TO RETURN TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
  (See related story, VACATION-TRAVEL) 
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge issued an order on Wednesday for pilots at
American Airlines to return to work, apparently ending five days of
labor unrest that has grounded more than 2,500 flights and
inconvenienced tens of thousands of passengers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The order came none too soon for American, the country's
second-largest carrier, which canceled 906 flights on Wednesday, 40
percent of its 2,250 flights daily. It was the worst day since
hundreds of pilots began calling in sick on Saturday in a dispute
over American's recent purchase of Reno Air, a small airline in the
West. Without the court's intervention, the dispute threatened to
disrupt travel during the Presidents Day weekend, when flights at
most airlines are expected to be full.
</P>
<P>
   American said it expected most of the pilots to return to work.
Nonetheless, it said it would still have to cancel several hundred
flights on Thursday because many of its planes were out of position
because of the disruption. The airline said it expected service to
be back to normal by the weekend. It also announced that passengers
affected by this week's cancellations would be allowed to
reschedule their flights without penalty or to receive full
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing in Dallas on Wednesday, U.S. District Court Judge
Joe Kendall castigated both the company, which had sought the court
order, and the Allied Pilots Association, the union that represents
American's 9,200 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's silly for us to even be here,'' he said. ``It's like
killing a gnat with a sledgehammer.''
</P>
<P>
   After listening to both sides, he agreed that the sickout was
illegal and ordered the pilots to return to the cockpit, warning
them that he would hold them in contempt if they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders vowed to abide by the order, which barred the
pilots' association from making any concerted efforts to encourage
pilots to call in sick or otherwise withhold their services. But
the union has contended all along that the sickout was a
grass-roots protest that it did not control.
</P>
<P>
   There were 2,077 pilots out sick on Wednesday, American said.
Normally about 400 are on the sick list at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to scrupulously comply with the order,'' said
Brian Mayhew, a captain and vice president of the union. ``That
will not remove the elements of frustration and anger that is in
the pilot group as a result of the fact that the company is not
addressing our core concerns in the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between American and the pilots centers on how
American integrates Reno Air, the carrier in Nevada that American
bought in December for $124 million. American said it would take a
year to 18 months to integrate Reno's 25 airplanes and 300 pilots
into its operations. But the union says American is violating its
contract with the union, which requires all flying at the airline
to be done by its members. It is demanding that American integrate
Reno faster and pay pilots at both carriers as if the merger has
been completed.
</P>
<P>
   American's terminals at airports nationwide were largely quiet
on Wednesday, though passengers continued to complain of long
delays and poor service from American personnel. The airline
estimated that about 90,000 passengers were inconvenienced by the
day's cancellations and said it was doing its best to accommodate
passengers from canceled flights on later departures or on rival
airlines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the flights canceled at John F. Kennedy International
Airport in New York yesterday were five to San Francisco, two to
Los Angeles and two to Heathrow Airport in London.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Koumers said he had waited on the telephone for two hours
Tuesday night to try to find out the status of his trip to the
British Virgin Islands before finally giving up. He and his wife,
Jackie, arrived at Kennedy Airport from their home on Long Island
on Wednesday morning with their two daughters, ages 1 and 3, only
to find that their 11:30 a.m. flight to Puerto Rico had been
canceled. American then booked them on a Tower Air flight departing
nearly 12 hours later, at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent 60 bucks to get here in the limo with all the luggage
and the girls,'' he said. ``Now they're going nuts. It's definitely
a hassle, but we're going to go anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Karla Speed, a caterer from Dallas, and her husband got as far
as Miami International Airport on their way to Costa Rica to
celebrate their first wedding anniversary. After spending the night
in an airport hotel on Tuesday, they were hoping to get on a 6 p.m.
flight on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had planned a very expensive trip in a resort, and we got a
honeymoon suite booked after lots of trouble,'' she said. ``Now
it's all ruined. This has just been terrible. I'm breaking out in
hives.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
