<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9876 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CDROM-SFCHRON &LR;      02-10 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDROM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CD recorders have become cheap enough to use at home  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
You no longer need to be a major recording studio or a multimedia
software developer to produce your own compact discs and CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   All you need is a machine that sells for as low as $199, and
blank CDs that go for about $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   The incredible dropping prices of &UR;  &LR; CD recorders have sparked a
surge of home use. People are using them for multimedia projects,
backing up their data and making their own party-mix music CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the devices are built into stereo systems and personal
computers, while others are separate machines that can be moved
between PCs and stereos. Sales of machines to burn your own CD have
more than doubled in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Kristina Woolsey of Kentfield bought a CD recorder last year
when her daughter Erika was graduating from the Ross School eighth
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more interested in art than technology, and she had the
idea to take all the kids' faces (in her graduating class) and
morph one into the next,'' Woolsey said. When Erika completed the
project, she used the new machine to burn 50 CDs, one for each of
her classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The machines rely on a laser to literally burn the digital code
into the blank plastic disc. There is no smell or physical
manifestation of the burn, and people describe the process as
fairly easy to master.
</P>
<P>
   A song can be recorded onto a CD in less than two minutes; a
full CD can take up to half an hour to record.
</P>
<P>
   Music CDs _ even those with tunes &LR;   &LR; downloaded from the Internet
_ can be played anywhere. Software CDs can be designed to work on
both Macintosh or Windows-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquity of CDs has contributed to the recorders'
popularity. People have CD players not only in their stereo
systems, but also in their cars and portable CD devices that they
carry around with them. Almost every computer sold nowadays comes
with a CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   The familiarity with music CDs has led to a surging popularity
of CD recorders, said analyst Kevin Hause at IDC, a high-tech
research firm. Philips makes a dual deck CD player-recorder so
people can create custom mixes on CDs. ``They're doing very, very
well with that. They're having trouble keeping up with demand,'' he
said, noting sales of more than 500,000 units in the past six
months. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CDROM11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The recorders come in two flavors: those that can burn a disc
only once, and ``rewritable`' machines that can record over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   The Woolseys of Kentfield use their CD recorder for a wide
variety of projects. Erika's brother Matt, 16, a sophomore at Marin
Academy high school, records his own piano and saxophone playing
onto CDs, records songs off of other CDs, makes CDs for class
projects and also uses them to store discs from a summer job with a
multimedia studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go down to an electronics store, buy a (blank) CD for
a buck, and put whatever you want on it,'' Matt Woolsey said.
``What's really good about the CD is, if a file's really big, I can
just save it onto a CD.''
</P>
<P>
   He completed one school assignment on the Roman Empire by
scanning pictures from books, downloading images from the Web,
copying video clips from Grolier's multimedia encyclopedia and
writing original text. He stored the whole work on two CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's helping an English teacher at his school with a project
on ``Race, Redress and Recovery.'' A class of 14 students has
assembled writing, photos and video of what Woolsey called ``brutal
moments from history.'' A company told the teacher it would put it
all on CDs, one for each student, for $200; Woolsey is doing it for
her for free.
</P>
<P>
   As more sound and images move into the digital language of
computers, people need a place to store them. The 1.4 megabytes of
information that a floppy disk holds, and even the 100 megabytes of
a typical Zip disk, are proving inadequate for some of the
increasingly massive files.
</P>
<P>
   A CD, by comparison, holds a whopping 650 megabytes of data. But
some users are already straining the CD's capacity. Those people
are eagerly awaiting the next revolution: DVDs, or digital video
disks, which are two-sided and could hold up to 8 gigabytes of data
_ a more than tenfold increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think I could never use all this space. Now you can
never get enough,'' said Stephen Wallace, a test engineer at
Sandisk, a Sunnyvale computer chip company. He backs up his hard
drive onto a CD, and also duplicates computer games so that he can
play his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the market for CD recorders is growing phenomenally.
Mary Bourdon, a principal analyst at the San Jose market research
firm Dataquest, said 2.5 million CD recordable and rewritable
devices were sold in 1997. While the final sales figures aren't in
yet for 1998, she said manufacturers shipped as many as 6 million
units to stores, and most of those probably sold _ so sales more
than doubled from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of CDROM11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Demand for the products was truly grassroots, said Bruce Youmans,
director of marketing communications for TDK Electronics Corp.,
which makes blank CDs. ``It's one of those situations in which,
with very little heavy advertising or promotional marketing
support, but by the simple means of word of mouth, interest has
taken flight,'' Youmans said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the advent of CDs, both in computers and in music,
people have wanted to record on them. But CD recorders started out
at $125,000, which only a major studio could afford, Youmans said.
Within several years, though, that price dropped into consumers'
buying ranges of $500 and less.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Kruse, 36, recalls how ``I spent hours in my life creating
those party tapes. I'd pull out one album, record that song, then
another ... then my friends would want a copy, but I couldn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Kruse, the director of consumer products at Pinnacle
Systems, a Mountain View company, makes party CDs and can burn
multiple copies for whoever wants one.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Iampietro, 39, also works at Pinnacle, which makes hardware
and software for editing video on PCs. He uses the CD burner to
store the videos he's created.
</P>
<P>
   Iampietro has been editing video for years, he said, but putting
it on CDs is easier and more durable. ``You can always make a copy
of the CD as good as the original CD,'' he said. ``Videotape gets
worse and worse and worse, and by the time you notice, it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are downloading music off the Internet and
putting it onto CDs, which they can immediately play in their
stereos without any special technology.
</P>
<P>
   But many people still connect to the Net via telephone lines,
which can't handle many large files containing music and video.
Therefore, they prefer CDs to store those types of files.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Mann, who runs a San Francisco multimedia firm with his
brother, uses his CD burner to back up his data. With his frequent
backups, he can bring the CDs on trips and have access to his
entire hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My laptop has become my existence,'' Mann said. ``When I go on
a trip and I bring my computer with me, just having a CD-ROM with
all of my important stuff is so light in my bag, it relaxes me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
