<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-ART-70     02-10 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL RITUAL ON BANKING REGULATION BEGINS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Iowa, N.Y., Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic on political contributions by Wall Street
executives is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the annals of American politics, few lawmakers
have unwittingly done more to help members of Congress raise money
than Carter Glass and Henry Steagall, the authors of a
Depression-era law that sharply limited the cross-ownership of
commercial banks, securities firms and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 20 years or so, legislative proposals to break
down those barriers have been an annual rite of Congress, played
out invariably in turf wars between wealthy industries, competing
committee chairmen and powerful regulators who have fought to
congressional gridlock. The beneficiaries of the exercise are the
political parties and the members of three congressional
committees, who use the issue as a stalking-horse to raise millions
of dollars from those business interests who have a stake in the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997-1998 election cycle, for instance, a legislative
session in which the House of Representatives for the first time in
history passed legislation to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act, the
industries that lobbied the issue gave more than $15 million to the
members of the three committees _ House Banking, House Commerce and
Senate Banking _ and more than $42 million to political parties and
all candidates for federal offices, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan group that researches money and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The annual ritual began anew Wednesday, when top executives from
Wall Street and Main Street trooped to the House Banking Committee
to urge passage of financial services legislation that would make
it easier and less expensive for conglomerates to offer banking,
insurance and securities underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Overflowing from a committee hearing room, lobbyists lined
Capitol Hill hallways to glean the details of competing legislation
and to listen to the beginning of three days of testimony that will
feature Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman; Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, and a host of banking and securities
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is February, and like the swallows returning to
Capistrano, we return to financial modernization,'' said Rep. Bruce
Vento, D-Minn., the ranking Democrat on a House subcommittee on
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the table for a veritable feast of political
fund-raising events in the next few months, the lawmakers outlined
different proposals that, in one form or another, have been under
consideration for years. In those same years, financial
conglomerates have tried to get around the restrictions imposed by
the Glass-Steagall and Bank Holding Company acts through
complicated and expensive legal maneuvering that sets up corporate
structures to permit institutions to sell insurance, underwrite
securities and offer insured bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Competing measures were introduced by Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa,
chairman of the House Banking Committee, and Rep. John LaFalce,
D-N.Y., the committee's ranking Democrat. LaFalce's measure was
largely endorsed by the Clinton administration. But the LaFalce
measure contains as one of its main features a provision that may
doom it in the Senate: an endorsement of an older low- and
moderate-income community lending law that last year ran into
insurmountable opposition from Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, chairman
of the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who blocked a measure that had been worked out by former
Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York when he was chairman of
the banking committee, has said he intended to introduce his own
bill this month. Gramm has said Congress should not repeal the
Glass-Steagall Act without also rolling back the requirement that
regulators, when considering proposed mergers and new branches,
take into account the bank's lending record to lower- and
moderate-income customers.
</P>
<P>
   He has compared that law, the Community Reinvestment Act, to a
form of legalized extortion. Democrats have considered it a central
tenet of social fairness for a core constituency, and some aides
predicted Wednesday that although insisting on it may ultimately
mean that there will be no new banking legislation, it is far more
important politically to isolate Gramm on that issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another, longer-standing aspect of the legislative fight
concerns which regulatory agency should take the lead under any new
law. Greenspan has endorsed proposals that would require
diversified financial companies to be structured as separate
entities under one holding company. The Federal Reserve now
regulates bank holding companies and would continue to do so under
these proposals, which are part of Leach's bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration opposes that approach because it would
rob the Treasury, which oversees nationally chartered banks, from
playing a prominent role in banking issues. Rubin, in supporting
LaFalce's measure Wednesday, reiterated his long-held position that
financial conglomerates should be allowed to provide services like
securities underwriting or merchant banking through subsidiaries of
parent commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   While on one level the disagreement between Greenspan and Rubin
reflects an arcane issue of corporate governance and its
regulation, the debate has broader financial and policy
ramifications. The outcome will determine whether the Federal
Reserve, an independent agency, will regulate financial
conglomerates or whether they will fall under the supervision of
the Treasury, which is controlled by political appointments made by
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as a matter of corporate bookkeeping, the structuring
of securities or insurance departments as subsidiaries of banking
operations would mean that their activities would contribute to the
bank's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Another contentious issue is whether any new law should permit
the emerging financial behemoths to be affiliated with industrial
companies, as they are in some Asian and European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Leach proposal would permit existing financial companies
that have limited revenue from nonfinancial enterprises to continue
to exist for at least the next decade but would restrict new
affiliations between banks and commercial companies. The LaFalce
measure would permit a bank holding company to own a commercial
company, provided that the commercial company did not account for
more than 15 percent of the holding company's overall assets.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has long opposed close affiliations between
banks and industrial companies, particularly because customer bank
deposits are insured by a federally backed fund, and Rubin
expressed strong reservations Wednesday about the acceptance of
such combinations in the LaFalce bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whatever the outcome of the legislative fight, the clear
certainty is that it will fill many congressional coffers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 election cycle, the single biggest fund-raiser
from these industries, not surprisingly, was D'Amato, who was at
the center of a legislative compromise that failed. He raised more
than $1.7 million from the industries lobbying about the issue.
That figure represents the largest single block of money raised by
D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that money is not always decisive in elections, he
lost. The victor, Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., received $1.4 million
from insurance, securities firms and banking interests, more money
than any other member of the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer is now a member of the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
