<SLUG> BC-NUMBERIC-BOGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGLE QUITS NUMBERIC INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John C. Bogle Jr. abruptly resigned Wednesday from
Numeric Investors LP, a surprise move that cast a cloud over the
future of the Cambridge investment shop known for its
computer-driven style of ``quantitative'' money management.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle's sudden departure as a partner and managing director came
amid reports that he had clashed with Langdon B. Wheeler, the
firm's founder and head and a longtime friend of Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``two strong personalities'' as the reason for the
shakeup, Numeric spokesman Lynn Wickwire said Bogle, the son of
legendary Vanguard Group founder and chairman John C. ``Jack''
Bogle, had decided to pursue other opportunities. Wheeler and Bogle
Jr. both declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said Bogle, 39, and Wheeler, 51, had
disagreements over the pace at which Numeric bought and sold stocks
and that Wheeler had asked Bogle to leave last weekend. Wheeler,
who founded Numeric in 1989 and brought in his friend Bogle in 1990
as a partner, grew irritated at his sidekick's marquee status and
starring role at the firm, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Quantitative investing uses computers with sophisticated
mathematical models to crunch reams of numbers on stock prices and
earnings estimates. At Numeric -- which manages $5.5 billion,
mostly for institutions, and has 5 mutual funds -- Bogle was in
charge of the all-important research team that created and
implemented the firms two core models. He also launched and oversaw
the firm's N/I fund family, using the low-cost strategies for which
his father's firm is famed.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle and Wheeler were The Odd Couple of the investing world.
They met at the asset management division of Bos ton's State Street
Bank &AMP; Trust Co. in 1985 and forged a friendship based on a love
and talent for numbers and risk. Bogle, described by colleagues as
``extroverted, energetic, and head strong,'' is a brash Harvard MBA
``who always wanted his way,'' a former associ ate said. By
contrast, Wheeler, a Yale- educated Vietnam veteran, was ``more
introspective, quieter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their split is due to two struggling egos,'' one industry
source said. Ironical ly, it was personality clashes that led
Wellington Management Co. to fire Bogle Sr. as chief executive 25
years ago. Vanguard is now the nation's second biggest mutual fund
firm, after Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Numeric, an aggressive company that has had mixed success with
its quantitative models, is a ``momentum'' investor that chases
popular stocks. Div ing in and out of the market means Nu meric
portfolios can change their entire holdings up to three times a
year, giving them a high ``turnover'' rate. Higher turnover means
higher fees for the firm but greater costs to customers, which in
clude the Massachusetts Teachers Re tirement System. It was concern
about high turnover that led The Quantitative Group of Lincoln,
another investment shop, to ask Bogle and Wheeler to stop managing
their funds in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Numeric said a team of staffers would now manage its funds and
that Mark Engerman, a partner, would as sume Bogle's duties.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Bogle's departure was a blow to small Numeric,
which depends on human inventiveness as much as cold mathematical
logic. ``It's definitely a time of caution for the shareholders
there,'' said Jeffrey McConnell, who follows Nu meric funds for
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago fund tracker. ``John was the big
force in the development of their models, so we'll have to keep a
close eye on their funds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
