</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HOME-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SALES AT UNSEASONABLE PACE IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Matt and Tracy Teare of Arlington put their
two-family home on the market two Saturdays ago, they figured they
were getting a head start on the spring real estate season.
</P>
<P>
   To their surprise, by the end of the weekend the Teares had 19
offers, including at least one that was $10,000 above their
$249,000 asking price. ``It's shocking,'' says Matt Teare. ``At the
same time you are excited that you're selling your house and making
some money, but there's something disquieting about the whole
thing,... the amount of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Spring residential home sales market is expected to
top records set last year. Fueled by low mortgage interest rates
and a healthy economy, the demand for homes in Massachusetts and
the prices they fetch show no signs of braking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indications are that it's going to continue as the most
explosive market yet to date, more explosive than the 1980s,'' Jean
LeVaux, owner of DeWolfe New England/LeVaux in Cambridge, boldly
predicts. ``Spring started in late December.''
</P>
<P>
   While most real estate agents brace for a Spring that begins in
late February or early March and runs through late May, this year
many say consumers started shopping early, piqued perhaps by a
relatively warm winter.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a topper in Massachusetts: more than 49,456
single-family homes were sold last year, a 7.2 percent increase
over 1997, according to the Massachusetts Association of Realtors.
With increased demand came higher prices and in some locations,
inventory shortages. The average single-family home in
Massachusetts sold for $218,146, a 9.1 percent jump over the 1997
average, with Boston area homes fetching an average of $286,168, an
increase of 13.6 percent. Sales of condominiums, a favorite of
first-time buyers, climbed 17.6 percent last year, pushing the
average price of a condo to $134,161 in the state, and $164,145 in
Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer confidence is really what is driving the market, it's
that people believe tomorrow is going to be as good as today,''
said James C. Dougherty, president of the Massachusetts Association
of Realtors. Significantly, gains are being seen across the state,
from Cape Cod, where prices rose 12.2 percent last year, to the
Worcester area, where a single family home sold for an average of
$172,840 by the end of last year, a 14.8 percent gain over the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   The national median existing-home price was $131,000 during the
fourth quarter, according to statistics released Wednesday by the
National Association of Realtors, up 4.9 percent from the fourth
quarter of 1997 when the median price was $124,800. Single family
home sales in Massachusetts rose only .6 percent during that
period, while the average price of a single-family home increased
5.6 percent to $214,775, according to MAR.
</P>
<P>
   Intense demand in haute neighborhoods within Boston and
Cambridge has unleashed a kind of domino effect, pushing up prices
in neighorhoods once considered cheaper alternatives, like
Arlington, Somerville, Jamaica Plain, and parts of Dorchester. Most
segments of the market seem active -- from first-time home buyers
looking for condos to executives trading up for trophy houses in
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon has some analysts worried the market may be
poised for a repeat of 1985 -- when home prices shot up 40 percent
in one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time this cycle I am beginning to get a little
concerned about the warmth of the market,'' economist Karl `Chip'
Case said. ``I'm a little nervous that the conversation is turning
more and more to housing appreciation, because then every home
buyer becomes an unwitting speculator.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who worry about the plight of the state's dwindling
affordable housing stock say an especially active Spring season
will only intensify the scramble for more inexpensive homes and
managable rents. They point to recent studies that have shown a
marked decline in the number of minorities buying homes in Boston,
a reduction attributed to the city's escalating home prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an incredible housing crisis of affordability for most
renters, both those trying to be home buyers and those who cannot
afford their rent,'' said Lew Finfer, a longtime Boston housing
activist and organizer.
</P>
<P>
   But those with the means, it seems, are primed to buy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cape, it is consumers shopping for seaside second homes
who are fueling a buying spate. ``Basically there's only about four
waterfront properties left on the market in this area,'' said Olive
Jamieson, a broker with Meadow Marsh Real Estate in Eastham.
``Everything is selling so fast. I was trying to compile a list for
a customer coming down tomorrow, and the ones (properties) that I
set aside are now all under agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
