<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN LIFE EXECUTIVE SHAKEUP ANNOUNCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. plans a major executive shake-up
in a move to cut costs and meet higher profit goals as the
insurance giant goes public, the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the shake-up, Jim Benson, chairman and chief executive of
subsidiary New England Financial, will be put in charge of
MetLife's sprawling retail sales network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are streamlining operations across our entire enterprise,''
said Kevin Foley, a MetLife spokesman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, which take effect March 1, include dissolving the
insurer's Corporate Management Office, which made all major
decisions and created the ``perception MetLife was run by a
committee,'' according to an internal memo Wednesday by chairman
Bob Benmosche.
</P>
<P>
   The office will be replaced by nine executives, including New
England Financial's Benson, the company said. Benson, who oversaw
record 26 percent increases in premium sales at New England
Financial, is seen as a lynchpin in MetLife's strategy to rapidly
grow sales, the company said. He will take charge of MetLife's
nationwide sales force of 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the new executive group include vice chairmen Jerry
Clark and Stu Nagler, head of institutional sales Rob Henrickson,
general counsel Gary Beller, head of MetLife Auto &AMP; Home Cathy Rein
and Bill Toppeta, who will head a new client services department.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife also said it plans to cut costs by combining
administrative and marketing functions at subsidiaries, including
New England Financial, Nathan &AMP; Lewis, Texas Life and Security
First.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent moves come in the wake companywide layoffs over
the past year meant to cut non-sales costs by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife is planning to take the company public by offering
shares in an intitial public offering before the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
