<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIEBERMAN-ART     02-10 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIEBERMAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SENATOR EXPLAINS HIS PAINSTAKING DECISION TO ACQUIT THE
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-GRAMM) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At four or five points in the Senate impeachment
trial of President Clinton, Sen. Joseph Lieberman said, he came
very close to deciding that he would have to vote to convict and
remove his old friend, a man he had known and cared about for 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, though, Lieberman, D-Conn., ``pulled back from the
brink'' for a number of reasons, including the president's popular
support, he said. ``We're standing in place of the people, the
voters, and we'd be irresponsible not to take them into account.
They continue to trust him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lieberman said, ``the decision was harder than I would
have guessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about how he finally made that decision, and his
all-over-the-map feelings toward the president as he did so,
Lieberman began an hourlong interview in his office on Wednesday by
joking: ``I consider this therapy. Do you want me to lie down?''
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, the experience of the last year has been hard on
Lieberman, who is considered a bit of a moralizer and was the first
in his party to sternly reprimand the president after he admitted
his affair. On Wednesday, Lieberman called himself ``perhaps
naive'' to have felt betrayed by the president's behavior. And he
insists that the scandal has also been far more traumatic for
Clinton than most people think.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to maintain his dignity and his pride,'' Lieberman
said. ``He's told me that as president, he can't walk around
wounded and depressed.'' But Lieberman said he had seen Clinton's
remorse and believes that recent months have been awful for him and
his family. ``I've been with him,'' he said, ``and without getting
into those conversations, you just have to believe that it's been
what one would expect _ a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lieberman sees it that way. Though he generally
shares Clinton's politics, he has occasionally been critical, most
dramatically as the Democrat toughest on his fellow party members
during 1997 hearings of the Senate committee investigating possible
campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who is 56, got to know Clinton in 1970, when the
young Yale law student volunteered in Lieberman's first political
campaign, a race for a Connecticut state Senate seat. And Lieberman
was among the first to endorse his former aide as a presidential
candidate in 1992, ``with timing that was not what one would call
exquisite,'' he said on Wednesday. ``I endorsed him two days before
Gennifer Flowers'' made a sex scandal one of the first things that
many Americans ever heard about Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``So these stories had hung over his head for some time,'' the
senator said, crossing his arms over his chest. But a year ago,
when Lieberman first heard the allegations of an affair between
Clinton and a former White House intern, Monica Lewinsky, he said
he immediately felt that ``this was different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling the ground was shaking; it was like a
political earthquake,'' a time filled with great anxiety and
uncertainty, he said. ``Then we went through the finger-wagging,''
when Clinton insisted he had not had sexual relations with ``that
woman, Miss Lewinsky.'' Had the senator believed his friend then?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman sighed, clasped his hands, looked at the ceiling. ``I
was suspicious. Skeptical. But he deserved for me to say he
deserved the presumption of innocence. So in fairness, I put it
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Aug. 17 and the president's admission that there had
been an affair after all. ``That made me angry,'' Lieberman said,
suddenly jiggling his foot for all he was worth. ``I felt betrayed,
and felt that his admissions were not adequate to the facts, not
about just the relationship but lying to the country. It brewed in
me, stirred in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several generations of relatives, on vacation with Lieberman at
the Connecticut shore, gave voice to his internal debate, the
senator said. His 84-year-old mother pleaded: ``Joseph, give him
another chance. Everyone makes mistakes.'' His three children in
their 20s, on the other hand, were outraged and hurt, he said. And
his 10-year-old daughter said she would be embarrassed to go back
to school and have to face a young friend whose parents had
insisted all along that the president was lying.
</P>
<P>
   Very briefly, Lieberman considered asking Clinton to resign.
``But then I felt that unless things got terrible'' in terms of a
loss of public confidence, he said, ``that wasn't a decision for me
to make.'' Instead, on Sept. 3, he delivered a tough speech
condemning the president's behavior on a strictly moral, rather
than legal, plane.
</P>
<P>
   He and the president spoke several times around then, and on one
occasion ``had a long personal, even spiritual _ not to get too far
out here _ talk about his remorse and how he was trying to deal
with it.'' Then the House proceedings began, and Lieberman felt
himself getting angry again.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the Starr report, it reawakened so many feelings
of disappointment, almost the anger of a family member when they've
done something so stupid,'' he said, clenching his hand into a fist
and releasing it. ``And as the House managers presented the
evidence, very effectively, it brought me back to why I was so
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was swayed by the arguments of two House managers _
Reps. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas and James Rogan of California _ he
said, and particularly bothered by two things. One was Ms.
Lewinsky's suggestion that the president's secretary, Betty Currie,
had been dispatched by Clinton to retrieve gifts he had given Ms.
Lewinsky, gifts that had been subpoenaed in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   Second was Clinton's insistence, under oath, that he had somehow
carried on a physical relationship with Ms. Lewinsky without ever
touching her in any way that would meet a rather broad court
definition of sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he worried whether the president's actions might
be ``possibly not just a crime, but a high crime contrary to the
president's obligation to execute the laws. So while it might be
human nature to cover up an affair, it could also be an undermining
of his oath and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   At as many as five different points, ``I could imagine myself
voting to remove him or coming close to deciding that,'' Lieberman
said. But each time, he said, ``I asked, `Is this sordid story
justification for removing a president for the first time in our
history?''' No, he thought. Nor could he get past feeling that the
public should be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is troubling,'' he said, tapping his chest, ``but
ultimately I should not be deciding about whether he committed
crimes. The framers were clear; we're not a criminal court. One of
the shortcomings of the House case is they spent almost all their
time on perjury and obstruction of justice and not enough on
whether his behavior was a high crime or misdemeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the weakest links in the case, Lieberman said, was
the focus on what Clinton told his aides: ``How could it be
obstruction to tell aides the same lies _ I hate to use that word _
the same falsehoods he was telling the American people?''
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., filed his motion to dismiss the
case two weeks ago, Lieberman said, he finally forced himself to
decide. In the end, he felt overwhelmingly that Clinton's behavior
had not compromised his ability to govern in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, Lieberman planned to speak in the Senate,
to explain his decision and try to convince his colleagues to
provide a sense of closure by censuring the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less to condemn him and more for us and the country to
make clear that not removing him was not an exoneration,'' he said.
``We've all been through a trauma, the people and the country, and
he has, too. We've got to be about the business of reconciling,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
