</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFTER THE VERDICT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Feb. 11:
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate nears a vote on the impeachment of President
Clinton, some small measure of dignity may still be found in what
has been a depressing and tumultuous year. That will depend
primarily on whether the Senate can muster the will and unity to
censure the president after it acquits him. It would also help if
Clinton can finally summon suitable words to describe the harm he
has done to the country and the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must not bolt for the airport as soon as the trial
ends. Acquittal is the right decision, but Clinton must not go into
history without a stinging castigation by the Senate. Sens. Dianne
Feinstein and Robert Bennett have drafted a strong,
constitutionally sound censure resolution that commands broad
bipartisan support. To let a handful of opponents strangle it with
parliamentary maneuvers would deny the Senate and the nation the
chance to bring the Monica Lewinsky affair to a just and equitable
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like Trent Lott who can see beyond the narrow
horizons of their party's most conservative members must recognize
that the Senate should have the opportunity to condemn Clinton's
misconduct even as it allows him to remain in office. If Lott, who
has maintained public silence on the issue, uses his influence as
majority leader to support a censure resolution, the Senate can
defeat the filibuster and other blocking tactics threatened by Phil
Gramm, John Ashcroft and others. Apart from his misplaced support
for secret sessions, Lott has guided the Senate through the
turbulent impeachment currents with a steady, dispassionate hand.
He will mar that record if he now lets procedural gambits kill a
measure clearly favored by a substantial majority of senators,
including many in his own party such as Olympia Snowe, Mitch
McConnell and John Chafee.
</P>
<P>
   We respect but do not share the concerns of some senators that
censure might somehow skirt the constitutional remedy for dealing
with a delinquent president. Removal is the proper way for Congress
to handle high crimes and misdemeanors. In cases like this one,
however, where the president's misconduct is wrong but does not
represent a threat to the state, a formal rebuke by the Senate does
not offend the Constitution. The framers included no bar to
censure. One of the enduring strengths of American democracy is the
flexibility that the Constitution affords the government to deal
with novel and unexpected circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The stern but judicious language chosen by Ms. Feinstein, a
Democrat, and Bennett, a Republican, carefully avoids the
constitutional prohibition against legislative acts directed
against individual citizens. Coming after completion of the trial,
approval of the resolution would also not suffer from the same
constitutional problems as the ``findings of fact'' that
Republicans at one point hoped the Senate would endorse before a
final vote on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Ms. Snowe, the resolution contains an admonition to
future Congresses not to overturn it, as the Senate erased the
censure of President Andrew Jackson. The Snowe language, which
increases the bipartisan appeal of the measure, might be further
strengthened by adding that acquittal by the Senate should in no
way be read as excusing Clinton's misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gramm cloaks his opposition in constitutional arguments,
his intention is first to prevent wavering Republicans from voting
against the articles of impeachment in the expectation that they
will later be able to censure Clinton instead. His larger goal is
to keep Democrats from using censure to offset the impression that
they excused Clinton's behavior by acquitting him.
</P>
<P>
   But all these parochial calculations miss the larger point. The
country has had its fill of duplicity and partisan politicking in
this matter. Clinton disgraced himself and his office. Both Kenneth
Starr and the House have alienated the public. The Senate has a
chance to end the affair on an honorable note. So does Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, the nation will look to Clinton not for another
formalistic statement of remorse, but for an honest reckoning with
his abuse of the law and the gravity of the impeachment
proceedings. The Rose Garden rally that followed the House
impeachment vote in December was repugnant. This time Clinton needs
to step alone before the cameras and tell the American people he
knows he was not faithful to the law and understands that his
presidency has been tarnished. Only then can he try to regain the
trust of the people. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
