<SLUG> BC-DOOMSDAY-CULT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEARCHING FOR MISSING TEENS WHO MAY HAVE JOINED CULT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE JACKSON, Texas _ Police were scrambling Wednesday to
determine whether two teen-age girls _ who left goodbye notes in
their bedrooms before they disappeared _ may have fallen under the
spell of religious cultists.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investigators said, the disappearance of Harmony Olachia
and Nicole Conrad can be labeled nothing more sinister than a case
of two runaways.
</P>
<P>
   Still, authorities were taking unusual steps to make sure no
foul play is involved in the girls' vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Jackson is about 30 miles south of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-olds have not been home since Monday after a weekend
in which they asked their parents, among other things, whether the
so-called Y2K millennium bug signaled the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, described by their parents as churchgoing Christians,
left handwritten farewell notes telling their parents that they
were following God's command to leave home and asking that they not
be reported to police as runaways.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, however, that's exactly what police are calling them.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' disappearance coincides with the weekend visit of a
longtime friend of the Olachia family and her new husband, who
reportedly were on their way to a religious retreat in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The parents believe the couple convinced the teen-agers to leave
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Police, however, are not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we can't prove it's nothing more than runaways,''
said Lake Jackson police Lt. Dale Davis. ``We still can't prove
these people left with (the couple).``
</P>
<P>
   Davis said police have been unable to confirm that the couple
are affiliated with any sort of cult, religious or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he has five investigators working on the case and has
talked with the FBI and the State Department for help in contacting
authorities in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, before they disappeared, the girls each had
discussions with their parents about whether they should a follow a
vision from God, their parents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Harmony fell under the influence of these people,''
said Carol Ann Olachia, 50.
</P>
<P>
   The missing girls spent three hours Saturday talking with the
visiting couple, the Olachias said. They said the woman, 21, is a
longtime friend of the family who recently was discharged from the
Coast Guard and has been living with her 27-year-old husband near
Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Olachias, however, said they have no idea what matters were
discussed between the couple and the girls. They said the couple
never expressed any strong religious beliefs concerning doomsday
predictions, including the so-called Y2K millennium bug _ the
belief by some people that computers will malfunction at the start
of the year 2000, possibly threatening governments and economic
systems with collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had nothing to tell us something was wrong,'' said Ray
Olachia, 56, a retired maintenance foreman at Dow Chemical Co.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of both girls expressed doubt that the handwritten
goodbye letters were genuine and said the thoughts expressed in
them were the products of brainwashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A practiced speech is what it was,'' said Nicole's father,
Craig Conrad, 39.
</P>
<P>
   No arrest warrants have been issued against the Florida couple
or an unidentified third man who was traveling with them, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have notified authorities, however, to detain the brown
Ford pickup they reportedly are driving that bears Texas license
plate XHV95R.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping they get stopped,'' said Davis of the Lake
Jackson police. ``If they haven't crossed the border yet, they're
not going to now without getting stopped.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
