<HEADER>
A9893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      02-10 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS OF REPORT SUGGEST FURTHER DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Olympic officials boast that the time-honored
practice of rich countries helping athletes from poor countries is
the noblest expression of the ideal of a global ``Olympic family.''
</P>
<P>
   But buried in the report about Salt Lake City Olympic
organizers' ethical lapses is an e-mail exchange that casts a far
more nefarious light on the US Olympic Committee and its motives
for providing financial aid to Third World athletes. The e-mails
suggest US support for Sudanese runners was linked to a vote by an
International Olympic Committee member from Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Tuesday also details how a former top USOC
official who was involved in the e-mail exchange had secret
consulting deals with Salt Lake organizers and funneled money to an
IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the consulting contracts and the e-mail messages
raise larger questions about whether the USOC was more deeply
involved than previously known in the questionable practices that
have rocked the Olympic movement. At the very least, they suggest
that the USOC _ which has largely escaped criticism in the scandal
_ countenanced a see-no-evil climate in which corruption
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the new focus on the activities of the USOC puts a
different spin on the longstanding dependency between rich and poor
Olympic countries. While it long has been billed as an altruistic
system of sharing wealth, the new information suggests the
financial support has at least as much to do with bolstering the
candidacies of would-be Olympic host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tuesday's report, by an independent ethics panel of
the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, appeared likely to trigger more
expulsions of IOC members. The report linked an additional 10 IOC
members to the scandal, bringing to 24 the number under scrutiny;
nine already have resigned or been expelled. There were 115 members
before the revelations began in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC remains fully committed to investigating and taking
action based on all available evidence,'' the IOC said in a
statement Wednesday from Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, a top USOC official acknowledged that
the e-mails leave the impression of an attempt to buy the vote of
an IOC member, but he insisted that was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things are done innocently, and 10 years later, you
see them under a different spotlight and you see them in a
different context,'' said USOC executive director Dick Schultz.
``The e-mails are unfortunate in that they have a tendency to
create a scenario that I don't think existed.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail exchange involved a deal made in 1993 and 1994 under
which Salt Lake Olympic organizers agreed to pay the training
expenses of three Sudanese athletes who planned to compete in the
1996 Summer Games in Atlanta. The payments, which ultimately
reached $40,000, began in October 1994 and continued until August
1996, when the Atlanta Games were held.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1995, six months after Salt Lake had been awarded the
2002 Winter Olympics, local organizers were looking to unload the
Sudanese athletes' expenses on the USOC. On Nov. 11, 1995, three
USOC officials discussed that proposal in an exchange of computer
messages.
</P>
<P>
   First, Alfredo LaMont, then the USOC's director of international
relations and protocol, wrote an e-mail to Jim Page, the USOC's
assistant executive director for sport. In it, LaMont stressed that
``we need to help pay our debt to the Sudanese IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   Page balked at picking up those costs and inquired how the debt
was acquired. In response, LaMont wrote, ``A lot of promises were
made to secure votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Page wrote that he feared the money for Sudanese runners
would take resources away from US athletes. LaMont dismissed the
concern by saying, ``You can take it away from the additional
revenue we will ALL benefit from after having won the 2002 Games
for SLC.''
</P>
<P>
   With Page and LaMont at odds, in stepped Tom Wilkinson, the
USOC's executive director for administration. He wrote an e-mail
that said flatly, ``Seems to me a deal is a deal and Sudan
delivered. Games aren't that far away. Seriously doubt these three
guys will take anything away from any athlete we have training
here. May need Sudan again in the future. Don't burn bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the ballot was secret, there is no way to know whether
Sudan ``delivered.'' Sudan's IOC member, General Zein El Abdin
Mohamed Ahmed Abdel Gadir, was among those expelled. The Salt Lake
report said he received $17,000 in tuition payments for a son and
$7,000 in cash for a fictitious daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Wilkinson and Page at the USOC were not returned
Wednesday. Attempts to reach LaMont were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fuel to concerns about the USOC's role in questionable
activities were separate revelations that led to LaMont's
resignation from the USOC last month.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he was working for the USOC, the report says,
LaMont was involved with a company called Citius. The company won a
contract with the Salt Lake organizers to arrange meetings and
lobby IOC members before the vote on the host city for the 1998
Winter Games. From March 1990 to May 1991, Citius received nine
checks from the Salt Lake bid committee totaling $25,714.35.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake lost out to Nagano, Japan, in that round of voting.
But when it launched a new effort to win the 2002 Games, LaMont was
back in business. The report said another company connected to
LaMont, Arca Inc., was paid $18,185.90 between February 1992 and
October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Records from the Salt Lake bid committee did not detail what
services Arca provided, but they indicate that $3,000 monthly
payments were made through the company to Austin Sealy, an IOC
member from Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said he was satisfied that new policies on the
activities of Olympic bid cities _ adopted in November 1997, a year
before the current controversy began _ are adequate to prevent
future misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said the USOC might further tighten those rules based
on recommendations from a committee headed by former US Senator
George Mitchell. That panel's report is due by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to come out of this and say if there's something
we've done wrong, we hope to change those things and make sure they
don't happen again,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   He said one possible change would be to eliminate financial aid
from bid cities to foreign athletes, the very relationship that led
to the USOC e-mail exchange about Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whether other revelations are forthcoming, the
e-mails and LaMont's outside activities threaten to undermine the
USOC's attempts to keep itself clear from the tumult involving Salt
Lake City and the IOC. That might prove difficult, particularly
considering the USOC's close ties to the SLOC.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC is the body that named Salt Lake as the US choice to
host the 1998 and 2002 Games, and the USOC holds 10 seats on the
SLOC's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC and SLOC also are partners in the Olympic Properties of
the US program, known as OPUS, the sponsorship-marketing-business
entity that coordinates all Olympic commercial and fund-raising
activities in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Zuckoff reported from Boston, Powers from Salt Lake City.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
