<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES PLAN TO CONTINUE SUPPORT DESPITE OLYMPIC SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a warning shot from a significant sponsor _ the John
Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. _ and nearly two months of bad
publicity for the Olympics, major companies are continuing to
support the games by spending marketing budgets on television
advertising and sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   An array of marketing experts and Olympic and television
officials said that even while various Olympic committees continue
to grapple with allegations of corruption, corporate support is
likely to be unwavering, at least through the summer. That's
because the games offer enormous access to an international market
with broad demographics for their corporate messages, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to assessing the value of the Olympics, I don't
think one considers it in the context of the moment,'' said Carl
Langsenkap, manager of public relations for Xerox, which has
sponsored Olympics since 1964 and is currently negotiating to
sponsor the 2002 winter games in Salt Lake City and the 2004 summer
games in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``One considers the value by looking at what the Olympic
movement has always been, an international gathering of athletes
and their profound achievements on a world stage,'' Langenskap
said. ``That is likely to continue to be how the average person
continues to view the Olympics, despite the current trouble,
especially once the games themselves begin.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee has implicated 14 members in
questionable activities, including accepting large gratuities, in
connection with the decision on where the winter games would be
played in 2002. An ethics committee in Salt Lake City Tuesday
implicated an additional 10.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Hancock's president and chief operating officer,
David D'Alessandro, confirmed Wednesday that the company has halted
negotiations with NBC over commercial time for the 2000 summer
games. And D'Alessandro said he intends to increase pressure to
reform the way the IOC does business by threatening its revenue
sources _ even to the extent of reviewing whether Hancock should
spend its sports marketing dollars on Major League Baseball and
NCAA basketball rather than the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on whether to support the Olympics, at what industry
observers said is a rate of about $50 million, ``will be made over
the next 12 to 18 months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, if you want to get the attention of somebody in
business, whom you are sending money, the best way is to stop
sending them money,'' D'Alessandro said. ``And the real money
behind the Olympics is television and the sponsorships.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro said that it was the failure of the IOC and its
President Juan Antonio Samaranch to fully investigate events
leading to the siting of the summer games in Sydney, Australia in
2000 persuaded him to increase the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've said is that there are expectations based on what
Samaranch said he would do in January when he apologized and said
all allegations would be investigated,'' D'Alessandro said. ``So
far, the results have not been that.''
</P>
<P>
   But observers of the sports marketing industry and spokesmen for
several other Olympic sponsors said Wednesday that no other company
is likely to follow Hancock's lead on halting television
negotiations or altering sponsorship agreements. Some companies,
like UPS and Xerox, which are currently negotiating agreements with
the IOC, said the allegations are having no impact.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Coca-cola, UPS, Xerox and Panasonic all said
Wednesday that, while they continue to monitor events, they have no
plans to withdraw any support from the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably all go away by June or July,'' said Rob
Prezmark, a senior vice-president at IMG, a huge international
advertising and marketing agency, who once negotiated with Hancock
on behalf of the IOC. ``If not, then this will be a big problem.
But my opinion is that when Sydney opens, that day, this will
totally be by the books and the attention will be entirely on the
games, as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, spokesmen for both NBC and the IOC said that no one
has followed Hancock's lead, and that advertising negotations for
the summer games in Sydney in 2000 are proceeding well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Olympic ad sales have been very strong,'' said Ed Markey,
a spokesman for the network, who echoed similar comments by Michael
R. Payne, the IOC's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no erosion,'' Markey said. ``And the sponsors
understand the viewers watch the Olympics by the tens of millions
on a nightly basis because of their allure and because of the
events themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
