<HEADLINE>
ELITE NAVY TEAM DISPATCHED TO DESTROY FUEL ON STRANDED SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The emergency summons to ignite 400,000 gallons of fuel aboard a
stranded ship came by telephone late Tuesday night to an elite Navy
unit at Whidbey Island Naval Air Station near Oak Harbor, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   While Wednesday's mission _ destroying the fuel carried by the
639-foot-long New Carissa off Coos Bay, Ore. _ is unusual for its
magnitude and high visibility, the Navy explosive experts are
accustomed to emergency calls for help at all hours, said Cmdr. Sue
Fitzgerald, commanding officer of Explosive Ordnance Disposal
Mobile Unit 11 at Whidbey Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our operations are dangerous assignments,'' Fitzgerald
said. ``But this has been an interesting week.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit consists of 17 officers and 108 enlisted specialists
who are trained to detect, identify and dispose of explosive
hazards to people or property on land and under water. They also
provide support to the U.S. Secret Service in protecting government
officials, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent operations have included recovering and disposing
of loaded maritime flares that washed ashore on the coast, removing
World War II-era ordance discovered during construction projects
and helping the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service retrieve a small
chartered aircraft that crashed into the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Wednesday's environmental rescue mission in Oregon the
first time the team has been sent to destroy a stranded ship's
fuel. The team carried out a similar operation in Alaska in the
late 1980s, she said.
</P>
<P>
   An all-volunteer organization within the Navy, EOD recruits must
pass a tough physical test, demonstrate strong swimming skills and
undergo more than a year of training in ordnance handling,
demolition and safety practices, including work on nuclear and
chemical weapons, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Its members must be qualified in scuba diving, parachuting and
helicopter operations, and are trained in small-unit infantry
tactics for defense in hostile areas.
</P>
<P>
   There are less than 1,000 Explosive Ordnance Disposal
specialists in the entire Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The Whidbey-based command is organized into several squad-sized
detachments that specialize in different aspects of ordnance
disposal, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member team sent to Coos Bay was the unit's ``Detachment
Northwest,'' a shore-based component organized and trained to
respond to emergencies throughout the Pacific Northwest and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The unit is commanded by Navy Lt. Scot Wilson, 38, a career
explosive ordnance disposal specialist who joined the Navy 15 years
ago as an enlisted man but won an officer's commission through a
Navy-sponsored college program at the University of Washington in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Eight five-member detachments train for deployment with Navy
carrier battle groups, serving as ordnance disposal technicians for
the carrier and its escorts. Two of the five-member teams are
currently serving in the Persian Gulf aboard the carrier USS Carl
Vinson.
</P>
<P>
   These detachments attracted news coverage during Operation
Desert Storm when they were called in to detonate Iraqi anti-ship
mines that were found floating loose in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements include a detachment specializing in countering
sea mines, and two additional shore-based teams at the Bangor
Submarine Base in Kitsap County, Wash., and Fallon Naval Air
Station in Nevada _ two bases with large amounts of explosives in
storage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
