<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SKATER TAKES HER CAREER TRIPLE JUMP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Utah)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Sarah Hughes tries not to look at the graceful
woman on the ice with her. That would be bad form, in both senses.
</P>
<P>
   By the luck of the draw, 13-year-old Sarah Hughes has been put
in the same group as 18-year-old Michelle Kwan, the gold standard
of competitive figure skating these days.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer when the Goodwill Games were held near her home in
Kings Point, New York, Hughes spotted Kwan in a sushi restaurant
but was so tongue-tied that her 20-year-old sister, Rebecca, had to
do all the chatting.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the two skate here in the short program of the
national championships. Kwan, as defending champion, competes
against herself, while Hughes, making her first appearance in the
women's division, is a legitimate possibility for a medal.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is performing the equivalent of a career triple axel,
triple toe, leaping from junior skating to women's skating at 13
because, as she accurately notes, ``There's nowhere else to go.''
She won the national junior title last year in Philadelphia and
finished second in the world juniors in Croatia last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go backward, or just stand still,'' Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night she skates in the same group as Kwan, a mature
and flowing presence who graciously accepted her silver medal
behind Tara Lipinski in the Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, a
year ago. Now Kwan is back, keeping her gold-medal options open for
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the world and national champion, she's so great,'' said
Hughes, who can still muster up a 13-year-old's sense of awe.
``Sure, I know she's on the ice, but I don't look at her much. That
would not be very efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is nothing if not efficient. She defies skating
convention by actually living at home and going to Great Neck
Middle School, having a real life with her parents and five
siblings, while enduring dreadful traffic jams to find quality ice
time across two bridges in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   She's a trouper who was once asked what she liked best about
skating and replied with a perfectly Zenlike ``the ice.'' She says
her two goals in life are a perfect 6.0 score in skating and a
perfect 1,600 in her scholastic tests.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing perfection, Hughes spent two weeks with Kwan's coach,
Frank Carroll, out in California last summer while Kwan was on
vacation. But this is no gunslinger competition, with Kwan looking
over her shoulders for her skating assassin, the Woman Who Shot
Liberty Valance. ``She talks to me,'' Hughes reported. ``She wanted
to know what grade I was in, and I told her I was still in middle
school. She wanted to know if I had finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes admits there is a temptation to glance at Kwan during
practice, when six skaters take designated turns rehearsing their
routines, while the others keep out of the way, at least
theoretically.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic practice took on a macabre aura in Norway in 1994 when
Nancy Kerrigan and Tonya Harding wound up in the same practice
group, and Kerrigan reasonably had to wonder if Harding would be
packing a tire iron. International warmups always were enlivened by
Surya Bonaly unloading a backward flip in the general direction of
somebody's jugular.
</P>
<P>
   But there is none of that here, just one gold-medal prospect and
a lot of hopefuls. When Nicole Bobek withdrew the other day because
she just wasn't fit, Hughes said, ``It was horrible because Nicole
has put so much into skating, but that means there's another spot
on the podium.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no reverse psychology in skating as there was in tennis
when Tracy Austin's mother dressed her in oversize pinafores and
dangling pigtails to obscure the killer within. Last year Hughes
was doing four triples in junior competition and now she is doing
seven, but the judges will annihilate her if she tries to perform
beyond her years, or her girlish frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much passion you can have at 13,'' said Robin
Wagner, her coach from Manhasset, N.Y. ``Why try to look 15 or 17?
That would be silly. But there is so much beauty in her skating. I
just want that to come through.'' Her accomplished family keeps her
balanced. The oldest child, Rebecca, the editor of the weekly
Independent at Harvard University, enjoys watching Sarah conduct
interviews with poise far beyond the practiced sing-song neutrality
of most female skaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to remember she's only 13,'' Rebecca Hughes said.
``But when I take her shopping, I'm reminded.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen is a tricky age. Sarah Hughes would be quite happy to
stand on that podium and look up at Michelle Kwan. She already
does. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
