<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9903 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISA-SFCHRON &LR;      02-10 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Citigroup, Tired of Living in Visa's Shadow, Switches
to  MasterCard  By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Citigroup's move to shift its mammoth credit card business from
Visa to archrival MasterCard is seen as a bid to reshape the
industry by shifting power and visibility from credit card
associations to banks.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the No. 2 issuer of Visa cards, wanted the
association to get out of the marketing business and focus mainly
on the unglamorous job of processing card transactions, Michael
Beindorff, Visa U.S.A.'s executive vice president for marketing,
said in an interview. ``There are two distinct business models
emerging. They want to change (Visa's) role and mission, reducing
the organization to a network processor,'' Beindorff said.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a reversal of the role that Visa of Foster
City and MasterCard of New York have played for more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Both are membership associations that, over the years, became
more powerful than their members, the thousands of financial
institutions that actually issue credit cards. Since their
inceptions, Visa and MasterCard have spent billions of dollars
advertising their brand names and forging identities more widely
recognized than the institutions that actually extend credit to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, which holds nearly 17 percent of all Visa's
outstanding balances, is anxious to promote its own name as a
global financial brand and doesn't want to share attention with
Visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that for 20 years, we've been willing to live
with a communal-association brand so prominently displayed,'' John
Reed, Citigroup co-chairman, said in response to an analyst's
question recently.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card experts said the break between Visa and its
second-largest issuer will have have little direct effect on
consumers because MasterCard is accepted almost everywhere Visa is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a wash for consumers,'' said Stephen Brobeck,
director of the Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute reflects the growing clout of Visa's largest
issuers, whose share of the association's business has ballooned
because of bank mergers. The top four Visa issuers now hold more
than half of Visa's total outstanding balances.
</P>
<P>
   Small banks, meanwhile, strongly support Visa's marketing
efforts because their own names are not well known.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VISA11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``If you devalue the Visa card, you devalue the franchise of
community banks,'' said Ken Guenther, executive vice president of
Independent Bankers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Beindorff said Citigroup and Visa have been negotiating for more
than a year over fees and terms of the bank's membership.
</P>
<P>
   Visa was willing to accept Citigroup's demand to remove the Visa
name from the front of credit cards, leaving that space exclusively
for Citigroup, Beindorff said. But the association balked when the
bank insisted that its fees be slashed and that Visa cut back its
marketing activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A line gets drawn in the sand,'' Beindorff said.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup paid Visa $73 million in membership dues and
processing fees last year, about 6 percent of the association's
revenue, Beindorff said. Visa, whose income has been growing at a
17 percent annual rate in recent years, will be able to absorb the
lost revenue without major program cuts or layoffs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Reed and a second Citigroup official quit the board
of Visa U.S.A., one of several regional Visa units.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations signaled that Citigroup has reached an
agreement with MasterCard on fees and marketing issues and that the
bank will stop issuing new Visa cards except when it has contracts
that force it to do so, according to several news reports.
Citigroup spokeswoman Maria Mendler declined to discuss the bank's
arrangements with MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup hasn't formally notified Visa that it will stop
issuing new Visa cards but ``it's a pretty safe bet'' it will,
Beindorff said.
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard is smaller than Visa, controling about a quarter of
payment card volume compared with Visa's market share of more than
50 percent. Industry experts speculated that MasterCard agreed to
Citigroup's demands in order to win the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citigroup is going to an association where it will be top
dog,'' said David Robertson, president of the Nilson Report, a
newsletter covering the credit card industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
