<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AMERICAN TRAVELERS: EXPECT THE UNEXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Calif.)   (See also AMR-PILOTS) 
(jw) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if American Airline pilots return to work quickly after a
federal judge ordered them Wednesday to end their five-day sickout
that grounded 2,500 flights, travelers can still expect
inconvenience and disruption during the coming long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even a temporary settlement cannot come too soon for
airlines, passengers, cruise lines, hotels and residents of the
Caribbean, which depends heavily on tourism for economic survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strike was serious stuff, because this is one of the
biggest weeks of the year for Caribbean travel and American is the
biggest airline in the region,'' said Michael Youngman, executive
director of the Caribbean Tourism Organization. ``So even a
tentative settlement is an enormous relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Effective immediately, American customers can obtain a full
refund on all tickets, including nonrefundable tickets. They can
also postpone or reschedule flights without service charges or
penalties. And, when flights are canceled, American says it will
try to accommodate customers on other American flights or on other
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise industry was worried about the possibility that many
passengers booked on cruises from South Florida this weekend could
not get to Miami or Fort Lauderdale on time. ``We have 21,500
passengers booked from Miami, Fort Lauderdale and San Juan on nine
ships this weekend, and an equal equal number going home,'' said
Rich Steck, spokesman in Miami for Royal Caribbean and Celebrity
Cruises. ``So you can probably hear our sigh of relief about the
settlement all the way up in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Most business travelers apparently avoided major dislocations
during the sickout, said Norman Sherlock, executive director of the
National Business Travel Association. ``But corporate members have
told me they're going to recast their future travel plans,'' he
said, ``so as not to be so dependent on American or any single
airline.''
</P>
<P>
   Some travel agents viewed the sickout as further evidence of the
importance of their services, which are threatened by erosion from
the Internet. Rudi Steele, owner of a travel agency in Dallas, did
some juggling to get two clients to Los Angeles in time to catch a
flight to Hong Kong in order to board a cruise ship. ``I got them
on a late-night flight the night before to Ontario, Calif.,''
Steele said, ``put them up in a hotel and booked a rental car for
them to drive to L.A. in the morning.'' He could not resist adding,
``That's what a professional travel agent will do for clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boult, vice president of supplier relations for
Rosenbluth International, added that while the Internet might be
fun for surfing for information, it was of little help in a crisis.
``Try calling the Internet and complaining that your flight's been
canceled,'' he said. Early on, Rosenbluth sent a fax to corporate
accounts, telling them of the flight cancellations and promising to
keep them informed. ``Because there were good alternatives early in
the strike,'' Boult said, ``we were able to avoid any serious
disruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say they will do all they can to accommodate stranded
American passengers, but add that they do not have spare planes to
press into service, as is often believed. Moreover, work rules and
airport regulations prevent the scheduling of additional flights
except in unusual circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines booked more than 1,000 hotel rooms in Miami on
Tuesday for stranded passengers, but by and large the strike seemed
to be a mixed blessing for hotels, with no-shows offsetting the
number of guests who extended their stays after their flights were
canceled. However, the sickout hurt the 1,369-room Hyatt Regency
hotel at the Dallas/Fort Worth airport. ``Fifty percent of our
business is small meetings, booked 10 to 14 days in advance,'' said
Steve Trent, the hotel's general manager. ``We've had
cancellations, and we stood to lose an a lot more business if the
strike continued, because this is a busy season for conventions in
Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   When he learned of the judge's order to end the sickout, Trent
had a one-word reaction: ``Hallelujah!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
