NYT-02-10-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH11-COX     02-10 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conviction votes expected to fall short of majority
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three Republican moderates said Wednesday they will
vote to acquit President Clinton on both impeachment articles as
hopes waned that senators will wrap up secret deliberations and
take the historic vote today.
</P>
<P>
   While it is a foregone conclusion that the Senate will not
muster the two-thirds majority to convict Clinton, the trickle of
public statements Wednesday raised the prospect that the verdict
could fall short of a 51-vote majority.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James Jeffords (R-Vt.) said he would vote against both
articles, and Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) said he would vote ``not
proven,'' a vote Specter conceded would be recorded as not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee (R-R.I.) said House prosecutors did not prove
their case that Clinton lied before the grand jury Aug. 17 or
obstructed justice in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
Clinton is accused of perjury and obstruction of justice in his
attempts to conceal his relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried Vermont, Rhode Island and Pennsylvania in the
1992 and 1996 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords predicted at least six or seven of his Republican
colleagues would also vote not guilty, meaning the two articles
would get less than 50 votes if all 45 Democrats vote against
conviction. Five Democrats announced Wednesday that they will vote
to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffords later softened his prediction, saying, ``The
pressure is coming on to get a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Majority Leader Trent Lott said there had been
no attempt by the leadership to line up votes for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton will remain in office in either case, some
Democrats said a defeat of the impeachment articles by a majority
vote would send a powerful political message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is less than a majority (voting to convict), it will
be a strong statement that will discourage political
impeachments,'' said Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   By the end of deliberations Wednesday, only half the 100-member
Senate had used their alloted 15 minutes to speak in closed
session. Though the vote on the articles could come as early as
this evening, the slow pace of deliberations suggested the trial
will probably spill into Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There were also increasing signs that the votes on the
impeachment articles will be the last statement the Senate will
make on the charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic bid to enlist Republican support in a censure
resolution lost steam, as neither party could agree on the
language. Democrats want strong language but words that do not
imply that Clinton broke any laws, while many Republicans say such
language is too weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of censure has lost a lot of ground,'' said Sen.
Craig Thomas (R-Wyo.). ``Most people think that when we vote on the
articles that will be the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.), a principal Democratic
proponent of censure, suggested for the first time Wednesday that
the censure might not be a censure at all, but simply a ``letter of
censure'' signed by concerned senators. Such a letter would have
even less legislative meaning than a censure motion voted on by the
full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another, this is going to see the light of day,''
Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, senators on both sides of the aisle have listened to
the same arguments from prosecutors and defense lawyers, watched
the same videotaped depositions and read from the same impeachment
record compiled by independent counsel Ken Starr and the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But what became clear Wednesday was how differently senators
view the same set of facts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin (D-Iowa), who weeks ago called the case against
Clinton a ``pile of dung,'' stuck by his off-color remark Wednesday
and heaped scorn on Starr and the tactics of House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case should never have been brought to the United States
Senate,'' said Harkin. ``I believe it to be one of the most blatant
political vindictive actions taken by the House of Representatives
since Andrew Johnson's case was pushed through by the radical
Republicans of his time and forced upon the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin made pointed reference to House members such as Rep. Bob
Barr (R-Ga.), who called for Clinton's impeachment even before the
independent counsel submitted his findings to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven forbid that I saw something improper in the president's
actions and now I'm being attacked,'' Barr responded later. ``You
can never please (Democrats).''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dick Lugar (R-Ind.) said he would vote for both articles
and called for a ``cleansing of the presidency.'' Lugar said
Clinton exposed himself to blackmail and jeopardized national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not trustworthy,'' said Lugar. ``It will not be enough
simply to condemn the tragic misdeeds of President Clinton. He must
be removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most nuanced position came from Specter, who said he
will attempt to set a precedent and vote that the impeachment
articles were ``not proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsing blame all around, the Pennsylvania Republican called
Clinton's impeachment trial a ``sham trial.'' Specter said the
trial should have had live witnesses and more presentation of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not done impartial justice to House prosecutors
because we tied one hand behind their backs,'' Specter said. ``The
country has not seen a full development of the evidence. ... I
don't believe there has been an adequate trial to come to a
conclusion of not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords said he believed Clinton did make ``misleading
statements'' and did obstruct justice but that those crimes did not
rise to the level of impeachable acts. ``A vote to convict the
president on these articles may establish a low threshold that
would make every president subject to removal for the slightest
indiscretion,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote to convict may imperil every president who faces a
Congress controlled by the opposing party.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee said he thought perjury and obstruction of justice were
impeachable offenses, but that House prosecutors hadn't proven
Clinton's guilt beyond doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty with each of the charges in Article II
(obstruction of justice) is that circumstantial evidence in each of
these cases is rebutted by direct evidence or by confusion that
leaves it very murky,'' Chafee said.
</P>
<P>
   In a path that many Republicans may ultimately take, Sen. Slade
Gorton (R-Wash.) said he will vote to acquit the president of
perjury but convict him of obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to reconcile the president's course of
conduct with any purpose other than to preclude Miss Lewinsky's
truthful testimony in the Jones case,'' Gorton said. ``Obstruction
was his only motive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone (D-Minn.), making a plea to censure Clinton,
said he should not be removed, while Sens. Daniel Akaka (D-Hawaii),
Carl Levin (D-Mich.) and Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.) came out
strongly against convicting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conduct did not threaten our constitutional system, and
the national interest will not be served by removing him from
office,'' said Lautenberg. ``These proceedings should not serve as
a precedent for using impeachment as a political weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
