<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORE-OIL-SPILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD TO BURN SHIP LEAKING OIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Wash., Texas)  (Eds: Story will be updated if the Coast Guard sets fire to the
ship tonight.) 
(mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Faced with a cargo ship leaking oil, an approaching
Pacific storm packing 70-mph winds and the threat of an
environmental debacle along beaches in two states, Coast Guard
officials decided Wednesday to set fire to the 639-foot vessel,
which ran aground late last week about 150 yards off the coast of
southern Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are significantly concerned that this ship will not stay
together,'' Capt. Mike Hall of the Coast Guard said in a briefing
Wednesday. ``We're between a rock and a hard spot. If we don't do
something now, we would have to stand before you and tell you why
we let 400,000 gallons of oil spill on our beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Cracks in the hull of the ship, the Japanese-owned New Carissa,
which had been headed to the port town of Coos Bay to pick up a
load of wood chips, have already caused mucky black oil and diesel
fuel to wash over about eight miles of Oregon coastline, Coast
Guard officials said. That oil has come ashore near a prime habitat
for the Western snowy plover, an endangered shorebird.
</P>
<P>
   The storm expected to hit Wednesday night was carrying sharp
winds and rain, and the officials decided that there was a serious
risk that the vessel would simply break apart, which could send the
remaining oil onto beaches all along the Oregon coast and northward
along the Washington coast.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. Navy explosive experts boarded the grounded
ship and prepared to set it afire with remote-controlled grenades.
The blaze was expected to last a few days.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to burn the ship in such circumstances is unusual
but not unprecedented, experts said Wednesday, and in essence
involves opting for a fire that will blacken and pollute the skies
in the area as the cost of trying to save the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any of these things, it's a trade-off,'' said Steven
Barnes, director of the National Spill Control School, a branch of
Texas A&AMP;M University in Corpus Christi, Texas. ``There's no real
technique that doesn't cause problems, but the assumption here
seems to be that the fire is less of a risk than letting that ship
sit there and be pounded to pieces in stormy seas.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, while expressing dismay at the lack of
expanded safety regulations to prevent such spills in the first
place, said the decision to burn the ship appeared to be the proper
one under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction is that this is a terrible solution to an
even more terrible problem,'' said Allen Hershkowitz, a senior
scientist with the Natural Resources Defense Council, a
Manhattan-based environmental group. ``This might be a sensible
last-resort option, but it really underscores the need for double
hulls and safer ships. Tragedies like this are, frankly, not
uncommon, but they are also avoidable.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting the ship afire is itself not without some risks. At
worst, the fire could undermine the ship's structural integrity,
causing it to split apart before the oil has burned off. But as of
Wednesday evening, Coast Guard officials said the ship was still
sufficiently intact, giving the fire option a high likelihood of
success.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's worst oil spill involving a ship, the March 1989
Exxon Valdez disaster, in which nearly 11 million gallons of oil
poured into Alaska's Prince William Sound, a similar approach was
considered. But storms had broken up the tanker and spread oil for
miles around, making the fire option unfeasible, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, the New Carissa ran aground in the Leberti Hole, a
major area for commercial crabbers, and was within sight of the
beaches north of Coos Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred members of a clean-up crew, most of them
volunteers, gathered along the beaches Wednesday, picking up
oil-coated driftwood and tar-like balls from the spill. Several
oil-coated birds have been found; it is not yet clear how many
wildlife deaths have been caused by the spill, a Coast Guard
spokeswoman in Seattle said.
</P>
<P>
   In opting for the fire, the authorities have abandoned an
earlier plan to try to pull the ship free and then tow it in for
repairs. After the oil has been burned off, the burned steel hull
of the ship is expected to be towed to the beach and cut up. The
23-man crew, mostly from the Philippines, was safely removed from
the ship last Friday and has been interviewed by the Coast Guard,
which is still trying to piece together exactly how the ship ran
aground.
</P>
<P>
   The fire plan ``is not a perfect solution,'' said Jacqueline
Savitz, director of the Coast Alliance, a conservation group based
in Washington, D.C., noting that it will likely destroy a wide
swath of fish and larval sea life near the ocean's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
