<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-MAYOR-ART-1,100&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SHOOTING HIGHLIGHTS BLACKS' MISTRUST OF MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the greatest accomplishment of the Giuliani
administration is the precipitous drop in the city's crime rate,
its most glaring shortcoming may be the failure to cultivate a
trusting relationship with most of the city's black leaders. Now,
the best and the worst have melded into the Diallo case, presenting
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani again with that most delicate matter of race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Anger persists over last week's shooting death of an unarmed
African immigrant by four white police officers who riddled his
body and apartment-building vestibule with 41 bullets. On Monday,
the president of the NAACP attracted national notice by condemning
the shooting. On Tuesday, more than 1,000 people staged an angry
demonstration in lower Manhattan. Wednesday, the mother of Amadou
Diallo, the victim, heeded the advice of the Rev. Al Sharpton and
curtly rejected any assistance from the mayor while in the city to
retrieve her son's body.
</P>
<P>
   With every passing day, Giuliani struggles to bring a calmer
perspective to the tragedy, to convey convincingly the pain he says
he feels over this loss of life and compassion for the victim's
family. Several times he has imparted heartfelt thoughts, then felt
the need to defensively recite statistics showing that fatal police
shootings are less frequent in New York than in other large cities.
His recitation of statistics seems to linger longer than his words
of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for the mayor's predicament, including
his decision to reserve most comment during the investigation of
the shooting. But the overriding factor, critics say, is rooted in
the earliest days of Giuliani's tenure: Unlike his predecessors,
the mayor never established a lasting rapport with many of the
city's black leaders, either personally or through emissaries. That
failure, coupled with various slights and arguments along the way,
now leaves him with no capital of trust from which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   This was the clear message at a press conference convened
Wednesday by C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president,
and attended by, among others, former Mayor Ed Koch, who had
troubles of his own with many black political and civic leaders
during his tenure. But rather than score the mayor, most of the
speakers pleaded with him to open the lines of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Being mayor ``requires a willingness to hear,'' Koch said. ``So
we're saying to the mayor: `Listen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fields agreed. ``I certainly am not blaming Mayor Giuliani
or Commissioner Safir for the tragedy that took place,'' she said,
referring to Police Commissioner Howard Safir. Nevertheless, she
said that the city ``must change the tone and move in a different
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani responded Wednesday night by impeaching the event's
credibility, noting that Koch is a persistent critic and saying
that Ms. Fields failed to acknowledge the Police Department's
accomplishments, including reduced crime in black neighborhoods. He
maintained that he has working relationships with other black
leaders _ citing Rep. Charles Rangel and former Rep. Floyd Flake _
and tends not to deal with ``highly partisan Democrats'' who he
said strive for headlines rather than substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hold a press conference and attack me, attack the
police department and completely discredit everything that's been
done, and if you have somebody who is a persistent critic sitting
next to you,'' the mayor said, it suggests ``no real willingness to
work out a real solution. That happens in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the mayor said that he understood ``the frustration. I
can understand the anger. I can understand all of it and I feel
terrible that this happened as I have expressed on numerous
occasions.'' But he said ``that there's a tendency of some people
in our society to blame the police in broad strokes that is just as
vicious a prejudice as any other prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions about Guiliani's relations with
minorities, his aides listed a series of accomplishments _ from
crime reduction to job growth _ that they say have improved the
lives of everyone in the city, and offered a familiar and short
roster of ministers, business owners and neighborhood leaders who
are both black and willing to talk of their admiration for the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But this gambit backfired. One of them, the Rev. Michel
Faulkner, said Wednesday that he met with Giuliani this week to
convey the emotion that the Diallo case has sparked in black
neighborhoods, and to suggest that the administration more
emphatically display empathy for communities jarred by the
shooting. But Faulkner said he left that meeting feeling
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of where we go from here, I really would hope the
mayor would understand the amount of tremendous pain that
communities of color are in over this incident,'' Faulkner said.
``If he does not, I really think this will be a permanent blight on
his administration.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he took office in 1994, Giuliani's relationship
with various black leaders has been complicated, even
dysfunctional. A Republican, he saw many of them as cogs in a
Democratic machine that had brought city government to a
standstill; he saw no need to curry their favor. He famously
refused to meet with Sharpton, whom he saw as divisive.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mayor's first actions was to end the practice that
his predecessors had of having liaisons to the many constituencies
in the city, from gays and lesbians to Hispanics and blacks. ``He
didn't want to Balkanize the city,'' said his press secretary,
Colleen Roche.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Paterson and City Councilman Bill Perkins,
among other black Democrats, have contended that the decision in
fact Balkanized neighborhoods like Harlem, leaving them with no
access to the administration.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the tension is the Police Department, whose
members have given the mayor something to brag about _ crime
reduction _ even as they resent him for blocking their requests for
pay increases. There is the perception that the department's
get-tough policy has been largely directed at young black men.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the very ones who are being singled out are the ones who
are being saved'' by the crackdown on crime, said Kenneth T.
Jackson, a professor of history at Columbia University. ``If you
look at just who's alive and who's dead, it's saving the lives of
black men. The people who were getting killed were never white
women or old white guys or even black women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complicated issue,'' he added. ``It's a terrible
situation when people fear government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Symbolizing that fear of government was the Louima case of 1997,
in which a Haitian immigrant was brutalized inside a Brooklyn
police precinct. Giuliani immediately called for a task force to
explore community-police relations. But months after his
re-election, he ridiculed some of that task force's recommendations
with sarcasm that overshadowed that fact that he had set aside $15
million for sensitivity training for officers.
</P>
<P>
   That sarcasm, along with memories of the administration's
aggressive handling of the Million Youth March in Harlem last
summer, returned to haunt Giuliani when Diallo was killed in a
fusillade of police bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's challenge, according to Dr. James Forbes, pastor of
Riverside Church in Harlem, is to better convey a universal
message: ``Guess what. You all count.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
