<SLUG> BC-GOD-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY REVEALS HERSELF IN AUTOBIOGRAPHICAL `GOD SAID'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Julia Sweeney's acclaimed, one-woman stage show
``God Said, `Ha!' '' has now been preserved on film. It's a good
show, but barely a movie.
</P>
<P>
   For those unfamiliar with the piece, the former ``Saturday Night
Live'' comic built a monologue out of one very bad year in her
life. Freshly and amicably divorced and retired from the TV
program, she'd moved to L.A., found a perfect little house that she
furnished just so, and was all set to indulge a life of cozy
independence when her brother was diagnosed with terminal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She took him in. Her parents from Washington state wanted to
help out. They moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney found herself reduced to sneaking cigarettes in the car
and making out with her boyfriend in the hall, hoping not to get
caught but kind of turned on by the prospect. Hilarious
descriptions of this premature second childhood are balanced by
loving and harrowing recollections of her brother's inspiring,
inevitably losing struggle.
</P>
<P>
   And then comes the day when Julia gets her own call from the
oncologist ...
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who's otherwise best known for creating such ``SNL''
characters as the sexually ambiguous Pat, is an engaging raconteur
with a nice way of imitating people while still remaining Julia.
She doesn't do characters here; rather, she makes it clear that
she's giving you her take on somebody. It's a nice way to prevent
sharp or even angry observations from degenerating into cheap
disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the person we learn the most about is Julia. And even
though what she reveals is unavoidably selective, the piece could
not work as well as it does without a great degree of self-honesty;
indeed, there would be no other reason for it to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot on a soundstage designed to look like the
stage of a small theater, dressed to resemble Sweeney's living
room. There are a few pieces of furniture, a lamp. Four cameras
were employe$X}y
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HONGKONG-NYT     02-10 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG LEGAL DECISION ON CITIZENSHIP UPSETS MAINLAND CHINESE
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This story, held yesterday, is now released for publication.
Subs the original first 3 pargraphs and rewrites into 2 grafs.
Grafs 3 and 4 are rewritten significantly as are grafs 7, 8 and 9.
Subs 11th graf for a different quotation.) 
 (fe) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ever since Chinese officials this week started
publicly criticizing a groundbreaking decision by Hong Kong's
highest court, a new sense of tension and uncertainty has crept
into the relationship between China and Hong Kong, the former
British colony that was reunited with the mainland 19 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, handed down by a unanimous Court of Final Appeals on
Jan. 29, says that four children born in mainland China to parents
who are Hong Kong residents have the right to live in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court decision is a mistake and against the Basic Law,''
Zhao Qizheng, the information minister for China's cabinet, told
reporters who gathered on Monday for a party for the Chinese New
Year. ``This is a very serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the case's details involved immigration policy, the
judges seized the opportunity to make broader statements about the
independence of Hong Kong's judiciary and about Hong Kong autonomy
in general.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time Hong Kong officials have so openly clashed
with mainland authorities over gray areas in the Hong Kong Basic
Law, which both sides had agreed would serve as the legal
foundation for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region when it
reverted to China from Britain on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And, after the charges and the countercharges of the last two
days, it is clear that there are major differences of opinion about
the meaning of ``one country, two systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The case that sparked the debate was simple enough, concerning
the status of tens of thousands _ if not hundreds of thousands _ of
mainland Chinese with parents who are legal Hong Kong residents.
The ruling opens the way to admission of people to Hong Kong if at
least one of their parents is a resident _ even if the children
were born before their parents lived in Hong Kong and even if they
are now adults.
</P>
<P>
   The justices set an important precedent and sailed headlong into
uncharted and treacherous waters. They said that Hong Kong's Basic
Law, not the laws or policies of the mainland, should decide the
matter and that Hong Kong courts have full authority to interpret
the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in Hong Kong believe there was clear intent among
the judges to set out a landmark case,'' said Wang Chenguang, an
associate professor of law at the City University of Hong Kong, who
was formerly at Beijing University. ``It reflects a desire to use
this formal document to reinforce and assert the autonomy of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and also the independence
of the Hong Kong judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Zhao, the Chinese official, set off a round of
dire predictions and paroxysms of dread among politicians, scholars
and diplomats in Hong Kong, who have long feared that Beijing would
try to force its values on their turf. Thus far, Hong Kong remains
a freewheeling place whose newspapers are quick to pick up hints of
mainland scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any move to restrict the independent judicial power of the
Court of Final Appeal would be a matter of serious concern to us,''
the British Consulate General in Hong Kong said in a statement on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear what, if anything, the Chinese government
plans to do about the situation. Many Hong Kong legal scholars said
the decision by the Final Court of Appeals is just that _ final.
And China's leaders are savvy enough to know that any direct
interference with Hong Kong's judiciary would cause foreign
investors to flee from this slumping but still vibrant metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   The central legal issue is how to interpret two somewhat
contradictory clauses in the Basic Law. Article 22 of Chapter 2,
which deals with relations between Hong Kong and the mainland, says
that Chinese residents wishing to go to Hong Kong must first gain
the permission of China's authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But Article 24 of Chapter 3 _ dealing with Hong Kong citizens'
rights _ says that children of Hong Kong citizens who are born
outside of Hong Kong will enjoy the rights of citizens. ``According
to this,'' said one legal scholar, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, ``these kids have an inalienable right of abode and
don't need a permit.''
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the judges put Article 24 above Article 22,
effectively proclaiming that mainland rules that interfere with the
constitutionally protected rights of Hong Kong citizens are
invalid, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   In narrow terms, that decision means that Hong Kong will now
accept children of residents whether or not they have the blessing
of the mainland authorities to leave and giving thousands of
mainland immigrants already in Hong Kong illegally a potential
legal mechanism for staying. But to many liberals in Hong Kong, the
significance of the decision is much broader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court asserted in this way both the self-government of
Hong Kong and the necessity of rights and the rule of law,'' wrote
Yash Ghai, a law professor the University of Hong Kong, in The
South China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
   China has yet to explain its objections fully, and Zhao said the
government would present its formal opinion at ``an appropriate
time.'' At a previously scheduled Foreign Ministry briefing on
Tuesday, a spokesman said only that the central government was
``concerned'' about the issue, adding that the opinion of mainland
legal scholars ``is worthy of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, the state-controlled news agency featured
interviews with four legal scholars who helped draft the Basic Law.
They attacked the court decision, contending that the Hong Kong
court could not disregard Chinese legislation and that its
jurisdiction is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Wu Jianfan of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences said the
authority to interpret the law ``rests with the National People's
Congress Standing Committee.'' Some mainland scholars contend that
the Chinese Congress should have been called upon to clarify any
contradiction in the Hong Kong Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities have also said they are worried about a
possible large-scale influx of immigrants into Hong Kong at a time
unemployment is rising. For the same reason, the court's decision
provoked criticism from both many Hong Kong residents and the Hong
Kong government.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the government decision may not be fully enforceable
anyway. The court instructed the Hong Kong government to meet with
mainland authorities to devise a new system to process immigrants.
But mainland officials may be less than eager to cooperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
