A9940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-PREWITT-NYT &LR;      02-10 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PREWITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS DIRECTOR ACCUSES HOUSE REPUBLICANS OF MEDDLING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., MD.)   (nk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The director of the Census Bureau criticized
congressional Republicans on Wednesday for what he described as
their efforts to ``micromanage'' preparations for the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Kenneth Prewitt, said in an interview that
Republicans on the House Subcommittee on the Census had suggested
changes in bureau plans like how many census takers should be
hired, where they should be deployed, the language other than
English in which census forms should be printed for a given area,
and the ability of municipal governments to challenge the count of
local populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put all these together, it's as if the subcommittee is
trying to design the census,'' said Prewitt, whom the Senate
confirmed to his post last summer. ``It strikes me as a very risky
enterprise to try to micromanage the census.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the career professionals in the Census Bureau's
headquarters in Suitland, Md., outside Washington, have long held
views like Prewitt's, but they have generally grumbled in private.
The director's comments stand out not so much because of their tone
or content as because he chose to make them publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said he was particularly bothered by a bill introduced
by Rep. Dan Miller of Florida, chairman of the House Subcommittee
on the Census, that would permit local governments to review the
Census Bureau's work after completion of the count. If a
municipality challenged the bureau's count of a given block, for
instance, the agency would have to send census takers to recanvass
the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It invites 39,000 independent jurisdictions to tell us that
they have more people than we found,'' Prewitt said. ``It's an
incentive for anyone to try to boost their numbers for either
economic or political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, known as Post Census Local Review, was used for
the 1990 census, and challenges then forced the bureau to revisit
20 percent of the nation's census blocks. Prewitt and other
officials of the bureau said that it had proved expensive and had
found only a tiny fraction of those who had earlier been missed and
that as a result, the agency had made no plans to use it in the
2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller said: ``This is something that local officials want.
I don't see why the Census Bureau would object. I don't know what
they are afraid of. Are they afraid local officials will find a
mistake, or do they think they are perfect?''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled subcommittee is holding a hearing on
the bill on Thursday and has scheduled a vote then. Prewitt said he
was particularly upset that no Census Bureau official had been
invited to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel almost aggrieved,'' he said, ``that the subcommittee
would hold hearings on something that would lead to such a major
change in census procedures without inviting the Census Bureau to
testify.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that discussions about the bill had taken place ``at
the staff level'' and that the bureau's objections had been noted.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats maintain that the Republicans are pressing for Post
Census Local Review to throw a monkey wrench into the Census
Bureau's ability to produce population counts that can be used for
the drawing of boundaries for congressional and state legislative
districts. Bureau officials say Post Census Local Review would add
five to six weeks to the time to compile official numbers for such
redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Supreme Court ruled that the Census Bureau could
not use a hotly debated method known as statistical sampling to
help produce an official population figure that will be used to
determine the number of House seats each state will be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   But the High Court did not explicitly rule on whether sampling
is permitted to establish precisely where inside a state people
live. Such information is used to draw boundaries for congressional
and state legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that sampling will increase the number of members of
minorities that are counted. Since minorities tend to live in areas
that are strongly Democratic, increasing their numbers could help
Democrats when district lines are drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Most states must have official numbers for redistricting by
April 1, 2001. If they do not get the number affected by sampling
by then, they will have to use the basic figures the Census Bureau
prepares for apportionment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT &LR;      02-10 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE WILL WEIGH FUTURE OF THE LAW COVERING COUNSELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel law, which for two decades
has been the foundation for investigations involving deep
constitutional issues as well as venality and sexual misbehavior,
will be debated in Senate hearings beginning on Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings before the Governmental Affairs Committee, headed
by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., are sure to be heated. The law,
enacted in 1978 after the Watergate scandal, has been controversial
from the start. It has been re-enacted several times and will
expire on June 30 unless Congress reauthorizes it.
</P>
<P>
   The law's supporters argue that it enables outside investigators
to delve into possible wrongdoing by the president, vice president
and other high government officials without fear of retribution.
Its detractors contend that some investigators have gone on fishing
expeditions, trampling on individual rights and spending millions
of dollars, often with little to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and the committee's ranking Democrat, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut, said the panel would hear the views of
former attorneys general, legal scholars, subjects of previous
investigations and independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The committee announced on Wednesday that witnesses for the
opening hearing would include Howard H. Baker Jr., the former
Republican senator from Tennessee who was vice chairman of the
Senate Watergate Committee, and Griffin B. Bell, who was attorney
general from 1977 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Bell served on an independent bipartisan commission,
established by the University of Virginia, that issued a report in
December concluding that the independent counsel law does not work
properly. Among its shortcomings, the commission said, is that the
law does not provide subjects of investigations with ``the
safeguards afforded to all other subjects of federal criminal
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some 20 independent counsels have been appointed
to investigate possible transgressions, ranging from the sale of
weapons to Iran and the diversion of profits to Nicaraguan rebels
to President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
