<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PILOTS FOR AMERICAN AIRLINES ARE ORDERED BACK TO WORK
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered American Airlines pilots to return to
work, ending five days of labor unrest that grounded more than
2,500 flights and inconvenienced tens of thousands of passengers.
American said that it expected most of the pilots to return to work
and that service should be back to normal by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The order came after American, the country's second-largest
carrier, was forced to cancel 40 percent, or 906 of its 2,250 daily
flights yesterday, the worst day since hundreds of pilots began
calling in sick on Saturday as a result of a dispute over
American's recent purchase of Reno Air.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 pilots for Reno Air support the American Airlines pilots
in their labor dispute, but they have their own problem. They do
not want to be put on the bottom of the seniority list of
American's more than 9,000 pilots as if they were all hired on Dec.
23, the day the merger took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Even if pilots for American Airlines return to work quickly,
travelers can still expect inconvenience and disruption during this
coming long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   JURY AWARDS A SMOKER $51.5 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   A California jury awarded a former three-pack-a-day smoker $50
million in punitive damages in her lawsuit against Philip Morris.
Earlier she had been awarded $1.5 million in compensatory damages,
bringing the total award to $51.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   FORD WILL NOT TRY TO ACQUIRE BMW
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, chief executive and president of Ford Motor,
said the car maker would not try to buy BMW as long as BMW wants to
remain independent. He hinted, however, that Ford would be
interested in buying the German auto maker if it puts itself up for
sale. Speculation about BMW has increased since the German company
replaced its chairman last week, attributing the move to the poor
performance of Britain's Rover, which BMW bought in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PLANS TO INCREASE OIL RESERVE
</P>
<P>
   To shore up the nation's shrinking protection against oil
emergencies, the Clinton Administration is expected to announce
today that it plans to add oil to the Strategic Petroleum Reserve
for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   PHARMACIA &AMP; UPJOHN PROFITABLE
</P>
<P>
   Drug maker Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn reported net income of $137
million, or 26 cents a diluted share, for the fourth quarter
compared with a loss of $128 million, or 26 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED; INTERNET ISSUES DROP
</P>
<P>
   Stocks meandered narrowly as bargain hunters stabilized some
battered high-technology issues even as most Internet companies
continued to slide. The Nasdaq composite index fell 1.29 points, to
2,309.50. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 44.28 points, to
9,177.31, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 7.41
points, to 1,223.55.
</P>
<P>
   E(star)TRADE SHARES SOLD BEFORE WOES
</P>
<P>
   Several major investors in the on-line brokerage firm
E(star)Trade Group sold big portions of their holdings last week
just before its trading system malfunctioned for several hours over
three days. Shares of E(star)Trade had been soaring, reaching a
high of $66.4375 on Feb. 1, but fell sharply after the trading
problems. Shares of ETrade closed at $42.75 yesterday, up $2.5625.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-MOGUL ENDS BID FOR LUCAS
</P>
<P>
   Federal-Mogul has dropped out of the bidding for Lucas Varity,
saying the purchase would not clear its financial hurdles. That
lets TRW proceed with its offer of $6.53 billion in cash, or 288
pence a share, for the maker of automotive brakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
