<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lack of TV interest, corporate support KO fight series at Roxy
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Evander Holyfield drew more than 40,000 fans for
a heavyweight title defense at the Georgia Dome in September, it
was reasonable to assume that the pro boxing scene in Atlanta would
experience some growth. Instead, it has suffered a significant
passing.
</P>
<P>
   After staging eight monthly fight cards at the Roxy Theater in
1998, Michael Morrison has decided not to bring the shows back this
year. The original plan was to have the first in a series of cards
this month, but a lack of local television interest and poor
corporate support led Morrison to shelve the series. It averaged
$20,000 to stage each show, he said, and he broke even on only a
few, losing an average of $5,000 per show on the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last show was in October, so we had four months to sell
out our next show,'' Morrison said. ``But we had only sold 30 of
the 45 tables (at $400 to $500 each). Television was really the
main thing, though. Without TV, we couldn't get the caliber of
fighters we wanted. People get tired of seeing the bum-of-the-month
club after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mishou, executive director of the Georgia Boxing Commission,
said the end of the Roxy shows shouldn't be viewed as anything
tragic. Morrison said he would promote one or two higher-level
shows during the year if he can get the corporate support, and the
Buckhead shows sparked interest from other local and national
promoters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like there to be monthly shows, but this doesn't hurt us
or help us,'' Mishou said. ``What Michael did, in essence, was
introduce boxing back to Atlanta. It had been several years since
smaller-venue shows had been done on a regular basis. Does this
hurt? Yeah. Is it devastating? He opened the door, and he's
leaving, but he's not closing the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight cards are scheduled Friday at the Center Stage Theater in
Midtown and March 3 at the World Congress Center. Promoter Don King
has staged some shows in the area and says he might do some on a
regular basis beginning in April.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison also is planning to move the Biggs-Morrison gym, which
he co-operates with trainer Xavier Biggs. Morrison said he hopes to
have a deal completed in the next 90 days to move the gym from its
location off Linden and Peachtree to a warehouse district off
Northside, two miles west of Peachtree. The current facility is
hampered by minimal parking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
