<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albany Nursery WMA may be sold
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Zell Miller no longer is governor of Georgia, but his
presence is still being felt, uncomfortably, in the Wildlife
Resources Division of the state Department of Natural Resources
because of controversy over the possible sale of a Wildlife
Management Area in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-acre Albany Nursery Wildlife Management Area, located in
Dougherty County, was suggested for sale last year by WRD as part
of its 2000 budget proposal now being considered by the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we regret that some hunters will lose the opportunity to
hunt at Albany Nursery, we believe that the proposal to sell this
area is a sound business decision and is in the best interest of
the state's sportsmen and women,'' WRD director David Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly will make the final decision whether to
sell the Albany Nursery during deliberations on the state's 2000
budget, probably sometime in March.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the budget process initiated by Miller, state
agencies must develop options for cutting their budgets or
generating additional revenue. The DNR proposed selling the small
tract, valued at $1.2 million, to generate funds instead of closing
other, larger wildlife management areas or fish hatcheries.
</P>
<P>
   Big-game hunts on the WMA are available only to people with
physical disabilities, yet it is so small that only 26 disabled
hunters were allowed to hunt deer and wild turkey during the
1998-99 season. There are limited small-game hunting opportunities
for other visitors. If the General Assembly approves the sale, WRD
will retain a portion of the funds to buy replacement land that
would provide facilities and hunting opportunities for physically
challenged hunters.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY TIME
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the free seminars at this weekend's Turkeyrama
can cut the learning curve on hunting wild turkey in Georgia by
years. Not only will the best hunters and callers be on the podium
at the Georgia Wildlife Federation-sponsored show at the Perry
Agrirama Friday through Sunday, some pretty good ones will be at
the show's many exhibits both as exhibitors and visitors. The show
features the cutting edge of turkey hunting, with shotguns,
accessories, calls and information. Tickets are $6 for adults and
$3 for seniors and children 6-12.
</P>
<P>
   GET BETTER `SARGE'
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shumaker, better known as ``Sarge'' to customers at the Fish
Hawk in Buckhead, is recovering from quadruple bypass heart surgery
at Emory University Hospital. Shumaker, 56, a retired Marine
gunnery sergeant, experienced chest pains while quail hunting
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At work on Monday, he continued to feel _ and look _ bad, so
Phyllis Merriman, mother of Fish Hawk proprietor Gary Merriman,
took charge and called Emory cardiologist Dr. Steve Clements, a
longtime customer. Shumaker met Clements at the emergency room, and
surgery was deemed necessary. Dr. Joe Craver, the surgeon, used a
new technique on Shumaker, using one vein from his leg and a radial
artery, rather than the usual pair of leg veins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
