<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beating Germany a boost
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was almost a year ago to the day since the U.S.
stunned Brazil that the Americans vanquished another formidable foe
in a 3-0 rout of Germany in Jacksonville on Saturday. But unlike
the Brazilian match, which came right before the World Cup, this
one wasn't followed by grand pronouncements that the U.S. is on the
verge of becoming a world power.
</P>
<P>
   New U.S. coach Bruce Arena got his first win in dominating
fashion against the ailing Germans, and while he's not jumping on a
bandwagon, he also was eager to pat his club on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics might say that the Germans didn't field a full
team, but neither did we,'' Arena said. ``In that game, we were
pretty good. It didn't matter who was in a German uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Three German-based players _ midfielders Jovan Kirovski and
Claudia Reyna and Hertha Berlin-bound MLS product Tony Sanneh _
scored as the U.S. displayed surprising offensive potency, getting
all three goals in the first 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, which plays Chile on Feb. 21 in Fort Lauderdale,
will probably have some different faces in camp. The German winter
break is ending, and Arena is continuing his policy of looking at
as many untested prospects as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a feeling coming out of the World Cup that American
soccer had hit rock bottom again,'' he said. ``I never thought that
was the case. The results are not totally surprising. I think it's
an indication that we're heading in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   WORLD CUP DRAW SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women have known for months when and where they will be
playing in the World Cup this summer. On Sunday, they'll find out
their first-round opponents when the draw and the first FIFA
Women's All-Star game take place in San Jose (8 p.m. ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   The draw is during halftime of the game pitting the U.S. team
against a side of international stars. The United States will open
on June 20 at Giants Stadium and then will play at Soldier Field on
June 24 before completing round-robin play June 27 in Foxboro,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The draw will place the 16 teams in four groups of four teams.
The other seeded teams are defending champion Norway, China and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   SILVERBACKS DRAFT THREE
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Silverbacks, looking for goalkeeping help, selected
Furman University's Ronnie Pascale in the A-League draft Sunday.
They also chose two local college standout forwards, Andy Leech of
Life University and Emory's Ahmed Mohyeldin. The team begins
training camp next month.
</P>
<P>
   NIKE DROPS ITALY
</P>
<P>
   As part of a range of cost-cutting moves, Nike has discontinued
its $15 million shoe and apparel sponsorship of the Italian
national team. Don't look for Nike to scale back its eight-year,
$200 million deal with Brazil, however, not with the global appeal
of the club and star player Ronaldo, whose Inter Milan club
recently joined the Nike stable. ... With perennial Italian Serie A
power Juventus stuck in ninth place, coach Marcelo Lippi resigned
abruptly Monday and was replaced by Carlo Ancelotti.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
