A9961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-FRANCE11-C     02-10 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-FRANCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racing change at top
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ NASCAR got its start on the beach here in
February 1948, and for the past 50 seasons a member of the France
family has held the torch as stock-car racing evolved into
America's fastest-growing spectator sport.
</P>
<P>
   After half a century, however, the France family turned over
control of stock-car racing's governing body on Wednesday. Bill
France Jr., who replaced his father as NASCAR president in 1972,
relinquished control of the organization's daily operations to Mike
Helton, the vice president of competition since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, former general manager at Atlanta Motor Speedway, was
named senior vice president and chief operating officer. France
Jr., 66, will remain as president, although he concedes that his
position will be largely ceremonial. ``I'm going to back out the
door,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   France said his decision is not because of health. He will keep
his position as CEO of International Speedway Corp., which owns the
Daytona and Talladega tracks and four others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in 1933,'' France said. ``You've got to do it
sometime, and I guess (now) is as good of a time as any. ... I
think Mike's ready, but that's not going to make it any easier to
walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also lines up Helton, 45, as France's successor
as president when he retires. Brian France, France's son, is
NASCAR's senior vice president and handles most marketing and
licensing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Under France, NASCAR evolved from a regional attraction in the
South into a national one. NASCAR attracted more than 6 million
fans to its 33 Winston Cup races last year, an average of 190,940
per event, including practice, qualifying and race day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, France negotiated a deal with CBS to televise the
Daytona 500, the sports' premier event. Now, every Winston Cup and
Busch Grand National race is telecast nationally, either on a
network or on cable.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the sport expanded, moving from smaller markets
to the major metro areas of Dallas, Los Angeles, Miami and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The France family is the sport,'' said Ray Evernham, crew
chief for two-time defending Cup champion Jeff Gordon. ``It's not
what they've done for the sport; they are the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
