<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-HUMMER11-C     02-10 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-HUMMER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    France family puts stamp on NASCAR
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You can keep your Sterns and your Tagliabues. And hold
the Seligs.
</P>
<P>
   The modern commissioner is a capable corporate juggler at best.
At worst, a grinning figurehead with all the authority of a movie
usher.
</P>
<P>
   To find the last of the great empire builders in sports these
days one looked to NASCAR, where the France family had raised stock
car racing from the bootlegger's shack to the luxury skybox. There
was a single vision, and it was Bill France Sr.'s. There was a
single opinion on improving the plan, and that was Bill Jr.'s. It
was just one of those racing deals. And the autocracy made many
rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   The junior France announced Wednesday that he was stepping back
from the daily watering and fertilizing of NASCAR, taking with him
the sport's founding surname. It's like a Steinway leaving the
piano business, a Spalding walking away from balls.
</P>
<P>
   A new sounding name, Mike Helton, now will be charged with
keeping the Fords, Chevys and Pontiacs reasonably happy. His
promotion signals the intention to keep NASCAR's focus on what got
it here. He's a car guy, who as vice president of competition did
all the mechanical fine-tuning that drivers and crew chiefs love to
debate. He kept such terms ``spoiler'' and ``front-air dam'' alive
and hot. While the next generation of France, Brian, cast his lot
with the merchandising end of the business.
</P>
<P>
   An era passes quietly. Junior was in tow in 1934 when Bill and
Annie France fled Washington D.C., stopped the family car on the
hard-sand beach of Daytona to take a quick swim and ended up
staying a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   What Bill France, the original, did then was race a little and
dream a lot. He had this idea that there was more to racing than
grease under the nails and dirt on the face. In 1947, he gathered
some fellow promoters at a hotel bar and mid-wifed NASCAR. The
organization's first address was France's service station.
</P>
<P>
   France handed the business over to his son in 1972, twenty years
before his death. It was the second year of racing's marriage with
Big Cigarette. The Daytona 500 was a part of the culture. The
circuit was just begining to break out of its Southern boundaries.
The styles of father and son were a little different, but they
shared a real low tolerance for nonsense or distractions. They
accomplished stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're racing in the deserts of Las Vegas and Phoenix, and
the green hills of New Hampshire. They've invaded the open-wheel
holy ground of Indianapolis. They're even racing in Japan, home to
the hated Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the Frances for the traffic, as NASCAR's popularity has
outgrown infrastructure. Blame them for a loss of soul, as the
humble tracks and the hardcore fans get pushed aside in the name of
progress. Blame them for night racing. Blame them for turning
drivers into multi-media celebrities. Sponsors and giant track
owners like Bruton Smith have helped shape racing, but the France
name is on every aspect of this boom time.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR never had a player's strike or an owner's lockout. The
drivers do not appear regularly at your local police precint.
Salaries are not the dominant theme. All in all, it has been a
pretty good run.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: steve(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
