</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-HELTON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Humble start launched Helton rise
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ In the early 1970s, Mike Helton took his
first job in automobile racing, operating a concessions stand as a
teenager at Bristol Motor Speedway in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than two decades later, Helton will be in charge of
the whole operation as NASCAR's senior vice president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR president Bill France Jr. said on Wednesday that Helton
would assume control of the organization's day-to-day operations.
The promotion probably means Helton eventually will replace France
as NASCAR president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started working at Bristol, I didn't have a clue
what I wanted to do,'' Helton said. ``I never dreamed I'd come this
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton spent a few years driving the dirt tracks of the Blue
Ridge Mountains as a teenager. After wrecking more than his share
of race cars, though, Helton said, it was obvious his future wasn't
on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured out pretty quick I wasn't much of a driver,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Helton crossed the state line to Tennessee, selling drinks and
popcorn part-time on the weekends at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first big break in stock-car racing when the three
original owners of Bristol sold the track to Lanny Hester and Gary
Baker of Nashville after the 1976 Winston Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything, cutting grass, painting walls, picking up
trash and selling advertising,'' Helton said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Helton moved to Atlanta to serve as public-relations
director at what was then known as Atlanta International Raceway.
By January 1985, Helton was promoted to be the track's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Helton held that role for more than a year before joining the
France family's International Speedway Corp. in June 1986. He
started his career with ISC at Daytona International Speedway,
working in promotions and marketing development.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1989, he was named a vice president of ISC and
president at Talladega Superspeedway. He was moved back to Daytona
in 1994 and served as NASCAR's vice president of competition until
Wednesday's promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in Atlanta, I didn't have many dealings with
him,'' France said. ``I didn't have as much (in Daytona) because he
was over in the marketing side. When he went to Talladega, though,
I had an awful lot of dealings with him. Needless to say, I was
certainly impressed with his analytical ability. He was able to
sort things out and not shoot from the hip. He's fulfilled all of
our expectations on the NASCAR side.''
</P>
<P>
   In his former role, Helton oversaw NASCAR's garage area, serving
as the governing body's liaison to drivers, crew chiefs and car
owners in both the Winston Cup and Busch Grand National circuits.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Winston Cup Series director Gary Nelson, Helton
spearheaded NASCAR's inspections. He also oversaw approval of the
Ford Taurus last year. This year, he's working closely with
Chevrolet in developing the new Monte Carlo, which still is
awaiting approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody in the garage area unhappy with
that announcement,'' said Ray Evernham, crew chief for Jeff Gordon.
``He's a super guy. When you went to talk to him, he'd listen.
Whenever you've got a problem and you call him, he'll call you
back. He'll sit and listen to you and won't fly off and get
excited, scream and holler. I don't think you'll find anyone that's
unhappy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   One year after its 50th anniversary season, NASCAR faces several
questions, many of which center on its future. At the top of
Helton's list is growth. The Winston Cup season already includes 34
races, but several tracks, including Las Vegas and Texas, are
requesting second dates.
</P>
<P>
   Speedways also are under construction in Chicago, Kansas City
and Kentucky, and plans are being completed for tracks in Baltimore
and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can grow a little bit more after talking with the
competitors, as long as we do it smartly,'' Helton said. ``We've
got to schedule the races correctly. Transportation is an issue,
but with the transporters and airplanes, we get around better than
we ever have.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 34 points races and the Bud Shootout and The Winston,
we've got 36 events in 1999. The issue would be, can you make it
37, 38 or 39? We think there's still room, but we just don't know
how much.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton takes over the daily operations from France Jr., who will
remain as president. But the France family still will have a
watchful eye. France's brother, Jim, is NASCAR's executive vice
president, and his son, Brian, is senior vice president. Still,
Helton doesn't anticipate a power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The France family still owns NASCAR,'' he said. ``My job is
just not to screw it up. We've got a pretty good thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   MIKE HELTON FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Aug. 30, 1953.
</P>
<P>
   _ Birthplace: Bristol, Va.
</P>
<P>
   _ Residence: Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: wife, Lynda; children, Richey and Tina.
</P>
<P>
   _ Experience: General manager, Atlanta International Raceway
(1985-86); general manager, Talladega Superspeedway (1987-89);
president, Talladega (1989-94); NASCAR vice president of
competition (1994-99).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
