<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sponsorless owner can't keep rookie
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Longtime Winston Cup owner Junie Donlavey
Jr. thought he arrived at Daytona International Speedway with a
sponsor for his No. 90 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   With only four days remaining before NASCAR's biggest event,
however, Donlavey says he still doesn't have a sponsorship check
from Big Daddy's Barbecue of Oklahoma, which produces sauces,
spices and meats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather they just forget this and not go through with
it,'' Donlavey said. ``I would rather just release them and we go
and look for someone else. You feel like you've been taken
advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Donlavey replaced Winston Cup rookie Mike Harmon
with veteran Mike Wallace as his driver for Sunday's Daytona 500.
Donlavey says Harmon's ride was contingent on Big Daddy's coming
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had Big Daddy's, we had money to be able to take some
time to bring a boy along, like Harmon,'' Donlavey said. ``It looks
like Big Daddy's has gone down the drain. . . . We like Mike, and
we wanted to go with him. But with the sponsor not coming through,
it put us back a lot further than we needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Donlavey said he decided to replace Harmon, a short-track
specialist from Alabama, on Tuesday night. After agreeing to drive
the No. 90 Ford, Wallace was scrambling to find a doctor for
medical clearance, as well as equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over and borrowed four shocks from (brother) Rusty's
(Wallace) team just to get us a baseline,'' Wallace said. ``I had
to go find a set of ear molds and gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace ran one Cup race last season, finishing 23rd and
collecting $86,105 in the Daytona 500. Wallace will drive full-time
in the Craftsman Truck Series this year, and his deal with Donlavey
appears to be for only Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace will start 24th in today's first Gatorade 125 qualifying
race, and must finish in the top 14 to make the Daytona 500 field.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harmon is holding out hope that Big Daddy's comes
through and that he's back in Donlavey's car at North Carolina
Speedway on Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a done deal,'' he said. ``We're not through running
Winston Cup this year, even with the No. 90. The sponsorship
package was on top of the fence, and it could fall either way.''
</P>
<P>
   GATORADE 125S
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for Sunday's Daytona 500 resumes today at 12:30 p.m.
with the Gatorade 125 twin races. Each race will include 30
drivers, including Jeff Gordon and Tony Stewart, who will sit on
the poles of races 1 and 2, respectively. The twin races determine
positions 3-30 of the Daytona 500 field, so some drivers starting
near the back will have to move through the field to qualify for
the race.
</P>
<P>
   DISQUALIFIED
</P>
<P>
   Lance Hooper, who qualified for the No. 26 spot in Saturday's
NAPA Auto Parts 300 Busch race, was disqualified after
post-qualifying inspection found parts had been altered to allow
more air into the manifold.
</P>
<P>
   Races at Daytona and Talladega are run using restrictor plates,
which reduce the airflow through the carburetor to reduce speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper won't participate in the race, allowing Brad Loney, who
qualified 37th, to move into the field in the No. 36 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
