<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-REACT11-CO     02-10 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-REACT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drivers endorse choice
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Bill France Jr. spent the past 26 years
shaping NASCAR into America's fastest-growing spectator sport, but
the sport's drivers say stock car racing won't miss a beat with
Mike Helton running the show.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers, crew members and owners say they were surprised at
Wednesday's announcement that France was handing over day-to-day
operations to Helton.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup teams learned the news in the garage area of Daytona
International Speedway, while the announcement was being made in
the Benny Kahn Infield Media Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, if you've been around as long as I have, I saw the same
thing happen with (Bill France Sr.), when he passed the torch to
Billy,'' veteran driver Darrell Waltrip said. ``It looks to me like
they're doing about the same thing. I've watched Mike Helton over
the last couple of years here. He's a very capable man of doing the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton, who spent the past five years as NASCAR's vice president
of competition, received an overwhelming endorsement from drivers
and owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't come to me, but if they came to me and said they
were getting ready to do this and asked me who I thought would be
the guy, Mike Helton would be my choice,'' said Jack Roush, who
owns five Winston Cup teams, including the No. 6 Ford of Mark
Martin. ``Mike has got maturity, he's got wisdom, and he's
certainly embroiled in France's philosophy of stock-car racing, so
it'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan, driver of the No. 36 Pontiac, credits Helton with
helping to revive his career after a nearly fatal accident during
practice at Michigan Speedway on Aug. 20, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan, who was given only a 10 percent chance of survival
immediately after the wreck, was hospitalized for several weeks,
but returned to racing after only 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has really played a major part in my career,'' Irvan
said. ``When I was trying to come back from my injuries, Mike kept
a close eye on everything that was going on. He's a very personable
person. We know that him being bumped up is definitely a positive
note for NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say they hope that France, who says he'll spend much of
his extra time fishing, will still be a familiar sight at race
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill deserves to take some time off,'' said Michael Kranefuss,
who owns the No. 12 Ford of Jeremy Mayfield. ``He's got some good
people in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that he'll be around in case his presence is
needed, but I really think that Mike is the man that can take it
from here. What Bill's done for the sport of auto racing, his whole
family, it's remarkable, and I hope he's going to be around for a
long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
