</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-Mail's Security Called Shoddy  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Millions of people who get free e-mail services from Yahoo, Hotmail
and Excite are subject to hacker attacks because their privacy
protections are so poor, a nationally known Internet security
expert said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Winkler, a former analyst for the National Security Agency,
said these accounts are easy to break into because they allow an
unlimited number of log-on attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody can try every possible password to get into the
system,'' said Winkler. ``They will get in eventually _ and you
will never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackers can create software programs that will automate password
selection, going through countless combinations of numbers and
letters until hitting on the right one.
</P>
<P>
   Other security experts confirmed Winkler's observation, saying
it is just one of the security weaknesses of the free e-mail
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, you should look a gift horse in the mouth,''
said Peter Neumann, an expert in computer security at SRI
International, a Menlo Park research firm. Companies that offer
free services, don't spend a lot of time worrying about security,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some paid e-mail services, including America Online, and most
corporate networks will lock out users after a certain number of
failed log-on attempts. In such cases, the user is often e-mailed
about the failed log-in trys and told to contact system
administrators who verify the user's identity, Winkler said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hotmail, recently acquired by Microsoft, and Excite issued
statements yesterday saying they offer protections for e-mail
customers.
</P>
<P>
   MSN Hotmail has ``no knowledge of any Hotmail accounts ever
being compromised'' because of unlimited log-in attempts, said
product manager Laura Norman. Hotmail ``has plans in place to
implement a solution'' to address the problem, Norman said, but she
could not provide any details.
</P>
<P>
   Excite said it gives users the ability ``to protect their e-mail
accounts with longer passwords than other free e-mail services.
Accounts protected with long passwords can be more difficult to
hack as they are more difficult to decipher.'' The Redwood Shores
Internet company did not directly address the log-on issue.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo did not respond to a request for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, now a private Internet security consultant in Maryland,
disclosed his security concerns in a column yesterday on ZDTV's Web
site ( &LR; www.zdnet.com/zdtv &LR; ). He said he was working on a column
about free e-mail when the question of password security came up.
Just to experiment, he tried to break in and found it surprisingly
simple to randomly find a user's password.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be so easy, security experts said. First, the
services should require users to choose a strong password _ one
that is seven characters or more and is a combination of letters
(uppercase and lowercase) and numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The services also should not allow an unlimited number of log-on
attempts, and they should notify users if someone has been trying
to get into their account, Winkler said. Although Yahoo asks users
if they need help after three failed log-ins, it does not prevent
them from trying again and again.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail users can take some preventive measures, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't pick anything that is too simple or too easily
identified with you,'' said Peter Shipley, who gained notoriety _
not to mention the nickname ``Evil Pete'' _ by hacking into
computer systems at the University of California at Berkeley in the
1980s. He is now a computer-security consultant for KPMG in Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Other advice: Use a different password for each e-mail account
or, if that's too difficult, a different password for different
types of accounts: one for work and one for home, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But even the best password may be vulnerable, he said, because
Excite, Yahoo and the other Internet companies send password and
user ID information as plain text that is not encrypted. In these
cases, sophisticated computer users can use software programs known
as ``sniffers'' to grab your data as it travels over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: be careful what you say in e-mail, Shipley
said. ``E-mail sent over the Internet should be treated as if it
were a postcard _ and not necessarily private.''
</P>
</TEXT>
