r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     02-10 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TO GET TASTE OF MAPLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During their high school careers, UCLA's freshmen played
throughout the country and on several continents. They encountered
prep all-star teams and junior national teams. They played in
bandbox gyms and spacious arenas. But nothing prepared them for
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   There is no place like Stanford's Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like anything they've experienced before,'' UCLA
sophomore Travis Reed said. ``It's the worst place to play in the
Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Three factors will conspire to make tonight's experience unique:
at home, following a loss to Connecticut, Stanford probably will
play at a higher level than any team UCLA has faced; the fans, who
are part-funny, part-crude and completely raucous; finally, there's
that floor, basketball on a wooden trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the great home-court advantages in college
basketball,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``The floor shakes.
You have to shoot at a moving basket.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's veterans _ sophomores Reed, Earl Watson and Baron Davis _
were indoctrinated last year in a 13-point Stanford victory. Only
junior Sean Farnham and senior Brandon Loyd experienced the Maples
Massacre, UCLA's 48-point loss at Stanford in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, the Bruins have the size and depth
to counterpunch. And like Stanford antagonists Arizona and
Connecticut, they have the quickness to disrupt the Cardinal
offense.
</P>
<P>
   But quickness is half the equation. Do the Bruins have the
structure _ the fundamentals, discipline and poise _ necessary to
defeat a team that exists on a different plane of precision? The
Bruins could be the quickest team in basketball history, but
without smarts and fundamentals, Stanford will carve them like a
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to push the tempo, not get into a grinder game,''
Reed said. ``If we slow it down, it'll be to their advantage, but
we have to be smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the freshmen. UCLA cannot survive on sophomores
alone. The freshmen must contribute in their varying states of
health and spirits. Forward Jerome Moiso expects to play but will
not be at full speed because of tendinitis on the bottom of his
foot. Center Dan Gadzuric is plagued by tendinitis in his knees.
How will they react to the Maples court?
</P>
<P>
   Has forward JaRon Rush's recovered from his one-game benching
for poor practice attitude? How will Alameda native Ray Young react
to familiar territory? And what of Matt Barnes, whose playing time
fluctuates wildly? Will his recent progress continue?
</P>
<P>
   So many questions and only one answer. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Clunk and clank: If the game is decided on the foul line, it
might be a forfeit. UCLA is the worst free-throw shooting team in
the conference (59 percent) and Stanford is dropping fast after a
12-of-24 performance against Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   They have a similar problem: the most-fouled players _
Stanford's Mark Madsen and UCLA's Baron Davis _ are among the worst
shooters. Davis has taken 30 more free throws than any UCLA player
and is shooting 59.6 percent. Madsen has taken 65 more free throws
than any Cardinal and is shooting 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them that front rim misses are on them, and back rim
misses are on me,'' Lavin said. ``Ninety percent of our misses are
(front rim) because we're not extending and following through.''
</P>
<P>
   A clarification: There was some confusion Sunday about the
reason Gadzuric did not start. UCLA officials said his tendinitis
was the problem, Lavin said is was a lethargic practice Saturday,
and Gadzuric claimed ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason he did not start was because he did not practice to
the (proper) level of intensity,'' Lavin said Tuesday. ``We told
Dan before the game that he wouldn't start.''
</P>
<P>
   Case closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
