<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ACTIVEWELLNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUIDE TO HEALTHFUL LIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA WAGNER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Active Wellness
</P>
<P>
   Time Life Books, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   A motivating guide to a lifetime of healtful living, ``Active
Wellness'' shows how to balance the demands of career and family
with your mental and physical well-being. Author Gayle Reichler
says the success of her program is that it recognizes that ``no one
diet, exercise regimen, stress management plan, or behavioral
change can possibly be right for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Far beyond the days of ``No Pain, No Gain,'' the '90s' holistic
approach to health treats the person: mind, body, and spirit. A
registered dietitian, Reichler furthered that concept as a
corporate wellness coach for megacompanies such as NBC, Sony,
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, and McGraw-Hill. She gained further respect after
bringing the success of the Active Wellness program to New York's
respected Beth Israel Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The key to long-term success with the Active Wellness program's
10 steps is to understand your health needs and history. In
addition to other valuable tools, you'll learn how to start a
personalized eating plan, form new healthful habits, manage stress,
cook low-fat foods that are actually edible, and deal with the
things that can sabotage success.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
