<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAKE VENOM AND THERAPY BY ZAPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NO SNAKE OIL
</P>
<P>
   An experimental drug derived from the venom of a pit viper is
helping stroke victims recover their physical and mental abilities,
according to scientists reporting at last week's American Heart
Association International Conference on Stroke and Cerebral
Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a 500-person trial of the drug ANCROD (not yet
approved by the FDA) found that 42 percent of those treated with
the drug within three hours of stroke onset regained their
pre-stroke faculties.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers discovered that in people who were bitten by the
snake, blood did not clot, leading to speculation that the venom
could be used as an anticoagulant, helping blood flow more freely
through vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ZAP THE PAIN
</P>
<P>
   Electrical nerve stimulation may help reduce chronic pain in
cancer patients, especially those whose cancer has spread to the
bones, say researchers at the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical School in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Some cancers that spread to bones produce severe chronic pain
that is unresponsive to analgesic drugs, including morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists report that percutaneous electrical nerve stimulation
(PENS), a technique that involves the insertion of acupuncturelike
needles into the soft tissue surrounding bones, produces
significant pain relief. During the procedure, an electrical
current is passed through the needles, apparently disrupting normal
pain signals by stimulating local nerves.
</P>
<P>
   PENS may reduce the need for narcotics and other more invasive
procedures but should be used to complement, not eliminate, other
pain-management techniques, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGEST KILLER
</P>
<P>
   On an average day in Texas, 156 people die of cardiovascular
diseases, according to data released last week by the Texas
affiliate of the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease remains the No. 1 killer in Texas, claiming the
lives of 57,050 people in 1997 (40 percent of the 142,569 Texas
residents who died). Cancer was the second leading cause of death,
claiming 32,144 lives.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce your risk, keep blood pressure under control, eat
nutritious foods in moderate amounts, have regular checkups,
exercise and don't smoke. .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
