<HEADLINE>
ROMNEY'S CHANCES TO HEAD SLOC LOOKIN GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Mitt Romney could be named head of the
embattled Salt Lake Organizing Committee when the board of trustees
meets this morning, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Romney, the wealthy Belmont, Mass., venture capitalist and
former US Senate candidate, met with members of the selection panel
here Tuesday night and spent much of Wednesday conferring with
board members.
</P>
<P>
   The board's first task, however, will be to expand from 33 to 50
members and transform the 12-member executive committee into a
20-member management committee as part of a reorganization due to
the widening Olympic payoff scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Romney was identified last week as the top choice to replace
Frank Joklik, who resigned as chief executive last month. But the
board did not name a search committee until Tuesday, after the SLOC
ethics panel released a blistering 300-page report on a seven-year
campaign to induce International Olympic Committee members to name
the Utah capital host of the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had a chance to talk about the issue in any
depth,'' said board chairman Robert Garff. ``We plan to talk about
it on Thursday. Whether we will be in a position to nominate
anybody remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Romney tops a decidedly short list that includes Dave Checketts,
the Madison Square Garden CEO and former Utah Jazz president.
Another potential candidate, Jon Huntsman Jr., a chemical company
vice chairman and former ambassador to Singapore, withdrew from
consideration after it became clear there would be no real search,
he told The Associated Press. He also rejected Leavitt's request
that he serve on SLOC's new management committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly has a lot of wherewithal to do the job,'' said
Garff, who is one of Romney's two prime boosters, along with Utah
Governor Mike Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Romney fulfills what Garff has said the board is
looking for in a ``white knight'' _ a prominent figure with Utah
roots, a business background, and a clean image.
</P>
<P>
   Romney, who has made hundreds of millions of dollars as chief of
Boston-based Bain Capital, is a Mormon and former Brigham Young
University valedictorian who owns a winter home in nearby Park
City.
</P>
<P>
   Though Romney wants the job, a source close to him said he
needed to familiarize himself with the ethics report and was
concerned that some board members with business ties to the SLOC
may have conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Alan Layton heads a construction company that is
building the roof for the Olympic speedskating oval, and Earl
Holding owns the Snowbasin ski resort, where the downhill races
will be held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
