<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BIDS FOR FINAL FOUR IN 2004 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The FleetCenter has applied to the NCAA to host the
women's basketball Final Four in 2004. Harvard and Northeastern
would serve as co-hosts for the event, which would mark the first
time a women's basketball championship has been held in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be terrific for the area; it will be a lot of
fun,'' said Harvard athletic director Bill Cleary Wednesday. ``I'd
love to see us get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA women's site committee is studying bids to host the
women's Final Four in 2003 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the preliminary stages of just gathering applications
now,'' said Tricia Burke, the NCAA head of the women's selection
committee. ``We'll be sorting through those in the next several
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA will announce the potential sites next week and pare
the list to a handful of finalists by the end of March. ``The
committee will then make on-site inspections,'' said Burke, who
added that many factors beyond the actual venue are taken into
consideration. ``The committee will look at the city as a whole and
decide if it can handle an event like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter hosted a men's hockey Final Four last year and
will host first- and second-round NCAA men's basketball tournament
games March 12 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NCAA has no written policy on geographical sites,
it prefers to move its championship venues to different areas of
the country each year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's women's Final Four will be in San Jose, Calif. Next
year it will be in Philadelphia. St. Louis and San Antonio are the
sites for 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The final decision and announcement on 2004 will be in late
June.
</P>
</TEXT>
