<SLUG> BC-AVERSTAR-CBSI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERSTAR TO BUY COMPUTER BASED SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Government software contractor AverStar Inc. plans to announce
Thursday the purchase of another computer services firm, in a deal
valued at roughly $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   AverStar, based in Burlington, Mass., said it plans to acquire
Computer Based Systems Inc. of Fairfax, Va., bringing AverStar's
total yearly revenue to nearly $200 million and adding about 600
employees to the 1,300 who presently work for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase will help AverStar compete for service contracts
for federal agencies where CBSI has been more successful than
AverStar to date, said AverStar chairman and chief executive
Michael Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Those agencies include the Patent &AMP; Trademark Office, the
Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Labor.
AverStar is best known for testing and developing software for the
Navy, the Postal Service, NASA and the Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes as part of an expansion campaign meant to
increase AverStar's annual revenues to $500 million by 2002.
According to Alexander, an increase to that size will make the firm
more competitive with rivals like EDS and Computer Sciences Corp.
at a time when government contracting procedures are changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal government competitions are offering larger and
longer-term contracts, and we need to be able to convince them that
we're able to handle it,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Specific terms of the agreement weren't available. But a person
familiar with the transaction said it valued CBSI at around 60
percent of its 1998 revenue of $40 million, indicating a purchase
price of about $24 million _ in line with prices for similar firms.
</P>
<P>
   AverStar was formed a year ago as a combination of two other
software services firms, Intermetrics Inc. of Burlington, Mass. and
Pacer Infotech Inc. of Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the company is now controlled by former
Intermetrics shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with CBSI represents the first large purchase by
AverStar since the merger. About 85 percent of AverStar's revenue
now comes from work for public agencies.
</P>
<P>
   To support further growth, AverStar is considering an initial
offering of public stock later this year, said company vice
president Paul Serotkin.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that an IPO isn't likely until after the
purchase of CBSI is completed in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, CBSI founder and president
Mohan Kapani will retire and the unit will henceforth be headed by
Richard W. Zins, previously vice president of the company's
services group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
