<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN ASBURY LONG, PROFESSOR WHO ADVOCATED ARMS REDUCTIONS, DIES
AT 88  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Texas, Ore . )  By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Franklin Asbury Long, an emeritus professor at Cornell
University, former government adviser and advocate of international
arms reductions, died on Monday at a nursing home in Pomona, Calif.
He was 88 and had lived in Ithaca, N.Y., and Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A chemist by training, Long was a member of the President's
Science Advisory Committee in the administrations of Dwight D.
Eisenhower, John F. Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson. He also was
assistant director of the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency
in the early 1960s. His subsequent nomination as director of the
National Science Foundation ran afoul of officials in President
Richard M. Nixon's White House because of Long's opposition to its
antiballistic missile project.
</P>
<P>
   Heralded as a pillar of the country's nuclear defense strategy,
the missiles project stirred controversy from the start, and Long
had earlier argued in The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists that
the government's attempts to develop the antiballistic missile
would create ``strong pressure toward acceleration of the arms
race.''
</P>
<P>
   When a board of scientists nominated Long to be director of the
National Science Foundation, he went to Washington for an
appointment with Nixon, but later recalled that he learned from a
presidential science aide that things had changed because of the
missile matter. The White House disapproved of Long's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists voiced alarm over the implication that the
government wanted to hear only from advisers who agreed with its
policies. The White House later relented on the foundation
director's post, but Long then declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Asbury Long was born in Great Falls, Mont., and
graduated from the University of Montana in 1931, where he also
earned a master's degree in 1932. He obtained his doctorate in
chemistry in 1935 at the University of California at Berkeley,
where he began his academic career as an instructor.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Cornell faculty in Ithaca, N.Y., in 1937, and was
promoted to full professor in 1939, later serving as chairman of
the chemistry department. He was Cornell's vice president for
research and advanced studies in the 1960s and was named Henry Luce
Professor of Science and Society in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Long also directed the university's program on science,
technology and society and its peace studies program, retiring in
1979. He then moved to California, where he taught as an adjunct
professor at the University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   He was an editor of ``Weapons in Space'' (Norton, 1986), a
collection of essays on both sides of the debate involving
antimissile defenses and related technologies.
</P>
<P>
   He served on the boards of The Bulletin of the Atomic
Scientists, the Albert Einstein Peace Prize Foundation and the Fund
for Peace. He was also active in the international Pugwash movement
of scientists concerned about the world's arsenals of war.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Marion Thomas Long, died in 1992. Long is survived by
a son, Franklin, of Claremont; a daughter, Elizabeth Long of
Houston; a brother, George of Portland, Ore., and a grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
