<HEADLINE>
GINGERLY, FORD CHIEF DISCUSSES BMW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note subslug for FORD-AUTO-SHOW) 
(af) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Jacques Nasser, chief executive and president of Ford
Motor Co., said Wednesday that Ford would not try to buy BMW AG as
long as BMW wants to remain independent. He hinted, however, that
Ford would be interested in buying the German automaker if it puts
itself up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's board replaced the company's chairman last Friday, in a
sudden move that most industry executives attributed to the poor
performance of Britain's Rover, which BMW bought in 1994. BMW
officials have insisted since then that they want to remain
independent, but its stock has risen on the expectation that
pressure will increase for BMW to seek a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at the Chicago Auto Show, Nasser chose his
words with care, saying that he did not want to throw ``gasoline on
the fire'' of speculation about BMW's future. ``I wouldn't rule out
anything, but I think when a company with the stature of BMW and
its board come out and say they want to be independent, I have to
respect that,'' Nasser said.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked what Ford's position would be if BMW's insistence
on independence changed, Nasser replied: ``We never say never _ if
there's a tremendous opportunity out there, we always take a look
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW has one of the best brand names and some of the finest
engineers in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Pischetsrieder, BMW's chairman, was replaced last Friday
and Wolfgang Reitzle, BMW's head of new-model development, resigned
when he was not chosen to replace him. German media reported
Wednesday that Reitzle would join Ford to run vehicle development;
Nasser would say only that he admired Reitzle and felt sympathy for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Ford agreed at the end of last month to buy the car-making
operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.5 billion. The Quandt family
of Germany owns 46 percent of BMW.
</P>
<P>
   It would probably owe huge taxes in a cash sale of the
automaker. Such taxes could be avoided if Ford and BMW combined
their operations in a so-called ``pooling of interests'' and issued
stock in the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   But this could be difficult for Ford, because such a merger
might dilute the Ford family's controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also plans to announce on Thursday that it will install
rigid oval hooks in the base of rear-seat cushions. Some current
child-restraint seats and all future models will latch easily to
the hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators are expected to move as quickly as next week
to require the rigid hooks. Safety experts say the hooks are more
reliable than using seat belts to secure child restraint seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
