<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY COMPANIES NOT THE ONLY ONES BACKING DEREGULATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It understandably makes Texans nervous when they hear that the
state's largest electric utility companies favor deregulation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it should make Texans much more comfortable to learn that
large segments of business and industry that are major electricity
users are enthusiastically backing deregulation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That includes everybody from Foley's department stores to
Motorola, the electronics giant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They are among the many members of a broad-based group called
the Texas Coalition for Competitive Electricity. The coalition
forecasts that deregulation will lead to lower electricity prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I believe that indeed will be the case, if the Texas Legislature
has the wisdom to pass a good deregulation bill. It must be
structured to ensure strong price competition and provide adequate
consumer safeguards, particularly for residential customers.
Deregulation bills have been filed by two respected legislators,
state Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, and state Rep. Steve Wolens,
D-Dallas. There's a good chance that the Legislature will approve a
deregulation bill in its current session. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason that a deregulated market will increase
competition and lower prices, just as it generally has in the
airline and long-distance telephone businesses. Deregulation would
permit consumers to choose from whom they buy electricity, just as
they have a choice of long-distance phone services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under deregulation, you could continue buying your electricity
from TU Electric or whatever utility serves you. Or you could
switch to another provider without requiring a new power line to
your home. With deregulation, new electricity providers could pay
access fees for the right to use the transmission networks of
long-existing utilities such as TU Electric. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now let's talk about the Coalition for Competitive Electricity.
It includes trade associations representing the electronics,
petroleum, chemical, concrete and forest products industries, as
well as operators of apartment complexes, restaurants, hotels and
service stations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coalition representatives predict that deregulation is likely to
lower electric bills by 8 to 10 percent, with savings potentially
reaching 15 to 20 percent in areas that now have
higher-than-average rates. And they predict that the savings will
be realized not only by large commercial and industrial consumers
but also homeowners and apartment dwellers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the coalition representatives is Chris Perrault,
utilities director for the huge Tricon restaurant chain that
includes Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and KFC. Tricon has 1,300
company-owned and franchise restaurants in Texas alone. Nationally,
its nearly 20,000 restaurants spend $1.2 billion annually for
chicken and $800 million for cheese. But they also spend $450
million on energy, primarily for electricity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perrault said he is greatly encouraged by the initial results of
deregulation in Pennsylvania, where many residential customers
switching from Philadelphia Electric to other providers are
reducing their electric bills by 10 percent or more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why are utilities such as TU Electric and Houston Lighting &AMP;
Power backing deregulation? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's because they see the handwriting on the wall. At least 17
states have moved toward giving customers a choice of electricity
providers. In addition, the big Texas electric utilities saw their
enthusiasm for the current regulated market wane after a 1997
ruling by the state Public Utility Commission that lowered rates
charged by a large South Texas utility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation won't guarantee lower rates. If prices were to
skyrocket for natural gas (which is burned to generate
electricity), electricity bills would probably jump whether the
market were deregulated or not. But deregulation clearly increases
the odds for lower prices, and that's all we consumers can ask
for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
