<HEADLINE>
SNACKWELL'S TRIES TO LINK ITS PRODUCTS AND MOTHER-DAUGHTER
RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many companies brag about having a relationship with consumers.
But relationships come in a lot of varieties, and at RJR Nabisco,
executives in charge of Snackwell's want the relationship between
their lower-fat snack foods and their target market, the women of
America, to be meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be called the ``Our Cookies, Our Selves''
approach, the company is spending heavily on advertisements and
promotions that seek to form a treacly bond between Snackwell's
products and women's lives, with a particular emphasis on
motherhood. It's a drastic departure from the way Snackwell's was
promoted until recently, relying on the old standby 50-cents-off
coupon to drive sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women don't necessarily just want a transaction,'' said Terry
Preskar, Nabisco's senior business director for Snackwell's,
explaining the shift in emphasis. ``They want a relationship.
That's the way we are in our lives. We wanted to build a
relationship that would really drive deep loyalty to the brand, and
build in a reason for the purchase that goes above and beyond the
product. We want to stand for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Snackwell's will give away a paperback journal _
with the purchase of two boxes of Snackwell's products, that is _
that mothers and daughters can fill out for each other in time for
Mother's Day. To help people complete the task, the journal pages
have what Ms. Preskar called ``prompts,'' such as ``You made me
laugh when you did ___'' and ``You made me cry when you did ___.''
Participants then fill in the blanks. ``We've made it beautiful but
easy to do,'' Ms. Preskar said.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has allied itself with Girls Inc., a nonprofit
organization in Indianapolis whose motto emphasizes making girls
``strong, smart and bold.'' Snackwell's donated money to the group,
which has 350,000 members, and plans to sponsor four-hour workshops
in 27 cities that encourage mothers and daughters to talk to one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Print ads about the workshops, scheduled for the weekend after
Mother's Day, will run in women's magazines in April and May, and
information about the sites is available at www.snackwells.com, the
company's Web site. They are not free, however; participants must
pay $19.95 for each mother-daughter session and submit 10
Snackwell's proof-of-purchase labels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is continuing to run its television
commercials, created by the Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding Worldwide unit of
True North Communications, that carry the message ``Live well.
Snackwell.'' And to keep the momentum going, Nabisco is organizing
a direct-mail program derived from a data base that identifies big
Snackwell's purchasers and potential purchasers using sales
information from retailers.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes at a time when Ms. Preskar and others at Nabisco
are working hard to revive the Snackwell's brand, which soared on
its initial release but then declined drastically as other low-fat
products came along and the company's attention wandered.
</P>
<P>
   Sales peaked in 1995 and fell at double-digit rates until last
summer. In July, new products were added and old ones were
reformulated, all with more fat than the original versions but with
better taste, the company insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the company called in Faith Popcorn, the
trendspotter, who identified women as Snackwell's biggest
customers. ``We suddenly looked at all the activities in the
marketing mix very differently,'' Ms. Preskar said. ``Consumers
still want coupons, but we asked, `How can we spend the rest of our
money in a way that will be really meaningful to women?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The effort seems to be helping, or at least not hindering. Sales
of Snackwell's ``turned around in the last few months,'' said Nomi
Ghez, a food analyst for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``Part of it is new
advertising, and part of it is better advertising and promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   More programs about relationships are in the works, but the
company chose to lead with the mother-daughter theme because even
in focus groups composed of people with no daughters, and no
children at all, there was a certain emotional resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was such support because every woman is a daughter,''
said Ms. Preskar, whose own daughter is 2. ``They have tremendous
heart for making things better for the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cause-related marketing _ look for Snackwell's to join the fight
against diseases and social problems that particularly afflict
women _ is generally an effective way for companies to project a
positive image, said David Walsh, president of the National
Institute on Media and the Family. The nonprofit group studies the
effect of advertising and other media on families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can be against mothers and daughters having a better
relationship?'' he said. ``Ninety-nine percent of people would not
be against it. By linking their product to that particular
movement, the company is trying to create a halo effect, saying
that their product is somehow good for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst suggested that given the scant marketing of
Snackwell's until recently, almost any effort would help the brand.
Still, the improved flavor, which replaced what some had compared
to ``sugary straw,'' deserved at least partial credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snackwell's is really happy to have some money behind it,
finally,'' said Erika Gritman Long, a food analyst for J.P. Morgan.
``And the product tastes a lot better now than it ever has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
