<HEADLINE>
STANFORD HITS A LOW SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD _ The way people are talking up here, you'd think the
topic was Cardinal (begin ital)football(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Stanford remains the best basketball team in the Pac-10, one of
the best in the nation, a strong Final Four candidate and a
monstrous obstacle for UCLA (tonight) and USC (Saturday) in Maples
Pavilion. It has lost just four games, all to top-12 teams: North
Carolina, Maryland, Arizona and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cal coach Ben Braun said, ``I don't know why everybody's
into this Stanford bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Cardinal (19-4, 9-1) has clearly entered a
midseason lull. It's not functioning with the precision it showed
in Los Angeles a month ago. The proof is a slew of narrow victories
(Washington, Arizona State and Cal) and one stat: Stanford has
trailed by at least nine points in the first half of five
consecutive games. It may not be vulnerable, especially at Maples,
but it's as close to vulnerability as anyone would have imagined.
Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   Bad matchups: By quirk of scheduling, the Cardinal faced two of
its worst matchups (Arizona and Connecticut) in a one-week span.
The Wildcats and Huskies possess the one ingredient (quickness)
Stanford's chain-saw execution cannot counteract.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue: Early-season injuries to reserve guards Mike McDonald
and Ryan Mendez have forced starters Arthur Lee and Kris Weems to
log unexpected minutes, and their production has suffered. The
slender Lee is shooting 37 percent from the field in conference
play; Weems, 42 percent. (In his last four games, Lee has made 9 of
38 field goals.) For a half-court team that does not generate many
easy baskets, perimeter shooting is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Free throws: The Cardinal offense is designed to get power
forward Mark Madsen scoring opportunities in the low post, and it
has. Faced with two choices _ foul Madsen or surrender layups _
opponents have wisely started fouling. Madsen is shooting 56.1
percent from the line and made 3 of 8 against Connecticut (the team
connected on 12 of their 24 free throws against the Huskies).
</P>
<P>
   Are the glitches cause for alarm? No. Mild concern? Probably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit a lull about this time last year, too,'' Madsen said.
``Every team has its ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Stanford recovered from its ``downs'' to reach the
Final Four. Don't be surprised if it does that again.
</P>
<P>
   The debate rages: Rarely have the stakes for a specific No. 1
seed been as high as they are this season, with Duke and
Connecticut jockeying for the top spot in the East.
</P>
<P>
   It's a chance for UConn to play first- and second-round games in
Boston's Fleet Center, a few hours from its campus in Storrs, and
play the regionals in the Meadowlands in East Rutherford, N.J., a
Big East city.
</P>
<P>
   The other first-round East site is Charlotte, N.C., near
you-know-where. In addition, the Blue Devils view the Meadowlands
as Cameron Indoor North, since it has been the launch pad for
several Final Fours.
</P>
<P>
   The East is the home region for the Big East and Atlantic Coast
Conference champions, so both teams have a legitimate claim. But
that's a guideline for balancing the brackets, not a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Why won't the Blue Devils settle for the top seed in the South?
Check the regional site: Knoxville, Tenn. The last thing Duke wants
is to face Kentucky, a potential No. 2 seed, in the South finals in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy feet: Last week, St. Mary's announced 340-pound center
Brad Millard won't play this season, after all. Because of a series
of foot injuries and subsequent surgeries, Millard has played just
two games since his earth-moving matchup with Tim Duncan in the
first round of the 1997 NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But Millard has not disappeared from the NBA scouting screen. In
fact, he's considering applying for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not ready totally, but he's (7-foot-3), and in one year
he'll definitely be ready,'' said Oregon coach Ernie Kent, formerly
of St. Mary's. ``Some teams will have to take that gamble. He has
great hands, he knows how to catch, and his footwork is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: Cal guard Ray ``Circus'' King is living down
his nickname and giving the rudderless Bears much-needed stability.
His emergence allows struggling senior Geno Carlisle to play his
natural position, wing guard. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State rookie coach Rob Evans, formerly of the SEC, on
the difference between the conferences: ``The SEC is very physical
and has very good athletes, but the Pac-10 has more skill players
who can do things with the basketball.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   The difference between second place and eighth place is
excruciatingly _ or joyously _ thin: Arizona has won five games by
a total of nine points and Oregon has lost six games by a total of
14 points. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Washington has won seven of eight and Hec Edmundson Pavilion is
becoming a hot spot: Gary Payton has front-row seats. Next year,
the Huskies will play in Payton's place, Key Arena, while Hec Ed
gets a facelift. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Lute Olson has used 10 starting lineups with his
young team, but he's got nothing on UCLA coach Steve Lavin, who has
used 15. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The latest Ratings Percentage Index rankings: 3. Stanford, 15.
UCLA, 16. Washington, 17. Arizona, 55. Oregon. Unless they
collapse, the Huskies are in the tournament. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
