<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTIETH CENTURY EXPECTED TO REPORT SPIKE IN EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. -- Twentieth Century Industries Inc.,
once pushed to the brink of insolvency by the 1994 Northridge
Earthquake, is expected to report a 60 percent increase in
quarterly earnings today led by strong gains in its automobile
business.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's ninth-largest publicly traded insurer is also
expected to post an 11.6 percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a consensus estimate of four analysts surveyed by First
Call Corp., Twentieth Century is expected to report net income of
37 cents per share for the fourth quarter ended Dec. 31, compared
with 23 cents a share in the year-earlier period. For all of 1998,
analysts expect the insurer to earn $1.53 per share, compared to
$1.37 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Hill, a spokesman for the company, declined to comment on
the estimates or to discuss the company's business over the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   While still generating lower revenues than before the 1994
Northridge Earthquake, when it was one of the state's largest home
insurers, Twentieth Century has boosted its margins since shifting
attention more squarely to auto insurance. In the first nine months
of 1998 it earned $106.22 million on sales of $652 million,
compared with $110.9 million net income for all of 1997. Today's
expected earnings would give the company income of $138.63 million
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The annual earnings report will be the first for Twentieth
Century under its new ownership by American International Group
Inc. AIG stepped in with much needed cash in 1994 after homeowner
claims stemming from the earthquake depleted Twentieth Century's
reserves. Building on the equity stake it was given in exchange for
the money, AIG accumulated enough extra stock to take a majority
position last fall, a move generally supported by investors.
</P>
<P>
   Twentieth Century is expected to report its results after the
close of trading today. The company's stock closed at $21.3125
Wednesday, up 31.25 cents. Twentieth Century shares started the
year at $23.1875.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced Wednesday that it had started selling
policies in Nevada, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
