<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9999 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAGRAM-FILM-LADN     02-10 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM TO RETAIN INTERNATIONAL ARM OF POLYGRAM FILMED
ENTERTAINMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. -- Universal Studios announced Wednesday
it will launch its own foreign movie distribution arm by using the
international operations of PolyGram Filmed Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The move means Seagram Co., Universal's parent, has decided to
keep at least part of PFE rather than selling it. Seagram sold off
the PFE film library in two deals totaling $400 million, but has
not yet decided if it will sell PFE's domestic operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two months of extensive evaluation in determining the
most amount of value PFE brings to Universal, we have concluded
that retaining PolyGram's international operations provides the
strongest strategic advantage,'' Ron Meyer, president of Universal
Studios, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The move underscores the increasing importance of foreign
markets in the movie business. Foreign receipts amounted to $10.87
billion last year, or 60.8 percent of the worldwide box office.
Baskerville Communications has forecast that figure will hit $15.37
billion, or 65.6 percent, by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   PFE, which will retain its identity, distributes films directly
in nine countries and uses its London office for sales in the rest
of the world. Its top upcoming movies include ``Notting Hill'' with
Julia Roberts, ``The Green Mile'' with Tom Hanks and ``Being John
Malkovich'' with Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   PFE's international president, Stewart Till, will continue to
head the operation, which owns or has output deals with Working
Title, Dirty Hands, DNA Pictures and Revolution Films.
Additionally, Universal will continue to use UIP -- its joint
venture with Paramount and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer -- to distribute its
own films overseas. The UIP agreement expires in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram, which acquired PFE last year as part of its $10.4
billion buyout of music giant PolyGram NV, is also expected to
report quarterly earnings today with analysts forecasting profits
of 2 cents per share for its second quarter ended Dec. 31, compared
with 22 cents per share in the year-earlier period. The downturn is
due to feeble box office performance by ``Meet Joe Black'' and
``Babe: Pig in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagram also announced in December that it would take a charge
of as much as $700 million for the cost of integrating PolyGram's
operations. Since then, 700 jobs have been cut at the combined
music operations and another 1,500 slots could disappear by the
time the restructuring is completed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
