<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTEY BRINGS DRAMA TO FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Ike Quartey is the first Oscar De La Hoya opponent
who isn't too old, too light, too short, too weak, too ravaged and
too limited in boxing skills.
</P>
<P>
   If fact, if you listen to what Quartey plans to do Saturday
evening to De La Hoya at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center, you fear for the
safety of the popular World Boxing Council welterweight champion
from East Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to break De La Hoya in half like he's a chicken,''
promises Quartey, the 29-year-old fighter from Accra, Ghana who
recently was stripped of his World Boxing Association welterweight
title. ``I'm definitely going to knock him out. The only way I
won't knock him out is if he runs the whole fight, which he might
try to do. But he won't be able to hide from me. I'm going to catch
up to him, and when I do I'm going to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical pre-fight hyperbole from a 4 to 1 underdog trying to
establish his legitimacy?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But Ike Quartey is unlike any person De La Hoya ever has met in
the ring. He is unlike over-the-hill setups like Julio Cesar Chavez
and Hector (Macho) Camacho. Unlike undersized foils like Genaro
Hernandez, Rafael Ruelas, James Leija and Jorge Paez. Unlike unfit
clowns like Patrick Charpentier, Darryl Tyson, Narciso Valenzuela
and so many others.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Quartey is the youngest offspring of a most
active father, who produced 28 children with four wives in a
stunning exhibition of virility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 18 sisters and nine brothers,'' Quartey said during a
recent interview here at the Top Rank Gym. ``But when I was growing
up, there were only four of us living with our parents. A lot of my
brothers and sisters now live in England.''
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, Quartey hits just as hard as De La Hoya, is
as quick as De La Hoya, is as strong as De La Hoya, and has just as
an impressive record as De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Quartey does have a draw to mar his ledger it came in his
last start against Jose Luis Lopez on Oct. 17, 1997 but he has 29
knockouts among his 34 wins compared to 24 KOs among the undefeated
De La Hoya's 29 victories.
</P>
<P>
   And Ike Quartey, whose oldest brother, also named Ike Quartey,
won a silver medal in boxing at the 1960 Rome Olympics, will
solemnly tell you that he wasn't exactly in prime condition when he
fought Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a severe case of malaria and never should have got in
the ring that night against Lopez,'' said Quartey, who was knocked
down twice by Lopez late in the fight. ``I was terribly weak, had
absolutely no strength. I shouldn't have gone through with that
fight but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there hasn't been a fighter in the history of the
sweet science who doesn't have some sort of excuse for a
disappointing showing.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey isn't an exception, although his longtime trainer, Dan
Odamtten, insists he was ailing badly against Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at the film of the fight, and you'll see how thin
and sick-looking Ike was,'' he said. ``It's amazing he was able to
fight as well as he did against Lopez. It shows just how tough Ike
is.''
</P>
<P>
   How tough is Ike Quartey?
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely the best fighter Oscar De La Hoya ever has met,''
said De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum, who has an option on Quartey
just in case he pulls an upset and a rematch is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey has knocked out some tough individuals during his
11-year career, including Crisanto Espana, Vincent Phillips and Oba
Carr.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the only way he can emerge victorious against De La
Hoya is to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way I'm going to get a decision if it goes to the
scorecards,'' Quartey said. ``Look, what the judges did to Pernell
Whitaker. I thought Whitaker beat De La Hoya, and the three Las
Vegas judges all had De La Hoya an easy winner. They cheated
Whitaker, and I'm sure they'll cheat me if they get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonsense,'' Bob Arum said. ``The WBC is bringing in three
respected officials from out of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two of the judges, Larry O'Connell and John Keene, are
from England, while another, Ken Mouta, is from Japan. The referee
will be Mitch Helpern.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overwhelming feeling here is that Ike Quartey will
have to dispense a dominant performance to earn a decision against
De La Hoya, a proven box office magnet and now perhaps the most
glamorous figure in his mean profession.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are heavily against Quartey in this one, but they have
been against him ever since he was a kid growing up in the tough,
poverty-stricken Accra suburb of Bukom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place where Ike lived as a youngster is the poorest in all
of Ghana,'' Odamtten said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a day that went by when I was a kid that I didn't
get into a fight, and I usually won,'' Quartey said. ``And when I
didn't win, my dad would kick me out of the house and tell me not
to come back until I beat up the other guy. When I was 8 years old,
I even got into a fight with a guy who was 15. It was about that
time when my oldest brother started taking me to the gym, and I got
into boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ike Quartey is now a national hero in Ghana, and he can't walk
anywhere in that country without being mobbed.
</P>
<P>
   He is married with a son and daughter, and these days splits his
time between Ghana and America.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey said he has respect for Oscar De La Hoya, but he thinks
De La Hoya has been sheltered throughout his career and will suffer
culture shock from finally facing someone of equal skills and size.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Oscar fights me, I'll knock him out,'' Quartey said. ``If
he runs, he might survive.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, there is, at last, legitimate drama surrounding
an Oscar De La Hoya fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2228EST &QL; 
