<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY PLAYS FIRST EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA -- Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano will get a look
at newcomers Kevin Eastman and Tony Soto tonight in the first
exhibition of the season at 7:30 p.m. tonight against the Pacific
Coast semi-pro All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The game will be played in the stadium at Santa Barbara High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Soto, the 10th overall pick in Sunday's college draft from
Southern Methodist University, was named the Western Athletic
Conference player of the year this past fall.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman, the top pick in the supplemental draft, comes to L.A.
after two seasons with the A-League Nashville Metros. In 1997,
Eastman was named rookie of the year and this past season he was
named to the A-League all-star team.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano says Eastman will start on the backline with Ezra
Hendrickson, Greg Vanney and Paul Caligiuri. Soto will join Danny
Pena at the top of the central defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get a feeling right away for where these guys are
at,'' Zambrano said. ``You really don't know how they will do until
you put them out there with the rest of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Clint Mathis and Daniel Hernandez will start in the midfield for
Los Angeles while regular playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos remains in
El Salvador until his contract dispute with Major League Soccer is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Welton likely will start up front with Jose Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones arrived Sunday from Florida but will not start after
helping the U.S. National team defeat Germany, 3-0, in an
exhibition. Galaxy defender Robin Fraser played a big role with the
U.S. team as well, but he won't join the Galaxy until Monday. He is
getting married this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has been training at Oxnard College's World Cup
training facility since Feb. 1. Today's match is the first of seven
exhibitions before its season opener, March 21, against Colorado at
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of young players we need to evaluate,'' Zambrano
said. ``We pretty much have an idea at this point of who's going to
start and which roles certain guys will play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
