<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0024 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIRANDA-RIGHTS-1STLD-     02-10 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-RIGHTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING BY APPEALS COURT THROWS FUTURE OF MIRANDA IN DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ariz., Md., S.C., N.C. W.Va.)  (Eds: SUBS 21st graf to ADD explanation of Miranda ruling; Pickup
22nd graf, Supreme Court ...) 
 (nk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sat there unused by prosecutors for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, a law passed by Congress in 1968 was dusted off
by a federal appeals court in Virginia and used to declare that
federal law enforcement officials need not follow one of the best
known Supreme Court decisions of this century, Miranda vs. Arizona,
under which criminal suspects are routinely read their rights
everywhere in America.
</P>
<P>
   From coast to coast Wednesday, prosecutors, defense lawyers and
legal experts said the ruling provided the most serious challenge
to the Miranda ruling since it was issued in 1966, and opened an
unexpected debate about one of this country's bedrock legal rules.
Over the last three decades, ``Miranda'' has become part of the
language and its ``you have the right'' warning is one the most
familiar incantations of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   The court in Richmond, Va., held on Monday that Congress
overruled the 1966 Miranda decision in the 1968 law that sought to
make it easier for federal prosecutors to use confessions that are
given willingly. The Justice Department has never enforced that law
and now argues that it was unconstitutional. But the court in
Richmond, which has a reputation as one of the most conservative in
the country, dismissed that position as political.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we are a court of law and not politics,'' said
the opinion by a three judge panel in which one judge dissented.
The ruling came about not because of an argument made by the
government, but by private conservative organizations that filed
friend-of-the-court briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the decision would almost certainly be
reviewed by the full 13-member 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in Richmond, and could lead to a reconsideration by the Supreme
Court of its famous 1966 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets the stage for a significant Supreme Court decision
revisiting the status of Miranda,'' said A.E. Dick Howard, a
professor of constitutional law at the University of Virginia.
``The case presents squarely what, 33 years later, we think of
Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1968 law, part of a crime control bill, said that a
confession ``shall be admissible in evidence if it is voluntarily
given.'' Many legal scholars say that Congress meant to have
federal courts decide simply whether a confession was voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda's requirement that suspects be told their rights has
been interpreted to apply both to federal and state law enforcement
officials. But the 1968 law only applied to federal prosecutors. As
a result, the decision on Monday, if it stands, would apply only to
federal cases in the five states governed by the Richmond court:
Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, North Carolina and South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   State law enforcement officials in those states and elsewhere
are unaffected by the ruling, and Miranda warnings are to remain
standard practice unless the Supreme Court retreats from its 1966
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the states governed by the Richmond court, it was
unclear Wednesday whether federal prosecutors would follow the
panel's ruling. A few federal prosecutors in those states tried in
recent years to advance the argument made by the court in its
Monday ruling. But those prosecutors were directed by Justice
Department officials in Washington to follow the Miranda decision
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials declined to comment on the case and it was
unclear whether they would direct federal prosecutors to disregard
the panel's decision while it is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The popular mythology is that many guilty people go free because
of the technical requirements of the Miranda decision. Academics
have disagreed for years, though, about whether statistics prove or
disprove that belief. Because the Miranda ruling was one of the
landmarks of liberal judicial attitudes that shaped much of the
country's law in recent decades, the reactions to Monday's decision
were shaped by political perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives generally applauded it as an overdue limitation on
what some of them saw as excesses in favor of defendants. Some
conservatives have long argued that the Supreme Court merely meant
to state guidelines in its Miranda decision, not to lay down a
constitutional rule that would have a substantial impact on the
system.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is important because Congress would likely not
have had the power to overrule the Miranda ruling in 1968 if it had
been viewed as having established new constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda was not a constitutional requirement,'' said Douglas
W. Kmiec, a conservative constitutional expert at Pepperdine
University Law School. ``It was instead a constitutional
suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberals and defense lawyers Wednesday said the Miranda ruling
did establish new constitutional rights that could not be revoked
by the Congress in 1968. The decision by the Richmond court, some
of them said, would roll back what they view as important progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision as a society that the ends don't justify
the means,'' said Larry S. Pozner, president of the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``This says, `Forget about
protecting the individual.' I think its very frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, an expert on criminal law at Georgetown University
Law Center said: ``The decision takes away from suspects in federal
cases the right to know their rights and it resurrects the inherent
coersion of the interrogation setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberals have long said that police powers were so intimidating
that it was often difficult to tell before the Miranda ruling
whether a confession was truly voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   The 1966 Miranda ruling said people in police custody should be
told they had the right to legal representation and that any
statements they made could be used against them. The Supreme Court
has repeatedly undercut the strength of its own Miranda ruling over
the years by saying in later decisions that Miranda warnings were
merely ``prophylactic'' and ``not themselves rights protected by
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas have
suggested they might be sympathetic to the argument that the 1968
law overruled Miranda's application in federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department has been unwilling to make the
argument challenging the Miranda decision. In part, legal experts
say, that has been because law enforcement officials have been
divided about whether it would be useful to do away with the
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   There are cases in which guilty people go free because their
confessions cannot be used. But some law enforcement officials have
also said the clear requirement to give a warning has been
incorporated into police work. Some prosecutors say the Miranda
rule benefits them because confessions are routinely admitted if it
is established that a suspect was read the statement of rights.
</P>
<P>
   But for some conservatives the Miranda ruling remains
philosophically troubling. For them, it was also troubling that
prosecutors declined to use the 1968 law even though its
application could have helped win convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The case decided on Monday involved a Maryland man, Charles T.
Dickerson, who confessed to a series of bank robberies. A district
court judge ruled that he confessed voluntarily but that he was not
read his rights until after he confessed. The district court ruled
the confession could not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Under directives from the Justice Department, local federal
prosecutors did not make the argument that Miranda had been
invalidated by the 1968 law. But two groups, the Washington Legal
Foundation and the Safe Streets Coalition, filed
friend-of-the-court briefs making those claims.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, R. Shawn Gunnarson, senior counsel at
the Washington Legal Foundation, acknowledged that his
organization, which he described as a conservative law and policy
group, had selected the 4th Circuit to test the legal issue partly
because of its reputation as a conservative court. ``The 4th
Circuit,'' he said, ``is a very careful Circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts said Wednesday that the panel's ruling was
weakened because the court did not fully consider both sides of the
argument. The panel's decision said the Justice Department at first
took no position and then argued that the 1968 law was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision, written by Judge Karen J. Williams, said
the Justice Department had been ``elevating politics over law'' by
prohibiting the local federal prosecutor from arguing that the 1968
law would have permitted Dickerson's confession to be admissible.
Williams was appointed by President George Bush. A federal district
judge sitting by designation, Jackson L. Kiser, appointed by
President Ronald Reagan, joined in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   A judge appointed by President Clinton, M. Blane Michael,
dissented from the part of the decision dealing with the Miranda
case. He said he saw no evidence that seven consecutive
administrations since the enactment of the 1968 law were acting
because of politics.
</P>
<P>
   The dissent noted that Williams' ruling concluded that the
Miranda decision did not amount to a rule of constitutional rights.
``I don't know whether it is or not,'' Michael said, ``but before I
decide, I would want thoughtful lawyers on both sides to answer one
question for me. If Miranda is not a constitutional rule, why does
the Supreme Court continue to apply it in prosecutions arising in
state courts?''
</P>
<P>
   H. Richard Uviller, a professor of criminal law at Columbia Law
School, was one of several experts who said Wednesday that the
decision on Monday could force the courts to decide whether the
Miranda ruling created constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the familiar warnings were to fade from American
life, Uviller said, the effect of the Miranda ruling's broad
message protecting the rights of citizens would not quickly
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda,'' Uviller said, ``is part of a group if cases that
have shaped our historic view of ourselves. And I don't think any
decision will just wipe that away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
