<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA HOME SALES REACH RECORD LEVELS IN 1998
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California's home sales and prices hit record
levels last year with price gains in the suburban Los Angeles
community of Tarzana among the top 10 statewide, a trade group
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow closed last year on 628,260 existing, single-family
detached homes in California, a gain of 13.1 percent from 1997,
said the Los Angeles-based California Association of Realtors. That
topped the previous high of 604,950 homes sold in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the median price -- the point at which half the homes
sold for more and half for less -- gained 8 percent to $201,410.
That bested the previous high of $200,660 for all of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Prices increased in 287 of 353 California cities and
communities, or 81.3 percent, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tarzana, a small community in the San Fernando Valley
approximately 25 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles, the
median price soared 25.9 percent to $328,000, the ninth biggest
gain in the state. For the entire San Fernando Valley, prices
gained 15.3 percent to $177,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sales figures for individual communities were not available,
said Realtors spokesman Mark Giberson.
</P>
<P>
   Last year repeat buyers returned to the market, which fueled the
local price appreciation, said Jim Link, executive vice president
of the Southland Regional Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more expensive homes are selling and they weren't before.
The upper-end market was very strong in 1998. It was actually the
opposite in 1995 and 1996 and into 1997,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Market drivers were low interest rates, robust job growth and
strong consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the market now at its peak, some cooling is in the
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Appleton-Young, the state Realtor group's vice president
and head economist, said statewide sales should probably decline
about 8 percent this year while prices keep trending up. But
Southern California will probably see some sales gains, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with an 8 percent drop statewide that would be the fourth
strongest year in years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at two Los Angeles-area markets:
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Los Angeles County gained 9 percent to $192,580 and
sales increased 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Ventura County gained 6.6 percent to $233,770 and
sales increased 18.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
