<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRATERNITY-DEATH-HNS &LR;      02-10 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRATERNITY-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRATERNITY MURDER SUSPECT CALLED SMART BUT EXPLOSIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
and JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHART, Texas _ The man who committed suicide as he was being
sought as the prime suspect in the beating death of a San Marcos
college student was described Wednesday as highly intelligent, but
with an explosive temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a real bad temper that was seen even when he was a
kid,'' said a family friend who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``But I think he was smart enough to know how to control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah Marshall Wilkerson, 21, shot himself once in the head
Tuesday under a tree in his father's yard in Northeast Texas. His
father told Van Zandt sheriff's deputies that his son frequently
went to that spot to think or cool off when he was upset.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson was being sought in the death of Nicholas George
Armstrong, a 21-year-old Southwest Texas State University junior
who was beaten early Sunday morning as he slept at a fraternity
house.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, a fight erupted as four men were ejected
after crashing a party at the Tau Kappa Epsilon house. Witnesses
told police that Armstrong, a communications major from Baytown,
near Houston, was not involved in the fight, which was broken up by
police.
</P>
<P>
   A witness told police he later saw two of the intruders back at
the house shortly before Armstrong was found beaten at 3:15 a.m. He
died Monday at an Austin hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Wednesday that charges against the second man who
returned to the house are unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they were told that one fraternity member saw
Wilkerson leave the house shortly after the murder. When the member
asked whether Wilkerson and his friend had returned to the
fraternity house to steal something, Wilkerson allegedly responded,
``We're not here to steal, we're here to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the type of comment that fits into the general frame
of mind of this individual,'' said San Marcos Police Chief Steve
Griffith. ``There was a great degree of anger involved here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson, an Eagle Scout who grew up in Lockhart with his
mother, was remembered Wednesday as an intelligent young man who
often found trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in and out of trouble all the time, but basically he
was a good kid,'' said Dana Garrett, owner of the Lockhart
Post-Register.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, Wilkerson sold newspapers on street corners. After a
couple of years, he stuffed inserts into the Post-Register.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him since he was about 12 or so,'' Garrett said.
``He was so smart; maybe too smart some would say.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson graduated from Lockhart High School in May 1996 and
attended SWTSU for one year. He worked as a plumber in Lockhart
after dropping out of college.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilkerson had no felony convictions, he did have three
convictions, or deferred adjudications, for misdemeanors, including
one count of possession of marijuana and two counts of criminal
mischief.
</P>
<P>
   While a warrant charging him with murder was being prepared in
San Marcos, Wilkerson left the area Tuesday and drove 220 miles to
his father's rural residence north of Wills Point in Van Zandt
County.
</P>
<P>
   When his father, Gary Wilkerson, returned home from work about
4:30 p.m., his son's van was in the driveway but no one was in the
house. After a brief search, he found his son's body beside a large
oak tree about 100 yards behind the house.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Deputy Grady Tucker of the Van Zandt Sheriff's Department,
said the younger Wilkerson apparently had shot himself once in the
head with a 9 mm Colt pistol he had taken from his father's house.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the San Marcos police had requested that the vehicle
Jeremiah Wilkerson was driving be impounded as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson's body was sent to the Dallas County Medical
Examiner's Office. While it appeared that he died of a single,
self-inflicted gunshot wound, Tucker said, the cause of death will
be determined by an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Wednesday afternoon with the young man who
apparently returned to the fraternity house with Wilkerson, San
Marcos police said the still unnamed individual was probably not
involved in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the man, who unlike Wilkerson had never been
enrolled at the college, stayed outside while Wilkerson went inside
and struck Armstrong on the head three times with a metal rod about
one-half inch in diameter. ``Any one of the blows was fatal,''
Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe there was any intention on the part of the
second young man to cause bodily injury,'' Griffith said. ``The
statements and evidence we have certainly do not point in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Though authorities believe the murder weapon might have been a
tire iron, nothing has been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Most fraternity members declined to discuss what transpired
Saturday night and early Sunday morning. But one member, Chris
Jones, said he recalls thinking that Wilkerson seemed out of place
among the somewhat preppie crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing him, and I was like, `Man, I wonder who he
knows?''' said Jones, a senior who said he left the party a couple
of hours before the beating occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The party at the rambling two-story Tau Kappa Epsilon house was
held to celebrate the new pledge class, which included Armstrong.
Like most fraternity parties, it involved music, dancing and beer.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Armstrong had been drinking, and students with ties
to the fraternity said he passed out on a couch as the party broke
up.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, Jones said he recalls ``a little
scuffle'' involving Wilkerson and that the party crasher and his
three friends were escorted out the door by several fraternity
members. ``All I know is that some guys were causing trouble and we
sent them out,'' he said. ``I was dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though university officials do not classify Armstrong's death as
a fraternity incident, they nonetheless seized the opportunity to
temporarily suspend all the campus fraternities. Their action was
also in response to an alcohol-poisoning incident involving another
student who was attending a fraternity party last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   James Studer, dean of student affairs, said the school's
fraternities have a checkered history of low academic performance,
poor treatment of women and general social irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly shaken by the Armstrong incident, many fraternity
members agreed that some sort of time out was in the students' best
interest. Most expressed deep remorse over the incident and
struggled to understand how two lives were lost in such a short
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's killed the whole school,'' said Colin Copeland, a Tau
Kappa Epsilon member and a senior. ``I think right now we just all
have to sit back for a while and reassess.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's funeral will be at 3 p.m. Thursday at Grace United
Methodist Church in Baytown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
