<SLUG> BC-TAPES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPING ALLEGATIONS WON'T SLOW SENATE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans won't let the impeachment trial
be derailed by allegations that a U.S. intelligence agency may have
taped presidential telephone conversations in the Monica Lewinsky
affair, Sen. Jon Kyl said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to slow it down, stop it or affect it in any
way,'' Kyl, R-Ariz., said in an interview. ``If we had wanted to do
that, we would have sought to bring everything to a screeching halt
until we verified the information one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   `` The Arizona Republic'' and the ``Wall Street Journal''
reported Wednesday that information had been passed to independent
counsel Kenneth Starr that White House telephone conversations may
have been monitored by a U.S. intelligence agency. The
unsubstantiated allegations of the existence of such tapes ended up
in the hands of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who
forwarded the information to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Journal'' reported that Lott asked Starr to investigate
allegations of ``some type of communications-monitoring system
within the Defense Department or intelligence community (that)
might have picked up Mr. Clinton's telephone conversations in the
Monica Lewinsky matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said Senate Republicans, to preserve the integrity of the
trial, would resist stopping the proceedings while more is learned
about the possible new tapes. Among the many unanswered questions
are why an agency would record Clinton's conversations and, if any
tapes exist, whether they would shed more light on the two articles
of impeachment against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said that the Senate Republican leadership faced risks no
matter what it decided to do about the sketchy information, first
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If tapes exist, ``and if there is something on them, then we're
going to catch hell for not having stopped the impeachment process
until the whole thing could be checked out,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly added, ``We have done everything to keep the
impeachment process moving to a conclusion on Friday, with no
reference to this whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart was asked by a reporter
Wednesday whether there were recordings ``done not here at the
White House with any kind of built-in system'' but monitored in
some manner from outside the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990210.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOAT-LADN     02-10 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CHOPPY START, JIM AND SHELI ARE DOING SWELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. _ For nearly two years, one Kern County sailor's
love for a Ventura County woman left him sleepless in Bakersfield.
Not since Jack balanced Rose at the bow of a certain ill-fated
ocean liner has there been so much rapture on the open ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Santa Barbara Channel was the perfect place for a budding
romance,'' recalled Jim Harder. ``I would drive down to (Oxnard's)
Channel Islands Harbor from Bakersfield every Saturday on the
pretext of giving sailing lessons. But I was really there to see
(ITAL) her (END ITAL).
</P>
<P>
   ``After the lesson was over, we'd check out a sailboat and sail
till sunset.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``her'' was Sheli Fisher, and their saltwater soirees were
destined to blossom into an I-5 love affair to make the Grapevine
seem like an ant hill.
</P>
<P>
   There is something about the tides, the breakers and the salt
air that instills passion _ perhaps one of love's great mysteries _
and there is no better time to share such stories than around
Valentine's Day. And for all its stormy weather, true love will
eventually find safe harbor; it's the story of Jim and Sheli.
</P>
<P>
   After being introduced by a mutual friend, she said, ``I think
we clicked right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But their relationship didn't exactly commence in smooth
fashion; love was almost on the rocks, quite literally, before it
got started.
</P>
<P>
   The waves started rolling on their first sailing date in June
1997. Frenchy's Cove at Anacapa Island was the setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I wanted to impress this woman,'' Harder said. ``The
place you go is over to the (Channel) Islands. The circumstances
are idyllic. It's how California was before all the people came _ a
pristine, primordial place, nobody as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we get there, drop the anchor, open a bottle a wine and
relax in the late afternoon sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorable outing ... and how. When it was time to depart,
Harder showed Fisher how to get the engine started while he pulled
up the anchor. Just when Harder thinks he's pulled off the perfect
date, the wind comes up and the swells build.
</P>
<P>
   Before he knew it, Harder was crouched on the deckhouse,
clinging to the mast, with one hand on a winch handle and the other
on a halyard. He was struggling to get the mainsail up when a huge
wave hit the port bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost go over the rail,'' he said. ``There I am, hanging by
a knee and an elbow a few inches from the water, trying to look
nonchalant, like nothing's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder's trial by wind, sea and humiliation was far from over.
During the 11-mile sail back to Channel Islands Harbor, they faced
40-knot winds and 8-foot swells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were being bounced all over the place and couldn't hold a
course,'' Harder said. ``It got so bad that we just let the rudder
decide its own course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, 3 miles from shore, the wind eased and I was able to
regain the helm,'' he said. ``That was our first sailing experience
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Fisher went back to her job tending bar in Camarillo.
It was her boss, Doug Brown, who had served as matchmaker; Brown
had raced sailboats with Harder out of Oxnard's Offshore Islands
Sailing club and thought the two would hit it off because they were
both ``very easy-going.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harder was sure Fisher would never agree to go sailing with
him again. Yet when he asked her the next time, she didn't bat an
eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``(ITAL) That (END ITAL),'' Harder said, ``is when I knew it was
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Today they live in a stucco-and-redwood-trim home with a
shake-shingle roof in a suburb of Bakersfield, where Jim Harder
works for the Federal Bureau of Land Management. The two-year
courtship culminated in a large wedding at water's edge in Channel
Islands Harbor, whereupon Sheli took Jim's last name.
</P>
<P>
   When they do any serious coastal cruising these days, they head
to Willow's anchorage on the south side of Santa Cruz Island. It's
one of their favorite spots because of the secluded, unspoiled
beach and haystack rocks that rise like sentinels.
</P>
<P>
   The pitter-patter of small feet can be heard mornings at the
Harder household _ Sheba, his cat; and Samson, hers. The felines
haven't had much of a choice about the relationship. There's
definitely no love lost between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very independent,'' said Jim. ``They hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the sacrifices true love exacts.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
