<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOAT-SIDE-LADN     02-10 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP HOLDS SINGLES MIXERS ON THE SEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. _ The open ocean can be a lonely place for a
boater in search of companionship.
</P>
<P>
   A sailor has a better chance at finding romance cruising the
produce aisle of a neighborhood Ralphs than cruising the coastal
waters.
</P>
<P>
   That's where groups like the Single Mariners of Marina del Rey
come in.
</P>
<P>
   The Single Mariners, which holds half-day sails twice a month,
has been around for 14 years and provide a chance for unattached
men and women with an interest in sailing to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Most are first-time sailors, newly single, outdoors-oriented and
looking for a hobby, said club organizer Alan Gornick.
</P>
<P>
   After a collegial presail breakfast at a nearby hotel,
participants choose the vessels they want to sail on. These are
large sailboats captained by _ who else? _ single skippers.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of sailing season, 50 or 60 single mariners in a
dozen or so sailboats leave the protected waters of Marina del Rey,
Gornick said. During the winter, the number tapers off to about 30
people and a half-dozen boats.
</P>
<P>
   After the vessels are back in their moorings, members hold a
wine-and-cheese social.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people drop out because they've met someone; others
have stayed with it over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a core group of perhaps 35 to 40 people who are
consistently around,'' said Gornick.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, the Single Mariners organizes seven
multiple-day cruises. Some go to Santa Catalina Island, where
dinghies are taken ashore for a beachside barbecue after the fleet
ties off.
</P>
<P>
   The success stories are numerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couples have met through the club and literally sailed off
into the sunset together,'' Gornick said.
</P>
<P>
   There's Phil and Gunnel Seitz, who met through the club, dated
for three or four years, got married and now spend their time
sailing off Mexico together in their 40-foot craft. They reside
either in a slip in Marina del Rey or at anchor in some secluded
cove in Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   There's Steve and Lucie Lee, who, says Gornick, met in the club,
got married three years ago and are now live-aboards on a sloop
they recently bought.
</P>
<P>
   And love's labors were definitely not lost on Gail Wright and
Gary Strachn. Though the two have known each other since college
days, it took a single's sailing excursion to cement their bond.
Now they live in Long Beach and can be found aboard their 36-foot
boat on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Like many sailing couples, Wright and Strachn have weathered
nature's forces and are stronger for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably shouldn't have left the island that morning,''
Wright said of a recent San Pedro Channel crossing. ``By the time
they were at the halfway point, the seas had become confused with
very high waves and dangerous gusts. There were waves as high as
our mast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me aware of the strengths and weaknesses we both
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marina del Rey Single Mariners meet at 7 p.m. the first
Wednesday and third Thursday of each month at Pacific Mariners
Yacht Club, 13915 Panay Way, Marina del Rey. The cost is $7, which
includes a light buffet dinner. Day sails are scheduled on the
first Saturday and third Sunday of each month. For further details,
call (310) 289-3338.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
