<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0041 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING-TRIAL-1STLD-W     02-10 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$51 MILLION VERDICT AWARDED TO SMOKER IS BIGGEST OF ITS KIND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS to UPDATE with punitive damages of $50 million being
awarded late Wednesday, largest judgment ever in smoking-related
lawsuit; Story has been added to The New York Times front page.)  (jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state jury in San Francisco has awarded $51.5 million in
damages from the Philip Morris Cos. to a woman who says her
inoperable lung cancer was caused by more than 35 years of smoking
cigarettes, primarily Philip Morris's Marlboro brand.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment is by far the largest ever reached in a
smoking-related lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts _ $1.5 million in compensatory damages awarded on
Tuesday and $50 million in punitive damages awarded late Wednesday
_ resulted from the first cigarette lawsuit to reach a California
jury in more than a decade, following the 1997 repeal of a state
law that barred product liability suits by individuals against
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   And although the size of the judgment could be sharply reduced
on appeal, it signals that the cigarette companies may well have to
fight a brushfire of similar suits just as the industry was hoping
to put its legal troubles to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Defending themselves against thousands of suits brought by
individual smokers or their survivors _ particularly in California,
where juries lean to high damage awards _ would prove extremely
expensive for the companies. Indeed, analysts who were interviewed
about the verdict, which they described as stunning, said they
believed that its lure to prospective plaintiffs could bring a new
rush of litigation against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give incredible new strength to claims against
tobacco companies,'' said Mary Aronson, president of Aronson
Washington Research, which follows tobacco litigation for
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict awarding the 53-year-old plaintiff, Patricia Henley,
$50 million in punitive damages _ more than three times the $15
million her lawyer had asked for _ was returned after the stock
market had closed Wednesday. But on the basis of just the $1.5
million in compensatory damages awarded late the day before, prices
of cigarette company stocks fell sharply. Philip Morris was off
$3.8125 a share, to close at $41.5625, and the RJR Nabisco Holdings
Corporation was down $1.375, closing at $27.3125.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel wonderful,'' Ms. Henley told The Associated Press after
the verdict Wednesday. ``This is a great day for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Philip Morris said the company was expected to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment was the third in the last three years in favor of
smokers who contended that cigarette makers had failed to warn them
adequately of smoking's hazards. The two other awards, both against
the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., were later overturned, and no
such verdict has ever survived appeal. Until Wednesday, the largest
such judgment was about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the $1.5 million awarded on Tuesday was
compensation for Ms. Henley's medical costs, pain and suffering. In
addition, her lawyer, Madelyn J. Chaber, asked the jurors to award
her $15 million to punish the company for the negligence and fraud
that was found in Tuesday's verdict. The jury responded with that
much, and then $35 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley, of Los Angeles, discovered last year that she had
inoperable lung cancer. Although lawyers for Philip Morris argued
that she had understood the risks of smoking, her suit said she had
smoked since she was a teen-ager, taking up the habit a few years
before government-required warning labels began appearing on
cigarette packages in 1966. The tobacco companies, she said, never
told smokers that addiction might leave them incapable of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Until quite recently, though, Ms. Henley would have been
forbidden to bring her case. Under a 1987 tort reform law, product
liability suits against tobacco companies were prohibited in
California on the ground that the risks of smoking were universally
known. The law was repealed in 1997, around the time California
decided to file a claim against the tobacco industry in an effort
to recover smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, California was one of 46 states that struck a
$206 billion deal with Philip Morris and the other major cigarette
makers settling all remaining lawsuits brought to recoup those
costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
