<SLUG> BC-NJ-MOTHER-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMISSAL SOUGHT BY 41-YEAR-OLD WHO ADMITTED KILLING MOTHER WHEN
SHE WAS 14 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A lawyer for Susan Marie Watson, the 41-year-old
woman who confessed this fall that when she was 14 she had killed
her mother, said in court Wednesday that he would move to have the
case dismissed on the ground that it would be impossible to pursue
juvenile murder charges against a woman nearing middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watson, a data entry clerk and mother of three from
Schenectady, N.Y., was charged with murder under juvenile statutes
in October after she broke down in front of police investigators
here and admitted to fatally shooting her mother, Maylon Johnson,
in their home in Newark on Oct. 3, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   According to her confession, the police said, Ms. Watson shot
her mother in the chest because she scoffed when Ms. Watson told
her that she had been sexually abused by a man her mother was
dating.
</P>
<P>
   Though county prosecutors and legal experts alike have been
baffled by the task of prosecuting an adult under juvenile laws,
Ms. Watson's lawyer, Walter E. Florczak, said that such a
prosecution is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has jurisdiction in this case,'' Florczak said. ``The
law simply doesn't provide for a 41-year-old juvenile.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief hearing in Essex County Family Court, Florczak said
he would file a motion by March 4 to dismiss the case. After the
hearing, he added that he would contest the charges because the
juvenile criminal statutes in 1971 were largely meant to
rehabilitate youth offenders. Ms. Watson, who remains free on bail
and who, by all accounts, has lived a peaceful life in Schenectady
for nearly three decades, was already rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had the same job for eight years,'' Florczak said. ``And
she's never been arrested except in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County prosecutor's office,
said the county would challenge the dismissal but refused to say on
what grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts have also pointed to potential problems with
sentencing under 1971 juvenile laws. If Ms. Watson had been tried
as a juvenile and convicted at the time, sentencing guidelines
would likely have allowed her to be freed from custody at age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watson's admission has also drawn attention because the
investigation into the death of her mother was reopened at the
urging of Ms. Watson's own brothers, George and David Johnson, who
did not know where the new trail would lead.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the brothers, who were asleep in the
family home when the murder occurred, learned in October of a
special squad in the Newark Police Department dedicated to
investigating unsolved crimes and asked squad members to revisit
the case.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing Wednesday, George Johnson, now 35, said that
his family loyalties were split in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my sister,'' Johnson said. ``But I love my mother. I'm
torn between two loves now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
