A0189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-NYT     02-10 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S LAVIN GUIDES `BABY BRUINS' 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the youngest team in UCLA's storied history,
a collection of five freshmen, seven sophomores, a junior and a
senior. The coach, Steve Lavin, is a pup himself at age 34.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins have won 15 of their last 18 games, have put up a
17-5 record and have become the nation's ninth-ranked team. Lavin
has played 15 different starting units, and watched what often
resembles a kindergarten class off the court turn into hoops
prodigies on it.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Lavin will take his squad to Maples Pavilion,
decide at the last minute on a starting lineup and play No. 6
Stanford (19-4) and its lineup of seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are tough, they are unselfish,'' Lavin said of his baby
Bruins. ``They have high expectations of themselves individually,
and as a team. Sometimes we don't play with much intelligence _ we
reach, lunge, foul 3-point shooters. But everything this team has
done this season is within the realm of coaching basketball. It's
been a challenge, but that's why I got into this business.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach has faced no greater challenge than harnessing the
talent of the 6-foot-6-inch freshman JaRon Rush, a McDonald's
all-American who has been heralded as a Michael
Jordan-in-the-making by national basketball magazines since his
freshman year in high school at Pembroke Hill in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Rush was a star on the Amateur Athletic Union summer circuit and
the object of intense recruiting, a situation complicated by his
ties to a wealthy Kansas booster who financed a scholarship at his
private high school, treated him like a member of his own family
and was his benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   It was a foregone conclusion then that Rush would become a
Jayhawk until his mother, Glenda, refused to cosign an early letter
of intent for Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   She, along with Rush's grandmother, Jeanette Jacobs, wanted him
to get far away from the limelight in Kansas City. They got their
wish, but with unwanted national fanfare when Rush was widely
quoted as saying that Kansas coach Roy Williams ``substituted too
much.'' Williams indignantly rescinded the scholarship offer.
</P>
<P>
   Rush started the season strong, but didn't want to return from
Christmas break, saying he felt the pull of home and of his
14-month-old son, Shea. He missed two practices and a game against
Loyola-Marymount. When he finally showed, he was suspended for the
game with Arizona. Three weeks later, he tearfully refused to board
a connecting flight after the first leg was terrifyingly turbulent.
He had to be driven six hours to Louisville to be on time for
UCLA's game with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of pressure and a lot of advice given to me
since I was 15,'' Rush said. ``A lot of people want to tell me
what's best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His coaches and teammates say it's immaturity, not arrogance,
that has tripped up Rush, who has averaged 10 points and 6 rebounds
a game and is one of the Bruins' hardest working defenders. The
players like him, and the coaches respect that he has admitted his
mistakes along the way. ``His growth has been slowed because of the
pampered environment at home,'' said the Bruins' assistant coach,
Michael Holton, who recruited him. ``Now he's learning to take the
bumps head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him that he can let this stuff kill him, or be strong
and fight through it,'' said Earl Watson, a sophomore who has
started all 22 games this season and who is the Bruins'
second-leading scorer, averaging 13.5 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Rush might have grown up last week against
Oregon, when he scored 17 points on 6-of-9 shooting to lead the
Bruins to a 79-77 victory. Then, two days later, he fooled around
during stretching exercises and was tossed from practice. He called
his grandmother, who told him to return to the gym. But Lavin
wouldn't let him back in, and benched him against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the growing pains of UCLA's two foreign-born
players, Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric, have been far less
disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, a 20-year-old freshman by way of the West Indies and
Paris, worries that he shoots too much, that despite being the
Bruins' third-leading scorer and most dependable inside player,
someone is going to realize he doesn't deserve his scholarship and
take it away.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric, a freshman who has just turned 21, is from The Hague
and had no idea who Bill Walton was despite continually reading
that he was UCLA's best center prospect since the big redhead.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have lost and regained starting jobs this season.
But Moiso especially requires gentle handling. Explosive and fluid,
the 6-10 power forward is so timid about demonstrating his
offensive skills that against Kentucky _ on his way to a 25-point
game _ he asked to sit so Gadzuric could get more shots. ``The
coach wants me to shoot the ball; every chance he gets, he tells me
to shoot the ball,'' said Moiso, who is averaging 12 points and 6
rebounds a game. ''But I'm not sure I'm good enough to shoot the
ball that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric, a bruising 6-10, 245-pounder, barely seems to notice
when he is in Lavin's doghouse. He didn't start against Oregon
State, too, because his coach didn't think he practiced hard enough
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   But the center thought it was because Lavin wanted him to rest _
he has been plagued by tendinitis in his right knee. ``It's been
frustrating with my knee,'' Gadzuric said, still not conceding
three days after the game that he didn't start because of a poor
practice effort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lavin doesn't know how far his young team can go, or how
effective his efforts are to keep in line what he calls a
``high-maintenance'' bunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In only his third year as a head coach, he says he is learning,
too. ``Every time you get two guys on the wagon, it seems like two
more fall off,'' he said. ``It's what you expect, but we're trying
to put in place today what's going to keep them all on board in the
future.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
