<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-STATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR OFFERS NEW STATISTICS IN DEFENSE OF POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As other elected officials criticized the killing of
an unarmed immigrant by four police officers, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani defended the Police Department on Wednesday with a fresh
batch of statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani used graphs to show that city police officers fired 856
shots in 1998, down from 1,040 shots in 1997. The number of fatal
shootings by police officers last year _ 19 _ was the lowest since
1985, a ``remarkable'' fact given that arrests have risen
dramatically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were part of the Mayor's Management Report, a
self-evaluation that the City Charter requires to be published
every six months. Its presentation came as public protest persisted
about the fatal shooting of the West African immigrant, Amadou
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani said little Wednesday about the shooting, he
spent an unusual amount of time on police statistics before moving
on to other parts of the report.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that police in Boston, Washington and Chicago
fire their weapons more frequently than officers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the impressions that's given by those who have a hard
time giving the police credit for anything is that safety in the
city is brought about by the Police Department becoming more
violent,'' he said. ``Just the opposite is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the news about the Police Department was good: the
police are taking longer to respond to calls about crimes in
progress, especially in Brooklyn, the report said. The average
citywide response time was 10.5 minutes, up from 10 minutes in
1997. In Brooklyn, the average response time rose to 10.9 minutes,
from 10.1 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area where the Police Department has to do more
work, to find out why, and how that can be reduced,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
