u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-PILOTS-600&AMP;ADD-N     02-10 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-PILOTS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO PILOTS LOCKED IN DISPUTE OVER SENIORITY AT AMERICAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev.)   (See related stories: AMR-PILOTS and VACATION-TRAVEL) 
(jw) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. _ To hear American Airlines pilots tell it, they
called in sick and disrupted the airline's operations in order to
quickly raise the salaries of Reno Air pilots to American's level.
</P>
<P>
   But the pilots at Reno, which was acquired by American in
December, are not entirely grateful. Indeed, the Reno Air pilots
are locked in a sometimes bitter, though less publicized, dispute
with the American pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Many Reno pilots support the American pilots in their labor
dispute, which appeared to have ended at least temporarily
Wednesday, though they are not participating themselves. And they
will welcome the higher salaries that being an American employee
will bring.
</P>
<P>
   But they object to the proposal by American Air pilots to
``staple'' the roughly 300 Reno pilots to the bottom seniority list
of American's more than 9,000 pilots, as if the Reno pilots were
all freshly hired on Dec. 23, 1998, the day American acquired the
airline. Some Reno pilots are putting ``no stapler'' stickers on
their luggage, showing a stapler inside the red circle with a slash
through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not have all our years of service and the quality of
life that represents ripped away from us,'' said Bob Collins, a
Reno Air pilot who is also a spokesman for the local branch of the
Air Line Pilots Association, the airline's current union. ``Many of
us are in the last years of our career here and we shouldn't be
treated as new hires.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno senior pilots make an average of $65,000 to $75,000 a year,
less than half that of American pilots with equivalent experience.
Although American, a unit of the AMR Corp., has proposed raising
the salaries of the Reno pilots to its own pilots' levels in 12
months to 18 months, the American pilots' union wants those
salaries raised now.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Reno pilots, their salaries will not double because
they will have less seniority at American. Captains at Reno will
become second-ranking first officers or even third-ranking flight
engineers, posts that carry lower pay than captains. Collins, a
captain, for instance, expects his salary to climb to $100,000 a
year from $75,000. Lower seniority also means poorer choices of
flights, vacations and home bases, meaning many Reno pilots will
have to move from this city.
</P>
<P>
   Collins also complained that his union had not been able to
participate in discussions between American and the Allied Pilots
Association, the union that now represented the American pilots and
that would represent the Reno pilots. ``Allied Pilots have
basically closed the door on us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Engelke, a first officer at American Airlines, said the
issue of seniority was ``under negotiation.'' He said the union's
proposal was that the Reno pilots' length of service would count
toward their pay and benefits, although not toward their seniority
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   But some American pilots apparently think the Reno pilots are
ingrates, in that Reno might have gone out of existence if American
had not bought it. ``We're going to give you a raise, keep your job
and you're asking for the moon,'' said an anonymous phone call left
on the Reno union's voice mail, one of several obscene and
harassing phone calls the union says it has received.
</P>
<P>
   The disruption in air traffic spurred by the acquisition of Reno
Air is just the latest chapter in the history of the small low-cost
airline, which struggled for most of its seven years. Indeed,
judging by the disruptions this week, Reno has had a bigger impact
on air travel now than ever. Started in 1992 with one leased plane
and 150 employees, Reno has expanded to 25 planes and 2,000
employees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We accepted lower salaries to get the airline off the
ground,'' said Richard Vitzthum, a 47-year-old Reno captain who was
the sixth pilot hired.
</P>
<P>
   He said Reno promised that pilot salaries would be raised once
the airline became profitable. But for the most part, it was
plagued by heavy losses, frequent strategy shifts and service
problems. Last February, some 65 percent of callers to its
reservation system hung up in frustration before they could get
through to an agent.
</P>
<P>
   That same month, Joseph O'Gorman, a retired United Airlines
executive, took over as Reno's president. He cut the work force by
15 percent, eliminated unprofitable routes and replaced all 11
senior executives with five of his own choosing. Profits returned.
But O'Gorman decided Reno needed a big partner.
</P>
<P>
   American bought Reno for $124 million to bolster its presence on
the West Coast. While American has a strong east-to-west routes,
including San Francisco to New York, it has virtually no
north-to-south flights in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The California market is dominated by Southwest Airlines and by
United, a unit of the UAL Corp. United set up a low-priced shuttle
service and uses those short flights to feed its cross-country and
cross-Pacific flights. Without north-south flights, American could
not do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers who fly up and down the coast every week may
occasionally fly transcontinental and they are inclined to use the
same carrier,'' said Donald O'Hare, a 40-year employee of American
Airlines, who took over last week as the new president of Reno from
O'Gorman, who left after the takeover was completed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare, who has embarked on a whirlwind trip to meet Reno
employees in 16 cities, said almost all Reno workers would be
offered jobs at American, though the airline's headquarters in Reno
would close and some people might have to move. The Reno name is
expected to be discontinued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2320EST &QL; 
