u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSBACHER-PROFILE-680     02-10 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSBACHER-PROFILE-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGETTE MOSBACHER: YOU CAN'T BE TOO RICH OR TOO REPUBLICAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now for some really jarring news.
</P>
<P>
   Georgette Mosbacher, the voracious socialite and Republican
fund-raising juggernaut, grouts her own tiles. It also may shock
her Fifth Avenue friends, but Ms. Mosbacher was recently caught by
her butler drilling holes in the library wall to hide some unruly
computer wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just a pretty face,'' Ms. Mosbacher said with a husky
laugh as she sat in her drawing room, which was filled with the
kind of stuff one might expect in a sprawling $10 million co-op
whose windows perfectly frame the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   There are crystal chandeliers, gold-tasseled silk settees,
faux-Roman marble busts and a pair of hyperactive cavalier King
Charles spaniels that send Ms. Mosbacher's voice into another
octave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're my wild child!'' she squealed as Eve, the 1-year-old,
hopped into her lap. (The other dog's name is Adam.)
</P>
<P>
   She may have a domestic staff of four, but Ms. Mosbacher, 52,
takes comfort in knowing that she can change her own spark plugs if
need be. ``I learned a long time ago that I can't depend on anyone
but myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though more than two years have passed since Robert A.
Mosbacher, the Bush administration commerce secretary, phoned to
say he was filing for divorce, Ms. Mosbacher still gets weepy when
the matter is raised _ usually by her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just come from a place that is below hell,'' she said of
their breakup after 15 years of marriage. Tears began to well up.
``There were times I didn't think I would make it.''
</P>
<P>
   But made it she has, and Ms. Mosbacher has thrown herself back
into public life with zeal. She became an executive member of the
Republican Leadership Council, and in November she organized a
$1,000-a-plate gala for New York Gov. George Pataki in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This year Fortune magazine crowned her one of the nation's top
Republican fund-raisers. ``I once raised $15 million in one night
for the Republican National Committee,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has also been busy lately promoting ``It Takes Money,
Honey,'' a chatty personal finance primer for women that has
headings like ``Put a Price Tag on Your Dreams,'' ``Consider a
Makeover'' and ``Establish a Secret Stash.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, written with Diane Harris and published by Reganbooks,
is already in its fourth printing.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Ms. Mosbacher qualified to give out financial advice?
``I've been rich and I've been poor,'' she said, echoing Sophie
Tucker's credo. ``And let me tell you, rich is better.'' More than
that, she knows a thing or two about making money.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago she sold her cosmetics company, La Prairie, for
$60 million. Her one-woman marketing consultancy, Georgette
Mosbacher Enterprises, brings in a nice income. And there's the
half-million dollars in annual alimony she gets from Mosbacher, a
Houston oilman.
</P>
<P>
   Though she married three well-moneyed men, she is quick to point
out that she never stopped working. ``I didn't make the mistake of
confusing their wealth for my own,'' she said. That is because she
has never been able to get the taste of poverty out of her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Mosbacher was 7, her father was killed in a car
accident, leaving her unskilled mother penniless and jobless. The
family, which lived in a down-and-out Indiana steel town, moved in
with Georgette's maternal grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Georgette, the oldest of four children, became a breadwinner as
soon as she could count out change. She was a baby sitter, took in
ironing, worked as a carhop, bookkeeper, dressmaker and switchboard
operator. ``You name it, I did it,'' she said, explaining the
grouting and drilling skills.
</P>
<P>
   It was that by-the-bootstraps childhood that drew her to the
Republicans, she said. While her classmates at Indiana University
were protesting the Vietnam War, she was holding down three jobs
and voting for Barry Goldwater. ``I missed the 60s, emotionally and
intellectually,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; She says she is proud to have never voted Democratic, mostly
because she finds the party's fondness for taxes ``obscene'' and
``fundamentally contrary to democracy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of her heroes? New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who she says
has made it possible for her to walk her dogs along Fifth Avenue
late at night.
</P>
<P>
   The glamour-filled years living in George Bush's Washington
helped solidify Ms. Mosbacher's Republican ardor. ``It was like a
dream come true,'' she said, recalling the state dinners, the trips
around the globe and the notoriety of being a fun-loving,
party-throwing redhead in what was probably the most staid epoch in
recent presidential history.
</P>
<P>
   Her windowsills remain thick with signed photographs of Newt,
Ronald and Rush. Lady Thatcher's portrait sits in the guest
washroom, and another snapshot features Ms. Mosbacher waltzing with
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Ms. Mosbacher idolizes her party. When it
comes to the Republicans' doomed impeachment drive, she offers the
following adjectives: Confused. Idiotic. Impotent.
</P>
<P>
   She may be one of the few party stalwarts publicly to cheer the
end of Clinton's trial. ``It's really been a disaster for us,'' she
said. ``We've been flailing around, bumping into walls, clueless
about what to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she has kind words for Clinton (whose photograph is
also displayed in her Republican gallery). ``My God,'' she said
with a stage whisper, ``what a dummy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
