<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spencer Samuels, 85, Longtime Art Dealer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spencer A. Samuels, a leading art dealer for more than 50 years,
died Jan. 30 at St. Johns Hospital in Santa Monica, Calif. He was
85 and lived in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Samuels was born into the business. The son of Mitchell Samuels,
a co-founder of French &AMP; Co., a major New York art concern, he
attended Yale University and then went to Europe to continue his
studies at the University of Florence and the Courtauld Institute
in London.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career at French &AMP; Co., as an elevator operator,
said his cousin Eugene S. Jones. He ultimately became president of
the company. Over the years Samuels organized acquisitions for
museums like the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Louvre and the
Tate Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   He also arranged sales to collectors like J. Paul Getty and
Norton Simon, specializing in works by Old Masters but also
including contemporary artists like Picasso and Jackson Pollock.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually formed his own company, and even after retiring to
California continued to sell Old Master drawings to an
international clientele.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Maxine; a son, Geoffrey; a daughter,
Susan, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Klynn, 81, Pioneer in Film Animation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Klynn, a pioneer in film and television animation, died
Feb. 3 at a hospital in Tarzana, Calif. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Klynn helped create prize-winning cartoon shorts, including ``
Magoo,'' ``Gerald McBoing-Boing'' and ``Madeline,'' at the United
Productions of America Studios, where he worked from 1944 to 1959.
He became a vice president and production chief at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 he founded Format Productions, where he created such
cartoons as ``The Alvin Show,'' ``The Lone Ranger'' and ``The
Curiosity Shop.'' He was president of the company until 1982. Klynn
also created the opening graphic titles for the television series
``I Spy.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Selma; a brother, Marvin, of Encino,
Calif.; a daughter, Gail Spindler of Los Angeles, and two sons,
Lee, of Los Altos, Calif., and Richard, of Upper Nyack, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
