<SLUG> BC-AZNOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGIVENESS FOR CLINTON A COMPLEX NOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ended when Corpus Christi Catholic Church opens its
confessionals to those who need a midweek penance.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they retreat behind closed doors, reveal their sins
and ask for forgiveness. Many sit and pray for a while in the
church with austere white walls and stained-glass windows before
going on with their lives. They have come to clear their
consciences.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the back of the church, a twentysomething couple sit
in a pew and clutch each other tightly. Tears trickle down her
face, and he kisses them off her cheeks. They sit that way for
several minutes. Finally, they get up and walk together toward the
confession booth. He goes in first; she waits her turn.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness. Punishment. Penance. It is a simple concept.
</P>
<P>
   For a nation wrestling with the sins of their president, such
notions are far more complicated. Behind closed doors Wednesday,
senators spend another day grappling with President Clinton's
iniquities and whether he should be forgiven or punished.
</P>
<P>
   As Judith Walters lights candles to the Virgin Mary, she reveals
her conflicting emotions over the president's transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Christian, I know what is right to do. I believe anyone
who is sorry for their sins should be forgiven,'' she says. ``But
outside the church, I have different feelings. I think about
politics. I think about what the office of the presidency should
stand for. I think about what a leader should be. And I think he
shouldn't get away with what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrugging her shoulders and heading toward the door, Walters,
nonetheless, adds compassionately, ``I think he is just flesh and
blood, too. So we should forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to face his judgment by day's end. Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott wants a vote by midafternoon on whether
Clinton is guilty. But some already have granted their
dispensations.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Vermont Sen. James Jeffords was the first
Republican to offer his. He acknowledged that Clinton had committed
shameful acts. But the senator, grudgingly perhaps, echoed the
refrain of the president's supporters and insisted that Clinton's
offenses ``do not reach the high standard'' of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Harkin, though he has made little effort to conceal his
views on the matter, did the same. The Iowa senator told reporters
Wednesday he would not vote to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Will America follow suit?
</P>
<P>
   At Corpus Christi, Mark Rowan was forgiving. Sitting in one of
the church gardens, as he does after confession, Rowan gazes at a
statue of Jesus with outstretched hands and talks about absolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who hasn't been wrong before? Who hasn't done something they
regret and they are very sorry for?'' Rowan asks, adding that he
believes in the power of confession and forgiveness. ``(The
president) is sorry for what he did. He deserves forgiveness, too.
We all do.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people remain in the church as Teresa Margolis dips a
fingertip into a bowl of holy water. She doubts the Senate will
ever truly forgive Clinton for his lies. Margolis predicts the
president will be acquitted by the Republican-controlled Senate,
but only because they couldn't get enough Democrats to vote with
them. But she said Clinton has another jury to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this is over, I think we're going to need lots of
spiritual healing,'' Margolis says. ``The trial has shown an ugly
side of human nature. In the end, it'll be everyday Americans like
me and you who will decide whether he should be forgiven, and
whether he deserves to be forgiven. Of course, God, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano is taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they care
about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed from
office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the answers.
Amparano can be reached at 444-8394 or at julie.amparano(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
