<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE REPUBLICAN SENATORS TO VOTE FOR ACQUITTAL IN CLINTON
IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican support for removing President Clinton
began crumbling Wednesday when three Republican senators said they
would vote to acquit him on obstruction of justice and perjury
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the Senate's second day of closed-door
deliberations, Sens. John Chafee of Rhode Island, Jim Jeffords of
Vermont and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania became the first
Republican senators to say they would not vote to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords stressed that his votes against conviction in no way
absolve the president of wrongdoing. ``Yes, you are not guilty,''
the senator said. ``But you (Clinton) created a hell of a mess for
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords said six or seven Republican senators would break ranks
and side with the Democrats when final votes are cast on the
articles of impeachment late Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate's 45 Democrats reportedly unified behind him,
Clinton has long been safe from conviction. On Wednesday, it
appeared the president also would escape a Democratic effort to
censure him for his affair with Monica Lewinsky and the subsequent
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, officials said Clinton plans to make a
public statement after the Senate votes, but officials were
uncertain how soon after his acquittal the president would speak,
where he would deliver the statement and how long it would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you can ever pretend that none of this ever
happened,'' said presidential press secretary Joe Lockhart.
Clinton's reaction likely would be ``relief and anxiousness to
continue doing the job that he's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, tried
to counter the GOP defections and divert attention from the
prospect that both articles of impeachment might fail to win a
simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence presented during the five-week trial ``shows the
president has committed perjury and obstructed justice,'' Lott
declared. ``The only question left is: Will the Senate vote to find
him guilty of committing these crimes?''
</P>
<P>
   To convict Clinton, two-thirds of the senators present for the
final vote would have to find him guilty on either of the two
charges _ lying under oath or obstructing justice during his
cover-up of his affair with Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Although a handful of senators missed portions of the trial,
only the second of a president in U.S. history, so far all 100 have
been present for the closed-door deliberations with Chief Justice
William Rehnquist presiding. By day's end, just less than half had
spoken, and most had used the 15 minutes allotted for each senator
to deliver remarks. Lott acknowledged that unless some senators
relinquish time, deliberations will spill over into Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, proponents of censure _ a formal statement
condemning Clinton's affair and cover-up _ abandoned efforts to
overcome procedural barriers and Republican opposition, led by Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, to get an up-or-down vote on their resolution
condemning Clinton's affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said she would
circulate a letter rebuking Clinton and ask senators to sign it.
The letter would be inserted in the Congressional Record and made
public after the final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties said the perjury count will fail by a
wide margin while the obstruction of justice charge might receive
barely 50 votes. Less than a majority vote on both would be a
symbolic blow to the Republican-led House, which voted along party
lines in December to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to get 50 votes undermines the credibility of the
entire impeachment process,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, was less strident. ``It certainly
would say the Senate disagrees with the House vote on
impeachment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said ``most senators think you can't
impeach the president on a party-line vote. You just can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said evidence presented by House
prosecutors fell short of proving the perjury charge but succeeded
in buttressing the obstruction of justice charge. Gorton announced
late Tuesday that he would vote not guilty on the perjury charge
and guilty on the obstruction charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jeffords was the first Republican to announce his
plans to vote for acquittal on both charges. Clinton ``gave
misleading statements ... did obstruct justice, but his actions in
this case do not reach the high standard of impeachment,'' the
Vermont senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter blamed his fellow senators for not giving House
prosecutors more leeway to develop their case more fully and
present a full complement of witnesses during the trial. ``On the
record of this pseudo-trial, it is my view that the Senate failed
to fulfill the constitutional mandate to try this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Specter said he would vote that the charges
were ``not proved,'' a category that he said exists alongside ''not
guilty'' or ``guilty'' under Scottish law. ``That is not to say
that the president is not guilty, but to specifically say that the
charges in my judgment have not been proved,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Chafee said House prosecutors had failed to
convince him that any effort by Clinton to cover up his affair
would justify removing him from office. In addition, he said,
``circumstantial evidence in each of the cases is rebutted by
direct evidence or by confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts and circumstances of this case are low and tawdry,
but these same circumstances do not, in my opinion, cause his
offenses to rise to the level of impeachable acts.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, announced that he, like other
Democrats, would vote to acquit on all charges, he lashed out at
independent counsel Kenneth Starr and drew a quick rebuke from
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin accused Starr of engaging in a conspiracy to trap Clinton
into lying under oath about his sexual contacts with Lewinsky. He
said Starr is ``out-of-control, with his own political agenda and
vendetta, with a blank check to spend millions looking into every
nook and cranny of President Clinton's public as well as his
private life. It's a counterfeit case. This was a sin but not a
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott replied: ``The issue is not Ken Starr, but the president's
conduct. To shift the blame today, which is apparently their
strategy and suggests there is some conspiracy, is totally
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
