<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF NOT FLYING: AIRLINES TAKE A BACK SEAT TO BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airports all over the country have been in a mess, particularly
ours. People-wise, thousands have at least been inconvenienced, if
not worse. Dollar-wise, millions have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   All this in the name of a work slowdown at American Airlines,
which a federal judge ended yesterday. The pilots' union and
corporate management were in a hissing contest over a financial
issue that only those involved deem important.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest, however, has been the reaction of the Regular Joes,
who have had to endure delayed and canceled flights. By all media
accounts, anger has been at a minimum while patience and
understanding have prevailed. Very few screams of indignation are
heard against either the union or management.
</P>
<P>
   Which proves one point:
</P>
<P>
   In our part of the world, American Airlines is as vital to the
living process as any industry we have. But baseball is more
important.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Baseball has never or could never get off this
easy with the paying customers. Labor strikes and shutdowns over
the years have created more backlash for baseball than a
presidential visit to a sorority house.
</P>
<P>
   When it happens in baseball, it becomes a personal insult to the
general public. Greedy players. Greedy owners. Anger, combined with
frustration, boils over among fans. And absolutely nobody has a
good or understanding word to say about either side.
</P>
<P>
   But pilots vs. the airline company? Oh, well, that's just a
business dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Miller, the retired king of union leadership in sports,
laughed heartily yesterday when I ran by him my theory of
``baseball is more important than American Airlines.'' Also
laughing was Rangers president Tom Schieffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized very early there is a huge difference in public
perception,'' said Miller from his home in New York City. ``I took
over the players association in baseball \Rin the late 1960s\S
after a lot of years with the national steelworkers union.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the players went out for the first time \Ra strike in
1972\S, I was stunned at the public furor. I had been involved in
nationwide strikes with the steelworkers that had basically shut
down industries from coast to coast. But that created nothing that
compared to the reaction over baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Miller added, the general public doesn't regard
baseball, or professional sports, as a business, at least not in
the same way it does an airlines or a steel company.
</P>
<P>
   He's right, or course.
</P>
<P>
   But Schieffer takes it beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is part of the cultural fiber of this country,'' he
said. ``I think it's good that people hold us to a higher standard
than they do business in general, or any other sport, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what this creates is a heavier burden that we have to
carry. When we have had these unfortunate disruptions of the game,
our fans do take it personally. For one thing, we are cutting into
their free time. Part of the lure of baseball is you can get away
from it all at the ballpark. When that is taken away, the reaction
is like a sacrilege has been committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some will single out the monster salaries of the baseball
players as the real issue causing the public to resent any labor
disruption.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, the negative reaction to strikes and lockouts was
as strong in the '70s and the '80s, long before salaries escalated.
Plus, NBA players are in the same top-dollar category, and this
season's basketball shutdown was greeted by a collective yawn from
fandom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' said Schieffer. ``Baseball carries a higher
importance in the thought process of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in retirement, Miller said he's still amazed when he hears
baseball fans react to a work stoppage with the traditional, ``I'll
never go to another game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've yet to hear anyone say they'll never buy another car
from General Motors, or ever ride public transit again, or ever
allow their garbage to be picked up again,'' he noted. ``Work
stoppage happens all the time in industry. But baseball, without
question, does exist under a different set of guidelines, at least
in the mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   What it comes down to is this:
</P>
<P>
   You can cancel my plane, but don't you dare cancel my baseball
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
