<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTITUTE-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ON GUILTY PLEA IN PROSTITUTE MURDER CASE COULD HINGE ON ONE
WORD 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. CHEN with CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last September, Kendall L. Francois, 27, an unemployed school
aide, was arrested on charges that he strangled eight prostitutes
at his home in Poughkeepsie, N.Y. Later that month, after the
police found the decaying remains of several victims stashed in his
filthy, ramshackle house, Francois confessed. Before the year was
over, his lawyers tried to enter a guilty plea that would spare him
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the district attorney would hear none of it.
</P>
<P>
   As angry relatives called for the harshest possible punishment,
William V. Grady, the Dutchess County district attorney, announced
that he would seek the death penalty against Francois, and he urged
Judge Thomas Dolan of Dutchess County Court to ignore the guilty
plea.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a case being watched nervously by death penalty
advocates and opponents, Dolan is expected to decide as early as
Thursday whether to accept the guilty plea or put Francois on trial
with death as the ultimate penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The case, at its most literal, hinges on the interpretation of a
single word in a Dec. 22 ruling by the State Court of Appeals that
essentially jettisoned as unconstitutional most of the
plea-bargaining provisions in the state's death penalty law. The
question is: did Francois even have the right to plead guilty
before the district attorney decided to seek the death penalty?
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, lawyers and scholars say, the case is an
example of yet another leak in a flawed death penalty law that
critics have said is only made worse, and more confusing, with each
ruling or test case.
</P>
<P>
   But on a more personal level, the case also threatens to pick at
the scars created by a series of crimes that were so brutally
gruesome that they seemed almost unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the victims' relatives have urged the judge to reject
the guilty plea and clear the way for a death-penalty trial. Others
want to bank on the sure-fire life sentence; that way, the families
avoid an emotionally draining spectacle in a community that
recently weathered the Tawana Brawley defamation case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so split,'' said Tammy Coppola, whose sister, Catina
Newmaster, was among Francois' victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I feel I don't care what happens to him; other days
I feel there's no other justification than facing the death penalty
for what he did. It would be nice if we could be spared the trial,
but that means that he would be spared the death penalty and we're
talking about eight people here _ not just one.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois was charged with 17 counts of murder and assault for
killing eight prostitutes who vanished in the last two years. All
were found inside Francois' dilapidated house, which is less than
two blocks from Vassar College.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed, at first, like a straightforward case: Francois had
confessed. Grady was weighing whether to seek the death penalty. No
plea bargain was in the offing, because both sides have to agree to
any deal.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Dec. 22, the State Court of Appeals, considering
several unrelated cases, essentially voided the state's
plea-bargaining provisions, saying that they unfairly encouraged
defendants to plead guilty _ with a punishment of life without
parole _ rather than risk a death sentence by going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, the court acknowledged, was that the decision would
``reduce the flexibility of both prosecutors and defendants who
wish to plea bargain in capital cases,'' Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, Francois' lawyers entered into Dolan's court
and tried to enter a guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   To Francois' lawyers, one sentence in Kaye's ruling had given
them a constitutional opening: ``a defendant may not plead guilty
to first-degree murder while a notice of intent to seek the death
penalty is pending.'' The word ``pending,'' in their minds, meant
that their client could plead guilty before there was an actual,
formal notice from the district attorney, said Randolph F. Treece,
the first deputy capital defender who is representing Francois.
</P>
<P>
   As in most criminal cases, prosecutors in death penalty cases
must agree to a plea bargain before a judge can approve it.
</P>
<P>
   But since Francois pleaded to the full indictment, his lawyers
reasoned, it was not a plea bargain and therefore did not require
prosecutorial consent. It was the first time, Treece added, that a
defendant in New York state had ever attempted to plead guilty to
an entire indictment before a death notice was served.
</P>
<P>
   Grady did not agree, and on Christmas Eve he announced that he
would seek the death penalty. His interpretation of the word
``pending,'' he said, is that it refers to a 120-day window given
to prosecutors by law within which district attorneys can decide
whether to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a total distortion,'' Grady said, ``if a defendant
rushes to the courthouse and attempts to plead guilty before the
district attorney files his notice, just to avoid the death
penalty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
