r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-FEATURE-LADN     02-10 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGGELING BACK TO DEFEND TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE -- It wasn't so much the thrill of victory that had
golfer Dale Eggeling jumping for joy after last year's win in the
Los Angeles Women's Championship at Oakmont Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sense of relief. She had just won her first tournament
in three years and was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that putt went in on 18, you can't believe it. It's like
birth,'' she said with a laugh. ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Eggeling, who defeated Hiromi Kobayashi in a one-hole playoff,
is back to defend her championship, which begins Friday, with a
fresh outlook. As much as the tournament has undergone a name
change -- it now is called the Valley of the Stars Championship --
so has Eggeling's game.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old admitted she had been ``going through the
motions'' despite winning more than $2 million since turning pro in
July of 1976. She arrived at Oakmont last year with few, if any,
expectations and was five shots behind Kobayashi after the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Eggeling, however, shot a three-under-par 69 in the second round
(tying Cindy Figg-Currier for low round of the day), met her
husband, Mike, in the Oakmont clubhouse and prepared to go to the
airport to catch a 6 p.m. flight to Hawaii for the tour's next
stop. But before she knew it, the leaderboard started changing.
</P>
<P>
   Eggeling's name started moving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing was I finished my round, and I knew conditions
were getting a little bit tougher, but I never even thought about
having a chance to win the tournament,'' she recalled. ``As soon as
I got in, I said to my husband, `OK, let's get ready to go.' I
hadn't even looked at a leaderboard. But he said, `I don't think
we're going anywhere.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going, `What do you mean?' He said, `Look at the
leaderboard.' I saw everybody starting to drop, and I thought, `Oh
God ... oh (bleep).' Then I had to wait an hour and 20 minutes, and
all the girls are saying, `Would you relax?' I was just a nervous
wreck, like a bull in a china shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most exciting part, just waiting around to see.
You just don't know ... you don't want to get your hopes up. Then
you do, and it's like a see-saw. When it happened, I was like,
`Yes!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The triumph was worth $97,500, and Eggeling said it didn't
matter if the tournament was shortened by rain. It was a victory,
something she hadn't experienced since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being in that position and being able to get in the
playoff ... 36 holes, 54 holes, 72 holes,'' she said. ``I don't
care how many holes, it's always great to win. I'm saddened it was
shortened by the rain, but I am glad I got in position to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa, Fla. resident, who shows and trains horses in the
off-season and is a big fan of drag racing, said she now tries to
find the time to work on her game, which never has been a favorite
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the world's greatest procrastinator,'' she admitted with a
grin. ``I have to be kind of cattle-prodded to get out the door and
practice and stuff like that. My husband is always after me to do
it, so that helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``But winning at Oakmont kind of helped keep me in it. It
vaulted me up the money list (she finished with a career-high
$277,217) and it also gave me a big boost in confidence. I was kind
of getting to the point where I was just out there playing, and I
hadn't really set any goals for myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I won in 1995, I thought, `Well, this is great. It's
going to give me a boost and I'm going to be out here longer.' My
general attitude is if you play well enough to win, it's going to
happen. But after winning at Oakmont, I made a commitment to myself
to practice a little bit harder and concentrate a little bit
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to a very good year this year.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she also is looking forward to Oakmont, which she
called one of her favorite courses. Eggeling said she likes the
par-72, 6,276-yard test.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pretty much know where you have to hit it,'' she said.
``There aren't any tricks ... it keeps you thinking for 18 holes,
and there aren't many courses like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings out the best in you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
