<HEADLINE>
ORLANDO BEATS NETS, 89-81 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There was no inspiring victory for the
New Jersey Nets Wednesday night at Continental Arena. Unable to
follow up Sunday's performance against Atlanta, the Nets fell hard
to the Orlando Magic, 89-81.
</P>
<P>
   But the night was not a total loss for Nets coach John Calipari.
With four of his top eight players sidelined, winning the game was
not his only concern. Escaping injury-free was also a priority. And
thankfully for the Nets and their fans in the boisterous crowd of
13,217, no one else was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Now 1-2, the Nets' makeshift club will have to wing it one more
time, Thursday in Milwaukee. Under the leadership of their new
coach, George Karl, the Bucks are 2-0 and will probably not have to
worry about the injured Sam Cassell, Kerry Kittles, Rony Seikaly
and Eric Murdock of the Nets. Calipari said before the game that
none of the four would play against Milwaukee, though he hopes to
have everyone in the lineup Monday against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wednesday night, the Magic took command a few minutes in
and never looked back, sprinting to a halftime lead of 51-43 and a
third-quarter advantage of 69-51. The Nets, who trailed by 73-53
with 10 minutes remaining, pulled within eight points three times
but never truly challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson and Anfernee Hardaway did the most damage for the
Magic (3-1), scoring 21 points apiece. Anderson built Orlando's
lead early, hitting four of five 3-pointers in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn and Scott Burrell led the Nets with 17 points
each, and Kendall Gill added 15. Jayson Williams was monumental on
the boards, grabbing a game-high 21 rebounds. But the
6-foot-10-inch center, who is playing with a broken nose, continued
to struggle from the field, missing all 10 of his shots. He
finished with two points and has not made a basket since the
opening game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando was sharp from the outset, moving the ball well in
half-court sets and driving hard to the basket. The Nets were not
nearly as sterling, as they struggled to get into their offense and
missed several open jump shots. The Magic began putting distance
between the clubs four minutes into the game when Anderson drained
his first 3-pointer to give Orlando a 15-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Though Van Horn was hot, scoring eight points, and Williams was
active, grabbing eight rebounds, the Nets finished the quarter down
by 27-21. Hardaway was too much for Gill, who went to the bench at
the 3-minute-51-second mark after picking up his second foul, and
scored 10 in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit two of his three 3-point attempts to give the crowd
a taste of things to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
