<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLEGE-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCETON'S UNFORGETTABLE COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With dozens of college basketball games each night, there is
barely enough newspaper space for the contests involving ranked
teams. A report on other games is usually brief and reserved for
the unusual.
</P>
<P>
   This sentence appeared in yesterday's ``Star-Telegram'':
``Trailing 40-13, Princeton (16-4, 7-0 Ivy League) rallied for a
50-49 victory over Penn (14-4, 6-1) in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, Paul Harvey and basketball fans, the rest of the story:
</P>
<P>
   Princeton was playing Penn in an Ivy League game between the two
teams that have dominated that conference this decade. And the game
was played at the Palestra, which is to college basketball there
what the Cotton Bowl is to football here.
</P>
<P>
   With that background, here's what happened. Princeton took a 3-0
lead and then didn't score for nearly 14 minutes as Penn went on a
29-0 run. At halftime, the Quakers led 33-9. With 15:15 remaining,
Princeton was down 40-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have gone home, I would have,'' Princeton senior
forward Gabe Lewullis said.
</P>
<P>
   But he stayed and played, as did the rest of the Tigers. They
closed the game with a 37-9 run that produced an improbable
victory. It was the biggest comeback in a game since Kentucky
rallied from 31 down to win at Louisiana State in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all in a little bit of shock,'' Penn coach Fran
Dunphy said. ``We succumbed to the pressure. I was very
disappointed with not finishing what was as good as we can play in
the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn was scoreless over the last 5:15. The Quakers had 12
turnovers in the second half and made only four of 12 shots after
going 13-of-27 in the first half. Not even Michael Jordan _ yes,
that's the name of Penn's best player _ could save the Quakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many big shots, I don't even remember which one
was the winning basket,'' said Princeton coach Bill Carmody, who is
35-0 in Ivy League games.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, coach, freshman center Chris Young of Highland
Park High School put the Tigers ahead to stay with 2:14 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shot wasn't any different than the shots I got in the
first half,'' said Young, who missed all eight of his first-half
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But Young's shot provided symmetry. Princeton scored first and
last. What was in between, well, even those who were there to watch
or participate still can't believe what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was over I had nothing left,'' said Princeton senior
guard Brian Earl, who had a game-high 20 points. ``I just broke
down. I don't remember ever feeling like that after a game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won in the NCAA Tournament, we beat UCLA, we've won a
lot of big games since I've been here,'' Lewullis said. ``But this
game was just unbelievable. I still can't even realize the fact
that we won. We were so far back. It's just mesmerizing.''
SPOTLIGHT
Vertically challenged Rogers is soaring in Penders' offense
</P>
<P>
   Big surprises can come in small packages. Ask Shawnta Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is George Washington's senior point guard. He is listed
as 5 feet, 4 inches tall. Actually, that might be stretching it.
He's probably closer to 5-3. But 64 inches is not Rogers' key
statistic.
</P>
<P>
   He's leading the Atlantic 10 Conference in scoring (21.5 per
game), assists (7.0 per game) and steals (3.75 per game). No
Atlantic 10 player has ever accomplished that statistical hat trick
for a season. He's also fourth in 3-point field goals per game and
is making 85.3 percent of his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while, you see him walking around campus and you
realize how short he is,'' senior forward Yegor Mescheriakov said.
``But he's got a lot of heart. He's an amazing player. Fearless. He
goes up against 6-8 guys, scores and gets fouled.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has been a starter for four years. This season, under
coach Tom Penders, Rogers has flourished. Penders' open-court style
has spread out opposing defenses. That has turned Rogers loose to
drive and dish or pull up and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He affects the game on both ends of the court as much as any
player can,'' Illinois coach Lon Krueger said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is a finalist for the John Wooden player of the year
award and a probable lock for the Frances Pomeroy Naismith Award
that goes to the nation's best player under six feet tall. And
having people talk about his height _ or lack of height _ doesn't
bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reality,'' said Rogers, a Baltimore native who also
averages four rebounds a game. ``People are always going to talk
about it. It's no big thing to me. Sometimes I walk on the court
and people think I'm too short to play.''
IN THE CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Friday the NCAA overturned its postseason ban of Louisville,
meaning coach Denny Crum's team is eligible for this year's NCAA
Tournament. Louisville is 12-7 going into tonight's game at North
Carolina Charlotte and Saturday's game with Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Louisville's postseason eligibility has been restored,
organizers of the Conference USA tournament in Birmingham, Ala.,
are smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The C-USA tourney sold 2,000 tickets after Friday's
announcement. If Louisville had remained ineligible for the NCAA
Tournament, it would not have been able to play in the C-USA
tourney.
BEATING UP FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Mark Madsen is nicknamed ``Mad Dog.'' At 6-foot-8 and
235 pounds, he leaves contusions and abrasions as he moves around
the basket for the Cardinal. Madsen remembers when he realized he
was destined to be a banger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, my dad and I would always play
one-on-one,'' he said. ``One night, when I was in the eighth or
ninth grade, I lifted him, got him in the air, and just jumped
right into him. He ran off the court, really upset, and in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how many of his ribs got broken, but he couldn't
play again for about two months.''
WRONG-BASKET BROWN
</P>
<P>
   When Illinois' Cleotis Brown grabbed the game's final rebound,
it was dramatic. ``We were holding our breath,'' Illinois coach Lon
Kruger said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Brown grabbed the ball after Wisconsin's Sean Mason shot and
missed, securing a 53-51 victory over the Badgers. The final score
would have been 53-49.
</P>
<P>
   With 38 seconds remaining in the first half, Brown grabbed a
Wisconsin free- throw miss and scored in the Badgers' basket to
make it 24-all at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind just went blank,'' Brown said. ``I wondered why I was
so open. Then I was like, `Man, look what I just did.' That last
rebound felt good. I knew not to put that one back up.''
POWER SHIFT?
</P>
<P>
   Think Big Ten Conference basketball and it's hard not to think
Indiana and Purdue. Since the 1966-67 season, one of those schools
has always finished third or better in the Big Ten. Indiana has won
12 Big Ten titles, Purdue has won eight.
</P>
<P>
   But after Purdue's 86-81 overtime defeat of Indiana on Tuesday
night, the Boilermakers are 5-5 (tied for sixth place) and the
Hoosiers are 5-6 (eighth place) in the Big Ten.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Ray Minland of St. Francis, N.Y., is leading NCAA Division I in
scoring at 24.9 per game. Unless he significantly improves that
average, he'll finish with the lowest average for a scoring
champion since 1950, when Villanova's Paul Arizin led the nation
with 25.3 points per game. The five lowest scoring averages to lead
the nation: Player, school Year Avg. Murray Wier, Iowa 1948 21.0
Tony Lavelli, Yale 1949 22.4 Paul Arizin, Villanova 1950 25.3 Kevin
Granger, Texas Southern 1996 27.0 Xavier McDaniel, Wichita State
1985 27.2
</P>
<P>
   _ First year NCAA kept such scoring statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
