<SLUG> BC-BKC-WYOMING-MCCLAIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYOMING COACH USES TUBBS' STYLE AS BLUEPRINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Chants of ``Billy Jr.'' surrounded
first-year Wyoming coach Steve McClain.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa fans were trying to rankle him with comparisons to TCU
coach Billy Tubbs. McClain instead infuriated them by smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's a compliment,'' McClain said. ``I told somebody:
`If I win half as many games as him, then they can chant all they
want.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McClain likes being compared to Tubbs, likes imitating Tubbs'
style of play. McClain likes Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before,'' McClain said. ``The man has never
gotten the credit he deserves. He has taken a program to a Final
Four. He has turned losing programs into winners. He has done all
of this his way.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain, whose team plays TCU tonight at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum,
had a ringside seat for Tubbs' TCU years.
</P>
<P>
   He came to TCU as an assistant under Tubbs in 1994, and they
began building a program from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs supplied a fast-paced, just-like-at-Oklahoma style.
McClain supplied a big-name, big-time recruit named Lee Nailon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a recruit that TCU needed, and Lee Nailon needed us,''
McClain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that he recruited me to come here,'' Nailon said.
``He stayed on me pretty hard to be successful and so far it's paid
off.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU suddenly became a legitimate program, and programs became
interested in Tubbs' assistants.
</P>
<P>
   McClain exited in April to become an assistant under first-year
coach Melvin Watkins at Texas A&AMP;M, a weeklong hiatus until Wyoming
called with a chance for him to be boss.
</P>
<P>
   A head coaching position at Wyoming? Why not? But an assistant's
job at Texas A&AMP;M?
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to do with TCU or Billy Tubbs,'' McClain said.
``It was a situation where financially it was a substantial amount
more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach, you sure you want to talk about money? The politically
correct thing to do would be to play coy, shower a bunch of
compliments on TCU, Texas A&AMP;M, Wyoming and any other school that
you could possibly think of.
</P>
<P>
   McClain is rarely politically correct, though. It's that Tubbs
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Be honest; be fair; be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the advantage when you're an assistant coach and you
come up through the ranks,'' Tubbs said. ``You take this from the
coach that you like. This is what you don't like, so you throw it
away. You just get bits and pieces and you keep what you like and
throw away what you don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain has borrowed substantially from Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of Tubbs' up-and-down, back-and-forth style of
play in McLain, and a lot of Tubbs' in-your-face way of dealing
with officials and his so-what-if-people-get-mad way of talking in
McClain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took TCU's program and ideas and took them to Wyoming,''
McClain said, without a tinge of remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, Tubbs taught McClain too well.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming defeated TCU on Jan. 14, breaking a streak of 16
consecutive Horned Frogs victories in Western Athletic Conference
regular-season play.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, McClain used a style of play that looked eerily
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   And don't look now, but McClain has his Cowboys (14-6, 5-4)
poised to possibly sneak into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expected us to be a factor in the race this year,''
McClain said. ``I inherited a team that didn't have one leader, and
I think we made ourselves into a good basketball team anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a number of similarities exist between Wyoming now and
TCU then: lack of players, lack of purpose, lack of success.
</P>
<P>
   He has recruited players, instilled purpose and achieved success
_ in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   He misses TCU, though.
</P>
<P>
   He said he finds himself glancing at scores sometimes. If TCU
loses, he feels like he lost, too. He finds himself glancing at
articles. If Tubbs says something particularly irreverent, McClain
laughs along. He finds himself watching highlights sometimes. If
Nailon has a particularly nasty dunk, McClain cheers, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a lot of love for him,'' Nailon said. ``Just
because he's over there doesn't mean I have to stop liking him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon embraced McClain before TCU's game in Laramie, Wyo.
Nailon simply told McClain that he missed him.
</P>
<P>
   Then play began, and McClain began pacing in front of Wyoming's
bench. A constant stream of words spewed from his mouth at decibels
that made his face turn red with fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ref!'' McClain screamed. ``Nailon's fouling him.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got a bit of Tubbs in him all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine with me,'' McClain said. ``People who think we're
alike are right on one thing: We're both very driven to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
