<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOYA-NYT &LR;      02-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA KNOWS HE CAN'T JUST GO THROUGH THE MOTIONS AGAINST
QUARTEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ There is a side of Oscar De La Hoya that hasn't been
seen. The De La Hoya who talks about getting hurt in the ring,
about having to take a knee during a bout. The boxer who talks
about whether it is nobler to stand and sling punches, or stay out
of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya shared those thoughts with reporters Wednesday as he
talked about fighting Ike Quartey on Saturday at the Thomas and
Mack Arena in a 12-round bout for De La Hoya's World Boxing Council
welterweight championship. The bout will be broadcast on
pay-per-view by TVKO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who wanted this fight,'' De La Hoya said. ``I'm
the one who stepped up to the plate, and I said I wanted Ike
Quartey. If I hadn't, I would be fighting some Joe Schmoe.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I was losing it. To become a champion is tough. To
stay a champion is tougher. I was losing that motivation.'' For the
past couple of years De La Hoya has been going through the motions.
Training just enough to get past the likes of David Kamau, Hector
Camacho, Wilfredo Rivera and Patrick Charpentier.
</P>
<P>
   For the bout with Charpentier, who landed five punches before De
La Hoya stopped him in the third round last June, De La Hoya could
have had a tougher workout by balancing his checkbook. ``When I was
fighting ordinary fighters, I began to lose my motivation,'' De La
Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
   That was why De La Hoya, 26, went to his promoter, Bob Arum, the
president of Top Rank, and asked for Quartey, who is one of the
toughest welterweights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is the one that also wanted this fight, because he
knows that my last six or seven fights I haven't been in good
shape,'' De La Hoya said. ``He knows that. He knows who I am, and
he knows my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Asking for Quartey, 29, is like asking for an audit from the
Internal Revenue Service. ``If I beat him, it will boost my
confidence level up,'' De La Hoya said. ``It's high now, but this
will take it way up. Ike Quartey is one of the better guys out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a risky venture for De La Hoya, who is used to sure
things. It is his first fight under a new partnership that he
reached with Arum, who has been his promoter since the boxer turned
professional after winning a gold medal in the 1992 Olympic Games
in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (29-0) will pocket $9 million for this fight, but
this time he might earn every penny.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey (34-0-1), the former World Boxing Association
welterweight champion, is a hard puncher. He has the potential to
knock De La Hoya into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In his last fight, De La Hoya stood toe to toe with a fading
Julio Cesar Chavez and slugged him into submission in the eighth
round. It was a calculated, macho response to a situation that De
La Hoya knew he would victoriously walk away from. Chavez couldn't
hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   If he tries the same thing with Quartey, a fighter in his prime,
De La Hoya might find himself looking up at the ceiling. Either De
La Hoya is still working on his fight strategy, or he is truly
puzzled about the best way to fight Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ike Quartey has good physical conditioning; he can last 12
rounds,'' De La Hoya said. ``I might box him. But I might stand and
slug with him. I'm capable of slugging it out with him, but that
might not be the best thing to do in the fight. He can knock me out
if he hits me with a good shot, and I can knock him out if I hit
him with a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stand in there with anybody. I can go in there and bang
with him. I can take it, because that is how I've prepared for this
fight. I've trained to stay in there and slug.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
