<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CORDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIOT CORDAY, CARDIOLOGIST, DIES AT 85  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Cal., N.C., Canada)  By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Eliot Corday, a Los Angeles cardiologist who played a major
role in conveying American knowledge about cardiology to other
countries, particularly underdeveloped ones, died on Monday at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles. He was 85 and lived in
Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Corday, a Canadian who became a U.S. citizen in
1951, was a member of the board of Cedars-Sinai, where he was a
senior attending physician from 1961 until recently. He was also a
longtime clinical professor of medicine at the University of
California, Los Angeles School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Another cardiologist, Dr. Samuel M. Fox III, a past president of
the American College of Cardiology, said, ``For the better part of
30 or 40 years, Dr. Corday was the contact person arranging
overseas lecture tours'' by American cardiologists. ``They had
tremendous influence in increasing personal contact with our
colleagues overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Forrester, a Cedars-Sinai colleague of Corday, said
that Corday was ``the leading force in initiating federal support
of cardiovascular research'' and that he contributed to a number of
``fundamental practices of cardiology, including the management of
acute coronary syndromes.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1965 and 1966, Corday was president of the American College
of Cardiology, and in the years that followed, he became one of the
most prominent advocates of federal financing for cardiovascular
research.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, he also became a noted champion of the conveying
of American cardiovascular expertise to other countries. To help
achieve that goal, he founded the American College of Cardiology's
international education program.
</P>
<P>
   Over 20 years, more than 70 groups of American cardiologists
went to underdeveloped countries, where they gave instruction in
cardiovascular diagnosis and treatment. That program has been
credited with greatly improving care.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Corday was invited by President Ronald Reagan to
head the U. S. Information Agency's Medical Science Advisory
Committee, and he went on to arrange live televised communication
sessions between American cardiologists and cardiologists in the
Middle East, India, Hungary and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A cardiologist who is a former president of the American Heart
Association, Dr. Sidney Smith, said, ``Dr. Corday has been a real
ambassador in terms of sharing ideas internationally and in
encouraging the cardiovascular community to see themselves beyond
national borders and understand that cardiovascular disease has
become a worldwide problem and requires worldwide dialogue if we
are going to to be effective in combating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is also a professor and chief of cardiology at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, added: ``Dr. Corday
was a leader in cardiovascular disease. He was highly respected for
his contributions to clinical cardiology, and we will miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1967 to 1977, Corday was national consultant in cardiology
to the surgeon general of the Air Force and he rose to be a major
general.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Prince Rupert, British Columbia, and received his
medical degree in 1940 from the University of Alberta School of
Medicine. During World War II, he served in the Royal Canadian Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he came to the United States and went on to become a
resident at two New York hospitals, Bellevue and then Mount Sinai,
before moving to Los Angeles. There, from 1950 to 1961, he was
chief of cardiology at Cedars of Lebanon hospital, which merged
with another hospital, Mount Sinai, to form Cedars-Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 59 years, the former Marian
Lipkind; a son, Dr. Stephen Corday, who lives in the Los Angeles
area; a daughter, Joanne Kozberg, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
