<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-REST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NEED R&AMP;R BEFORE BUSY STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seriously, now. What good is it going to do a bunch of
millionaire hockey players to take a couple of days off and sun
themselves in Southern California while enjoying some of the
nation's finest golf courses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because for a couple of days, we don't have to think about
hockey,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``I don't think we'll
talk about it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars just finished a two-day hiatus in Newport Beach,
Calif., where they hoped to dodge scattered thunderstorms in
pursuit of leisure activity. It's a strange way for a team coming
off a 3-0 loss to prepare for its game tomorrow against the Mighty
Ducks in Anaheim, but it's a break coach Ken Hitchcock said will be
helpful in getting the team ready for the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these situations, we're just best when we get away,''
Hitchcock said of an NHL scheduling glitch that has the Stars
playing one game in 10 days. ``We want to keep the skating to a
minimum and let the guys get their energy back.''
</P>
<P>
   To retrieve their energy and ``reload,'' as Hitchcock likes to
say, some Stars players took in a Rolling Stones concert, played
some golf or went fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be some guys who will find a television
somewhere and have to watch a game,'' center Mike Modano said.
``But not me. I'm staying away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have had success on such bonding trips in previous
seasons, traveling to Banff, Alberta; Whistler, British Columbia;
and Colorado Springs, Colo. This time, there could be even more on
the line. When they finally get back on the ice, the Stars will
play 10 games in 17 days and follow that with a March schedule that
has 10 road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure the guys are relaxing, but we all know there's real price
to pay for that,'' Hitchcock said. ``Starting Friday night, we're
going to pay for this, and we need to be ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, strength and conditioning coach J.J.
McQueen put the team through high aerobic activities last week and
tried to stop the ``deconditioning'' of the team that comes with
regular-season play, he said. McQueen will continue that plan the
remainder of the season with 15 minute exercises each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each player will have a certain area to work on, and he'll
work it hard for 15 minutes,'' McQueen said. ``That will be
different for every player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he likely will give days off from skating for
players to work only on McQueen's programs. The focus will be
toward keeping the team physically and mentally sharp heading into
the final 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to measure ourselves against the Detroits and
Colorados, and now everybody is measuring themselves to us,''
Modano said. ``We know that every night we're going to get a hard
push from teams, so we have to take it upon ourselves that we're
one of the top teams and we're going to have to expect it every
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
