<HEADLINE>
USC FALLS TO LOYOLA 8-5
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It didn't matter if it came against the defending
national champion or an NAIA team. Loyola Marymount needed a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions got it, at the expense of the defending national
champion.
</P>
<P>
   LMU broke a three-game losing streak with an 8-5 win over USC on
Wednesday afternoon at home. Jacob Minter and Scott Walter both hit
late-inning home runs for the Lions, who were swept at home this
past weekend by Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tough weekend,'' LMU coach Frank Cruz said. ``A `W'
was badly needed.''
</P>
<P>
   USC, which began the season ranked No.1 by Baseball America,
dropped to 1-4, matching its worst start since 1993. The Trojans
host No.13 Texas Tech this weekend at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty down,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie said. ``We'll
have to fight through this. We've got to show a little more
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans tied the game in the sixth on junior designated
hitter Carlos Casillas' leadoff homer, the first of his USC career.
</P>
<P>
   Minter responded with a two-out, two-run homer in the seventh
that gave the Lions (2-3) a 5-3 lead. Two batters later, Joe
Sulentor had an RBI single that increased the lead to 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans cut the lead to 6-5 in the eighth on Eric Munson's
two-run single. But Walter, a sophomore catcher who was the West
Coast Conference's Player of the Year last season, gave the Lions
extra cushion with a two-run homer off reliever Steve Immel.
</P>
<P>
   Walter said the Lions were down after the weekend sweep, but
they hadn't lost their composure, especially this early in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't panicking,'' he said. ``We wanted to put together a
good game. We hit the ball when we needed to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
