<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-AUDITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC MAYOR QUESTIONS STATE COMPTROLLER'S AUTHORITY TO DO MANAGEMENT
REVIEWS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALAN FINDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A lawyer representing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
contended Wednesday that state Comptroller H. Carl McCall lacked
the legal authority to evaluate the efficiency and management of
New York City's government, even though McCall and his predecessors
have conducted hundreds of such reviews for nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the comptroller has been doing municipal
performance audits, but we can all agree that that doesn't mean it
is constitutional,'' Jane L. Gordon, a lawyer in the city's Law
Department, argued before the state's highest court, the Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing McCall, who sued the city two years ago
after the mayor ordered city officials to stop cooperating with his
auditors, maintained that both state law and the state constitution
give the comptroller the power to determine whether the city is
spending public money efficiently, effectively and in compliance
with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that the state comptroller has the right to
conduct traditional financial audits of the city. The heart of the
dispute between two of the state's senior political officials lies
in Giuliani's assertion that McCall lacks the statutory and
constitutional authority to perform broader reviews of how
effectively the city delivers services. Those reviews are known as
performance audits.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, which entered what is likely to be its final stage
Wednesday, began in March 1997. McCall informed the city that he
wanted to audit the performance of a half-dozen city agencies,
including the accuracy with which the city had been reporting
significant improvements in street cleanliness, crime reduction and
moving people from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that McCall's effort was politically motivated, the mayor
barred McCall's auditors from evaluating city programs. Senior
mayoral aides said that Giuliani had ordered city agencies to stop
sharing most information with the state comptroller's office
because the mayor believed that McCall, a Democrat, was motivated
solely by the desire to embarrass the Republican mayor and harm his
re-election effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
