<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-TRIAL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$51 MILLION VERDICT AWARDED TO SMOKER IS BIGGEST OF ITS KIND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS to ADD comment from Philip Morris attorney on grounds
for appeal, raise industry's national settlement higher in story;
UPDATE closing stock prices for Philip Morris in 8th graf, The
verdict ...ADD that Henley's cancer is in remission.)  (jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state jury in San Francisco has ordered the Philip Morris Cos.
to pay $51.5 million to a woman who says her inoperable lung cancer
was caused by more than 35 years of smoking cigarettes, primarily
Philip Morris's Marlboro brand.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment is by far the largest ever reached in a
smoking-related lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts were $1.5 million in compensatory damages, awarded
on Tuesday, and $50 million in punitive damages, awarded late
Wednesday. They resulted from the first cigarette lawsuit to reach
a California jury in more than a decade, following the 1997 repeal
of a state law that barred product liability suits by individuals
against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   William S. Ohlemeyer, a lawyer representing Philip Morris, said
the company would appeal. He said there were sure to be substantial
grounds, since, in the absence for so long of any smoker's suit in
California, the law there was somewhat unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   But while the judgment could be sharply reduced on appeal, or
even thrown out, it signals that the cigarette companies may well
have to fight a brushfire of similar suits just as the industry
hoped that its legal troubles had been put to rest with a $206
billion settlement reached with 46 states three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Defending themselves against thousands of suits brought by
individual smokers or their survivors _ particularly in California,
where juries lean to high damage awards _ would prove extremely
expensive for the companies. Indeed, analysts who were interviewed
about the size of the award said they believed that its lure to
prospective plaintiffs could bring a new rush of litigation against
cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give incredible new strength to claims against
tobacco companies,'' said Mary Aronson, president of Aronson
Washington Research, which follows tobacco litigation for
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict awarding the 53-year-old plaintiff, Patricia Henley,
$50 million in punitive damages _ more than three times the $15
million her lawyer had asked for _ was returned after the stock
market had closed Wednesday. But on the basis of just the $1.5
million in compensatory damages awarded late the day before, prices
of cigarette company stocks fell sharply. Philip Morris was off
$3.9375 a share, to close at $41.4375, and the RJR Nabisco Holdings
Corporation was down $1.375, to $27.3125.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel wonderful,'' Ms. Henley told The Associated Press after
the verdict Wednesday. ``This is a great day for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The judgment was the third in the last three years in favor of
smokers who contended that cigarette makers had failed to warn them
adequately of smoking's hazards. The two other awards, both against
the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., were later overturned, and no
such verdict has ever survived appeal. Until Wednesday, the largest
judgment was about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the $1.5 million awarded on Tuesday was
compensation for Ms. Henley's medical costs, pain and suffering. In
addition, her lawyer, Madelyn J. Chaber, asked the jurors to award
her $15 million to punish the company for the negligence and fraud
that was found in Tuesday's verdict. The jury responded with that
much, and then $35 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley, of Los Angeles, discovered last year that she had
inoperable lung cancer, which is now in remission after
chemotherapy and radiation treatment. Lawyers for Philip Morris
argued that she had understood the risks of smoking. But her suit
said that she had smoked since she was a teen-ager, taking up the
habit a few years before government-required warning labels began
appearing on cigarette packages in 1966, and that the tobacco
companies had never told smokers that addiction might leave them
incapable of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Until quite recently, though, Ms. Henley would have been
forbidden to bring her case. Under a 1987 tort reform law, product
liability suits against tobacco companies were prohibited in
California on the ground that the risks of smoking were universally
known. The law was repealed in 1997, around the time California
decided to file a claim against the tobacco industry in an effort
to recover smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, California was one of the 46 states that struck
the $206 billion deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-10-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
