<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-ALPINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODE MILLER: YOUNG PROSPECT STILL IN SEARCH OF A MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.H.)  (bl) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVER CREEK, Colo. _ It was a hungry young Bode Miller who
popped out of the gate here Tuesday in search of a medal in the
combined downhill at the world Alpine ski championships. But the
slippery course ate him instead, taking a chunk out of the young
skier's equilibrium and spitting him out like crushed ice in a
fast-food line.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Miller fought back. Never mind that his ski had
elaminated in a brutal turn on the upper third of the Birds of Prey
slope. Nor that he had lost one ski altogether near the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping back onto the only foot still capable of sliding, the
racer from Franconia, N.H., somehow kept his balance, finishing
only eight seconds behind the pack. Had it not been that Miller
missed a final gate, he would have gone on to compete in the two
slaloms that make up the combined event.
</P>
<P>
   He will have another chance to show his ability. Miller is
expected to race in the world championship giant slalom at Vail on
Friday. And there are those back East who think he can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bode came to us as a totally raw talent,'' Joan Dolan,
athletic director for Carrabassett Valley Academy, a ski school at
Sugarloaf, Maine, said in a recent telephone interview. ``He was a
kid with natural athletic ability who has really refined his
technique. He's also a real risk-taker. Nothing scares him. It
wouldn't matter to him that Hermann Maier was racing. He just
worries about himself, and his own skiing.''
</P>
<P>
   At a strapping 6 feet 2 inches and 200 pounds, Bode (pronounced
BO-dee) Miller, a member of the U.S. A-team, has both raced and
conquered the equally brawny Herminator. The two competed in a
giant slalom last Jan. 12 in Adelboden, Switzerland. Maier won the
competition, but Miller recorded the fastest second run of the day.
That means the American beat Maier in one-half of a two-race event.
Maier captured first over all. Miller was eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Miller went on to place fourth in a slalom several days later in
Wengen, Switzerland. The experience has whetted his podium
appetite. ``A lot of the Austrians are getting older,'' he said
last week. ``About a dozen are 26 or older. They're looking at me
in two or three more seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``they'' he is referring to are United States ski officials
who have been faced with mediocre results since the retirement this
season of America's Olympic block _ Tommy Moe, A.J. Kitt and Kyle
Rasmussen. ``In the past year or two, Bode is one of, if not the,
single-most exciting young skier we have,'' said Tom Kelly, a U.S.
Ski Team vice president. ``He has shown an incredible potential and
motivation to do really well.''
</P>
<P>
   But the young Miller had some ground to make up first as a ski
racer. Having taken up snowboarding before it was popular, he only
skied now and then. His parents, who lived frugally, didn't push
it. He also was not highly motivated at school. ``I'd ace all the
tests, but I never did my homework,'' Miller said. ``I'd get bored
easily. Once you get in the habit of that, it's very easy to stay
that way. I just wasn't getting that much out of public school. To
be inside was tortuous.''
</P>
<P>
   By ninth grade, his parents decided, with a boost from an uncle,
to send him to the private Carrabassett Academy for academics and
ski training. ``I was a skinny little kid without good technique
who was getting beaten,'' he said. ``Meantime, I was looking at
these snowboarders who I knew I could crush easily. But I didn't go
that way. I was stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   That same nonconformist streak didn't make him the easiest
youngster to coach. ``I skied to survive,'' he said. ``I went out
into the woods if I had to _ to make things tougher. It was hard
for me to have coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   He still struggles with the limitations of self-discipline, but
he is refreshingly candid about it. And he doesn't lack for self
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not able to stay put on the right spot on my skis,'' he
said, ``mostly from a lack of experience. But in two years, I'd
like to be winning World Cups in every discipline.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
