<HEADLINE>
BILL FRANCE JR. STEPS DOWN AT NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TARIK EL BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the stock-car racing world preparing for its biggest race,
the Daytona 500, in its 41st running Sunday, and the sport at its
height of popularity, NASCAR announced a major change in management
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After 27 years handling the day-to-day operations of NASCAR,
Bill France Jr. handed off those responsibilities to Mike Helton,
who was named senior vice president and chief operating officer of
the circuit, in addition to his current duties as NASCAR's director
of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which came as a surprise to most but had been
discussed within NASCAR for some time, marks the first time that
someone named France hasn't been in charge since the start of the
series 51 years ago. France Jr. assumed control in 1972 from his
father, Bill France Sr., the founder of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knows Mike Helton understands why we made this
decision,'' France said. ``Mike has done a fantastic job and has
been a quick study. He is one of, if not the best, executives in
motorsports. The day-to-day operation of NASCAR is in excellent
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   France Jr., 66, is credited with transforming NASCAR from a
popular Southern sport of the 1960s and 1970s into the
multibillion-dollar sport it is today. He will remain as president.
</P>
<P>
   France, who has experienced minor health problems in recent
years, said he was looking forward to taking a step back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part is that nothing is broken so there is no urgent
mission for a fix,'' Helton said.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, 45, came upon the racing scene in 1980 as director of
public relations at Atlanta International Raceway and was named
general manager in 1985. For the next nine years, Helton served in
various capacities at Daytona International Speedway, Talladega
Superspeedway and the International Speedway Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   It was Helton's versatile resume that made him the first choice
to replace France. Helton had more experience than Brian France,
Bill France Jr.'s only son, who seemed to be a logical choice to
take over. Brian France, 36, is one of NASCAR's senior vice
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Helton was the No. 1 choice for that job,'' said Richard
Childress, owner of the RCR Chevrolet Monte Carlos. ``Mike's the
kind of guy who can run the show. He's got the experience, the
knowledge. I think he'll do a good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
