<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: INJURIES ARE ALREADY CRAMPING WOUNDED SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell sat with his bulky walking boot in
front of his locker room cubicle Wednesday night, explaining how he
would rehabilitate the stress fracture in his right heel _ an
injury that may sideline him for six weeks. Swimming and the
exercise bike, but no basketball for now.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, Joe Dumars' hamstring is cramping up. In Toronto,
Kevin Willis is battling back spasms. In Miami, Pat Riley's team is
in big trouble. Jamal Mashburn will miss at least two weeks with a
severe bone contusion in his left knee. Voshon Lenard has decided
to have surgery for a stress fracture in his left tibia and may
miss the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lockout basketball . . . it is fatalistic.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be turnovers were the problem. But in this
labor-ravaged season, the team with the fewest magnetic resonance
imaging tests may be the one to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there are more people on the injury list
now than during most regular seasons,'' said Steve Traina, the team
physician with the Denver Nuggets and a member of the Association
of Professional Team Physicians. ``If you look at the injuries,
though, most aren't career-threatening. There aren't any blown-out
ACLs or dislocated shoulders. It's mostly quadriceps injuries,
hamstring pulls, tendinitis, sore feet and ankle sprains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those types of injuries were bound to happen, given how
quickly they put a training camp together.''
</P>
<P>
   In their rush to put a season together after the six-month labor
dispute, the National Basketball Association and the players union
each agreed to play as many games as possible after only a two-week
training camp and two preseason contests.
</P>
<P>
   The result has already tested the depth and resolve of several
teams. Wednesday night in New York at Madison Square Garden, for
example, Marcus Camby, who has been a nonfactor since being
acquired for Charles Oakley, received significant playing time
against Washington in the first half because of Sprewell's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy sidled up to Camby before the game and
whispered, ``You see how quickly opportunity can come?''
</P>
<P>
   Many teams also see how quickly their post-season dreams have
already faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know if there are more injuries or not,'' said
Russ Granik, the league's deputy commissioner. ``But it wouldn't be
a shock because of the combination of a short training camp and the
longer time off. It does create a little greater jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there would be some risk; that's why we kept insisting
we have a two-week training camp instead of one,'' Granik said.
``At some point, everything was a trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, coaches predicted this rash of injuries several weeks
before the lockout ended. They knew many players without a contract
were not working out, and wondered if the league and the union had
the NBA's best interests in mind by trying to cram 50 games into 89
days.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Van Gundy are just one example of a team and a
coach that has to cut and paste and wait. It should make for some
interesting lineup changes the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In one game, the Knicks went from a team fielding the smallest
starting lineup in the league to a beefier, less athletic outfit.
Kurt Thomas started Wednesday night at power forward, and Camby and
the forgotten Dennis Scott received playing time in the first half.
If that big lineup produces, maybe Sprewell returns in a few weeks
as a sixth man _ the role John Starks filled so well for the last
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, in a three-month season, depth becomes so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was great concern from the teams and the physicians
because you can't legislate to make guys come into camp in shape,''
said Glenn Perry, the NBA's team physicians' president, who works
as the Charlotte Hornets' doctor. ``Some of the players who came to
camp weren't in shape and they didn't have a long period of time to
get in shape. It's hard to say whether it's circumstance or due to
something else. But when you play a lot of games at a compressed
level, the body needs time to recover. Those back-to-back-to-back
games are probably going to take their toll.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, New York, Detroit and Toronto, they already have.
Charles Barkley went for an MRI on Wednesday in Houston. It is not
an aberration anymore. It is what happens when a season is thrown
together in a short amount of time. In a year of lockout
casualties, you don't wonder who is going to the finals. You wonder
whose hamstring is the next to go. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
