<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-BUDGET--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR STRESSES SPENDING CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Setting a course his aides called
``responsible Republicanism,'' Gov. John Rowland proposed a
two-year Connecticut budget Wednesday that took advantage of the
galloping economy by giving taxpayers a rebate for a second year in
a row, but also aimed to eliminate state offices that he considered
wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland proposed income-tax credits for tuition and property tax
payments, but did not seek a cut in the state income tax rate.
Democrats have opposed such a cut, saying that could create
problems when the economy turns down. The omission was a reminder
that Rowland has abandoned his drive to eliminate the income tax, a
campaign pledge when he was first elected governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest challenge we face in the years ahead is
controlling the growth of government spending,'' he said during
Wednesday's address to a joint session of the state Senate and
House of Representatives. ``As our economy continues to grow and to
gain momentum, the worst thing that state government can do is
abandon the tight-fisted control that we have maintained during the
1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who control both houses of the Legislature, said the
new budget incorporated so many of their priorities that there was
an odd dynamic on the floor, with Democrats embarrassed to be
clapping so much and Republicans aghast at the largess the governor
was dispensing. The scene reflected the delicate line moderate
Republican governors have to tread as they try to ease their party
toward the center without losing conservatives, who are the party's
backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland did pick one political fight, proposing elimination of
the state's eight high sheriffs, a last vestige of county
government. Under his plan, which would be put to voters as a
constitutional amendment, sheriffs would no longer be elected, and
their duties _ transporting prisoners, maintaining court security
and serving legal papers _ would be absorbed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   He surprised some legislators with a plan to offer a state
income tax credit for tuition paid to public or private colleges in
Connecticut. The program, which piggybacks on a similar federal
credit, offers families 15 percent off their state tax return, up
to $225 for each student.
</P>
<P>
   But one Democratic leader suggested Rowland had become a
born-again big spender. Rep. William Dyson, D-New Haven,
Appropriations Committee co-chairman, said he would work to reduce
the proposed spending increase, 4 percent the first year and 4.8
percent the second, to the rate of inflation, 1 percent to 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget is $11.6 billion for the fiscal year
beginning July 1 and $12.1 billion for the next year. A final
version is due by June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Some hope Rowland will be considered as a vice presidential
candidate next year, and his budget is in sync with the
``compassionate conservatism'' of Gov. George Bush of Texas, whom
Rowland endorsed this week for the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
