<SLUG> BC-OLY-SPONSORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT ON IOC AGENDA: APPEASING ITS SPONSORS  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also OLY-WELCH) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The marketers of the International Olympic Committee
will try to assure their top sponsors Thursday of the
organization's resolve to reform itself amid the widening scandal
surrounding Salt Lake City's fevered drive to snare the 2002 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings in Manhattan, scheduled a month ago, will update
the 11 worldwide sponsors on the investigations into improper
gift-giving that have implicated 24 IOC members, and the plans for
cleaning up the IOC's insular business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're understandably concerned,'' said Michael Payne, the
IOC's marketing director. ``They've told us to do what we have to
do to get to the bottom of it, to go all the way. Clearly, things
have to be changed, but it's not possible to fix it all in 24
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne will join Richard Pound, the IOC vice president in charge
of marketing, in the sponsor briefings. Assuaging the concerns of
the worldwide sponsors is paramount because each pays an average of
$40 million to attach its corporate image and products to the
Olympic rings. If the widening scandal cannot be contained quickly,
and the IOC's proposed reforms fail, the value of the sponsorships
could fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be satisfied until the issue is finally put to
rest,'' said Ben Deutsch, a spokesman for Coca-Cola, which has
committed to sponsoring the Olympics through 2008. ``We're anxious
to hear what they have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor that has been most vocal about the Olympic scandal
has been John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance. David D'Alessandro,
John Hancock's president, has consistently criticized the IOC's
ability to investigate itself. He has also halted talks with NBC
Sports about buying $20 million in commercial time for the 2000
Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, and ordered the Olympic rings
stripped from a John Hancock billboard at Fenway Park and on
courtside signs at the Fleet Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at this situation carefully, the IOC isn't
listening to the national organizing committees or the press, so
perhaps they'll listen to the people sending them money,''
D'Alessandro said. He added that he was particularly dissatisfied
that the IOC had absolved the Australian Olympic Committee of
wrongdoing for offering $70,000 to two African IOC members on the
eve of Sydney's two-vote victory over Beijing for next year's
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro said he was not trying to force the IOC to rebate
any of Hancock's fee. ``This isn't about forcing the price down,''
he said. ``But if the rings devalue in the consumers' mind, then
they decline in value to the sponsors and to television.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said that sponsor fees were secured through signed
contracts, but acknowledged that ``we're in trouble'' if the
scandals were not contained quickly. Payne, perhaps seeking an
optimistic spin, said a series of swiftly enacted, enforceable
reforms ``could make the sponsorships worth more in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   At Coca-Cola, the company has chosen to ``move forward on all
things Olympic,'' said Deutsch, despite the uncertainty generated
by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a very specific distinction between the
administration of the Games and the Games themselves,'' Deutsch
added. ``We'll do everything we can to support our sponsorship and
to get the full value from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch said he was not certain if Thursday's meetings would end
with any joint action or statement by the sponsors. ``We'll find
that out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Klingensmith, the president of Sports Illustrated
magazine, a worldwide Olympic sponsor through 2004, said, ``It's
our sincere hope that the IOC faces its problems in a serious,
expeditious way.'' He declined to say if he believed that the IOC
has handled itself in such a manner.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt abandoned a plan for
statewide Internet deregulation in the face of an accusation that
US West, a U.S. Olympic Committee telecommunications sponsor that
would have benefited from the proposal, had released $5 million in
sponsorship money that it had withheld, in return for favorable
treatment. US West denied the accusation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
