r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-CHANGES-2ndTa     02-10 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-CHANGES-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: and succession of officials.
</P>
<P>
   Zine and Glushon have raised questions as to whether there is an
effort to water down what was approved by the conference committee
on these and other issues in which the elected panel's
recommendations were to be incorporated but the language was
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Elected Commissioner Janice Hahn has questioned why they should
even bother going to the City Council with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   She has suggested the elected group just take over the unified
plan, refine it and submit it directly to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Chemerinsky and Kieffer think it is important to get the
City Council on board to present a unified front to try to pass the
reform plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we want to take into the next century,''
Kieffer said. ``I think it does make meaningful change. Look, there
are always going to be your hard-core secessionists who will oppose
this. But there are just as many who support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Xandra Kayden, president of the League of Women Voters who
served briefly on the appointed panel, also defended the reform
plan from attacks by homeowner groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the self-selected advisory neighborhood councils, you
undercut the power of the homeowner groups,'' Kayden said. ``You
also have a chance to build a network of neighborhood groups that
we haven't seen in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his skepticism and suspicions, Glushon said he will
campaign for the charter plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it have all I want? No,'' Glushon said. ``As it sits
right now, it is better than what we have. It does provide for
greater accountability. It does provide a basis for improved
representation. It does provide for a better structure of
government than we have today.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to remind ourselves it is not the end-all, be-all.
It is a start. We can continue to make changes to make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, one of the two fathers of the charter reform movement,
admits some disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way, I had far greater expectations for my
child,'' Fleming said. ``But there's an old story of you never
going broke if you take a profit. What this does is give us
something far better than we have now. But considering the
potential, it's a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fleming said he would support the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does give some more community empowerment,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it going to abate the sentiment of those who want to split
off? No, that's still going to be there. This is a small step
forward, but still a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
