<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-CHANGES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY EFFORT TO REVISE L.A. CHARTER FALLS SHORT OF GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It started three years ago in the parking lot of
a suburban supermarket with the promise of neighborhood empowerment
and decentralized government.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan and Fire Commissioner David Fleming, their
shirt sleeves rolled up on a hot August day in 1996, stopped
shoppers to collect petitions to deal with perhaps the most arcane
aspect of city government -- rewriting the City Charter.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was designed to make the city more responsive to its
communities and was seen as a way to head off the then-nascent San
Fernando Valley secession drive.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan was successful in seeing his charter reform movement win
voter support although his candidate slate was routed in electing a
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a compromise proposal hammered out between the elected and
City Council-appointed commissions is nearly complete and the
process might be adding fuel to the effort to create a new city,
not only in the Valley but in other areas around Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of the reform effort, some of the most
far-reaching proposals -- elected neighborhood councils and an
independent redistricting commission -- have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives ammunition to Valley secession,'' said Gerry Silver
of Homeowners of Encino.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was exactly what I expected. There was never a doubt in
my mind that city government would suddenly relinquish its power to
the people. What we wanted was more decision-making authority in
the community. What we got was more power for the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he is prepared to mount a campaign against the new
charter and has received indications from other homeowner groups
around the city that they are prepared to join him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see is an unholy alliance between the unions and the
city and nothing will change,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Brain of Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment, the
group seeking the cityhood study, said it would not take a position
on charter reform.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, however, Brain questioned the effectiveness of the
new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a valid question to ask if it satisfies the concerns of
the Valley,'' Brain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that regard, I think it falls short. People in the Valley
wanted to have local decisions made locally. We wanted to see some
decentralization in terms of distribution of services and
representation. In that sense, it doesn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   George Kieffer, chairman of the council-appointed commission who
dominated the process of arriving at a consensus, concedes that the
debate has exposed a deep lack of trust in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of trust, by the public in government, by
government officials with each other, is what is so troubling,''
Kieffer said. ``That's what I hope this new charter will do. Bring
back some level of trust by making the government more
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a twisted road over the past 27 months to get to
where the reform effort now stands.
</P>
<P>
   Even before voters selected the 15 members of the elected
Charter Reform Commission, the City Council formed its own
21-member panel to review the charter and come up with
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief early effort by Kieffer, chairman of the
appointed panel, and elected commission Chairman Erwin Chemerinsky
to work together, but that fell apart. At one point, one elected
commissioner suggested the appointed group disband itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the commission elected by the voters,'' said elected
Commissioner Dennis Zine. ``That's who we are responsible to. The
others were appointed by the City Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Elected Commissioner Rob Glushon said there were other
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their commission was staff-driven,'' Glushon said. ``For
better or worse, ours was commissioner-driven where each
commissioner has been hands-on with all policy decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The skepticism went beyond that, with many commissioners
critical of the appointed commission's final document -- some call
it City Charter Lite -- and suspicious of the roles of various city
officials, in particular Chief Legislative Analyst Ron Deaton.
</P>
<P>
   Deaton, the council's top appointee who is widely regarded as
the most powerful person at City Hall, said his only participation
was in forming a working group to go over the appointed
commission's final draft to make sure it complied with state law
and didn't have conflicting proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the appointed panel said Deaton played no role in
drafting the final document or in pushing proposals with the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deaton had no input,'' Kieffer said. ``And, as a matter of
fact, we received more input and lobbying from the Mayor's Office
than the council or anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The new consensus plan, which the City Council is scheduled to
review today, was hammered out over the past several months in a
series of conference committee meetings where Kieffer and
Chemerinsky engineered compromises on key issues from the size of
the City Council to the power of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But that compromise has left a number of hurt feelings among
commissioners and staffers -- on both panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity to really do something,'' said one
official, who asked not to be identified. ``About six months ago, I
thought it was really going to happen and then it got scaled back.
It's better than what the city has now, but it's not as good as it
could have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension between the groups remains, particularly with a series
of unresolved issues -- on when the new charter provisions should
take effect, police discipline, details on neighborhood councils
and succession of officials.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
