<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Immigration Laws Eased
</P>
<P>
   The government says it will modify its immigration laws to allow
as many as 200,000 illegal aliens to obtain residency permits,
leading to concern in other European countries that some of them
might move in search of better jobs. Every year, tens of thousands
of Albanian, Kurdish and North African refugees come ashore on the
Adriatic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: Opposes Missiles on Crete
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied at having pressured Cyprus into abandoning its
plans to deploy Russian-made missiles, Turkey said it would oppose
moves to deploy them on Crete. Turkey will not leave any threat
directed against it ``without a response,'' a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said. He said Greece and Cyprus were ``escalating the
tension in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Banks' Apartheid Role
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks are being urged to compensate South Africa, through
direct payments and debt forgiveness, for their role in supporting
apartheid. A Swiss financial watchdog group said in a report that
Switzerland and Germany were the largest financiers of South
African public entities during apartheid, helping prop up the
regime when other countries were imposing sanctions to try to
eliminate it.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Setback for Land-Seizure Plans
</P>
<P>
   A court threw out government plans to seize 841 mostly
white-owned farms, saying it had missed its own deadline for filing
confirmations of its seizure notices. Since the notices were handed
out in mid-November with 60-day deadlines, some political analysts
said President Robert Mugabe did not want the farms, but wanted to
be able to tell his party's December congress he had seized them.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Police and Students Clash
</P>
<P>
   Firing tear gas at rock-throwing students, riot policemen broke
up an anti-government demonstration at the University of Zimbabwe
in Harare. The students were protesting government corruption,
Zimbabwe's intervention in the fighting in Congo, a recent
crackdown on the news media and delays in the payment of student
grants.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Arms Mystery Revived
</P>
<P>
   Mangosuthu Buthelezi, head of the Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom
Party, accused Robert McBride, a foreign service official, of
distributing guns to assassins trying to kill Inkatha leaders.
McBride was arrested last year on gun-smuggling charges in
Mozambique, held for months and then mysteriously released without
trial. McBride's wife called Buthelezi's charges ``baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Russians Flocking In
</P>
<P>
   Russian immigration in the last two months increased by almost
50 percent over immigration in the same period last year, the
Jewish Agency of Israel reported. Some 3,319 immigrants arrived in
December and January, pushed to Israel by the Russian economic
crisis but also pulled by aggressive recruitment, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Big Protest Planned
</P>
<P>
   Strictly Orthodox Jewish leaders are planning a large rally in
Jerusalem on Sunday to protest what they see as a wave of Supreme
Court rulings that clash with Jewish law. Organizers told the
police they expected up to 300,000 demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Victory for Liberal
</P>
<P>
   Brian Tobin, the Liberal Party premier of Newfoundland and
Labrador, has been easily re-elected, strengthening his position as
a potential candidate to succeed Prime Minister Jean Chretien, 65.
Tobin, 44, left, served as Fisheries Minister in Chretien's Cabinet
and vigorously defended Canada's seizure of a Spanish fishing
trawler off Newfoundland in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Bank Case Thrown Out
</P>
<P>
   An appeals judge has thrown out a $6 million bank fraud
conviction against Angel Isidoro Rodriguez Saez, former chairman of
the Mexican bank Banpais, S.A. In a case that symbolized impunity
for the rich to many Mexicans, regulators accused Rodriguez, who
was a fugitive from justice for more than a year, of making illegal
loans that drove his bank into bankruptcy in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: `No War' Pact Possible
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who plans to travel to
Pakistan later this month on the inaugural run of a New
Delhi-to-Lahore bus route, said a ``no-war pact'' between the two
countries may be on the agenda when he meets with his Pakistani
counterpart, Nawaz Sharif. Vajpayee has proposed Feb. 20 as the
date for the historic bus ride.
</P>
<P>
   Philippines: Rebels' Link to Bin Laden
</P>
<P>
   The head of a Muslim rebel group fighting to set up an Islamic
state in the Philippines said in an interview with BBC News that
his group received money from the Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden,
accused by the United States of supporting terrorism. The leader,
Salamat Hashim, of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, has reached
agreements with the Philippines military that are expected to lead
to formal peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
