<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-STOCK-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BIG INVESTORS IN E(asterisk)TRADE SOLD STAKES BEFORE SYSTEM ( E ditors: in references to E(asterisk)Trade, replace (asterisk),
including parentheses, with the asterisk typographical symbol)  
(bl) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several major investors in the E(asterisk)Trade Group, the
online brokerage firm whose trading system failed for several hours
during parts of three trading days last week, sold big chunks of
stock last week just before the problems occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The two largest individual shareholders in E(asterisk)Trade,
which is based in Palo Alto, Calif., and its second-largest
institutional shareholder all sold large blocks. But the company's
biggest investor, Softbank Corp., a Japanese software company, did
not sell any shares.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of E(asterisk)Trade soared from $5 on Oct. 8 to $66.4375
on Feb. 1, but fell sharply after clients could not execute trades
Wednesday, Thursday and Friday last week. E(asterisk)Trade shares
closed Wednesday at $42.75, up $2.5625.
</P>
<P>
   General Atlantic Partners, a Greenwich, Conn., venture capital
fund, and an affiliate, GAP Coinvestment, sold 4.2 million shares
or about 48 percent of their holdings, according to Lisa Nash, an
E(asterisk)Trade Group vice president. The sales were registered
before the problems and were to have taken place Feb. 2 and Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The sales were dictated by the fund's ``very strict investment
policy discipline,'' Ms. Nash said. Tom Murphy, a General Atlantic
spokesman, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Christos Cotsakos, the chairman and chief executive of General
Atlantic who has the second-largest individual stake, and his
family sold 370,000 shares, lowering their stake to 2.6 percent,
from 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was part of a planned portfolio diversification
strategy,'' Ms. Nash said. ``It was planned, and largely executed,
at the beginning of last week'' during a brief window when insiders
are allowed to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were absolutely no changes in the planned sales because
of the outages,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   William Porter, E(asterisk)Trade's founder, sold 200,000 shares
in a family trust, reducing his stake to 4.3 million shares, Ms.
Nash said, while Debra J. Chrapaty, the chief information officer,
sold 50,000 of her 833,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   E(asterisk)Trade's system problems have raised questions about
the vulnerability of investors who execute their own trades in
highly volatile stocks.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said last week
that he would investigate the Internet trading industry after his
office received dozens of complaints about delayed orders and
unavailable trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
