<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT TICKETS 
BIRTHDAY BASH 
OF MEN AND MODELS
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now even the tickets to the Senate impeachment trial are
collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Public Library, which has a purple-and-blue ticket
from the Andrew Johnson trial, will soon have one from the Clinton
trial. Sen. Charles Schumer, a Democrat from New York, is giving
the library one from the first day of the trial, Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   And Riki Ellison, a former linebacker for the San Francisco
49ers who is now an aerospace executive in Washington, bid $1,600
at an auction Tuesday night for a similar ticket _ a used one. Sen.
Ted Stevens, a Republican from Alaska, had donated it to raise
money for the Juvenile Diabetes Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens ``felt sorry for the guy'' because Ellison apparently
thought he could use the ticket he had bid on for admission to the
impeachment session Friday, said Stevens' spokeswoman, Connie
Godwin. That was when Stevens said that for a bit more money than
the original bid, the winner could have lunch with him _ and go to
the session on Friday, using a ticket Stevens had been assigned in
the section for senators' families. Stevens' wife, Catherine, will
be in Chicago Friday. And yes, Ellison will have to return that
ticket. Stevens wants it for his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine's Milestone
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elaine Kaufman, the grande dame of the Upper East
Side gathering place for people who inevitably seem to have
boldface names, turned 70 Wednesday. She celebrated the milestone
the night before with what, if this were a police lineup, would be
described as the usual suspects: the novelist and Hemingway
biographer A.E. Hotchner, the writers Gay Talese and Peter Maas,
the playwright Jack Richardson, the actor Michael Caine, the
producer Jean Doumanian, the socialite Blaine Trump, the
photographer Nancy Ellison and the gossip reporter Claudia Cohen,
who was the second wife of Ronald O. Perelman, who was not there.
</P>
<P>
   But Perelman's third wife, Patricia Duff, who has been caught up
in a custody battle with him for months, was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patricia Duff walked in, she stood at the bar, then went to
her table, stopped,'' said Robert Zarem, a publicity agent who
counts himself as a longtime friend of Miss Kaufman. ``Graydon
Carter and I stood up and kissed her. Three minutes later Joe
Armstrong and Claudia motioned for me to come back. They both said
to me they saw me kissing Patricia Duff. I just said: `I'm a
Southern gentleman. I've kissed probably everybody here.''' (E.
Graydon Carter is the editor of Vanity Fair. Armstrong is a former
publisher of Rolling Stone who now oversees Worth, Civilization,
American Benefactor and Equity magazines.)
</P>
<P>
   Hotchner, who gave an impromptu speech, said the evening was
more like a reunion than anything else, with customers who had been
regulars since Elaine's opened in the 1960s chatting with more
recent habitues of the restaurant, which is on Second Avenue near
89th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were there to be sure they'd get a table,''
he said of the partygoers. ``This is the only family Elaine had. We
are it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad Lines
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Supper Club, a restaurant on West 47th Street
near Eighth Avenue, was a sea of blue suits belonging to
middle-aged men trying to chat up women they had seen pictured in
swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the conversation starters at a Tuesday night party
for the supermodels pictured in Sports Illustrated's swimsuit issue
fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what happened to one man who approached Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos, the model on the cover of the magazine. ``You were
terrific in the Victoria's Secret show,'' he said. She gave him a
puzzled look and said, ``But I wasn't in that show.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, hoping for a quick recovery, stammered, ``I mean last
year's Victoria's Secret show.'' She smiled. ``OK,'' she said, ``I
was in that show.''
</P>
<P>
   The model Heidi Klum was the only person (man or model) smoking
a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   How healthy is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said sheepishly, ``I only do it socially.'' The
cigarette she was smoking at that moment was, she said, ``only my
second one tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
