<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-10 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-WELCH-NYT &LR;      02-10 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WELCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE CITY'S OLYMPIC SALESMEN
</HEADLINE>
   (See Also OLY-SPONSORS) 
(DW) 
 By KIRK JOHNSON and JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Christmas morning, in many households, is one
of those special times when the world can be walled off and the
family becomes everything. But that was not the case in Thomas K.
Welch's house.
</P>
<P>
   In the early to mid-1990s, as Salt Lake City was pursuing its
dreams of playing host to the Winter Olympics, Welch _ then
president of the city's Olympic bid committee _ merged his personal
life and his Olympic agenda, friends and acquaintances say.
Christmas became part of the package, with International Olympic
Committee members from around the world coming to his mountainside
home here. Friends said that the Welch's six children had to wait
to open their presents until the IOC guests had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sacrificed his family,'' said Bradley A. Olch, a longtime
acquaintance of Welch's, who worked with him on the early years of
the bid campaign _ Salt Lake City was awarded the Games in 1995 _
and who is also the mayor of Park City, the town where nearly half
of the events in the 2002 Winter Games will take place.
</P>
<P>
   The report released here on Tuesday by a Board of Ethics panel
investigating Salt Lake City's efforts to win its Olympic bid
concluded that Welch and David R. Johnson, the bid committee's
former vice president, acted improperly in channeling money, gifts,
junkets, tuition payments and reimbursement for shopping sprees to
IOC members whose votes were crucial in getting the Olympics here.
</P>
<P>
   Before a ballroom full of journalists, the actions of Welch,
Johnson and a third former bid committee official, Craig Peterson,
were condemned as ``disgusting,'' by the organizing committee's
chairman, Robert H. Garff.
</P>
<P>
   But the deeper picture of Welch and Johnson that emerges _ from
the ethics report and from interviews with people who know them or
worked with them _ is not so simple.
</P>
<P>
   The report, while stuffed with evidence of how they used money
to try and influence IOC members' votes, goes out of its way to
note that Salt Lake City probably owes the fact that it will be
host to the Games to Johnson and Welch, and that most of what they
did constituted a legitimate marketing and lobbying campaign
</P>
<P>
   There are other contradictions. Much of what they did was
secretive, the report said, especially in issuing checks to IOC
members or their children, with little documentation. But more was
entirely open, completely documented in the 50,000 pages of files
examined by the ethics board.
</P>
<P>
   While the report criticized Welch for opening a joint investment
account in a local bank with an IOC member, the report said that
investigators found no evidence that any investments were ever made
from the account, or that Johnson or Welch, through their years of
working for the bid committee, and later the organizing committee,
ever took any inappropriate financial benefit for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But there also were some earlier warnings that Welch and Johnson
were not always sticklers for financial detail. In the 1980s, for
example, both men were working for related organizations involved
in fund-raising and lobbying for the development of sports in Utah
when reports began circulating about irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The state's legislative auditor general concluded in a report in
1988 that the organizations with which Johnson and Welch were
involved ``have not been effectively managed.''
</P>
<P>
   The auditor's report found conflicts of interest and inadequate
spending controls. ``Personnel costs have increased significantly,
double billings have occurred, some expenses lacked documentation
and future appropriation requests should be reduced,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Welch and Johnson, the cumulative evidence suggests, were
both what they seemed to be to many people _ hard-working,
well-paid promoters of the city they unquestionably love,
consummate salesmen, former Mormon missionaries _ and what they did
not seem to be to many of those same people: active participants in
a corrupt scheme of site selection in which financial largesse to
those with votes was equated with success.
</P>
<P>
   Their conduct, interviews and documents show, was at varying
times ethical and unethical, open and secretive, honest and
deceptive, dedicated to their city and yet profoundly embarrassing
to it in the end.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Johnson and Welch began in the 1970s,
when Welch, who is 54, was leading a Mormon church youth group at
the University of Utah, where Johnson, 40, was a student. Welch
went on to a career at Smith's Food and Drug Centers, a grocery
chain, and he became the company's top lawyer; Johnson began a
career that mostly involved sales, of cars when he was initially
out of college, and later of state tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is married with four children, was the detail man,
the one who kept track of IOC members and their interests and
needs. Welch was the one with the vision and the broad pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Godfrey, a teacher and former city councilman, who has
watched the Olympic story unfold, said he thought that Salt Lake
City's motives in wanting the Olympics were contradictory, and that
Welch in particular mirrored those impulses precisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed and pride; it's down to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey said that after Welch resigned from the organizing
committee in 1997, after a charge of spousal abuse, the vision that
had captivated many Utahans about the Olympics began to fade. Welch
and his wife, Alma, were later divorced, and he remarried last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson knew how to sell a dream too, or at least identify a
market. When Johnson was a boy, for example, his family lived for
three years in Oslo, where his father, who owned a candy company in
Salt Lake City, was the head of the Mormon mission. They lived in
the mission home, which meant that a young missionaries would
arrive, live with the Johnsons for a year or two and then return
home. The young Johnson found a niche in buying the belongings of
missionaries who were leaving and selling them to the next wave.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Johnson and Welch are personable men who know
how to make friends. Tuesday's ethics report said, for example,
that in 1991 Welch withdrew $30,000 from his daughter's college
fund and lent it to Julia Wallwork, the wife of an IOC member from
Western Samoa, Seiuli Paul Wallwork. Wallwork said in a telephone
interview that her husband had not been aware of the loan, which
was repaid, and that she believed it was a gesture of friendship
from Welch, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Welches are like family to us,'' she said. ``We have known
them over 10 years now. They came to Samoa many years ago. We have
maintained very close contact. Their son was here the year before
last with a rugby team, and we hosted them because their son is
like our son.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she had requested the loan, Wallwork declined to say.
``I can't tell you that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Welch's say that his friendship is almost too much
sometimes because, like his personality, it can be overwhelming in
its intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets so focused and obsessive, he seems to lose good
judgment,'' said Sydney Fonnesbeck, a former City Council member
and longtime friend. She said the bid committee should have known
to rein Welch in. Fonnesbeck said, ``Why wasn't someone saying, `We
know you want to do this, you think you're part of the Olympic
family, but you can't do it?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
