<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL IS WAITING TO RETURN THE FANS' EMBRACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell had just begun to feel the fans
embrace him as tightly as a bag of groceries. He was pleasantly
surprised. He had just begun to understand how forgiving people
could be when he produced. And he enjoyed that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had started to believe he could, at least in many
corners of New York, separate himself from the demonic image
attached to him after choking his former coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to hear people cheer,'' Sprewell said, sitting in
the Knicks' locker room as his teammates prepared for a game
against Washington last night. ``I almost feel like I've let people
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will have to function without him for three to six
weeks. A magnetic resonance imaging test on Tuesday revealed a
stress fracture in Sprewell's right heel. He will be required to
wear a plastic boot for at least three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment to put wheels on the Knicks is over for now. They
will likely drift back toward a more plodding half-court offense
that revolves around Patrick Ewing. Any thought coach Jeff Van
Gundy had of changing Ewing's emphasis and resting him for games on
a jam-packed 50-game schedule are over. ``That's out the window,''
Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell is as disappointed over the change of plans as anyone.
In the back of his mind, he had to wonder if his return after
sitting out for 14 months was too much for his body to endure.
There was no easing into his comeback with so little time to
prepare for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that had something to do with it,'' Sprewell said.
``But I tried to do everything I could to come into camp in shape.
I worked hard in the weight room and tried to prevent something
like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked if I could continue to play because I was playing on
it. The pain wasn't such that I couldn't play. But that was one
thing we were weighing. If I kept playing, what would happen? If I
did, there would be a point when I couldn't play with the pain. And
then it would have taken even more time to let it heal. It was best
to let it heal and get it out of the way. I'll be able to come back
later.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to make an impact early. This was his chance to work
through the early growing pains of learning how to play with other
stars on the court and emerge as the player capable of pushing the
Knicks toward a title.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's hard to predict how the Knicks will integrate Sprewell
into their team when he returns from his injury. Will he be a
starter or sixth man? Will the Knicks stay the course or integrate
change halfway through the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll get back and be able to contribute,'' Sprewell
said. ``The way it's been here, the way I've been embraced, I
really want to come back and do something for this team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
