<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DEMOCRATIC ENDORSERS OF PATAKI, NEW BUDGET MEANS REWARD TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When Gov. George Pataki announced his relatively
frugal budget the other day, he drew the usual catcalls from
Democrats hoping to depict him as the Scrooge of the Statehouse.
But the plan elicited mostly smiles from one faction of the
Democratic Party's leaders: those who endorsed Pataki for
re-election last fall.
</P>
<P>
   While the governor proposed freezing or cutting one type of
local aid to nearly every city, he called for a 36 percent increase
for Buffalo, whose mayor, Anthony Masiello, was one of the most
prominent Democrats to support the Republican governor. Niagara
Falls got an extra 25 percent; its mayor, James C. Galie, was
another Democratic defector.
</P>
<P>
   A third mayor, Edward A. Hanna of Utica, who not only backed
Pataki last year but then became a Republican, did not receive more
aid but is expecting a sizable chunk of a $5 million fund that the
governor put in the budget to help localities demolish buildings to
spur development.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democratic state senators from New York City who endorsed
Pataki, Olga A. Mendez and Alton R. Waldon Jr., are also slated to
get more money for their districts, particularly from a new pool of
at least $200,000 that the governor wants to spend on asthma
prevention and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Rewarding allies with cupfuls from the honey pot of the state
treasury is an Albany custom, and one of the best times to view it
is after a gubernatorial election, when politicians seek recompense
from the winner for their labors on the stump. These budget items
stand out even more this year because Pataki is pledging a new lean
regimen for the state, including an overall increase in spending of
just 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The modest growth in the proposed budget, which comes as the
state has a surplus of more than $2 billion, has infuriated some
lawmakers and local officials, including New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is a Republican who supported the governor in his
re-election bid (though not when Pataki first ran in 1994), but the
mayor maintains that the budget did him no favors and would be
disastrous for his city. The governor has staunchly disputed that
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   New York City does not receive the kind of aid that Pataki
sharply raised for Buffalo and Niagara Falls, but in general, the
governor proposed that the city's share of the state budget remain
flat.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki administration officials demur when asked about budget
items that appear intended for Democrats who endorsed the governor,
saying he has called for selective major new spending where most
needed, ignoring political considerations. ``We have put the
resources where we can have the most effect,'' said Michael McKeon,
a Pataki spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon denied that Democratic mayors or legislators had endorsed
Pataki last fall in return for promises of government largess after
the election. ``The reason why these people supported the governor
was because his policies have made cities stronger and our streets
safer and kept the economy growing,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Masiello, Peter K. Cutler, said the mayor made
his case to Pataki that Buffalo was managing its money better but
needed more help from the state. ``For anybody to criticize the
receipt of general-fund appropriations as based on political
paybacks is misguided,'' Cutler said. ``We reject that.''
</P>
<P>
   Galie of Niagara Falls did not respond to two telephone messages
left at his office.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna of Utica acknowledged that maintaining good relations with
Pataki might give his city more access to aid. ``How much are you
going to get from a governor if you knock him?'' said Hanna, who
garnered a $1 million state grant for a recreation center in Utica
last year around the same time that he was endorsing Pataki.
``That's just human nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
